<HEADER>
A0275 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NYS-ELECTION-LAW     08-06 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NYS-ELECTION-LAWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW YORK'S TWISTED DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Aug. 6:
</P>
<P>
   New York state's election laws are a national laughingstock, and
the state is infamous for the way in which candidates prefer to win
their races in court rather than at the polls. The public is inured
to the spectacle of little-known insurgents being dumped from the
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   But occasionally the system claims a celebrity victim, forcing
New Yorkers to confront the nuttiness of these laws. That happened
this week when Rep. Sue Kelly, a two-term Westchester County
Republican, was told she may be wiped off the ballot this fall
because her lawyers failed to number the pages on her list of
petition signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kelly's would-be Democratic opponent, Dick Collins, says
that Republicans frequently use technicalities to keep Democrats
off the ballot, and that he is using the same means to get rid of
Ms. Kelly. In other countries, this sort of thinking leads to
thousand-year wars. In New York it mocks the civic principle that
voters should be given the widest possible choice among candidates
who are given the fairest possible chance to compete.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the state Board of Elections who reviewed Collins'
objections this week recommended that Ms. Kelly be disqualified for
want of those page numbers. That was not what the state Legislature
envisioned when it tried to clean up the ballot-access laws two
years ago, in hopes of ending the humiliating incidents in which
candidates were disqualified for oversights like using the wrong
color ink.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the Legislature still has work to do. But while it
tidies up the existing laws, New York must also engage in a broader
debate about whether the system is simply too broken to be
repaired. Two-thirds of the states require nothing but a filing fee
for candidates to run for office. Some local election experts fear
that would lead to a flood of frivolous candidates who would clog
up an already confusing ballot.
</P>
<P>
   But that may turn out to be the only alternative to a system in
which people's urge to participate in the political process is
constantly being blocked by legal challenges.
</P>
<P>
   State election laws should promote, not limit, voter choice. New
York's work the opposite way. In 1996 only Steve Forbes' large
private fortune let him overcome Republican leaders' determination
to give Bob Dole an automatic victory in the New York presidential
primary. Voters in Rep. Kelly's district may now fear that Collins
will be given a free pass into Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The full Board of Elections has yet to hear Ms. Kelly's case,
and she has plenty of money for legal appeals. But right now,
dozens of candidates for minor offices are being disqualified
because they cannot afford to pay the legal fees required to mount
a court fight. Witnesses who circulated petitions are being dragged
into court and terrified out of ever volunteering to work for a
candidate again.
</P>
<P>
   It is on that level that New York's democratic process is turned
into a mockery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 0009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
