<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0277 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-BIRDHOUSES-N     08-06 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-BIRDHOUSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: BIRDHOUSE LANDLORDS CATER TO RENT-FREE TENANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Duplication warning: also sent with `s' code)  
 (bl)  
 By STEPHEN C. SAUTNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For six weeks last spring, beginning at precisely 4:30 a.m., a
strange sound would reverberate from an otherwise quiet
neighborhood in Columbus, N.J., a farming-community-turned-suburb
20 miles northeast of Philadelphia. Through the pre-dawn darkness,
and continuing for hours, the noise, an endlessly repeated
``cher-ch-cheer-cher,'' carried over manicured lawns and past newly
built homes.
</P>
<P>
   The sound grew especially loud around two enormous backyard
birdhouses mounted on poles. There, a small waterproof speaker
blared a recording of the ``dawn song'' of America's most sought
after song bird: the purple martin. Male martins use the song as a
vocal ``all's well'' and to perhaps attract a mate.
</P>
<P>
   For Jim Leedom, who had wired the speaker to the CD player in
his living room, it was just the beginning of a long initiation
into the semifanatical fraternity of martin ``landlords.''
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, purple martins _ the largest member of the
swallow family _ have shared a strong, mutual attraction with
humans. Ornithologists theorize this affinity began with native
Americans who hung hollow gourds as nesting cavities to attract the
birds to their villages. European colonists took this custom
another step by constructing ornate wooden houses with multiple
compartments.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the practice of housing martins has spawned its own
subculture of conservation societies, magazines, web pages and
merchandise catalogs selling everything from high-tech plastic
gourds with built-in, molded rain guards, to adjustable aluminum
dwellings that fetch several hundred dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The martins, in turn, have become so dependent that it is
generally believed they would become extinct in their range east of
the Rockies without human-supplied housing (the more solitary
western race still nests mostly in natural cavities).
</P>
<P>
   Leedom's indoctrination began last year when he heard martins
singing over his house as they migrated south. He spent the winter
studying their habits and come spring, had erected two houses and
two hanging gourds. Within weeks, a pair of martins reciprocated by
immediately calling one of his gourds home.
</P>
<P>
   As much as people have helped martins, we have also contributed
to their decline through the introduction of English sparrows and
European starlings in the 19th century. Both birds now out-compete
martins for nesting sites, and will often destroy eggs and young
birds. The human landlords of martins, for the most part a peaceful
lot, collectively see red when their houses are invaded by these
birds, which they have dubbed ``sky rats.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent visit to Leedom's house, I saw this firsthand when
three starlings landed on his lawn. Leedom quietly excused himself
and immediately returned with a pellet gun. Before he had a chance
to take a shot, the birds took off (like pigeons, neither species
are protected by conservation laws).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a constant battle if you're a responsible landlord,''
Leedom said. ``Martins get constantly harassed by the bad guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides guns and early morning serenades, I quickly learned some
of the other extremes landlords go to just to keep their tenants
happy. Twice during nesting season, they lower their martin houses
and replace nests with clean materials to minimize parasites. Some
have rigged sprinklers to cool down the roofs of houses during heat
waves, while others have installed lamps to protect martins during
cold snaps. Landlords also commonly supply bowls of crushed
eggshells as a calcium supplement, or a dish of meal worms in the
early season when flying insects are still scarce.
</P>
<P>
   When Leedom's martins eventually produced a clutch of eggs, he
videotaped the nest and showed it off to his friends. He admits the
response was lukewarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think we're crazy,'' he said. ``We're a group that,
among ourselves, seems very normal. But to everyone else we're
weird.''
</P>
<P>
   This solicitous behavior may have come to a head last June, when
the National Weather Service posted a tornado watch for this area.
According to Leedom, while his neighbors huddled in their
basements, he stood at his window throughout the storm staring at
his martin houses as 60-mile-an-hour winds ripped lawn furniture
from his patio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had eggs and I'm waiting and waiting,'' he said. ``My
wife gave me a lot of grief for that.''
</P>
<P>
   But his birds survived and produced two young, which by late
July fledged in a matter of days. On this day in early July, he
lowered the house and showed them off like prize-winning tomatoes
from a backyard garden.
</P>
<P>
   The birds did their best to play dead, but couldn't help showing
their iridescent purple backs and narrow, pointed wings, which
would soon be used for mid-flight maneuvers to overtake and catch
flying insects.
</P>
<P>
   Leedom carefully hoisted the house back up. Within a minute, the
adult female swooped to the gourd with a plump dragonfly in her
beak and presented it to her young.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the dark, cobalt male took to soaring overhead. We
watched the martin adjust its tail like a rudder and glide over the
neighborhood, eventually disappearing behind the rooftops. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 0010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
