u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LOUIMA-BEATING-NYT     08-06 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-BEATING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLEGED POLICE BEATING VICTIM TO SUE UNION AS WELL AS OFFICERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Abner Louima, the Haitian immigrant who prosecutors
say was brutalized at a Brooklyn police station, has broadened his
planned civil lawsuit by adding the union that represents police
officers to the list of defendants, lawyers and others familiar
with the suit said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   They said that the lawsuit, which is expected to be filed today
in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn, will contend that the union _
the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association _ is liable because it has
fostered police brutality in general by ``encouraging and
maintaining a blue wall of silence'' designed to protect officers
accused of brutality. The other defendants are the city, the Police
Department and the individual officers accused in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Louima's lawyers have said that the suit would seek a total of
$155 million in damages from the defendants, but from what others
familiar with the litigation said Wednesday, it appeared possible
that a figure might not be cited in the papers filed Thursday and
would be left unspecified until later in the litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Those who spoke Wednesday _ on condition of anonymity _ about
the planned lawsuit declined to say whether it would contend that
the policies or actions of the union specifically obstructed the
department's attempts to investigate Louima's charges that he was
tortured in the bathroom of the 70th Precinct station house in
Flatbush.
</P>
<P>
   It is said to be quite unusual for a police union to be named as
a defendant in a lawsuit charging police brutality.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the charges in the suit are to be made available at a
news conference today at the Manhattan offices of three of Louima's
lawyers, Johnnie Cochran, Peter Neufeld and Barry Scheck. Neufeld
declined Wednesday to discuss the suit. Another lawyer for Louima,
Sanford Rubenstein, did not return a call to his Brooklyn office.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement of the news conference said that the suit also
``seeks compensation from police officers who witnessed or were
aware of the events surrounding the beating of Louima,'' but no
details were provided.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association, Joseph
Mancini, said he would have no comment on reports that his group
would be named as a defendant.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest of Louima, now 31, in a brawl outside a Flatbush
nightclub a year ago, has led to one of the most racially and
politically charged cases of alleged police brutality in New York
City in years.
</P>
<P>
   Four 70th Precinct officers have been indicted on federal
charges of violating Louima's civil rights. The four _ Justin
Volpe, Charles Schwarz, Thomas Bruder and Thomas Wiese _ are
accused of beating Louima in a police car on the way to the
precinct's station house. Volpe and Schwarz are also accused of
torturing him in the bathroom of the station house, Volpe by
ramming a stick into Louima's rectum and then into his mouth,
inflicting severe internal injuries, and Schwarz by holding Louima
down.
</P>
<P>
   A sergeant, Michael Bellomo, has been charged with trying to
help the four cover up the beating.
</P>
<P>
   All five officers insist that the charges against them in the
criminal case, pending in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn, are
untrue.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz's lawyer, Stephen Worth, asserted Wednesday that naming
the PBA as a defendant in Louima's civil suit was ``nothing more
than a cheap publicity stunt'' that ``has no merit.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit reportedly contends, among other things, that the
so-called 48-hour rule has contributed to police brutality in the
city by helping implement blue walls of silence. The rule, part of
contracts negotiated between the union and the city since the early
1970s, says that officers accused of wrongdoing do not have to
answer the questions of Police Department investigators for two
full business days after the incident in question.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the rule outside the Police Department maintain it
gives officers involved in wrongdoing time to coordinate their
accounts or tamper with witnesses. But while police officials and
the Giuliani administration are seeking to eliminate the rule, they
also point out that it is irrelevant in such situations as the
Louima case, because in such instances officers retain the same
right as civilians not to be compelled to incriminate themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
