<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0286 &Cx1f; tth-z
U s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI     08-06 1446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MARK RYPIEN, IT'S A HOME SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no world outside of Post Falls, Idaho, right now for
Mark Rypien. No world outside of his home, his family, his
3-year-old son, Andrew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything now is about Andrew,'' said Rypien, the strapping
quarterback with the Super Bowl XXVI ring and MVP trophy; with
nearly 19,000 passing yards in his 13-year NFL career; and, don't
forget, a couple of good years left in his throwing arm. That's why
the Atlanta Falcons had signed him to a two-year deal this year.
</P>
<P>
   Rypien gave it back. The $1.8 million the Falcons had paid him.
The backup job in Atlanta that would have all but guaranteed some
of Rypien's autumn Sunday afternoons would have been spent flicking
off passes in the face of rushing linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   All of that is meaningless now.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a time for us all to be together as a family. We want
his sisters to know their brother. Every day he's here, it's a
blessing to be together. You never know what could happen,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For the last 20 years or more, the 35-year-old Rypien has spent
every August sweating under the summer sun, training for another
football season.
</P>
<P>
   High school football at Shadle Park in Spokane. College at
Washington State, where the fraternity of Cougar QBs keeps growing
more elite. And all those NFL camps in Washington, where he won the
Super Bowl, and St. Louis, where he learned just how soul-less a
business professional sports can be. The Rams let him walk away
even though the fans in St. Louis loved Rypien and the Rypiens
loved it in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   But this August is different. Rypien is playing no football. In
fact it's the last thing on his mind, ever since he left Falcons
camp a month ago without a split-second of hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just called his agent and said, `There's no way I'm going
back,''' said Rypien's wife, Annette. ``He said, `There's no way
I'm walking out of this house.'''
</P>
<P>
   And that is why, ever since July 2, after Andrew had suffered
another seizure _ one that let them know all their prayers and all
the agony of surgery, chemotherapy and radiation treatment had not
done a shred of good to rid Andrew of his cancer _ Rypien knew what
had to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who would even think about doing anything different
doesn't have their priorities straight,'' the father of three said.
</P>
<P>
   And that conviction is why Mark Rypien and his wife have set up
another kind of camp at their home _ one that serves them all as a
cocoon and a retreat and, if not a place to heal, then as a place
where Andrew can live out whatever time is left in peace and love
and complete adoration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend a lot of time complimenting each other, talking,
playing. Sometimes the girls (Amber, 7, and Angela, 9) get shafted.
But everything we're doing is about Andrew's quality of life,''
Rypien said. ``We want to keep that going. If there's a drastic
situation, we'll deal with it then.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, there is no more science, no more invasive
modern medicine, no more trips to the hospital in Spokane, where
Andrew endured the machines, the needles, the careening blood
counts and radical procedures with more bravery than a grown man
could have shown.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the focus is home and each other. When Andrew feels up
to it, the family rides into town to play at Chuck E. Cheese's, or
they head down to the river that rolls through the front of their
property to splash and swim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, though, the sun seems to take more out of him. You can
see how drained he gets. Outside, the heat sends more pressure to
his brain, so we're staying inside more,'' Rypien said the other
day from his home in northern Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   This past Saturday, Rypien said his son complained of a
headache, too, so the father administered a dose of steroids to his
son, hoping it would alleviate the swelling enough to eliminate the
pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside of that, we're trying for the highest quality of
life,'' Rypien said.
</P>
<P>
   Then the glitch in his voice became evident, despite the elder
Rypien's bravery and stoicism. He is talking about Andrew's
prognosis, now that the tumor in the front left lobe of Andrew's
brain has come back with a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, Andrew Rypien had his first seizure, which led
to the diagnosis of a brain tumor. There was surgery, chemotherapy
and later the doctors did what has rarely been done to a child as
young as Andrew: they planted radiation seeds in his brain, hoping
to devastate the tumor bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was on March 23,'' Rypien said.
</P>
<P>
   And for the next 87 days, the radiation seeped into the
surrounding cells, and the doctors were hopeful the cancer had been
eliminated. But one week later, just one lousy week after the seeds
had died and just as Andrew celebrated his third birthday, the
tumor was back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had tripled in size,'' Rypien said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, we were praying for recovery,'' Rypien said,
displaying his long-standing faith that has only grown stronger and
more precious, just as his love for his son has grown so deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're praying for a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Like it happens sometimes with families caring for a terminally
ill child, the Rypiens are the ones who offer strength, who see the
truth clearly and ask everyone to embrace it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be sorry,'' is what Mark Rypien finds himself telling
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``People see us and say they are sorry, and I tell them you have
nothing to be sorry about. You didn't do anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want people to know Andrew. We pray every day for a
miracle of healing, but if and when a time comes and he's not going
to be around, we want people to know they knew Andrew.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes the Rypiens' struggle all the more daunting is that,
in the middle of Andrew's illness, Annette was diagnosed with
cervical cancer. The doctors performed a hysterectomy, and
thankfully, as the cancer was detected in time, there was no need
for chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   But just as Annette was recovering from major surgery and being
given a clean bill of health, Andrew experienced that second
seizure. That was on June 19. Andrew was flown by helicopter back
to Spokane, cradled in Annette's arms despite how ill and sore she
was, as Mark Rypien made his way by car.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never justify or find a balance for this,'' Rypien
said of the duality of such good news about Annette and such
devastating news about Andrew.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really brought us back down to reality. And Annette felt
much worse. She felt, as I would, that maybe she was the sacrifice,
that maybe it was like saying it's your turn, now let's spare
Andrew,'' Rypien said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Rypiens had to face choices about how to proceed
with their son. The doctors at Deaconess Medical Center in Spokane
sat down with the Rypiens and discussed the difficult scenarios,
which included more radical surgery that could have left Andrew
paralyzed or just as likely caused him to die on the operating
table.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some people are upset with us, and this was the hardest
thing we ever had to do. But I just told Mark, `God either wants
him or He doesn't.' So we just decided to let Andrew be Andrew,''
Annette said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt it was out of respect to him. But I just said I cannot
do this. I cannot take him back to the hospital and watch him
hyperventilate, especially after everything we had already tried
had blown up in our faces and it came back so viciously, even after
using the strongest medications.''
</P>
<P>
   All that happened about six weeks ago. At that time, the doctors
gave Andrew as little as two months, which is why every day is
precious and why every day Andrew is home with his family, the
world feels a little more blessed and lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going about life as normal,'' Annette said, ``but we
just wanted to say thank you to everybody who has sent their
prayers and blessings. We have gotten so many cards and letters
from people all over the country. A lot of the letters, people
didn't even know our address. They just write to the postmaster and
asked if he could send the card or letter on to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some letters of prayer and hope and encouragement just say ``The
Rypiens. Idaho.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mind-boggling to know how many lives that Andrew has
touched, from Washington to St. Louis to Atlanta. There has been
such an outcry of support,'' Mark Rypien said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has given us such a big boost, feeling others are out there
who care and who are praying as much as we are.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rypiens are all home together, but hardly home alone.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
