<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLADES ENJOYING SMALLER ROLE WITH SEAHAWKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ In the past few months, Brian Blades has seen
his role in the Seahawks' offense diminished significantly and his
salary reduced even more.
</P>
<P>
   He also has had to watch the forced retirement of his brother,
strong safety Bennie Blades, because of bulging discs in his back.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was celebrating his 33rd birthday two weeks ago by
practicing twice in 99-degree heat at the team's Eastern Washington
University training camp.
</P>
<P>
   So why is the veteran wide receiver smiling so much?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having a great time out here this year,'' Blades says.
</P>
<P>
   Make that a really great time, Blades' body language adds.
</P>
<P>
   This might be the twilight of Blades' productive career, but he
has big plans for his 11th season.
</P>
<P>
   Blades is in better shape than he has been since 1994,
physically and mentally. He has lost a step, but now uses cunning
and quick wits to continue getting open and catching the ball as
well as ever. And, he's having fun again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is to have fun,'' Blades said. ``I'm toward
the end of my career, and I know that. One thing I also know is
that I can still play this game. So I'm just going to have fun with
whatever I have left.''
</P>
<P>
   Fun isn't exactly the word that describes Blades' life the past
three years.
</P>
<P>
   After setting club records with 80 and 81 receptions in 1993 and
1994, the injuries that accumulate from years of making tough
catches over the middle reduced Blades' numbers, playing time and
effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Off the field, Blades accidentally shooting and killing his
cousin, Charles Blades, in July 1995 plunged him into a personal
hell. A jury convicted him of manslaughter, but the judge
subsequently overturned the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Blades never will forget that tragic night in Florida, but he
has learned to cope with the loss of his best friend and has put
behind him the seemingly endless legal proceeding that followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt, he's changed this camp,'' offensive
coordinator Bob Bratkowski said. ``I think the emotional strain of
what he's been through wore on him physically the last few years.
He's to the point now where he's recovered from that. Mentally,
he's probably a little more at peace with himself.''
</P>
<P>
   It shows.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Blades still couldn't talk about his cousin without
tears coming to his eyes. He was sullen and withdrawn. The team's
signing of Bennie in free agency gave Brian a shoulder on which to
lean, and at times even cry.
</P>
<P>
   Bennie is Brian's younger brother, but he's larger and more
gregarious. So Bennie's presence also cast a large shadow that
Brian either didn't want to or couldn't elude. Now Bennie is gone,
just another reminder of how quickly an NFL career can end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very hard on me,'' Blades said. ``It was hard seeing
Bennie go through what he went through during the offseason and
what he went through at the end of last season. I gave him all the
love and support I could. When it came down to the decision of
whether he should try to play this year or hang them up, I gave him
my honest opinion as far as life after football.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a discussion Blades admits having while looking into the
mirror, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Why he is still out here competing against players who were in
junior high school when Blades broke into the league as a
second-round draft choice in 1988? Why agree to a pay cut to the
NFL minimum of $325,000? Why accept a demotion to the No. 4
receiver behind Joey Galloway, Mike Pritchard and James McKnight?
What's left to prove for the player who has caught more passes
(566) than any player in club history besides Hall of Famer Steve
Largent?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to this season. I'm looking forward to
doing whatever I can to help this ballclub get back to where it was
when I first got here,'' Blades said.
</P>
<P>
   Blades is the final bridge to where the Seahawks once were and
where they want to be again _ the playoffs. The last time this team
played in the postseason was during Blades' rookie season. Since
then, he has survived two coaching changes, an ownership change and
the attempted move of the franchise to Southern California. Blades
also has endured the past seven years, when the Seahawks have not
had one winning season, while compiling a 44-68 record and watching
their fan base dwindle.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got here, it was great,'' Blades said. ``The fans
were great. The Kingdome was always crowded. That's why I'm looking
forward to this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the motivation, Bratkowski is just glad to still have
Blades around.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been here so long he wants to see that great year that's
hanging out there on the edge,'' Bratkowski said. ``He wants to be
a part of that. He said he'll cover kicks or do whatever he has to
to be a part of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   That from a player who already has been so much a part of this
team's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't ask for more than Brian Blades has done for this
team,'' Bratkowski said. ``Or is willing to do for this team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
