<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHOPPER' WHO GOT AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ So this is how The Disney Co. goes about
evening the score. Not on the scoreboard but in the boardroom.
</P>
<P>
   Four days after pitcher Carlos Perez slips through the fingers
of the Disney-owned Angels and into the laps of the Fox Group-owned
Dodgers, Disney offers the NHL a Kingdom's ransom for league
broadcasting rights once the current Fox contract expires.
</P>
<P>
   Considering this latest ``Disney on Ice'' production carries a
$400 million price tag, you'd think there'd be a movement underfoot
to assemble something a little more entertaining for the hockey
fans at home than a No.1 defensive pairing of Jason Marshall and
Pavel Trnka, which is what the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim boasted at
the close of the 1997-98 season. And yet, over the summer, all
that's changed are the dates on the calendar.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney-owned Ducks so far have shown remarkable financial
restraint, refusing to pay any free agent on ice twice what they
deem he's worth.
</P>
<P>
   And how much more is the Disney bid than what Fox forked out,
you ask? Roughly double, proving that fiscal responsibility is as
adaptable as baseball's strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   That said, tight pockets are not what landed the Angels in
another too-snug-for-comfort pennant race. If the Angels happen to
miss the playoffs again this year, as they have the previous 11,
it'll be because of the deal they didn't make a year ago, not any
they failed to consummate before this past Friday's trading
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels were right to hold on to the likes of infielder Troy
Glaus and left-handed starter Scott Schoeneweis when all impatience
broke loose. To mortgage the farm, as the Dodgers so foolishly have
done by trading three of their four best prospects, is the way to
salvage a season, maybe. But it's ultimately destructive to the
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Time remains on the Angels' side, though you have to wonder
where they'd be today if they hadn't let slugger Mark McGwire slip
through their fingers like sand in an hour glass.
</P>
<P>
   When McGwire was being offered by the Oakland Athletics before
the 1997 trading deadline, the Angels were prepared to make a deal.
It seemed like a no-brainer, what with McGwire having made it clear
he'd like to play near his son, who lives in Huntington Beach with
McGwire's ex-wife and her second husband.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels offered Oakland outfielder Jim Edmonds and
left-handed pitcher Jarrod Washburn. They also requested permission
to talk to McGwire's agent so they could get a feel for their
prospects of re-signing the superstar free-agent-to-be.
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics, not eager to lose McGwire to a division rival,
anyway, balked. OK, countered Angels general manager Bill Bavasi,
then how about throwing in third baseman Scott Brosius as a
consolation prize in the event McGwire should walk after the
season's end?
</P>
<P>
   No way, said the Athletics. At which point Bavasi should have
counted to 61, if that's what it took, then found a way to make the
deal happen. How often, after all, is the next coming of Babe Ruth
up for grabs like a home run ball?
</P>
<P>
   Oakland could have been counted on to provide more opposition
than McGwire, for whom the 18-mile commute to the ballpark from his
offseason home in Huntington Harbour and a more constant
relationship with his 10-year-old child would have been no small
enticement to stay awhile.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Angels dropped out of the bidding and the first
baseman went to St. Louis for a song (pitchers T.J. Mathews, Eric
Ludwick and Blake Stein). A year later, McGwire is chasing history
while the Angels are trying desperately not to repeat it.
</P>
<P>
   On July 3, they led the American League West by 3{ games. Today
they are a 1{ games behind the Texas Rangers who, wisely or no,
traded away a good chunk of their future last week with an eye
toward gunning down another Angels postseason run right now.
</P>
<P>
   If the Angels can't hold off all challengers this time, it'll
mark the third time in four seasons that they've made like home
base and let someone trample all over them.
</P>
<P>
   A so-called full house witnessed the Angels' 6-5 loss to
Cleveland Wednesday afternoon. It was their sixth announced
capacity crowd of the season. With McGwire's bat in the lineup,
they surely would have had at least that many during their
just-completed nine-game homestand.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with McGwire as a draw, the Angels probably could have
augmented their 45,050 capacity by instituting festival seating on
the fake green hillside on either side of the plastic rock
formation of the redesigned and renamed Edison Field. With McGwire
an everyday presence, the stadium really would have been electric.
Every game would have been the Fourth of July, especially with
every Angels home run duly celebrated with fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   With McGwire chasing Roger Maris' single-season home run record,
Angels fans might not have noticed all the beach balls and bleached
blondes.
</P>
<P>
   With McGwire in an Angels uniform there would have been no need
to designate Cecil Fielder for assignment, as the Angels did
Wednesday; the designated hitter would have been someone else's
extra baggage from the season's start.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind filling McGwire's shoes. ``I know I haven't exactly
been myself in my four months here,'' a disappointed Fielder
admitted on his way out.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels shouldn't cry over Fielder or the Perezes and Todd
Stottlemyres and Mike Piazzas that got away last week. Those are
small fish compared to the whopper that was theirs to reel in last
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
