<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0293 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     08-06 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADERLESS DODGERS CONTINUE STRUGGLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The Los Angeles Dodgers didn't need Gary Sheffield
and Raul Mondesi. They needed Kirk Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   They needed what the team has been lacking during all the
September meltdowns and all the summer slumber parties like
Wednesday's 5-1 loss to the lowly Montreal Expos in front of 9,611
at Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Someone to say this is not good enough.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Dodgers were content with saying it was tough
playing without the suspended Sheffield and later Mondesi, who left
the game early with more lower- back pain.
</P>
<P>
   Tough is being 30 games out in early August like the Expos.
Tough is hearing there might not even be a team in Montreal in a
few years. Tough is fans back in L.A. knowing that the Dodgers are
underachieving again.
</P>
<P>
   Tough is not being only 5{ games back in the wild-card race,
even after losing for the second consecutive night to a far lesser
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Bobby Bonilla appeared to address the problem. Playing
for the first time since July 15 (sprained left wrist), Bonilla
returned to a down team. He was brought to the Dodgers to replace
the reluctant Mike Piazza as clubhouse leader but later implied the
only trouble with this team lies in the absence of Sheffield and
Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is every big-league team has a chance to kick
your butt if you're not prepared to play them,'' said Bonilla, who
singled in the sixth and hit the ball hard twice in four at-bats.
``Obviously, we're not prepared. Either you come in with the eye of
the tiger or you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what Gibson brought the Dodgers during the 1988
championship season. He not only won the National League Most
Valuable Player award, he dragged passive players like Mike
Marshall and Jeff Hamilton into playing well with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   It is a rare skill. Within three years, Gibson was broken down
and off the team. But if fired general manager Fred Claire never
works another day in his life, he always can smile about that
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were hoping Mondesi could step up and fill the
leadership role. He is the most energized player on this team. But
now he is hurt again. On this 10-game trip, Mondesi has missed two
games altogether and left three others early because of back
trouble. He will see a doctor in Los Angeles on Friday to determine
the extent of the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Glenn Hoffman didn't second-guess himself for
sending Mondesi out despite the obvious pain. Mondesi, who leads
the team with 25 homers, reinjured his back sliding into second
with a first-inning double. Hoffman is desperate to jump-start this
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew if we could get him warmed up and loose he might be
OK,'' Hoffman said. ``He gave it all he could, but he was
tightening up and we knew we had to get him out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, who is serving a three-game suspension for his
involvement in the June 28 fight with Pittsburgh's Jason Kendall,
will be back Friday. He is the club leader with a .312 average and
75 RBI. Maybe he could have helped figure out Montreal's rookie
starter Carl Pavano (4-5), who pitched six scoreless innings to
lower his earned-run average to 4.59.
</P>
<P>
   But Sheffield probably would have had no control over Eric
Karros making outs to end four innings and stranding four base
runners. And could Sheffield have helped Darren Dreifort (6-10)
avoid walking five batters, including three in the sixth inning,
when the Expos increased their lead to 4-0?
</P>
<P>
   To that point, Dreifort's only mistake was a two-run double by
Scott Livingstone in the first.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth, however, had an ominous beginning when Dreifort
opened by walking former teammate Wilton Guerrero. It was just
Guerrero's fifth walk in 215 at-bats this season.
</P>
<P>
   And it only got worse.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick May followed with a single and Vladimir Guerrero scored
his brother with a slow roller to third that Adrian Beltre could
only stand and watch.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort appeared out of trouble when Livingstone grounded into
a double play, but May moved to third and scored on a passed ball
by Tom Prince with Ryan McGuire at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like there was more pressure on me tonight
because guys were out,'' said Dreifort, who has just one victory in
his last seven starts. ``We'll be all right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 0047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
