<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONDY'S PAIN UNBEARABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Raul Mondesi left Wednesday's 5-1 loss to Montreal
with more soreness in his lower back and will not play today's
series finale against the Expos.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that after Tuesday's game but played anyway. Before
the game he could barely walk, then reinjured his back sliding into
second on a first-inning double.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very painful right now,'' Mondesi said after the game.
``I won't be playing (today). We have to get this figured out.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing keeping the Los Angeles Dodgers from a full panic
is that Mondesi's problem is in the muscles and not a disc, which
is far more difficult to mend. Mondesi will be examined Friday by
the club's back specialist, Dr. Robert Watkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to take the ball out of his hand right now,''
said manager Glenn Hoffman. ``We knew how he was before the game,
but he wanted to play. This time he won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi has missed two games and left three others early on the
Dodgers' 10-game East Coast trip. His latest problems came on the
day Bobby Bonilla returned after missing 20 games with a pain in
his surgically repaired left wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla started in left, with Matt Luke moving to right field.
During a sixth-inning double switch, Bonilla moved to third base.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, the Dodgers planned to send down rookie
third baseman Adrian Beltre to make room for Bonilla. But general
manager Tom Lasorda, who is back in Los Angeles, called Hoffman in
the manager's office and told him infielder Alex Cora was being
sent back to Triple-A Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre had a second-inning double Wednesday but has not hit
well. He turned 20 in April and, like many rookies, has had trouble
with breaking balls away.
</P>
<P>
   But Luke, another rookie who has been getting most of the
playing time in left, has gone just 3 for 26 on the trip and might
be getting a little overexposed. By sending down Cora, who went 4
for 30 in 24 games with the Dodgers, Bonilla goes back to left.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla said he was ready to go before Wednesday's game. He had
an excellent batting practice session on Tuesday and awoke the next
day without pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm gonna finish out this season, go home and rehab and come
back really strong next year,'' said the always bubbly Bonilla.
``My hand feels very good right now.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Once upon a time: This is Hoffman's first visit to Olympic
Stadium since he was traded to the Dodgers from Boston in August
1987. Hoffman, then a shortstop, arrived only to learn he had not
cleared waivers and was forced to wait three days before he could
be activated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't supposed to be with the team until I cleared
waivers,'' Hoffman said. ``But I just holed up in the clubhouse
until the whole thing blew over.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Day off: With a day game today, catcher Charles Johnson was
given Wednesday off. It is the third day off on this trip for
Johnson, who missed the July 28 game in Philadelphia when his wife
had a baby in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard Mondy was going to play, I thought I could sneak
a day off for C.J.,'' Hoffman said. ``Then Mondy was gone and
without C.J. we didn't have a lot of pop in there. We have a few
days coming up, so he will be in there every day for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Prince started and went 0 for 4. He singled and scored the
winning run as a pinch hitter Friday but went hitless in 12 at-bats
in those three starts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
