<SLUG> BC-NY-HELL'S-ANGELS-BUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG RAID ON HELL'S ANGELS YIELDS NO DRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was a drug bust gone bust.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 FBI agents and 9th Precinct detectives pried their
way into the Hell's Angels clubhouse in the East Village on
Wednesday night, working on a tip that narcotics were being sold in
the motorcycle club.
</P>
<P>
   But when the authorities arrived, they found no illegal drugs _
nothing illegal, in fact, except a pair of unregistered handguns,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All they had to do was knock,'' one gang member said.
</P>
<P>
   Four members were arrested: one on an assault charge, two on
outstanding robbery charges, and another on a charge of criminal
possession of the weapons, said Detective Joseph Pentangelo, a
police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The clubhouse at 75{ E. Third St. _ actually incorporated under
New York state law as a religious nonprofit organization and
formally known as the Church of Angels _ has been at that address
for three decades.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, chapter president ``Big'' Vinnie Girolamo was charged
with throwing his girlfriend to her death from the clubhouse roof.
He died before his day in court. Then the club was shut down for a
time in 1985 after a cocaine and methamphetamine raid.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, as police had the block cordoned off for the
raid, Ronald Kuby, a lawyer who has defended some gang members
before, denounced the raid as harassment and said the authorities
were running a ``police state.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors insisted that the bikers kept the area clean and
sober.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're good neighbors,'' said Caren Goldstein, 32. ``They're
very peaceful and they protect the block. I feel safe here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
