<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
 
PHYSICAL LaFLEUR ADDS DIMENSION FOR COWBOYS 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ After catching a pass in Friday's
preseason game against the Seahawks, Dallas Cowboys tight end David
LaFleur hurled his 6-foot-7, 280-pound frame into Seattle safety
Darryl Williams to finish a 26-yard gain.
</P>
<P>
   Williams (6-0, 202) certainly won't forget it. And if LaFleur
has his way, defensive backs across the NFL soon will get the same
message.
</P>
<P>
   Call it a calling card of sorts for the big tight end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like \Rdelivering a hard hit\S,'' said LaFleur, the Cowboys'
first-round pick in 1997. ``I'm not going to run away from anybody,
so the best thing I can do is run over somebody. That's pretty much
what they can expect.''
</P>
<P>
   LaFleur's bronc-busting ways are a departure from the finesse
play of recent Cowboys tight ends Jay Novacek and Eric Bjornson.
But the style seems to suit Cowboys coach Chan Gailey, who inserted
LaFleur into the starting lineup ahead of Bjornson because he
believes LaFleur is perfect for the Cowboys' new offense.
</P>
<P>
   But Gailey said LaFleur would have to take a huge leap in
development from his rookie year, when he caught only 18 passes,
for the offense to reach its full potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tight end is very important to our football team as a run
blocker and a pass catcher,'' Gailey said. ``David's development is
very important to our football team. We'll need him to make a good
jump from last year for us to be effective on offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said LaFleur stepped up against Seattle. In addition to
the reception, LaFleur made an impact in the running game by
throwing a key block during Chris Warren's 15-yard touchdown run.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the reasons everyone talks about him being a
prototype tight end,'' Cowboys tight end coach Les Miles said.
``He's big, he's strong, he has good hands. I think it's warranted
when people suggest he could be as good as there is.''
</P>
<P>
   LaFleur began to emerge near the end of the 1997 season when he
started three of the last four games in place of an injured
Bjornson. Eleven of his receptions came during that time, including
a three-catch, two-touchdown performance against the Bengals in
Week 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I showed in that game what I'm capable of doing,''
LaFleur said. ``I was put in a good situation, and I was able to
make some plays. I think I can make some plays to help this team
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey agrees. And while the Cowboys four- and five-receiver
sets have been the subject of much talk during training camp,
Gailey said the Cowboys will get the ball into LaFleur's big hands.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey wouldn't guess any season reception totals for LaFleur,
but he almost guaranteed that the second-year player would have
more receptions than the 18 caught last season by Steelers tight
end Mark Bruener when Gailey was his offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to do everything I can to help us win,'' LaFleur
said. ``Whether that's catch 20 balls and go to the Super Bowl or
60 balls and go to the Super Bowl. It doesn't worry me. But the
tight ends will have some balls in this offense.''
</P>
<P>
   And judging by the Seattle game, if LeFleur can get the ball he
will be a big hit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 0120EDT &QL; 
