</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MILLION-YOUTH-MARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI ASSAILS ORGANIZER OF MILLION YOUTH MARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani lashed out Wednesday at the
organizers of the proposed Million Youth March, calling its lead
organizer's words ``race-baiting and anti-Semitic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From my point of view, this is a hate march,'' the mayor said
at a City Hall news conference. He noted that the strongest
language had come from the march's primary organizer, Khalid Abdul
Muhammad, although the mayor did not mention him by name.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad, a former aide to Louis Farrakhan, the minister of the
Nation of Islam, wants to hold the rally in Harlem on Sept. 5.
Organizers are billing it as a show of strength and unity by black
teen-agers from across the country, much like the Million Man March
that was held in Washington in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But the city, citing traffic concerns, has denied Muhammad a
permit to hold the march on that date or on Harlem's Malcolm X
Boulevard. Muhammad has said the march would go ahead anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Last week he threatened to shift its route to Crown Heights,
Brooklyn, as a ``direct confrontation with the Jews of that area.''
But Wednesday night he did not repeat that threat, saying instead,
``We do not choose to take our march to any other location in the
city. We would like to stay at home'' _ a reference to Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad was dismissed by the Nation of Islam as its spokesman
in 1994 after a 1993 speech in which he referred to Jews as
``bloodsuckers'' and made other inflammatory remarks against Roman
Catholics, whites and homosexuals. He later founded the New Black
Muslim Movement and the New Black Panther Party, both based in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Muhammad called New York a ``Jewish-controlled city''
and implied that Jews and other whites working for the mayor were
secretly responsible for the difficulties that march organizers
were having with the city. Giuliani excoriated that assertion
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rhetoric is extraordinary,'' the mayor said. ``The
attributions of the city's position to Jews in the administration
doing this is mind-boggling in this day and age.'' He called on New
Yorkers to stand up against the march's ``core of hatred.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Muhammad said his group had gone ``in good
faith'' to the city over the last year seeking permission for the
march. He said the group had shifted its focus for the march from
areas such as Central Park or Fifth Avenue to Harlem, in part
because it thought the city would not oppose a march in a black
area. ``The spirit of war that is in the air certainly did not
begin with us,'' Muhammad said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor repeated several times that the group had a right to
demonstrate, and said that he would defer to the corporation
counsel and the Police Department as to when, where and whether the
march would be permitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when you are filled with hate rhetoric, you do have a
right to demonstrate and protest to a certain extent,'' he said.
``But you don't have a right to do it any place you want, anywhere
you want, anytime you want.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials have offered two locations that they said could
accommodate large crowds _ Randalls Island and Van Cortlandt Park
in the Bronx _ as well as the alternate date of Sept. 19. Muhammad
has called the offer ``totally unacceptable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
