<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-CLASH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION HALT HOME SKID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution began the week hoping to
acquire Carlos Valderrama from Miami. But after that deal failed,
they placed their offense under the guidance of a lower-profile
Colombian, Oscar Alexander Pareja Gomez, and took a 3-0 victory
over San Jose Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Pareja brought a semblance of control and creativity to the
midfield as the Revolution snapped a Major League Soccer-record
eight-game home losing streak and moved within a point of the final
playoff spot in the Eastern Conference. The Revolution, with 19
points in 23 matches, visit Columbus Saturday, and fourth-place
Miami visits last-place Tampa Bay Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can win the next nine games, 3-0, we can say it was a
smart thing that Carlos decided it was too cold here,'' Revolution
coach Thomas Rongen said. ``They are all professionals and they are
paid to do a job. That's what we talked about. Valderrama was the
last thing on our mind and had no influence on the way we played.
We just came out to get the victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Revolution seemed focused and purposeful at the
start. Pareja crossed to Joe-Max Moore, whose header was tipped off
the bar by diving goalkeeper David Kramer in the fifth minute. The
Revolution continued to pressure, and Moore dribbled through two
defenders to set up a corner that Ivan McKinley converted in the
13th minute.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution soon reverted to their old habits and lost
control of midfield. But the Clash failed to capitalize, and Ian
Feuer made several spectacular stops, including tipping a 35-yard
Braeden Cloutier blast off the bar in the 26th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Moore converted a poor clearance against the run of play for a
2-0 lead in the 42d minute. And Raul Diaz Arce scored his 15th goal
of the season in the 89th minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed a win at home because we want to get into the
playoffs,'' said Pareja, a former Valderrama teammate. ``When I
have the ball at my feet, I can play football. Thomas wanted to use
me in that role because we had been working hard and not winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for a while, we lost communication and started doing what
we had been doing in previous games.''
</P>
<P>
   But if fortune had been against the Revolution since May 10,
when they took a 4-3 win over Tampa Bay at Foxboro Stadium, it was
with them in this match.
</P>
<P>
   Feuer, starting for the first time since July 15, remained
secure as San Jose pressured for most of the first half and at the
start of the second. And Paul Keegan, who started on the left side
of midfield, provided an extra threat in the penalty area and also
bolstered the defense with an energetic performance. The Diaz
Arce-Moore striking combination also showed promise.
</P>
<P>
   But without Pareja's poise, the Revolution would have had little
to build on for the final two months of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to find Oscar better,'' Rongen said. ``There was a
phase when we weren't maintaining possession, and we can't allow
that to happen against better teams because they will punish you
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pareja is accustomed to winning _ he helped Deportivo Cali take
the 1996 Dimayor title in Colombia and has played 11 times for the
national team _ but he had been playing a minor role with the
Revolution. But with Moore moving to striker and Edwin Gorter to
sweeper, the midfield has opened. And Wednesday night Pareja seized
the opportunity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
