<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-A'S-NYT </SLUG>
  
 STINGY KNUCKLER WINS ONE FOR A's  
 (bl)  
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The Oakland Athletics crawled away after
Tuesday's doubleheader totally demoralized, stunned at blowing a
four-run lead in the ninth inning of the second game, some of their
players declaring the New York Yankees to be the game's best team.
</P>
<P>
   But the Oakland knuckleballer Tom Candiotti salvaged the final
game of the four-game series, outdueling Hideki Irabu to beat the
Yankees, 3-1, on Wednesday night. Irabu allowed no hits in the
first four and one-third innings and only one hit in his first
seven and two-thirds innings, yet his record fell to 10-5.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees (80-29), who won 7 of their 10 games on this West
Coast trip, were scheduled to fly home after Wednesday night's
game. Friday they will return to Yankee Stadium, where they will
play 35 of their final 53 games.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu was on the verge of becoming only the 57th pitcher in
Yankees' history to pitch a one-hitter, but Rickey Henderson
slammed a solo home run in the eighth to clinch the Athletics'
victory. Candiotti allowed four hits and one walk, striking out
Darryl Strawberry, Tuesday's Yankee hero, on three soft
knuckleballs for the final out. With the victory secure, Candiotti
thrust his arms in the air as if he had just won the final game of
the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu had his best stuff since very early this season, when he
was leading the league in earned run average. His fastball
repeatedly reached 95 miles per hour on the radar gun _ Irabu would
pump it an extra two or three mph each time he threw with two
strikes. His splitter dove, his curveball bent sharply. He had
everything, and the Athletics were getting nothing early in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu retired the first 11 batters he faced, registering 3
strikeouts. In a season when the Yankees are re-inventing success,
it was natural for a mind to wander back to May 17, when David
Wells pitched a perfect game.
</P>
<P>
   That potential drama disappeared when Irabu walked Ben Grieve
with two outs in the fourth inning. Irabu struck out Matt Stairs in
an eight-pitch at-bat, which the Yankees' pitcher finished with a
95 mph fastball that violated the personal space of Stairs'
knuckles. Bu-Bu, as Derek Jeter nicknamed Irabu, had gone through
four innings without allowing a hit.
</P>
<P>
   But Irabu bounced a fastball off Ed Sprague's side to open the
fifth and, with a temporary loss of control, threw four consecutive
fastballs high and out of the strike zone to walk Mike Blowers.
Miguel Tejada bunted the runners to second and third.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu tried getting ahead of Rafael Bournigal with a first-pitch
fastball, but Bournigal smacked it to right field for Oakland's
first base hit. Sprague scored and Blowers stopped at third. When
A.J. Hinch flied to deep right, Blowers tagged and crossed home for
a 2-1 Oakland lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez had been responsible for that Yankee run. Leading
off the fifth inning, Martinez waited for a knuckleball to float
over the plate, then powered it far beyond the right-field wall.
Martinez has 18 homers, and it was the Yankees' 23rd home run of
the road trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees threatened in only two other innings. Jeter doubled
with one out in the first, before Paul O'Neill flied out and Bernie
Williams fouled out. O'Neill singled leading off the seventh, and
Williams also singled, with O'Neill stopping at third.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez struck out. Strawberry walked to load the bases before
Chad Curtis popped to shallow center and Jorge Posada flied to
medium-deep center, ending the inning.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ In need of a fresh pitcher, the Yankees called up the Queens
native MIKE JERZEMBECK and returned MIKE BUDDIE to Class AAA
Columbus. Jerzembeck, 26, was 3-7 with a 4.79 ERA for the Clippers.
He will pitch in long relief.
</P>
<P>
   _ ANDY PETTITTE, bothered by a strained muscle in his upper
back, will try to play catch Friday. If he feels all right, he will
start against the Kansas City Royals on Sunday. If not, then RAMIRO
MENDOZA will start in Pettitte's place and Yankees officials will
consider placing Pettitte on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Yankees are monitoring ORLANDO HERNANDEZ, too, who has
lost more than 10 pounds since joining the team in early June. His
diminished weight hasn't affected his performance _ he pitched a
three-hitter Monday _ or his workouts. Torre suspects that
Hernandez weighs himself immediately after workouts, and is
confident the Cuban right-hander be fine.
</P>
<P>
   _ JASON GIAMBI, knocked out when DEREK JETER accidentally kneed
him in the head in the ninth inning of a game Tuesday, was not in
the lineup Wednesday night. The Oakland first baseman said he had
no recollection of the play. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
