<SLUG> BC-NY-INTERNET-KIDPORN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 CHARGED WITH SENDING CHILD PORN VIA INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A state deputy correction warden and a man who said
he was a teacher were arrested Wednesday on charges that they
transmitted pornographic images of children over the Internet in
separate cases, state and local prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy warden, Thomas Burke, 47, who works in the prison
ward at Brooklyn's Kings County Hospital, faces a four-count
indictment for possessing and transmitting two graphic photos of
children engaged in sex acts with adults, said state Attorney
General Dennis Vacco.
</P>
<P>
   The other suspect, Anthony Wade, 30, faces 20 counts for
possessing and transmitting 10 such photos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vile images allegedly transmitted by these defendants
graphically depict young children who are being sexually abused by
adults,'' Vacco said. He added that he had ``no tolerance for those
engaged in the trafficking of child pornography and those who
perpetuate the abuse and exploitation of young children.''
</P>
<P>
   Both suspects are from Staten Island. Prosecutors said Wade
claimed to be a teacher of disabled children at a local school, but
he did not specify which one and city school officials said his
name could not be found in their employee database.
</P>
<P>
   Burke has been a correction officer for 25 years, said Thomas
Antenen, a spokesman for the Department of Correctional Services.
Burke was suspended without pay, pending the ruling on the charges
against him, Antenen said.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, the suspects each face up to seven years in prison
on each count and could be required to register with the local
authorities as sex offenders under ``Megan's Law'' after their
release, prosecutors said. Bail was set at $250,000 for both men.
</P>
<P>
   A message left on Wade's answering machine was not returned
Wednesday, and a woman who answered the telephone at Burke's home
hung up when called for comment. Burke's lawyer was out of the
country and could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants live less than 20 blocks from each other on
Staten Island but did not work in tandem, prosecutors said. Each
was brought to the attention of investigators after customers of
America Online, an Internet service provider, told the service that
they had received pornographic images from the defendants while
writing instant messages to other members in what are commonly
referred to as chat rooms, the prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the criminal complaints filed against the men, Wade
transmitted the explicit images from February to May, both to
members of the online service and later to undercover agents who
logged into the chat rooms. Burke transmitted explicit images twice
in January, the complaint said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
