<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0334 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-THROOP-LADN     08-06 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-THROOP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCAL TRAIL AFFORDS BREEZES, FOREST VIEW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA CANADA FLINTRIDGE, Calif. _ Trying to escape the heat? The
rarefied air of the San Gabriel Mountains' high country can usually
be counted on to do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even at altitudes approaching 9,000 feet, recent
temperatures have surpassed 80 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the lure of coolness _ be it perceived or actual _ is
overwhelming, as evidenced by weekend foot traffic between Dawson
and Islip saddles in the Angeles National Forest. Dozens of
trekkers were drawn on a recent Saturday to Throop Peak, Mount
Hawkins and the other landmarks that identify the 7{-mile one-way
route that requires two vehicles. (Count on about 8{ miles if side
trips to both peaks are conquered.)
</P>
<P>
   If you can bear to part with your air conditioner, expect these
certainties from the expedition: fresh air, shade and downhill most
of the way... if you follow this descent enthusiast's
recommendations. Throw in some breeze _ always a possibility on a
course that passes a benchmark dubbed Windy Gap _ and it's a cool
trip after all.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest option is to start out where the Angeles Crest
Highway meets Dawson Saddle Trail at an elevation of 7,900 feet and
trek to 6,575-foot Islip Saddle. But, remember, !ilal!most!off! of
the way is downhill. First you must tackle the ridge rising to the
crest that traverses nearly three-quarters of the route. As you
cover Dawson Saddle Trail's 900-foot rise in 2 miles, keep
repeating, ``What goes up must come down.''
</P>
<P>
   From the highway, an old trail zigzags immediately from the
parking area while a newer, wider and safer version leaves the
roadway 150 yards to the east. The choice is yours; they couple
about a quarter-mile up.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Taylor, an off-highway vehicle technician with Angeles
National Forest, suggests getting an early start to avoid the
hottest part of the day. He hit the dirt at 6 a.m. to shoot some
videotape for his children in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I send them clips whenever I can get out... just the limber
pines and the high country,'' Taylor said above the first extended
flat site on Dawson Saddle Trail.
</P>
<P>
   He warned of snow patches after slipping twice. It's not often
snowballs can be thrown in August outside of Los Angeles, but count
on it up here. Just ahead, visitors will also spot the first of
several appropriately named snow plants, a parasite that grows
alongside conifers. Its scarlet coloring contrasts the dull bark
and green needles of its hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Just when your gams start burning and you figure it's going to
be an uphill battle to the apex of 9,138-foot Throop Peak, the
trail begins to follow the contours of the peak's east shoulder.
The old route went straight up. Thankfully, the last trailblazers _
Boy Scouts in 1982 who logged 3,540 volunteer hours, according to
the guidebook ``101 Hikes in Southern California'' _ were more
sensible.
</P>
<P>
   At the 2-mile mark the course meets the crest (8,800 feet),
which is at once the Pacific Crest Trail, the Silver Moccasin Trail
and the northwestern boundary of the Sheep Mountain Wilderness.
Turn right and admire the white fir, Jeffrey pine and lodgepole
pine that line the path. Sharp eyes might spy the uncommon limber
pine.
</P>
<P>
   In less than a half-mile, a trail is scratched on the southwest
shoulder (8,925 feet) of Throop Peak. It is named after the founder
of Cal Tech, Amos G. Throop. The short scramble to the summit is a
precipitous but worthwhile side trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fantastic, from go to whoa _ the entire adventure,''
said Catherine Bailie of Engadine, Australia, who, upon bagging the
peak, was greeted by butterflies near the hiker's register. ``I've
never been this high. I'm getting an altitude buzz.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people dislike L.A. because they only see the city,
downtown and the intense heat and smog,'' Bailie said. ``I find it
incredible that you are an hour from the snow, the beach and the
desert.''
</P>
<P>
   Once rejoining the crest trail, the gentler detour to 8,850-foot
Mount Hawkins _ apparently named for a turn-of-the-century waitress
named Nellie Hawkins _ soon appears. As one hiker said, ``After
scaling Throop, you can't not do Hawkins.''
</P>
<P>
   With the outing's highlights behind you, continue the slow and
steady 4.2-mile decline northwest toward Islip Saddle. Hikers
quickly stumble upon a sign sandwiched between snow and pine cones
that flags Lily Spring (8,600 feet). A half-mile jog to the north
uncovers the only water in the excursion's first 5 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Talus, steep switchbacks, thick shade, the junction with the
trail to South Mount Hawkins (8,375 feet) and a sweeping view of
the San Gabriel Wilderness accent the 1.6 miles from the Lily
Spring sign to Windy Gap (7,575 feet), where pathways converge from
four directions.
</P>
<P>
   Take a lunch break to enjoy the refreshing blasts of air, then
tramp north less than a half-mile to the primitive but pristine
Little Jimmy Campground (7,475 feet); easily accessed Little Jimmy
Spring is situated midway. With picnic tables and rest rooms, the
camp is more luxurious than many along the Pacific Crest Trail.
</P>
<P>
   The next destination is a fire road in 1.2 miles (7,350 feet).
Between are long flat stretches, sugar pines, Windy Spring,
red-headed lizards and unwelcome highway sounds as the collision
with civilization becomes inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Cross the dirt road and the final mile _ though not the most
scenic portion of the trip _ exposes some interesting outcrops in
an abrupt ravine and the first glimpses of 8,214-foot Mount
Williamson.
</P>
<P>
   As the pines disperse and chaparral takes over, a splendid
meadow and the source of Cortelyou Spring marks the end of the
trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``If You're Going ...''
</P>
<P>
   The hike described here is a shuttle trip requiring two
vehicles. Drive both 40 miles northeast of La Canada Flintridge on
Angeles Crest Highway (2) to the Islip Saddle parking lot. (Look
for the first turnout to the left past the twin tunnels.)
</P>
<P>
   Park one car, load up everything and everybody into the second
rig and proceed up the highway 5{ miles to Dawson Saddle. Park and
begin your trek south to Throop Peak.
</P>
<P>
   National Forest parking passes are required; fees are $5 per day
or $30 per year. Camping is allowed; a free campfire permit is
necessary. Both documents can be obtained en route from the Angeles
National Forest's Clear Creek information center, located at the
junction of the Angeles Crest and Angeles Forest highways.
</P>
<P>
   Dogs on leashes are OK.
</P>
<P>
   The hike is found on the Crystal Lake 7.5-minute series
topographic map and Tom Harrison Cartography's ``Trail Map of the
Angeles High Country.''
</P>
<P>
   Allow five hours to complete the one-way route, longer if you
plan to scale Throop Peak and Mount Hawkins.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call the Arroyo Seco Ranger District,
(818) 790-1151.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
