<HEADER>
A0343 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-BEST-LADN     08-06 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-BEST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASTAIC LAKE MAINSTAY HOPES TO `SCHOOL' COMPETITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CASTAIC, Calif. _ His friends call bass angler Randy Best a
vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   Vrooo, vrooooooooooo.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the sound of him sucking up all the fish in the lake,''
said angling companion Darrel Dagdigian during a recent day on the
water at Castaic Lake.
</P>
<P>
   The vacuum will have to have all his accessories and talents in
high gear today as the BASS Masters Classic _ the world
championship of bass angling _ kicks off at High Rock Lake in
Lexington, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a winner-take-all tournament,'' said Best, 38, of Norco,
who is Southern California's sole representative at freshwater
fishing's Super Bowl. ``If you don't win, you're nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually the winner takes $100,000 of the Classic's $350,000
purse. Even the last-place finisher in the field of 46 earns
$4,000. But Best's point is not lost: Only the champion is
remembered.
</P>
<P>
   And the tall and slender, sun-chafed angler with the brownish
mane and mustache streaked with gray _ ``That's kids,'' explained
the father of two _ predicts his name will be on the lips of the
120,000 fans officials expect to attend the three-day event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be first or worst,'' said Best as he pitched a
customized spider jig toward a bank along Castaic's northwest arm.
He got a feel for what the bite will be like at High Rock Lake
during the Classic's practice session July 5-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get the area I have selected pretty much to myself _ or
at least the key spots _ and get a good start on them, I at least
have a chance of doing real well or possibly winning,'' said Best,
his piercing blue eyes never diverting from the line. ``But if it's
an area that I have to share with a few other competitors, my
chances will get lessened quite a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   His trip East is the farthest he has traveled to compete, and
the bite at the lake is notoriously picky. Anyone who gets a
five-bass limit even one day might take the title after the final
fish is weighed Saturday afternoon in front of the vocal crowd at
Greensboro Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   A reaction-bite specialist whose go-to lure is a spinnerbait,
Best plans to fish under docks and around brush using ``hardware''
to lure larger bass prone to pounce on fast-moving forage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will avoid the finesse fishing,'' said celebrated regional
bass-circuit angler Mike Folkestad, 57, of Yorba Linda, who Best
credits as his mentor. ``And I don't think the finesse fishing will
win that tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has a good chance of winning. He just has to get a
feel, get a bite going.''
</P>
<P>
   However, if the bass only react to plastic worms and other
slower applications that compose the finesse baits _ which
typically get bit more frequently but by smaller fish _ Best could
be in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my biggest downfalls is changing up and scraping out
the worm fish,'' Best said. ``I hang on and try to break the bank
every time (with reaction baits).''
</P>
<P>
   Best sped his bass boat to another Castaic fishing hole, dipped
the trolling motor into the lake and tossed a new jig,
 &UR; !ital! &LR; zing &UR; !off! &LR; . It splashed down between questions. After
boating a half-dozen ``dinks,'' he finally hooked a bigger
largemouth bass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nicer fish, nicer fish,'' an onlooker said as Best hooked up
on a bucketmouth that would probably have gone over 2 pounds had he
managed to get it to the boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a long-distance release. I don't like touching the
fish,'' he joshed.
</P>
<P>
   The jokes and ribbing are all part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest key with fishing is it's meant to be fun,'' said
Best, who for 18 years has juggled his passion for bass circuits
with operating a poolside brick and tiling subcontracting business.
``If it's not fun, you don't belong in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he scaled back his routine of 10 or so tournaments a
year to four to spend more time with his family and ``keep it
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a career to me; it's a hobby,'' he said. ``Family
life is way more important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Best will be a decided underdog at the 28th annual Classic, as
will the other four anglers who qualified via the Western
Invitational circuit _ the inaugural series staged on the West
Coast by the Bass Anglers Sportsman Society, or B.A.S.S., the
Montgomery, Ala., fishing and education group that runs the Classic
and its various circuits.
</P>
<P>
   However, his low profile among fishing-household names like
Jimmy Houston and Rick Clunn may work to his advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a tournament of this caliber, you have spectators
following you around (on the water), and there are television
boats, and that is a hindrance. It's unbelievable,'' Best said. ``I
probably won't have to worry about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Best's 11-year-old son, Brandon, is star struck.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son loves to fish. He's real excited because he gets to go
meet the true pros _ the Roland Martins and the Kevin VanDams. I
guess I'm just the tagalong for him,'' said Best, who will be
joined in North Carolina by Brandon, his daughter, Brittany, 8, and
his wife, Carolyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, after he named off about 10 names, I said, `They are
all going to be there, but just remember one thing: Your pop can
beat them.' I told him that and he said, `Oh, Dad.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bass angler Dagdigian also likes Best's chances, because he has
the attitude it takes to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very confident,'' said Dagdigian, a 44-year-old La Mirada
dentist. ``I wouldn't say he was a braggart, but he doesn't have
any problem fishing behind anybody _ going right through that same
area someone else just went through and catching his fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Best would rather be known as a nice guy, not a good angler.
Still, the title of BASS Masters Classic Champion has a certain
ring to it.
</P>
<P>
   Vrooo, vrooooooooooo.
</P>
<P>
   BASS MASTERS CLASSIC
</P>
<P>
   When: Today through Saturday. &QL; 
Where: High Rock Lake, Lexington, N.C. &QL; 
Purse: $350,000 (winner's share: $100,000). &QL; 
Field: 46 anglers. &QL; 
The big names: Rick Clunn, George Cochran, Mark Davis, Davy Hite,
Jimmy Houston, Gary Klein, Roland Martin, Kevin VanDam. &QL; 
Defending champ: Dion Hibdon. &QL; 
Most Classic wins: 4, by Clunn. &QL; 
Largest Classic bass: 8 pound, 9 ounces, Ricky Green, 1976. &QL; 
Scoring and rules: Each day anglers may weigh five bass measuring
at least 14 inches. The fisherman with the heaviest total for three
days wins. Only artificial lures are permitted. All fish are
released alive; anglers are penalized 4 ounces for each dead bass
brought to the scales. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 0232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 02:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0346 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-BOOKS-LADN     08-06 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-BOOKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISH STORIES BY WHICH TO LEARN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Overviews of a few recent angling titles, from
all-around trolling techniques to an education in fly-rodding for
trout to a guide for Eastern Sierra day-trippers:
</P>
<P>
   The latest addition to the ``Hunting &AMP; Fishing Library'' _ an
encyclopedia of how-to titles for the outdoorsman _ offers a
potpourri of tidbits for the beginning fly-angler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fly Fishing for Trout in Streams'' (Cowles Creative
Publishing, $19.95) takes the uninitiated from the parts of a rod
(cigar grip vs. half-wells grip) to photography tips (natural light
_ the most attractive _ is best early or late in the day).
</P>
<P>
   The latter recommendation proves essential to this book, for its
most striking element is the artwork. One can earn an entire
education by studying the stellar step-by-step photographs and
graphics, and their captions. In the ``Subsurface Fly-Fishing
Techniques'' chapter, for example, a photo illustration solves the
mystery of the ``wet-fly swing.'' To cover as much area as possible
from one spot, cast across the current, mend the line to control
the speed of the fly and let the fly ``swing'' downstream until it
begins to rise to the surface. Lengthen each subsequent cast 1 to 3
feet until the water is worked thoroughly. Move to a new post and
repeat the process.
</P>
<P>
   The shots of trout foods, their life cycles and their imitations
are remarkably telling.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the text is often just as illustrative. Consider:
``Even though some live insects skitter across the surface of the
water, they rarely leave a visible wake. The wake left by a
dragging dry fly, by comparison, is very obvious to trout, and such
a presentation will rarely draw a strike.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not quite understood why the 176-page book is included in
the publishing house's ``Freshwater Angler'' series instead of its
``Complete Fly Fisherman'' sequence. Perhaps the thinking is that
novices who wish to continue the recreation will want to graduate
to the purely fly-angling category. Whatever the marketing
strategy, ``Fly Fishing for Trout in Streams'' is certain to pique
interests. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though written with little imagination and far from polished in
presentation, ``Eastern Sierra Fishing Guide for Day Hikers''
(self-published by author John Barbier, $14.95) offers just enough
enticement and factual details to lure the angler away from Highway
395.
</P>
<P>
   The 120 pages have directions to dozens of backcountry lakes
that can be found by treading from 10 minutes to three hours beyond
the blacktop. Tackle and technique suggestions are woven into basic
descriptions of destinations, hiking access and fish life.
Primitive maps point to good fishing spots. There's room to keep an
extensive log.
</P>
<P>
   And it all fits into the glove box, offering just the solution
when the boats are all rented at Crowley and the cabins and camp
sites are all booked at Convict. Barbier, who hails from San
Marcos, makes a strong argument for getting away from the Eastern
Sierra's intensely popular roadside lakes: ``Only 5 percent of the
waters in the region are accessible by vehicle, but 95 percent of
the anglers concentrate on those waters. Of course, this means
uncrowded conditions and plenty of hungry trout for those willing
to walk a bit.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you feel ready to advance your trolling methods to the next
level, check out ``The Troller's Handbook'' (Frank Amato
Publications, $12.95).
</P>
<P>
   The 92 pages in small print by Livermore author and photographer
Ray Rychnovsky largely cater to those anglers who already know a
thing or two about enticing fish by using the movement of a boat.
</P>
<P>
   Especially helpful are details on lead-core line and down
riggers. Both are under-utilized practices that allow baits to be
trolled deeper and more easily. But both can be complicated.
Rychnovsky unravels the formulas with straightforward descriptions
of gear and usage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want a light pull from a fish to release the clip so even
a small-hooked fish will pull the line from the down rigger,'' he
notes.
</P>
<P>
   In other chapters, however, such as ``Basic Trolling Depth,''
his explanations are less clear. And while billed as
``easy-to-use,'' the graphs employed to portray his points might
scare off landlubbers or anyone else who doesn't have the
background in engineering that Rychnovsky has.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 0236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
