<HEADER>
A0348 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-TOURNEY-LADN     08-06 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-TOURNEY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVER-THE-HILL-GANG ENDS 2-YEAR SKID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENTURA, Calif. _ On a day when momentum shifted like currents,
contestants could sense that the team with the ``hottest sticks''
on the last stop would capture the third Big Bass Shoot Out between
two of the area's most visible angling clubs.
</P>
<P>
   When the Sea Biscuit anchored Sunday for the eighth and final
time off the south side of Santa Cruz Island, the nine members
representing the Los Angeles Rod &AMP; Reel Club made the most of it.
Down by five fish in a contest of total weight of calico bass
landed, the L.A. squad out-fished the San Fernando Valley Saltwater
Fisherman's team 22 bass to 11 to capture the coveted Shoot Out
trophy for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest part of winning today was the relief of not losing
again,'' said LARRC's Joel Zide of Sherman Oaks, one of eight
designated baitfish anglers from both teams who held positions at
the stern. ``Our talent came through.''
</P>
<P>
   Granada Hills' Rob DiGioia of the losing SFVSF squad said
momentum's fickle pendulum swung L.A.'s way to end the day: ``They
hung in there. Maybe we got a little complacent; I could feel it
slipping away.''
</P>
<P>
   When the fish counts and weight totals were tallied, the
scorecard read: Los Angeles _ 44 bass, 86{ pounds; San Fernando
Valley _ 38 bass, 75 pounds, 15 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   LARRC had lost the annual interclub event in 1996 by the
thinnest of margins _ less than the weight of a single bass _ and
last year in a blowout of proportions club anglers would rather
forget. Tarzana's Dan Felger, a charter member of the 48-year-old
L.A. coterie, summed up the triumph in simple terms: ``Wonderful,
fantastic, finally.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was the delicate wording in the current club
newsletter that spurred the Los Angeles team, ``We hope to end our
unblemished record of no wins and two losses in this series.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was the inspirational words of LARRC's team captain
Michael Grossman of Tarzana, spoken in a hushed huddle after his
platoon made a spirited run to cut an early four-fish lead by the
Valley club to 16-15. ``You've got to keep fishing. We've made some
ground on them,'' Grossman said following the second stopover, on
the island's west end. ``Never quit. You've got to have your lines
in the water.''
</P>
<P>
   The score was knotted at 20 bass when the party boat motored
away from the sixth fishing hole. On the lucky seventh whistle-stop
_ off the island's east end _ the Valley caught fire and registered
seven bass in a row before L.A. boated a pair to close the gap to
27-22 entering the final round.
</P>
<P>
   There was desperation in the faces of the L.A. squad, but its
anglers worked feverishly to overcome adversity. Half of its yield
came here as L.A. doubled the opposition's catch for the stop.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley's outspoken team captain, Dimitri Peros of Westlake
Village, was at a surprising loss to explain his club's sudden
letdown. ``No comment,'' he said. ``I plead the Fifth.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Robin Gist of Simi Valley was more candid: ``We got
spanked. It was their turn to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 0238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
