<HEADER>
A0353 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RANGERS-BLUEJAYS-TEX     08-06 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANGERS-BLUE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS SCORE LATE KNOCKOUT
</HEADLINE>
 JAYS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ National League-style baseball invaded The
Ballpark in Arlington for eight innings Wednesday night. Then good
old American League muscle took over in the bottom of the ninth and
the Texas Rangers stole a thriller from the Toronto Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez, winning a gripping battle against reliever Randy
Myers, belted a game-tying home run leading off the inning, and
Mike Simms later followed with the winning single, allowing the
Rangers to rally for a 4-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Walks worked by Will Clark and Todd Zeile in the ninth also
proved crucial for the Rangers, who earned their fourth consecutive
victory and opened up a 11/2-game lead over the Anaheim Angels in
the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got that grind attitude right now,'' Simms said. ``You
score one run, we're going to come back and score two. Everybody's
doing a great job, and everybody is doing their part. It's not just
one or two guys, it's all 25 guys. If we keep playing like this, I
like our chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers starter Esteban Loaiza did his part, limiting the Blue
Jays to two runs on five hits through eight innings. But he left
with a 2-2 tie.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays took the lead in the ninth. Jose Cruz Jr. bounced
a single through the middle off reliever John Wetteland, pinch
runner Juan Samuel stole second and Samuel scored when Felipe
Crespo bounced a two-out single into right field.
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza has a 3.62 earned-run average in four starts with the
Rangers since being acquired from the Pittsburgh Pirates but is
still looking for his first American League victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't have any luck getting that first victory, but it
was still a great game,'' Loaiza said. ``I'm throwing the ball
great and feeling great.''
</P>
<P>
   With Blue Jays starter Kelvim Escobar matching Loaiza, both
teams had to manufacture their runs using walks, stolen bases,
sacrifice flies and hitting behind the runner.
</P>
<P>
   Then Gonzalez flexed his muscles in the ninth and changed
everything.
</P>
<P>
   Myers, like most pitchers, tried to pitch Gonzalez with the
usual assortment of soft stuff. But Gonzalez worked the count full
and fouled off a couple of pitches before Myers tried to surprise
him with an inside fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like they use to say with Hank Aaron,'' Rangers manager
Johnny Oates said. ``Trying to slip a fastball by him is like
trying to slip the sun past a rooster.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez wasn't surprised and smashed the fastball 415 feet into
the left-field seats to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking to go deep,'' Gonzalez said. ``I was looking for
something close that I could hit out of the yard. The fastball was
right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers, struggling with his footing on the mound, then walked
Clark. Ivan Rodriguez lined out to center, but Zeile also worked a
walk, putting runners on first and second.
</P>
<P>
   Myers then asked for the grounds crew to work the mound, while
Simms, pinch-hitting for Lee Stevens, waited patiently in the
on-deck circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked Royce \RClayton\S, `Is this like icing the kicker?' ''
Simms said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clay was really really damp and slippery,'' Myers said.
``I couldn't follow through or drive the way I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   The mound work didn't help. Myers got ahead 1-2 in the count but
Simms then ripped a pitch into the left-field corner, scoring pinch
runner Luis Alicea with the game winning run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 0246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
