<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 03:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0378 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     08-06 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS ON A ROLL, BUT ANGELS NOT ROLLING OVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ This will come as a shock to those of you who
have been in a state of euphoria since general manager Doug ``Deals
'R Us'' Melvin turned the baseball world on its ear Friday, but the
1998 American League West flag has yet to be raised over The
Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   It's true. I did a personal wall-to-wall search Wednesday night
and couldn't find hide nor hair of it, which also seemed to
surprise club president Tom Schieffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``What?'' Schieffer said, rolling his eyes. ``They're actually
going to make us play the last 50 games?''
</P>
<P>
   At least I think that's what he said. His tongue was planted so
firmly in cheek, it was hard to tell.
</P>
<P>
   Schieffer also confirmed the worst. There has been no official
communique from the Anaheim Angels _ or the Mariners or A's for
that matter _ conceding the division championship to the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   They will not, common sense and logic to the contrary, roll over
and play dead.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, in fact, are sticking to the Rangers like a grass
burr in the seat of their trousers. Irritating as it may be, they
show absolutely no signs of going away.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has the American League faxed the Rangers indicating that,
due to Melvin's megadeals, they have already been seeded into the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, those lines that snaked around The Ballpark on Tuesday
weren't fans in line for playoff tickets, but for Pugsly the Beanie
Baby (No, that's not Pudge Rodriguez's new nickname).
</P>
<P>
   ``I still say what I said a hundred games ago _ this thing is
going down to the last week of the season,'' manager Johnny Oates
said.
</P>
<P>
   Oh my. Best stock up on the Zantac now. Just remembering what
September was like in '96 is enough to raise the blood pressure 20
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we've got a chance to pull away but I don't think it's
going to happen, It just doesn't happen this late in the year.
We're going to play better and \Rthe Angels\S are going to play
better.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be especially difficult for the Rangers to stretch their
West Division lead _ or maybe even to hold onto it _ over the next
2 1/2 weeks. Tonight kicks off a 17-game stretch against the Red
Sox (6), Indians (4) and Yankees (7).
</P>
<P>
   You may gulp at your leisure.
</P>
<P>
   Over the same period, the Angels play the White Sox (5), Tigers
(5) and Blue Jays (7).
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   It gets better at the end of the month and into September when
it's the Rangers taking on the White Sox, Tigers, Twins and Royals
while the Angels are dealing with the Yankees, Red Sox and Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Survive the next 2 1/2 weeks and Melvin may have won himself an
executive-of-the-year award for his trade deadline deals...``if''
Oates and the Rangers can take it home from here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing you learn is never assume anything,'' Oates
said. ``I like our ballclub but we've still got to go out and play
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, if we went by what all the people said was going to
happen, we'd be in third place, about 10 to 12 games back. But I
don't pay any attention to that because I know we've got to come
out here and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing nods and pensive ``harumphs'' from the press box
pundits, who have proclaimed the Rangers division favorites because
of four key additions, don't faze Oates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't put any stock in that stuff,'' said Oates, proving
once again that he's no dummy. ``I know we've got a better ballclub
than we did last week... better defense, better starting pitching.
We're deeper and we've got a little more consistent offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we still have to play these last 50 games.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin, in the meantime, is working the phones again, trying to
find a left-hander for the bullpen. Lefties are hitting .296
against Eric Gunderson, and Scott Bailes is on the disabled list
with bursitis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some left-handed hitters coming up we need to get
out,'' Oates said, ``and Doug's working on it. But right now, if a
guy can even wipe his nose left-handed, there's no way he can get
through waivers.''
</P>
<P>
   The excitement level, Oates conceded, has been cranked up a few
notches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time of year, when you're in the hunt, is when it gets
exciting,'' he said. ``This is what you started out back in the
middle of February working for. You don't want to be 25 games out
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five games up would be nice but, like those concession
letters, that's just wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   The last 12 games of the season? Five are with the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Best buckle up tight. The next seven weeks may get a little
hairy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 0312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
