<P>
   &UR; Innovative therapies and better health habits have helped to
substantialy reduce new cancer cases and deaths. &LR;   &UR; Now doctors are
about to test a new drug on humans, a treatment that controls
tumors in laboratory mice. With this development, hopes are soaring
among researchers that years of laboratory and clinical work are
finally paying off. To evaluate whether science has indeed made
strides against the dreaded disease, Globe health/science reporters
Richard Saltus and Larry Tye have prepared a five-part series,
``Cancer: Turning the Corner.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SCI-CANCER-I-SPCL (Undated) _ Frustratingly slow advances in
the ``war on cancer'' are starting to pay off in dramatically
better treatment and prevention. (3 takes) PHOTOS (2), GRAPHIC
</P>
