<SLUG> BC-TOY-TESTERS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kindergartners test toys for Disney
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE WORTH, Fla. _ Here's the toy that should top your Christmas
shopping list:
</P>
<P>
   Stop My Hiccups Dil.
</P>
<P>
   Who says so?
</P>
<P>
   The kids at the KinderCare center on Jog Road who are testing 45
toys _ some of them not on the market yet _ for Disney's FamilyFun
magazine's annual Toy of the Year issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cries and sucks his binky,'' explains Rachel Edelson, 7,
who neglected to mention that Dil belches authoritatively as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says `I love you,' '' added 8-year-old Ashley Tapper, and
says ``Mama'' and ``Goodbye,'' too.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of dolls do that. But this doll is modeled on a Rugrats
character who isn't even in the hugely successful Nickelodeon
cartoon show yet.
</P>
<P>
   He's Dillon, Tommy's little brother, who will debut in a Rugrats
Thanksgiving movie. But the kids know that already. Dil, made by
Mattel, will cost $40 when he's released later this month.
</P>
<P>
   The 3- to 4-year-olds and 5- to 7-year-olds are part of 1,000
children in eight child care centers across the country who are
trying out the toys for several weeks. Next week, they choose their
favorites in various categories.
</P>
<P>
   For the seventh year, FamilyFun will publish the winners in 23
age groups and categories in its November issue, out in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents need some advance information on what to buy. Who
better to ask than kids?'' said Executive Editor John Adolph.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine has a good track record, choosing Tickle Me Elmo as
a top choice in 1996 and Sleep 'N Snore Ernie last year. Could the
T.O.Y. awards be creating a market?
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with our 1.2 million circulation, we wouldn't generate
that kind of groundswell (as Elmo caused),'' Adolph said.
</P>
<P>
   Also popular is the Godzilla Rampage game in which children
fashion Play-Doh figures. ``The fun part is when you get to squish
the people's cars and trucks (with Godzilla),'' said Lauren
Brackman, 6.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for filling out forms and interviewing the children
on their preferences, the Lake Worth KinderCare keeps the toys.
</P>
<P>
   What to leave on the shelf? Walk 'N Talk Big Bird.
</P>
<P>
   ``They liked him the first day _ his shoes and clothes come off
_ but ever since he's been standing over there against the wall,''
said child care worker Jennifer Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
