r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD07-COX     08-06 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woodworking information more readily available
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A query on the Internet brings to mind the days not so long ago
when information on fine woodworking was nearly impossible to find.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm relatively new and inexperienced to woodworking,'' it
asks. ``Can anyone recommend a magazine which will be instructive
and understandable?''
</P>
<P>
   I believe the 1980s marked the woodworking boom. Before then you
got your information out of Popular Mechanics and a rather dismal,
hard-to-find magazine whose name escapes me. I'm not sure it's
still around.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a visit to the magazine section of a major bookstore will
display at least half a dozen excellent periodicals.
</P>
<P>
   I've always believed that Fine Woodworking magazine and its
publisher, the Taunton Press, was largely responsible for the boom.
In addition to the magazine, the firm started publishing
well-written, beautifully illustrated books on design and
technique.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine and books were a revelation to most of us.
Virtually the only books available before the revolution were
wretched technical school textbooks on how to make commercial
cabinets as cheaply as possible and weekend-hobbyist books of
projects that weren't worth the fir plywood of which they were
supposed to be made.
</P>
<P>
   Fine Woodworking ruled the roost for several years. Its only
competition for a while was a subscription-only, no-advertising
publication called Woodsmith. Woodsmith was, and I assume still is,
a no-nonsense but never pedestrian magazine presenting projects
with plans and detailed articles on how to execute them. While the
design of the projects was rarely remarkable, it was seldom bad,
either.
</P>
<P>
   I dropped my subscription to the magazine, and to a companion
publication called Shop Notes, when I began running out of space.
From a look at WoodSmith's Web site --
www.augusthome.com/woodsmth.htm -- it may have changed hands, but
when I see it on newsstands it looks exactly as it did several
years ago. It's still punched out for a three-ring binder, and it
still carries no ads.
</P>
<P>
   Fine Woodworking has not fared so well. It has shrunk somewhat
from its glory days, and run through enough editors to staff
several other magazines -- particularly its chief competitor,
American Woodworker. I've never quite understood why so many
woodworkers get upset with Fine Woodworking. Many traditionalists,
of course, reel with disgust at the avant garde designs it often
presents. A truly lovely offshoot concerning itself entirely with
furniture design died after a year.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, I still find it the most satisfying of all the
magazines, even if it does cost a rather staggering $7 at the
newsstand.
</P>
<P>
   American Woodworker has grown from just another wannabe to an
outstanding publication, somehow seeming to satisfy many of the
amateurs that Fine Woodworking does not, and at half the newsstand
price. It has retreaded several of Fine Woodworking's original
stars, especially one-time editor John Kelsey and British
woodworker-teacher-writer Ian Kirby -- who set up shop briefly in
Atlanta about 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise the two magazines share a lot of writers, like the
ebullient Hungarian master craftsman Frank Klausz.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that American Woodworker does well that Fine
Woodworking rarely ever attempted is reviewing tools. It does this
frankly and honestly, always trying to get as broad an overview of
a particular kind of tool as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Better Homes and Gardens Wood has gone from a jumped-up Popular
Mechanics to a very good middle-of-the-road magazine. Woodshop News
is an industry newspaper geared largely to small-shop professionals
and, as such, is generally of interest to the proficient amateur.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   We want to hear from you but are unable to acknowledge every
message.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
