<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CANCER-EARLY-SPCL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY DETECTION KEEPING CANCER RATES IN CHECK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spotting cancer before it spreads is the next best thing to
preventing it, and doctors are getting better at that sort of early
detection.
</P>
<P>
   In June the US Food and Drug Administration approved the
ImageChecker, a computerized system that rechecks a radiologist's
review of mammograms and possibly catches signs of breast tumors
that the eye missed. High-tech digital mammograms and magnetic
resonance imaging are further refining detection, giving doctors
pictures that let them pick out cancers that otherwise would remain
hidden, and weeding out false positive readings.
</P>
<P>
   Breast cancer deaths fell by 1.7 percent a year from 1990 to
1995, ``and if we can find cancers that we're missing now, we
potentially can lower that another 25 percent,'' says Dr. Daniel B.
Kopans, who runs the breast imaging program at Massachusetts
General Hospital. But for that to happen, he adds, ``women should
definitely come in once a year for screening.''
</P>
<P>
   Early detection also is having a growing impact on colon cancer.
Tests for blood in the stool can signal the presence of polyps or
tumors, while optical rectal scopes can pinpoint suspicious-looking
cells. And researchers are using CAT scans to take multiple images
of the colon, creating a ``virtual colonoscopy'' that avoids the
need to insert an instrument.
</P>
<P>
   Additional screening tests are available for cancer of the
pelvis, oral cavity, prostate, skin, thyroid, testicles, and other
organs. Most should be done with increasing frequency as a patient
ages, or if the patient has a family history of that cancer. Some
tests, like the one for skin cancer, involve a physical examination
that patients can do themselves; others, such as for cervical
cancer, involve procedures that require medical personnel and a
laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Screening is sure to become even easier and more precise as it
capitalizes on recent advances in the laboratory. ``Most tests now
are based on anatomy and subtle differences between normal and
aberrant, like looking for blood in the stool,'' says Dr. Barnett
S. Kramer, deputy director for prevention at the National Cancer
Institute. ``But they're crude because you have to wait for the
polyps or cancers to bleed. Since the tumors are so close to the
surface of the gut, perhaps the next generation of early detection
is to look for the DNA signatures of cells and look for molecular
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll try to fish out molecular needles in the haystack.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 0941EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0566 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPLIT-TOWN07-COX     08-06 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPLIT-TOWN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A downtown that straddles two states finds unity and prosperity
in division
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 9: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   McCaysville, Ga.-Copperhill, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   There's a new line in town.
</P>
<P>
   You see it slice through the Hometown Foods IGA and its parking
lot, then continue diagonally across the street before scaling the
yellow brick building that houses the Copper Emporium furniture
store.
</P>
<P>
   The long blue line isn't just the talk of the town; it's the
talk of two states.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the Copper Basin, known now for tourism and white-water
rafting instead of its once-flourishing copper industry, the North
Georgia town of McCaysville (population 1,062) shares a downtown
with Copperhill, Tenn. (501). And they share the blue line, rich in
irony: Closely approximating the border separating the two states,
it was painted to unify the two municipalities and to draw the
attention of a new wave of visitors brought in on an excursion
train from nearby Blue Ridge, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Goss, who with his wife, Cricket, owns the IGA, calls the
line ``a point-of-interest line, not a dividing line. It reminds us
that we have common problems and concerns and that we have to work
together.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bob Myers tells it, the idea for the line surfaced a few
months ago when a ``spontaneous group'' of about a dozen area
residents got together at a coffee shop and began talking about
``the common misconception that the Toccoa River is the border''
between Georgia and Tennessee. Actually, the state line slices
across the river, which is called the Toccoa in Georgia and the
Ocoee in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Not only would a line clear up the confusion about the border,
the group believed, but it also would be ``an oddity that people
could relate to, something to have fun with,'' recalls Myers, a
computer consultant.
</P>
<P>
   So, in early June and mostly at night to avoid traffic, he and
others, including artists Rebecca Williams and Marilou Knight,
began painting the block-long line, using the same kind of paint
that marks handicap parking spaces. Their efforts were temporarily
foiled when the parking lot was resurfaced, but the group recently
began restriping the lot, tackling the job on a sultry Saturday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Goss is a longtime line man, having painted one in the store lot
several years ago, amid the influx of visitors for Olympic events
on the Ocoee. And he's also a veteran of the two-state business
world, noting with a laugh that ``we have the privilege of paying
taxes in both states.''
</P>
<P>
   How's the line working? It's fun, doing its job of getting
attention and bringing in visitors, say business owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of visitors come in and want to know where the line
is,'' reports Kay Brown, co-owner with daughter Becky Morgan, of
the Colonial House, which sells antiques, jewelry and collectibles.
``They love to straddle the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Jack, adds that many people ``come in and say, `We
walked all the way from Tennessee to get to your place.'''
</P>
<P>
   The line was a hit one recent Saturday when the Blue Ridge
Scenic Railway train roared in and unloaded passengers for an
hourlong visit before making the 13-mile trip back to Blue Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   Several people took turns straddling the line while friends and
family recorded the event on film. And Lillian Thomason of Canton,
Ga., played with her young granddaughter, Maria Allison, holding
hands across the blue stripe. ``We're a long way apart,'' Thomason
joked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was quite an experience, being in two states at once.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there is something profoundly moving about this
seemingly simple act. In this vast country, where the sheer
magnitude of place can diminish a mere human, the ability to touch
two states at once somehow makes a person feel more in scale, more
a part of the great big space.
</P>
<P>
   The new blue line, which so keenly looks to the future, also
recalls the past.
</P>
<P>
   Just about everybody around here tells the story of how the
official state border -- the one that the blue line closely traces
-- is bogus because surveyors back in the 1800s spent too much time
sampling from a moonshine still they had wandered upon.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that's the reason for the mistaken survey or just a good
story, Georgia rightly has contended that its boundary with
Tennessee should lie farther north -- at the 35th parallel, as
specified in the laws of both states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Correcting the boundary would shift a mile-wide strip of south
Chattanooga and most of Copperhill to Georgia,'' says Edwin
Jackson, co-author with Marion Hemperley of ``Georgia's Boundaries:
The Shaping of a State,'' published in 1993 by the University of
Georgia's Carl Vinson Institute of Government.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not likely to happen, says Jackson, a faculty member at
the institute. ``Although suit could be filed in the U.S. Supreme
Court, rulings of that court in similar situations suggest that a
boundary long recognized and accepted will stand, even if later
found to have been drawn in error.''
</P>
<P>
   The state line has worked in strange ways. Consider Marion
``Cap'' Hamby, a barrel-chested, big-voiced copper plant foreman
who rose to political power in the 1920s and lived in a house on
the border. His daughter-in-law, Luneta Hamby, has a newspaper
clipping from the Feb. 11, 1944, Copper City Advance, which
reports:
</P>
<P>
   ``Marion Hamby has served, at different times, as the mayor of
McCaysville and the mayor of Copperhill without moving his
residence. He was mentioned in `Ripley's Believe It or Not' several
years ago as the only man who had served as mayor in two cities, in
two different states, while living in the same house.'' (The
article notes that the law at that time allowed residents on the
line ``to choose the state of their choice.'')
</P>
<P>
   Strolling around town on a recent steamy morning, Luneta Hamby,
history lover and onetime tour guide, said that shopping and living
and dining and attending school in two states always has been part
of everyday life for area residents, and that now the blue line
brings that duality alive for tourists. ``I think it's great.''
</P>
<P>
   And a big change. The 54-year-old article notes, ``For all
practical purposes the line is disregarded and the north side of
the river is called Copperhill and south of the river is known as
McCaysville. Or more simply, the Georgia side and the Tennessee
side.''
</P>
<P>
   Comes now the blue line.
</P>
<P>
   It's already highly visible, and organizers want to make it even
more notable; plans call for extending the line for several blocks
-- over the tops of five buildings. ``It'll be fun for small
airplanes,'' says Bob Myers. ``We hope to become a landmark they
could use for points of reference. And the line could be part of a
sightseeing trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus it seems that, for this blue line, the sky's the limit.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
