<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 09:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0567 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CANCER-V-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     08-06 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CANCER-V-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... of the risk.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Diet and obesity account for another 30 or so percent of cancer
deaths. While the onslaught of studies on diet is confusing, the
1996 Harvard Report on Cancer Prevention offers some clearcut
advice: Eat less animal fat. Reduce consumption of red meat to once
a week or less. Eat more fruits and vegetables, a minimum of five
servings a day. Don't blacken or char meat, fish, or chicken. And
don't consume too much alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   With alcohol, knowing just how much is too much is difficult, as
it is with many health recommendations. The Harvard report, which
distilled the latest findings in the field, provides a bit more
guidance, at least for women. Two drinks per day, it says, probably
increases the risk of breast cancer by 25 percent, and women with a
family history of the disease should avoid alcohol entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, says Dr. David Hunter, director of the Harvard Center
for Cancer Prevention, that warning must be tempered by knowledge
that ``while alcohol almost certainly increases the risk of breast
cancer, it decreases the risk of cardiovascular disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Exercise carries fewer caveats, since obesity is a major risk
factor for heart disease and diabetes, as well as for cancers of
the cervix, uterus, ovary, endometrium, and gallbladder in women,
and of the colon and prostate in men. Women who are more than 35
percent above ideal body weight have a 55 percent higher chance of
developing those cancers, while overweight men stand a 40 percent
greater risk of obesity-sensitive cancers. And there's new evidence
that preventing weight gain also lowers the risk of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Other critical contributors to cancer, the Harvard report says,
are dangerous workplaces, a family history of cancer, viruses and
other infectious agents, pollution, and too much exposure to the
sun.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, the most exciting development has been
the prospect of developing cancer-preventing drugs. Last spring
came the news that tamoxifen, now a standard treatment for older
victims of breast cancer, could save 20,000 more lives a year
worldwide. Taken just after surgery for five years, it halved the
recurrence rate over 10 years, along with the risk of developing a
new cancer in the other breast. But two comparable studies from
Europe last month produced inconclusive results, leading many
scientists to conclude that it is too early to know whether the
drug really does prevent breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Prevention advocates insist that much more research must be done
on tamoxifen and other potential ways to head off the disease. NCI
officials counter that, since 1993, spending on prevention and
control programs has more than doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter, meanwhile, says it's critical that ``we not get into a
prevention-or-cure debate if we can help it. We need to concentrate
on prevention because there are some proven methods there and a lot
more we can do. But we have to recognize that if someone has a
diagnosis of cancer, it's too late for prevention.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Wide array of treatments
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What cancer patients often want as much as anything is help in
deciding which conventional treatments might work for them and,
even harder, which unconventional therapies they should try.
</P>
<P>
   The list of touted therapies is overwhelming, from Chinese herbs
to shark's cartilage, tai chi to homeopathy, biofeedback and
acupuncture. And oncologists generally aren't much help sifting
through the possibilities to see which make sense and how they
might interact with mainstream medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually every patient I have inquires about alternative
therapies,'' says Dr. Thomas J. Lynch Jr., who runs the thoracic
oncology unit at Mass. General. ``I try to tell them that there's
far more we don't know than we do. If the therapy lets them gain
some sense of control, it can have a positive impact.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all most cancer doctors can offer. They say they want to
support anything that makes a patient feel better, but don't have
enough scientific evidence to endorse a particular approach. For
many medical doctors, it's also a matter of overcoming a historic
distrust of alternative therapists, one that sees them peddling an
unproven art, even as many alternative healers see MDs as promoting
toxic, ineffective, and expensive conventional treatments.
</P>
<P>
   That gap is beginning to be bridged, however, largely in
response to an insistence by patients that their doctors and other
healers start working together.
</P>
<P>
   One sign of detente involves vocabulary. Rather than being
described as ``alternative'' or ``unconventional,'' nontraditional
techniques are being called ``complementary,'' which puts the
emphasis on collaboration rather than differentiation. And rather
than operating from offices that are isolated physically and
politically from the mainstream, they are being invited in to
hospitals and research institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Another sign of the growing good will was a first-ever meeting
last month outside Washington, where hundreds of high-level
conventional and complementary therapists gathered to discuss the
roles that herbalism, meditation, and other nonmainstream therapies
can play in treating cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is not so much, will conventional medicine pay
attention to specific therapies? The real question is, are we going
to develop an integrated way of working with patients who have
cancer?'' says Dr. James S. Gordon, who organized the conference
and runs the Center for Mind-Body Medicine in Washington. ``The
public demands that we all work together. Ordinary decency demands
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Wittes, director of cancer treatment and diagnosis at
the NCI, also struck a conciliatory note at the conference, but he
didn't shy away from the hard work that lies ahead before
mainstream doctors will endorse nontraditional treatments: ``If I
have to give up much of what I know about chemistry and physics,
then the evidence that it does work will have to be
incontrovertible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
