<HEADER>
A0570 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIRE-GEL07-COX     08-06 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-GEL07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fireproof gel overnight hero
 &HT;    By John Murawski
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM HARBOR, Fla. _ John Bartlett coated his hand with the milky
lotion he was trying to sell and turned a 3,000-degree,
propane-torch flame on it.
</P>
<P>
   Not a knuckle hair was singed.
</P>
<P>
   It's the type of stunt the Palm Beach County firefighter has
performed hundreds of times across the nation in the past four
years to promote his invention, Barricade Fire Blocking Gel, a
slimy material that's mixed with water and sprayed on buildings and
underbrush.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the product remained relatively unknown outside firefighting
circles until Bartlett and business partner Bruce Hill, also a Palm
Beach County firefighter, used it on 20 homes in Flagler County
during the recent wildfires there. They coated the homes and
retreated. When the fires passed and they returned, the homes were
still there.
</P>
<P>
   Barricade become an overnight hero.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Bartlett and his Jupiter-based Fire Protection Inc.
have been featured on CBS and ABC news and written up in newspapers
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   And the company has had more sales and inquiries than ever. The
men are talking to more distributors and sending out videos and
information packets instead of spending all their time at trade
shows, although they still give their share of demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday they demonstrated the fireproof gel to several dozen
Tampa-area firefighters on a fire road in Brooker Creek Preserve in
Pinellas County.
</P>
<P>
   They torched plywood partially coated with with the gel, leaving
one side charred black and the other unscathed. They set palmetto
scrub on fire in an area demarcated by Barricade. The fire stopped
dead in its tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This stuff is truly impressive,'' said Phil Travis, an
environmental specialist with the Pinellas County Department of
Environmental Management. ``You can steer fire with it. You can run
along side of fire and divert it. You can run it around things. You
can steer it into a lake.''
</P>
<P>
   Barricade is currently being bought by Martin, Flagler and
Putnam counties, and fire departments in California and Oregon,
Hill said. The U.S. Army has also used it to protect buildings when
burning down old barracks.
</P>
<P>
   But what the men really want to do is build up the capability to
sell Barricade on a mass scale in hardware stores and perhaps on
QVC, the home-shopping channel.
</P>
<P>
   They are a little worried that there's nothing keeping
competitors from making their own slime. While they have patents
pending, a well-financed chemical company could make a similar
product by modifying enough molecules to make it distinct. The
product could be cheaper than Barricade and backed by a national
marketing strategy that Bartlett and Hill could not match.
</P>
<P>
   But Bartlett, 44, of Jupiter and Hill, 41, of Palm Beach
Gardens, say they're not overly concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're two firefighters. We know what we're doing. We've got
the diaper-story connection. We've had great successes in (Flagler
County),'' Hill said. ``We are the product. It's not the gel.''
</P>
<P>
   The creamy gel retards fire by trapping water up to 700 times
its own weight. Bartlett happened on the idea in 1993, after
putting out a trash fire in Jupiter and noticing that disposable
baby diapers hadn't burned.
</P>
<P>
   Fire Protection has spent about $500,000 developing Barricade.
Most of the money has come from Bartlett and his father and has
been used to attend fire shows to demonstrate Barricade.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a million layers of polymer particles, and each layer
protects the layer underneath,'' Bartlett said. ``It allows us to
'stick' the water where we want.''
</P>
<P>
   Barricade must be mixed with water in order to work. As it is
watered down, Barricade becomes more viscous. After use, it can be
hosed off with water. It's biodegradable and environmentally safe,
according to Bartlett, because it's similar to the material in baby
diapers.
</P>
<P>
   Once sprayed on, Barricade will last six hours or more before it
begins to evaporate, allowing the user to apply the goo and clear
out well before a fire is dangerously close. Class A foam, by
comparison, lasts about 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing whatever we can so people can see we're not a
bunch of charlatans,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Fire Protection created a gallon-sized dispenser that
hooks up to an ordinary garden hose. It resembles a plastic
anti-freeze jug with a hose and nozzle, and sells for $189 -- $35
of which is for one gallon of the goo and the rest for the
container. It takes about three gallons to coat an average-sized
residential home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're building our infrastructure, getting the marketing
people and getting warehouse space,'' Hill said. ``But when this
thing starts hitting the market, you're going to get a Monsanto and
other competitors out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
