r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLORIDA-DROPOUTS07-OC     08-06 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-DROPOUTS07-OC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bad news for school dropouts means better news for parents
 &HT;    By Stephanie Desmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ To see a play at the Kravis Center or to
take soil samples from the Lake Worth Lagoon, Florida, high school
students need a permission slip signed by mom, dad or a legal
stand-in.
</P>
<P>
   But to drop out of school? No signature required.
</P>
<P>
   Until now.
</P>
<P>
   Starting this fall, a Florida student can't drop out of school _
even at age 16 _ until a parent or guardian signs off on the
decision. The student also must sign a statement saying he knows
he'll probably earn less and have a greater chance of being
unemployed as a high school dropout.
</P>
<P>
   Both requirements are part of a law passed by the Florida
Legislature this spring designed to make students understand the
consequences of leaving school early _ and maybe help them change
their minds. No one can force them to comply, but students who
aren't officially withdrawn from school risk being picked up as
truants or even losing driving privileges.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will give everybody a chance to take a deep breath and
think this through,'' said David Mosrie, a state education
official.
</P>
<P>
   But it may not be that easy.
</P>
<P>
   Many teens who drop out don't tell school officials; they simply
disappear, often with hundreds of dollars worth of textbooks and
uniforms or equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just stop showing up,'' said David Cantley, principal at
Lake Worth High School.
</P>
<P>
   Forest Hill High School Principal Carlos Rosello said the school
tries to contact parents of missing kids _ through letters and
phone calls _ often with no success.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had a chance to even talk to a kid or a parent, I could
easily cut down on dropouts,'' he said. ``I don't know how I'm
going to get anyone to sign anything.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1996-97 school year, 2,737 of 23,827 students in
grades 10 through 12 dropped out of the county's schools. The year
before, 1,639 of 22,412 students in those grades were dropouts.
</P>
<P>
   School district officials were officially notified of the
changed law this week. Forms need to be created and the procedure
will have to be written into school board policy, meaning it will
take time before schools can start seeking signatures.
</P>
<P>
   There is no penalty for parents or students who don't comply.
``Since we're not an armed camp, they can walk out and not come
back,'' concedes Ron Armstrong, director of pupil personnel
services for the school district.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said police may pick up students who don't withdraw
properly for being truant, which means a trip to the West Palm
Beach Truancy Center and a call home to be picked up. These
unofficial dropouts also risk losing driving privileges because the
district is required to report habitual truants to motor vehicle
officials, Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   State and district officials said they hope to make this an
opportunity to counsel more students to stay in school _ or to
pursue alternative schooling.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing out the pain dropouts can feel in their wallets may
help. Students will be told that dropouts typically earn one-third
less over a lifetime compared with high school graduates, that they
are twice as likely to be unemployed and their chances of going to
jail are three to nine times greater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some kids drop out because they want the jobs (immediately),
whether it's for a car or clothes,'' said Associate Superintendent
Cynthia Pino. ``What it's an attempt to do is tell them it's not a
good long-term decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
