<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You can't fight the IRS
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The newspaper headline said President Clinton had signed a bill
to make the Internal Revenue Service simpler and fairer. I'm afraid
it comes too late for me, and the lady who does most of the
arithmetic at our house.
</P>
<P>
   Since she remains in the work force, supplementing my Social
Security check in order to keep me up in the style to which I have
become accustomed, we still have to ante up. Being self-employed,
she has no payroll deductions. She has to write a check.
</P>
<P>
   Last April 15 we couldn't lay hands on a K-1 form having to do
with a disastrous investment in a well-known Atlanta hotel, an
investment made when I was gainfully employed and had a few dollars
available for sucker schemes.
</P>
<P>
   We had to ask the IRS for an extension. When you apply for an
extension, you have to send in approximately what you owe. Sammy
Freeman, our friendly CPA, told us we'd have to cough up $7,000. We
sent the IRS a check for $7,000.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later we got a notice from the IRS informing us we
owed $6,479, including interest and penalties. About the same time,
while attempting to balance our checkbook, she discovered we had an
extra $6,300 in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   After half a morning of punching telephone buttons and listening
to elevator music, she finally got through to a real person. The
real person said in depositing our $7,000 check, an IRS clerk had
left off a zero. Instead of $7,000, only $700 got punched in.
``Happens all the time with the IRS,'' said the bank person.
</P>
<P>
   When the bank caught the error, it followed the rules. It
notified the IRS of its error and sent $6,300 to the Federal
Reserve Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the wonders of electronic banking we get canceled
checks in our monthly statements only if we request them. She asked
the bank for a photostatic copy of our canceled $7,000 check so she
could send it to the IRS as proof of payment.
</P>
<P>
   The bank person said we'd have it within two days. Two weeks
passed, and no check. She spent another half morning punching
telephone buttons and listening to elevator music. When she finally
got to talk to a real person she was told the bank had no record of
our request for a canceled check. Since the IRS was making ominous
threats, she drove to the bank to plead her case. She got the copy
of the canceled check, and the bank's explanation of the IRS
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Anxious to keep the IRS at arm's length, we issued power of
attorney to Freeman. By certified mail, he sent the IRS: 1. Our
bank statement reflecting the IRS error. 2. The bank's explanation
of the error. 3. The location of the $6,300 in the Federal Reserve
Bank. 4. A photostatic copy of the canceled $7,000 check.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later we got a notice from the IRS informing us that
if we did not pay delinquent taxes immediately they were going to
seize our checking account and file federal liens on any and all of
our property.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy immediately called the IRS to again inform them that we
don't owe any money. After checking our file, the IRS person
informed him there was no record of having received any money from
us, and no record of hearing from either him, or from us. As they
talked, Sammy was holding in his hand the little green card from
the post office showing where the IRS had received, and signed for,
his certified letter.
</P>
<P>
   He pleaded until they promised not to seize our bank account and
put liens on all our property. We were not heartened to read a
newspaper story reporting that, according to its own internal
audit, the IRS improperly seized property from taxpayers in more
than 25 percent of cases studied in fiscal 1997. Sure enough, we
soon received another friendly letter. With continuing penalties
and interest, we now owe $6,519. 83. The letter said pay
immediately, or we'll seize your paycheck, bank account, auto and
other property.
</P>
<P>
   This may signal the end of a checkered column-writing career. To
my knowledge, the Journal-Constitution has never had a
correspondent domiciled in a federal penitentiary, and I don't know
if they would make an exception in my case.
</P>
<P>
   Going way back
</P>
<P>
   It was 1925, not 1929.
</P>
<P>
   After my mention of the record drought year of 1929 a couple of
weeks ago, I got a call from my Uncle Donald Harp.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're four years off,'' he said. ``The dry year was 1925.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course it was. I must have been thinking of another calamity,
the stock market crash of 1929.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Griffin pointed out that '29 actually was a wet year.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters and columnists depend on careful copy editors like
Sharon Bailey to pick up their fumbles. But how would even Sharon
Bailey know whether it was wet or dry in 1925?
</P>
<P>
   If newspapers are going to let senile people write columns, they
ought to hire alert senior citizens to keep them from making stupid
errors.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
