<HEADER>
A0574 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOLS-ROAST07-COX     08-06 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-ROAST07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Schools anticipate a steamy first month
 &HT;    By Andy Alford
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ While most students are stocking up on school
supplies, Austin school bus driver Ida Collins is freezing bottles
of water in preparation for the first day of school.
</P>
<P>
   Collins will take the frozen bottles with her on her twice-daily
drives and drink the water as it melts. She'll also soak a bandana
or towel in ice water to wear around her neck. And now and again,
she'll get a little relief from a parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are so sweet,'' Collins said. ``They'll bring you
iced tea or lemonade or water.'' Collins hopes it will all work to
help her beat the heat that has throttled Central Texas all summer.
When school starts next week, the Austin area may still be in the
clutches of a heat wave that has produced a marathon of
near-record, triple-digit days.
</P>
<P>
   Local meteorologists say it probably won't cool off until
September. Until then, students will trudge to and from school
beneath blazing skies, swelter on school buses without air
conditioning and sweat their way through outdoor athletic
practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that kind of summer,'' said Larry Lewis, an area
superintendent for the Austin school district. He said overtaxed
air conditioners at several Austin schools have quit this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working feverishly to get them back on,'' he said.
``And it's expected that they will be on when school starts.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers at Murchison Middle School held their breath as
maintenance staff labored until 5 a.m. Wednesday to get their air
conditioning back up at the Northwest Austin school. The cooling
unit failed while the school was being rewired and the unit had to
be overhauled.
</P>
<P>
   ``So from this day forward we are up and running and doing
fine,'' Murchison Principal Lynda Redler said.
</P>
<P>
   Some physical education teachers and athletic coaches have
scheduled exercise indoors when possible. When athletes must take
to the field, many coaches have scheduled sports activities for
early morning or in the evening to dodge the afternoon heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good idea to have your water bottle with you. My dad
insists that I bring it,'' said Jennifer Pohl, who was on the
Westlake High track at 8 a.m. Wednesday. Pohl is a West Ridge
eighth-grade hurdler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early morning is not too bad, but around mid-day it starts to
get pretty tough,'' said Hays Junior High Principal Dan Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said Hays coaches and physical trainers take care to keep
football players hydrated with juice, water and Gatorade, as many
youngsters aren't used to toting the full 30-pound armament of
football padding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be competitive, but that's not everything,'' Murphy
said. ``We have to look at the interest of the kids first _ it's
going to be a pretty long season, and they'll be around a lot
longer if we don't kill them first.''
</P>
<P>
   Some elementary schools are considering indoor or early morning
recesses. Karen Sisler, principal of Faubion Elementary in the
Leander school district, said teachers may bring coolers of ice
water to recess because the school has no outside water fountains.
</P>
<P>
   Faubion worked around the smoky haze alerts at the end of the
last school year, Sisler said. ``This will probably be the same
kind of thing. We'll probably have a hot weather room for kids _
just like for cold days and rainy days when parents request that
they don't go outside _ and have puzzles and board games.''
</P>
<P>
   After school, some students will have to hope for a quick ride
home. Newer buses have tinted windows and white roofs to reflect
the sun's rays. But most school buses, which can hold up to 72
children, don't come with air conditioning. Only those equipped to
carry special education students, some of whom can be susceptible
to seizures when it's hot, have air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We use the famous 40-50 air conditioning system: You roll all
40 windows down and drive 50 miles per hour,'' joked Fred Filley,
Austin's assistant director of pupil transportation. ``It's a never
ending battle with the heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
