<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 09:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0575 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHIPWRECK07-COX     08-06 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHIPWRECK07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    La Salle shipwreck ID runs aground
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ A centuries-old shipwreck whose discovery last February
off the Texas coast excited historians is not the long-lost
flagship of French explorer La Salle as initially thought, state
officials announced recently.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it may be a Spanish warship 100 years younger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The artifacts that were initially recovered from the site
looked to be of the right era for this to have been the l'Aimable,
but subsequent research shows it is not,'' said Jim Bruseth,
director of antiquities protection for the Texas Historical
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The l'Aimable is still the crown jewel, and it's still
missing. We intend to continue looking for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the initial theory that the wreck was l'Aimable
(pronounced luh-MAB-luh) unraveled in recent weeks as state divers
recovered additional artifacts from the site, and tests conducted
at a Texas A&AMP;M University lab confirmed they were much more recent
than Rene Robert Cavelier, Sieur de La Salle.
</P>
<P>
   Bruseth said copper sheathing was found on remnants of the hull,
a shipbuilding technique that dates to the mid-1700s, long after La
Salle's ship sank in 1685.
</P>
<P>
   A musket initially thought to be French in origin and from La
Salle's era has since been determined to be a perfect match for a
1752 Spanish firearm, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bayonets and other firearms recovered from the shipwreck site in
recent weeks are characteristic of the mid- to late-1700s, Bruseth
said. And an 18-pound cannonball was found on board, much heavier
than one La Salle's ship would have carried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've answered the question of whether this is
L'Aimable. It's not,'' Bruseth said. ``It appears to be a Spanish
warship. and several Spanish ships ran aground in this area during
that period. The Spanish were continuing to patrol this area.''
</P>
<P>
   The wreck was discovered Feb. 23 by divers from the the
privately funded National Underwater and Marine Agency (NUMA), who
identified it as l'Aimable based on X-rays of a flintlock and a
musket found amid the ship's remains _ both identified as French,
from the mid-1600s.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gronquist, an Austin attorney who is president of the
maritime history group, said he thinks the historical commission is
right. ``We're disappointed, but what this means is that l'Aimable
is still out there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Best-selling author Clive Cussler, who founded NUMA, said
Wednesday he is ready to renew the search for l'Aimable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state has looked for it for 17 years and has not been able
to find it,'' he said. ``I know we can. If they'll only let us come
back in.''
</P>
<P>
   Historical accounts show l'Aimable ran aground in February 1685
while trying to enter Matagorda Bay, which some historians think La
Salle mistook for the mouth of the Mississippi River.
</P>
<P>
   The wreckage was found just outside Cavallo Pass, the narrow
passageway that connects the Gulf of Mexico with Matagorda Bay near
the present day town of Port O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   L'Aimable, a broad-hulled cargo vessel, was among four ships
that carried La Salle and more than 300 colonists to the New World
in 1684 to establish a French colony at the mouth of the
Mississippi and to lay claim to the vast adjacent lands for France.
</P>
<P>
   The wreck of a smaller ship in La Salle's fleet, La Belle, was
located about three years ago by state archaeologists in Matagorda
Bay. La Belle ran aground in January 1686, when a storm blew it
across the bay into shallow water near the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   After La Salle landed in Texas, he was met with a hostile
climate, belligerent natives and disease. A handful of people led
by La Salle left on foot in 1687 and headed inland, hoping to find
the Mississippi. But he subsequently wound up being murdered by his
own men.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun County Judge Howard Hartzog, who earlier hailed the
discovery of La Salle's missing ship as a world-class find, said he
was disappointed by the new finding _ but remains hopeful the
Spanish wreck will yield important artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it's a Spanish ship, it's still pretty old. And it's
still significant in the history of this area,'' Hartzog said.
``The site should be fully investigated.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruseth said state officials have no plans to undertake a major
archaeology project at the wreck site _ something Hartzog said he
intends to press for.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't want to do it, I'll find someone who will,'' he
said. ``Whoever's ship this was, we need to know as much as we can
about it. It's part of our history.''
</P>
<P>
   Historical Commission officials said attempts will continue to
identify the ship, using the 50 to 75 other artifacts recovered
from the site _ from pig iron and stones that were used as ballast
to a piece of ``bar stock'' _ an hourglass-shaped piece of metal
that was fired from cannons to destroy another ship's rigging.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bruseth rates the chance at doing so at ``about 50-50. ``If
it's not one of the wrecks that was documented, we may never
know.''
</P>
<P>
   After the wreck site was discovered, Gov. George W. Bush
approved a grant of $132,000 to pay for underwater research.
Bruseth said less than $10,000 was spent before the determination
was made that the ship was not l'Aimable.
</P>
<P>
   Hartzog said he hopes that Wednesday's anouncement will not slow
the search for l'Aimable, an effort that state and private divers
have unsuccessfully pursued for almost three decades. Curtis
Tunnell, executive director of the state historical commission,
said it will not.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more than 36 historic shipwrecks in the Matagorda
Bay vicinity,'' he said. ``(The agency) intends to continue working
with NUMA, Calhoun and Matagorda counties to investigate the area
in an ongoing effort to locate the Aimable.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
