<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 09:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0576 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CANCER-IV-SPCL-AR     08-06 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CANCER-IV-SPCL-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PIONEER'S PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Graphics (2) are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The media hounds him a bit less. Calls from desperate cancer
patients have subsided _ now a mere hundred or so daily, down from
over 1,000 a day during what some staff members call ``Folkman
Week.''
</P>
<P>
   That was in mid-May, when an overwrought newspaper story about
the potential of two novel cancer drugs from Dr. Judah Folkman's
laboratory at Children's Hospital touched off a media frenzy that's
still resonating.
</P>
<P>
   The drugs, while stunningly effective in mice, have yet to be
tested in a single human, and won't be until sometime next year.
Nevertheless, cancer patients everywhere wanted them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The publicity ended up causing difficulties,'' says Dr. Elise
Kohn at the National Cancer Institute. ``I've been inundated with
calls from patients demanding to be treated with these `miracle'
drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Folkman, who pioneered the radical strategy of cutting off
the blood supply of tumors instead of attacking the cancer
directly, is easing back into his routine while acknowledging that
the premature publicity has complicated his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to work under the spotlight,'' said Folkman in a
rare interview. While confident that the two drugs _ angiostatin
and endostatin _ will bring something new and important to cancer
therapy, he frets about the unrealistically high expectations that
have now been created.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there are failures'' in early tests of drugs, even
those that eventually prove valuable, Folkman says. ``And,'' he
worries, ``the failures are magnified (by critics) to mean the
whole field won't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Folkman is all too aware of potential criticism, having endured
it for 30 years during his lonely crusade to show that tumors, in
order to grow, must recruit new blood vessels from the tissues
around them, and that attacking this blood supply could halt or
shrink cancers.
</P>
<P>
   Now he has been largely vindicated: Angiogenesis, the process of
forming new blood vessels from existing ones, is accepted as a
crucial step in cancer, and he and others have found a long list of
substances, including angiostatin and endostatin, that block
angiogenesis.
</P>
<P>
   In mice, a combination of angiostatin and endostatin has shrunk
large lung cancers to invisibility _ and without apparent side
effects.
</P>
<P>
   While time has not yet proven Folkman correct that angiogenesis
inhibitors will write a new chapter in cancer treatment, many
believe that day is coming.
</P>
<P>
   Starving tumors with angiogenesis blockers is ``probably the
most exciting anticancer therapy out there right now,'' says Robert
Weinberg, a leading cancer researcher at the Whitehead Institute in
Cambridge. But, ``there are some very substantial problems'' in
turning the findings into useful therapies, among them difficulty
manufacturing the complicated proteins in quantitites large enough
to test _ let alone market _ if they prove to be useful in humans.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, ``my judgment is that it's going to work
eventually,'' Weinberg says, predicting that the drugs will enter
clinical use in five to seven years.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 angiogenesis inhibitors are already in early-stage
clinical trials, according to the Boston-based Angiogenesis
Foundation. But they are first-generation drugs, far less potent
than angiostatin and endostatin, discovered in 1994 and 1995. The
current tests aren't expected to yield dramatic results, because,
as with all new drugs, they are being tested first in the sickest
cancer patients. In fact, the preliminary results have been mixed:
Some of the inhibitors have caused dramatic improvement in a small
number of patients, while others have had little effect.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Trials swamped with volunteers
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since the wave of publicity in May, however, even these trials
of less potent angiogenesis inhibitors have been swamped with more
volunteers than they can take. Folkman and others agonize over
having to tell desperate patients that until one or more of these
drugs is proven safe and effective, access to them will be
extremely limited.
</P>
<P>
   Angiostatin and endostatin are being hurried as quickly as
possible toward their first tests in humans by scientists at the
National Cancer Institute and a Maryland biotech company, EntreMed,
Inc., which has licensed the drugs for development from Children's
Hospital in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly is hope that in a year to 18 months there will
be enough of this material'' to begin testing in a small number of
patients, says Dr. Richard Klausner, director of the National
Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Holaday, CEO of EntreMed, said recently that the
company's goal is to match the speed record for moving a drug from
initial discovery to approval for widespread use _ about seven
years. That would put endostatin and angiostatin on the market in
about five years if they prove effective in people, but this is
predicated on ``zero error and flawless execution'' in
manufacturing and winning regulatory approval, Holaday
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Under the relentless scrutiny of patients, doctors, and the
stock market, the odyssey of endostatin and angiostatin may turn
into one of the most closely-watched chapters yet in the war on
cancer. And these two potent angiogenesis inhibitors are not the
end of the line _ Folkman and his colleagues have recently found
two more inhibitors, one of them named vasculostatin; neither has
even been tested yet in mice.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is still bemused by the recent media attention,
Folkman says the recent hubbub has had ``one positive effect: I've
had many calls from senior people at drug companies across the
world saying they've considered establishing angiogenesis units but
thought it was too early. Now they're asking if it's too late.''
</P>
<P>
   The roots of this enterprise lie in many years of painstaking
research by Folkman and his colleagues, who now occupy a large
laboratory in the Enders research building at Children's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Folkman, whose single-minded focus on angiogenesis grew out of
research he did in the Navy and later as a surgeon at Children's,
came to believe that a solid tumor couldn't grow without getting
the body to extend new blood vessels to nourish it.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't sound like a radical idea now, but Folkman's hunch
was long rejected.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
