<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Advice to Joe Clinton
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just about everybody seems to think President Clinton should
confess, though they are foggy about exactly what to, and since I'm
as ignorant as they are about what really went on, I figure I'm
qualified to put my two cents' worth in, too. So here's what I
think the president should do. I wish he'd call up Kenneth Starr
and say:
</P>
<P>
   You know, you've been saying _ and scoring all sorts of points
with the courts by saying it _ that the president is just like any
other Joe. He gets no legal slack. Anybody wants to sue him, sue
away. Anyone he talks to who isn't his wife or personal attorney,
haul 'em in and given 'em the third degree. I guess any cop on the
beat can ticket the whole shebang if a presidential motorcade pulls
out of the White House without a parade permit.
</P>
<P>
   Well, if I'm just Joe Citizen with a swank address, then I'm no
less than Joe Citizen, either. So I've been thinking and I've
decided not to testify to your grand jury after all. You've been
out to get me for four years. Nobody in their right mind would walk
into a trap like that, and most prosecutors wouldn't even bother
asking them to. You think you can get away with it because it would
be too politically embarrassing for me to refuse.
</P>
<P>
   I'm refusing. And if you issue a subpoena, as far as I'm
concerned you can shove it in the nearest pigeonhole because I'm
gonna pay no more attention to it than I do those fliers for
Chinese takeout. Try forcing the matter and I'll take the Fifth
Amendment, just as any other Joe would do in the circumstances. In
fact, as any lawyer who bills more than $1.98 an hour would insist
they do.
</P>
<P>
   Whitewater was one thing. It was old news and small potatoes,
but I signed off on that investigation myself, figuring you'd run
though the paperwork, say your say and close up shop. But nooooo.
Somehow, you wound up spending two years investigating Vince
Foster's death after three law enforcement agencies already had,
before finally deciding Vince really killed himself and neither
Hillary nor I had shot him or had hired some gunsel to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Then you got yourself into so-called Travelgate and Filegate,
two screw-ups early in my administration that had zero to do with
any constitutional issues of the office. And then, then!, you
started asking around about women I've known and, like a lunatic
oil spot, finally managed to spread yourself into the Paula Jones
case and come up with Monica Lewinsky as a Judas goat.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny, frankly, my personal life is none of your damn business.
Actually, come to think of it, bloodhound breath, you're fired.
Write up what you've got to say about Whitewater and the -gates,
file your report and close your boiler room. I'm shutting down your
racket.
</P>
<P>
   I'll take my chances with a real jury of Joes and Janes just
like me and see what they make of a case about disputed testimony
that was ruled irrelevant in a civil case the judge threw out as
groundless, a case based now on stuff you wrung out of a young
woman by threatening to send her and her mom to prison _ her mom! _
if she didn't change her tune.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect a regular Joe like me might do just fine with other
regular folks on that one.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 0944EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 09:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0582 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CANCER-IV-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     08-06 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CANCER-IV-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... long rejected.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I think part of it was other peoples' perception that
angiogenesis was going to be a trivial consequence'' of other
events in a tumor's progression, says Douglas Hanahan, a researcher
at the University of California at San Francisco and longtime
Folkman collaborator.
</P>
<P>
   Because the scientific means to study blood-vessel formation in
detail didn't exist, Folkman was many years in proving his case.
But in time, he and others were able to show that angiogenesis is a
crucial, and early, step in a tumor's career. If the tumor doesn't
succeed in recruiting new blood-vessel support, it is doomed to
remain ``in situ'' _ a small, harmless knot of cells unable to
invade healthy tissue &UR;  &LR; or metastasize.
</P>
<P>
   To understand why angiogenesis is so crucial for tumor growth,
imagine a small town beside a large highway that has no exit
nearby. The few houses and a store or two can get along fine with
this arrangement. But if the town wants to grow, there's a
logistical problem. As the town expands in all directions, trucks
can't make deliveries to the center of town. Without a network of
new roads connecting the highway and the buildings, the middle of
town will figuratively die.
</P>
<P>
   And so it is with tumors. To grow beyond the size of a pea,
Folkman proposed, the tumor has to induce nearby blood vessels to
grow new capillaries _ vessels thinner than a hair _ to reach into
and entwine the cancer cells. This is angiogenesis, and it has
recently been shown to occur not only in the growth of solid tumors
but even in leukemia, a blood cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Angiogenesis is a normal process that also occurs during
development and childhood, and in adults in menstruation and
wound-healing. The question Folkman asked was, how do tumors induce
the body to send out new capillaries? He reasoned that tumors must
send some sort of chemical signal _ and he proved correct.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, he and colleagues in his laboratory
discovered what would be the first of a number of ``angiogenic''
substances that serve as ``on'' signals for new capillary growth. A
few years later, he found the first of numerous inhibitors of
angiogenesis _ ``off'' signals in the process. It appears the body,
and tumors themselves, make these competing substances as part of
an on-off system to regulate normal new blood-vessel growth. Most
recently, Folkman and others have discovered that a tumor's
angiogenic switch goes on when the pro-angiogenesis signals
outweigh the inhibitory ones.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a momentous discovery that tied together angiogenesis
and the burgeoning field of cancer genetics _ the finding by Noel
Bouck at Northwestern University Medical School that a
tumor-suppressing gene called P53, which normally keeps cancer from
arising, works in part by switching on an inhibitor of
angiogenesis. A defective P53 permits angiogenesis to take place,
making cancer more likely to develop.
</P>
<P>
   The list of different substances that block angiogenesis is
already long, and growing. It includes:
</P>
<P>
   _Thalidomide, the infamous morning-sickness drug that caused
severe birth defects in the early '60s;
</P>
<P>
   _A form of interferon and a form of interleukin, both substances
in the immune system;
</P>
<P>
   _Angiostatin and endostatin. Discovered by Dr. Michael O'Reilly
in Folkman's laboratory, they are fragments of larger proteins
found in the body;
</P>
<P>
   _Monoclonal antibodies made in the lab to block a chemical
messenger called Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor (VEGF), which
induces endothelial cells to divide and form new vessels.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows why tumors produce substances that inhibit
angiogenesis as well as others that promote it. But the phenomenon
may explain why metastases, cancer cells that have escaped the
original tumor and lodged elsewhere in the body, often grow rapidly
after the primary tumor is removed. &UR;  &LR; Whatever the explanation, it
is good fortune for cancer therapy that these potent vessel
growth-blockers exist. And their discovery has reversed years of
disbelief that dogged Folkman: He is now considered almost a
shoo-in for a Nobel Prize, particularly if the angiogenesis
inhibitors have a major impact on cancer treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judah is a visionary, and as such, very few people understood
the message he was trying to project,'' says Isaiah (Josh) Fidler,
a cell biologist at the M.D. Anderson Cancer Institute in Houston
who also does research on angiogenesis.
</P>
<P>
   It was just last fall that Folkman reported results of the most
dramatic experiment of his career. Using a combination of
angiostatin and endostatin, he and his colleagues were able to
shrink large tumors and mestastases in mice to the point of
undetectability, and they remained microscopic indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the drugs didn't lose their effect over time. That was
an unprecedented result.
</P>
<P>
   While Folkman and the rest of the world await the first human
trials of angiostatin and endostatin, researchers are developing
numerous twists on the basic theme.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, an experiment reported in the journal Nature
Genetics showed that angiostatin combined with radiation treatment
shrank tumors in mice far more effectively than either agent alone.
Folkman hailed the work as laying the foundation for a new form of
radiation treatment that could be more potent without causing
additional side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Folkman and others continue to emphasize that none of this
good news has meaning for human patients until the drugs prove
themselves in clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   The first-generation, relatively weak inhibitors that have made
it into human testing haven't performed like miracle drugs, but
there have been some tantalizing results.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, a team from M.D. Anderson Cancer Institute reported
that a woman with metastatic cervical cancer who received an
angiogenesis blocker called TNP-470 for 22 months in 1995 went into
complete remission of her disease _ and suffered few side effects.
Such remissions are rare.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraging responses to angiogenesis inhibitors have also been
seen in trials carried out at the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute and
other centers.
</P>
<P>
   In some brain tumor patients, the drugs shrank or halted the
cancer for many months. ``There are some long-term survivors, but
we don't know what this means,'' because of the small numbers of
cases, says Dr. Howard Fine, a brain tumor specialist at
Dana-Farber.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs of anticancer effect in some cases, he says,
which is ``proof of principle that using an entirely different
approach to cancer therapy we can actually cause regression of
human cancer. That's exciting to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fine, like many in the field, remains cautious: ``I don't
believe this will be the magic bullet. You need to attack a tumor
on many fronts.''
</P>
<P>
   Folkman agrees. He believes the inhibitors likely will be teamed
with radiation and chemotherapy and their first achievements will
be to reduce side effects and a tumors' ability to be
drug-resistant.
</P>
<P>
   As for the much-abused ``c'' word _ cure _ that is not yet in
the lexicon of angiogenesis researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Hanahan, the San Francisco researcher, puts it this way: ``There
is no question in my mind that angiogenesis is an incredibly
exciting target, and that we are going to develop very effective
treatments that have a major impact on the ability of tumors to
grow new blood vessels. But is a particular compound going to cure
cancer? It seems improbable to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
