<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-MAURO07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mauro claims support of 49 Hispanic mayors
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Democratic gubernatorial nominee Garry Mauro
recently trumpeted endorsements from 49 Hispanic mayors, including
one who said he is not a Mauro man.
</P>
<P>
   ``This strong show of support from elected officials will help
our campaign win the Hispanic vote by a record margin,'' Mauro said
in Edinburg.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Texas Poll indicates otherwise. In June, the poll _
which showed Republican Gov. George W. Bush with a 53-point overall
lead _ showed the incumbent with a 67 percent to 20 percent edge
among Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro has said there is no chance the Hispanic vote will look
anything like that on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``On almost every major issue of importance to Hispanics,
Governor Bush is on the wrong side,'' he said. ``Hispanic mayors
have joined my campaign because they know that Governor Bush can't
be counted on to look out for the interests of Texas families.''
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic voters, despite traditionally low turnouts, have long
been a dependable cog in the Democratic machine in Texas. Bush,
however, has targeted the Hispanic community as one in which he can
score well.
</P>
<P>
   The list of mayors backing Mauro include many from small South
Texas cities, as well as some from somewhat larger cities such as
Alice, Del Rio, Edinburg and Presidio. Manor Mayor Joe Sanchez is
the only Central Texas mayor on the list.
</P>
<P>
   One mayor on the Mauro list, Raul Diaz of San Elizario in El
Paso County, said he should not have been included. For the first
time in his life, Diaz is backing the GOP nominee for governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has done a lot for the people here,'' Diaz said of
Bush. ``I think he is a governor for the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro campaign manager Billy Rogers said Diaz had assured the
Mauro staff he was backing the Democratic nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Another mayor on Mauro's list, Arnoldo Cantu of Freer, also
signed a form indicating he is endorsing Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, who has taken to speaking in Spanish at many
campaign stops, has made repeated trips to El Paso to tap into the
Hispanic vote there.
</P>
<P>
   El Paso Mayor Carlos Ramirez is a Bush backer, as are the
Hispanic mayors of Los Fresnos, San Diego, Harlingen and
Kingsville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush has worked hard to earn the support of Texans
across the state and will keep doing so,'' said Mindy Tucker,
Bush's campaign spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro insists Hispanics will not like what Bush has to offer on
various topics. The challenger cited Bush's proposal to use
statewide exams to determine if third-, fifth-, and eighth-graders
are promoted, as well as Bush's position on bilingual education.
Bush has said he is awaiting results of new state exams to
determine whether bilingual education is successful.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro also said Hispanics should question Bush's conditional
support for placing a low-level radioactive waste dump at a West
Texas site near Sierra Blanca. Mauro claims the location violates a
treaty with Mexico, and he has said he would kill the project.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Association of Business and Chambers of Commerce
political action committee also recently announced its backing for
Republican candidates for all top statewide offices.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
