<HEADER>
A0588 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CANCER-DEATHS-SPC     08-06 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CANCER-DEATHS-SPCL-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOOD UPBEAT OVER FIRST-EVER DROP IN CANCER DEATHS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Based on government data just released for the
first 11 months of last year, 1997 will almost certainly be the
first year since statistics have been tracked in which fewer
Americans died of cancer than the year before.
</P>
<P>
   The drop was small, but it happened even though the nation's
population grew by 2.5 million and the average age continued to
climb. Coming on top of six straight years of decline in the
per-capita rate of cancer deaths _ and with that rate now falling
faster than ever _ the drop in total deaths is being called a
momentous turning point in the battle against the dreaded disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the beginning of the payoff,'' says David S.
Rosenthal, president of the American Cancer Society and director of
Harvard University Health Services. ``And in my rose-colored
glasses, I think we'll see even better trends downward.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Philip Cole, a professor of epidemiology at the University
of Alabama at Birmingham and a national authority on tracking
cancer trends, is even more upbeat: ``Not only is the rate of
cancer deaths coming down every year, but the rate of decline is
accelerating.... Of all the decline that has occurred since 1991,
almost one-third of it has occurred in the last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more remarkable, says Cole, is the finding that ``for the
first time in history, the actual number of deaths by cancer in
this country is going down.''
</P>
<P>
   After years of frustration and doubt, the hard numbers seem to
be documenting that improvements in chemotherapy, radiation, and
surgery _ along with more effective prevention _ are making real
inroads against cancer, even as researchers make the most promising
strides yet in their search for cures. The statistics offer hope
that the coming years will see cancer at last follow the trend of
heart disease, whose toll has dropped dramatically over 25 years,
although it remains America's leading killer.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics are contained in the latest monthly mortality
reports prepared by the US Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta.
The reports include 23 additional months of data since federal
officials announced in March the first downturn in over 20 years in
rates of &UR;  &LR; cancer incidence, covering the period 1990 to 1995, as
well as continued progress on death rates. It will be at least a
month before the government finishes analyzing the new information,
which covers January 1996 through November 1997, but Cole and key
federal officials say some trends already are apparent.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the rate at which Americans are dying of all
cancers combined continued to fall during those 23 months. That
makes nearly six consecutive years of declines, in stark contrast
to the way rates rose inexorably from 1973 to 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The decline, adjusted for the rising age of the population, was
just .6 percent in 1996, Cole says. But over the first 11 months of
1997 cancer death rates fell by 2 percent _ and the actual number
of deaths fell by 1 percent, from 497,110 during that period the
year before, to 491,350.
</P>
<P>
   The latest 23 months of data must be refined before they are
released in final form, but the recent trend suggests the final
figures will reflect even ``more decline,'' says Harry M.
Rosenberg, chief of mortality statistics at the CDC's National
Center for Health Statistics. ``What we can say with this is that
the cancer trend overall has continued to decrease.''
</P>
<P>
   The death-rate decline cuts across most major types of cancer,
with the biggest drop in breast cancer _ nearly 8 percent. There
were modest decreases in cancers of the respiratory and digestive
organs and genitals. There were more modest increases in cancers of
the urinary organs and the lymphatic and blood tissues. Those rates
reflect the number of deaths per 100,000 people, based on a
nationwide sample of 10 percent of the death certificates filed
with states during that period.
</P>
<P>
   The rates for the last month of 1997 are not available yet, but
Cole says it is inconceivable that a single month's data could
reverse the trend of the previous 11 months.
</P>
<P>
   While it is not known precisely what is driving the drop in
deaths, one clear factor is that Americans are getting better at
detecting cancer early, when it is easiest to contain, says Brenda
K. Edwards, associate director of surveillance research at the
National Cancer Institute. Another key, says Rosenberg, is the
decline in smoking, especially among men.
</P>
<P>
   How much of a role better treatment plays is more controversial.
Dr. John Bailar, chairman of the Department of Health Studies at
the University of Chicago and a leading critic of the cancer
establishment, says the lion's share of credit goes to Pap smears
and other early-detection techniques, along with campaigns against
tobacco and other carcinogens. The only place where treatment has
produced compelling results, he adds, is with cancer of the colon
and rectum, along with cancers in children.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Richard Klausner, director of the NCI, insists that
better ways of delivering chemotherapy and radiation are a big
reason death rates are going down for cancers of the breast and
other organs. ``I can list a whole number of pretty significant
types of cancer where survival is increasing,'' he says. ``The
ability to preserve organs or function, or control side effects of
disease and therapy, have significantly improved in the last 10
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Former cancer patient Laurel Simmons of Cambridge doesn't feel a
need to choose between treatment and prevention. Simmons is a
strong advocate of prevention, but she says she stands as personal
proof that treatment saves lives, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I am part of the process of bringing those rates
down,'' says the 36-year-old graduate student at the Harvard School
of Public Health, who was diagnosed with chronic myelogenous
leukemia in 1987, had a relapse in 1990, but is symptom-free today
after receiving a bone marrow transplant and other state-of-the-art
therapies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I owe my life to this vast scientific complex that really does
produce some lifesaving results at the end of the day,'' she says.
``When we see data about cancer rates coming down I guess it means
all those folks are making progress. It's really wonderful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
