<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 09:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0590 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CANCER-V-SPCL-ART     08-06 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CANCER-V-SPCL-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAINSTREAM WIDENS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo and a graphic are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeannine Bibeau is feeling miserable.
</P>
<P>
   It is just hours since she had a walnut-sized tumor cut out of
her esophagus. Her doctors have done all they can, giving her drugs
for the pain and running tubes to her lungs and stomach. But
Roberta Raskin's work is just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   She slowly moves her hands along Bibeau's body, her fingers
within inches of her patient's skin yet never touching it. As a
therapeutic healer, Raskin's job is to calm an ``energy field''
only she can feel, bringing Bibeau back into balance with the
metaphysical universe.
</P>
<P>
   Spiritual healing like this has been going on for centuries, but
it's hardly what you'd expect in the high-tech halls of
Massachusetts General Hospital. Yet it's happening there and in
other temples of traditional medicine, as therapists who deal with
things they can't see, hear, or sometimes even name increasingly
are working yards away from doctors who deal with things they can
cut, stitch, and count.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to beat back patients' demands for alternative therapies,
mainstream medicine in America is trying a new tack: making those
therapies available itself. And nowhere is that change more
profound, or more confounding, than in cancer treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer doctors today are reciting the mantra of ``complementary
therapies'' much as they proclaim the once-scorned virtues of
prevention. Once the chanting stops, however, confusion often sets
in over which complementary treatments doctors can recommend with
confidence that they actually work, or that they at least provide
psychic relief without doing harm. There also is confusion about
whether physicians trained in western medicine are competent to
judge therapies that derive from decidedly different traditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a lot of people are using these therapies, let's get the
best clinical trial people in the country to do rigorous trials
that sift out what's helpful from what's not helpful,'' advises Dr.
Harold Varmus, director of the National Institutes of Health. ``And
let's do it without any preconceptions about what might work and
what won't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we're trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But many cancer patients can't wait, and don't see why they
should. ``I don't really care if doctors say it works,'' says
Catherine Kerr of Cambridge, Mass., who is using qi gong, a Chinese
system of breathing and exercise, to help her deal with her
multiple myeloma, a cancer that lodges in the bone marrow for which
there are treatments, but no cure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Western doctors,'' she says, ``are hugely important. They
monitor my biochemistry really closely. But there's just this whole
other level of illness that they don't really know that much about,
and patients have to look for that knowledge elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Prevention moves to the forefront
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People also are often on their own when they look for ways to
prevent cancer from starting, although that's changing.
</P>
<P>
   Until this century, prevention was the hallmark of medicine's
approach to battling disease, whether it was tuberculosis or
malaria, diphtheria or dysentery. Long before there were cures,
doctors and nurses looked for ways to avoid illness, from better
hygiene to vaccines to quarantining the sick to stop the spread of
infection.
</P>
<P>
   In the war on cancer, however, prevention generally took a back
seat to the search for treatments and cures. You could see that at
the National Cancer Institute, where prevention-related activity
typically received considerably less money than treatment, although
the gap has closed in recent years. And you could hear it in
conversations with doctors, for whom prevention generally was an
afterthought, albeit one they now strongly endorse.
</P>
<P>
   That was partly a matter of politics: It is difficult to take on
the tobacco companies and other powerful interests whose products
promote cancer-causing behavior, and it is hotly disputed how much
factors like industrial pollutants are to blame. It's also a matter
of practicality: Cancer doctors generally see patients after
they've got the disease, primary-care doctors generally feel more
comfortable dispensing treatments than educating patients about
healthier ways of behaving, and patients often won't listen even
when they get such advice. And, of course, little was known about
what causes many types of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Even with those impediments, the focus on prevention is
intensifying. Based in part on the way the drop in smoking
nationwide has led to a drop in lung cancer rates, health officials
now conclude that more than 50 percent of cancer can be prevented
by applying what we know about its causes.
</P>
<P>
   Any discussion of cancer prevention still has to start with
smoking, which continues to account for about 30 percent of cancer
deaths in America. And it's not just the lungs that tobacco
attacks, but the mouth, larynx, esophagus, bladder, kidney,
pancreas, head, neck, and colon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we took all the other reliably known effects, and added
them all up, it probably wouldn't add up to 50 percent of the
number of cancer deaths caused by smoking,'' says Richard Peto, a
professor of medical statistics at the University of Oxford whose
population studies were among the first to cement the link between
tobacco and cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we're putting perhaps too much emphasis on kids. It's
easy politically to say, `Let's try to avoid companies deliberately
encouraging kids from getting into smoking.' But that's only part
of an appropriate way to reduce deaths from tobacco,'' Peto says.
``Stopping smoking even in middle age you can avoid most of the
risk.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
