<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 09:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0591 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CANCER-III-SPCL-2     08-06 1385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CANCER-III-SPCL-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINE-TUNED TREATMENT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: Two photos and a graphic are being sent to NYTNS
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM _ To most cancer doctors, a breast tumor is a poison
that must be removed as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   But to Dr. Herbert M. Pinedo, it's also its own potential
antidote.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to make the tumor turn on itself. Pinedo came to
that radical concept after watching survival rates climb by 25
percent when, before operating, he gave women with large tumors
chemotherapy treatments large enough and for long enough to
substantially shrink the growths. That meant putting off surgery, a
prospect that would have alarmed most oncologists. But Pinedo
thinks the delay allowed the body to kick-start its own
disease-fighting mechanisms even as the chemotherapy controlled the
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not those particular findings hold up, the Dutch
doctor's strategy of trying new and creative uses of long-standing
cancer treatments is being replicated worldwide. The result: tens
of thousands of lives saved or prolonged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the incremental improvements that matter,'' says Pinedo,
who runs the medical oncology program at the Free University in
Amsterdam and is considered one of Europe's foremost cancer
researchers.
</P>
<P>
   He knows that retooling conventional therapies never will garner
the attention of the would-be breakthroughs that seek to starve
tumor cells or fix cancer-spawning genes. But he also knows that
exciting laboratory advances aren't much help for cancer patients
like Arne Roodenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Roodenberg had an enormous tumor in her breast, one that she and
her doctors for months mistook for extra milk produced while she
was breast-feeding. By the time it was diagnosed nearly three years
ago and she went to see Pinedo, it had grown to more than three
inches across, large enough to set off alarms and get her enrolled
in his clinical trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got my first chemotherapy my tumor was 8 centimeters;
the next day it was 4. In one day. It was great,'' the 38-year-old
mother of three recalls. The treatment worked so well that
Roodenberg went on an extended regimen, followed by surgery and
radiation. ``And I've had no cancer for two-and-a-half years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say that we are happy that doctors know so much
about this. We are happy that many women can be better about breast
cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Blazing new ground with radiation therapy
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is the incremental progress driving today's cancer
treatment more apparent and impressive than in radiation therapy.
And nowhere have radiologists had more success in pushing that
envelope than in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   One successful treatment involves a proton accelerator, which
draws on the special properties of positively-charged nuclei of
hydrogen atoms to target radiation directly at the tumor. While
conventional X-rays go clear through a patient, losing energy along
the way, a proton device delivers a stream of particles directly to
the tumor. Once there, the radiation simply stops, which means
there is more energy hitting, and hopefully killing, the tumor, and
less damage to surrounding tissue.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The therapy should take another big leap forward in December
when Massachusetts General Hospital opens its $46 million Northeast
Proton Therapy Center in what used to be the workout yard of the
Charles Street Jail. The facility, jointly funded by the hospital
and the National Cancer Institute, will pump out radiation at
higher energies, allowing it to reach deeper-seated tumors in the
lungs, abdomen, prostate, uterus, bladder, and rectum. And the beam
can be rotated to reach different parts of the patient; in the old
Harvard cyclotron, where proton treatment is now performed, the
beam is fixed and the patient must be rotated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be able to treat any site in the human body,'' says Dr.
Herman Suit, who directs Mass. General's Radiation Oncology
Department and pioneered many of the improvements in proton beam
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the same sorts of gains oncologists at Mass. General
are hoping for with another radiation technology being tried on
breast cancer patients. Hollow tubes about the size of an
intravenous line are inserted at half-inch intervals around the
tumor, then filled with seeds of radioactive iridium, eliminating
the need for less precise external beams and taking just five days,
compared to six weeks with standard radiation. ``So far all our
patients are fine, but we're still awaiting final proof in five or
10 years that it's effective,'' says Dr. Simon Powell, who oversees
the implant program.
</P>
<P>
   At Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, meanwhile, cancer
specialists are trying out another radiation treatment on patients
with low-grade lymphomas. Researchers recently developed an
antibody that targets those tumors, and doctors now are attaching
to those antibodies a radioactive iodine solution they hope will
help kill cancer cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to find a biological attack point,'' explains Dr.
Lowell Schnipper, the medical center's chief of hematology and
oncology. ``It's the first in a series of strategies that will be
more tailored to the tumor itself.''
</P>
<P>
   That challenge of getting radiation where it can do the most
good has preoccupied radiologists ever since Wilhelm Conrad
Roentgen discovered X-rays in 1895. The latest tack being tried is
delivering the radiation during surgery, rather than before or
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   With certain spinal tumors, for instance, doctors use a
seemingly-endless series of CAT scans as a roadmap to delicately
plant catheters of cancer-fighting radioactive material in the
spine. The challenge with cancers in the rectum, pancreas, abdomen,
and pelvis is getting the radiation there without damaging the
bowel or other tissue that is in the way. The solution: During
surgery, after the visible tumor has been removed, the bowel,
bladder, and other critical organs are manually pushed aside so a
radioactive beam can zero in on whatever cancer cells remain.
</P>
<P>
   This ``intraoperative electron beam'' technique was inaugurated
in 1978, and now is widely used at Mass. General, the M.D. Anderson
Cancer Center in Houston, and other major hospitals, with dramatic
results: Recurrence rates of 45 percent for locally-advanced rectal
cancer have been lowered to 10 percent, and outcomes are equally
good for certain sarcomas of the abdomen and pelvis.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur S. Athanas is one of those remarkable statistics. Two
years ago, he had a tumor in his bile duct so difficult to reach
that three doctors told him ``they wouldn't touch it with a 10-foot
pole,'' the 78-year-old Athanas recalls. At Mass. General, however,
surgeons used a combination of conventional radiation, surgery, and
the intra-operative beam to destroy the tumor.
</P>
<P>
   Today, says Athanas, there is no sign of any cancer and ``I
don't have to go in for another checkup for another year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Surgery best hope for many cancers
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, when chemotherapy and radiation were in their
infancy, surgery was the best hope for most cancer patients. It
still is, at least when the cancer hasn't spread.
</P>
<P>
   That's partly because solid tumors in the liver, lungs, and
other organs often are resistant to chemotherapy and radiation, so
surgery often is the only option. It's also because surgeons have
refined their techniques, lowering the risks and raising the
precision with which they can excise cancerous cells. Most
promising is the way surgeons are collaborating with colleagues in
radiation and chemotherapy, using them to shrink tumors before an
operation and to kill remaining cancer cells afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation has been dramatic with surgery for cancers of
the rectum, as well as those of the head and neck, bones, and
cartilage. ``Fifteen years ago, if you got a sarcoma involving a
limb, it was sacrificed. Now, because of the ability to use
radiation and drugs after surgery, you can just resect it and spare
the limb,'' says Dr. Bruce Chabner, chief medical officer at
Dana-Farber/Partners CancerCare and former head of treatment
programs at the NCI.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 0951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 09:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0595 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CANCER-III-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     08-06 1424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CANCER-III-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 AMSTERDAM: ... at the NCI.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As with other types of surgery, new methods are allowing
surgeons to do much less cutting to get at cancerous tumors. Using
laparoscopes, physicians can insert a slender tube into the body
through a keyhole incision and direct it to the site of a tumor. A
fiber-optic cable beams images onto a screen in the operating room
to guide the doctor, who cuts and sews using tiny instruments
inserted through other dime-sized slits.
</P>
<P>
   Newer refinements offer hope of even less traumatic surgery. For
example, radiofrequency ablation, a thermal technique for attacking
diseased tissue, is being tested on liver tumors at Mass. General.
A needle is inserted into the tumor, then connected to a device
that generates 500-kilohertz radio waves capable of coagulating and
ultimately destroying the cancer cells. Five years ago it wouldn't
work on lesions greater than half an inch; today it is being used
on tumors as big as two inches.
</P>
<P>
   Surgeons aren't the only ones who have been fine-tuning their
techniques. Better ways of administering anesthesia, providing
intensive care, and boosting nutrition have meant fewer pre- and
postoperative complications. The bottom line, says cancer surgeon
Kenneth Tanabe of MGH, is that ``surgery is an option for many more
patients than it was before. This is especially true for
complicated procedures like cancer of the esophagus, pancreas, and
liver.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chemo benefits discovered by chance
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chemotherapy, the third major weapon in the war against cancer,
also has been the subject of continuous experimentation and
refinement. And here more than anywhere, those refinements have
arisen as much from serendipity as from science.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened 37 years ago when Barnett Rosenberg, a
biophysicist at Michigan State University, made an unusal
observation: When an electric current generated by platinum
electrodes was run through a solution of E. coli bacteria, the
organisms continued to grow but stopped dividing. When the
electricity was shut off, the bacteria started to divide again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was the electricity, because the effects
followed precisely after we turned it on and off,'' recalls
Rosenberg, who now runs his own research institute in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out it was the platinum _ or, more specifically, a
chemical called cisplatin produced when platinum electrodes leached
into the solution _ that turned off the cell division. Rosenberg
suspected that if cell division could be arrested in bacteria, it
also could be arrested in cancer cells. So he tested cisplatin on
mice, then on humans with testicular cancer. In 1978 the FDA
approved its use.
</P>
<P>
   The results have been breathtaking. Before cisplatin, fewer than
10 percent of patients with testicular cancer survived for five
years; now, more than 90 percent of even advanced cases are cured.
And it can be effective in treating cancer of the lungs, ovaries,
and head and neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young men were lying in bed dying of testicular cancer, and
women of ovarian. They gave them this new drug and they stood up
and walked out. You're dead and now you're alive,'' recalls Dr. Lee
Nadler, head of adult oncology at the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson, says Dr. Harold Varmus, head of the National
Institutes of Health, is that ``pure serendipity is important. It
illustrates what is meant by incremental progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes progress means adding one old-standby drug to another
that has been around for years, creating the sorts of potent
``cocktails'' that have proven so effective in battling the AIDS
virus. Combinations of fluorouracil and levamisole gave oncologists
their first real success with cancers of the colon, while cisplatin
works even better when mixed with bleomycin and etoposide for
patients with tumors of the testicles.
</P>
<P>
   Other advances have come from altering the timing of treatments,
first moving the chemotherapy to just after the operation, then to
just before.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think of chemotherapy as conventional, as old hat,''
says Dr. Emil Frei, former physician-in-chief at the Dana-Farber
Cancer Institute and a front-line fighter against cancer for 43
years. ``But chemo continues to march as the most important
systematic approach to cancer cure and treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   People also think of chemotherapy as bringing with it vomiting,
depletion of white blood cells, and other sickening side effects.
But many of those problems, too, are becoming more memory than
reality, as researchers over the last 10 years have developed
medicines to control nausea and pump up production of white and red
blood cells.
</P>
<P>
   While hair loss still ``is absolutely as prevalent as ever,
we've tried to get rid of the most feared side effects,'' says Dr.
Douglas Faller, director of the Cancer Research Center at Boston
Medical Center. And while lessening side effects is a major relief
to patients, it also can give a big boost to their therapy. ``It
gives us greater ability to deliver these chemotherapy drugs
without interruption,'' explains Dr. Charles Fuchs of Dana-Farber.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca McClintock of Francestown, N.H., who has twice had to
contend with cancer, says she is living proof of the difference
those refinements have made.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an absolute walk in the park,'' the 30-year-old says,
comparing recent chemo treatments for breast cancer with those she
received for leukemia as a teenager. ``When I think of chemotherapy
15 years ago, that's what I think of, throwing up. This time I was
in my second trimester of a pregnancy when I was having chemo. If I
had been sick it might have been difficult to tell whether it was
the chemo or pregnancy that was causing it. But I didn't get sick
once.
</P>
<P>
   ``My attitude has always been that chemo is better than nothing,
and now it's a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Doctor seek out better treatment formula
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pinedo, the Dutch doctor, knows that patients are skeptical
about medicine's ability to make a difference with cancer,
especially when the disease has reached an advanced stage. That's
why, when he began treating patients with breast tumors as large as
six inches, Pinedo resolved to devise a better formula for mixing
and blending the latest techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of administering the three 21-day cycles of chemo before
surgery that is becoming the standard for large breast tumors, he
has tried four to six cycles. In this way, Pinedo hopes to shrink
the tumor enough to give surgeons a better shot at excising it all
while preserving more of the breast. And he gives his patients a
biological growth factor, known as GM-CSF, to protect the bone
marrow and, he hopes, to stimulate the body's own cancer-fighting
T-cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we observed in our group of 24 patients was that 76
percent are disease-free and surviving, versus about 50 percent if
you do three cycles of treatment,'' says Pinedo. ``And we never saw
one during chemo who had progression of the disease in the breast
or beyond, so we were not at all nervous about the longer
treatments.''
</P>
<P>
   Why does longer treatment work so well? Pinedo isn't sure, which
is why he has begun more extensive trials in Mexico City, where
early detection is spotty and women often develop large breast
tumors before they are diagnosed. Over the next four years he hopes
to try the technique on at least 300 Mexican women.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hypothesis,'' explains Pinedo, ``is that if you can
preserve the lymph nodes longer you may help build up an immune
response to the primary tumor, which would help make the
chemotherapy work better.'' He also suspects that the tumor, along
with surrounding cells, might be producing anti-angiogenesis
factors that choke off the supply of blood to cancer cells that
have spread to other organs, ``which may be why with these big
tumors there's no manifest metastasis.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this proves to work in big tumors in the breast, it's
certainly worthwhile to try it on smaller tumors,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Pinedo isn't the only one who's intrigued by these
possibilities. Scientists from Boston to Houston are following his
work and collaborating in his follow-up studies. ``Most people
think of chemotherapy as being immunosuppressive, but these
findings suggest it is actually the opposite under certain
circumstances,'' says Dr. Gabriel Hortobagyi, chairman of breast
oncology at the M.D. Anderson Cancer Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot more work to be done, but these preliminary
results certainly are of major interest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
