<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 09:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0599 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CANCER-KENNEDY-SP     08-06 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CANCER-KENNEDY-SPCL-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NATIONAL CRUSADE' HITS KENNEDYS CLOSE TO HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WASHINGTON _ Senator Edward M. Kennedy has waged two wars
against cancer _ one political, the other personal.
</P>
<P>
   He stepped into the political crucible in 1971, when he and his
colleagues on the Senate health subcommittee pushed a bill to give
the National Cancer Institute enough money and power to make
conquering cancer ``a national crusade.'' They weren't worried
about opposition from the National Institutes of Health, which was
concerned that it would lose authority over the NCI. And they
weren't worried about resistance from the medical and science
establishments, which were concerned that more money wouldn't cure
cancer but might jeopardize funding for their other pet projects.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was President Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   It was partly that the president objected to the independence
Kennedy was proposing for the NCI. But even more, those involved
recall, Nixon couldn't stomach the idea of signing legislation
bearing the Kennedy name. Older brother Jack, after all, had beaten
Nixon in a run for the White House in 1960, Bobby had hoped to
oppose him in 1968, and Ted, despite denials that he was running,
was among the rivals Nixon most feared in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   The solution: The Kennedy-Javits bill was scuttled, and nearly
identical wording was inserted into the administration's
hastily-filed cancer bill, which carried the name of Republican
Senator Peter H. Dominick of Colorado and had originally envisioned
a decidedly different program. The prospect of a Democratic Senate
passing a Republican bill, especially one as important as the
cancer act, was nearly unprecedented, but in this case it also was
the only way to ensure the president's signature.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Kennedy pulled away, Nixon agreed to make the
announcement,'' recalls Dr. Vincent T. DeVita Jr., a former NCI
chief. ``I saw Nixon later, and he told me this law was one of his
finest achievements.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, meanwhile, looks back with some amusement at what must
have been a painful moment: ``I said, `It's fine with me to put
Peter Dominick's name on it.' I asked Peter, and he said `yes.'''
</P>
<P>
   The rest is history, as the senator from Massachusetts joined
other legislators at a White House signing ceremony the morning of
Dec. 23, 1971.
</P>
<P>
   While he extended an olive branch in the morning, Nixon later
that afternoon plotted a dirty tricks campaign that would make it
appear that Kennedy was planning to challenge Democratic
frontrunner Edmund Muskie in the upcoming New Hampshire
presidential primary. That scheme, which surfaced in a tape
released last year, prompted Kennedy to signal again that he wasn't
a candidate and pushed the Democrats deeper into a tailspin.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two years after he helped launch the war on cancer,
Kennedy found himself back on the front lines, in a painfully
personal way.
</P>
<P>
   His son Teddy Jr., just 12, had an ache in his right kneecap
that wouldn't go away. Doctors thought it was a calcium deposit,
and young Teddy preferred to ignore it, but eventually he went to
Georgetown Hospital for an X-ray, a biopsy _ and very bad news.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad told me that I was going to lose part of my leg due to
cancer,'' Ted Jr. said in a recent interview. ``I thought he meant
the doctors would simply have to cut out the swollen part in my
kneecap, but he said, `not exactly. It's from the knee down.' I
thought my life was over. It's the typical thing when most people
hear those words, `You have cancer.' It's an unforgettable
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally unforgettable were the odds in 1973 that a child would
survive osteogenic sarcoma, a rare cancer in which the tumor
invades the cartilage along with the bone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd amputate, and 80 percent of them would relapse in the
lungs. They lost life and limb,'' recalls Dr. Emil Frei, the former
physician-in-chief at the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute who was a
consultant on Teddy's treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, doctors were beginning to experiment with a two-drug
combination of methotrexate and leucovorin. Methotraxate, an
antitumor drug, was given in doses 30 to 40 times higher than
normal to kill the cancer cells. Twenty-four hours later,
leucovorin was added to keep the methotrexate from killing the
patient.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Jr. became just the fourth participant in a clinical trial
of the experimental regimen. Every three weeks he'd take the
Eastern shuttle back to Boston on Friday afternoon and spend the
weekend in the hospital, with the chemicals slowly dripping out of
a plastic bag into his body. The senator came, too, bringing movies
and games, friends and relatives, trying to keep his son amused
during the day, and spending nights in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The side effects from the chemotherapy at times seemed
unbearable. ``It was pretty bad,'' says Ted, the middle of the
senator's three children. ``There were mouth sores, and I couldn't
keep anything down because I had these open sores.''
</P>
<P>
   He lost most of his blonde hair, always felt tired, had to get
regular injections to temper the effects of other medicines, and
was trying to get comfortable with the prosthetic where his lower
leg used to be.
</P>
<P>
   But the experimental treatment was working. Two years of the
chemotherapy was killing whatever cancer remained in his body, to
the point where he can say today, ``I'm totally clean.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost from the outset, the new regimen doubled the cure rate
for osteogenic sarcoma, compared to amputation alone, from 20
percent to 40 percent. Other drugs were added to the mix later, and
doctors began giving the chemotherapy just before surgery, not
after, improvements that eventually achieved a success rate of 80
percent and saved the limbs of many patients. Now 36, Ted Jr. can
look back with some perspective on his ordeal, and on the phone
call he got 25 years ago from President Nixon wishing him a quick
recovery from surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Today the senator's son avoids the spotlight, but he is
passionate about his practice of health and disability law in New
Haven. He speaks to groups of cancer patients and disability rights
advocates. He also skis, sails, and swims, and, with his wife, is
raising two children.
</P>
<P>
   ``My experience has given me a profound appreciation of
everything in my life today,'' he says. ``There was a time when I
never thought I would be able to raise two young children. Not just
because of my own recovery, but because of the toxic effects my
chemo could have had on my ability to reproduce.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, meanwhile, thinks about Ted Jr. every time he's
asked to assess the success of the still-controversial war on
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has the $34 billion we've spent been worth it? I can speak as
a father,'' the senator begins, his voice softening. Without the
medical innovations supported by the war on cancer, the elder
Kennedy continues, his son ``never would have made it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 0954EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
