<HEADER>
A0602 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN09-CO     08-06 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: More Nazi files curiously disappear
 &HT;    (For release Aug. 9, 1998)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why did it not surprise me late last month to read that files
documenting gold stolen from Jews by the Nazis mysteriously
disappeared from German archives well after the conclusion of World
War II _ and that U.S. negligence played a role?
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times story suggested that the 26 secret files may
have disappeared to cover the tracks ``of former Nazi banking
officials entrusted by the Allies with high offices in postwar
Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   It is but another example of how Nazi war criminals have been
able to escape accountability for their foul actions. The trail of
at-large Nazis reaches from Argentina to Syria to the United States
as well as in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, one is flushed out, tried and deported, but there
will be no end to this issue as there have been too many coverups.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. involvement is long-documented, from Gen. George Patton's
coddling and use of Nazis in the immediate postwar to the flood of
suspected Nazi war criminals who entered the U.S., lying about
their past but exposed by others and still allowed to stay until
their lives were close to life-cycle completion.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most notorious cases was that of Valerian Trifa, a
leader of Romania's pro-Nazi Iron Guard who was responsible for the
deaths of thousands of Jews as well as an attempt to overthrow the
Romanian government.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Valerian Trifa and his Romanian-born New York City
tormenter, a Jewish dentist names Charles Kremer, is documented in
a remarkable book by Howard Blum. Called ``Wanted: The Search for
Nazis in America,'' it exposes U.S. negligence in pursuing persons
such as Trifa, even after mounds of documents were presented by an
obsessed Kremer detailing Trifa's diabolic activities in Romania.
</P>
<P>
   As early as 1941Trifa was tried in absentia by the Romanian
government, convicted and sentenced to life in prison. By then,
however, he was spirited out of Romania by the Nazis and under
their protective custody.
</P>
<P>
   For five years, he avoided authorities and, in 1950, arrived in
New York. He lied about his past and was admitted. And what did
Trifa do while he was in the U.S.? He become head of the
Michigan-based Romanian Orthodox Church; Bishop Trifa, if you
please.
</P>
<P>
   Now, here's the most astonishing thing about Trifa's U.S.
presence. On May 11, 1955, Bishop Trifa gave the opening prayer at
the U.S. Senate. It had been requested by the president of the
Senate, Vice President Richard M. Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   It never has been answered to my satisfaction why Nixon asked
for Trifa, or if Nixon even knew of Trifa's past. Blum's book
speculates on much of it, not in favor of Nixon, but I won't go
into it here.
</P>
<P>
   By 1957, and despite a U.S. law that anyone belonging to the
Iron Guard before 1952 will be denied citizenship, Bishop Trifa
became a U.S. citizen. Understand that Kremer had been writing U.S.
officials about Trifa since 1941!
</P>
<P>
   The Trifa case is but one; there are dozens of similar episodes
of known Nazis getting into the U.S. Look how long it took for the
issue of Nazi gold and Swiss, Portuguese and U.S. complicity to
surface. And now some of the secret files are announced as missing.
</P>
<P>
   The article said the files were shipped to the U.S. after being
found by U.S. troops in Germany in 1945. Now, they're nowhere to be
found, not even microfilm copies.
</P>
<P>
   The long, wicked arm of ODESSA, that secretive Nazi SS
protective organization, still is being felt.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
