<HEADER>
A0647 &Cx1f; ttg-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     08-06 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LETTERS HOME TO TREASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our son is off for a week at baseball camp, which means that we,
his parents, being the saps that we are, are taking full advantage
of this ``free time'' by staring glumly out the window, waiting for
the mailman to deliver a letter home.
</P>
<P>
   There is about as much chance of our son writing a letter home
as there is of Bill Clinton joining the priesthood, but we remain
hopeful, shuffling out to the mailbox several times a day in case a
letter had been regurgitated by one of the resident, Frisbee-size
spiders that make mail retrieval such an adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is no guarantee that a letter from our son
would calm our fears for his safety and assure us that he is having
a good time, flossing regularly and refraining from stepping on the
face of the kid in the lower bunk. Indeed, some letters home _ a
few of which were published recently in USA Today _ create more
anxiety than they alleviate.
</P>
<P>
   Take this one from Rebecca L. Baum, 14, of Loveland, Ohio:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Mom, Dad, Ry, and Pip:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey guys! What's up? I miss all of you soooooooo much! I was
going to send you guys another letter today, but I decided not to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Camp is totally awesome! It has been so dang hot down here
it's not even funny! Well, you know how I am the sweating queen? I
have the worst heat rash ever! The health center told me that I had
one of the worst cases they have seen the whole session!
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely love it here! I was really sick yesterday. I
could barely get out of my bed! Annie thought I was dehydrated. I
probably was! I love you and miss you all but I best be goin' to
arts and crafts or the person will probably put the smack down on
me!''
</P>
<P>
   The parents of Carrie Ince, 14, of San Antonio probably wish
they had let the postal spiders devour this letter home:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Mom and Dad:
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to go home. I've had bad luck ever since I got here. So
far I stayed up to at least 3:00 p.m.-3:47 p.m. every night because
I'm sick. I got a splinter that was so deep they cut my pinkie to
get it out. I have no friends 'cause I'm in the younger cabin so
the older kids think I'm immature and the younger ones think I'm
too mature.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a food fight yesterday and a chicken thigh knocked the
wind out of me and a roll was thrown at my head. The girl on the
top bunk steps on my bed with mud on her shoes and when I'm at an
activity she throws her swimming supplies on my bed so I sleep with
a wet and muddy bed. She also steps on me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, there are scorpions in our cabin. I'm always hot. To
tell you the truth, I hate the food here. It's gross. I haven't
eaten much. Also, a lot of girls in the cabin swear. It really
bothers me.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the girls have candy here but none will share. The
bathrooms are disgusting and my top part of my toothbrush (the part
that I brush me teeth with) fell down the drain and we can't get it
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was inner-tubing in the river a thing stabbed me right
next to my eye and it's all scraped up. I'm getting sicker and
sicker. I don't think I'll last much longer. If you really love me,
you'll pick me up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love, Carrie
</P>
<P>
   ``P.S. _ I drink tons of water.''
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Sarasota (Fla.)
Herald-Tribune.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
