<P>
   RINGEL-COLUMN Shane never came back. But Jamie Lee Curtis has.
Twenty years after her breakthrough role in ``Halloween,'' she's
returned to her scream-queen roots in ``Halloween H2O.'' Herewith,
the cream of the slasher crop, including two movies that,
technically, owe nothing to ``Halloween'' but should be on the list
of anyone in the mood for mindless gore: (list follows). (Ringel,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-DVD _ Slowly but surely, the phenomenon known as DVD is
invading the American market. DVD stands for digital video disc.
Currently, DVD movies can be found in Atlanta at most high-tech
electronics stores and, on a limited basis, at selected Blockbuster
stores. Players cost between $500 and $1,500; most discs sell for
$24.95 to $29.95. Recommended in stores this week: (short reviews
of recently released videos follows.) (Ringel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED 8/5.
</P>
<P>
   TOY-TESTERS _ LAKE WORTH, Fla. _ Here's the toy that should top
your Christmas shopping list: Stop My Hiccups Dil. Who says so? The
kids at the KinderCare center on Jog Road who are testing 45 toys _
some of them not on the market yet _ for Disney's FamilyFun
magazine's annual Toy of the Year issue. (O'Meilia, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   SPLIT-TOWN _ MCCAYSVILLE, Ga. _ Here in the Copper Basin, known
now for tourism and white-water rafting instead of its
once-flourishing copper industry, the North Georgia town of
McCaysville (population 1,062) shares a downtown with Copperhill,
Tenn. (501). And they share the blue line, rich in irony. (May,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED. EMBARGOED UNTIL 8/9.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-DROPOUTS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ To see a play at the
Kravis Center or to take soil samples from the Lake Worth Lagoon,
high school students need a permission slip signed by mom, dad or a
legal stand-in. But to drop out of school? No signature required.
Until now. Starting this fall, a Florida student can't drop out of
school _ even at age 16 _ until a parent or guardian signs off on
the decision. (Desmon, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FIRE-GEL _ PALM HARBOR, Fla. _ Fire gel remained relatively
unknown outside firefighting circles until John Bartlett and
business partner Bruce Hill, also a Palm Beach County firefighter,
used it on 20 homes in Flagler County during the recent wildfires
there. They coated the homes and retreated. When the fires passed
and they returned, the homes were still there. Barricade become an
overnight hero. (Murawski, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SHIPWRECK _ AUSTIN _ A centuries-old shipwreck whose discovery
last February off the Texas coast excited historians is not the
long-lost flagship of French explorer La Salle as initially
thought, state officials announced recently. Instead, it may be a
Spanish warship 100 years younger. (Ward, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ A query on the Internet brings to mind the days
not so long ago when information on fine woodworking was nearly
impossible to find. Today, a visit to the magazine section of a
major bookstore will display at least half a dozen excellent
periodicals. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
