<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   TUBES-UNTIED _ ATLANTA _ A tornado ripped up Robynn Wilson's
home and her life. Along with destroying her house, it killed her
youngest child. In an act of kindness, Blue Cross &AMP; Blue Shield of
Georgia has joined forces with local doctors to pay for an
operation to untie her reproductive tubes in an effort to allow her
to get pregnant again and restore some hope in a life torn apart.
What are her chances? And is the procedure _ which was outpatient
surgery _ getting more common? (Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   BABY-BANDS _ Hospitals admit it's almost impossible to prevent
nurses from switching babies, as happened in Virginia. But they've
taken high-tech precautions, such as banding babies at birth and
installing alarms, to prevent as much switching and abduction as
possible. (Hill, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HORMONE _ For the first time, researchers have shown that
estrogen, the female hormone that is believed to protect against
heart attacks, also may protect against stroke. The study was done
in mice, but supports theories that giving a dose of estrogen after
a stroke might be a good idea for male and female patients. In the
study, rats took estrogen before researchers cut off blood flow to
their brains; those on estrogen had about half the brain damage as
those who took a placebo. (Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
