<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0771 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-ZHIVKOV-SHORT-NY     08-06 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ZHIVKOV-SHORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZHIVKOV, COMMUNIST LEADER OF BULGARIA FOR 35 YEARS, DIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds, a longer version of the obit will move as OBIT-SHIVKOV)  
(gm) 
 By DAVID BINDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Todor Zhivkov, the Communist ruler of Bulgaria from 1954 until
his ouster in 1989, died Wednesday night at a hospital in the
capital, Sofia. He was 86. Doctors said he died of complications
following a respiratory infection in July.
</P>
<P>
   Zhivkov was a conventional party apparatchik and this, more than
anything else, may have enabled him to endure the turmoil of Balkan
politics and the periodic upheavals in the Kremlin, to which he
paid fealty throughout his long career.
</P>
<P>
   In his heyday, he boasted more than any other European Communist
leader about his intimate ties with the Soviet Union, saying the
two countries `breathe with the same lungs, and the same blood
flows in our veins'' and that they were as close as ``teeth to
lip.'' This served him well through the three decades in which
Nikita Khrushchev and Leonid I. Brezhnev ruled the Soviet Bloc.''
</P>
<P>
   But in November 1989 as East European regimes were collapsing
one by one, he was brought down with the blessing of the
reform-minded Mikhail Gorbachev in Moscow in a bloodless putsch
organized by senior officials in the Sofia government.
</P>
<P>
   During Zhivkov's long tenure, he authorized a forced
assimilation drive against Bulgaria's 1 million ethnic Turks in
which more than 100 were killed and 310,000 forcibly expelled. In a
campaign that aroused international condemnation in the mid-1980s,
ethnic Turks were deprived of linguistic, cultural and religious
rights. They were dismissed from jobs and rounded up at night,
trucked to police stations, and forced to change their Islamic
Turkish names into Slavic names.
</P>
<P>
   He was responsible for the construction in 1959 of concentration
camps for political prisoners just as the Soviet Union was
dismantling Stalin's Gulags. He was also said to be behind the
murder in London in 1978 of Georgi Markov, a Bulgarian writer in
exile who had made mocking broadcasts about Zhivkov for Radio Free
Europe. In one of the strangest assassinations of the Cold War,
Markov was killed on Waterloo Bridge by an agent who used a special
umbrella to shoot a poisoned pellet into his leg.
</P>
<P>
   The Zhivkov-era concentration camps were at Kotsian, Bogdanov
Dol, Belene Island in the Danube and Lovech. As many as 1,000
prisoners were held in Lovech from 1959 to its closing in 1962 and
at least 100 died or were killed there, according to the Interior
Ministry. Disclosures of their existence came in 1990 a few months
after Zhivkov was ousted. A Ministry of Interior spokesman said,
``Todor Zhivkov at least knew or gave the orders. The problem is
that from this period there were few material traces. It was done
on the telephone.''''
</P>
<P>
   He was never tried for political crimes; prosecutors concluded
it would be too difficult to make charges stick. Instead he was
tried on charges of illegally spending the equivalent of $24
million in state funds. In 1992, after a trial that lasted 18
months, during which he was scornful and defiant, he was convicted
and sentenced to seven years in prison. Apparently, the
post-Zhivkov government, which included many of his former
associates, was reluctant to rake over the coals of their mutual
past.
</P>
<P>
   In deference to his heart problems and age he was allowed to
serve his time under house arrest at the mountain slope home of his
granddaughter overlooking Sofia, and even to make a foray to his
birthplace in Pravets, 44 miles northeast of the capital.'' In
February 1996, Bulgaria's highest court acquitted him of the
embezzlement charges.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, at the height of his power, he turned
Pravets into a model town, reached from Sofia by a rare four-lane
highway. The house where he was born was opened as a historical
monument. In addition, Pravets got a ``historical'' museum
chronicling his, and Communist Bulgaria's life.
</P>
<P>
   When he visited in 1995, the Zhivkov home was empty and the
museum closed. But he was given the deed to the eight acres of
farmland owned by his father and collectivized by the son in the
1950s and now returned to his private hands. A circle had been
closed.
</P>
<P>
   Zhivkov married Dr. Mara Maleeva, a physician, in 1938. She died
in 1971. Their daughter Lyudmila, who, under her father's tutelage
became minister of culture at age 32 in 1975 and encouraged modern
art and published works by authors like Allen Ginsberg, died under
mysterious circumstances six years later. Some suspected that her
death in a bathtub at her father's official residence was a
suicide, others that she was killed by political enemies.
</P>
<P>
   A son, Vladimir, and two grandchildren survive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1154EDT &QL; 
