<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0797 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATOMIC-BOMBS-HNS &LR;      08-06 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATOMIC-BOMBS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOGIC OF WAR, IMPERATIVE FOR PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM C. BRADY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ By the time the bomb was dropped on Hiroshima
and Nagasaki on Aug. 6 and 9, 1945, respectively, the moral line
had been crossed by the saturation bombings in Germany and the fire
bombings of Japan, as well as other large-scale bombings of
civilian centers by both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The great problem of war is that it gets out of hand and grows
by what it feeds on, despite initial good intentions to keep it
limited. Consider the reasoning behind the use of the atomic bombs:
End the war sooner, impress the Soviet Union or just use it or lose
it. Take your pick. When the weapons are so extreme, war becomes
unconscionable and should be unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, since the opening of the nuclear age in 1945, in Korea,
Vietnam, the Middle East and elsewhere, the use of nuclear weapons
has been seriously contemplated and even threatened. One mistake,
and we would have obliterated and been obliterated in turn.
</P>
<P>
   The inscription on the memorial Cenotaph in Hiroshima reads:
``Rest in peace, for the mistake shall not be repeated.'' Is it
unduly optimistic? No power has actually unleashed nuclear hell on
another since Nagasaki. Still, many nations have made ruthless war
on each other since the end of World War II, occasioned in large
part by the fact that the presence of nuclear weaponry had
ratcheted up the degree of violence considered permissible.
</P>
<P>
   The actual body count from carpet bombing, napalm, expanding
bullets, missiles, flame-throwers, Agent Orange, poison gas,
bacteriological weapons, ad infinitum, is a staggering figure. Two
million people perished in Korea by so-called conventional means; 3
million to 5 million in Vietnam, Cambodia, and Laos; 1 million in
Indonesia; 2 million in Nigeria; 1 million in the Iran-Iraq War;
hundreds of thousands in Central America; several hundred thousand
within just six weeks in the Gulf War, and tens of thousands
elsewhere in the Middle East; hundreds of thousands in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In the 53 years since 1945, there have been about 170 wars with
22 to 25 million mortalities, as estimated by United Nations
agencies and Amnesty International. In addition, millions have
starved to death because of war and its aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   All of this on top of the 10 million killed in World War I, the
millions killed between the world wars, and the 40 million to 50
million dead in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   With new technologies, the nature of war has been totally
transformed. The change is different in kind, not just in degree.
The quantum-leap from conventional to nuclear warfare is more like
the difference between the airplane and the spaceship, an ape and a
human being and (why look any further?) between war and peace. It
makes killing profligate and indiscriminate, causing more deaths
among noncombatants than among combatants and extending its
consequences far into the future, way beyond the proximate causes
of war.
</P>
<P>
   How can there be any just war or good war under such inhuman and
antihuman circumstances? Isn't it time to employ the same ingenuity
to making peace as we have to making war? Yet many argue that it is
human nature that impels us to warfare. It would seem rather that
the instinct for survival would incline us against
self-destruction, and therefore, against war.
</P>
<P>
   If it's true that we human beings are more inclined to love than
to hate, and that the Supreme Being is the positive force while the
Prince of Darkness is the negative force and exists only by God's
sufferance, then can we dare say that war is natural? If we are
enjoined to love our neighbors as ourselves, can we ever despise
the enemy? Are there really any good guys and bad guys or evil
empires? Aren't these all really just disguises for ephemeral power
and glory, for vanity? Isn't it true that for every Coventry there
is a Dresden, for every Pearl Harbor and Death March there is a
Hiroshima and Nagasaki, for every Tet Offensive there is a My Lai?
</P>
<P>
   We have come once again to those mind-wrenching and
heartbreaking anniversaries of Hiroshima and Nagasaki. We must make
real the truth that to remember Hiroshima and Nagasaki is to devote
ourselves to peace. Hiroshima and Nagasaki, representing the arch
logic of war, represent for us now the supreme imperative for
peace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
