<HEADER>
A0850 &Cx1f; tab-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIROSHIMA-COMMENTARIE     08-06 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIROSHIMA-COMMENTARIES-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;    To commemorate the 53rd anniversary of the bombing of Hiroshima
on Aug. 6, a formal ``Appeal for Negotiations to Eliminate Nuclear
Arms'' _ sponsored by the Fourth Freedom Forum _ has been signed by
world leaders including Mikhail Gorbachev, Oscar Arias, Jimmy
Carter and Joseph Rotblat.
 &HT;    To bolster your coverage of this issue, we offer the following
excellent commentaries. &HT;    _ All have been released on the wire in the ``k'' commentary and
``a'' general news categories. _
 &HT;    
 WHY I JOINED _ AND LEFT _ THE A-BOMB PROJECT  
 By JOSEPH ROTBLAT  
 c.1998 The Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this compelling commentary, Dr. Joseph Rotblat, a Polish-born
physicist, who won the 1995 Nobel Peace Prize, tells why he started
on the A-bomb project, and then withdrew, and why other scientists
did not. (slugged: BC-HIROSHIMA-ROTBLAT-ABOMB-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PLEASE STOP SPENDING MONEY ON WEAPONS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By OSCAR ARIAS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In this op-ed, Oscar Arias, former president of Costa Rica and
the 1987 Nobel Peace Prize winner, asks a poignant question: How
can the world spend more than $750 billion per year on weapons and
armed forces while 1 billion people languish in poverty? (slugged:
BC-HIROSHIMA-ARIAS-DISARMAMENT-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A PLEA NOT TO REAWAKEN THE NUCLEAR ARMS RACE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By MIKHAIL GORBACHEV &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In this column, Mikhail Gorbachev, the former Soviet president _
who helped bring an end to the Cold War and the superpower nuclear
arms race _ draws attention to the tragedy of a renewed arms race
in South Asia. ``We should do all we can to help Pakistan and India
understand that they're not gaining anything. They're actually
losing a lot by embarking on the nuclear path.'' (slugged:
BC-NO-ARMS-RACE-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHY INDIA WANTS TO BE A NUCLEAR POWER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JASWANT SINGH &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In this story from Foreign Affairs, Jaswant Singh, a senior
adviser on defense and foreign policy to Indian Prime Minister
Vajpayee, says India has been sandwiched between two
nuclear-weapons powers, Pakistan and China, while the nuclear
``haves'' were extolling the virtues of disarmament. (Article will
be available by Aug. 7 or sooner _ slugged:
BC-INDIA-WANTS-NUKES-NYTSF.)
</P>
