<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0856 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAN-HOSTAGE-REUNION-     08-06 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-HOSTAGE-REUNION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT JUST A MATTER OF SHAKING HANDS AND SAYING `SORRY' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By FLORA LEWIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    PARIS _ Despite vague expressions of interest in improving
relations, a Paris encounter between an American and an Iranian
last week showed there is still a very long way to go, and a very
different view on each side of the history that led to rupture and
hostility between the two countries.
 &HT;    The American, Barry Rosen, had been held as a hostage in the
U.S. Embassy in Teheran for 444 days, which he remembered with
obviously great distress. The Iranian, Abbas Abdi, was one of the
students who directed the seizure of the Embassy in 1979. They had
not met since, and they managed to shake hands after a couple of
hours of public debate, although Abdi refused to express any
regrets for the forced imprisonment saying ``our whole nation was
held hostage for 25 years.''
 &HT;    The meeting was arranged by the Cyprus-based organization Center
for World Dialogue, one of the many non-governmental groups
springing up around the world with the aim of finding ways to
enable people to talk out their grievances when their governments
can't. It revealed, in a subtle way, what must be a raging argument
in Iran about opening up the country and making up with the United
States.
 &HT;    Although he castigated the media for failing to report what was
going on his country before the revolution, Abdi refused to say
anything about what is happening now. He wouldn't even say why he
was imprisoned for eight months in 1993 and since 1996 has been
banned from publishing or editing the newspaper with which he is
still associated. But he listed both punishments at the end of a
long resume otherwise full of his exploits on behalf of the
Khomeini revolution.
 &HT;    Evidently, the pressures for relaxation have not gone far enough
to make it safe to talk about them publicly abroad. But he did
come, and _ an ironic detail _ he was the only member of the
three-man panel who did not sport a traditional Islamic beard. The
American panelist and the French mediator both did.
 &HT;    The exchange showed how much each side still misconstrued the
history of their confrontation. Abdi said the students who invaded
the Embassy thought they would keep the hostages for a week at most
_ and that they would find support among that part of the American
population which had forced the United States out of Vietnam.
 &HT;    It is clear that the prime motive for the seizure was not to
challenge the United States but to force the resignation of the
Iranian premier and foreign minister who, the Khomeini
revolutionaries feared, might make a deal with the United States to
overthrow them. The mullahs had gained considerable power through
the Mossadegh revolution in 1951, but they were ousted by a
U.S.-backed coup which restored the Shah's power in 1953. The
memory still burns. Abdi said if relations were resumed with the
United States, it should be on the ``pre-1953 basis.''
 &HT;    Just before the hostages were taken, the then U.S. National
Security adviser Zbigniew Brzezinski had met the Iranian premier
and foreign minister at a big anniversary celebration in Algiers.
He told them, and repeated publicly, that the ``U.S. has nothing
against religion and Iran'' so they could get along. But as soon as
the Iranian officials returned, the Embassy crisis led to their
overthrow.
 &HT;    But the United States took it as a direct assault. President
Jimmy Carter said he would not go out of the White House Rose
Garden to campaign until he had secured the hostages' release.
Americans everywhere displayed yellow ribbons to show their
sympathy with the captured diplomats. The Teheran students
discovered to their surprise that they had a much bigger political
weapon than they had imagined, so they clung to it.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, Iraq's invasion of Iran mobilized national feeling
and helped the Khomeini regime to consolidate. Iranians claim that
the United States aided Iraq, which was not the case until late in
the eight-year war when Iran seemed on the way to victory. There is
every reason to believe that the push for modernization and
moderation now delicately but visibly stirring in Iran would have
begun a decade earlier but for Saddam Hussein's attack.
 &HT;    It is clearly a push from below, particularly from the young in
support of President Mohammed Khatemi who first suggested starting
cultural exchanges to warm up relations with the United States. But
Abdi, who obviously agrees, showed by his reticence that too warm a
response by Americans might hurt more than help his cause in the
conflict with hard-line fundamentalists.
 &HT;    It is time for the United States and Iran to find a way to
reconciliation. But grave past misreading of each other's
intentions and expectations remain a barrier, and the cloudy
situation in Iran makes assumptions of how best to go about it
unwise at this point. Good will isn't enough when historic wounds
still ache. Ignorance is a serious handicap.
 &HT;     (Flora Lewis is the former foreign-affairs columnist for The
New York Times.) 
 &HT;     c.1998 Flora Lewis 
<TEXT>
