<HEADLINE>
SUPERBUGS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    There was nothing out of the ordinary about the slender glass
tubes of blood that arrived in Sharon S. Rotun's laboratory late in
the afternoon of March 20, 1998.
 &HT;    A pale, stocky woman with the impatient manner of someone who is
overworked and underpaid, Rotun was the microbiology supervisor at
United Hospital Medical Center, a small community hospital in the
working-class town of Port Chester, N.Y., just north of Manhattan
in Westchester County.
 &HT;    The two blood cultures were among roughly a dozen sent to the
lab that day. Whoever ordered the testing was evidently in a hurry,
Rotun recalls, because he or she hadn't even bothered to scribble
the usual instructions on the accompanying slip.
 &HT;    The blood belonged to a 79-year-old Westchester County man, a
retired New York City narcotics detective who had been admitted to
the hospital earlier that day. For the past year and a half, the
detective's kidneys had been failing him, a condition that required
him to undergo dialysis three times a week.
 &HT;    On most days, he tolerated the tedious procedure with a smile.
But on the morning of March 20, the retired detective awoke in an
unusually sour mood.
 &HT;    ``He didn't want to eat; he didn't want to get dressed; he
didn't want to get washed,'' said his daughter Carole, who agreed
to be interviewed on the condition that she be identified only by
her first name and that her father not be identified at all.
 &HT;    She got him dressed, quickly served him breakfast and, despite
his protests, sent him to the local dialysis center. ``You have to
go,''' the daughter told him. ``You have no choice.''
 &HT;    The old man was feverish, short of breath and so disoriented he
could barely speak by the time the kidney specialist, Dr. Sam
Natarajan, saw him. Natarajan immediately suspected staphylococcus
aureas, a bacteria that frequently causes illness among dialysis
patients, who become infected when the microbes enter the
bloodstream along their intravenous lines.
 &HT;    The doctor performed just enough dialysis to clear the fluid
backed up in his patient's lungs _ a ``dry cleaning,'' in the argot
of renal disease _ and then called an ambulance to take the man to
the hospital. Twelve hours later, the patient was dead.
 &HT;    In what turned out to be the final hours of his life, the ailing
detective was hooked up to an intravenous drip of vancomycin, a
powerful antibiotic that has been the ultimate weapon against staph
for the last three decades. Doctors regard vancomycin as the drug
of last resort, the medicine they rely on to kill germs that are
too vicious to respond to anything else. Normally, vancomycin
begins attacking staph in the bloodstream immediately.
 &HT;    ``We call vancomycin `the big gun,''' Rotun says. Which is why,
when she first examined the lab results from the dead detective,
she did not believe what she saw.
 &HT;    A staph infection was indeed flourishing in the detective's
blood when he died. But not just any strain of staph. This was a
rare and unusually dangerous germ, a supermicrobe that
infectious-disease experts have been dreading for years. It goes by
the name of VISA, for Vancomycin Intermediate-Resistant
Staphylococcus Aureas, and it represents the bacterial world's most
potent counterattack against antibiotics.
 &HT;    As soon as the results of the detective's blood tests came in,
Rotun posted signs all over her laboratory, instructing her
subordinates not to give out any information. The last thing the
hospital needed, she thought, was a swarm of reporters generating
panic over a killer superbug that could be spreading through the
hospital's corridors.
 &HT;    Not even Carole, the detective's daughter, was told. Instead,
Rotun repeated the lab tests. Then, when she had convinced herself
there was no mistake, she picked up the phone and called her
longtime colleague and friend, Ginny McMath, United Hospital's
infection control officer.
 &HT;    ```I hope you're sitting down,''' Rotun told McMath. ``I think
we have the first VISA in New York State.''
 -0- 
 &HT;    In recent years, it has become fashionable in the media to warn
of the exotic new infectious diseases percolating in faraway lands.
The gruesome Ebola virus, which swept through Zaire three years
ago, has captured the public imagination in books and on film. But
while Hollywood has been busy making scary movies,
infectious-disease experts know that the bigger danger is in our
own backyard: garden variety germs that for decades have been so
easily felled by antibiotics that most people, including some
scientists, naively assumed they were no longer a threat.
 &HT;    For the past decade, however, scientists at the Federal Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta and all over the
world have been sounding alarm bells about the growth of antibiotic
resistance, a problem that has been fueled by patients who demand
antibiotics for every bout of the sniffles and by doctors who give
in to such demands. The list of dangerously virulent drug-resistant
microbes is growing all the time: streptococcus pneumoniae, which
causes pneumonia, childhood ear infections and meningitis;
mycobacterium tuberculosis, which causes TB, and neisseria
gonorrhoeae, which causes gonorrhea.
 &HT;    But none are as frightening to medical experts as the VISA
strains of staph. Within the past 18 months, the CDC has documented
the first four cases ever, the most recent being that of the New
York detective. Their emergence is an ominous harbinger of what Dr.
Stuart B. Levy, director of the Center for Adaptation Genetics and
Drug Resistance at Tufts, calls ``the worst thing that could happen
in clinical infectious disease.''
 &HT;    One reason for concern is that staph is a particularly common
and robust organism; it lives on the skin and in the nostrils of
otherwise healthy people as part of what scientists call the
``natural flora,'' where it is relatively harmless. But if it gains
access to the body through scrapes, cuts or surgical incisions, as
it often does, it can cause a range of ailments, from pus-oozing
cuts to sepsis, an often lethal infection of the bloodstream.
 &HT;    Children who scrape their knees are susceptible to staph, as are
housewives who cut their hands in the kitchen or anybody else with
an open wound. Should VISA strains become common, simple cuts and
scrapes could become mortal wounds.
 &HT;    To complicate matters, hospitals are already breeding grounds
for a host of dangerous bugs. Each year, nearly 90,000 patients in
the United States die of a hospital-acquired infection, and many of
those cases are theoretically treatable with antibiotics. Staph is
often the culprit, picking on vulnerable patients such as the
elderly, the immunocompromised and those undergoing surgery. The
emergence of an untreatable strain of staph would put virtually any
healthy person at risk, and could turn a bad situation into a
disastrous one.
 &HT;    As Levy says, ``Right now, we are still in most cases able to
use vancomycin. Now let's say we lose vancomycin. Where are the
deaths going to go? They're going to go up. This number could
double.''
 &HT;    Now that these bugs are figuring out ways to evade the very
miracle drugs that have always worked so well against them, there
is little on the horizon to keep the virulent new supergerms in
check. Joshua Lederberg, a Rockefeller University professor who is
widely regarded as one of the nation's leading authorities on
infectious disease, warns that far too little attention is being
paid to the threat of drug-resistant germs.
 &HT;    ``The odds of Ebola breaking out are quite low, but the stakes
are very high,'' Lederberg says. ``With antibiotic resistance, the
odds are certain and the stakes are just as high. It is happening
right under our noses.''
 &HT;    And it is happening at a particularly precarious moment, when
many hospitals are cutting back on services as they struggle to
survive the changing economics of health care. United Hospital in
Port Chester, for example, reflecting national trends, plans to
``outsource'' Rotun's lab. Meanwhile, drug manufacturers, which in
the early 1980s all but abandoned development of new antibiotics on
the theory that they were no longer needed, find themselves behind
the curve. They are hustling to invent new treatments and put them
on pharmacy shelves. And that is why the emergence of the
vancomycin-resistant strains is viewed as such a worrisome public
health threat.
 &HT;    The next generation of new antimicrobials is, by the industry's
own estimate, at least several years away, creating a dangerous
window in which the virulent new microbes might be able to spread
unchecked. If that happens, modern medicine might revert to the
days before penicillin, when sore throats could become fatal and
patients who walked into the hospital for routine surgery might be
carried out in coffins.
 &HT;    ``If we have no antibiotics, it reopens the whole question of
intrusive surgical procedures and vastly changes the calculus of
their safety,'' Lederberg says. In the pre-penicillin era, people
occasionally died while having their appendixes removed _ not
because the surgery itself was dangerous but because germs crept
into the patients' incisions, causing infections that spread to the
bloodstream and raged out of control.
 &HT;    ``Those days,'' Lederberg says, ``have a chance of coming back
if the drugs we have been relying on just stop working.''
 &HT;    As the race to find new drugs proceeds, supermicrobes such as
the one that infected the New York detective will undoubtedly
continue to flourish, leaving a trail of nervous public-health
officials and grieving families in their wake.
 &HT;    Three days after the former detective died, mourners gathered at
a stately stone church in the town of Harrison. On that same day,
with utmost secrecy, officials at United Hospital were frantically
trying to determine where the vancomycin-resistant staph bug came
from and, more important, whether the germ had spread.
 &HT;    The unenviable job of getting to the bottom of those questions
fell to Ginny McMath, the hospital's infection-control official.
The name of the detective was familiar to her; she remembered him
from a previous admission in January, when he was treated for a
staph infection that was resistant to methicillin.
 &HT;    He was given vancomycin for several weeks, but the episode
earned him an entry into a red loose-leaf binder where McMath
carefully catalogues every instance of a drug-resistant strain at
the hospital. The case fell under the worrisome category of MRSA _
methicillin resistant staph aureas.
 &HT;    When Rotun called with news of the detective's blood tests,
McMath was alarmed but not altogether surprised. A 79-year-old man
with a history of kidney disease and methicillin-resistant staph,
she knew, was the optimal candidate for a VISA strain.
 &HT;    ``It's sort of like the natural experiment that we would do in
the laboratory except that in this case, the patient is the Petri
dish,'' explains Fred C. Tenover, chief of the CDC's Nosocomial
Pathogens Laboratory Branch, the national reference laboratory for
hospital-acquired, or nosocomial, infections.
 &HT;    McMath immediately began to track down everyone who had contact
with the detective in the days before he died. Working with
Natarajan, the kidney specialist, she identified 44 people _
dialysis workers, doctors, nurses and family members _ who might
have been exposed to the deadly microbe. Each had their nostrils
and, in some cases, their hands cultured to see if they were
``colonized'' with the bug.
 &HT;    Making the notifications was a delicate task. The cause of the
detective's death had not been made public, and Natarajan and
McMath were careful not to reveal too much.
 &HT;    ``There's a fear that people won't want to come here,'' McMath
said. It was left to Natarajan to call the detective's family. ``I
told them that he had a staph infection, but there was a
peculiarity and we wanted to see if anybody else had the same type
of infection,'' he said. ``I didn't want to cause them any panic.''
 &HT;    That instinct _ not to cause panic _ is an understandable one,
experts say, but it can also lead to public-health problems of its
own. Suppressing information about a potentially deadly germ might
lead people who have been exposed to it not to take the testing
seriously. Indeed, Carole's daughter declined at first to be
cultured, thinking it was unnecessary.
 &HT;    On April 24, one month to the day after the detective's funeral,
Carole was driving to work when she heard a report over the car
radio that an elderly dialysis patient in Port Chester had died of
a rare staph infection. Her father was not identified, but it did
not take much to put two and two together.
 &HT;    ``I didn't realize how serious a bacteria it was until I heard
it on the radio,'' she said. ``It really upset me that they were
not more forthcoming.''
 &HT;    As it turned out, 14 of the 44 people who were tested were
carrying staph aureas. Of the 14, 2 _ a doctor and a patient _
harbored a germ that was resistant to methicillin. Genetic typing
conducted by Tenover's lab, however, found that none of these bugs
were identical to the one that infected Carole's father. It was an
encouraging sign; the deadly bug, it seems, is buried with the
detective.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, McMath's investigation, supervised by both state
health officials and the CDC, quickly established that neither the
hospital nor the dialysis center was a problem. Dr. David Ackman,
who directs the state's Bureau of Communicable Disease Control,
said infection control practices were meticulous at both. Even so,
Ackman said: ``We were very concerned. We wanted to make sure that
there weren't other people carrying this around.''
 &HT;    Ackman and other infectious-disease experts no longer view these
episodes as isolated incidents. They are more like bullets that are
becoming increasingly difficult to dodge. ``We were lucky,'' says
Tenover, who has no trouble spinning out scenarios for the near
future that are far worse.
 &HT;    ``The next time it may be somebody who is on an open hospital
ward, or maybe they have been in the hospital for several weeks, or
been a lot of places before their infection is recognized. Or it
might be someone in a nursing home that can spread it among 80
patients, in which case we are going to have a big job on our
hands.''
 &HT;     (Sheryl Gay Stolberg is a medical and science reporter in the
Washington bureau of The New York Times.) 
 &HT;     c.1998 The New York Times Magazine  
