<HEADLINE>
HEAVY SYMBOLISM AND HEAVY PETTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 2 Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``First Love, Last Rites'' strives to be a
realistic depiction of teen-age love's consuming passions and
devouring fears. But despite its low-key character interaction and
deliberate, observational atmosphere, it still comes off as
mannered and unnecessarily symbolic.
</P>
<P>
   Mildly eccentric behavior is nicely limned by Natasha Gregson
Wagner as a sex-loving Louisiana lass and Robert John Burke as her
loser/dreamer daddy.
</P>
<P>
   But the main character, Giovanni Ribisi's vacationing New Yorker
Joey, is an annoying little twit. He spends his time either
too-earnestly helping Burke's Henry pursue ridiculous moneymaking
schemes or hectoring Wagner's Sissel about their physically
satisfying but emotionally shaky relationship.
</P>
<P>
   This is Joey's first exposure to intimacy and, it's indicated,
Sissel's a little more experienced. We all know how easy it is to
act like an idiot at such a key juncture in your life; still, a
movie about a guy making nothing but the wrong moves, then
passively whining about it, gets old fast.
</P>
<P>
   Based on an Ian McEwan short story, the film has been removed
from a British industrial town to a sleepy bayou fishing community
by first-time feature director Jesse Peretz. Though a music-video
veteran, Peretz goes for a leisurely, conversation- and
performance-based style here. If the characters were more
intriguing or had more interesting things to say, this might have
been a good strategy. In this case, though, it slows already pokey
pacing to a crawl.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the, uh, artsy stuff. Sissel and Joey shack up
in a smelly one-room apartment, where she plays _ when she gets
uneasy _ 45-rpm vinyl records of pop hits you've never heard before
(though the story presumably takes place in the CD '90s).
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and there's a rat in the wall that stands for the forces
slowly eating away at their love. Similarly, Joey and Henry's
doomed eel-catching venture lets us know that for these folks, the
future is a slippery, probably hopeless proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Yeesh.
</P>
<P>
   At least the lovemaking scenes are good, maybe because they
aren't as burdened with misjudged metaphorical weight. When you
boil it all down, ``First Love, Last Rites'' is really just about
two kids who don't have anything between them except sexual
compatibility. Though they might think their problems are the
tragic stuff of high art, we all know that, once they fully grow
up, they'll probably remember each other fondly, if not very often.
</P>
<P>
   Which is still more of an impression than this slight but
self-serious movie will leave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
