<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0894 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SNAKE-MOVIE-LADN     08-06 1388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNAKE-MOVIE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURE DE PALMA _ AND MORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A new Brian De Palma movie is always a cause for
celebration and dread.
</P>
<P>
   Cineastes and suspense lovers alike know they can look forward
to shocking plot twists, outlandish-yet-accomplished homages to
great films of the past and virtuoso visual techniques. But they
also know that he sometimes opts for an incoherent commercial
production to keep his stock high with Hollywood studios, which
results in muddled messes like ``Bonfire of the Vanities'' and
``Mission: Impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, those who don't appreciate De Palma's
compositional gifts and outrageous imagery wish he'd stick to nice,
accessibly brutal entertainments like ``The Untouchables'' and
``Carrie,'' and leave the electric drills (``Body Double''), rape
abductions (``Casualties of War'') and homicidal transvestites
(``Dressed to Kill,'' ``Raising Cain'') well enough alone.
</P>
<P>
   His new thriller, ``Snake Eyes,'' finds De Palma trying to
satisfy both audience segments. It's relatively restrained _ for De
Palma _ on the gory graphics and violence against women fronts
(this time, he lost a fight with the MPAA to get a PG-13 rating
rather than an R, as opposed to his usual struggles to dodge X's
and NC-17's). But it also boasts some of De Palma's most
spectacular formal flourishes, beginning with the most complicated,
20-minute Steadicam shot in movie history.
</P>
<P>
   But it also has a protagonist as unsympathetic as any in the De
Palma canon and a story line that preview audiences are finding
hard to swallow. Nicolas Cage plays Rick Santoro, a corrupt,
over-the-top Atlantic City cop who finds himself embroiled in the
assassination of a high-level government official. He then has to
locate his long-lost decency while investigating the mystery, which
involves his unlikely best friend (Gary Sinise's navy commander
Kevin Dunne), takes place at a championship prizefight and
incorporates a hurricane approaching the packed arena.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so the plot (by David Koepp, a writer on De Palma's
``Mission: Impossible'' and ``Carlito's Way'') will prove a bit
excessive for some tastes. But with this director, something has to
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had extreme harsh criticisms; anyone who can survive
`Bonfire of the Vanities' and still be here is kind of a miracle in
itself, not to mention `Body Double,''' De Palma notes in his usual
blunt manner. ``But, basically, I have to make the movies that I
think are right. The ideas or stories or emotions have to stir me,
and if nobody agrees with me ... Too bad!''
</P>
<P>
   He admits lavishing more attention on ``Snake Eyes'' staging and
high-tech electronics jokes (another favorite De Palma motif that's
popped up in ``Mission,'' ``Blow Out,'' ``Dressed to Kill'' and
others) than on, perhaps, molding a waterproof narrative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like suspense movies because they're visual, and I think you
see very few directors working visually today,'' De Palma says. ``I
do tend to focus on the visual image more than the story in many
films. It's a big, white canvas up there _ what are you filling it
with? Closeups of people talking? I hope not.''
</P>
<P>
   Tough as he sounds, De Palma is enough of a craftsman to try to
tell the best story he can by whatever means necessary _ indeed,
Koepp wrote ``Snake Eyes'' from the director's original idea.
</P>
<P>
   And it should not be forgotten that he gave no less an actor
than Robert De Niro his start in movies with the 1968 ``Greetings''
and the 1970 ``Hi, Mom!'' He also directed Sean Connery to an
Academy Award in ``The Untouchables,'' and elicited some of the
best performances of their careers from Al Pacino (``Scarface,''
``Carlito's''), Sean Penn (``Casualties''), Sissy Spacek
(``Carrie'') and John Travolta (``Blow Out'').
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really equally devoted to both camera and his actors,''
says Cage, an Oscar winner (``Leaving Las Vegas'') known for taking
enormous risks with his performances. ``Brian loves actors, so you
get that sense that you can trust him. I felt like I could really
go for it with this character, take chances and get kind of wild,
and that he would use the right takes. I've always been a huge fan
of Brian's, and I felt safe with him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``De Palma's an artist, so he's always going to do something
interesting,'' adds highly respected stage, screen and television
actor Sinise. ``Sometimes it's going to work better than others,
but there's always some kind of strong vision there. That always
gives an actor a sense of confidence; you want to be following
somebody who has a real point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   Never more so than in that opening traveling shot, which begins
with a TV news report on the stormy Boardwalk, then shifts inside
the packed Atlantic City Arena (actually, the old Montreal Forum,
which was restocked with up to 14,000 extras, many of them diehard
Canadiens fans who were stoked to be back in their old sports
shrine). It follows Santoro as he weaves through the throngs, bets
with bookies, roughs up gangsters, talks to his wife on one cell
phone line and his girlfriend on another, and generally reveals his
entire character while leading a tour of the massive, teeming
facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``These extremely long takes would go on and on and on, with
mountains of dialogue,'' Cage recalls of the eye-popping shot,
which was filmed in complexly choreographed, five-minute intervals.
``There was so much adrenaline going on in these takes; we knew we
were doing something exciting. But when you're moving and talking
that fast and the camera's going with you and all of those people
are there, you get into this buzz that's undeniable. You can't
really think, you're like an animal moving and talking on instinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``That does create a certain mania,'' Cage adds with a smile.
``Good thing I trusted Brian De Palma to use material that would
not embarrass me.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of faith. De Palma admits that getting everything
to work on cue for the Steadicam shot was a challenge even for
someone of his formidable formal prowess.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how everything is supposed to be, but you're trying
to get through it and keep everyone else lively and up,'' the
director says. ``That's especially hard when you're doing stuff
that's frenetic, because people get tired if they keep repeating it
and you don't get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And in those Steadicam shots, so much stuff happens that you
can't predict, and you have to adjust the shot for that. The
cameraman can't get to a certain position, you've got crossing crew
people running into each other, you've got extras having to be
moved from one place to another _ it's a very complicated logistics
problem. But it's also a lot of fun to shoot those scenes, like a
high-wire act without a net. It's very exhilarating.''
</P>
<P>
   Once things calm down after the, um, blowout establishing shot,
De Palma's trademark cynicism kicks in. Meanwhile, Santoro tries to
piece together the plot behind the crime via a complicated series
of flashbacks from conflicting witnesses' points of view and taped
footage from surveillance cameras placed all around the arena.
</P>
<P>
   It connects crime, conspiracy and deceptive/revealing imagery in
a way that is pure De Palma.
</P>
<P>
   ``This stuff has always interested me, and it's been in a lot of
my movies,'' the filmmaker says. ``I've always kept up with what's
going on on the political scene, read all the assassination books,
and the influence of the media has always fascinated me because
it's become a really huge thing through my lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we can get cynical enough anymore. It's
incredible; when I watch what goes on on television, I say, `This
is unbelievable.' For everything, there's a left view and a right
view. Nothing's truth anymore, there's just a version of the spin.
How did we get like that? The camera lies all the time, and we see
it on television constantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Another incendiary statement, especially from a guy who's used
his mastery of cinematic technique to manipulate, appall and
mesmerize audience like nobody else in his image-inundated
generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're filmmakers,'' De Palma retorts with a rare, yet
appropriately sardonic, laugh. ``We're fiction-makers. We're not
pretending to tell the truth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
