<SLUG> BC-GENOCIDE-MINISTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. JUDGE ORDERS MINISTER TO FACE WAR CRIMES COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Stands for TEXAS-UN)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ A federal judge has ruled that a Seventh-day
Adventist minister should be turned over to a United Nations war
crimes tribunal on charges he helped slaughter people who took
refuge in his church during Rwanda's civil strife in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge John Rainey's decision marks the latest
round in a two-year legal battle and is the first time in history
that a person arrested on U.S. soil would be handed over to a U.N.
tribunal, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Elizaphan Ntakirutimana, 74, was taken to the Webb County Jail
after he was arrested at his son's home in Laredo on Wednesday.
Ntakirutimana, who is from Rwanda, has repeatedly denied any role
in the ethnic bloodshed that occurred in the Central African
nation.
</P>
<P>
   The war crimes tribunal, based in Tanzania, has accused
Ntakirutimana of leading attackers armed with machetes, grenades
and guns in a murderous April 1994 rampage that killed dozens of
people who were hiding in the church.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Rwanda was in the throes of a bloody feud between
the country's dominant ethnic groups, the Hutus and Tutsis, strife
that killed an estimated 500,000 and sent 2 million refugees
fleeing to neighboring nations. Most of those killed, including
those in Ntakirutimana's church, were Tutsis. Ntakirutimana, a
Hutu, also is charged with being a fugitive of a foreign
government.
</P>
<P>
   He suffers from a number of health problems.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman at U.N. headquarters in New York welcomed the
court decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It represents a step forward in ending impunity by bringing
those responsible for tragedy to court,'' Jessica Jiji said in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Attorney General Ramsey Clark, who is representing
Ntakirutimana, was given 30 days to appeal the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Clark has questioned the legality of the war crimes tribunal and
said that Ntakirutimana was a religious man who was being framed by
tribal hatred in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   The elderly man's family has said he's being persecuted by
members of the new government in Rwanda who resented his ethnicity
and his power as a minister in the 265,000-member Seventh-day
Adventist Church in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Don DeGabrielle said Ntakirutimana would
be held until the judge orders marshals to hand the man over to the
State Department, which would transfer him to the Tanzania-based
tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as his actual guilt or innocence, that's up to the
tribunal to decide,'' DeGabrielle said.
</P>
<P>
   Ntakirutimana faces up to life in prison, if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rainey's 61-page ruling pushes aside a federal magistrate's
December 1997 decision that Ntakirutimana should not be turned over
to the tribunal because his arrest violated the U.S. Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   In an appeal filed to Rainey, prosecutors had said U.S.
Magistrate Judge Marcel Notzon's decision was an ``embarrassment''
to the U.S. government and threatened to harm future efforts to get
countries to turn over suspected war criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Jiji said the tribunal expects to issue its first two sentences
in the next few weeks after the recent convictions of Rwanda's
former interim prime minister and a regional government official.
</P>
<P>
   Ntakirutimana had spent 15 months behind bars until Notzon ruled
he be freed.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. tribunal has a dozen witnesses who supposedly would
testify at the trial of Ntakirutimana, but their identities are
being kept secret, according to court documents.
</P>
</TEXT>
