A0909 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYAN-VETS-HNS &LR;      08-06 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-VETS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS ADVISE A GO-SLOW APPROACH IN TALKING ABOUT WAR STORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ ``Saving Private Ryan,'' the critically acclaimed
film by Steven Spielberg about World War II, has been a catalyst
for people seeking to learn more from veterans who saw combat.
</P>
<P>
   For those veterans, however, the subject can be fraught with
painful and emotional memories. So can watching the movie,
particularly the carnage depicted in the film's opening 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans hospitals reportedly have been inundated with calls
from veterans seeking help in dealing with disturbing memories
prompted by the film's realism.
</P>
<P>
   It's a reflection of why approaching veterans to talk about
their war experiences needs to be done with sensitivity, mental
health professionals say.
</P>
<P>
   James Garrett, clinical psychologist for the Veterans Affairs
Medical Center in Albany, said he and his colleagues at the center
were encouraging family members to ask veterans about the war but
to do so with care.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are classic questions you can ask that we use with
veterans,'' said Garrett, who is a Vietnam veteran. ``Such as,
`What did you do in the war?' `Where did you serve?' `What was your
job?' `When were you there?' Those are lead questions to start a
conversation. Give them the opportunity to tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that everyone experiences traumatic events such as
war differently, Garrett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can go to war and be changed in the same way. They see
and do things that most people have no concept of. Therefore, if
they choose not to talk and answer even the most basic questions,
switch gears and change to a different subject,'' Garrett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often, veterans would rather talk with groups of other
veterans, where there's an understanding of what happened between
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stephen Jankowski, a clinical social worker and director of
the Mental Health Clinic at the Veterans Affairs Medical Center in
Albany, said it was important to not probe or pressure an unwilling
veteran into talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do want to talk, always start out with general
fact-sharing questions to bring the conversation into perspective
for the veteran,'' Jankowski said. ``Sometimes they may just want
to share what the customs or politics were like in a country.
That's a way to initiate the conversation, rather than asking a
more emotional question. It's always better to allow the person to
say what they want to say and not what they are not ready to talk
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary Duncan, clinical manager of community-based veterans
clinics for the veterans hospital in Albany, said most people who
have never been in a war don't have a clue of what one is asked to
do in battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``War is brutal,'' Duncan stressed. ``Many of the veterans were
ill-prepared to handle such horrific situations, let alone just the
sheer stress of being there.
</P>
<P>
   ``This movie will bring back many memories, especially to those
who have suppressed them over the years. Don't forget that many men
and women came home from wars with no closure or recognition,
especially from Vietnam. No one wanted to hear about what they went
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Jankowski said that under the right circumstances it can be
healthy, even cathartic, for veterans to talk about their war
experiences. Not being able to do so can also take its toll on some
veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carrying secrets around isn't healthy for anyone,'' he said.
``Holding these traumatic images in has caused many veterans to
become depressed, have sleepless nights or ongoing nightmares over
the years, or to vent in other ways, such as turning to drugs,
alcohol and suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Veterans often don't talk about their experiences with their
spouses, because they realize that they don't understand the
trauma,'' Jankowski said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
