<HEADLINE>
_EXERCISE MAY NOT CUT RISK OF BREAST CANCER   
 _FOR ATHLETES-TO-BE, A CALL FOR HEART TESTS   
 _OPHTHALMOLOGISTS BACK USE OF AIR BAGS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Exercise may not cut risk of breast cancer
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new report deals a blow to the hope that strenuous exercise,
particularly in adolescence, could reduce women's risk of breast
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   That notion had gained support from studies that found a
protective effect of exercise. The hypothesis is that exercise
reduces a woman's exposure to estrogen by delaying the onset of
menstruation and making menstrual cycles longer.
</P>
<P>
   But an analysis of data from the Nurses' Health Study II, which
appears in the current Journal of the National Cancer Institute,
did not find any link between a woman's self-reported history of
exercise and her risk of breast cancer. Data from 104,468 women who
were aged 25 to 42 when they entered the study in 1989 showed no
difference in breast cancer risk between those who had engaged in
strenuous activity at least twice a week or more most of the year
during adolescence and those who had not done strenuous workouts.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was there an association between strenuous activity in more
recent years and breast cancer risk, found the authors, headed by
Beverly Rockhill at the Channing Laboratory of Brigham and Women's
Hospital, Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In an accompanying editorial, Joanne F. Dorgan of the National
Cancer Institute noted that physical activity is one of the few
potentially modifiable breast cancer risk factors, and that more
study on the possible link is needed. However, she wrote, ``given
the current evidence, recommendations to premenopausal women to
increase their physical activity with the specific aim of
preventing breast cancer would be premature.''
</P>
<P>
   But for postmenopausal women, in whom obesity is a breast cancer
risk factor, recommending physical activity to remain trim is
reasonable, she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; For athletes-to-be, a call for heart tests
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thorough heart checkups of young athletes before they begin
competing in sports can prevent many of the sudden deaths that now
occur, according to a new study from Italy. But US heart
specialists say such a comprehensive program is not likely in this
country because of the cost.
</P>
<P>
   Italy has required precompetition heart screening for the past
20 years, and the government pays the bills. In the current issue
of the New England Journal of Medicine, physicians from the
University of Padua and the Italian National Health Service report
on screening tests of 33,735 young athletes from 1979 to 1996 in
the Veneto region of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The tests, including taking family histories and administering
an electrocardiogram, led to disqualifying 22 athletes because of
hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, a heart muscle disease that is a
common cause of sudden cardiac death in young people. As a result,
only one sudden death from that disease occurred in the remaining
athletes over the period, while there were 16 sudden deaths from
the disease in nonathletes who hadn't been screened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows the power of a comprehensive screening program,''
said Dr. Barry Maron of the Minneapolis Heart Institute, and
chairman of an American Heart Association panel that drew up
guidelines for athlete screening. He said screening in the United
States varies widely on a state-to-state basis, and that a
government-funded effort is unlikely here.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Ophthalmologists back use of air bags
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even if you have only one good eye, you should keep your auto
air bags connected rather than disable them for fear of an ocular
injury, specialists say, making a strong argument against
disconnecting the safety devices.
</P>
<P>
   The American Academy of Ophthalmology issued the statement this
week after one of its members was asked by the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration whether there were vision-related
reasons to fear accidental air bag deployment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The air bag is more likely to prevent than to cause serious
ocular injury,'' said Dr. Dante Pieramici, the academy member.
``Overall, the life-saving benefits of air bags far outweigh the
risk of ocular injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Air bags have caused eye injuries ranging from bruises to
eyeball ruptures to blindness, but have saved more than 2,500 lives
since 1987, the academy statement pointed out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
