<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOB-MERCURIO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOB WITNESS SAYS HE WAS `TRAPPED' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was a secret that mob soldier Angelo ``Sonny''
Mercurio was willing to go to prison to keep: He did not want the
world, particularly the underworld, to know he was an FBI
informant.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there he was Wednesday, reluctantly testifying in federal
court in Boston for a second day about how he helped the FBI pull
off a major law enforcement coup, the 1989 bugging of a Mafia
baptism ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was giving them information, I was a stool pigeon,'' said
Mercurio, 62, as he sat in the witness box staring across the
courtroom at the defendants in a federal racketeering case: reputed
mob boss Francis ``Cadillac Frank'' Salemme, Stephen ``The
Rifleman'' Flemmi and Robert DeLuca.
</P>
<P>
   It was a strange series of events that put Mercurio on the
stand.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Flemmi and fugitive South Boston crime boss James
``Whitey'' Bulger _ both valued informants _ told FBI Special Agent
John Connolly that Mercurio's restaurant in Boston's Prudential
Center was a new mob hangout.
</P>
<P>
   A bug planted inside Vanessa's Italian Food Shop captured
Mercurio and several cohorts shaking down two elderly bookmakers
for $500,000 and talking about their sports betting operation.
</P>
<P>
   Agents &UR;  &LR; raided the restaurant and Mercurio's Malden home in
1987, but seized only one football card. Mercurio testified
Wednesday he had ``inside information'' that the restaurant had
been bugged by the FBI and that he suspected then that the bureau
had enough evidence to eventually indict him.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of that year, Mercurio testified, he bumped into
Connolly and, while talking about the raid, boasted, ``We're
getting better information than you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the FBI was conducting a leak investigation. Later,
according to Mercurio, Connolly came back to him and said,
``Listen, we know who the guy is who is giving you information. You
help us figure who he's working through and we won't let your
friends know.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, an FBI clerk was later fired for leaking confidential
information about the ongoing investigation to a local Mafioso via
her brother.
</P>
<P>
   Mercurio testified he reluctantly worked as an FBI informant for
the next two years because ``I felt trapped.''
</P>
<P>
   Dismissing the suggestion that Flemmi, an informant since 1965,
personally recruited him to cooperate with the FBI, Mercurio
testified, ``No, I never knew he was a stool pigeon.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, according to Mercurio, the FBI asked him if Bulger and
Flemmi were involved in drugs and he told them that as far as he
knew, ``they're like everybody else. They'll shake down a drug
dealer because they're open season.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Mercurio told the FBI that the Patriarca crime family
planned to induct four new members _ including DeLuca _ in a secret
ceremony at a Medford home on Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   When pressured to wear a wire during the ceremony, Mercurio
testified, he told agents: ``I ain't testifying. I ain't wearing no
wires. Forget about it. Whatever you do, you do. If everybody gets
busted, I get busted with them.''
</P>
<P>
   But months before he was indicted on racketeering charges in
March 1990 along with 20 other mobsters, Mercurio fled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure the longer you can stay away, the better you do,''
Mercurio told US District Judge Mark Wolf Wednesday. ``The guys who
stay away did better than the guys who went to trial.''
</P>
<P>
   When Mercurio was nabbed in June 1994 in Georgia, he told the
FBI to ``burn'' his informant file, insisting he'd rather face a
lengthy prison term than reveal his cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the FBI has revealed Mercurio's informant status, Wolf
is considering a government request to reduce his nine-year prison
term.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
