<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0918 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAYAN-TRAGEDY-BOS &LR;      08-06 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYAN-TRAGEDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRAGIC END TO A DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BEDFORD, Mass. _ His 2,200-mile flight from wartime
atrocities in his Central American homeland carried him to this
fishing capital's pungent waterfront, where he lived quietly and
died horribly, screaming in a language few understood.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Ajqui, 40, was part of a nearly invisible industrial
underground, achieving an identity in death that was inconceivable
in a life of struggle and flight and toil in a gritty blue-collar
workplace increasingly foreign to most US workers.
</P>
<P>
   He was crushed to death last week in a vat that steams and mixes
fish guts into fertilizer as his 19-year-old son, Francisco, stood
nearby _ close enough to hear his father's haunting screams in his
native Mayan tongue: ``Help me! Help me! Get me out of here!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the most tragic thing I've ever heard of,'' said
Earl R. Chase Sr., president of the American Indian Friends
Coalition Inc. ``He came here to help protect his family. He was
doing work that most of us wouldn't do and he took it gladly. It's
dirty. It's dangerous. They're working with razor-sharp knives.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when your family is starving, you do it. That's why he
jumped into that vat. He was told to clean it, and he did it with
no questions asked.''
</P>
<P>
   As authorities investigate, lawyers strategize, and officials of
the fish-processing plant ponder its liability, Ajqui's co-workers
and friends in a closely knit community of an estimated 2,000 Mayan
Indians here grieve a death more horrifying than they thought
possible in what they unabashedly consider a land of opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so very sad,'' said Anibal, a Mayan and a friend of Ajqui,
who asked, through an interpreter that his last name not be used.
``The rest of his children are too little to work and the family is
going to be just devastated financially.''
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Ajqui grew up in the Quiche region of Guatemala, part of
an estimated 80 percent of that nation's population that is
ethnically Indian, most of whom speak an indigenous language.
</P>
<P>
   Acquaintances said Ajqui's life was threatened two years ago by
members of an army engaged in a 36-year civil war that subjected
the country's Indians to massive human rights violations,
particularly in villages where they were they were suspected by the
Guatemalan military of collaborating with leftist guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   The father of four sons and two daughters concluded the only way
to protect and provide for his family was to leave them behind. He
immigrated to the United States two years ago, joined a year later
by his oldest son, Francisco. His employers knew him by his
mother's last name, Gutierrez. But he preferred his native Mayan
name, Ajqui, which carries the full flavor of a civilization that
thrived from nearly 2,000 before Christ until the Spanish conquest
in the 16th century.
</P>
<P>
   The New Bedford that Antonio Ajqui discovered in 1996 was a
hardscrabble tableaux of tenement housing, low wages, and
transportation by bicycle. But compared with conditions at home, it
was a workingman's haven.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the waterfront of what was once the world's whaling
capital in the 18th century is a collection of red-brick plastic
factories, grimy marine terminals, and processing plants which
package and sell fish around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Ajqui was a temporary worker, sent by his bosses to firms around
the city which needed fast help at a modest price. For the last two
months, he and his son worked at Atlantic Coast Fisheries, a
yellow-and-tan corrugated steel building surrounded by a chain-link
fence topped with barbed wire.
</P>
<P>
   Employees at packing houses here were represented by a seafood
workers union until the late 1980s. Wages at the houses declined
after the unions were busted, and the face of a historically
evolving workforce changed again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fish industry is going through a transition,'' said Harvey
Mickelson, a New Bedford attorney who has represented many
waterfront firms over the decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's becoming more mechanized and it's based on product being
processed and value added to it,'' he said. ``It's become an
industry that distributes frozen and finished product throughout
the world. The size of the plant that this gentleman was in would
not have been in existence 20 or 25 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   But last Thursday Atlantic Coast Fisheries, located just off a
boulevard named for Herman Melville, author of ``Moby Dick,'' was
running at full throttle.
</P>
<P>
   The company employs 200 people who process fish for sale in the
US and overseas.
</P>
<P>
   At mid-morning, Ajqui and a co-worker were undertaking the daily
cleaning of a 10-by-20-foot vat whose rotating bars helped mix the
fish parts. Officials said that when Ajqui yanked on a hose he was
using, it snared the machinery's on switch and started it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he pulled the hose, it pulled the switch and it
started,'' a plant supervisor told the New Bedford Standard-Times.
``It got the foot and rolled him around in it.'' The local
newspaper said workers reported that there was no sign posted
instructing employees to disable the machine's power source before
the vat is cleaned, and that supervisors did not make that
procedure clear.
</P>
<P>
   Gary W. Orlacchio, a Boston attorney representing the Ajqui
family, said death, attributed to crushing injuries to the abdomen,
did not come quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got shredded from the waist down,'' Orlacchio said. ``I
can't think of a more horrible way to die.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Bristol County district attorney's office
said Wednesday it had completed its probe without filing criminal
charges.
</P>
<P>
   The Occupational Safety and Health Administration is
investigating. The plant was fined $1,200 in 1989 for 10 violations
of the safety code, four of them serious. It was fined $5,000 in
1992 for 15 violations, 13 of them serious, including a citation
for failure to adopt procedures to ensure that machinery could not
be turned on while it is being maintained. The plant has been
operated under new ownership since last March. Officials there
declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how to interpret this any other way than to say
it's terribly insensitive to have a working population that is not
familiar with the language exposed to hazardous conditions and not
make darn sure that at least the OSHA requirements are being met,''
said Harry R. Carreiro, an outreach specialist with the Greater New
Bedford Fishermen's Family Emergency Center. ``Whether he forgot to
do it or should have done it, you can't hold the victim
accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   Ajqui's son was not available for comment. Friends said he was
receiving counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers are preparing a workers' compensation case that could be
settled quickly. A a civil suit could take years. Asked what
damages he might seek from a jury, Orlacchio said, ``A lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Ajqui's body was being prepared at a funeral home for its return
to Guatemala on a flight Thursday. Atlantic Coast Fisheries,
Orlacchio said, is paying the air fare.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably the most horrible thing that can happen,'' said
Mickelson. ``You're trying to do better for your family. Your son
is with you. You're working under not the best conditions and you
end up in a situation where your family will suffer for the rest of
their lives. A tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Donations to a fund established to help the Ajqui family may be
sent to the American Indian Friends Coalition, P.O. Box 50165, New
Bedford, Mass., 02745.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
