<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRY-UP OFFENSE IS MANDATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ In earlier times, times of potential rather
than necessity, it might have seemed ludicrous for Pete Carroll to
give Drew Bledsoe and his offensive mates this kind of message
after one quarter of ugly exhibition football _ you're going to
play the next game until you get it right.
</P>
<P>
   After all, these were the Patriots, the offensive machine. After
all, this was Drew Bledsoe, the quarterback with the golden arm. If
there were questions about the Patriots, they were seldom about
passing the football.
</P>
<P>
   But Bledsoe Tuesday ended his weekly 15-minute media gabfest
with a half-joke: ``I expect us to be sharp this Sunday when we
play the Vikings. I expect our passing game to be efficient this
Sunday. If it's not, I'll be very disappointed and we'll stay and
play until it is sharp. Heh-heh, you may see us play the whole
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said the starters will play ``until we get something
done ... and I don't know how many plays that will be.''
</P>
<P>
   The offensive starters seemed completely out of rhythm last
Sunday in San Francisco. Ordinarily, that is merely a wrinkle to
iron out in later exhibition games, but New England needs at least
one part of its offense _ passing _ to become reliable quickly
because the other half _ running _ has so many questions. And the
sooner the passing game finds a rhythm, the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously aren't at the point where we want to be,'' said
Bledsoe, ``but we are going to be there by the time we play these
next four games.''
</P>
<P>
   In ordinary times, such talk of finding passing rhythm one week
into August would seem silly. For one thing, teams generally have
only a skeleton of a game plan, if that, for their first
exhibition, and if the opposing defense does something unexpected,
there is little in the miniature game plan to call upon. Bledsoe
said this generally was what happened in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Niners did, and what they obviously have been working
on in their camp, was some cover two where they walk their corners
up and play thir safeties over the top, so they were really trying
to take away our outside receivers,'' said Bledsoe. ``And most of
our fast timing (passes) is with our outside receivers, but the
Niners took those guys away, and they played it in such a way that
the stuff we've been working on and focusing on in camp wasn't
really a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   So while the Patriots went into the game wanting to work on the
quick timing passes to the outside, the 49ers had the precise
defense to slow that, ``and that's one of the reasons why we
weren't as sharp as we wanted to be,'' said Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Bledsoe also didn't throw the inside passes well to
counter the defense and was burned when he didn't see San
Francisco's Chris Doleman drop back in a zone blitz, where he
picked off a pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal through camp is to build and continually improve
going into the regular season,'' said Bledsoe. ``And I think we're
doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   For many reasons _ not the least of which is that the Patriots
have no established runner _ this offense will be Bledsoe's, and
all football eyes in New England and nationally will focus on how
well he does. And as usual, Bledsoe is going into the season with a
new offensive coordinator and a new quarterback coach.
</P>
<P>
   He is working with his fourth quarterback coach in four seasons
(Jack Reilly now, Carl Smith last season, Chris Palmer in 1996, and
Ray Perkins in '95) and his third offensive coordinator in three
seasons (Ernie Zampese now, Larry Kennan last season, and Perkins
before that). If Bledsoe came into pro football a rough-cut gem
needing a master polisher, he has ended up being passed from hand
to hand.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristically, Bledsoe downplayed the constant change. He
said the switch in offensive schemes from Kennan's to Zampese's is
far from as drastic as was the turnover from Perkins and Bill
Parcells to Kennan last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an adjustment, but not as big an adjustment as it has
been in the past,'' said Bledsoe. ``We basically have the same
terminology and basically the same offense as we had (in 1997), but
there is a different emphasis now as far as getting the ball out
quicker. It's not as big an adjustment as it was in the past, but
it's still an adjustment in philosophy and timing and so on. But
we're going to make that adjustment.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly used virtually the same words that Blesoe's new coaches
used last year, saying he thought Bledsoe was a fine passer while
watching him from afar and is even more impressed in person.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us were real happy after the 49er game, and Drew
wasn't happy, either,'' said Reilly, who is with his fifth team in
six seasons, having previously worked for the Cowboys, Rams,
Raiders, and Chargers. ``We went into the game with the idea of
running the football. That was a major emphasis at the beginning of
the game, and as we moved on, we lightened up a little bit. But I
feel totally confident. We have five preseason games to get ready
for the Denver game.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said the new offense should not be too complicated to
pick up quickly. ``I think it's just a matter of getting used to
different language and different timing and different depth (in
pass routes) than he had before,'' said Reilly. ``It's just a
matter of getting to where they feel comfortable with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said he and Bledsoe have similar personalities (``We're
both low-key; I don't get super emotional about things, and neither
does he''), but that is neither an advantage nor a disadvantage.
``I think the important thing is how you get the job done,'' said
Reilly, ``and how you handle yourself under emotional strain and
stress. And I think Drew handles it very, very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said he ``was disappointed at the way we performed''
against the 49ers, ``and we've got a ways to go. Fortunately,
though, we've got time.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing time, too. Carroll is determined that Bledsoe find his
rhythm Sunday night against Minnesota. And if you see some big guys
in Patriot uniforms tossing the football around in the Foxboro
Stadium parking lot Sunday at midnight, don't be surprised if the
guy with the No. 11 on his back is Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
