<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENIUS-CAMP-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VACATION ACADEMY WHERE GENIUS BLOSSOMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA YUEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ It's well past the 11 p.m. bedcheck for the
13- to 17-year-olds attending the Research Science Institute, but
not one of the summer visitors is tucked in with the lights out.
</P>
<P>
   The masses are squeezed into a sweaty dorm lounge, moving their
bodies to the bass in their makeshift dance club. Those not dancing
are playing Ping-Pong or Foosball. In a moonlit courtyard, a few
stragglers chat idly about the film ``Austin Powers,'' or dating,
or astrophysics.
</P>
<P>
   No customary lights-out rule exists for the campers in this
summer colony, because the institute is not a traditional camp.
Housed at Massachusetts Institute of Technology, these teenagers
have been handed the freedom to make great discoveries _ about
science and about themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have reactive minds. Who are we to say how they're
learning or when they're learning?'' says director Mark Saul. ``We
can't say that if they're playing Nintendo or Dungeons &AMP; Dragons,
nothing is going on in their minds. They get treated like adults,
which adolescents crave.''
</P>
<P>
   Saul may seem lenient for an overnight summer-program
administrator, but his motives are clear: He's out to nurture the
brains of these teenagers, considered some of the top prospects to
propel their nations' technological prominence. For six weeks every
summer, 80 of the world'smost gifted high school seniors _ 53
Americans and 27 international students this year _ conduct
college- or graduate-level independent research in math and
science.
</P>
<P>
   In their high schools, some have been branded ``nerds'' and
``geeks,'' or at the very least ``the smart kids.'' But because
everyone at the institute is the smart kid, students say here they
can walk away from the stereotypes and find other components of
their identities.
</P>
<P>
   ``When something that has defined you socially for so long is
stripped away, it's nice to know there is still a lot left of
you,'' says Jeremy England, 16, of Durham, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   According to standardized gauges of intellectual precocity, the
students are nearly uniform. All have scored in the 99th percentile
on their PSATs. Many have skipped a grade _ or two or three. Only
55 of 1,000 American applicants were accepted, defying odds more
dismal than the selectivity rates at the colleges they will attend.
If past institute classes are prologue, more than half of them will
move on to Harvard or MIT after high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get here, you realize how special you are _ and how
special you aren't,'' says Charles Mathis, 17, of Watkinsville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The institute, a program of the Center for Excellence in
Education in McLean, Va., was founded 15 years ago by the late
Admiral Hyman G. Rickover and lawyer Joann DiGennaro. The outspoken
``father of the nuclear navy'' bemoaned slipping academic standards
in America's public schools. It roamed from university to
university, finally finding a home in 1992 at MIT.
</P>
<P>
   The Rickoids _ as the students like to be called _ work up to 12
hours a day in internships at science and computer labs, zoos,
research centers, and hospitals in the Boston area. At night, the
boys wear suits and ties, the girls dresses, to attend lectures.
The program concludes tomorrow after a final ``hell week'' of
completing papers and making oral presentations in all-night
caffeinated camp-outs at the computer labs. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hanging with peers
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In this intellectual haven, stimulation comes from teachers, to
be sure, but also from comrades with whom these young scholars can
slow dance and play ultimate Frisbee. For many of them, this is the
first time academic exhilaration has fused with social nourishment
in the same setting _ a summer colony of colossal brainpower and
young blood.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen young men crowd around a Ping-Pong table and gush
admiringly about a certain girl. But it's not the usual locker-room
talk one might expect of teenage boys. ``She's so smart, she should
just clone herself,'' one says.
</P>
<P>
   At the institute's talent show, one 13-year-old girl sings the
``Titanic'' theme song _ after rewriting the lyrics as a paean to
neutrinos, atomic particles that have almost no mass.
</P>
<P>
   But despite their intellectual prowess, the Rickoids can be
quite down to earth. Like other teenagers, they wear T-shirts and
gym shoes, play musical instruments and varsity team sports, and
exchange prized lines from ``Austin Powers.'' All that came as a
pleasant surprise to students who had internalized their peers'
stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought everyone would have thick glasses, high pants, and
squeaky voices _ the typical nerd,'' says Lavanya Parachuru, 15, of
Duluth, Ga. ``We try to be normal; we try to fit in.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it is with painful modesty that some Rickoids disclose
their achievements. England, a student at Phillips Exeter Academy,
was in third grade when his father, a professor at the University
of New Hampshire, asked a fellow chemistry prof to show his kid
around the lab.
</P>
<P>
   It started out with lessons on the structure of atoms _ ``neat
little chemistry things a little kid can appreciate,'' recalls
England, a lanky boy with a mop of brown hair. By the eighth grade,
he finished calculus and was studying the ``jiggling'' of the
earth's magnetic field. England was always enamored of physics, he
says, and has just recently delved into biology. ``Life just blows
me away.''
</P>
<P>
   Now cloaked in a white lab coat in a Northeastern science lab,
he's holding what looks like a turkey baster, measuring microliters
of a buffer solution. In his molecular biology project under mentor
Monsoor Amiji, a Northeastern pharmaceutics professor, he is
researching how protein drugs, such as insulin, can effectively be
delivered into a patient's body when encased in a polymeric
molecule.
</P>
<P>
   He insists it's much less complicated than it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   But in his absence, Amiji assesses England's research as
master's thesis level. ``You can imagine how bright he is,'' Amiji
says of England, his second student referred by the institute.
``The guy came in on the first day and started playing with all
these computers I have in here. He quickly learned the software
program in a week.'' He chuckles and shakes his head. ``If I did
it, it would probably take me a month to learn how to turn it
on.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A nurturing environment
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For a summer, the Rickoids leave some of their problems behind.
Those who attend mediocre high schools say they search, often
without success, for challenging classes, adequate resources, and
strong teaching. ``I always felt there was something missing in
me,'' says Attay Guvench, 17, of Falmouth, Maine, a town of 9,000.
At the institute, he is helping to create antennae for submarines.
``If you wanted to know something, it was hard to find the person
to teach it to you or the right book to read. Here, I can go find
that book or person to get the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-founder DiGennaro, however, acknowledges that locating
funding for programs for the intellectually precocious has been
tricky. Most schools earmark money to meet the needs of students at
the bottom, she says, rarely offering programs for those at the
top. Therefore the institute has been primarily funded by corporate
sponsors in what DiGennaro says is its mission to help train the
minds of the most promising few.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a pretty lonely world, having the brain of a
brilliant person in the body of a child,'' she says. ``They don't
have much. One in 10,000 students are like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Saul, a math teacher at Bronxville High School in New York,
watches over the students as the resident father figure. He lurks
on their electronic bulletin boards and scolds sleepyheads at
lectures. But as colorful metaphors sail from his lips, it becomes
clear he possesses the power to stimulate, the passion to educate,
the ability to bring out genius in adolescent minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see in them my own misspent youth,'' he says. ``I never had
a program like this. I grew up in the Bronx and had to build my own
environment. I had to find people who valued intellectual growth,
who loved math and science. No one acknowledged our abilities and
interests. No one acknowledged our subculture.''
</P>
<P>
   When he shifts focus to the students, his pale blue eyes reveal
both concern and recollection. ``These kids are begging for
stimulation. They are generally underserved. I see my old friends
in these kids.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A variety of futures
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Rickoids will meet again after the program ends. The
future holds in store math and science olympiads, Westinghouse
science competitions, and college. Many will return to Cambridge
for college _ perhaps influenced by one indelible summer memory. As
Saul knows, Rickoids will make their presence known.
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday morning, when the students are exchanging teary
goodbyes, Saul will sleep in. ``It's too painful. Everyone's
crying. It's very bad,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm old enough to know I'll see them again, and that they'll
find each other again,'' he adds. ``They're like a bunch of bad
pennies.''
</P>
<P>
   If they're like the last classes, these Rickoids will become
professors, doctors, scientists _ even investment bankers and
lawyers. Finally freed to escape labels and explore other parts of
themselves, many will leave with a quiet confidence that they, as
Whitman said, contain multitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Guvench, for one, dreams of playing in a band. ``Life is too
short, and the world is too big to focus on one thing,'' he says.
``Everyone I know is really good at something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
