<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YANKEE-RODEO-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEE WITH A DREAM BRINGS RODEO TO NEW ENGLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Two photos are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BECKET, Mass. _ At a nod from the young contestant, the bucket
shoot swung open and out bounded Kyle Robinson, 7, astride a
bucking steer named Tornado.
</P>
<P>
   Tornado heaved and twisted. Kyle managed to hold on for about 4
seconds before spinning off into the dirt _ not long enough to win
the steer-riding contest at the youth rodeo in Becket last weekend,
but long enough for his self-respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rodeo is not about winning, it's about believing you can do
it,'' the little guy said philosophically, as he dusted himself
off. ``It's really tough to be a cowboy.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially in New England.
</P>
<P>
   But Steve Robinson, a cowboy from Connecticut, and the members
of his Berkshire Rodeo Team, are determined to bring Wild
West-style thrills to Yankee hills. They're trying to establish New
England's only permanent rodeo-in-residence, and they say they're
bucking many misconceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Massachusetts, most people associate rodeo with hicks _
people with tight jeans and big belt buckles,'' said Elizabeth
Myrick 14, a freshman at Wahconah High School, in Dalton, before
the rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people drive by and see us practicing, they yell
`Yee-haw' and `Yippie-ki-yi-yay,''' added 'Tine Decker, a
12-year-old barrel racer and an 8th grader at Lenox Middle School.
``Or they tease us by saying `Howdy' all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   'Tine, an honors student and self-described ``horsaholic,'' has
been riding since she was five years old. But in staid New England,
that meant private trail rides or sessions at private stables or
riding clubs, where competitions focused mainly on English-style
jumping and dressage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got pretty snobby,'' said her mother, Deb Decker, of Lenox.
</P>
<P>
   By joining the Berkshire Rodeo Team, the youths _ currently four
boys and seven girls, ages 7 to 17 _ and their parents are pooling
their resources, sharing skills and equipment under Robinson's
watchful eye, to make possible something none could achieve alone.
</P>
<P>
   With welding and carpentry help from some of the fathers, and
supplies that were bartered or donated, Robinson built the rodeo
arena and the stables on 200 acres he inherited from his
great-grandfather. The kids helped dig fence post holes, level
pasture land, clean paddocks, care for the horses. To finance the
project, team members held car washes; parents sold baked goods,
T-shirts, and raffle tickets; local merchants bought rodeo banners
advertising their wares.
</P>
<P>
   And parents formed a nonprofit Berkshire Rodeo Team Association
to take donations, apply _ thus far unsuccessfully _ for grants,
and help organize rodeo logistics.
</P>
<P>
   It's all the brainchild of Robinson, 42, a former firefighter
and part-time cowboy who grew up in New Haven, which hardly was a
haven for cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up on a street corner in the inner city, no one talked
about rodeo,'' said Robinson, recalling his predominately black
neighborhood. ``They all wanted to be basketball or football
stars.''
</P>
<P>
   He spent his school lunch money on horse-and-rider magazines and
watched cowboy shows every Saturday morning, featuring Wild West
heroes like Roy Rogers and John Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I liked about them was, whatever happened, they could
handle it,'' Robinson said. ``No matter how bad the situation, they
were cool and collected.''
</P>
<P>
   So he became a fireman, which was as close as he could get in
New Haven to this essential cowboy ethos, Robinson concluded. But
on weekends, summers, whenever he could get free, he rode horses on
the Becket farm, or trained horses, or gave riding lessons, or
journeyed to some rodeo, wherever he could find one.
</P>
<P>
   Then one day &UR;  &LR; he was working as a fireman, standing atop a
burning roof as it began to collapse, thinking he might not survive
the blaze. ``And I thought, `What am I afraid of?''' Robinson
recalled. ```What am I waiting for?'''
</P>
<P>
   So last February, he retired from the fire department to devote
himself full-time to building a home-grown New England rodeo team.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far this summer, the team with help from parents has staged
three rodeos, with one more scheduled for August 29, at the Sunny
Banks farm in Becket. Any interested youth _ not just team members
_ can compete.
</P>
<P>
   Because this rodeo is especially for youngsters under 18, they
ride steers instead of broncos or bulls. As in adult rodeos,
competition also includes steer-roping, calf-wrestling, and racing
horses in a cloverleaf formation around three barrels.
</P>
<P>
   Team members come from a range of economic circumstances, ethnic
backgrounds, geographic locales. Some have been struggling with
personal problems _ such as depression, hyperactivity, low
self-esteem, or broken families. What they share is a love of
animals, a willingness to work on Robinson's ranch, and a desire to
learn about rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just always loved horses,'' said Teresa Torchia, 10,
expressing a common reason for joining the team. She has been
riding for three years, although she couldn't reach the stirrups
until last Tuesday, said the 4-foot, 3-inch cowgirl. She added that
``Black Beauty'' is her favorite book.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the safety of rodeo for youngsters, parents said
they occasionally worry but feel that the risks are well within
acceptable bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve has established a structure, and he keeps everything
under control,'' Deb Drucker said. ``If you're not listening, not
doing the safe thing, you're off that horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, who is donating his time to teach rodeo skills and
discipline, said no one has been seriously injured thus far. And
he, as well as several parents, said they have seen amazing changes
in the children since they began rodeoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before she started this, she was depressed, didn't hardly wash
her hair or bathe, just stayed in her room all the time,'' said
Cindy Taylor, of Becket, referring to her daughter, Angela, now 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now she's lost 30 pounds, got a lot of friends in school, goes
to dances, helps around the house. She took on some jobs to earn
her entry fees'' of $5 per rodeo, added Taylor. ``It's really
brought her confidence up.''
</P>
<P>
   In the future, Robinson hopes to have weekly rodeos, establish
an ongoing rodeo school and build cabins where visiting rodeo
participants can stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm living my dream,'' he said happily, ``and it just keeps
growing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
