<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DISTRESS CALL FROM THE FRONT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - From her wheelchair, Debra Richard holds the line for
people like us. She lives in a hunkered-down house in a
hunkered-down neighborhood, unseen, unknown, within the boundaries
of the city but at the edge of civilization.
</P>
<P>
   And she does not yield.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our home,'' she says. ``I live here with my mom. She's
71. My father lives nearby. I have seen a lot of changes but I'm
not running, no matter how scary it gets. It's just that sometimes,
like after what happened these last few weeks, you want people to
know what goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Her house is on a narrow street south of Baseline Road. From
some of the windows you can see the slopes of South Mountain, but
only if the metal security shields are rolled up.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, that's not often.
</P>
<P>
   When Debra was younger she was paralyzed from the waist down in
an automobile accident. It didn't stop her from living her life.
She has a son, now 15, whom she's managed to raise in a tough
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good boy,'' she says. ``He's not into any of the gang
stuff. I'd know if he was. But that isn't the only trouble there is
around here.'' &QL; 
SUDDENLY A TARGET
</P>
<P>
   Late last month at a nearby park, Debra's son got into a fight.
No one was hurt, and the family didn't fret over what happened
until later that night, when Debra was awakened by two loud booms
from the street. Someone had fired a shotgun at the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called the police and told them what happened,'' Debra
says. ``But we didn't see the shooting. They told us there wasn't
anything they could do.''
</P>
<P>
   She says officers spoke to kids in the neighborhood, but no one
admitted anything and no witnesses were found. Debra was worried
about her son, though, and asked officers what she should do.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me, `Send him away,' '' she says. ``They said
whoever did this would probably come back and there was no way to
protect him 24 hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of thing people in Debra's neighborhood must
deal with, while the rest of us fret over the stain on a White
House intern's dress.
</P>
<P>
   Debra called a brother who lives out of state. He offered to
take in her son. Reluctantly, she sent him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to think of my boy first,'' she says. ``It was a hard
thing to do, and I miss him, but I don't know that I had any other
choice. I've called every agency there is, talked to the police, to
volunteer groups. There aren't many options.''
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, someone took another shot at Debra's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't home and my mother didn't hear it, but there was a
bullet in the front door,'' she says. ``I'm calling you so that, if
you hear on the TV about two ladies getting shot in south Phoenix,
you'll know what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   This is what life is like on the front lines. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SAVING A NEIGHBORHOOD
</P>
<P>
   Still, Debra doesn't want to leave. It's her home. There are
memories in this place, and possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Why shouldn't she believe it?
</P>
<P>
   From her yard she can sit and watch as the giant antennas on top
of South Mountain scratch the bellies of passing clouds.
</P>
<P>
   The police say neighborhoods like Debra's only survive if the
neighbors band together, form watch committees and coordinate their
efforts with police.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wouldn't be needed if parents just taught their kids
respect,'' Debra says. ``But, not all of them do. So this is what
it's like, for some of us. I just wanted you to understand. To
know.''
</P>
<P>
   She figures maybe the rest of us can pressure politicians into
beefing up police presence in struggling neighborhoods like hers.
And encourage business people to invest in the place.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe even drive down there, under the freeway, across the
riverbed, to support those businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Or, we can ignore her part of town and wait until people like
Debra give up and move out. And the next neighborhood becomes the
front line. And the next. And the next. And ours.
</P>
<P>
   Then, we'll understand. Then, we'll know. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
