A0932 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-GOVERNMENT-HELP-BO     08-06 1385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-GOVERNMENT-HELP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A POPULATION WARY IN `GOOD TIMES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GEETA ANAND  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOBURN, Mass. _ If the 1980s were an era of intoxicating
affluence, this election year is a time of sober prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   The economy is humming in most of Massachusetts. Salaries are
rising, and most people can pay their rent and mortgages. For those
without a job, newspapers are full of Help Wanted ads.
</P>
<P>
   But voters are not reveling in the good times. They worry
intensely, across age and gender lines, about two commodities more
precious than money: their children and their health.
</P>
<P>
   And most believe strongly that government should help.
</P>
<P>
   They are people like Joanne Kovic, a single parent and the
manager of Bayview Kennels in West Barnstable, who wouldn't worry
if she lost her job _ but is clearly frustrated by two things she
believes are out of her control: education and medical care.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this place burned down tomorrow, I could get another job,''
she said as she ran a wire comb over a pit bull's back. ``The pay's
not bad. I scrape by. But the schools, they're another thing. And
health care? It stinks.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to their children, residents decry what they view
as lackluster public schools, the high cost and low quality of day
care, and the pervasiveness of violence on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put the money into kids,'' said Ed Wild, an engineer with EMC
Corp. in Hopkinton who mentors a 10-year-old boy through the Big
Brother Association. ``Kids are the guts of this century. It's
really important what morals they have.''
</P>
<P>
   As for their health, many residents complained of either not
being able to afford health insurance, or knowing people who
cannot. And they resent a government that doesn't help with what
they believe is such a basic human need.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Rodriguez, a hardware store owner in Springfield, said he
and his wife and new baby have no health benefits because the
cheapest plan cost $700 a month when he last checked.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the government could do something, that would be great,''
he said. As he speaks, he clutches a book on how to write a
business plan. He is ambitious, anxious to live the American dream,
but clearly frustrated by roadblocks like the high cost of health
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I eat, I live, I wear nice suits to church on Sunday
mornings,'' he said. ``But I want more. I want to prosper; I don't
want to just survive.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake: Most of the 119 residents interviewed in all
regions of the state for this story are not pining for a big,
intrusive government. Rather, they believe in an activist one:
lean, but compassionate, and willing to make tough choices. And not
tomorrow, but today.
</P>
<P>
   And they say they want a governor who will work to solve
specific problems, not simply cut taxes or mouth platitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Their mood is decidedly different from that of the last two
state elections.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, anger at perceived government overspending and
ineffectiveness helped elect William F. Weld, the first Republican
to be elected governor in two decades. Massachusetts was in a
recession, and people were focused on finding jobs and keeping
their houses.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, although the economy was on the mend, the electorate
was still consumed with pocketbook issues. Public education was as
troubled then as now, and health care nearly as expensive. But
voters focused on job security, and credited Weld with sorting out
the state's finances and fighting crime.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, the concerns have shifted. People describing
their wish-list for the next governor rarely mentioned cutting
taxes, and never talked about government excess. Only three said
they pay too much in taxes _ in spite of the recent high-volume
debate on Beacon Hill over tax cuts, and Acting Governor Paul
Cellucci's televison ads promising to lower the state income tax
rate from 5.95 to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Touting a tax cut seems so foolish,'' says Michael Kelley, a
locksmith with children ages 10 and 7 who recently moved from
Boston to Hopkinton in search of more space and better schools.
``What's that in savings _ a hundred bucks? A night out? It seems
to me the money should be put into education.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the state's billion-dollar budget surplus, most people
want the government to invest the money in the future. And in their
mind, the future is the children.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Education came up time and again in conversation. Voters are
irritated that nearly 60 percent of would-be teachers failed a
certification test earlier this summer. They worry about high
school students from other nations scoring higher than American
kids in science and math.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a disgrace, those teachers failing the test,'' Lorraine
Casey of North Wilmington said as she sat on a bench with two
grandchildren in the Woburn Mall while their mother shopped nearby.
``Something's wrong with the schools and colleges if teachers can't
pass the test. It just blew me away _ four years of college and
they can't pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Those advocating better schools include people who do not have
children, or whose children are long grown. The flush economy may
not have inspired a feeling of security, but it is nurturing a
spirit of generosity.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Pedrosa, 39, president of a Lowell electronics
manufacturing company, does not have children. But he would spend
more money on education in elementary and high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a huge number of startups in Massachusetts because of
the great (college) education here,'' he said. ``The economy has
moved away from manufacturing to high tech. We have to have a
skilled labor force.''
</P>
<P>
   As an employer, Pedrosa sees many of his 150 workers struggling
with child care _ another major concern voiced by residents across
the state.
</P>
<P>
   They say there isn't enough child care available, and what's
available is too expensive for the average two-earner couple.
</P>
<P>
   ``More companies should have day care on site,'' said Arlyss
Thomasino of Norwood as she shopped at the Natick Mall with her
father and newborn baby. ``Government should encourage that with
tax breaks or subsidies or something. How else can any of us afford
to work?''
</P>
<P>
   Their children's exposure to violence and sex in popular culture
disturbs many Massachusetts residents. They worry what effect such
exposure will have, and believe government should take steps to
curb it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they should think about all the filth on television
for our children,'' said Francis Fay of Methuen, 78, a grandmother
shopping in the produce section of a Lawrence gorcery store. ``The
language is disgusting. There aren't too many good things on except
sex and violence. Why can't they put in rules?''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that 97 percent of those who responded to a
Pulse of Massachusetts poll taken by the Globe in May said they had
health insurance, many residents interviewed at random this summer
said they had none _ usually because they owned or worked for a
company too small to offer benefits.
</P>
<P>
   And paying premiums on their own, they said, could cost as much
as a month's rent. As a result, many people aren't going to the
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Pavao, a salesman at Stride Rite in Barnstable who has no
insurance, figures it's been at least eight years since he's seen a
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't afford it,'' said Pavao, who makes less than $30,000 a
year. ``Our franchise is too small for group (rates). Some kind of
subsidy for health insurance would be nice for people like me who
are in the lower end of the middle-income bracket.''
</P>
<P>
   Art Maietta, an accountant from Milford who has a good job with
benefits, is willing to have the state use extra revenue to
subsidize health insurance for those who don't have it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Be they in the valleys of the Berkshire hills or the
three-deckers of Boston, by the inlets of Cape Cod or along the
canals of Lowell, the people of Massachusetts share a sense of
urgency.
</P>
<P>
   If the state's problems can't be solved in good times, they say,
they'll never be solved. And their children and their health are
too important to be left to chance.
</P>
<P>
   Says roofer Mark Table of Springfield: ``I want the best for my
kids. A good education. I want them to do good in life. If not now,
then when?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
