<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANKS FOR THE MEMORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the pleasures of my Chicago youth was the occasional bout
of car trouble. It gave me an excuse to visit Warshawsky &AMP; Co., a
vast auto-parts warehouse on the wrong end of State Street. You'd
get a salesman's advice on choosing a new ignition coil or a
rebuilt alternator, then wander through the fan belts and pine-tree
air fresheners till the goodies emerged from a room out back. There
were few better ways to spend an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, they didn't have personal computer stores back then.
These days, I prefer to hang out at a Cambridge, Mass. shop called
PCs for Everyone, a Warshawsky for nerds. Go to CompUSA for
attractive decor and lavish displays of merchandise. PCs for
Everyone is a boxy, bare-walled place with a carpet-covered bench
where you can sit and wait while the guy out back finds that hard
drive you asked for.
</P>
<P>
   There are salespeople in some stores whose only computer
experience is working a cash register. Not here. I hardly ever
visit without learning something, though the education generally
costs a few bucks. Like my recent quest for more memory.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, when I did a major computer upgrade, I
decided to keep using my old memory chips. I had 40 megabytes of
old RAM and the system worked well enough. But some of my software
experiments demand a bit more _ at least 64 megs more. Memory has
never been cheaper. I could get 64 megs for a little over $100. But
what kind?
</P>
<P>
   Like many newer motherboards, mine has two different sets of
memory slots. One set accepts the old-style memory chips, while the
other is designed for a faster type of computer memory called
Synchronous DRAM or SDRAM. SDRAM is designed to pump out data
significantly faster than the older type of memory chip. SDRAM is
standard equipment on many new machines. If you're in the market,
don't settle for less.
</P>
<P>
   Why is SDRAM better? Convenience, for one thing. Memory chips
come attached to little modules that look like miniature circuit
boards, and plug into slots inside the motherboard. But when you
use old-style memory in Pentium-type machines, you have to install
the modules two at a time. You can't buy one 16-megabyte module to
upgrade your machine. You need two modules of 8 megs each.
</P>
<P>
   Since most computers have just four slots for this kind of
memory, you run out fast. I've had to discard perfectly good memory
modules to make room for bigger ones. But this problem goes away
with SDRAM modules, which can be inserted one at a time. Just buy
one 64-megabyte module and you're set.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the sheer speed at which the computer can read and
write data to the chips. Never mind how fast your processor is;
these days the bottleneck between the processor and the memory is
at least as important.
</P>
<P>
   The data travels back and forth along a set of wires called a
bus, which is tuned to a particular frequency _ usually 66
megahertz. That means that pulses of data travel across the bus 66
million times every second. But old-style memory chips can't even
manage half that rate. So the computer spends half its time just
waiting for something to do. A newer kind of memory called EDO DRAM
is somewhat faster, but still not that hot. Ideally, you'd want
memory that can move data at exactly the same speed as the bus _
synchronized, in other words. And that's possible with SDRAM.
</P>
<P>
   There is a downside. SDRAM doesn't get along well with the older
type of memory, so my old chips would have to go. No problem: I'll
save them for my next building project.
</P>
<P>
   Then I saw there were two kinds of SDRAM, one about $40 cheaper
than the other. Not one to pass up a bargain, I began reaching for
the credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, said the salesman. He warned me that there are two
kinds of SDRAM out there. ``SDRAM Lite'' works on today's
motherboards. But the next wave of computers use boards that run at
100 megahertz, compared with today's 66-megahertz standard. SDRAM
Lite chips won't work with these boards, so I'd have to throw away
the memory the next time I upgrade. Pay a bit more for top-drawer
SDRAM, and it'll be good for years.
</P>
<P>
   The salesman kept me from doing something dumb, and got a few
extra bucks out of me at the same time. It was like the old days at
Warshawsky, only without the fan belts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (You can send Hiawatha Bray electronic mail at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
