<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0937 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-2TAK     08-06 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKING TO YOUR KIDS ABOUT GENOCIDE AND SLAVERY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When one of my son's choices from his fifth-grade summer reading
list was ``The Diary of Anne Frank,'' I felt a moment of panic. Was
he ready for this?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the more accurate question was the one I came to a day
or two later: Was I ready for him to be ready?
</P>
<P>
   Talking to our children about humankind's most awful deeds is
not easy for any parent. For those of us whose cultural heritage
includes a history of victimization, our personal sensitivity can
make it an even more onerous task. The Holocaust, slavery, the
genocide in Armenia or Cambodia _ these are painful subjects for us
to think about, let alone share with children.
</P>
<P>
   Our instinct to shield them is appropriate when they are young.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 3- to 6-year-old is easily overwhelmed by his own
imagination just in the normal course of things,'' says
developmental psychologist Joseph Reimer of Brandeis University.
It's normal, indeed common, for a preschooler to worry about
horrible things happening to his parents. ``So when you talk about
actual horrible things that have happened, it feeds his fantasies
even more,'' says Reimer. ``It makes him feel the world is unsafe
and he is, too.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, you don't need to go out of your way to talk
about the Holocaust or slavery with a preschooler. On the other
hand, if it comes up for any reason, including because there's a
survivor in your family, it's better to deal with it no matter what
her age.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you say things like, `You're too young to know about
that,' or, `Don't be looking at those pictures,' you shut a child
down. The conclusion he comes to can range from, `Mom doesn't care
about this, it's not important,' to, `This is too difficult to talk
about, so I won't,''' says educator William S. Parsons. He is chief
of staff at the US Holocaust Memorial Museum in Washington and
cofounder of Facing History and Ourselves, a national teacher
training organization in Brookline, Mass. that focuses on the
Holocaust and other examples of genocide.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A 4-year-old's question
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The best first conversation with your child happens because he
initiates it. Most likely, it will catch you by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologist Beverly Daniel Tantum's first conversation with son
Jonathan happened in the grocery store. He was 4, perched in the
shopping cart. ``If Africa is so great, what are we doing here?''
he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Tantum, a professor and dean at Mount Holyoke College, remembers
wanting to make three points. ``First,'' she says, ``I didn't want
him to think this was going to happen to him; kids this age are
very concrete in their thinking. Second, I didn't want him to think
his ancestors were just passive victims, and third, I didn't want
him to think all white people are bad.''
</P>
<P>
   What she told him went something like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``A long, long time ago, before there were grocery stores or
houses, the Europeans came and they wanted to build roads and
houses. It was going to be a lot of work, so they went to Africa to
get the strongest, smartest workers they could find. They didn't
want to pay them, so they kidnapped them and brought them here as
slaves. The Africans had to work very hard and they didn't get
paid. That was really unfair, so the Africans who were kidnapped
did whatever they could to escape, and even though some white
people did the kidnapping, other white people thought this was
unfair, too, and they tried to help them escape and to stop
slavery, which they eventually did.'' Tantum is the author of ``Why
Are All the Black Kids Sitting Together in the Cafeteria and other
Conversations about Race'' (Basic Books), which includes a section
on talking about slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Reimer says these points are good to keep in mind when talking
about genocide, too. ``With all children, but especially those
under 10, you don't want to paint a story that's all negative, all
passive,'' he says. ``That creates a troublesome dynamic: `Am I
part of these people who are always getting bashed?' No child can
indentify with that without being scared out of his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Setting the stage
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Psychologist Jessica Henderson Daniel tells parents that the
preschool years are a time to tell stories about the richness of
your heritage. Without that, she says, conversations about genocide
or slavery will seem to a child to be the beginning of the story
and the touchstone of their identity.
</P>
<P>
   This is as important a strategy for children whose ancestors
were the oppressors as for those who were the oppressed. Daniel
says many white or gentile children often feel hopelessness after
hearing about slavery or the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   She tells of a white first grader who told his mother, ``We're
bad people because we made blacks sit on the back of the bus.'' His
mother said only, ``You're right,'' which he took literally to
heart. Daniel says a better answer would have continued: ```But you
know what? There were a lot of white people who helped blacks.' By
talking about the Freedom Riders, or the Dutch who hid Jews, you
hold up models of courage and bravery,'' says Daniel. ``That
empowers children; it gives them hope.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
