<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0947 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-2ND &LR;      08-06 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... gives them hope.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because children under 7 are not only concrete but also
egocentric, Daniel tells parents to answer the question, ``What
about me?'' even if it doesn't get asked. ``For a first or second
grader hearing about slavery or the Holocaust for the first time,
there can be a lot of hurt. They wonder, `Is someone going to do
that to me, 'cause I'm black/Jewish, too?'''
</P>
<P>
   Her answer would be honest but hopeful: ``This won't happen to
you, but it's true there are still people in the world who are
racist (or anti-Semitic). There are also people who are not and
they are working all the time to make sure blacks (or Jews, or
Armenians, etc.) are treated fairly. That makes me feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Talking to 10-year-olds
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By 10, your message can include the idea that it is part of our
job to make sure things like this don't happen again, says Marc
Skvirsky, national program director at Facing History and
Ourselves. ``By fifth grade, they're beginning to get the idea of
justice,'' he says. ``You can ask things like, `Why do you think
prejudice exists? Where does it start?'''
</P>
<P>
   The more you get it down to your child's level, the better: What
about name calling on the playground? What do you and your friends
do when other kids poke fun at someone? Why is it that some people
turn their heads when they see something unjust and others don't?
What does it take to have courage?
</P>
<P>
   Middle school is prime time for racial jokes. When kids tell him
the jokes aren't a big deal, Parsons tells them about Julius
Streichter, one of 22 Nazis executed at the Nuremberg Trials.
``Streichter never killed anyone,'' he explains, ``but he wrote
such awful things about the Jews in his magazines that he broke the
moral backbone of the nation and he was found just as guilty as
people who murdered.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsons says this is a stunner for students. ``It's when the
power of words hits them,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Just because children may begin to grasp the issues doesn't mean
they'll change their behaviors. Parsons cautions parents not to be
discouraged. ``It'll kick in later,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He also tells parents not to feel you have to have an answer all
the time. ``Just because a kid raises an issue doesn't mean you
have to teach the whole thing all at once,'' says Parsons. In fact,
it's better to teach it little by little.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' he says, ``the best message to give a child, even
one who is older, is that these things are very complicated and
they can be painful to think and talk about. But they matter a lot
and thinking about them is important.''
</P>
<P>
   As my son gets deeper into ``Anne Frank,'' I find that very
reassuring.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SUGGESTIONS FOR PARENTS &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Children under 9 can't grasp the enormity of slavery or
genocide. Personalize it for them with stories about children.
</P>
<P>
   _A parent's first task is to make sure a child feels safe.
</P>
<P>
   _It's better for children to hear about these topics from you
before they hear about it in school. Find out when slavery or the
Holocaust is introduced in the curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   _Typical questions a young child might ask: ``Will there be
another Hitler?'' A good answer: ``There are always bad people in
the world, but there are also always good people. We hope there
won't be another Hitler. That's why it's important to vote and be
involved in our democracy, because we're in charge of choosing our
leaders.'' Q: ``Why did the Germans hate the Jews so much?'' A:
``Some people feel better when they put other people down, so they
make up lies and stories about them.''
</P>
<P>
   _Typical questions an older child might ask: ``Why do we have to
talk about this?'' A: ``We can't just pretend it didn't happen. We
remember because we don't want it to happen again.'' Q: ``When we
talk about slavery in school, everyone looks at me. Do they want me
to be a slave?'' A: ``Some people might think like that, but most
don't. You belong in that class, just like everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   _Offer examples of people who are working to keep bad things
from happening, especially examples from your child's life.
</P>
<P>
   _Save photographs of concentration camps or of slaves, or movies
like ``Schindler's List'' or ``Amistad'' for a child in eighth
grade or above. ``Anne Frank'' is generally recommended for seventh
grade or above.
</P>
<P>
   _Retired child psychiatrist Maurice Vanderpool of Brookline, who
is a Holocaust survivor and a Facing History volunteer, says that
when there is a survivor in the family, there is no magic age for
telling grandchildren. ``The survivor and the children both need to
be ready,'' he says. He waited until his grandchildren were school
age.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ Recommended for children anxious about going to
kindergarten: ``I'll Go to School if ...,'' by Bo Flood (Fairview
Press, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)nws.globe.com. Her
columns are now on line at Boston.Com, keyword ``parenting.'' For
photocopies of past columns, send a self-addressed, stamped
envelope to Barbara F. Meltz, The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston,
MA 02107-2378. Please specify the column.)
</P>
