A0948 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONICA-DRESS-DEVIL-NY     08-06 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONICA-DRESS-DEVIL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AH, MONICA, YOU DEVILISH RAVEN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Eastern time zone or Canada, call BOB FARNELL
at 1-800-535-4425. Or send a fax to him at (717) 646-4850.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Central time zone, call CONNIE WHITE at
1-800-444-0267. Or fax her at (816) 822-1444.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Pacific or Mountain time zones or in Latin
America, call OLIVIA VASQUEZ at (310) 996-0075. Or fax her at (310)
996-0089.
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1998 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WARNING: The following column is about the president of the
United States _ which means of course it's rated NC-17 and is
intended for mature audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Every time I hear about Monica Lewinsky and that stained dress
of hers _ a navy blue number from the Gap _ a certain song made
popular by Mitch Ryder and the Detroit Wheels comes to mind:
</P>
<P>
   Devil with the blue dress, blue dress, blue dress
</P>
<P>
   Devil with the blue dress on!
</P>
<P>
   Devil with the blue dress, blue dress, blue dress
</P>
<P>
   Devil with the blue dress on!
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the more obscure _ and much more graphic _
dance-pop song from the Prince-protege group known as Vanity 6. The
song was called ``Pretty Mess,'' and was about this fella who, um,
left his mark on Vanity's dress.
</P>
<P>
   Parody artists and DJs, feel free to go nuts with this
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty Mess'' notwithstanding, I'll go with ``Devil With the
Blue Dress On'' as Lewinsky's official theme song, because she IS a
devilish raven, no matter how this thing plays out. Either she has
plunged us deep into a sordid saga because she concocted a fantasy
romance with Bill Clinton _ or she really did have a series of
cheap sex encounters with the president of the United States in the
White House, and then blabbed like a barroom floozy about it.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, I'm tired of the reverse sexism that dominates
nearly every discussion about this alleged affair. It takes two to
tryst.
</P>
<P>
   I know: The older, married man in the position of power _ in
this case the ultimate position of power _ has to bear the brunt of
the responsibility for playing around with an impressionable,
vulnerable young woman.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewinsky was a young woman, not a girl, by the time the
romping began. Years older than, say, a Jerry Seinfeld girlfriend
or a Woody Allen wife. She was beyond the age of adult consent,
beyond the age when one is allowed to drink, vote, join the
military, own a house _ or have sex with a horny buffoon.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton made the first move, Lewinsky could have told him to
buzz off. If she was the seductress, it was her choice. She was not
``victimized.'' As I've said before, it's an insult to young adults
everywhere to say someone in her early 20s can't fend for herself.
</P>
<P>
   Let's assume there was a series of encounters with Clinton. That
means he's a lying idiot _ and she's a pathetic, attention-starved
young woman who acted like a spurned fourth-grader when her sleazy
sex affair with a married father started to fade. Consider her
behavior: The bitter, juvenile tone of her recorded phone
conversations with Linda Tripp; the bragging to friends about
having picked out a necktie the president was wearing; the idea
that she saved a stained dress and gave it to her mother for
safekeeping. Who acts like this outside of guests on ``Springer''?
Any young women you know?
</P>
<P>
   Me neither.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's crass behavior and Clinton's lewd behavior aside, I
still say it's Hillary who should be outraged, not a special
prosecutor or Congress. Even as I see the familiar Republican faces
blabbing on TV about impeachment, even as I sort through the daily
barrage of E-mail messages from Clinton-bashers who must have the
phrases ``suborning perjury,'' ``lying under oath'' and ``moral
issue'' on their computer's save-get keys, I want to stand on a
mountaintop and scream:
</P>
<P>
   ARE WE ALL INSANE OR WHAT?!?!?!?
</P>
<P>
   A long time ago, Kenneth Starr launched an investigation into
the Whitewater matter _ and somehow that led him to a McCarthyesque
witch-hunt that's so ludicrous it defies belief. While we're still
inside this chapter of history, I want to go on record as saying
this is a ridiculous, embarrassing investigation that should have
been abandoned a long time ago. Even if Clinton and Lewinsky were
to hold a joint press conference today to announce they're in love
and they intend to marry someday, it still wouldn't be cause for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   But there's nothing any of us can do to stop this rollercoaster
from completing its course. The stories will keep on coming, the
leaks will keep on leaking, and sometime in the near future the
country will be told exactly what caused the stain on that garment
of Ms. Lewinsky's.
</P>
<P>
   She's not too skinny, she's not too fat, she's a real humdinger
and I like 'em like that! Devil with the blue dress, blue dress,
blue dress, devil with the blue dress on...
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) can be heard on the
``Media Creatures'' show, which airs daily in Chicago from 10 a.m.
to 2 p.m. on WMVP-AM (1000) and appears Tuesday and Thursday at
7:55 a.m. on WFLD-TV's ``Fox Thing in the Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (A daily columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, Roeper has also
written for TV Guide, Spy, Playboy, Chicago magazine and many other
publications, and has appeared as a guest on ``Nightline'' and
``Oprah.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
