<HEADLINE>
ADMIRAL FOUGHT FOR EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA YUEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before there was the Research Science Institute, there was the
Rickover Science Institute, the brainchild of a brash, stubborn
admiral, himself widely acclaimed as a genius.
</P>
<P>
   Though more famous as the father of the nuclear Navy, Admiral
Hyman G. Rickover spoke out fiercely on education. Decrying an
``education crisis'' in 1959, he insisted that schools, unless
overhauled, would fail to produce mathematicians and scientists who
could help the United States stay competitive with the Soviet Union
and other nations. He urged more technical courses, higher teacher
pay, and higher standards, while scoffing at ``mediocre teachers,''
``lousy parents,'' and useless electives.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, an 84-year-old Rickover announced the inauguration of
the Rickover Science Institute. When a reporter asked if he thought
RSI students would be discontented after returning from the program
to their local high schools in the fall, Rickover said, ``I hope to
hell they're discontented and start working hard and stop loafing
like most of the high school students do.''
</P>
<P>
   The admiral's blunt and even scathing remarks did not cease in
institute summers to come. To one young man who introduced himself
to Rickover as the brightest physics student in the country, the
caustic admiral countered, ``You may think you are the brightest,
but you are the dumbest kid I've ever met.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He would catch them off guard, and they were in awe of him,''
said institute cofounder Joann DiGennaro who, with Rickover,
visited the teenagers every night during the first two summers.
After suffering a stroke, Rickover made his last public
presentation at 1985's RSI closing ceremony, reading the speech
from his wheelchair as DiGennaro held the notes. He died the
following year, at 86.
</P>
<P>
   DiGennaro remembers Rickover as a ``renaissance scholar,'' who
read poetry and autobiographies instead of science and math books _
because, DiGennaro recalls him saying, ``those are things you just
pick up.''
</P>
<P>
   The child of poor Polish Russian immigrants never claimed to be
ingenious, DiGennaro said, but he demanded the best from others and
from himself. When two members of the first institute class took
first and second place at the Westinghouse Science Talent Search
competition, he questioned why his students coudn't win all 10 top
places.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
