A0953 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-DECLINE-H     08-06 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-DECLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DECLINE III' STRESSES PUNKERS' ANGST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE GANAHL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a moment when a young female character in ``The Decline
of Western Civilization Part III,'' a new documentary depicting the
lives of a group of homeless punk-rockers in Los Angeles,
alternately hangs a loogie down to her navel, flips off the camera,
and then returns to the careful up-do of hair-spikes in the
bathroom mirror. Because, as a girlfriend says, ``she still wants
to look pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   And one boy, barely 22 and sporting a mohawk, notes how his
father used to beat him, using ``everything from fists to power
tools,'' and when asked if he was still angry, comes close to
welling up.
</P>
<P>
   The footage encompasses everything we should to know about these
kids. Scary-looking as Freddy Krueger and as defiant as wolverines,
they are still, well, kids. They pose and bluster and even get
violent, but they are also victims of abuse, or rejected by parents
even more screwed up than they are, or born with addicts' genes.
You vacillate between wanting to arrest them and wanting to hug
them and take away their pain.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the third installment of Penelope Spheeris' trilogy is
hardly an uplifting way to spend an evening at the movies. But it
is occasionally powerful, thanks to excellent camera work (mosh pit
scenes are like being there), and always engrossing _ like watching
a train wreck in slow motion.
</P>
<P>
   The first two chapters were far more fun to watch. 1981's
``Decline of Western Civilization'' captured the raw energy and
excitement of punk's early years in L.A.; and 1988's ``DWC II: The
Metal Years'' was a hilarious look at the new heavy metal scene _
and it's big-haired poseurs _ which punk had fought so hard to
reject.
</P>
<P>
   The third film, which premiered at Sundance and has had trouble
finding a distributor because it's so unrelentingly bleak, has in
comparison very little to do with the music around which its
denizens' lives revolve. Spheeris is more interested in the young
punkers as real people; for that she is to be applauded. Characters
in the first two films flitted by on the screen, giving us little
time to get inside their heads.
</P>
<P>
   But at times the film teeters on advocacy-journalism, a la
Michael Moore. During closing credits, it is noted that all
proceeds from the movie will be given to charities that assist
homeless young people. And throughout the interviews, Spheeris
posits questions to her young subjects like, ``What happened to
your eye?'' and ``When was the last time you took a bath?''
</P>
<P>
   While it's possible that she needed to earn their trust through
such maternal outbursts, it loses objectivity by showing sympathy
for the young losers. Don't forget, these kids also steal _ even
sell their dogs _ to buy beer.
</P>
<P>
   The film's unrelenting intensity would have been leavened by
more interviews from outsiders; as it was, there was only an
out-of-step nightclub owner, a fairly sympathetic cop, and one
mother who seemed more weird than her pierced-and-tattooed son. The
rest was all safety-pinned noses, young women passed out on
party-room floors, barfing in bathtubs.
</P>
<P>
   But after 90 minutes with the group, when an inevitable death
does occur, it hurts. Especially following footage of them
answering the question, ``What will you be doing in five years?''
Most answered, quite sincerely, ``I will be dead.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The music, supplied by such inconsequential bands as Final
Conflict, Litmus Green, Naked Aggression and The Resistance, is
pretty standard punk-club thrash: loud and screaming, with
occasional bursts of political venting. (Last year's ``Hype'' at
least featured bands that, while unknown, were at least enjoyable _
from Gas Huffer to the Fastbacks.)
</P>
<P>
   But Spheeris wasn't making a movie about music this time. She
wanted to open our eyes to the misery of these homeless kids. For
the most part, she succeeds admirably, but the impact would have
been greater if she'd stepped back from an advocate's role.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
