<HEADLINE>
THE NEIGHBORS MOVE IN WITH US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The family across the street moved in with us last week. All the
floors in their house were being refinished, with the resulting
fumes, and so late on Monday afternoon they marched across the
street, suitcases in hand, and came to spend four days here.
</P>
<P>
   David, Patti, and their two children have been our neighbors for
12 years. Their porch fronts on our driveway, and so it's a pretty
rare week that we don't run into one another by the cars and engage
in the kind of small talk that makes you feel connected over time.
David goes outside to smoke and often, coming home after a night
out, Jack and I have lingered in the dark street, discussing the
state of the world with the glowing end of a cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Matt, now 11, and Deenah, age 8, were 5 years old, my
husband's taken them with him once a month to prepare and serve
drinks at the Crombie Shelter in Salem. Matt and his dad use our
yard for pitching practice so I can easily look out of my office
window and watch Matt throw one right over the plate. Both kids
take part in the neighborhood skit I organize every Halloween, and
when I had an extra ticket this winter, I took Deenah to see
``Everest'' at the Omnimax. When the family's shed came down this
spring, their bikes temporarily moved into our garage. Suffice it
to say that when I left the house with my curling iron plugged in,
it was Patti I called to run over and shut it off.
</P>
<P>
   The folks across the street are more than neighbors, yet they're
not ``friend'' friends. They've never had dinner here. We've never
gone to a movie together. Patti and David are almost a generation
younger than we are, though that didn't occur to me until I began
to describe them here. Theirs is a family we know mostly through
casual observation, a family whose activities occasionally parallel
ours without intersecting. Because we don't have a word in the
English language to describe such a relationship, it's odd to
realize how fond of neighbors you can become without getting to
know them through the usual pathways.
</P>
<P>
   Still, living together was a big step.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you sure it's OK if we move in?'' David asked Sunday
night, for about the 10th time. David and Patty were worried about
imposing on us. What they didn't realize was that I was worried
that someone in their extended family would grab them before I
could convince them that we were offering the most desirable
accommodations in town.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't wait. The thought of having a table full of folks at
meals, of hanging out together evenings, of hearing ``Good Night''
from every occupied bedroom, just like in the Waltons, thrilled me.
I like running into people in my own hallways. I like conversations
that accompany doing things together. I like no frills, no fuss
cohabitation. I must have lived in a boarding house in one of my
previous lives.
</P>
<P>
   I find it's easier to have folks move in than to have those very
same people over for dinner. When I'm solely in charge, even the
simplest meal requires at least half a day for buying food,
straightening the house, setting the table, and preparing the meal.
House guests, especially if they're neighbors, are a different
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Invariably they become coproprietors.
</P>
<P>
   Patti did the food shopping. The kids set the table. Everyone
cleared. We cooked one meal over our Halloween bonfire pit. I
didn't wash a dish the whole time they were here. Instead we
lingered over meals, listening to Matt's concerns about global
warming, and Deenah's report about her part in a summer production
of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream.'' Watching videos together, I felt
the ease of a camaraderie that came about without the adults having
a single heart-to-heart talk.
</P>
<P>
   I like to think that this brief respite from 10 nerve-racking
months of renovations took the sting out of the fact that Patti and
David's electrician vanished before he got around to putting lights
in their bedroom. Perhaps it dampened the frustration they're
feeling because the man who built their kitchen cabinets won't come
to install the doors. And perhaps this brief trip away from home
deserves some credit for the fact that Patti stayed cool when she
discovered that the workmen had left hardened pools of varnish on
several floors. (Not to worry. They came back and redid it.)
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors come your way by chance. Some of them grow on you in
gradual, almost imperceptible increments. This is the best part
about getting close to them. When it's time to go home, they don't
go far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
