<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0958 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-SOLAR-BOS &LR;      08-06 1572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-SOLAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET THE SUN SHINE IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARGO MILLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bouts of cloudy weather this spring and summer have
not exactly turned people's thoughts to solar power. If, indeed,
people think solar. Why bother when the oil truck comes when
called? That attitude may be about to change. Following last
winter's conference on global warming in Kyoto, Japan, President
Clinton has committed America to installing 1 million solar roofs
by 2010. &UR;  &LR; There are two good reasons: Solar power is inexhaustible
and doesn't pollute.
</P>
<P>
   But do we want our houses to look as though we lived solar?
</P>
<P>
   New technology and good design should make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   What makes today's solar roofing different from the old
hot-water panels on the homes of solar pioneers is the way they are
integrated into the structure. That shiny black cladding that gives
enormous chic to the tower of 4 Times Square, New York City's new
environmentally friendly skyscraper, is really an electronic device
called photovoltaics (PV) that converts sunlight into electricity.
The same PV, sensitively used on a little dormer Cape Cod or a big,
turreted Queen Anne Victorian, will trap enough sun to light the
house and then some. You could use the surplus to run your lawn
mower. You could also import a solar mower (from Sweden) that's as
cute as a June bug.
</P>
<P>
   For an entertaining and enlightening picture of how this works,
go see a show called ``Under the Sun: An Outdoor Exhibition of
Light'' at the Cooper-Hewitt, the Smithsonian Institution's
national museum of design, through Oct. 25. Housed in the old
Carnegie mansion at 2 East 91st St., the Cooper-Hewitt boasts the
biggest, poshest back yard in Manhattan: Fifth Avenue runs along
the edge and the sun sets behind Central Park. Each year during the
warm weather, the museum uses the lawn for a show about outdoor
living. One year it was dog houses and another year, tents. When it
was lawn furniture, a chicken-wire structure planted with ivy
turned into a topiary armchair. This year, the star turn is Old
Sol.
</P>
<P>
   The show opened appropriately on the summer solstice and the
weather cooperated. Not so the following day: It did not exactly
pour rain but neither did the sun appear. Yet there was light
enough to power each of the exhibits. Amelia Amon's solar fountain
trickled water and Nicholas Goldsmith's sun clock told time. As
show curator Lucy Fellowes explained to a sun seeker from Boston,
sun bounces off clouds even on a cloudy day. A sun meter that
Fellowes consulted registered well under 10 percent but when she
covered the sun trap with her hand _ to simulate night _ the dial
went blank.
</P>
<P>
   Solar power in its latest manifestation is like a bank. If your
house (or business) is connected to the local power grid, you sell
your excess solar energy to the utility during the day. During heat
waves, when there is demand for air conditioning, utilities are
glad for the spare power. At night, or on a cloudy day, you
withdraw power from your solar account. (For people who live far
from a power grid, solar power is stored in a battery about the
size of a modern oil furnace.) The solar capital of Massachusetts
may be the the north-central city of Gardner, Mass., otherwise the
Chair Capital of the World. A whole neighborhood of 30 houses have
had their roofs retrofitted by Solar Design Associates of Harvard,
Mass. to cash in on sun power. The firm also did City Hall and the
library as well as a Burger King.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been doing homes since the 1980s,'' Marilyn Strong,
Solar Design's vice president, said in a telephone interview. ``Our
houses are all over the country.'' They include two in Brookline,
Mass. and another in Milton, Mass. So convinced of sun power are a
third client, William and Deborah Lord, that their solar home in
Kennebunk, Maine, has its own Web site: www.solarhouse.com.
Designed by Steven Strong, the Lord house delivers dependable
electricity at low cost, something under $10 a month during the
winter, the Lords estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Few houses will want or need the sun-trapping cladding on 4
Times Square. But when PVs mimic asphalt roofing tile, the
application to domestic housing is vast. ``We try to incorporate
PVs so it looks like part of the roof rather than sitting on it,
like the old solar-heated hot water panels. If your house is smoky
gray,'' said Strong, ``a roof of black PVs would look quite nice.''
The PVs for one of the Brookline homes, as well as the Kennebunk
house, are bright blue, formed from crystals. ``Typically black or
blue absorbs the spectrum of light that's most efficient for
conversion,'' says Strong.
</P>
<P>
   The technology behind PVs goes back to 1839, when a French
scientist named Edmund Pecquerel discovered the ability of silicon
to convert sunlight to electricity. As silicon is the most
plentiful element on earth after oxygen, it's available worldwide.
But the practical application of Becquerel's discovery had to wait
till 1954 when scientists at Bell Laboratories rediscovered PVs and
used them as a power source for rural telephone systems. Space
satellites began using PVs in 1958. PV cells run traffic signals
and street lights.
</P>
<P>
   At the Cooper-Hewitt show, the structures are a good deal more
fanciful than the Gardner neighborhood of post-World War II homes.
A sleek pavilion is the work of two New York-based architects,
Gregory Kiss (pronounced Kish) of Kiss &AMP; Cathcart Architects and
Nicholas Goldsmith of FTL Happold Architects &AMP; Engineers. This
consists of glass panels onto which a fine film of black PVs has
been applied. To show the variety of the product, some panels are
solid and others are scored with fine lines, which reduce somewhat
the solar receptivity. Each panel has a small red junction box from
which wires flow. Kiss likens the pavilion to a little powerhouse.
While architects of skyscrapers and commercial buildings will use
such rigid panels as curtain walls, Kiss thinks there is
application to the home market. ``For a sun room or a Florida
room,'' he said. The panels can themselves be paneled on the
interior: Glass, being porous, is not a good insulator.
</P>
<P>
   Kiss's pavilion consists of 54 panels of clear and photovoltaic
glass. Each costs about $120 (for a total of almost $6,500), half
what they did five years ago. Kiss thinks the cost will drop
further. His configuration of PV panels could supply electricity
needs for a 2,500-square-foot house.
</P>
<P>
   A true believer in solar power, curator Fellowes overstates
matters to say that ``every civilization except ours has built with
the sun.'' That is to ignore the siting of old Yankee farmhouses to
trap light and warmth, or conversely, banish heat. But she is on
the mark about the portability of the sun as a power source. ``It
comes to you,'' she said as drizzle fell on the Cooper-Hewitt lawn.
``You don't need ships and oil tankers.''
</P>
<P>
   And there as proof was one of Goldsmith's elegant white tents,
soaring over the show like a great bird. Even in the drizzle, the
mast of the solar tent registered a few light rays. To make this
tent a solar receptor, Goldsmith ran PVs in the form of a flexible
film that followed the swooping contours of the tenting material.
The lesson here is solar power for portable buildings. A helicopter
could drop a tent in a disaster area. ``You could set it up for
emergency shelter,'' curator Fellowes says. ``You could use tents
for hospitals or schools.'' The more PV strips a tent had, the more
sun it trapped. ``You certainly would generate enough power for
lighting, and for modest refrigeration,'' Fellowes said.
</P>
<P>
   Solar power interests Indonesia, a country of islands with
little in the way of a power grid. For the country's PT Sudimara
Energi Surya, Paul Hessels has designed a table that houses the
battery for home power while doubling as the television console.
And when the sun shines, as someday it will, the mind will turn to
solar for ... laptops (in the Siemens version the receptor is the
cover and the hinge conceals the battery) and for ... food cookers
(made of coated cardboard by the California design firm of Bernard,
Kerr, Pejack, Campbell) and for ... handheld lanterns (by designer
Hedda Beese and engineer Charles Ash). That cute green lawn mower
by Sweden's Andre Colens is also robotic. Its range is 13,000
square feet of lawn. It begins working in the morning and quits at
dusk. The idea is to maintain lawns much as grazing animals did,
trimming little but often.
</P>
<P>
   Many civilizations worshipped the sun and Goldsmith's Solar
Council clock is a nod to that. Arranged in a big circle are what
purport to be chairs, and are, but tall and angular, as though
Frank Lloyd Wright was trying his hand at patio or pool furniture.
Topping each chair is a fat metal bun. This is a reading light. For
light summer reading at night. Solar powered, of course. The chairs
number 12, each marking an hour on a solar clock. One is a sundial:
When you stand in the center, you are the gnomon or marker that
casts the time-telling shadow. Sundials, as they are wont to say,
``mark only sunny hours.'' But there was Goldsmith's analog clock.
The rain, it raineth evermore, but little colored lights winked
around the circle of chairs. Red stands for the hour, amber for the
minute, and blue for the second. As Chairman Clinton says: Let a
million sunroofs bloom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
