<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAULING NOT NEW FOR MANY BAY STATE COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The bear is in our back yard.
</P>
<P>
   Stock market analysts and money managers agree this week has
surely been hard on blue chip stocks, but they also point out that
the vast majority of other stocks have been struggling for a long
time.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of drooping local stocks should convince you they are
right.
</P>
<P>
   We examined the stock price activity of 176 public companies
based in Massachusetts, each with a market value of at least $100
million. It wasn't pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Among that group, 121, or more than two out of every three
companies, fit the technical definition of a market correction.
Those stocks had all fallen at least 20 percent from the highest
levels achieved over the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Even more striking, one of every four stocks in the group had
fallen at least 50 percent from their 52-week highs.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the hardest hit suffered from maladies common to
companies vulnerable to a downturn: unexpected
earnings &UR;  &LR; disappointments, stocks on the wrong side of erratic
price swings, or exposure to the Asian crisis. Most of them are
relatively small.
</P>
<P>
   But several other stocks came with no particular black mark or
special circumstance, simply sucked down by a worried market.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no sentiment to turn these (small-capitalization
stocks) at the moment,'' said Warren Isabelle of Ironwood Capital
in Boston, which specializes in small-company value stocks.
``People have just abandoned these things.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Cambridge Technology Partners Inc. enjoyed a good day
Wednesday, gaining 2 7/8 to 43. But the stock is still down by 26
percent from its 52-week high reached just a month ago, despite
backing from analysts at Donaldson Lufkin Jenrette who recently
named it a ``top pick'' and at CIBC Oppenheimer who have boosted
its rating to a ``strong buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge Technology Partners isn't so small, with a stock
market value of $2.4 billion, but it fit a familiar pattern. The
only recent news out of the technology consulting company: It met,
but did not beat, profit expectations when it announced quarterly
earnings three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Interneuron Pharmaceuticals Inc. of Lexington, down 85.8 percent
from its peak, was the biggest single loser. The company was trying
to recover from its Redux problems when it decided to withdraw
regulatory applications for an important stroke-recovery drug in
April, prompting a one-day, 50 percent cut in its stock price.
</P>
<P>
   PRI Automation Inc. of Billerica, which makes semiconductor test
equipment, got caught in the Asia economic spiral. Its stock has
sunk steadily from 58 1/2 in September to 13 7/8 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the leading Internet stocks in Massachusetts have taken
their lumps in the unpredictable market for Web companies, but only
after reaching dizzying heights.
</P>
<P>
   CMG Information Services Inc. of Andover has slumped from a peak
of 85 7/8 reached last month to 67 11/16 Wednesday. But that is
still far ahead of the stock's average price of nearly 28 11/16
recorded over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos Inc. of Waltham, an Internet search company, has plunged
from a high of 99 9/16 to Wednesday's close of 53 3/8 in a matter
of a month.
</P>
<P>
   Small-stock investors see lots of cheap investments today, even
if they are unsure when the market will rediscover those companies.
</P>
<P>
   Unitrode Corp. of Merrimack, N.H., which would have joined our
bear market list if it were located in Massachusetts, is a favorite
of David Diamond at High Rock Capital in Boston, another small-cap
value manager who invests about $525 million.
</P>
<P>
   Unitrode shares have sunk from a high of 41 13/16 last fall to
14 1/8 as of Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Small stocks dominated the group of sinking Massachusetts
issues, but several larger companies also took their lumps.
</P>
<P>
   Teradyne Inc. of Boston, another semiconductor test equipment
company with business in Asia, gave up more than 63 percent of its
peak price set last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok International Ltd., the struggling sneaker company based
in Stoughton, was off more than 60 percent from its 52-week high.
</P>
<P>
   Even BankBoston Corp., one of the region's most successful
stocks last year, has slumped 21 percent from its peak reached a
month ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
