<HEADLINE>
LOCAL TV NEWS A BLOODY SHAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's only a one-day snapshot, but the Rocky Mountain Media
Watch's examination of the night newscasts on 102 local television
stations March 11 revealed that no news succeeds like bad news,
particularly if it's bloody. (Earlier this year, the nonprofit RMMW
unsuccessfully petitioned the Federal Communications Commission to
revoke the license of four Denver TV stations on the grounds that
their crime-drenched news was detrimental to the public interest.)
</P>
<P>
   According to the RMMW report released Tuesday, crime stories
consumed 27 percent of the local news airtime, followed by coverage
of disasters such as floods, fires, and crashes, at 12 percent.
News about health, the economy, and government averaged about 10
percent of the airtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a successful business model to present the tabloid''
version of news, said RMMW executive director Paul Klite. There
was, however, at least one exception in the Boston market, where
RMMW surveyed WBZ-Ch. 4, WHDH-Ch. 7, and New England Cable News.
NECN was cited as one of only four stations nationally that
presented ``quality programs that provide empowering information to
viewers.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Klite, the day on which RMMW surveyed the stations
``was a slow news day'' in which cold weather dominated many
newscasts. In addition, 27 of the 102 stations carried California
video of a horse, stuck in the mud, that had to be rescued by a
helicopter; about half the stations ran stories abut the Monica
Lewinsky scandal, though there were no new developments; nearly
half the stations had footage of a hostage situation at a Seattle
bank; and almost 20 carried stories about a possible asteroid
collision with earth. Not much nutritional value there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was a sense of vindication at the new on-line Conservative
News Service last month. On June 16, CNS _ a division of the Media
Research Center _ featured a story about a Miami investigation
involving a $120,000 contribution to the Democratic National
Committee. Four days later, that information made it into a story
in the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   With a staff of four reporters and two editors, the month-old
CNS (www.conservativenews.org) hopes to function as a news service
that remedies some of the ``shortcomings in much of the American
news media.'' To wit: the liberal bias that the group says pervades
the mainstream press.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called it the Conservative News Service because we wanted
to make sure self-identified conservatives know this is news they
will be interested in,'' said CNS executive editor Scott Hogenson.
But ``we also look for stories that are underreported or ignored by
the establishment media.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the news service catches on, the on-line site has
already begun to attract a solid conservative following. Last week,
visitors were asked to vote on whether a sitting president should
be required to testify if subpoenaed before a federal grand jury in
a criminal inquiry. The final tally was 1,282 yes and 33 no votes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was Exhibit A in the case against the news media. Word of a
stained garment that might confirm a sexual relationship between
President Bill Clinton and Monica Lewinsky _ a story that bounced
around in January from cyber gossip Matt Drudge to ABC's Jackie
Judd to much of the mainstream media _ was considered a classic
example of unsourced gossip-mongering that characterized much of
the reporting on the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The Columbia Journalism Review characterized the story as a
candidate for the ``sleaziest report award.'' The American
Journalism Review cited it as one of the ``many juicy but
unconfirmed tidbits (that) took on the aura of fact.'' And in his
scathing assault on the media's reporting of ``Monica-gate'' in his
new magazine, Steven Brill used the dress story to illustrate
journalistic malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the dress has resurfaced as a potentially crucial
element in the case, some observers believe the media critics may
need their own watchdogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I think there is a lesson,'' said Bob Steele, the
director of the Ethics Program at the Poynter Institute for Media
Studies. ``In terms of critiquing and watchdogging ourselves, we
need to apply the same high standards that we ask of the
journalists we're challenging. Some of the criticism in this case
has been of the self-serving, bell-ringing `those idiots' nature.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One ubiquitous feature of Boston's burgeoning Irish pub scene is
the so-called ``Green Paper'' known as The Irish Emigrant. The
outgrowth of an e-mail newsletter that was begun by a Digital
Equipment employee in Galway, the South Boston-based Emigrant now
distributes about 8,000 local copies of the 64-page weekly, mostly
to local pubs and shops, where it has become a hot item.
</P>
<P>
   Part of its appeal is the listing of local Irish pubs and
restaurants, the Irish Calendar, and the Irish Pages version of the
Yellow Pages. But about 75 percent of the news comes from Ireland _
and where else could you read about a Newry couple who died in a
fire resulting from ``an unattended chip pan'' or how an injury to
star player Dara O'Cinneide proved crucial in the Kerry football
championship?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
