<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0972 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYDER-CUP-BOS &LR;      08-06 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYDER-CUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUCH EARLY RYDER INTEREST AMONG PUBLIC, CORPORATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Ryder Cup has become the area's talking topic, and between
the corporate world and the general public, there is plenty to talk
about. The latest news is that the PGA of America has bowed to the
weight of public opinion and agreed to refund the controversial $5
application fee for the random drawing for tickets to the event,
which will be played next September at The Country Club in
Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The fee will be refunded regardless of whether a person's name
is drawn. This is a good public relations decision, since many
balked at paying a $5 fee that was not refundable. The prepared
statement issued by the PGA of America read simply, ``After a
discussion with the Office of the Florida Attorney General, the PGA
made the decision to refund all shipping and handling fees for
processing ticket requests.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been 25,000 paid requests for entry into the drawing,
with 30,000 tickets available. There has been a little lull in the
rush for tickets, but news that the obligatory $5 fee has been
rescinded should stimulate interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate getting a rush before the Aug. 31 deadline,''
said tournament director Dan Baker. ``People tend to wait. I'm sure
with the PGA Championship being played next week, people will start
talking Ryder Cup. This is one of the biggest sporting events in
the world. There's discussions on the players, the captain's
choices.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the PGA of America decision to rescind the fee, Baker
said, ``They felt we hadn't done anything wrong, but they wanted to
take a close look at it ... and they did.''
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of activity Wednesday at The Country Club _
work on the locker room building the teams will be sharing next
September is in progress. ``We're focusing on the facility,
transportation, and presenting the best golf course we can,'' said
Baker.
</P>
<P>
   The Ryder Cup has become big business, especially since the
Europeans upended the US team last year in Valderrama on Sprin's
Andalucia coastline and two years prior to that at Oak Hill in the
suburbs of Rochester, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Boston will have the 103d Boston Marathon next year, plus
baseball's All-Star Game and Davis Cup tennis matches. The Ryder
Cup should eclipse all of them in terms of international interest
and financial involvement.
</P>
<P>
   This competition began innocently enough at Worcester Country
Club in 1927 _ there are plans to invite '27 US team member Gene
Sarazen next year. He was still active as an honorary starter at
the Masters in April.
</P>
<P>
   The United States dominated the competition when it was between
American golfers and their counterparts from Greater Britain and,
later, from Great Britain and Ireland. Since the Europeans came in
as a group in 1979, and players such as Seve Ballesteros, Nick
Faldo, Jose Maria Olazabal, Bernhard Langer, and Ian Woosnam
blossomed, it's been a different game. The Europeans won at The
Belfry in 1985 and repeated at Muirfield Village in 1987, their
first win on US turf.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1985 tournament, it's been a wild, woolly, and
wonderful competition, with the Europeans holding a 4-2-1 edge. And
the corporate community has taken notice of the increased
international interest. More than 2 1/2 years before the first tee
shot of the Ryder Cupo, there were 57 corporate tents sold,
bringing in $15.2 million. There had been no announcement of their
availability, no marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, two more have been sold, and additional corporate
tent availibility is being made available on the adjacent Putterham
Meadows, with the first $3 million in revenue going to the town of
Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our basic goals now are on parking and transportation,'' said
Baker. ``We'll park some cars at Putterham, but we'll basically
shuttle more people in to alleviate any congestion in the area.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest to become involved is International Management Group,
which has reached an agreement with Brae Burn CC to hold a golfing
event hosted by Arnold Palmer and featuring other IMG-represented
golfers. Groups of 10 can pay $40,000 to play a round _ four of the
10 on Thursday with an IMG client, the remaining six from the group
on Friday. The $40,000 package includes breakfast, lunch, a
reception, and dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clients,'' said Bev Norwood of IMG, ``depends on who is on
the Ryder Cup team and who's not playing somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   There also will be golf lessons available from guru David
Ledbetter and tennis lessons from Nick Bolletteiri.
</P>
<P>
   Even Norwood is amazed by the scope of the Ryder Cup. ``It used
to be players wanted to make the Ryder Cup team to indicate they
had a good year,'' he said. ``Now they want to play in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz Sports &AMP; Media of Atlanta has rented Winchester CC and
Belmont CC, and groups ranging from Pepsi, State Street Bank, and
the Boston Globe/Golf Digest have signed on. ``Everything is going
well,'' said company president Will Katz. ``We've signed on a
number of clients. People have heard of the golf courses. We're
getting great feedback. The activity level is still big, and all
the hospitality is sold out.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider the approach of BankBoston, which has spent $500,000
for a priority hospitality tent on site and $500,000 to rent
Charles River CC Tuesday through Saturday. This doesn't include
food or beverage, or the cost of flying in clients from Europe and
Latin America. BsnkBoston paid $250,000 up front a year ago
September, and the remaining $250,000 is due next month _ a year
before the event.
</P>
<P>
   Helps soften the blow of refurbishing the clubhouse, doesn't it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1336EDT &QL; 
