A0974 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-06 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CAMBRIDGE, IT'S THE THOUGHT THAT COUNTS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   I love living in Cambridge for so many reasons, many of them
wrong, I suppose, according to the Chamber of Commerce. But I love
it just the same.
</P>
<P>
   It's an incredibly tolerant city, as long as you're a liberal.
It's one of the world capitals of eccentricity. It's so many other
things. A smoke-free zone. A nuclear-free zone. A domestic
violence-free zone. A prejudice-free zone. A drug-free zone. Have I
forgotten anything? A fat-free zone? Not yet. But it may be just a
matter of time.
</P>
<P>
   It's a town with principles, a town that, for example, is not
afraid to reach out across the globe to support the people of East
Timor in their struggle against Indonesian oppression. Last week,
the City Council voted not to purchase goods or services from
companies that sell military equipment to Indonesia or that
prospect or drill for oil or natural gas in the Timor Gap.
</P>
<P>
   That ought to bring the Indonesian government to its knees. But
I support my City Council's courageous action on the East Timor
situation, although I wonder just how much impact the ban will
have, especially when a Cambridge Chronicle story reports that the
prohibition won't apply if a particular good or service is deemed
``necessary to protect or preserve the health, safety or welfare of
the the public'' or if ``no comparable product is available without
incurring substantial additional costs or suffering substantial
decrease in quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's a nice gesture. It's the thought that counts. You
don't see them passing a resolution like that in any other city or
town around here. You'd have to go all the way to Northampton or
Brattleboro to find a place that thinks as globally and acts as
locally as Cambridge. That's one of the things I love about it. But
there are so many things to love. It's multicultural, multiethnic,
multireligious, multigenerational, multisexual, multipurpose. I
can't imagine living anywhere else. All this and the Red Line too.
No wonder people are clamoring to live in Cambridge, throwing great
piles of money at even the unlikeliest-looking real estate.
</P>
<P>
   The People's Republik of Cambridge. That image of Cambridge is
fading fast. Someday soon the only trace of it may be the bar of
the same name in Central Square. Right now Cambridge is less like a
People's Republik and more like some economically booming Eastern
Bloc country after the Berlin Wall came down. Everybody wants a
piece of the action, except for the people who can't afford to live
in Cambridge anymore. I watch the mall-ing of Central Square and
wonder how long it will be before it goes the way of Harvard
Square, which more and more resembles Disney World. A great place
to visit but you wouldn't want to live there.
</P>
<P>
   Some of my neighbors have lived in the same houses 40, 50, 70
years, all their lives. Now people like me are moving in and
changing the character of the neighborhood. But who could blame
people for wanting to live on my street? It's a real neighborhood
with families (including families of raccoons and skunks) where
kids play in the street and everybody is civil to one another, most
of the time. How long will it stay that way?
</P>
<P>
   The thing I like best about living where I do is that I never
know what I'll see when I walk out my front door and head to
Central Square. One day it was a flier nailed to a utility pole
inviting one and all to a ``potluck supper and crime update.''
Another day it was a bus full of singing socialists about to embark
on a pilgrimage to Cuba. And one day I saw the Fringe Voice
himself, walking down my street. The star of a local cable TV show
of the same name, the Fringe Voice finds conspiracies everywhere. A
favorite theme is that President Kennedy is alive. On one memorable
show, he connected the late president with Nicole Simpson and Ron
Goldman, saying, with studied irony, ``I'm suggesting that Nicole
and Ronald are as dead as President Kennedy.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to argue with that, but why would anybody try? It's
Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
