</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SAFE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SAFE MEN' GOES NOWHERE, BUT DOES HAVE ITS MOMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Safe Men,'' this week's low-budget American Independent comedy
by a first-time writer-director, is a movie that goes absolutely
nowhere, but the journey is brief (89 minutes) and not without its
engaging characters and moments of pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   The heroes are Sam (Sam Rockwell) and Eddie (Steve Zahn), a pair
of dim-witted, harrowingly untalented entertainers obviously
modeled after the Hope and Crosby of the ``Road'' pictures, or
perhaps Beatty and Hoffman of ``Ishtar.''
</P>
<P>
   In a bar one night, the guys are mistaken for a pair of gifted
safe-crackers (hence the title), and hauled before Big Fat Bernie
Gayle (Michael Lerner), the head of the local branch of the
Providence, R.I., Jewish mafia.
</P>
<P>
   Since Bernie intends to kill them if they don't rob a series of
safes he has lined up for them, they naturally pretend to be the
real safe men, and spend the rest of the movie trying and failing
to live up to their unearned reputations.
</P>
<P>
   After a straight-forward opening, the film gradually settles
into a farce that thinks nothing of having its protagonist suddenly
disclose he's wearing false buttocks (he feels his own are too
small), or stopping the action to have a character tell a
three-minute story about a woman destroyed by a pair of flammable
slacks.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, it's been a while since a tiny movie like this one
has provided so many meaty character parts _ not only leads
Rockwell (``Lawn Dogs'') and Zahn (``Out of Sight''), but also
Lerner, Harvey Fierstein (as a rival gangster) and particularly
Paul Giamatti (as Bernie's insecure toadie).
</P>
<P>
   The considerable downside of the picture is that it doesn't
really have a script _ nothing close to a three-act structure or
the profusion of plot that even a farce needs to be credible over a
feature length. It's just a succession of acting-class exercises
that are all rather well done but unconnected to any satisfying,
larger design.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's more inspired goofiness than in most of the
cookie-cutter American Indie comedies that have whisked through the
multiplexes so far this year. If writer-director John Hamburg (who
is only a year out of film school) can ever master the basics of
screenwriting, he could be a filmmaker to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Safe Men. Directed and written by John Hamburg. Cast: Sam
Rockwell, Steve Zahn, Mark Ruffalo, Harvey Fierstein, Michael
Lerner. October Films. Varsity. 89 minutes. Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0984 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SNAKE-SPI &LR;      08-06 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SNAKE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN VIEW `SNAKE EYES' TWO WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A good argument could be made that Brian De Palma's ``Snake
Eyes'' is a fairly dreadful movie: arty, over-blown, preposterous
beyond preposterous, filled with groaning coincidences and fueled
by one of Nicolas Cage's most self-indulgent performances.
</P>
<P>
   But I choose to see it as De Palma's most daring,
let-it-all-hang-out adventure in storytelling _ virtually his
late-in-life attempt at a ``Citizen Kane.'' It doesn't completely
work, but he has great fun with the medium, and it's infectious.
</P>
<P>
   The film is about a conspiracy to assassinate a controversial
Secretary of Defense while he's watching a world heavyweight boxing
championship in an Atlantic City gambling casino. To complicate
matters, it takes place while the city is being battered by a
hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   The main characters are a marginally crooked cop (Cage), who is
sitting ringside and has a huge bet on the fight, and his best
friend, a naval officer (Gary Sinise) who is in charge of the
secretary's security guard while he attends the event.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a mysterious lady (Carla Gugino) who confronts the
secretary moments before the shots ring out, a heavyweight champ
(Stan Shaw) who takes an obvious dive at the same time, and
assorted cops, gamblers, gangsters, journalists and conspirators.
</P>
<P>
   When the secretary is shot, pandemonium breaks out, the
entrances of the arena are blocked, and the cop and his Navy buddy
work together to try and solve the complicated crime in the hour or
so it will take the federal cops to make their way through the
storm to the casino.
</P>
<P>
   But De Palma constantly diverges from this narrative line to
examine every aspect of the story from an array of viewpoints,
often going back in time and working up to scenes we're already
witnessed from a fresh perspective. So the film is a succcesion of
``Rashomon''-like layers of truth.
</P>
<P>
   And he complements this scheme visually. Not only does he
skillfully integrate the video technology involved in the huge
sporting event into his thriller plot-line, he moves his own camera
through walls and ceilings, occasionally allows it to take the eye
of one of his characters, and zips it around the auditorium as if
it has a mind of its own.
</P>
<P>
   It's a challenging movie, and one to which, frankly, it's not
always easy to stay connected. We often see sequences in which the
most important scene appears to be missing (to be supplied later),
or find ourselves lost in a flashback from some secondary
character's point-of-view.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if we pay attention, the puzzle all comes together
neatly. And the movie's energy, wit and directorial boldness
finally make us forget its absurd improbabilities. Even Cage, who
bounces off the walls throughout as if he's on speed, ultimately
wins us over.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, ``Snake Eyes'' is one more in a surprising number of
big Hollywood movies this summer that are simply sick to death of
the old formulas and the old conventions and are desperate to try
something _ anything! _ new. For this alone, it deserves our
respect, and a look.
</P>
<P>
   Snake Eyes. Directed and produced by Brian De Palma. Screenplay
by David Koepp. Cast: Nicolas Cage, Gary Sinise, John Heard, Carla
Gugino. Paramount. 99 minutes. Rated R for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
