<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHIES-ETIQUETTE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM BYTES TO BITE: SILICON VALLEY ELITE TACKLE MANNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN McKINNEY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ You can tell a lot about people by the way
the eat. In Silicon Valley, where big business is often conducted
over burritos, most executives take a simple point-and-click
approach to dining. But that's about to change.
</P>
<P>
   Web heads and techno-titans are learning that, even in an
entrepreneurial environment, where casual is king, it sometimes
takes more than a million-dollar idea to woo capital and clients.
</P>
<P>
   It takes good manners.
</P>
<P>
   So for the past three years, Sue Fox and Lyndy Janes have made
manners their business. Since the two Los Gatos residents opened
The Workshoppe, they've been teaching the etiquette illiterate of
the high-tech literati the proper way to eat Cornish hen, or how to
correct wardrobe and grooming.
</P>
<P>
   With a list of clients that include Apple, Hewlett Packard and
Web TV, the two have their work cut out for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``One man thought that licking your knife was the acceptable way
to clean it,'' laughs Workshoppe co-founder Fox. ``It may be a
dog-eat-dog world out there in high tech, but that doesn't mean you
should behave like one.''
</P>
<P>
   Janes and Fox began their protocol training workshops for teens,
but soon moved on to teaching their parents as well. According to
Janes, who is British, many Silicon Valley executives feel a little
insecure and even embarrassed when it comes to entertaining and
fine dining. A certain ``je ne sais quoi'' has been lost amid the
hustle and bustle of high tech-life styles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a reason for mum saying `Get your elbows off the
table,' and it's coming into play now in business and socially.''
says Janes, in her crisp British cadence. ``With people from Europe
and other areas coming to do business here, we all should be more
aware of our own culture,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   True, first impressions do count. But in a valley where
executives proclaim their status at the office by wearing shorts
and sandals, and computer code often takes precedence over dress
code, isn't emphasizing proper manners a little too Victorian?
</P>
<P>
   Not a bit of it, Janes argues. The Workshoppe stresses function
over formality _ taking the prissiness out of etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about making other people feel comfortable around you and
being considerate towards them. We don't expect clients to leave
here behaving like a character in a Merchant Ivory movie,'' Janes
says. ``Although that would be very romantic,'' she adds with a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   And Janes is all-too-often reminded of the scope of her work as
a manners missionary. Walking through the San Jose Fairmont's
fanciest eatery on the way to teach a class on table etiquette, she
passes a man with something stuck in his teeth, something enormous
that he's attempting to gouge out with his finger. The well attired
young woman seated across from him doesn't seem to mind, but Janes
knows better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look very nice. I wouldn't want that man to pass me
the bread basket, would you?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Workshoppe participants have stories of their own. Kathleen
O'Roarke, of San Jose, went to the class after attending a state
dinner at the White House. It was a formative experience for the
new etiquette connoisseur.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting in between these two guys, and the one on the
right really knew what he was doing, made it look easy; but the one
on the left was lost.''
</P>
<P>
   She found out later that the man to her left, made so vulnerable
by forks and fingerbowls, was a former secretary of Defense.
</P>
<P>
   Even among the cultivated, manners still make the man. O'Roarke
remembers a brother-in-law with an doctorate who chewed loud enough
to deafen table conversation. Janes has noticed similar tendencies
among Silicon Valley elite. ``Some CEOs don't care so much about
manners, but even the most powerful man could be dreadful to sit
next to at dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   Among tales of terrible teeth pickers and embarrassing gristle
gaffes Janes reminds her class that even the most well-intended
diner may not be well-informed. In one case, a woman took her
fiancee in for a private consultation because she was concerned
about his table manners. The man was a corporate executive and the
couple enjoyed all the trappings of a sophisticated lifestyle; but
one thing was horribly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``He insisted on licking his knife before putting it back on the
table.'' recalls Janes, who had to delve into the client's past to
get to the root of the problem. It turned out that the impulse was
well-intended: save a clean table cloth from being soiled. While he
was barely tall enough to reach the table, the man had used the
technique to impress his mother. As his fiancee feared, it wasn't
going over as well at corporate luncheons. And perhaps worst of
all, it was threatening their marriage plans: his future
mother-in-law couldn't stomach his table behavior.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
