<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of FRIDAY, Aug. 7:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Monica Lewinski, the former White
House intern, testifies about her relationship with President
Clinton before one of Kenneth Starr's grand juries. Other
developments in the investigation. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LEWINSKI (Washington) _ For six months she's been a
virtual prisoner in her own home. But with her appearance today
before the grand jury, Monica Lewinski takes the first step toward
resuming a life free of lawyers, publicists and a daily recounting
of the most personal details of a private relationship turned
public. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   RENO-CONTEMPT (Washington) _ Rep. Dan Burton, chairman of the
House committee investigating campaign fund raising, tries to get
his committee to cite Attorney General Janet Reno for contempt of
Congress for refusing to turn over memorandums from her top
investigators recommending an outside prosecutor. By David E.
Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-FINANCE (Washington) _ The House is expected to take
final action on campaign finance, with Shays-Meehan supporters
trying to fight GOP leaders' effort swing support behind weaker
bill. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANICS-CENSUS (Washington) _ The nation's Hispanic population
is nearing the 30 million mark and is poised to overtake blacks as
the country's largest minority group in just eight years, if not
sooner, the Census Bureau said today. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   ALASKA-OIL (Washington) _ Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt opens
part of the Alaskan oil reserve for drilling, over the objections
of environmentalists. By John H. Cushman Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-MISSING-GIRL (Seaside, Calif.) _ Two months ago,
13-year-old Christina Marie Williams took her dog, Greg, for a walk
in her neighborhood on the evening of June 12. About a half-hour
later, Greg wandered back alone. Over the next few days, witnesses
reported seeing two men in an old sedan lurking in the area before
and after Christina and the dog went walking. One woman told the
authorities she saw a girl who matched Christina's description
sitting in the car, looking frightened. Those sightings, unusual
for a kidnapping case, enabled the federal authorities to develop
sketches of the men and the car they were driving. But in the seven
weeks since Christina disappeared, the drawings remain all they
have to go on. That, and fervent prayers that Northern California
does not have another Polly Klaas case on its hands. By Michael
Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   PHILLY-BABY-DEATHS (Philadelphia) _ A look at Marie Noe, who has
been charged with killing 8 of her 10 children between 1949 and
1968.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON-COLUMNIST (Undated) _ Developments on Mike Barnicle, who
refused to resign as Boston Globe columnist after charges he used
jokes taken from the comedian George Carlin. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ Chief U.N. weapons inspector Butler
briefs the Security Council on Iraq; other developments. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.S. (Washington) _ U.S. reaction to Iraqi developments. By
Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ The government moves to seize the assets
of three semi-privatized oil companies for failure to pay back
taxes; finance official says July tax collections, while up from
previous months, were still well behind IMF projections. By Michael
Wines.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-REBELLION (Abidjan, Ivory Coast) _ Developments in the
rebellion in Congo. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-KOSOVO (Dateline to come) _ Developments in the ethnic
Albanian separatist movement in the Serbian province of Kosovo. By
Mike O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-ZHIVKOV (Undated) _ Todor Zhivkov, the Communist ruler of
Bulgaria from 1954 until his ouster in 1989, dies at 86. By David
Binder.
</P>
<P>
   Story has MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:50 p.m. the Dow industrials were down 8
points and the Nasdaq index was up 24 points. Earlier, shares fell
0.7 percent in Tokyo and 2.8 percent in Hong Kong. Stocks were down
1.5 percent in Frankfurt and 1.4 percent in London. At midday, the
long bond was off 4/32, with the yield at 5.68 percent. By David
Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ A judge will hear arguments
from Microsoft and the government regarding the availability of
documents and company officials. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-VALLEY (San Jose, Calif.) _ Microsoft's new president,
Steven Ballmer, makes his first public visit to Silicon Valley,
attempting to mend fences between the software publisher and the
nation's high-technology center. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   SUNBEAM-PROBE (Undated) _ Sunbeam will be required to restate
financial results for 1997 and the first quarter of 1998 based on a
review that follows a Securities and Exchange Commission
investigation of its accounting practices. By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   RETAIL-SALES (Undated) _ Retailers report strong same-store
sales for July, aided by continued demand for clothing, garden
products and other summer goods. By Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   BANKAMERICA-NATIONSBANK (Undated) _ BankAmerica's chief
executive, David Coulter, could collect $30 million if he leaves
for any reason once the Nationsbank merger is completed. By Timothy
L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   CHRYSLER-DAIMLER (Washington) _ Chrysler's chairman, Robert J.
Eaton, would get cash and stock with a value of $69.9 million and
future rights to stock valued at about $239 million when the
Daimler-Benz deal is completed, according to a proxy filing. The
final terms of the deal are set: Chrysler holders will receive
0.6235 share of the merged company, while Daimler-Benz holders will
receive 1.005 shares. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   VW-ROLLS (London) _ Volkswagen's plan to acquire all of
Rolls-Royce Motor Cars was brought to a sudden halt last week.
Instead, in an extraordinary deal, BMW and Volkswagen agreed to
carve up the rights to Rolls-Royce and Bentley. How did
Volkswagen's plan come undone? According to some of the
participants in the negotiations, the reasons lay on and under the
hoods of the cars themselves _ in the engines and components
supplied since 1994 by BMW and in the rights to the Rolls-Royce
name and winged emblem on the hood, both owned by Rolls-Royce PLC,
a separate company. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   AMEX-OUTLOOK (Undated) _ Amrican Express says Asia will hurt
business in the second half. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-PORN-SHOPS (New York) _ New York City and porn shops battle
in court today over efforts to close down six of the shops. By
David Rohde.
</P>
