<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1049 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN07-COX     08-06 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Travel light, but be prepared
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've been traveling the world and writing about its people and
politics for almost nine years. My latest assignment was the
Baltics. A series of stories over the next couple of weeks will be
forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   But with all my travels _ everywhere from South Africa to
Siberia to Baghdad _ you'd think I would've garnered much wisdom of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there are just two things I've learned:
</P>
<P>
   1. That the world is divided into two distinct cultures:
Countries where buses pass on hills and curves and countries where
buses do not pass on hills and curves.
</P>
<P>
   2. How to pack.
</P>
<P>
   If you're taking a trip, take it from me _ there are but three
necessities for the traveler:
</P>
<P>
   Passport, tickets, money. Everything else is dead weight.
</P>
<P>
   On my latest trip, involving stops in six countries in 16 days,
I managed with one suitcase (a folding bag with rollers and lots of
pockets) plus a carry-on. The carry-on is for passport, tickets and
money.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I can't believe the stuff I feel I can't leave home
without. Here's an inventory I took along the way:
</P>
<P>
   _ Penlight, duct tape, multi-purpose knife/tool.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rain-resistant cap, collapsible umbrella, Scotch tape.
</P>
<P>
   _ Office stationery for faxes, business cards, press card.
</P>
<P>
   _ Walking shoes, dress shoes, one pair each.
</P>
<P>
   _ Three pairs of pants, six shirts, six to eight changes of
underwear and socks. (I usually take old clothes and often discard
them toward the end of the trip. I'm probably the only man who ever
left Hong Kong with one less suit than he arrived with.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Miniature clock that covers the world's time zones.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adhesive tape, Band-Aids.
</P>
<P>
   _ Blue blazer, weatherproof zipper jacket.
</P>
<P>
   _ Photocopy of passport.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bath sponge, bath brush. (Washcloths are a novelty in much of
the rest of the world.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Paperback novels. (English-language reading material is often
scarce and always expensive.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Extra pair of eyeglasses, extra batteries.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shower shoes, sweat suit. (Comfortable attire on overnight
trains.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Sleep mask, earplugs. (Necessities on overnight trains.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Wet Ones. (Next best thing to a shower on overnight trains.)
</P>
<P>
   _ One necktie.
</P>
<P>
   _ Antibacterial ointment, stomach medicine, allergy pills.
</P>
<P>
   _ Recyclable cameras preloaded with film.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pocket notebooks, ballpoint pens, micro-tape recorder and
extra tapes.
</P>
<P>
   That's about it _ most everything that I required for France,
Russia, Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania and Poland, making my way by
trains, planes and automobiles, starting out in Paris and ending up
in Warsaw.
</P>
<P>
   So it is that they tell this joke about the train that runs
between Paris and Moscow:
</P>
<P>
   When travelers from Paris arrive in Warsaw, they look out the
windows and say, ``Oh, we're already in Moscow.''
</P>
<P>
   When travelers from Moscow arrive in Warsaw, they look out the
windows and say, ``Oh, we're already in Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Warsaw likes to think of itself as the Paris of
Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   I saw Paris, and I saw Warsaw. Warsaw, at best, is the Paris of
Eastern Poland.
</P>
<P>
   More later.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
</P>
<P>
   AWEW18A(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
