<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUVENILE CROCODILE GETS A HOME ... FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY DELGADO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A 3-foot crocodile that was found in the back
yard of a San Francisco home will be turned over the a Golden Gate
Park aquarium rather than put to death, animal control officials
say.
</P>
<P>
   The Steinhart Aquarium will provide a temporary home for Ernest
the crocodile, which was netted July 28 by an animal control
officer at a Mission District house. The resident had reported that
a ``large lizard'' was threatening her cat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the Steinhart came through, we realized that it was
better,'' said Animal Care and Control spokeswoman Melissa Flowers.
``We keep him in our own city, and he doesn't have to go through
shipping'' to a facility in Boulder, Colo., that also agreed to
take the reptile.
</P>
<P>
   The feisty juvenile croc had been living in temporary shelter
where it was fed frozen hamsters.
</P>
<P>
   Since the capture, animal care and control officials had tried
hard to find him a home. Request after request was turned down,
including a rejection from Steinhart, and officials said they had
no choice but to kill the reptile.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Bushwater Reptiles of Boulder, a company that specializes
in reptile transfers, offered to assume the burden of looking for a
home for Ernest.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes of the offer, shelter officials began making
arrangements to send Ernest to Boulder, but they learned that the
reptile could not be flown because of an airline embargo on
shipping animals during the summer as protection against the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Officials were looking into other travel options for Ernest,
Flowers said, when an official from Steinhart said Wednesday
morning that the aquarium would take over the responsibility of
finding a permanent home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to do the most appropriate thing for the animal,
and that's to find it a good home,'' said Ken Howell, senior
aquatic biologist at the aquarium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1430EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
