for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Friday,
Aug. 7, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Tina
May at (206) 448-8355.
<TEXT>
<P>
   FILM-SAFE (Undated) ``Safe Men,'' this week's low-budget
American Independent comedy by a first-time writer-director, is a
movie that goes absolutely nowhere, but the journey is brief (89
minutes) and not without its engaging characters and moments of
pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BILLY (Undated) ``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss'' has some
wonderful moments. By Paula Nechak. (story will move in the ``e''
category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-EYES (Undated) A good argument could be made that Brian De
Palma's ``Snake Eyes'' is a fairly dreadful movie: arty,
over-blown, preposterous beyond preposterous, filled with groaning
coincidences and fueled by one of Nicolas Cage's most
self-indulgent performances.
</P>
<P>
