A1075 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-BILLY-SPI &LR;      08-06 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BILLY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BILLY'S KISS' WORTH IT SOME OF THE TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a delicious scene in Tommy O'Haver's first feature,
``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy (Sean P. Hayes) is in love with an irrationally idealized,
perfect and obsessive vision of a straight man named,
prophetically, Gabriel (Brad Rowe). The two become friends and,
after a night of drinking, Gabriel conveniently crashes at Billy's
house. Gabriel has an estranged girlfriend somewhere in San
Francisco but the two spend the night in, first, adjoining rooms
and later share the bed.
</P>
<P>
   It's a telling and truthful universal moment that beautifully
captures the sleepless anxiety that occurs when the senses, the
mind _ and the body _ are fully aroused by the presense of the
exalted beloved and the consequences of chance and its aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, a couple scenes do not a movie make. O'Haver
professes to having been tainted early on by ``women's melodramas''
_ ``The Heiress,'' ``Imitation Of Life'' and probably anything
starring Joan Crawford _ but ``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss''
feels, in truth, more akin to ``Gidget'' or the ``Beach Party''
genre.
</P>
<P>
   Billy wants to be in love. He claims to be a romantic but he's
really a fussy film director and photographer whose lens keeps him
removed from real life. He's a human third eye. When he meets
Gabriel, all of that changes. He's always picked ``unavailable''
partners in the past, and Gabriel initially seems decent and open.
There's just a minor problem _ he's heterosexual. Billy at first
suffers and then again retreats behind the camera until, when fate
intervenes, he finds there is life after true confessions.
</P>
<P>
   Opening with a Pedro Almodovar-esque, dark subversiveness that
promises to add a little snap to the recent mediocre gay film
scene, the film opts to segue into the bright light and sunny
superficiality of '60s movie purity and moral caution. The second
half of the film never matches the brooding intensity of the
opening act and that proves to be its downfall. It's sanitized
beyond belief to be a comforting ``crossover'' film.
</P>
<P>
   Billy's journey doesn't equal much more than that of any scared
young guy who can't fathom commitment with anyone who might be
emotionally available. It's the same old plotline that threatens to
curse all recent Third World cinema: the protagonists just keep
lusting after the wrong people because they're trying to gain
acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   Camille Paglia once wrote that counter-culture groups such as
gays (or any minority) are in danger of becoming acculturated into
society and giving up the fight in exchange for a mainstream stamp
of approval. If ``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss'' _ as well as
other new ``Big Chill'' gay/ethnic cinematic blends such as
``Relax, It's Just Sex''_ are any indicator, then the anarchic,
sexualized out-there movies of gay cinema, like ``Swoon,'' ``The
Living End,'' ``Go Fish'' and ``The Watermelon Woman,'' may be the
next endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss. Directed and written by Tommy
O'Haver. Cast: Sean P. Hayes, Brad Rowe. Trimark Pictures. 92
minutes. Rated R for gay themes, sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1435EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
