 ART ADV.: Photos with YANKEE-RODEO (2) and GENIUS-CAMP are being
transmitted to NYT Photo Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MAYAN-TRAGEDY (New Bedford, Mass.) -- His 2,200-mile flight from
Central America to New Bedford's waterfront, brough him a horrible
death, screaming in a language few understood. Antonio Ajqui was
part of a nearly invisible industrial underground. By Thomas
Farragher. 1300 words. (a and i coding)
</P>
<P>
   YANKEE-RODEO (Becket, Mass.) _ Steve Robinson, an Afro-American
cowboy from Connecticut, and his Berkshire Rodeo Team are
determined to bring Wild West-style thrills to Yankee hills. By
Judith Gaines. 1000 words. PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   MA-GOVERNMENT-HELP (Woburn, Mass.) _ There's a widespread and
strong conviction among voters that government be more activist in
helping its citizens take care of their children. By Geeta Anand.
1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   MOB-MERCURIO (Boston) -- By reputation, Sonny Mercurio was a
stand-up guy, unwilling to wear a wire or testify against his mob
pals. Now he's squealing on everyone -- including the FBI. By
Shelley Murphy. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JACOBY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Seventy-five years of underestimating
Calvin Coolidge. By Jeff Jacoby.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE &LR;   &UR; (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GENIUS-CAMP (Cambridge, Mass.) -- For six weeks every summer, 80
of the most gifted international high school seniors do college or
graduate-level independent research in math and science at MIT. By
Laura Yuen. 1800 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   GENIUS-RICKOVER (Undated) -- Before there was the Research
Science Institute, there was the Rickover Science Institute. By
Laura Yuen. 450 words.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-SOLAR (New York) -- What makes today's solar roofing
different from the old hot-water panels on the homes of solar
pioneers is the way they are integrated into the structure. By
Margo Miller.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDCARE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Talking to our children about
humankind's most awful deeds is not easy for any parent. By Barbara
Meltz. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY-COLUMN (Undated) _ The neighbors move in with us. By
Linda Weltner.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-PROJECT (Undated) -- Two cardinal rules when painting: Buy
quality (expensive) brushes and clean them properly _ and
immediately _ after use. By Peter Hotton.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   HANDYMAN-HOTTON (Undated) _ Stamped concrete gains popularity.
By Peter Hotton.
</P>
<P>
   WHITE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Right now Cambridge is less like a
People's Republik and more like some economically booming Eastern
Bloc country after the Berlin Wall came down. By Diane White.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-NOTES (Undated) -- It's only a one-day snapshot, but the
Rocky Mountain Media Watch's examination of the night newscasts on
102 local television stations March 11 revealed that no news
succeeds like bad news, particularly if it's bloody. By Mark
Jurkowitz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEALTH (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEDNOTES-SCI (Undated) _ Exercise may not cut risk of breast
cancer; Italians screen young athletes for heart problems, with
good results; air bags in cars protect against eye injuries. By
Richard Saltus.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMPUTERS (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Buying more memory for your
computer is cheaper than ever, but more confusing too. A bit of
help in picking the right kind. By Hiawatha Bray.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WEB-MEDICINE (Washington) -- Pushing the frontiers of
long-distance medicine, two physicians are making money in
Massachusetts with a Web site that allows them to prescribe
medicine and diagnose ailments by e-mail for patients all over the
globe. By Aaron Zitner.
</P>
<P>
   ONBUSINESS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Those people who say the bear
market is old news for most stocks can make their point in
Massachusetts. By Steven Syre and Steve Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;   &UR; (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PATRIOTS (Smithfield, R.I.) _ New England needs at least one
part of its offense _ passing _ to become reliable quickly because
the other half _ running _ has so many questions. And the sooner
the passing game finds a rhythm, the better. By Michael Madden.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-RYDER (Boston) _ The PGA has bowed to public opinion and
agreed to refund a controversial $5 application fee for a random
drawing for Ryder Cup tickets. By Joe Concannon. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
