<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINMENT-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Weekend Section stories in sight at this hour from The New York
Times News Service for Friday, Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON-ARTS-HUB (Boston) _ Boston, the ``Athens of America'' a
century ago, is called the Hub by its current residents. Certainly
in terms of art, the moniker is apt. Museums abound, large and
small, old and new, independently run or affiliated with colleges.
Some are in the heart of the city; others form a bright
constellation across the surrounding countryside. By Holland
Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   BERKSHIRES-WHARTON (Undated) _ In the fall of 1899, a young
woman of old New York society and fledgling literary notice grew
disgusted with what she considered the vapid wasteland of Newport,
R.I. On an impulse, she packed up dogs, servants and husband and
headed for Lenox, Mass., the fashionable Berkshire mountain
retreat. Within three years, the young woman, Edith Wharton, had
built the Mount, a classical American home. My family and I spent a
recent weekend touring the Mount and wandering around other
literary landmarks of the Berkshires. By Elisabeth Bumiller. &UR; (BU) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRIDGEHAMPTON-MUSIC-FESTIVAL (Undated) _ The Bridgehampton
Chamber Music Festival opens its 15th season on Long Island this
weekend. By Allan Kozinn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FIRST-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``First Love, Last Rites'': Jesse
Peretz, director; with Ian McEwan, Natasha Gregson Wagner, Giovanni
Ribisi. Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   GADJOE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Gadjo Dilo'': Romain Duris,
director; A celebration of gypsy culture. In French, Romanian,
Romany, with English subtitles. Reviewed by Anita Gates.
</P>
<P>
   SAFE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ `'Safe Men'': Jon Hamburg,
writer/director; with Sam Rockwell, Steve Zahn, Michael Lerner,
Harvey Fierstein. By Lawrence Van Gelder.
</P>
<P>
   SNAKE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Snake Eyes'': Brian De Palma,
director; with Nicolas Cage, Carla Cugino, Gary Sinise, John Heard.
Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
