<HEADER>
A1126 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUTLER-INHERIT-FAITH-     08-06 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUTLER-INHERIT-FAITH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEALING WITH YOUR RELIGIOUS INHERITANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York Times
Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative CONNIE
WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or fax
her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Recently, I attended an Orioles baseball game at Camden Yards in
Baltimore. I grew up in Baltimore in the 'sixties during the team's
glory days. Back then, my family attended hundreds of games.
 &HT;    After we moved west in 1972, I became convinced that the team's
decline was directly tied to our departure.
 &HT;    Baseball is my mother's religion. As long as I can remember,
summer meant baseball. She taught us everything about the game. She
embodied its passion.
 &HT;    Arriving at old Memorial Stadium, Mom acted as if she were
making a pilgrimage. We always sat on the third-base line and
followed her lead. Mom's baseball liturgy was simple:
 &HT;    --Don't applaud after the national anthem. It is irreverent to
applaud a hymn.
 &HT;    --Don't leave your seat for any reason until the seventh-inning
stretch.
 &HT;    --Cheer. But be polite unless the umpire is really stupid.
 &HT;    --Don't leave the game until the last pitch is thrown.
 &HT;    --Believe the Orioles will win and they will (if they don't,
your faith was inadequate).
 &HT;    At Camden Yards with my family, I sensed my mother's presence.
Throughout the game, I kept instructing my stepson on Mom's Rules.
He'd only been to one major league game. His behavior shocked me;
he seemed to be a baseball pagan. The boy needed training.
 &HT;    I, however, felt inadequate to the task. I needed Mom. Breaking
a rule, I phoned her and held up the receiver so she could hear
that baseball park sound. She cried.
 &HT;    Baseball is my mother's faith. It is not mine. I enjoy and
understand it. I know how to watch a game. Occasionally, a great
game gives me chills. But I don't worship it. In the end, as it did
for my stepson on that hot Baltimore Saturday, baseball eludes me.
 &HT;    Poor Mom. Passing one's faith to children is difficult. And
inheriting one's parents' faith can seem like a curse. I never
fully embraced mother's baseball religion, no matter how thoroughly
she indoctrinated me.
 &HT;    Sitting in Camden Yards, I imitated her ritual but lacked her
passion. I felt guilty all the while.
 &HT;    In her recent book, ``Amazing Grace,'' Kathleen Norris writes of
family faith: ``Human inheritance is both blessing and curse. And
in religious inheritance this paradox is acute. For many of us
religion is heavy baggage.''
 &HT;    That baggage takes many forms. For some, the difficulty is
summoning the faith of a devout forebear. Some depart from
long-standing family tradition and choose another way. Some reject
faith altogether. Some embrace faith contrary to familial
skepticism. Some pick a narrower path; some, a broader one.
 &HT;    Whatever the case, it is a rare family that maintains a faith
tradition over generations. More often, families are patchworks of
faith -- a number of stories and traditions stitched into one.
 &HT;    Embracing my mother's faith has not been easy. As a college
student, I thought myself above baseball's proletarian pleasures.
``Lower class,'' ``uneducated,'' I sniffed. Eventually I passed
through that stage, but still found the game dull -- bored by my
mother's incessant summertime monologue.
 &HT;    Finally, baseball summoned to mind the narrow-mindedness and
violence of my working-class Baltimore childhood. I just couldn't
believe the way she did. Too many bad memories.
 &HT;    At Camden Yards, however, I realized that I needn't embrace my
mother's faith. I needed to accept it as hers, appreciate the
beauty of what she found, and pass the ritual onto a new
generation. I could both honor her and could be honest regarding my
own beliefs.
 &HT;    Yes, baseball is a boring sort of game. But it is my mother's
boring game. It was her way to salvation. I don't understand it,
but it is important to her.
 &HT;    Norris says all religious inheritance -- good and bad -- can
neither be forgotten nor undone. The baggage is always with us.
 &HT;    Our task is to live with it, to embrace the good and redeem the
bad. And then to pass on to our children an open-minded and
listening faith -- one described by the Episcopal prayerbook as
``an inquiring and discerning heart, the courage to will and to
persevere, a spirit to know to love you, and the gift of joy and
wonder in all your works.''
 &HT;    If my children embrace that, I won't even care if they worship
football.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1998 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
