<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINMENT-BUDGET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
.
</HEADLINE>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
SNAKE-MOVIE (Los Angeles) _ A new Brian De Palma movie is always a
cause for celebration and dread. Cineastes and suspense lovers
alike know they can look forward to shocking plot twists and
virtuoso visual techniques. His new thriller, ``Snake Eyes,''finds
De Palma trying to satisfy both audience segments. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
KONG-FILM (Los Angeles) _ Fay Wray and King Kong share the marquee
again at the ``Battle of Apes'' double feature, a presentation of
the Academy Standards. Plus, some Wray trivia about the 1920s
starlet whose dramatic acting career is overshadowed by the giant
gorilla. By Bob McCarthy. 
. 
LAST-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``First Love, Last Rites'' strives to
be a realistic depiction of teen-age love's consuming passions and
devouring fears, but comes off as slight and unnecessarily
symbolic. 2 Stars. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
SAFE-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ There are a couple of dim bulbs at the
center of the engagingly offbeat comedy ``Safe Men,'' but unlike
the recent dimwit duos of ``BASEketball'' or ``Dumb &AMP; Dumber,''
these guys mind their manners. Credit goes to first-time
writer-director John Hamburg for this charming, warm and, yes,
funny movie debut. 3 Stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
SNAKE-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Just a few minutes into ``Snake
Eyes,'' you know you're watching a Brian De Palma movie as the
camera seamlessly follows Nicolas Cage through an Atlantic City
arena, twisting through corridors, climbing stairs, hopping onto an
escalator and finally landing on the floor of the arena in the
middle of a heavyweight prize fight. 2{ Stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
SOREL-THEATER (Los Angeles) _ Eccentricity, in Louise Sorel's book,
is a good thing because it shows you're ``taking life in.'' That's
exactly what Sorel, a past winner of Soap Opera Digest's Best
Villainess Award, appears to be doing with a vengeance these days.
By Reed Johnson. 
. 
RAMBLERS-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ Some of California's top
country-rock musicians have turned their attentions to another
American musical form and now perform as the Laurel Canyon
Ramblers, focusing on the bluegrass music pioneered by Kentucky
multi-instrumentalist Bill Monroe in the '40s. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
POP-BEAT (Los Angeles) _ Local blues-funk guitarist Stevie Gurr has
a few points in his favor right off the bat. For starters, he spent
much of the '80s recording and touring with bluesman Elvin Bishop.
Then the guitarist joined Dr. John's. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
DISCS-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ Jermaine Dupri's ``Life in 1472''
could've been the hip-hop record of the year. Musically, it just
might be. Lyrically, it makes you want to reach for the earplugs.
By Fred Shuster. 
. 
ALTMAN-VIDEO (Los Angeles) _ Watching a Robert Altman movie can be
a frustrating experience for moviegoers. His latest film, ``The
Gingerbread Man,'' recently hit video stores, and the so-called
legal thriller based on a John Grisham script amply demonstrates
Altman's faults and virtues. By Rob Lowman. 
. 

<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
