<HEADLINE>
WHERE THE BLUEGRASS GROWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; For those afraid the sound of authentic,
traditional California country music might be disappearing, there's
the Laurel Canyon Ramblers.
</P>
<P>
   The group formed four years ago from the ashes of the Desert
Rose Band, which had been founded by Chris Hillman, a former member
of the Byrds and Flying Burrito Brothers. Ex-Desert Rose members
Bill Bryson (bass) and Herb Pedersen (guitar and harmony vocals)
later launched the Laurel Canyon Ramblers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're songwriters, musicians and singers,'' said Kenny
Blackwell, who plays mandolin in the Ramblers. ``Some of our stuff
will sound very traditional, but some stuff will show our folk,
rock and jazz influences.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackwell, who grew up in southern Michigan and studied mandolin
with Jethro Burns of the famous hillbilly bluegrass duo Homer &AMP;
Jethro, said the ability to improvise is extremely important for
bluegrass musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both jazz and bluegrass are very improvisational genres,'' he
said. ``Stylistically, the styles are very different but that
element is consistent in both forms.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime bluegrass fan and guitarist Dave Provost has caught the
Ramblers three times and said each was a very different experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really depends on their mood,'' Provost said. ``Sometimes
they'll lean toward gospel, or they'll play fast and furious _ even
faster than punk rock but with much more precision. Their music
doesn't seem dated, but you get the sense of a tradition that goes
deeper than the Smithsonian Institute. It's not that they're
emulating a style, it's what they've grown up doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ramblers, who mix the traditional Kentucky bluegrass sound
with the Southern California country-rock sound of Gram Parsons,
have released three albums, including the current disc, ``Back on
the Street Again'' (Sugar Hill).
</P>
<P>
   The band _ which also includes Roger Reed (guitar) and Gabe
Witcher (fiddle) _ appears Saturday at the John Anson Ford
Amphitheatre on a bill with traditional bluegrass outfit Lost
Highway and young bluegrass group Nickel Creek.
</P>
<P>
   The Ramblers will also appear at McCabe's in Santa Monica in the
next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bluegrass seems to be getting more exposure than ever these
days,'' said Blackwell, who lives in Granada Hills and has repaired
guitars at the Blue Ridge Pickin' Parlor in Canoga Park for the
past 10 years. ``And that's good for everybody _ all the bands that
are really good and all the bands that are just starting out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bluegrass originally grew out of the traditional string band
music that formed the roots of country music. Led by Kentucky
multi-instrumentalist Bill Monroe in the '40s, the original
bluegrass movement adhered to the songs, structures and conventions
of string bands but made the music faster, harder and more
technically demanding.
</P>
<P>
   The result was bluegrass; the genre named after Monroe's backing
band the Blue Grass Boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The musical form is very simple, and that gives you the
freedom to express your own personality in the playing,'' says
Blackwell. ``You can put your own stamp on the music.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with bloodlines that include such legendary country-rock
outfits as the Byrds and the Burrito Brothers, the Laurel Canyon
Ramblers encompass such current pop artists as Beck. Witcher, the
band's new fiddle player, has played not only with Beck but Willie
Nelson, too.
</P>
<P>
   Witcher replaced Byron Berline, formerly a Parsons and Emmylou
Harris sideman and a member of the Ramblers for the band's first
three months before moving to Oklahoma where he runs his own fiddle
shop and performs locally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bluegrass has a lot of tradition for everyone that plays it,''
Blackwell said. ``The instrumentation doesn't change, but the
songwriting does. These days, there are more folk and country
influences in the music.''
</P>
<P>
   In concert, the Ramblers perform mostly originals, including
such well-known tunes as Pedersen's ``Wait a Minute'' and ``Old
Train,'' songs that have been covered by, respectively, innovative
bluegrass guitarist Tony Rice and the great ``newgrass'' band the
Seldom Scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bluegrass isn't the kind of music where you turn on the radio
and it's there,'' Blackwell explained. ``You have to search it out.
It requires some effort to uncover it. First of all, the level of
musicianship is so high. The hardest kind of guitar playing is
bluegrass flatpicking. It requires a high degree of skill,
dexterity and musicianship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
