<HEADLINE>
GEARING UP FOR BACK-TO-SCHOOL WOES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All summer, our children have stayed up late, slept until noon,
used the heat as an excuse to be couch potatoes planted in front of
the TV all afternoon, and eaten mostly what and when they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   But, smack in the middle of this lazy, hot summer break, it's
suddenly time to start thinking again of back-to-school concerns.
Half the health tips and news releases I've gotten in the past week
seem to have a back-to-school theme. Among the better ones:
</P>
<P>
   TAMING THE WIDE-EYED MONSTER
</P>
<P>
   What's a parent to do with a child whose body clock isn't in
sync with alarm clocks, school bells and homework?
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joel Steinberg, vice president of medical affairs at
Children's Medical Center of Dallas, says we should start preparing
two weeks before the first day of school (it may already be too
late) to get our children back on schedule for fall classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Start two weeks before the first day of school, and wake him
at the school wake-up time and expose him to natural light,''
Steinberg says. Getting a sleepy child up early and outside to play
is much better than forcing a nonsleepy child to go to bed early.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, the child will begin to get sleepy earlier.
</P>
<P>
   PACKING HEALTHFUL LUNCHES
</P>
<P>
   To ensure children receive a nutritionally balanced diet,
parents should remember their ABCs, says Dr. Debby Demory-Luce of
the Children's Nutrition Research CYter X: BaykK$(+VV$K$eYYkV-
</P>
</TEXT>
