<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRST-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FIRST LOVE, LAST RITES': IS A DEAD RAT AN OMEN, OR JUST A DEAD
RODENT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Production notes at end)  
 (JT)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Except for the killing of a large rat, almost nothing happens in
Jesse Peretz's somnolent, richly atmospheric debut film, ``First
Love, Last Rites,'' which is set in the Louisiana bayou country at
the steamy height of summer. That rat, of course, has to carry a
lot of symbolic weight.
</P>
<P>
   In several edge-of-sleep dream sequences, the sounds of the
creature scuffling behind the walls of a bare apartment conjure up
in the characters' minds pictures of rodent claws, blurred with
out-of-focus images of eels and swirling blood. By the time the rat
is beaten to death with a stick it has come to embody the lurking
doubts and fears that threaten to undermine a romantic summer
idyll.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's unlikely lovers are Joey (Giovanni Ribisi), a
sallow, skinny young man from Brooklyn who is inexplicably idling
away the summer in southern Louisiana, and Sissel (Natasha Gregson
Wagner), an attractive local girl whose parents have acrimoniously
separated for reasons that are never specified. Sissel's bratty
little brother, Adrian (Eli Marienthal), is always popping up at
inconvenient moments and throwing tantrums out of sheer boredom.
</P>
<P>
   The film follows the course of a relationship that is the first
sexual affair for both partners, and it is adept at capturing the
rhythms and peevish undercurrents of a first-time sexual
relationship between lovers who are barely out of high school and
have nothing better to do than sprawl around and feel their
feelings. Sissel's father, Henry (Robert John Burke), a Vietnam
veteran who wants desperately to reunite with his wife, befriends
Joey and takes him hunting in the knee-deep waters of a swamp.
Henry conceives a get-rich-quick scheme in which he and Joey will
trap eels to be sold for sushi at fancy Japanese restaurants. Joey
dutifully sets about building eel traps out of chicken wire. While
he's building traps, Sissel begins a menial job at a local sugar
factory.
</P>
<P>
   ``First Love, Last Rites'' was adapted from a 1975 story by Ian
McEwan, and it is an example of how the fiction of inference and
indirection resists being turned into a film. Peretz has transposed
the setting from an English industrial fishing town to the bayou
country around New Orleans. Although the geographical shift makes
for a film that is steeped in local color (this world of ruddy
tattooed fishermen and houses on stilts and crushing humidity is so
richly evoked you can almost smell the thick summer air), its main
characters seem distinctly out of place.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gregson Wagner may be convincing as an indolent brooding
young everywoman, but she doesn't seem especially Southern, and
there's barely a hint of Brooklyn in Ribisi's Joey. These two
talented actors and the pesky rodent that symbolically gnaws away
at their bliss really belong in another movie, one not as
site-specific at this one.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   FIRST LOVE, LAST RITES
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jesse Peretz; written by David Ryan, from an
adaptation by Ryan and Peretz of a story by Ian McEwan; director of
photography, Tom Richmond; edited by James Lyons; music by Nathan
Larson and Craig Wedren; production designer, Dan Estabrook;
produced by Scott Macaulay, Robin O'Hara and Herbert Beigel;
released by Strand Releasing. Running time: 93 minutes. This film
is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Natasha Gregson Wagner (Sissel), Giovanni Ribisi (Joey),
Robert John Burke (Henry) and Eli Marienthal (Adrian).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
