A1223 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-BOOKS-TEX     08-06 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTINENTAL CEO TELLS HOW HE PULLED AIRLINE OUT OF SPIRALING NOSE
DIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Continental Airlines Chief Executive Gordon Bethune saw it
four years ago, his company was going nowhere _ very fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a terrible company that did a lousy job of providing
service, paid its work force badly, barely managed to hold onto
disgruntled, unhappy employees long enough for them to drop
wrenches on their feet and file workers
</P>
<P>
   compensation claims, and lost so much money that (we) were
perilously close to our third (and no-doubt final) bankruptcy,'' he
frankly observed.
</P>
<P>
   Bethune's views are supported with even more blunt statistics of
that fateful year when he took over as CEO of the airline. At that
time:
</P>
<P>
   _Continental was dead last in on-time arrivals, measured by the
Transportation Department. The airline was also the worst in
mishandled baggage and received more complaints than any airline _
almost three times the industry average, according to the
department.
</P>
<P>
   _Continental had 10 years of consecutive losses and had gone
into Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection twice. In 1994, it lost $204
million, and its stock was at ``rock bottom,'' Bethune said,
trading at $3.25 a share.
</P>
<P>
   _Continental employees were paid far below industry average.
On-the-job injuries, turnover and sick leave were ``astronomical.''
The company culture was ``dysfunctional.''
</P>
<P>
   A pretty dismal portrait of one of the 10 largest airlines in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   But what a difference a change in management can make. Bethune
took over as CEO in November 1994 _ the 10th chief executive in as
many years. He had some strong ideas about leadership, and he was
ready to lead.
</P>
<P>
   Now move forward to Continental today:
</P>
<P>
   _Since 1995, the airline's on-time performance has been in the
top five nearly every month, often first; lost-baggage claims are
among the top two or three best and customer complaints are below
the industry average.
</P>
<P>
   _Customers have returned, making the airline profitable. In
1995, Continental made $202 million in profit; in 1996, $556
million. The past 11 quarters have each been more profitable than
the one before. The stock has climbed rapidly, splitting 2-for-1,
and now is trading at more than $50.
</P>
<P>
   _And the work force is content. Wages have gone up 25 percent,
sick leave is down 29 percent, turnover is down 45 percent and
workers compensation claims are down 51 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, trade journal Air Transport World called Continental
the 1996 Airline of the Year out of more than 300 worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   So how do you turn around a $6 billion, 200-airplane,
international airline in such a short time?
</P>
<P>
   Bethune discusses that challenge with a refreshingly frank and
insider view in his book ``From Worst to First: Behind the Scenes
of Continental's Remarkable Comeback'' (John Wiley &AMP; Sons, 294
pages, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   He started by sitting at his dinner table with Greg Brenneman, a
consultant who later became Continental's president and chief
operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   There Bethune and Brenneman created the Go Forward Plan, a broad
strategy with two lofty goals: to improve the product and to change
the culture. The plan targeted four areas: markets, financial,
product and people.
</P>
<P>
   The first hurdle was grabbing the CEO spot and selling the plan
to Continental's board of directors, a passage vividly described by
Bethune. (When originally voted down as CEO, Bethune writes: ``I
consider it a great testimonial to skull design that my head did
not at that moment explode.'')
</P>
<P>
   But the board came around, and then Bethune faced customers,
management and employees with a myriad of practical, but profound,
changes at the airline.
</P>
<P>
   Major changes such as canceling unprofitable routes, changing
pricing structure, refinancing debts and renegotiating leases had
profound effects, which seems obvious.
</P>
<P>
   But so did casual dress day every Friday, monthly open house at
the executive suites for all employees, burning the old conduct
manual, and issuing a $65 bonus in every month that the airline's
Transportation Department performance rating improved.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Bethune tells us that effective CEOs are not
dictators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your real job as boss _ my real job as chief executive _ is to
let people do their jobs. It's to assemble the right team, set the
big-picture direction, communicate that, and then `get out of the
way,''' he writes. ``A boss's job _ a leader's job _ is to
facilitate, not to control. You have to trust people to do their
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's how you turn around a company.
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
