   HISPANIC-POPULATION (Washington) _ The Census Bureau reports
that the number of Hispanics living in the United States grew to
nearly 30 million, or about 11 percent of the population, in 1997.
The bureau projects that by 2050, a quarter of the country, about
90 million people, will be of Hispanic origin. By MARK HELM. (Story
is for release at 12:01 a.m. Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-FAA (Washington) _ A Federal Aviation Administration
official tells Congress that top FAA officials will fly
coast-to-coast on Jan. 1, 2000, to show that nation's air traffic
control system isn't compromised by the Year 2000 computer problem.
By NICOLE TSONG.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-FINANCE (Washington) _ As the House of Representatives
hurries to adjourn, it defeats one campaign finance bill, leaving
another measure passed earlier this week as the overhaul measure
that will be sent to the Senate. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-RUNNERS (Laredo, Texas) _ Federal agents have charged 24
people with running a sophisticated drug-smuggling and
money-laundering operation that reached from the Rio Grande to
Chicago and Ohio. Investigators say the ringleader is 21-year-old
man who is accused of murder. By DANE SCHILLER.
</P>
<P>
   DPS-AUDIT (Austin, Texas) _ Millions of public safety and
criminal activity records are at risk because the Texas Department
of Public Safety has been slow to address potential year 2000
computer glitches, the state auditor warns. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Life is not fair, as John F. Kennedy
once said. Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr and the Supreme Court
have been making it clear that a president is not above the law.
But Congress, which may ultimately sit in judgment of the
president, is itself above the law in several ways. By MARIANNE
MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-COWBOYS (Wichita Falls, Texas) _ The offensive line was one
of the biggest problem areas for the Dallas Cowboys in their slide
to a 6-10 record last season. And former All-Pro Nate Newton was
one of the biggest offenders _ in more ways than one. Newton has
dropped more than 70 pounds and vows he will be back better _ if
not bigger _ than ever. By JODY GOLDSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-WELCOME (Houston) _ Houston is planning a big-time welcome
for Randy Johnson when the Astros' new pitcher makes his debut
Friday night in the Astrodome. The Astros are expecting to draw the
largest crowd in regular-season history for Johnson's debut against
the Philadelphia Phillies. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-WAGNER (Houston) _ Lost amid the hoopla over Randy Johnson's
Houston debut is the return of Astros bullpen ace Billy Wagner, who
has been for more than three weeks since being hit in the head by a
line drive in Arizona. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   BKO-WORLDS (Athens) _ Advance on the quarterfinal round of the
World Basketball Championships, where the U.S. team will face Italy
on Friday. By EDDIE SEFKO.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1559EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
