<SLUG> BC-MYANMAR-ANDAMANSEA-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL ABOARD FOR ADVENTURE IN SOUTHEAST ASIA'S MERGUI ARCHIPELAGO
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by ANDAMAN SEA-HOW TO) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JUNE NAYLOR RODRIGUEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE ANDAMAN SEA _ The journey promised adventure, but we didn't
know the half of it.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of sailing through waters off the coast of Myanmar _
formerly known as Burma, and shut off from the outside world for
the past half-century _ seduced nine intrepid travelers who had
previously done plenty of exploring in exotic places. Here was a
chance to investigate a tiny part of the world inhabited only by
sea gypsies and by wild monkeys and other assorted beasts, a
section of Southeast Asia that was last effectively documented when
European traders came from India to explore the famous Silk Road.
</P>
<P>
   So, in October, when we boarded the trimaran appropriately named
the Wanderlust, we were among the first 100 Westerners to take such
a voyage since Burmese officials opened their part of the Andaman
Sea _ in the easternmost Indian Ocean _ to outsiders late in 1996.
Our specific destination was the Mergui Archipelago, a group of
some 800 islands covering 10,000 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling to an area rampant with political and profound
financial troubles was less daunting because our sailing outfitter
had been running this particular trip for nearly a year. What
little we could find ahead of time on the Internet looked pretty
good.
</P>
<P>
   We learned that our captain was Adam Frost, an Englishman who
owns and runs the sailing company from Phuket, Thailand, along with
his mother and brother. They have operated scuba diving trips in
Thai and Indonesian waters for five years, and they seemed certain
we wouldn't be accosted by Burmese pirates.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching the Wanderlust from our American homes took nearly 40
hours of travel. But we immediately experienced the first of many
thrills to come as we listened to Burmese monks chanting in odd
cadence from the mountaintop temple above the port, where a giant
reclining Buddha watched over us. We squeezed around the tiny table
in the sailboat's salon, dining on an exquisite feast magically
prepared in a pint-sized galley by our 18-year-old Thai chef.
</P>
<P>
   It rapidly became clear that the Wanderlust is not for people
who demand comfort: The bunks were scarcely larger than a dresser
drawer, and heat and humidity were phenomenal, even though October
is the ``coolest'' month in this part of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the nine of us shared good humor along with a
thirst for adventure. This came in handy when it was time to visit
the one head, which was the size of an airplane's bathroom and had
a shower operated by pumping a foot lever. The whole showering
thing, in fact, was highly entertaining; when washing away the
shampoo, we had to stick our heads under the nozzle and work the
lever behind us _ kicking much like a donkey would.
</P>
<P>
   Such inconveniences vanished from memory the moment we awoke the
first morning in a dreamlike spot called Crescent Bay. From the
deck we gazed across bottle-green water at odd little birds called
island thick-knees skittering around on a cream-colored beach.
Beyond the sand rose dense rain-forest jungle, clinging thickly to
giant granite hills.
</P>
<P>
   Every morning and afternoon were consumed by snorkeling forays.
Most of us had already snorkeled from the Caribbean to Australia,
and still we thought the Andaman Sea was more impressive. Because
no divers have been there to disturb nature, its reefs teemed with
Technicolored coral and fish.
</P>
<P>
   Each underwater journey offered views of exotic fish:
tiger-striped wrasses, big parrotfish colored bright green, cobalt,
pink and purple, gorgeous angelfish and Moorish idols, which had
fantastically long ribbons of dorsal fins. Some of these, said the
experienced diver in our group, were rare sights even to her.
</P>
<P>
   And there were extraordinary coral palettes in which the fish
live. The best we saw were just off Fire Beach and Cavern Island,
where the reefs were crowned not only by elkhorn and brain coral
but fat purple sea anemones and bushes of bright green coral.
</P>
<P>
   The two scuba divers on our boat went exploring twice a day,
finding several black-tipped reef sharks, huge moray eels, lobster
and wahoo. One morning as we anchored off Kyun Pila, an island in
the Great Swintons, we saw dozens of squid just off the bow of the
Wanderlust. And the afternoon we were anchored off Clara Island at
a spot we named GNT Beach (for Adam's favorite drink, gin and
tonic), one of our snorkelers found a lovely rare blue starfish
among the rocks near shore.
</P>
<P>
   Because there would be stretches of time when there was no wind,
leaving us feeling as though we were boiling inside our skin, we'd
just stay in the water for hours at a time. Sometimes we'd just
float around the Wanderlust in the late afternoon and watch
hornbills, sea eagles and Brimmany kites sailing the skies and
diving for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
