<HEADER>
A1260 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SQUIRRELNUT-BAND-AZR &LR;      08-06 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SQUIRRELNUT-BAND-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SQUIRREL NUT ZIPPERS SWING TO THEIR OWN BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KATHY CANO-MURILLO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - One evening as musician Jim Mathus relaxed at home, he
decided to teach his wife a cute vintage song on the banjo. It was
at that moment that he noticed something very peculiar about his
soulmate.
</P>
<P>
   She had one of the strangest singing voices he had ever heard.
</P>
<P>
   Other husbands may have firmly, but lovingly, asked her to
refrain from such refrains. Mathus, however, chose to build a band
around her sleepy song stylings.
</P>
<P>
   He named the group after a vintage candy bar, and the seeds of
the Squirrel Nut Zippers were planted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quite odd how it all happened,'' says Katherine Whalen,
the now-seasoned vocalist of the Cotton Club-inspired band.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never sang a note in front of anyone,'' she says from
the couple's North Carolina home. ``I knew I had a funny-sounding
voice, so I always held it in and ended up as a groupie, never once
even considering myself as a singer. So when Jim told me his plans
for this new band featuring me as the singer _ I was absolutely
terrified!''
</P>
<P>
   Whalen chats candidly with a charming Southern drawl as she
recounts the nerve-racking yet fun days of the band's infancy. For
starters, the couple quit their serving jobs at a local restaurant
so they could take the show on the road.
</P>
<P>
   They were already living in the past, favoring ragtime sounds,
classic artwork and even a refurbished home. Translating that love
of retro into songs came naturally.
</P>
<P>
   Mathus spent hours writing and practicing pseudo-swing tunes as
Whalen diligently worked on her stamina for public crooning. The
band has come a long way since its first gig four years ago,
appearing at a North Carolina bistro.
</P>
<P>
   In those four years, the concept has taken off faster than a
flapper's fancy footwork. The band's flair with trombones, violins,
pedal steel guitars and slap-happy rhythms was new to the ears of
flannel-wearing grunge heads and mainstream radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Zippers, their efforts have coincided with a
tidal wave of old-fangled acts such as Cherry Poppin' Daddies, the
Brian Setzer Orchestra and Royal Crown Revue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been really lucky,'' Whalen says. ``People really like
it or they just don't vocalize their dislikes. It's fun to see
their faces open up and blossom when we begin to play onstage.
Especially when they are expecting some rock band, then we come
bursting out with our ukuleles.''
</P>
<P>
   The talent and charm of the Squirrel Nut Zippers have garnered
them a long-term contract with Mammoth Records. They also have
enjoyed a platinum album (1996's ``Hot``), countless tours, stints
on national television, plenty of radio airplay, multiple songs on
movie and television soundtracks and _ most importantly _ a
juke-joint reputation for being the '90s band to resurrect the
Charleston dance.
</P>
<P>
   But despite ever-growing attention, members have managed to stay
comfortably humble.
</P>
<P>
   Whalen contends that it's not superstar fame that motivates the
band, but love of music. One of Whalen's goals is to remain
successful enough to retire the crew with no financial worries.
Thanks to a barrage of positive reviews for the band's lastest
effort, ``Perennial Favorites,'' that goal shouldn't be difficult
to attain.
</P>
<P>
   Whalen confesses she sometimes thinks about becoming a parent as
well as about those bygone waitressing days. But she is quickly
reminded of the fortunes this project has brought.
</P>
<P>
   She thinks her musical adventure could be a song in itself, and
she has the perfect way to listen to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love for people to hear our music on AM radio _
driving in an old convertible down a dirt road, right by a lake and
under full moonlight,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what the Squirrel Nut Zippers are all about.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kathy Cano-Murillo can be reached at kathy.murillo(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1602EDT &QL; 
