<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1264 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MYANMAR-ANDAMANSEA-2n     08-06 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MYANMAR-ANDAMANSEA-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
THE ANDAMAN SEA: diving for dinner. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sole exciting brush with wildlife came at daybreak on the
third morning. Anchored about 200 yards from the shore in a
gorgeous, covelike channel called Salet Galet, we watched as a
large family of monkeys wandered out of the jungle to the beach. We
could hear parental screeching and baby monkeys crying for food in
the woods, while some adults explored. A couple of them bathed at
the water's edge and dug around for clams. We were mesmerized.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'' were the curiosity when we ventured onto Palau Nala, the
island occupied by a sea gypsy village. Some 300 or so of the
Moken, or sea gypsies, live there in shacks built on stilts. Every
few years, they'll move from one island to another, but they seem
fairly rooted at present. The Burmese government provides them with
diesel fuel and rice, and the fishermen make a living selling
nasty-looking dried sea cucumbers (also called sea worms) to the
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Because Adam has forged a friendship with the Burmese monk in
residence, we were welcome to visit for about an hour, walking
through the village, observing a group of women busy with some kind
of gambling on a blanket in the stifling heat. We listened to Adam
have a brief conversation with the monk about, we presumed, food
and health. We didn't speak Thai or Burmese, so they might have
been discussing the Florida Marlins' chances at winning the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   We later asked Adam if visits to the sea gypsy village are
conscionable _ or are we making a human zoo of the Moken? He
disputed that any exploitation is involved. On his weekly visits,
Adam brings medicine, rice and other goods that the monk has
requested, and nothing is taken from the residents or their island.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the outside world has touched the Moken in other ways.
Some of the exquisitely beautiful children were dressed in such
Western garb as Bugs Bunny T-shirts, and then there's the enormous
satellite dish, rising from behind the monk's home over the cove.
They have their MTV.
</P>
<P>
   FREE AS A WELL-FED BIRD: There was almost no structure to the
entire trip _ other than meals, of course. One sunset as we sipped
white wine, one woman in our group said she couldn't recall another
time when she had felt so free. She observed that with no schedule
to keep, our days simply revolved around three meals.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, we woke up, ate, put on sunblock, snorkeled, ate, read,
snorkeled again, wrote letters, took notes, ate, quizzed Adam about
the islands and slept. Day in, day out.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfasts were usually tidy, individual omelets made with ham,
cheese and tomatoes, or poached eggs and bacon, or fried eggs with
tomatoes and cheese, and toast. Lunch one day consisted of
delicious hamburgers and french fries, while fabulous fried chicken
and mashed potatoes were another noon meal. At every lunch our chef
_ who goes by the nickname ``Boy'' because his proper name is the
less manageable Boontun Nimala _ would include a huge, leafy salad.
</P>
<P>
   Each evening meal _ which in proper Thai home-style tradition is
a soup and three separate dishes of beef, pork and fish _ consisted
of courses like beef with lobster sauce and oyster mushrooms, green
curry with chicken, and prawns with pineapple or beef with red
curry and pumpkin or turnips, or sweet and sour fish soup. Rich or
robust flavors were provided by Boy's masterful ways with fresh
ginger, galangal, cilantro, basil, mint, curries, coconut milk,
lime and lemongrass. And in typical Thai style, Boy decorated every
dish with intricately carved chiles, carrots, tomatoes and
cucumbers, which he fashioned into floral wonders.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Boy was sparing with chiles, but gradually he jacked
up the heat. The two chiles he most often used were the long green
and red ones called ``prik chiba,'' and the smaller, thin ones _
that are often alarmingly mistaken by Westerners for green beans _
called ``prik kee ngoe.''
</P>
<P>
   By the second evening, we found ourselves sweating profusely
through our magnificent dinner _ from the intense heat in both the
salon and the chiles. Our good manners disappeared; we would wolf
down the divine food and mumble over the flavors before scrambling
to the deck the moment we finished the final bite.
</P>
<P>
   It's over so soon
</P>
<P>
   By the fourth day we were relaxed to the point of asking Adam if
it was Wednesday or Thursday. There were no cell phones, no faxes,
no television. The two electronic devices we noticed were the CD
player, on which Adam sometimes played Sheryl Crow or Ella
Fitzgerald, and Adam's laptop, which he used in the evenings to
update his log.
</P>
<P>
   We were stunned to find ourselves back in the Burmese port of
Kawthong on the sixth morning. Although we relished the idea of
real showers and beds, our adventure seemed much too short. We'd
gotten used to the heat, and the donkey-kick shampoo affair had
even become fun. We really had no idea what adventurers we could
be.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
