<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOBCAT-COMEDIAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILD MAN BOBCAT ON A TV ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MONTY PHAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - When Dad's the host of a game show that has the words
``Big Ass'' in its name, expect to get away with more stuff than
most kids.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the predicament of Bobcat Goldthwait's 16-year-old
stepson, fresh off a weekend of partying while Game Show Host Dad
was away doing his other job, Stand-Up Comedian Dad.
</P>
<P>
   ``He apparently had some sort of hootenanny at my house when I
was out of town,'' says Goldthwait, who also has a daughter. ``I'm
just finding the wreckage of that. It's going to be very hard for
me to keep a straight face and be upset over that. `How'd you have
a party and didn't invite your dad or his friends?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Like father, like stepson.
</P>
<P>
   Although Goldthwait, 36, has done stand-up for more than half of
his life, only recently has he worked his other job, that of host
of ``Bobcat's Big Ass Show,'' which runs weeknights on the FX cable
channel. Contestants reveal embarrassing secrets and talents,
apparently of their own volition. Whether the modifier ``Big Ass''
refers to the show or to its contestants is still unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Goldthwait is a stranger to outrageous behavior.
Remember, this is the same guy who, in 1994, smashed up the set on
``The Arsenio Hall Show'' and set a couch ablaze on ``The Tonight
Show With Jay Leno.''
</P>
<P>
   Try explaining that to your children. ``Kids, Daddy had too many
Twinkies that night. Actually, both nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Goldthwait is a stranger to explaining his outrageous
behavior, either. After the first few televised acts of
destruction, the admonition ``Do as I say, not as I do'' becomes
somewhat implicit.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far I haven't had to give that speech,'' he says. ``Once I
did, and (my stepson) asked me, `Are you really going to tell me
with a straight face not to act up in class?' I'm like going,
`Yeah, you're right. But you better work it out with this lady
because I don't want to come over here anymore.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The game show marks a resurgence of sorts for Goldthwait, who
landed roles in various comedies in the '80s, including ``Police
Academy 2,'' ``3'' and ``4'' and ``Scrooged.'' In 1991, he took his
first stab at writing and directing with ``Shakes the Clown,''
which achieved cult status but little more.
</P>
<P>
   He hit a bit of a lull thereafter but recently has taken up
various projects, such as the voice for Mr. Floppy, a stuffed bunny
that comes to life in the WB show ``Unhappily Ever After.'' He also
was the voice of Pain in the animated Disney film ``Hercules'' and
is working on writing and directing another film, ``Teen Jesus,''
described by Goldthwait as ``Jerusalem, 90210.''
</P>
<P>
   All that is in addition to taping five episodes of the game show
each Wednesday and Thursday and spending weekends doing stand-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always doing so many different things that it's kind of
hard to get bored,'' he says. And if boredom ever does set in, he
could always party with his stepson. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
