<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARIE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MARIE BAIE DES ANGES': RESTLESS AS TEENS IT POR TRAYS 
</HEADLINE>
 BAIE-MOVIE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - If ``Marie Baie des Anges'' had been made in
Hollywood, it would make no sense at all. Instead, it's a French
film that makes no sense at all. But c'est la vie _ who needs sense
when you're French?
</P>
<P>
   This impressionistic rumination on the sexuality and violence of
French youth will challenge moviegoers who look for coherence in
their stories, but will reward the fewer viewers who value an
interior, psychological approach to cinema.
</P>
<P>
   The film is set among a restless group of teenagers on the
French Riviera, most of them portrayed by non-actors. Because they
spend most of their scenes staring stonily into the camera, their
naturalness is no stonier than professional actors might have
achieved.
</P>
<P>
   The film deals primarily, when it deals with anything at all,
with the unspoken attraction between Marie (Vahina Giocante) and
Orso (Frederic Malgras).
</P>
<P>
   Marie is a teenage girl spending a summer at the seashore
flirting with all the boys, particularly some older American
sailors, who always seem ominous. But then so does everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Most ominous of all is Orso, a wandering teenage thief. He may
also be a killer, but because most of the scenes of what might be
violence are shot through dark shadows, it's difficult to tell.
</P>
<P>
   Marie and Orso glance off each other a number of times, while
each pursues some enigmatic purpose. They eventually adhere, and
their coastal romance is both as pretty as the seashore and as
dangerous as the legend of the angels who live in the bay.
</P>
<P>
   The angels referred to in the movie's title are a mysterious
kind of shark that both protects and kills.
</P>
<P>
   French filmmaker Manuel Pradal, making his first movie, is
consumed with the dichotomy of seduction and violence, which he
doesn't illuminate but glimpses.
</P>
<P>
   Pradal succeeds only as long as he keeps us enmeshed in his
mysterious purposes. I didn't stay caught up for long.
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating the film's difficult allure is the
unfortunate subtitling. Because the movie takes place during a
French summer, many of the characters wear white clothes. Thus,
we're often subjected to subtitles playing in white on white. Add
in all the scenes shot in the dark, and the dark nature of Pradal's
purpose, and we have a movie that's not only difficult to grasp,
it's hard to see.
</P>
<P>
   What comes through, however, is a disturbing portrait of French
youth as hooligans.
</P>
<P>
   Rated R for profanity, violence and nudity, ``Marie Baie des
Anges'' is in French with English subtitles. 2 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
