<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1286 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDAMANSEA-HOWTO-TEX     08-06 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDAMANSEA-HOWTO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO THE ENDS OF THE EARTH
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Accompanies MYANMAR-ANDAMAN SEA) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Getting there, we found out, was step one in the adventure.
After long flights to Bangkok (about 25 hours from Dallas/Fort
Worth Airport), there was an hour's flight to Phuket, an island in
southern Thailand. From the Phuket town of Patong, it's a five-hour
ride in a minivan to Ranong, a Thai town with a smelly port. There
we piled into a long boat with all our luggage and took a 45-minute
trip across the Pakchan River, propelled by a crude motor not
unlike that on a lawn mower.
</P>
<P>
   The long boat took us directly to the Wanderlust, anchored in
the harbor at Kawthong, the port in Myanmar from which we sailed.
Adam Frost, our captain, spent two hours in government offices with
our passports and the $80-U.S.-per-guest entry fee. Before he
returned to the Wanderlust, he'd had to visit with 28 different
``officials,'' to whom he must give whiskey and cigarettes upon
each visit. That's just part of the game, he says. No one seems
certain if or when the Burmese will lighten up or if they'll shut
down again.
</P>
<P>
   Adam owns Southeast Asia Live-Aboards, the company we booked our
trip with, with his brother and mother; they've been sailing off
the coast of Myanmar since January 1997. SEA Live-Aboards was the
first diving/sailing outfit to obtain permission to do business
from the Burmese, a process that took a couple of frustrating years
of negotiations. Their company has already enjoyed five years of
success with similar trips in Thai and Indonesian waters.
</P>
<P>
   The going rate for the sailing adventure cruise we took, which
operates year-round, is $850 from mid-October until mid-May, and
$680 the balance of the year. This includes all meals, lots of
bottled water, Burmese entry fees, and snorkeling and diving gear.
Soft drinks are $1 and beer is $2 extra. You must bring your own
wine and spirits. Prices are not affected by the shaky Thai
economy, the owners say, because the captains and sailboat expenses
have always been paid in U.S. currency.
</P>
<P>
   SEA Live-Aboards also offers diving trips with three daily dives
in the Mergui Archipelago, and in Thai, Indian and Indonesian
waters. For information on SEA Live-Aboards, call 011-66-76-340406,
or visit its Web site at www.sealiveaboards.com.
</P>
<P>
   Other Phuket-based companies now sailing the Mergui are Dive
Phuket (www.divephuket.com), Fantasea Divers Co. Ltd. (e-mail at
info\Nfantasea.net), and Faraway Sail &AMP; Dive Expeditions Co. Ltd.
(e-mail info\Nfar-away.net).
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Things to take on the Wanderlust:
</P>
<P>
   Insect repellent, and lots of it
</P>
<P>
   Sunblock, ditto
</P>
<P>
   Paperback books
</P>
<P>
   Battery-operated reading light
</P>
<P>
   Loose, lightweight clothing
</P>
<P>
   Diet Coke, wine and hard liquor
</P>
<P>
   Washcloths
</P>
<P>
   Wet Ones or other moist wipes
</P>
<P>
   Beach towel
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of film
</P>
<P>
   Waterproof camera case
</P>
<P>
   Sturdy, waterproof footwear
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
