<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1303 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WELFARE-FRAUD07-COX     08-06 0346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELFARE-FRAUD07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'BOUNTY' REDUCES WELFARE PAYMENTS TO PRISONERS
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A ``bounty program'' that pays sheriffs' offices
and prisons for alerting the federal government when prisoners are
improperly receiving Supplemental Security Income payments has
stopped checks to 17,280 inmates over the past 15 months, the
government reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The law has always denied SSI benefits to people held for more
than a month in a public institution such as a prison or mental
hospital, but until 1996 it relied on individuals to notify the
government that they were not entitled to benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 welfare reform law included the bounties for agencies
notifying the government _ by providing lists of prisoners which
can be checked against Social Security records _ of inmates who may
be ineligible for benefits. The bounty is paid to the institution,
not to individual law enforcement officers.
</P>
<P>
   The new program is expected to save $3.5 billion over seven
years, according to David Williams, the Social Security
Administration's inspector general.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great news for taxpayers and horrible news for
convicts who were illegally getting welfare and Social Security
checks in jail,'' said Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., a Florida Republican
who spearheaded the reform bill. ``This shows that creative and
common-sense solutions like our bounty system can stop fraud cold.
If you're doing time, you don't get a dime.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Wally Herger, R-Calif., a co-author of the bounty
provision, noted that pending bills supported by the Clinton
administration would expand the notification system to cut off
benefits for other programs, such as food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   Supplemental Security Income is paid to about 6.6 million poor
Americans, most of them blind, aged or disabled. In most cases,
inmates may qualify for SSI payments if they are poor and mentally
or physically disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
