<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1306 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRESIDENTS-LOVE-EXHIB     08-06 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESIDENTS-LOVE-EXHIBIT-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL POWERS OF LOVE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Deanne Stillman is the author of a play called ``Inside in the
White House''  
 By DEANNE STILLMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   YORBA LINDA, Calif. _ The item in the newspaper appeared in a
listing for museum shows. ``Come see Hillary Rodham Clinton's
wedding gown,'' the tiny print said. ``We're just an hour from Los
Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   This was an announcement from the Richard Nixon Library and
Birthplace here in Yorba Linda. I called to double-check. Was it a
prank perpetrated by one of the old Watergate plumbers? The
recording explained everything: the establishment was presenting
the exhibition ``My Dearest Partner,'' all about husbands and wives
in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of love and romance at the Nixon museum sounded
almost surreal: could passion exist, even in souvenir form, at an
archive devoted to a man whose passions were remote and covert?
Passion in the White House _ between spouses?
</P>
<P>
   You never know. I had been meaning to visit the museum, if only
to see the Nixon bird feeder, which I had heard was available in
the gift shop. But now that (italics)other(end italics) dress _ of
the blue cocktail variety _ was in the news. Nevermind the odd
Nixoniana, I decided, now was the time: I must see Mrs. Clinton's
gown.
</P>
<P>
   What had the First Lady got married in? I wondered as I drove
past an endless chain of strip malls featuring Chuck E. Cheese. Was
it very feminine? Did it have a long train? Silk or satin? I could
not conjure an image.
</P>
<P>
   The moment I arrived, I made a beeline for the area dedicated to
the Clintons. There was the gown, walled up behind plexiglass, a
peculiar artifact that Mrs. Clinton evidently deemed suitable for
framing.
</P>
<P>
   A simple affair, it was a long-sleeved, full-length, cotton
hippie wedding dress (circa 1975) gathered at the bust, with a
scooped neck. I guess it could be referred to as Shaker style. An
annotation next to the dress explained its provenance: ``found by
Hillary Rodham's parents in a local Fayetteville department
store.''
</P>
<P>
   Deep down inside, Mrs. Clinton is a flower child, I thought, and
a low-maintenance one at that. Perhaps the woman who seems to be
ruffled by nothing wilted a long time ago, covering it all up with
a steely smile. I thought I heard Nixon's ghost talking to the
First Lady: ``You could have been top banana, but you stood by your
man. I forgive you for your part in the Watergate hearings, but if
there's one thing I support it's family values.''
</P>
<P>
   But then a more recent photograph near the dress told another
story. Taken at the Arkansas governor's mansion in 1992 by Harry
Benson, it is the highlight of the show, so surprisingly sweet and
intimate that the Clintons would be well-advised to circulate it
immediately. Bill is lying in a hammock, gazing dreamily at his
wife. Hillary is bending down close, looking happy and seductive
and beautiful; the moment appears to be the prelude to a kiss. They
are in love, and it seems like a million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And then came more surprises. There were relics from the love
affair between Harry and Bess Truman, including ``trench art,'' or
engraved artillery casings, which Harry sent to Bess from the front
at Verdun in World War I, as well as a love letter he wrote after
he was elected president. ``Dear Bess,'' he penned on White House
stationery, ``Twenty-nine years! It seems like 29 days ... What an
old fool I am.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a note from Lyndon Johnson regarding Lady Bird,
written to a friend: ``I love that woman and she wants that Highway
Beautification Act ... By God, were going to get it for her.''
</P>
<P>
   At the display for the Bush presidency, I was struck by evidence
of girlishness in the First Lady, and how much in love the Bushes
were long ago. On display was a pair of Keds, mismatched _ the
right one was pink; the left, floral _ given to Barbara by the
president. I wondered if I would have thought differently of the
Bushes if I had known that George named his World War II fighter
plane after his betrothed.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``why would anyone save this?'' category were kernels of
rice thrown at Dwight and Mamie Eisenhower at their wedding, as
well as a powder puff that said ``Mamie,'' and a tube of Mamie's
trademark ``Parisian Red'' lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   I liked this diorama, rice and all. Whether or not Ike liked
someone else, as has long been chatted about, became irrelevant;
Mamie tried to look good. With Parisian Red, there was always hope.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Richard and Pat Nixon were well represented, with
lots of love mementoes available for viewing. On May Day 1940, the
young law student Richard had a diamond engagement ring _ on
display here _ delivered in a flower-filled May basket to the
classroom of his intended. So here was another oddly heartening
moment in this show _ Nixon sweaty, but hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   The sexiest item in this exhibit is a dark-blue silk bodice
given to Rachel Jackson by her husband, Andrew, shortly before he
became president. With black overlace, scalloped edges, and black
ribbon trim, it suggests that here was a man who was looking
forward to long nights of frolic in the White House. Alas, this was
not to be: Rachel died of a heart attack three weeks before the
inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   I looked for mention of extramarital affairs in the exhibit _
after all, we hear about more of those than of conjugal bliss in
the White House; happiness has now become the secret rather than
the facade _ but there was not one reference, not even to Marilyn.
</P>
<P>
   But I did find a hint of darkness; it was lurking in the life of
John F. Kennedy, conveyed in a poem written to him by Jacqueline
Kennedy, very prophetic as it turned out, shortly after their 1953
honeymoon in Mexico. It read in part: ``He would find love/He would
never find peace/For he must go seeking/The Golden Fleece.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no bird feeder for sale in the gift shop, but as I hit
the freeway, I was glad I had spent the afternoon in Yorba Linda,
which bills itself as the All-American Town. While President Nixon
was forever giving his Checkers speech down the hallway in another
part of the museum, ``My Dearest Partner'' proved that there has
been plenty of romance between presidents and their wives. To quote
Peaches and Herb, the First Couple of soul, ``Love is strange.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
