<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNAKE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SNAKE EYES': IN ATLANTIC CITY, LUCK IS CERTAINLY NO LADY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brian De Palma's hot new thriller ``Snake Eyes'' is a great big
juicy gob of apocalyptic paranoia set in a garish Atlantic City
hotel and casino called the Millennium on the night a tropical
storm named Jezebel is bearing down on the New Jersey coast. The
storm, which is later upgraded into a hurricane, has swished in
just in time to jack up the excitement surrounding a heavyweight
championship boxing match.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's vertiginous opening sequence follows the mad dash of
the event's maniacal security chief, a local police detective, Rick
Santoro (Nicolas Cage), through the arena minutes before the
opening bell. Leaping down stairs, dancing through corridors,
barking salutations to one and all as though he were the world's
official greeter, this shark-grinning, bullying speed demon fields
calls from his girlfriend and his wife on his cell phone and places
a last-minute bet with his bookie.
</P>
<P>
   It is the night of nights for Rick, a petty king of sleaze who
dreams of one day becoming Atlantic City's mayor, and Cage squeezes
every last rancid drop of self-congratulatory ferocity out of his
character's glad-handing rampage. This pre-bout strut ends at
ringside where Rick joins forces with his best friend, Comdr. Kevin
Dunne (Gary Sinise), the ice-cool naval officer in charge of
security for the visiting secretary of defense (Joel Fabiani).
</P>
<P>
   As the fight begins, the camera, ignoring the boxers, anxiously
pans the flushed faces at ringside and notices two conspicuously
out-of-place patrons. One, wearing a cheap blond wig, awkwardly
plunks herself down beside the secretary of defense. A few seats
away sits a buxom, frizzy-haired red-haired woman who appears to be
without an escort. The fight has barely begun before the knockout
punch arrives out of the blue, and the ensuing pandemonium muffles
the sound of gunshots.
</P>
<P>
   But when the secretary of defense falls, mortally wounded, and
the woman in the blond wig flees, her arm grazed, her white dress
spattered with blood, panic sweeps through the arena, and 14,000
terrified patrons stampede toward the exits.
</P>
<P>
   So begins the director's most flamboyant fantasy of high-flying
conspiracy and corruption since ``Blow Out.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else in ``Snake Eyes'' matches the opening sequence
in adrenaline-pumping excitement, the movie never quite fizzles. It
just gets sillier and more exaggerated in the self-parodying ways
that De Palma's movies often do.
</P>
<P>
   As the preposterous plot of this cartoonish pop fable unwinds,
the championship bout turns out to have been rigged. It's all part
of a broader conspiracy involving an air defense system, a
cover-up, a whistle-blower and the schemes of a megalomaniacal
developer and industrialist (John Heard) who bears a distant
resemblance to Howard Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   As the story rolls along, you can't help notice the flashy
accessories that are thrown in just for fun, like that buxom,
frizzy-haired redhead. De Palma has always preferred playing
ingenious technological games to developing characters and making
narrative sense, and ``Snake Eyes,'' which he conceived with the
screenwriter David Koepp, takes some entertainingly gimmicky
tangents.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, which rarely ventures outside the hotel and resort
complex, replays the assassination from various perspectives,
including that of the prizefighters (in a boxing scene that looks
and sounds transparently fake). In another clever sequence, the
hotel's surveillance system becomes a critical tool in locating the
elusive room where a character is hiding from an assassin. During
this scene, the voyeuristic camera gratuitously becomes an overhead
Peeping Tom observing the goings-on in several adjacent hotel
suites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snake Eyes'' has deeper issues on its mind than cheap thrills,
conspiracy theories and the titillating joys of surveillance. In
its more dramatic scenes it becomes a hyperventilating inquiry into
the limits of friendship and loyalty and what constitutes
character.
</P>
<P>
   When Rick discovers to his astonishment and sorrow that Kevin is
a very different creature from the person he thought he knew, he
makes a screeching moral U-turn and suddenly becomes the
incorruptible guardian of truth, justice and the high road. Having
invited us to despise Rick, the movie asks us to take a deep breath
and swallow the notion that beneath his tarnish, he is really a
true-blue kind of guy with a rock-solid conscience that neither a
vicious beating nor a million-dollar bribe could begin to sway.
</P>
<P>
   From this turning point, Cage is so intent on winning back our
sympathy that his performance seems schizophrenic. As though
touched by a magic wand, this fire-breathing cell-phone-wielding
wheeler-dealer is suddenly an earnest, masochistic goody-goody
clawing his way through the pits of hell (now that Las Vegas has
turned into a family theme park resort, America's metaphorical hell
seems to have moved back East to Atlantic City) to uphold his
principles. Oh, please!
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   SNAKE EYES
</P>
<P>
   Produced and directed by Brian De Palma; written by David Koepp,
based on a story by De Palma and Koepp; director of photography,
Stephen H. Burum; edited by Bill Pankow; music by Ryuichi Sakamoto;
production designer, Anne Pritchard; released by Paramount
Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 99 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Snake Eyes'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It has strong language and
scenes of violence.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Nicolas Cage (Rick Santoro), Gary Sinise (Kevin Dunne),
John Heard (Gilbert Powell), Carla Gugino (Julia Costello), Stan
Shaw (Lincoln Tyler), Kevin Dunn (Lou Logan) Michael Rispoli (Jimmy
George), and Joel Fabiani (Charles Kirkland).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
