<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-POIROT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEARING UP FOR BACK-TO-SCHOOL WOES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All summer, our children have stayed up late, slept until noon,
used the heat as an excuse to be couch potatoes planted in front of
the TV all afternoon, and eaten mostly what and when they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   But, smack in the middle of this lazy, hot summer break, it's
suddenly time to start thinking again of back-to-school concerns.
Half the health tips and news releases I've gotten in the past week
seem to have a back-to-school theme. Among the better ones:
</P>
<P>
   TAMING THE WIDE-EYED MONSTER
</P>
<P>
   What's a parent to do with a child whose body clock isn't in
sync with alarm clocks, school bells and homework?
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joel Steinberg, vice president of medical affairs at
Children's Medical Center of Dallas, says we should start preparing
two weeks before the first day of school (it may already be too
late) to get our children back on schedule for fall classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Start two weeks before the first day of school, and wake him
at the school wake-up time and expose him to natural light,''
Steinberg says. Getting a sleepy child up early and outside to play
is much better than forcing a nonsleepy child to go to bed early.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, the child will begin to get sleepy earlier.
</P>
<P>
   PACKING HEALTHFUL LUNCHES
</P>
<P>
   To ensure children receive a nutritionally balanced diet,
parents should remember their ABCs, says Dr. Debby Demory-Luce of
the Children's Nutrition Research Center at Baylor College of
Medicine in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good guideline for packing nutrition into your child's
school lunch is to have a source of vitamin A, a source of the B
vitamins and a good source of both vitamin C and calcium because
many foods rich in these nutrients are also good sources of vitamin
D, iron, protein and carbohydrates,'' Demory-Luce says.
</P>
<P>
   For vitamin A, provide a half-cup serving of a deep yellow or
orange fruit or vegetable such as baby carrots (packed with a
favorite yogurt dip), cubed cantaloupe or dried apricots.
</P>
<P>
   B vitamins are found in whole grains, meat, nuts and seeds.
Meat, cheese or peanut butter sandwiches on whole- grain or
enriched breads, low-fat cheese with whole-wheat crackers, pasta
salad with cheese and kidney beans and treats like graham crackers,
oatmeal cookies studded with raisins and sunflower seeds are good
choices.
</P>
<P>
   Vitamin C and calcium are both found in calcium-fortified orange
juice. Or pack a half-cup of fresh strawberries, cubed pineapple,
citrus fruit or juice for vitamin C and a cup of low-fat milk,
yogurt or pudding for calcium.
</P>
<P>
   PROTECTING AGAINST DISEASE
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, the FDA approved CERTIVA, a new DPT vaccine with
the pertussis component modified to reduce the fever, redness,
pain, irritability and swelling sometimes associated with the
vaccine that protects children against whooping cough.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Fernando Guerra, public health director for the San Antonio
area, has been field-testing the vaccine for five years and says he
has seen better protection, fewer mild reactions and no seizures.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1618EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
