<SLUG> BC-SNAKE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPENSE THRILLER `SNAKE EYES' A SURE BET 
</HEADLINE>
 EYES-MOVIE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Roll snake eyes and you've got nothing. House wins.
</P>
<P>
   That's the rule in gambling, but also in the games of big
business, crime and espionage, all of which rattle through the
first-rate thriller ``Snake Eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   While Nicolas Cage is the on-screen star, ``Snake Eyes'' is
turned electric by the cinematic pyrotechnics of director Brian De
Palma, who takes the same zap with which he enlivened ``Mission:
Impossible'' and applies it to a more-intelligent suspense story.
</P>
<P>
   That story begins in a rush on the night of a heavyweight
championship fight in an Atlantic City casino, when one of the
ringside celebrities is assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   Eyewitness to the crime is Rick Santoro (Cage), a corrupt
Atlantic City cop who's also a savvy homicide detective.
</P>
<P>
   Santoro jumps into the investigation to help out his best
friend, Kevin Dunne (Gary Sinise), a Navy commander in charge of
security for a high-ranking government official, who may become the
fall guy for the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Santoro and Dunne race to unravel a conspiratorial web before
they become the next victims of a plot that's bigger than both of
them.
</P>
<P>
   As they search for a mysterious woman (Julia Costello) who holds
the key to the assassination, she's on the run for her life while
trapped inside the casino.
</P>
<P>
   Working with a smart, cynical script from David Koepp, director
De Palma twists this one, tense night of people trapped in
buildings and conspiracies into a zip of a thriller.
</P>
<P>
   Koepp and De Palma have worked together before, on ``Mission:
Impossible'' and ``Carlito's Way.'' They clearly think along the
same devious lines, giving us plenty to ponder while we enjoy the
whirlwind action.
</P>
<P>
   As a visual virtuoso, De Palma is at the top of his cinematic
game with ``Snake Eyes,'' avoiding the wretched excesses that blew
up ``Carlito's Way'' and ``Raising Cain.''
</P>
<P>
   De Palma needs all his camera tricks because the story at heart
could have, in the hands of a lesser director, been ordinary. But
he shares with us the wizardry of a sly craftsman who's having as
much fun playing games as we are being played.
</P>
<P>
   He opens the movie at the championship fight with a long
tracking shot that rivals Robert Altman's playful opening to ``The
Player.'' Instead of the typical short cuts that most directors
use, De Palma keeps the camera and the action rolling through a
dizzying one-shot set-up that makes us feel like we're in the
casino and as giddy with excitement as Cage is.
</P>
<P>
   The fast-talking, cynical wise guy who suddenly finds himself
over-matched is a perfect role for Cage. He puts on display his
flashy humor and his intelligent desperation, all of which helps De
Palma build the sense that the more he reveals, the less we know.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's largest shortfall: De Palma reveals a little too
much a little too quickly. He seems to doubt that we can follow the
intricacies of the mystery, so he spells them out before he needs
to, relying thereafter upon his showmanship, which is considerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snake Eyes'' is easily the best suspense film of the summer,
much smarter and more exciting than ``The Negotiator, ``A Perfect
Murder'' or ``The X Files.'' It's in a class with Kevin Costner's
``No Way Out'' and ``Nick of Time.'' Go see it before you know
</P>
<P>
   too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snake Eyes'' is rated R for violence and profanity. 4 stars.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1618EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
