<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1341 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PENN&AMP;TELLER-AZR &LR;      08-06 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PENN&AMP;TELLER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENN &AMP; TELLER: NOT PLAYING WITH A FULL DECK, AND PROUD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Penn &AMP; Teller aren't reverent about anything.
</P>
<P>
   Their stage magic show is a full-frontal deconstruction of every
hoary cliche the ancient art has produced. In it, they gleefully
lampoon all kinds of truths commonly held to be sacred.
</P>
<P>
   A Penn &AMP; Teller performance isn't a good choice for a church
outing.
</P>
<P>
   So, who would expect them to be reverent about plate-spinners
and odd puppet acts? The duo's new series on the FX cable network
presents pop music acts side-by-side with top-notch practitioners
of the variety arts, all on one Las Vegas stage. Plus showgirls, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   Penn &AMP; Teller also do tricks, but their skewed outlook fits the
format.
</P>
<P>
   Comedy Central does a Vegas-based revue show, ``Viva Variety,''
which airs Tuesday nights. Where Comedy Central aims for a campy
sendup of variety shtick _ its hosts sport fake Eurotrash accents _
Penn &AMP; Teller are going for something a little more, well,
reverent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Letterman and other shows have had really good variety acts,
but never with respect,'' said Penn Jillette, who, with his usually
silent partner, met recently with TV critics to promote the show:
``Penn &AMP; Teller's Sin City Spectacular,`` airing Monday on FX.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always a little embarrassed when there was an act on
television that requires a great deal of skill but is a little
goofy, and the host comes over and acts like the person doing this
skill is some sort of fool for having learned to do something
that's very, very difficult. I started out as a juggler, so I know
what it means to spend eight hours a day, seven days a week
practicing something that people just dismiss with a wave of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've thought a lot about what it means to be Lou Reed and a
rock-and-roll legend, but we haven't thought very much about how
much it takes to sit in a room with animals that have brains the
size of a walnut and enough RAM to run a 1987 laptop and actually
train those animals to work on voice commands in Russian _ without
killing them. And we wanted to point that out to people.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, our idea was to do some of our stuff and put it in the
context of a variety show.''
</P>
<P>
   The message, said Jillette, will be ``that what a guy who trains
house cats does for a living and what Bob Dylan does for a living
and what Johann Sebastian Bach did for a living are exactly and
precisely the same thing. And there hasn't been a show since Ed
Sullivan that has really stated that in no uncertain terms.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days before channel-surfing, Sullivan was able to hold
the home audience's attention by presenting a parade of unrelated
acts. Sometimes Sullivan's bookings seemed calculated to vex fans
who were dialing in for one particular performer or pop group, but
he ruled television for a long, long time with a format that Penn &AMP;
Teller are now attempting to reinvigorate.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional TV wisdom says that the clicker has become our
Sullivan surrogate, that the embarrassment of niches available on
cable TV has become every viewer's own endless variety show.
</P>
<P>
   Teller, who can, in fact, talk, said he and Jillette hope to
reclaim Clicker Nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ideal would be that you would get the same sensation from
watching our show as you do from hitting the remote control button
_ that you're popping into entirely different worlds, one after the
other, but without the effort of pressing that little thing with
your thumb,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laziness,'' added his tall partner, ``is our friend.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dave Walker is the television critic for The Arizona Republic. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1627EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
