<HEADLINE>
&HT;      (CORRECTS TO MINORITY LEADER RICHARD GEPHARDT)
 &HT;      HISPANIC CAUCUS CONDEMNS DORNAN LEGAL REIMBURSEMENT, PROMISES
TO TRY TO BLOCK THE FUNDS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Elliot Zaret  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Aug. 6 -- House Latinos attacked Republicans
Thursday for the decision to reimburse ex-Rep. Robert K. Dornan for
most of his legal fees incurred during the investigation into
alleged voter fraud in the 1996 election, saying Hispanic voters
``continue to be assaulted.''
</P>
<P>
   And they plan to try to block the decision. Minority Leader
Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., plans to introduce a resolution this
(THURSDAY) evening that would block the funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to do what we can on the floor of the House today,''
said Rep. Xavier Becerra, D-Los Angeles, who chairs the House
Hispanic Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the House Oversight Committee decided to reimburse
part of the legal fees for both Dornan and Rep. Loretta Sanchez,
the Garden Grove Democrat who beat Dornan by 984 votes in November
of 1996. The committee gave Dornan $320,526 -- 69 percent of his
legal costs -- and Sanchez received $252,536 -- 61 percent of her
costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find this action an affront to the Orange County tax
payers,'' said Sanchez, who said the decision was merely an attempt
by Republicans to fund Dornan's campaign, as Dornan used campaign
funds to pay his lawyer fees. Sanchez payed her lawyers from a
legal defense fund separate from her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a partisan use of taxpayer funds for campaign
purposes,'' said Sanchez. ``This is a political contribution (by
Republicans) to one of their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Menendez, D-N.J., said the decision to reimburse Dornan
was one of a series of measures against Latinos, including a the
way the 2000 Census will be conducted -- which he said would keep
Latinos from being counted, and a pending bilingual education bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to be assaulted by the majority party of the
House,'' said Menendez.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans are in a state of denial -- they just cannot
accept that a Hispanic woman has won the seat,'' said Rep. Jose
Serrano, D-NY. ``They have found a new way to donate money to the
Bob Dornan campaign without following the rules and regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lucille Roybal-Allard, D-Los Angeles, criticized the
Republicans on the House Oversight Committee for making its
decision without allowing input from the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only should the Latino community be outraged by what has
taken place,'' said Roybal-Allard. ``It is a direct attack against
the democratic process that will affect every person in this
country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
