<HEADER>
A1377 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      08-06 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE A GOOD LOOK BEFORE CONVERTING REGULAR IRA TO A ROTH IRA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. We retired this May, earning enough to qualify for IRA
contributions this year, but not so much as to affect our ability
to collect full Social Security payments. Our tax man suggested
that since this is the last year that we will be able to purchase
an IRA that we establish a Roth IRA for this year and also transfer
our exiting IRAs to Roth accounts. We know very little of this, and
don't understand most of what we've read, except that we would have
to pay taxes on our old IRAs if we transferred them to Roths. Each
IRA is about $50,000 and they are in bank CDs. Would a transfer be
advisable at our ages _ 62 and 64? We will be in the 28 percent
bracket for this year, and in 1999 we will have Social Security, a
small pension, and interest earned _ which we hope will mean we
will go down to the 15 percent tax bracket. Which way should we go?
</P>
<P>
   F.W., Orion, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. With all respect to your tax adviser, I can see nothing to
gain either by establishing Roth IRAs for this year or converting
the traditional IRAs to Roth accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Let's do the math. If you were to convert the traditional IRAs
to Roths, you would be allowed to spread the tax obligation over
the course of four tax years. This would mean that $25,000 would be
added to your income in each of the next four years. This year that
$25,000 would be taxed at the 28 percent rate _ unless the amount
is sufficient to push you into a still higher bracket. In the next
three years, the same amount would be added to your income, and
again would probably be enough to drive you to a higher tax
bracket.
</P>
<P>
   In the alternative, if you retain the accounts as traditional
IRAs, you will have a little more control over your tax destiny.
For example, you might look at your tax situation each year,
determine how much money you might be able to withdraw from the
IRAs without taking you beyond the 15 percent tax bracket, and
simply withdraw that amount. With luck, over the long haul, most of
the money eventually would be taxed at only 15 percent, rather than
at the higher rates that you would pay through with a transfer to a
Roth.
</P>
<P>
   The general rule of thumb for a transfer to a Roth is that it is
inadvisable if you expect to be in a lower tax bracket when the
money is withdrawn than when the proposed transfer would occur.
Some people, and especially people who are a lot younger than you
are, might decide that they want to make a transfer because they
feel tax rates in general are likely to be higher in their later
years. And finally, some might make the transfer without regard to
the tax rates, but rather because they want to escape the schedule
of mandatory minimum annual withdrawals from traditional IRAs which
begin after the owner reaches age 70 1/2. Unless you fall into this
last category, I see nothing for you to gain by transferring to a
Roth.
</P>
<P>
   For the same reason, I see no reason you would profit by putting
your 1998 IRA contributions into Roth accounts. Since you're in the
28 percent tax bracket, you would cut your tax bill by $1,120 with
a traditional IRA. Compare that with the prospect of withdrawals at
the 15 percent, which might be made as early as 1999, and which
would bring a $600 tax bill if you are in a 15 percent tax bracket.
Yes, the growth of the account would also be taxed if you used the
traditional IRA, but especially when you are using CDs as the
vehicle for your IRA savings, the growth is not likely to be enough
to offset the difference between a 15 percent and a 28 percent tax
rate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am as spooked about the market as you are. My wife and I
have IRAs with Vanguard. My total is about $803,000, of which
$603,000 is in the Vanguard GNMA fund, $20,000 in its Specialized
Gold and Precious Metals fund, $131,000 in a brokerage account, and
the rest in Vanguard Prime Money Market fund. My wife's $63,000
account is entirely in Vanguard GNMA. I am 66 and retired, and my
wife is 60. Am I too conservative?
</P>
<P>
   I also have IRAs with Janus, consisting of $96,000 in money
markets, $31,000 in Janus Worldwide and $3,000 in Janus Twenty. I
am thinking of moving $4,000 a month from the Janus money market
fund to Worldwide for four or five years as a dollar cost-averaging
approach. Should I do the same with Vanguard, moving funds from the
money market account into Vanguard Index Value fund?
</P>
<P>
   E.O., Allentown, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I'd say you're a good deal more spooked with our stock market
than I am. Your brokerage portfolio is heavily dominated by foreign
stocks; between that portfolio, the 25 percent of Janus Worldwide
that's in U.S. equities, and the small position in Janus 20, I
calculate just 2.7 percent of the total portfolio in domestic
stocks. (This calculation does not include the Vanguard Specialized
Gold and Precious Metals holding, which is about 20 to 25 percent
invested in US companies, but not necessarily US companies with
most of their operations here.)
</P>
<P>
   Are you too conservative? Yes, and you're too sour on the US
markets as well. While I agree that they're overvalued right now,
at age 66 you're simply too young to throw in the towel on the
world's strongest economy. I think a dollar cost-averaging program
moving the Vanguard money market account into Index Value is a good
idea _ a program of moving $1,100 a month into Index Value would
complete the investment within 49 months, presuming 5 percent
average returns from the money market.
</P>
<P>
   As for the more substantial amount of money in the Janus money
market fund, I agree that it should be moved to the equity side,
but I think you have enough overseas holdings already. I'd rather
see a dollar-cost-averaging program with tried-and-tested Janus
fund as the target for about 75 percent of this money, and with
Vanguard Specialized Health Care as the target for the balance.
(Incidentally, you have miscalculated in determining that a
sequence of $4,000 monthly withdrawals from the Janus Money Market
account would spread your investment over four or five years; it
would take only a little more than 25 months. A 48-month program
would entail moving about $2,200 a month, while a 60-month program
would require $1,800 monthly purchase of the stock funds; both of
these calculations again assume 5 percent money market returns.)
</P>
<P>
   Where would all of this take us? Currently the total equity
portion of the portfolio is 18.6 percent of the portfolio. If all
of the transfers discussed were completed at once (rather than
spread out over several years) the new portfolio would be 33.1
percent equities, and 17.3 percent of it would be in US equities.
Given the vagaries of the markets, it is of course impossible to
estimate what the actual percentages might be by the time the
investments are completed. But in any event, none of these moves
would affect the bedrock of your combined portfolios _ the
$666,763, or 66.9 percent of the total, in Vanguard GNMA.
</P>
<P>
   Are all of these suggestions too rich for your blood? Well, if
so, what about a compromise? You might doctor the formula by
building the equity side to 25 percent of the total portfolio,
which would entail moving only $64,184 of the money market accounts
into stock funds. Again, if you made this move I would go entirely
into US equity funds with this money. That would leave $130,658 in
the money markets. At this point you certainly have plenty of the
Vanguard GNMA fund, and I suggest that if you take this course the
$130,658 be evenly divided between Vanguard Short-Term Bond fund
and Vanguard Corporate High-Yield Bond fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
