<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEDS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`UNMADE BEDS': STORIES OF 4 REAL PEOPLE, WITH A HANDFUL OF LIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brenda isn't really looking for love; she just needs a man to
pay off the $2,700 in mortgage payments she owes.
</P>
<P>
   Michael is looking for the right woman but thinks he'll never
find her because he's 5 feet 4 inches tall.
</P>
<P>
   Mikey considers himself ``a catch'' at age 54 (because he's
HIV-negative, he says). He takes pride in never having dated ``a
mutt'' but doesn't seem to be having much luck with the purebreds.
</P>
<P>
   Aimee sometimes feels her situation is hopeless because she's
``28 and not married _ it's absurd.'' She weighs 225 pounds and has
no plans to try to lose weight.
</P>
<P>
   These four single New Yorkers are real people who were filmed by
Nicholas Barker, a British television and radio producer, for a
little more than six months in 1996-97. Their stories and feelings,
which they express directly to the camera, constitute ``Unmade
Beds,'' Barker's fascinating, depressing and undeniably cruel new
film.
</P>
<P>
   Aimee comes off as the most sympathetic character. One minute
she's in a taxi with a Lord &AMP; Taylor shopping bag and a cell phone,
laughing with a friend about a bad date: ``He looked exactly like
Humpty Dumpty. And he was as old as my father.'' The next, it
seems, she has tears in her eyes, saying: ``I am so pathetic. I
just feel like there's no hope.'' In one scene she calls an old
boyfriend and a woman answers. She tells her best friend that she
won't try a dating service because if that, the last resort, didn't
work, what would she do next?
</P>
<P>
   Mikey comes off as the most unlikable. In his opening lines,
toned down for print, he welcomes the filmmakers to his home by
saying that his apartment is for women to have sex in. If they
don't want to have sex, he adds, they shouldn't visit. He complains
about having spent $197 for dinner on a failed date but is seen in
another scene taking a date to a deli near the Milford Plaza Hotel.
He describes his mother as ``the best person I ever met in my whole
life.'' You do have to feel for him, though, when the junior
cashier at the Angelika movie theater automatically gives him a
senior discount.
</P>
<P>
   Brenda, a woman of a certain (and unspecified) age, is the most
entertaining. Standing in her apartment in a bra, denim shorts and
hot rollers, she explains that she's not attracted to Jewish men.
There is one exception, however: Tony Curtis. ``I would sleep with
him now,'' she says, ``just for how sexy he USED to be.'' She has a
peculiar kind of honesty, considering shoplifting of small items a
right, stepping out of the shower to demonstrate her baby-oil
beauty treatment and pointing out the place in her bra where, she
says, she keeps her drugs. Brenda is the only character in the film
who gets what she wants by the end.
</P>
<P>
   Michael, 40, seems saddest. ``Why do these women hang out with
effeminate homosexual men? How do you expect to meet guys?'' he
asks, adding two gruff words of advice to those absent women:
``Grow up.'' Admitting to a fear of dying alone, he decides to go
to a dating coach and to work at trying ``not to be so intense.''
It seems completely appropriate that he has an Edward Hopper print
over his kitchen table.
</P>
<P>
   The camera takes a long look at the Hopper, as well as at a
dripping bathroom faucet. The artistic intent must be to make them
symbols of despair. But if so, why does the camera give us a
lingering close-up of Aimee's Balducci's bag, with a baguette and a
pineapple sticking out?
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `UNMADE BEDS'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Nicholas Barker; director of
photography, William Rexer II; edited by Paul Binns; music by
Rupert Lord; produced by Steve Wax; released by Chelsea Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 93 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Unmade Beds'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It contains partial nudity
and profanity.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Brenda Monte, Michael De Stefano, Aimee Copp and Mikey
Russo. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
