<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1406 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELARUS-LUKASHENKO-$A     08-06 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELARUS-LUKASHENKO-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SLAMMING THE DOOR SLOWLY,' BELARUS' LEADER LOOKS TO THE PAST
 &HT;    With BELARUS-US-$ADV09, BELARUS-BOX-$ADV09.
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Aug. 9 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINSK, Belarus _ This is not the Soviet Union. But the man who
controls this small nation wedged between Poland and Russia is
doing his best to reproduce the original.
</P>
<P>
   The autocratic president of Belarus, Alexander Lukashenko, has
jailed opponents, muted the free press and propped up a
languishing, state-run economy, even as the emerging markets of
Eastern European neighbors blossom around him.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, he revived the Cold War on a diplomatic scale in
Minsk, the country's capital. Lukashenko provoked a dispute with
the United States and other Western governments by dislodging
ambassadors from their residences.
</P>
<P>
   The episode prompted a further chill over already cool
diplomatic relations with America (See related story).
</P>
<P>
   But for Lukashenko, who turns 44 this month, such controversy
only fuels a political career propelled by the nostalgia among his
people for Soviet glory. It has made Belarus the most Soviet-like
of the 15 independent countries created when the Soviet Union
dissolved in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   A former collective farm director who speaks plainly and acts
forcefully, Lukashenko has cultivated an image as champion of the
Slavic world, loath to grovel for Western aid or world acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   He is a maverick with a mouth, who appeals to the simple farmers
and factory workers of Belarus. He has spoken with admiration of
Joseph Stalin. He has warned his people of the dangers of NATO
expansion to their borders.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent example of Soviet-speak, he went on
television to urge the population to amass in August to assist in
harvesting crops, saying ``it is necessary to have bread'' to
defend the country. ``We are being perpetually kicked everywhere;
everybody is trying to suppress Belarus,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Many, if not a majority, of Belarus's 10 million people support
the man they freely elected in 1994, and share his dreams for the
economic security and global stature of the Soviet years.
</P>
<P>
   It is a phenomenon viewed with alarm by Western diplomats and
international human rights advocates, who fear that the tail could
end up wagging the dog -- that the Soviet-style revival in tiny
Belarus could infiltrate problem-plagued Russia, which is
struggling with democratic and market reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Lukashenko advocates a political reunion with Moscow and, say
friends and foes alike, harbors one over-arching ambition: to rule
a neo-Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a strong desire for power,'' said Pavel Daneiko, an
economist and political analyst in Minsk. ``That dream, that idea,
pushes everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukashenko has made frequent campaign-style trips to Russia's
provinces and hosted local Russian politicians in Minsk, cementing
political ties while circumventing the power structure in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the belief that Lukashenko is angling for a seat in the
Kremlin ignores a host of political and logistical obstacles, not
the least of which are a number of strong Russian contenders who
want to replace Boris Yeltsin. And there is the question of how
Lukashenko, as the leader of a separate state, would circumvent the
Russian constitution to add his name to the ballot there.
</P>
<P>
   In Belarus, Lukashenko emerged in 1993 as head of a government
anti-corruption commission and used it as a launching pad to the
presidency, winning 85 percent of the votes in the July 1994
balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, he pushed a referendum that extended his
six-year term an additional two years, to 2001, and gave him
sweeping controls over the parliament (which he dissolved) and the
courts.
</P>
<P>
   He also began a crackdown against opposition leaders, stifled
newspapers and closed a popular FM radio station which broadcast
reports from western news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't have access to information. And if they don't
have access to information, they cannot make informed decisions,''
complained Zhanna Litvina, president of the Belarus Association of
Journalists and former director of the FM station.
</P>
<P>
   He set about restoring and preserving the symbols of the past:
wheat sheaves, hammers and sickles, statues and busts of Lenin and
other icons of the Communist era. Soviet-era textbooks have been
reintroduced in schools.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while Belarus retains the heavy and soul-less architecture
of the Soviet era and a sputtering economy beset by massive
inflation, the capital offers signs of liberties despite the
efforts of the president.
</P>
<P>
   On a balmy midsummer evening, the young and stylish set dine at
sidewalk cafes, mobile telephones at the ready. McDonald's sells
its burgers here. A Ford Motor Co. plant on the edge of the city
cranks out the pride of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   And while many Lukashenko opponents have been jailed, many
others walk freely and speak openly.
</P>
<P>
   But what worries human rights activists and western diplomats is
a steady erosion of freedoms in the four years since Lukashenko was
elected. ``People here call it slamming the door slowly,''' said
one American aid worker.
</P>
<P>
   The long list of abuses has been catalogued by human rights
groups -- the jailing and beating of political opponents, arrest
and harassment of independent local journalists and a near-monopoly
on information by state-run newspapers, radio and television.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a decade that has seen the emergence of eastern Europe from
Soviet repression, Belarus is turning back the clock,'' said Holly
Cartner of New York-based Human Rights Watch.
</P>
<P>
   Given its blank history, perhaps it is not surprising that
Lukashenko has been able to mold Belarus to fit his fancy.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a brief period following World War I, Belarus has
never before existed as a sovereign state. For centuries, the
territory, about the size of Kansas, was a battleground and
possession for warring Russia, Germany and other imperial European
powers, and then a province of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   If Lukashenko wishes to build an empire of his own, opponents
say his time is running out.
</P>
<P>
   The centralized state economy has withered in recent years
despite official figures showing 10 percent growth in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The local currency, the ruble, has taken a beating so far this
year and inflation has soared to an annual rate of more than 120
percent by some estimates. In March, Lukashenko ordered prices not
to rise more than 2 percent a month. Pensioners and workers get
paid on time -- in contrast to Russia, where massive wage arrears
have prompted Yeltsin's popularity to plummet -- but their currency
buys less. The average monthly wages equals only about $60.
</P>
<P>
   ``He satisfies their needs by printing more money. The policy is
destructive and it doesn't allow us to attract any new investment.
We are approaching the collapse of the economy,'' said Yuri
Khadyka, vice chairman of the Belarus Popular Front, a leading
opposition group.
</P>
<P>
   But Daneiko, the economist, asserts that time is still on
Lukashenko's side. He can sustain the economy from the goodwill of
Russia, Belarus' main trading partner and with whom it has joined
in an economic union, and avoid begging for Western aid, and the
ties that come with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the president can decide that things will change,'' said
Danieko. ``And for him, the one main goal is that nothing will
change.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
