<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BELARUS FACTS AND FIGURES
 &HT;    With BELARUS-LUKASHENKO-$ADV09.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELARUS At-a-Glance
</P>
<P>
   (For purposes of a locator map: Belarus is situated in Eastern
Europe, bordered by Russia, Poland, Lithuania and Latvia.)
</P>
<P>
   Area: 80,153 square miles, slightly smaller than the state of
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 10.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Life expectancy at birth: 62.5 years for men; 74.6 years for
women.
</P>
<P>
   Gross domestic product (GDP): $51.9 billion (1996)
</P>
<P>
   Per capita annual income: $5,000 (1996)
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment rate: 3 percent
</P>
<P>
   Government: Alexander Lukashenko became the first democratically
elected president in 1994, but pushed a 1996 referendum giving him
broad, dictator-like powers over parliament and the courts. He has
been condemned by Western nations, including the United States, for
human rights abuses and curbs on personal freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   Economy: Main exports are machinery, agricultural produce,
chemicals; less than 5 percent of the economy is in private
ownership. Triple-digit inflation is countered by artificial price
controls and the printing of more currency. Chief trading partner
Russia helps subsidize economy by with fuel and raw materials.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
