</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELARUS-US-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN 'SEWER WAR,' ISOLATED BELARUS DEFIES U.S. AND THE WORLD
 &HT;    With BELARUS-LUKASHENKO-$ADV09.
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Aug. 9 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINSK, Belarus _ This summer's heated dispute between Belarus
and the United States began with an abrupt demand from the
president's office: the American ambassador, and those of 20 other
countries, must leave their residences in an exclusive compound in
the capital.
</P>
<P>
   It resulted in the angry departure in June of U.S. Ambassador
Daniel Speckhard and envoys from seven other nations, the largest
diplomatic exodus from a European country since the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Cold War-style rhetoric followed. In Washington, the U.S. State
Department called President Alexander Lukashenko ``an authoritarian
dictator who is unable to understand the basic difference between
right and wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the Vienna Convention, the treaty which states that
an embassy is the sovereign territory of the country it represents.
The agreement was last breached in 1979, when revolutionaries in
Iran swept into the U.S. embassy and took hostages.
</P>
<P>
   In Minsk, the press dubbed the diplomatic controversy the
``sewer war'' after Lukashenko said the evictions were necessary
because the luxury residences, near his own mansion, needed
plumbing repairs.
</P>
<P>
   But the widely held view in Minsk is that Lukashenko, who rules
his country like a Soviet-era dictator, no longer wished to share
the compound, called Drozdy, with foreigners -- particularly the
Americans, whose residence was right across the fence from the
president's.
</P>
<P>
   The compound gates were locked, electricity and water to the
houses were cut off and a new brass plaque proclaimed Drozdy an
official presidential residence.
</P>
<P>
   The Belarus foreign ministry explained that the compound, once a
collection of summer houses for Soviet-era officials, had always
been considered ``temporary housing for diplomats'' -- despite
long-term leases that, in the case of the American residence, ran
until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the first time Washington and Minsk have tangled.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Lukashenko aroused worldwide condemnation when his
government shot down and killed two American recreational
balloonists who were flying over Belarus during a race. Lukashenko
claimed they were spying and expressed no remorse.
</P>
<P>
   While America and other countries currently are without
ambassadors in Minsk, none has broken off relations, instead
keeping minimal staffs in place to monitor affairs and maintain
contacts with human rights activists, opposition leaders and
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The Lukashenko government offered to relocate the ambassadors
and their families to temporary housing until their countries could
build permanent residences. The offer was rejected because
maintained that they already had valid leases, and should not have
been pressured to move before the leases expired.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are few options facing the West. Over the past
year, the International Monetary Fund, the World Bank and other
donors have suspended aid. Private foreign investment has slowed to
a trickle.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts in Minsk believe the eccentric Lukashenko relishes such
attention and isolation from the West, kindling his
self-perpetuated image as a champion of the Slavic people against
the approach of an expanding NATO and the influences of Western
culture and consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Soviet times, the people were told we were always
surrounded by enemies,'' said Vladimir Glod(CQ), a former
journalist and outspoken critic of Lukashenko. ``This is simply a
return to the past.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
