<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1427 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEVIS-SECEDE-$ADV09-C     08-06 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEVIS-SECEDE-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPSCALE NEVIS SET TO SPLIT FROM BIG SISTER ST. KITTS
 &HT;    With NEVIS-BOX-$ADV09.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Aug. 9 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Covering just 36 square miles, the island of Nevis is a
mere speck on the map of the Caribbean Sea. With only two large
grocery stores -- and no major airports or cruise ship docks --
it's the kind of place where straggling goats often stop traffic.
</P>
<P>
   But despite its small size, some 6,000 voters will decide in a
referendum on Monday(Aug. 10) whether to secede from Nevis' big
sister, St. Kitts, located just two miles of water away.
</P>
<P>
   If two-thirds of those voting say yes, Nevis will become the
hemisphere's tiniest -- and one of the world's smallest --
independent nations, boasting a population of scarcely 11,000
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need to go our separate ways,'' said Mark Brantley,
who chairs the Nevis Constitutional Committee and is a staunch
proponent of secession.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as if we're involved in a limping marriage,'' he said.
``We may be together but we're not going anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The British first united the islands -- along with nearby
Anguilla -- more than a century ago. But Anguilla left the cluster
in 1967, before independence, and remains a British dependent
territory today.
</P>
<P>
   Nevis reluctantly joined St. Kitts in a federation after the two
islands won independence from Britain in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   But Nevisians have since complained of being treated like a
neglected stepchild instead of a valued sibling.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-secessionists say that Nevis contributes 38 percent of the
federation's tax revenue, but only receives 21 percent of
government spending. As a result, they say Nevis has a deficient
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, St. Kitts enjoys the country's only
international airport and a deep-water channel for cruise ships.
</P>
<P>
   ``They treat us like second-class citizens,'' groused Malcolm
Guishard, Nevis' deputy premier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nevis wants to determine its own destiny,'' he said. ``We
don't need them telling us what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Rising to a volcanic peak, Nevis was named ``Las Nieves'' --
Spanish for snow -- by Christopher Columbus because the island's
summit, shrouded in white clouds and mist, reminded him of the
snow-capped mountains in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Today the tourist-rich island is dominated by the posh Four
Seasons Resort Hotel, and has become a playground for the rich and
famous, including Woody Allen, Sylvester Stallone and Robert
DeNiro. With more than 700 employees, the Four Seasons is the
island's largest employer.
</P>
<P>
   The destination garnered even more cachet a few years ago when
Princess Diana vacationed in Nevis, accompanied by Princes William
and Harry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of tourists shoots up every year, and there are new
hotels going up all the time, so Nevis has had great success with
this industry; more than St. Kitts has had,'' said Kenneth
Williams, who owns the Nevis Observer, the island's weekly
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   But besides tourism, there's also a $1.9 million-a-year offshore
business in Nevis, where 10,000 international business corporations
(IBCs) are registered, the majority of which are asset-protection
trusts.
</P>
<P>
   It was when the St. Kitts-Nevis government introduced new
financial regulations a few years ago to gain greater control of
investments and offshore business services in Nevis that the move
for secession really took off.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the economy of St. Kitts is driven mostly by a
troubled sugar industry, a smattering of assembly plants, and a
tourism industry that is less upscale than in Nevis, where some
hotel rooms fetch $500 a night.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, St. Kitts has been plagued by drug-related crime in
recent years, further troubling image-conscious Nevis, which prides
itself on its number of churches -- 60.
</P>
<P>
   On July 31, the U.S. State Department reported that an accused
drug trafficker, Charles ``Little Nut'' Miller, threatened to
randomly kill U.S. veterinary students in St. Kitts if he lost his
fight against extradition.
</P>
<P>
   He and two other alleged drug traffickers believed to be in St.
Kitts are all under U.S. indictment for smuggling cocaine into the
United States, and a court in St. Kitts is now considering a U.S.
extradition request for them.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have even urged Americans traveling to St. Kitts
to take precautions, along with the 250 students and 50 faculty
members at Ross Veterinary University.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the disparities and disagreements between the two
islands, Nevis' referendum on secession has raised concerns in an
era that has countries in the Caribbean working toward closer
economic and political integration.
</P>
<P>
   In a strongly worded statement, Kenny Anthony, the chairman of
the 15-nation Caribbean Community, or Caricom, said the regional
trade and political group was disappointed over the planned vote.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony said he was worried about ``the undesirable
fragmentation of the Caribbean.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement from the U.S. State Department, spokesman James
Rubin expressed hope that the voters of Nevis will preserve their
historical ties to St. Kitts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maintaining the federation would be more compatible with the
trend toward greater regional integration, with all its
considerable benefits and advantages,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   St. Kitts-Nevis Prime Minister Denzil Douglas also has lamented
the vote in Nevis, but said he'll do nothing to undermine the
effort to secede.
</P>
<P>
   He blames a ``flawed'' 1983 constitution for fomenting
discontent and separation.
</P>
<P>
   That constitution provides not only for 11 elected federal
parliamentarians -- eight from St. Kitts and three from Nevis --
but also for a five-member Nevis Island Assembly that has
substantial autonomy over local Nevis affairs. The federal
government has its seat in Basseterre, in St. Kitts.
</P>
<P>
   The constitution includes a provision that allows Nevis to
secede unilaterally, and the Nevis Island Assembly voted
unanimously last October to approve the secession vote.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's hard to predict the outcome, there's a growing
sense that secession will succeed. In a non-binding vote in 1974,
about 80 percent of Nevisians favored secession.
</P>
<P>
   If pro-secessionists do succeed Monday, Nevis would become an
independent nation within the next year or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very ready to end the abuse and neglect,'' Brantley
said bluntly. ``The relationship has always been an uneasy one.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
