<HEADER>
A1429 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-BRITAIN-$ADV0     08-06 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-BRITAIN-$ADV08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: TOUGHING OUT THE ENGLISH SUMMER HEAT . . . ER. . . SORT
OF
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Aug. 8 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST HORSLEY, England _ In late June, I stood on the front porch
of my mom and dad's place an hour south of Dallas and marveled at
the old plastic thermometer.
</P>
<P>
   It reported the temperature to be 112 degrees. I would have
thought it hotter. The heat was such that the wood of the porch
smelled as if it would soon burst into flames. Much of what Dad had
planted over the years to civilize their patch of prairie grasses
and mesquite trees was surrendering its last moisture, becoming
straw-colored and brittle. His organic garden, a source of pride
for a man who spent too many years living in cities, was barren.
</P>
<P>
   Inside their little home, the air-conditioners were working
frightfully hard to create an oasis of cool where a couple of older
people might survive, so long as they kept the doors and windows
sealed and ventured outside only moderately. They might as have
well been space travelers trapped in their spaceship on Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Tempered somewhat by altitude and longitude, the heat also had
visited my home in Atlanta, where my garden was only slightly
better off than dad's. The tomatoes and greens I'd planted couldn't
seem to get enough water to provide much of a salad. The
honeysuckle planted on the arbor in May didn't make it to July.
</P>
<P>
   So imagine the relief of arriving to this place, where a cool
spell is caressing an already mild climate. The garden at Meadows
-- that's the name of the house we leased south of London; we don't
use anything so impersonal as street numbers in West Horsley _ is
lush and brilliant with purples, reds and whites. The grass is
thick, soft and green. My apple trees are heavy with fruit and the
berries are making the birds crazy.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Sunday, it was sunny with a high of 73 degrees. I
sat on the patio reading tacky English newspapers and reveling in
the glory of this early fall or late spring or whatever it is.
Really, it's as if the weather gods have knitted spring to fall
without using a summer at all.
</P>
<P>
   In the evening, you need a jacket -- a fashion necessity anyway
to a man of a certain age beset with the humbling combination of
vanity and pudginess. At night, you need a light blanket.
</P>
<P>
   I feel some guilt, but not much, when I see stories in the
London press about the miseries of the American broil. (Am I crazy
or do I detect a suggestion by the writers that the uppity
colonists at last are getting their due?)
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the English television weather ``Kens'' and ``Barbies,''
like their American cousins, are putting on their grim faces to
report their own weather disaster: The Missing Summer. No one can
find it anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   I gather that this is bad news to people who pass all those
drizzly months of leaden skies longing desperately for the heat, if
you can call it that, of summer. People here are talking about how
the weather has damaged the British tourism industry and generally
made everyone cranky.
</P>
<P>
   In record numbers, Britons are fleeing to the warmth of southern
France, Spain and Florida, where they can frolic on the beaches,
exposing their alarmingly unprepared white bodies to searing
ultraviolet sunrays. (I wonder if there's a market for a travel
package to sunny, exotic central Texas?)
</P>
<P>
   Well, they can have it.
</P>
<P>
   I'll remain in the natural air-conditioning, testing the various
ales and beers you can buy in the little store down Ockham Road
from Meadows in a quest for a regular brand.
</P>
<P>
   And I'll remain to watch the bloom. My soul needs to see at
least one garden come to full flower this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
