<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S NEW AND NEWS IN HOME VIDEO  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; World War II In the Movies &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see a show,'' an officer tells the troops
gathering in England for the invasion depicted in the Academy
Award-nominated documentary ``D-Day Remembered.'' This summer's
D-Day show, of course, with its horrific carnage in the water and
on the beaches, takes place in Steven Spielberg's ``Saving Private
Ryan.'' Adding no small degree of poignancy to the scene is a fact
pointed out in the documentary: fewer than 15 percent of the troops
who slogged ashore in Normandy that day had ever been in combat.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, the Spielberg epic will serve as backdrop for a
quieter investigation of the war. This time the medium is video,
but the films, a collection of award-winning documentaries, will be
available not in stores but at the public library.
</P>
<P>
   The series, ``From Rosie to Roosevelt: A Film History of
Americans in World War II,'' is to be introduced in 20 libraries
across the country. The effort is a joint project of National Video
Resources _ a New York organization that helps to mount and finance
independently produced films and videos _ the National Endowment
for the Humanities, the American Library Association and the John
D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to promote thought and discussion about the war.
``One of the things library programs can do is fill people's need
to get together and engage in discourse,'' said Sally
Mason-Robinson, director of library projects for National Video
Resources.
</P>
<P>
   The program includes six weekly sessions. At each library, a
scholar from a college in the area will introduce the films, some
of which are set on the battlefield and others on the home front.
The documentaries, it is hoped, will stimulate discussion not so
much about the details of battles as their origins and their
consequences and, for older people,stir personal recollections and
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   For many people, there is much basic history to be taught. In
``Days of Waiting,'' an Academy Award winner about the internment
of Japanese-Americans, an internee who committed suicide lies
beside railroad tracks, having killed himself by placing his head
on the rail. The image is as stark as some in ``Saving Private
Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosie, of course, is the heroine of ``The Life and Times of
Rosie the Riveter.'' In ``F.D.R.,'' a Peabody and DuPont award
winner, President Roosevelt gains approval of the 1941 Lend-Lease
Act to get weapons to the desperate British while maneuvering
around isolationist critics, who opposed providing the money to buy
them. Let the British borrow the weapons ``like a garden hose,
you'd lend it to a neighbor and they'd give it back,'' says the
narrator in ``F.D.R.'' Roosevelt was so sure the country would
support lend-lease that he filled the Atlantic with supply ships on
their way to England before he even signed the document.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. George C. Marshall has a different challenge in ``George
Marshall and the American Century.'' President Roosevelt had just
appointed him to prepare what was then still a largely untrained
and unseasoned Army. ``The trouble with the Army,'' Marshall says,
``was that there wasn't any Army.''
</P>
<P>
   Librarians interested in taking part in the series may call Ms.
Mason-Robinson at (312) 491-0844 or send an e-mail query to
National Video Resources at nvrinfo(AT)nvr.org.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New Releases &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Big Lebowski &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Basting in his bubble bath, his head phones turned high, Jeff
Lebowski (Jeff Bridges) doesn't hear the intruders, who toss an
attack ferret in the water with him and then deface his living room
rug. Seems that this Lebowski, a loosely strung fellow called the
Dude, has been mistaken for the big Lebowski, a tycoon (David
Huddleston) with a missing wife named Bunny (Tara Reid). Hired to
find Bunny, the Dude balances that assignment with all the doings
at the bowling alley where he congregates with the dim-witted Donny
(Steve Buscemi) and the blustery Vietnam veteran Walter (John
Goodman, above). After the more mainstream ``Fargo,'' Joel and
Ethan Coen are after something loopier here, and, Janet Maslin
wrote in The New York Times, their ``ensemble players are as funny
and as harmonious as they've ever been.'' _1998. Polygram. $108.01.
127 minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Man in the Iron Mask &LR;
</P>
<P>
   So which Leonardo DiCaprio is it to be: the arrogant, spoiled
Louis XIV or the shy, decent Philippe, Louis' twin, who has been
locked away in the dungeon with the iron mask to disguise him? In
Randall Wallace's cheesy adaptation of the Dumas story, nostrils
flare in the kitschy showdown between the two Leos after Philippe
has been sprung by the three musketeers (John Malkovich, Gerard
Depardieu and Jeremy Irons), but ``the haste with which this
laborious costume drama has been slapped together is strongly
apparent'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   _1998. MGM. $104.17. 132 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Wedding Singer &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a veneer of civility with his formal wear, Robbie (Adam
Sandler) croons at other people's weddings while still nursing the
wounds of his own abandonment at the altar by a fiancee who at the
last second figured she could do better. In testier moments, the
memory of it drives Robbie from the schlock he usually sings to the
kind of insulting repartee at the microphone that gets him slugged
by outraged clients. Fortunately, there's Julia (Drew Barrymore), a
sunny waitress, to soften the edge in a film ``with enough
enjoyable silliness to please Sandler's fans'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   _1998. New Line. $107.37. 96 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nice Guy &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It's all over in a flash as Jackie Chan performs his
hand-and-foot assaults on the bodies of drug gang goons. An
intrepid television reporter (Gabrielle Fitzpatrick) gets in
trouble when her cameraman films a vicious drug czar in an
unfavorable light. Jackie back-flips into the fray, sending legions
of heavies flying with a quick chop to the jowls, and a lot of
things get broken. Beyond that, there's not much else to say about
a ``fast, slick, silly tale'' (Lawrence Van Gelder). _1997. New
Line. $104.17. 132 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13. Release date:
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time or appeared on television.
</P>
<P>
   THE GREAT SINGERS OF RUSSIA, VOL. 1: FROM CHALIAPIN TO REIZEN;
VOL. 2: FROM PETROV TO KAZARNOVSKAYA. More than 20 singers _ from
Feodor Chaliapin to Ljuba Kazarnovskaya, who narrates _ cover the
vocal tradition of the 20th century. $29.95 per volume. $29.95
each. Vol. 1, 76 minutes; Vol. 2, 95 minutes. Information: (800)
477-7146.
</P>
<P>
   A LESSON IN LOVE (1954, 95 minutes) and THE DEVIL'S EYE (1960,
90 minutes). If you want to catch Ingmar Bergman in a playful mood,
``Lesson'' is an opportunity. The story of a middle-aged
gynecologist (Gunnar Bjornstrand) who breaks off an affair with a
married 21-year-old patient (Yvonne Lombard) but whose philandering
ways have alienated his wife (Eva Dahlbeck), who is in her own
affair with an old amour, may not tickle every funny bone, but it
counts as a Bergman foray into comedy. More humorous, perhaps, is
Bergman's ``Devil's Eye'' (1960), in which Don Juan is sent back to
earth by the devil to seduce a young woman who finds him more
comical than alluring. Both films are reissued by Home Vision.
$29.99 each. Swedish with English subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   MERLIN. In NBC's popular two-part rendition of the Arthurian
special shown in April, Sam Neill was the magician both in
idealistic young manhood and snowy old age, Miranda Richardson is
the Lady of the Lake and Merlin's creator, her evil sister Queen
Mab, and Isabella Rossellini is Nimue, the woman Merlin adores.
Hallmark. $19.98. 180 minutes. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
