<HEADER>
A1452 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLMONEY-HOUSE07-COX     08-06 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLMONEY-HOUSE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE FINALLY PASSES BIPARTISAN CAMPAIGN FINANCE BILL
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Applauding themselves wildly, House members
concluded months of debate Thursday by sending the Senate a
bipartisan campaign finance reform bill.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would bar unlimited ``soft money'' gifts to parties and
restrict ``issue ads'' that are broadcast by nonparty groups in the
closing days of congressional campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Scotty Baesler of Kentucky, a leader among the ``Blue Dog''
Democrats whose bipartisan petition drive among House members
forced GOP leaders to permit the debate, scoffed at predictions
that the bill would never pass the Senate, where a similar bill was
blocked by a Republican filibuster in February.
</P>
<P>
   Gleefully, he tallied more than a dozen times since last fall
that pundits or opponents called efforts to change campaign finance
laws ``dead'' or ``really dead'' or ``really really dead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who say we will see Elvis before this bill is passed by
the Senate ... are the same people who said the House would never
pass it,'' Baesler declared.
</P>
<P>
   The 252-179 vote for final passage was a long-awaited victory
for supporters of the bill shaped by Reps. Chris Shays, R-Conn.,
and Martin Meehan, D-Mass.. The measure was eventually endorsed by
President Clinton, Democratic congressional and party leaders and a
coalition of nonpartisan advocacy groups led by Common Cause and
the League of Women Voters.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-one Republicans, 10 more than had voted for the
Shays-Meehan vote in a do-or-die preliminary showdown Monday,
joined 190 Democrats and one independent on Thursday's final vote.
They were opposed by 164 Republicans and 15 Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to banning corporate or union gifts to parties,
putting enforceable limits on the size of gifts by individuals to
parties and regulating pre-election broadcast ads, the Shays-Meehan
bill would tighten disclosure rules and create a nonpartisan
commission to suggest further changes to the next Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Though House Republican leaders were eventually rebuffed by the
House, they too could claim some consolation prizes. Because of the
leaders' adamant opposition, the co-sponsors had to water down
their bill in order to attract enough GOP rebels.
</P>
<P>
   And by stretching out the confrontation for nine months after
the start of the petition drive, the leaders made the debate far
too complex for routine TV coverage and shortened the time period
in which Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., will have to
maneuver in order to avoid a straight up-or-down vote on the Senate
floor.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate began its summer vacation July 31. When it reconvenes
after Labor Day, it will have only one month before adjournment to
deal with a long list of other legislation.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, according to Senate Minority Leader Tom
Daschle, D-S.D., the Shays-Meehan proposal has the best chance of
any of the alternatives discussed during the House debate, because
52 of the 100 senators already support a similar bill co-sponsored
by Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Sen. Russ Feingold, D-Wis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passage of any other measure in the House _ no matter how
well-intentioned _ would only have the effect of offering political
cover for the opponents of reform to kill the bill in the Senate,''
Daschle said in a statement circulated to House members prior to
Thursday's final vote.
</P>
<P>
   Before sending the Shays-Meehan bill to the Senate, the House on
Thursday swiftly debated and killed several substitutes that were
weaker or stricter than the Shays-Meehan bill.
</P>
<P>
   The last alternative to go down was a slightly milder proposal
created by an unofficial bipartisan task force led by Reps. Asa
Hutchinson, R-Ark., and and Tom Allen, D-Maine. That plan received
only 147 votes, while 222 opposed their plan and 61 sympathizers
voted ``present'' in order to keep the Shays-Meehan bill alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not let the good be used to get in the way of the
better,'' urged Rep. Lloyd Doggett, D-Texas, in opposing the
freshman bill.
</P>
<P>
   Shays and Meehan told reporters that they would hold a strategy
session Tuesday with McCain and Feingold, whose bill was blocked
earlier this year when they obtained only 52 of the 60 votes needed
to end a GOP filibuster in the Republican-controlled Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're eight votes short, but there are senators like Al
D'Amato (R-N.Y.) and Ben Nighthorse Campbell (R-Colo.) who are
involved in races in states where many voters like campaign
reforms,'' Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing a House member says will change the outcome in the
Senate,'' commented Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn. ``I believe that it
is only if American citizens speak out with a loud and clear voice,
that we will get the additional votes needed in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
