<HEADER>
A1516 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     08-06 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WOMAN ROBS THE CRADLE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ After a spate of movies involving older men with
women young enough to be their daughters, there's finally a film
that turns the subject upside down: an older woman with a much
younger man. It's a topic that Hollywood generally ignores.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain level of taboo about that, which is why so
many women keep it a secret,'' said Terry McMillan, author of the
novel ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back'' and co-author, with Ron
Bass, of the screenplay for the film version, which opens on Aug.
14. (It is also showing Friday night in Manhattan at the Urbanworld
International Film Festival.) ``It's taboo because you look as if
you might be desperate and it's all sexual, which is not the case
at all. My thing is, men do it all the time. Let's not make a big
deal of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The film of Ms. McMillan's novel ``Waiting to Exhale'' was one
of 20th Century Fox's big hits in 1995. The movie, which cost $14
million, grossed $67 million in the United States and tapped an
audience that had been ignored by Hollywood: black women.
</P>
<P>
   The new film stars Angela Bassett as a successful investment
banker and 40-year-old single mother from Northern California who
goes to Jamaica and embarks on a serious relationship with a
20-year-old student, played by Taye Diggs, who appeared in
``Rent.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McMillan, who lives in Northern California, said the Bassett
character was patterned after herself. In 1995, Ms. McMillan said,
she flew to Jamaica on the spur of the moment because events of the
previous year had left her incapable of writing. ``My mother had
suddenly died, my best friend had suddenly died, and I couldn't
write a word after that,'' she recalled. ``I decided to go to
Jamaica and break the monotony.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there a couple of days and met this young man who worked
in a hotel _ of course I didn't take it seriously,'' she continued.
``But then we befriended each other. I went back home. And to make
a long story short, two or three months later he moved up here with
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McMillan said her friend, Jonathan Plummer, who is now
attending college in Northern California, is in his 20s. ``That's
all I'm saying _ and I'm 46,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Schindler, who produced the movie as well as ``Waiting
to Exhale,'' and is a friend of the author, said: ``I still
remember her call from Jamaica. She said, `I'm having the most
outrageous time.' After she got back, she started writing this
book.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been notable exceptions to Hollywood's tendency to
avoid stories about older women and younger men, for example, the
1973 film ``40 Carats,'' in which a 40-ish Liv Ullmann is pursued
by a 20-ish Edward Albert. But Ms. Schindler and Ms. McMillan said
the norm is films with older men and younger women. Some recent
examples: Warren Beatty, 61, and Halle Berry, 31, in ``Bulworth'';
Michael Douglas, 53, and Gwyneth Paltrow, 25, in ``A Perfect
Murder''; Jack Nicholson, 61, and Helen Hunt, 35, in ``As Good as
It Gets,'' and Robert Redford, 61, and Kristin Scott Thomas, 38, in
``The Horse Whisperer.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McMillan laughed at the response of some women at early
screenings. ``Women practically had their airline tickets to
Jamaica in hand after they saw the movie,'' she said. ``But I told
them, `You guys miss the point.' The point isn't, gee whiz, I fell
in love with this younger guy. The point is, it's really about a
woman's right to choose her own path when it comes to happiness and
be willing to take the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Men do it all the time, don't they?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Living Happily So Far &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Andy Tennant, the director and co-screenwriter of ``Ever After:
A Cinderella Story,'' the latest movie version of the fairy tale,
given a feminist twist, summed up Hollywood's conventional wisdom
about Drew Barrymore, the film's female lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something about certain stars like Drew,'' Tennant
said. ``The camera loves them. It's sort of undefinable. It's in
the genes, I suppose.''
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought that the 23-year-old Ms. Barrymore, a
member of the famous and tortured Barrymore acting clan and a
granddaughter of John Barrymore, would have emerged as a respected
and coveted actress after a childhood that seemed straight out of a
terrible Hollywood novel.
</P>
<P>
   At age 6, Ms. Barrymore got a top role in ``E.T.: The
Extra-Terrestrial,'' but then endured publicized drug and alcohol
problems at 12, a rehab stint at 13, a suicide attempt at 14, and a
marriage and divorce at 20. She enjoyed playing bad girls, on and
off screen, and seemed destined to be a front-page fixture on
supermarket tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Ms. Barrymore now seems not only poised for major
stardom but has also apparently straightened out her life so that,
the actress said with a laugh, she's become a very average person.
She said she watches CNN, reads newspapers carefully and is a
strict vegetarian. She speaks of spirituality, is popular on movie
sets and seems to live the kind of stable life that once seemed
elusive.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barrymore attributed the changes, in part, to accepting
responsibility for her problems. Seven years ago, she also took
control of her career from her mother, Jaid, who had been her
manager. The two barely speak now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad, it's not there,'' she said, a bit cryptically.
</P>
<P>
   Of her blossoming career, she said: ``I've had the kind of life
that appreciates a slow pace now. I like the fact that my career
has been a gradual process.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood began taking her acting seriously with her appearance
in ``Boys on the Side,'' ``Batman Forever,'' ``The Wedding
Singer,'' ``Scream'' (a memorable cameo) and Woody Allen's
``Everyone Says I Love You.'' She is making a new film, ``Never
Been Kissed,'' about a newspaper reporter in Chicago who poses as a
high school student to report on what teen-agers are thinking _ and
winds up rediscovering herself.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barrymore said the new approach to Cinderella in ``Ever
After'' intrigued her.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a different Cinderella; I wouldn't have wanted to play
a woman who waits to be rescued,'' she said. ``This is not only a
woman who doesn't wait to be rescued; she rescues others. She's
smart and well read and ahead of her time; she's incredibly strong.
That's what's so appealing about her.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barrymore is a national spokeswoman for the nonprofit Female
Health Foundation, which focuses on safe-sex education for young
women. She said that understanding her childhood and teen-age
years, as strange and troubled as they were, had led her to work
outside the movie business and seek to help troubled girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We experience so much in our lives,'' Ms. Barrymore said.
``The truth is, we need to find empowerment and strength out of
those experiences rather than allow them to be an excuse for
bitterness or having it cripple us. It would have been easy for me
to be crippled by the past. But I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Not `The Parent Trap' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 years ago, the director Jacques Demy and the
composer Michel Legrand teamed up to make ``The Young Girls of
Rochefort'' (``Les Demoiselles de Rochefort''), a Gallic homage to
the American musical, especially the films of Vincente Minnelli.
</P>
<P>
   The film, an elegant fairy tale about twin sisters, starred
Catherine Deneuve as Delphine and her sister, Francoise Dorleac, as
Solange. Newly restored, it is set to be re-released in New York on
Aug. 14 and elsewhere in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I remember most was the joy of making it,'' Ms. Deneuve
said. ``Gene Kelly was in the film and we were so amazed that on
the set he was like he was on the screen: white pants, charming,
seeming to work without any effort.''
</P>
<P>
   But watching the film, originally released in 1967, is
bittersweet for Ms. Deneuve. She and her sister were selected for
their roles by Legrand and Demy (who died in 1990) over actresses
more famous at the time: Brigitte Bardot and Geraldine Chaplin, and
Ms. Bardot and Jeanne Moreau. Soon after the film was finished, Ms.
Dorleac died in a car accident in Nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, it's less difficult to watch this film than others
with my sister,'' Ms. Deneuve said. ``It was the only film I did
with her, but it was a musical. The scenes are so charming and
related to what we were as sisters in real life. Somehow it's more
difficult to see her in other films.''
</P>
<P>
   The film was part of Demy's romantic trilogy, which included
``Lola'' (1961) and ``The Umbrellas of Cherbourg'' (1964). Its
restoration was undertaken mostly because of the determination of
Agnes Varda, the filmmaker and Demy's widow. ``The Umbrellas of
Cherbourg,'' which made Ms. Deneuve a star, was also re-released,
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Musicals are out of time, I suppose,'' Ms. Deneuve said. ``You
can't do musicals today with the lightness and atmosphere that
those musicals had. Those days are finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Deneuve, who lives in France, visits the United States
frequently, and has considered finding an apartment in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The excitement of life in New York: you're always working,
it's a very busy city, very beautiful,'' she said. ``I could not
live in Los Angeles. It's very artificial to me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
