A1526 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-REFORM-NAT     08-06 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-REFORM-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        HOUSE OK'S REFORM, NIXES FROSH BILL
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Paul Kane  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Aug. 6 -- The House reaffirmed its support Thursday
for a ban on unlimited campaign contributions from special
interests to political parties, casting aside a similar but less
restrictive effort by freshmen lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The freshmen could not round up enough support from House
Democrats, many of whom applauded the freshmen effort but said the
stronger reform bill was the one drafted by Reps. Chris Shays,
R-Conn., and Martin Meehan, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   And some proponents of Shays-Meehan, which had already received
237 votes earlier this week, said the freshmen bill was a
``respectable fall-back position'' earlier this year when passing
Shays-Meehan was in doubt. With enough votes to now pass their
bill, Shays-Meehan supporters feared that reform opponents would
vote for the freshmen bill in an effort to pass the weaker bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The freshmen bill has now become Custer's Last Stand for those
who oppose reform,'' said Rep. Charles Bass, R-Vt., who voted for
Shays-Meehan.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Reps. Tom Allen, D-Maine, and Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark.,
who co-wrote the freshmen bill, vigorously defended their plan --
which would have banned ``soft money'' contributions to the
national parties -- as a constitutionally palatable alternative
free of federal mandates on state and local elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is good, solid, substantial reform,'' Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Allen and Hutchinson received 147 votes in support
of their bill, with 121 coming from Republicans. There were 222
``no'' votes.
</P>
<P>
   As a show of support to the freshmen, who were the first in the
105th Congress to hold any hearings on campaign finance reform, 60
Democrats and one Republican voted ``present'' -- meaning they
supported the bill but were afraid to vote for it in fear that it
would gain more votes than Shays-Meehan.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who voted ``present'' were House Minority Leader
Dick Gephardt and House Minority Whip David Bonior. ``We would not
be at this point in passing real campaign reform were it not for
their commitment,'' Bonior, D-Mich., said of Allen's campaign task
force.
</P>
<P>
   After rejecting the freshmen bill, the House was forced to
re-vote on Shays-Meehan, which it did, giving the reform measure
another resounding victory, 252-179.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the strongest bill that we have before us,'' said Rep.
John Baldacci, D-Bangor, who voted for Shays-Meehan and ``present''
on Hutchinson-Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Baldacci said it was an important matter of consistency to make
sure Shays-Meehan was sent to the Senate, which has a similar
version to the House bill, sponsored by Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz.,
and Russ Feingold, D-Wisc.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the passage of Shays-Meehan, it is questionable
whether the Senate will take up McCain-Feingold, which could only
muster the support of 52 senators last spring, eight short of the
60 needed to break filibuster tactics. And time is tight: on
vacation until September, senators will return for just one month,
before leaving town in early October for the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   If ever approved by both chambers, President Clinton has vowed
to sign Shays-Meehan. It would end the soft money contributions by
unions, corporations and other special interests to the political
parties, which have been at the center of investigations into
illegal donations to the Democrats in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The freshmen bill allowed for soft money donations to state
parties, something opponents said would result in a mere shift of
big money from party headquarters in Washington to state parties in
places like Augusta. ``It is well intended,'' Shays said. ``But it
is also a gigantic loophole.''
</P>
<P>
   Shays-Meehan also banned independent groups from airing attack
ads against candidates within 60 days of an election, something
Allen and Hutchinson called constitutionally questionable as a
limit on 1st Amendment rights.
</P>
<P>
   Allen contended his bill would prohibit candidates for federal
office from raising soft money for their state parties, eliminating
the biggest problem soft money presents -- lawmakers who do favors
for the biggest of the big donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is real reform. That is a real soft money ban,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But even some freshmen campaign task force members backed away
from Allen's bill, voting present to support Shays-Meehan. ``Not
because (Allen's bill) represents artificial reform, as some on
both sides of the aisle have suggested,'' said Rep. Harold Ford,
D-Tenn., ``but because it has become a tool (of reform
opponents).''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past nine weeks of debate on campaign finance, the
House voted on eight different plans. With 147 ``yes'' votes and 61
``present'' votes, Allen's bill easily received the second most
votes of any plan.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
