<P>
   THE ANDAMAN SEA _ The journey promised adventure, but we didn't
know the half of it. The idea of sailing through waters off the
coast of Myanmar _ formerly known as Burma, and shut off from the
outside world for the past half-century _ seduced nine intrepid
travelers who had previously done plenty of exploring in exotic
places. Here was a chance to investigate a tiny part of the world
inhabited only by sea gypsies and by wild monkeys and other
assorted beasts, a section of Southeast Asia that was last
effectively documented when European traders came from India to
explore the famous Silk Road. So, in October, when we boarded the
trimaran appropriately named the Wanderlust, we were among the
first 100 Westerners to take such a voyage since Burmese officials
opened their part of the Andaman Sea _ in the easternmost Indian
Ocean _ to outsiders late in 1996. By JUNE NAYLOR RODRIGUEZ. Story
