<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GADJO-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBRACING THE GYPSY CURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at the end of review.) 
(js) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget yoga, tai chi, psychotherapy and monastery vacations. The
antidote for the quiet desperation and alienation of contemporary
urban lives is much simpler: become a Gypsy. Gypsies are wacky,
fun-loving and hard-drinking; they have a hearty appetite for sex,
a visceral connection with music and a real sense of community. The
women bathe in pairs with flowers in their hair. What's more, the
men can do shoe repair.
</P>
<P>
   At least that seems to be the message of ``Gadjo Dilo,'' the
third in Tony Gatlif's Gypsy trilogy. In 1994, Gatlif wrote and
directed ``Latcho Drom,'' sort of a musical travelogue of Gypsy
culture. Last year, in ``Mondo,'' he told the story of a homeless
Gypsy boy in France.
</P>
<P>
   His intriguing, skillfully made new film is in love with its
subjects. ``Gadjo Dilo'' opens with a shot of Stephane (Romain
Duris) walking, in shoes that are coming apart, in the middle of a
desolate road covered with snow and ice. When he finally reaches a
building with lights on, it's locked. He's soon joined by a very
drunk man shouting: ``May I die! May I rot!'' and lamenting the
injustice of his son having just been sent to prison.
</P>
<P>
   Against his better judgment, Stephane accepts the man's offer of
a place to sleep. The next morning, two little boys scream with a
combination of terror and pleasure, ``There's a great big gadjo
sleeping at our place!'' Gadjo, in the Gypsies' Romany language,
means outsider. Dilo, as in the film's title, means crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Stephane, a sophisticated Parisian, has a good reason for being
here. To honor his dead father, he has come to locate the father's
favorite singer and record her for posterity. Needless to say, he
does not immediately make contact with her but finds himself drawn
into an exotic new lifestyle instead.
</P>
<P>
   Izidor (Isidor Serban), his host, is horrified when Stephane
tries to spruce up the place. ``Aren't you ashamed of yourself for
cleaning my house?'' he asks. Two women, observing Stephane's
dusting and sweeping, conclude that he's gay.
</P>
<P>
   Sabina (Rona Hartner), the village's fallen woman (for some
reason connected with a stay in Belgium), is pretty sure he's not.
Her idea of letting him know she doesn't want his attentions is to
bite his hand, then raise her skirts revealing her bare bottom to
him. Despite that initial lack of interest, Stephane is soon making
love to her hungrily. He is also dancing in a near-trance in
Bucharest, drinking vodka and crying out: ``May I die! May I rot!''
Just as it's time for him to go back to Paris, tragedy strikes the
Gypsies. The question is whether Stephane will stay in this
new-found but misunderstood utopia or return to the world he knows.
</P>
<P>
   Gatlif, who wrote and directed the film, and Eric Guichard, his
cinematographer, have done well. The film contains gorgeous shots
of the forest blanketed in snow, heartwarming and hysterical
wedding scenes and a moment of inspired silent-film-style humor
when a man tries to get his double bass past a clothesline.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   GADJO DILO
</P>
<P>
   Written (in French, Romanian and Romany, with English subtitles)
and directed by Tony Gatlif; director of photography, Eric
Guichard; edited by Monique Dartonne; music by Gatlif; produced by
Doru Mitran; released by Lions Gate Films. Running time: 97
minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Romain Duris (Stephane), Rona Hartner (Sabina) and Isidor
Serban (Izidor).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
