<HEADLINE>
TEXAS AUDIT WARNS OF POTENTIAL DPS PROBLEMS BECAUSE OF 2000 YEAR
GLITCH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Millions of public safety and crime records are
at risk because the Texas Department of Public Safety has been slow
to address potential year 2000 computer glitches, the state auditor
warns.
</P>
<P>
   The auditor's office, in a report issued this week, concluded
that the computer problem and several other management weaknesses
``challenge the department's ability to provide efficient and
effective public safety.''
</P>
<P>
   The report noted that DPS, whose management has been criticized
in previous audits, hasn't conducted a comprehensive review of its
own organizational structure in more than 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Other state agencies as well as governments and businesses
around the world are scrambling to solve the year 2000 computer
problem. It is the result of most computer programs recognizing
years by only the final two digits. That is, the year 2000 could be
recognized by computers as 1900.
</P>
<P>
   At stake in the DPS computer system are criminal histories,
drivers license records, accident reports and other information
routinely needed each day by law enforcement officers, insurance
companies, employers and private citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The DPS, in a formal response to the report, said it plans to
complete by the end of the year a contingency plan for dealing with
possible service interruptions.
</P>
<P>
   Agency spokesman Mike Cox said the agency also has signed a
contract with an outside vendor for correcting any potential
glitches in the agency's mainframe systems. Cox said that work,
which should protect most agency records, is to be completed within
15 months and within DPS' budget.
</P>
<P>
   The auditor said DPS' potential computer problem has been
compounded by employee turnover _ in part because of low salaries
for agency computer specialists _ and by waiting too long to
address the issue.
</P>
<P>
   According to the auditor, DPS received information on possible
year 2000 computer glitches more than 30 months ago from the
Department of Information Resources. Then in January, that
department issued a warning that changes to the DPS computer system
``may not be completed in time to avoid disruption in some of the
DPS functions that are critical to Texas state government.''
</P>
<P>
   But DPS didn't complete an inventory of its automation systems
until May of this year, which hampered planning.
</P>
<P>
   The audit also noted that cost estimates for correcting DPS'
computer problems _ as high as $20 million to $40 million _ far
exceed the agency's available funding of $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
