<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-FAA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENCY ASSURES CONGRESS AIR TRAFFIC WILL BE SAFE ON JAN. 1, 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Federal Aviation Administration official told
Congress Thursday that top FAA officials will fly coast-to-coast on
Jan. 1, 2000, to show that the computer-driven air traffic control
system hasn't been made unsafe by Year 2000 computer problems.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Long, director of the FAA's Year 2000 program, assured the
House committee on technology that the agency will be fully and
safely operational when Dec. 31, 1999, arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Both Long and FAA administrator Jane Garvey will fly from the
East Coast to the West Coast on New Year's Day, 2000, starting at
midnight, Long told the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a demonstration of our confidence in the system,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   As the year 2000 closes in, agencies and companies alike have
been scrambling to fix computers that were originally programmed to
recognize only the last two digits of a year, as in ``99'' for the
year 1999. Some computers are expected to fail or malfunction on
Jan. 1, 2000, when the machines might assume it is 1900.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Willemssen, the General Accounting Office's director of
civil agencies information systems, told the subcommittee there was
a chance that the FAA wouldn't be fully operational on Dec. 31,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA hasn't done enough to assure the GAO that all FAA-linked
computers, such as national air traffic control, have fixed the
Year 2000 glitch, also known as Y2K, Willemssen said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the FAA fixes the Y2K problem in its main computer
systems, separate systems that link the ``mission-critical''
computers to one another may still have Y2K programming problems,
according to Willemssen. ``Critical systems may fail,'' he added,
if the glitch is not repaired in all the linking systems, which
keep air traffic control information flowing.
</P>
<P>
   As of July 31, the FAA had not accounted for all of the
interfaces that hook up the agency's computers, he said. FAA plans
to fix the Y2K problem by next June 30 are overly optimistic,
Willemssen said.
</P>
<P>
   He cited an FAA official who said making one modification to a
computer system can take from four weeks to six weeks to test and
implement.
</P>
<P>
   Falling behind schedule in fixing the problem ``could affect
hundreds of thousands of people,'' he said. ``This is a tremendous
challenge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
