<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-POPULATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISPANIC POPULATION NEARS 30 MILLION; EXPECTED TO TRIPLE BY 2050 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: For release at 12:01 a.m. Friday, Aug. 7)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fueled by immigration and higher birth rates, the
number of Hispanics living in the United States grew to nearly 30
million in 1997, a trend that is projected to triple their
population by 2050, according to a Census Bureau report released
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics now make up 11 percent of the U.S. population, up from
9 percent in 1990, according to Census Bureau statistics. The
bureau projects that number will jump to 25 percent by 2050, when
the Hispanic population is expected to reach 96.5 million _ more
than 10 times its number in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel de la Puente, chief of the ethnic and Hispanic statistics
branch of the U.S. Census Bureau, said immigration from Mexico and
Central American countries is the main impetus for the steep rise
in Hispanics in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at where immigrants to the United States are
coming from, there has been a complete reversal from the turn of
the century when the vast majority of immigrants came from Europe
and only a few came from Mexico, Central America and Asia,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1900, 98 percent of immigrants came from Europe. By 1990, the
percentage of immigrants from Europe fell to 26 percent, while the
percentage of immigrants from Spanish-speaking countries grew to 43
percent. Immigrants from Asian countries also increased to 25
percent of the 1990 total.
</P>
<P>
   According to the new Census report, fewer than half, 44 percent,
of the current Latino population was born outside the United
States. For the country as a whole, 9.7 percent of the population
is foreign-born.
</P>
<P>
   De la Puente added that a higher birth rate among Hispanics also
has contributed to their rising numbers. ``Since immigrants tend to
be younger than the population as whole, they also tend to have
more children,'' he said. About a third _ 35.7 percent _ of
Hispanics were under 18 last year, the report showed.
</P>
<P>
   De la Puente said Hispanics are expected to outnumber blacks by
2005, which would make them the country's largest minority group.
Earlier this year, the number of Hispanic school children for the
first time was larger than the number of black school children.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau report also said that Hispanics continue to
get married and stay married in higher numbers than the overall
population. Nearly seven of every 10 Hispanic families (68.2
percent) consisted of married couples in 1997. The number of
non-Hispanic white families who were married couples in 1997 was
about 60 percent. The comparable number for black families was 42
percent and for Asian families, 62 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``From all of our numbers, Hispanics appear to be very
family-oriented people,'' de la Puente said.
</P>
<P>
   The report also noted that more than a quarter of Hispanic
families in the United States (26.4 percent) were living below the
poverty line in 1996, compared with 14 percent for the overall U.S.
population.
</P>
<P>
   The study said the Hispanic jobless rate in 1997 was 9.2
percent. For the entire population, the rate was 4.9 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1731EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
