<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Aug. 7, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Weather changes will be slow over most of the nation as weak
winds at high levels persist. Cool and unsettled conditions will
linger over much of the Mississippi Valley and Great Lakes, while
high pressure keeps most of the East warm with little rain. The
interior West will stay mainly sunny and very warm.
</P>
<P>
   Slow-moving showers and a few thunderstorms will surround a
sluggish low pressure center over southern Minnesota. Rather cloudy
and cool conditions with generally light showers will occur from
the southern Missouri Valley to the western Great Lakes. Recurrent
showers will produce locally heavy rain in the sultry air from the
southern Great Lakes to the Ohio and Tennessee Valleys, although
some dim sunshine will alternate with the rain.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the Northeast will have another day with ample sunshine.
Humidity will gradually increase, especially near the west slopes
of the Appalachians and at the coast. Clouds and some showers will
occur over the mountains of New England.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Southeast will be seasonably warm and humid.
Cloudiness will prevail near the Carolina coast as clusters of
offshore thundershowers drift near the region. Strong thunderstorms
will be scattered over Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures will remain below the seasonal average over the
southern Plains. A few heavy showers will linger over eastern
Texas, but little rain will fall elsewhere in the Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the West will be dry. However, a few strong
thunderstorms will form near a front in the northern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Dry Brownsville
</P>
<P>
   Since March 17, measurable rain has fallen at Brownsville,
Texas, on only four days, with 0.17 inches the greatest daily
rainfall. From March 17 to August 5, a time when rates of
evaporation of surface water increase and rain becomes crucial,
only 0.35 inches of rain have been measured. The town's average
rainfall for the period is 9.67 inches. Though located close to the
tepid waters of the Gulf of Mexico, Brownsville is modestly moist,
with an annual average of 27 inches. Like dry Brownsville, most of
south Texas has received less than a half an inch of rain from
April through July.
</P>
</TEXT>
