<SLUG> BC-HISPANICS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HISPANIC POPULATION NEARS 30 MILLION
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Hispanic population in the United States is
nearing 30 million and growing at a rate that may help it eclipse
African Americans sooner than anticipated as the nation's largest
minority group, the U.S. Census Bureau reported Friday(cq).
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics totaled 29.7 million in 1997, about 11 percent of the
U.S. population, according to the report. African Americans
numbered 34.2 million in 1997, or 12.8 percent of the population,
according to a Census Bureau report released a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Demographic experts have predicted in recent years that the
Hispanic population would exceed the African American population in
the year 2005. But the new figures suggest that could occur as soon
as the 2000 census _ partly depending on whether Republicans in
Congress allow the use of statistical sampling techniques to
compensate for undercounting of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've maintained all along that Hispanics have been
undercounted by the Census Bureau,'' said Lisa Navarrete,
spokeswoman for the National Council of La Raza, the nation's
largest Hispanic advocacy group. ``We think that will be clear
after the 2000 census.''
</P>
<P>
   John Reed, a Census Bureau analyst, said the latest population
figures ``do not surprise us.'' He noted, for instance, that the
Census Bureau reported last month that the number of Hispanic
children in this country surpassed the number of African American
children.
</P>
<P>
   Today's report also revealed that within the Hispanic
population:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Slightly more than half, 55.8 percent, were born in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  About 68 percent of families were married-couple families.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  About a third, 35.7 percent, were under 18 years of age.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nearly a fourth, 24 percent, work in technical, sales and
administrative support positions.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Census Bureau data reflect the continuing effects of
immigration. A decade ago, more than 62 percent of Hispanics in the
United States were U.S.-born, a percentage that continues to
decline.
</P>
<P>
   But Sonia Perez, the chief demographic researcher for La Raza,
noted that two-thirds of the Hispanics under the age of 18 were
born in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a very young population,'' she said. ``And it's in the
interest of the country to be developing these young people and
making sure they have the opportunities they need to be successful,
not just for our community, but because it has implications for the
whole country.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
