<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-BEACHES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATER TESTING PLAN MAY GET TEXAS OFF OF `BEACH BUM' LIST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KEVIN MORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ A plan to monitor water quality at popular
beaches could get Texas off of a national environmental
organization's list of places where swimmers aren't adequately
warned of health threats.
</P>
<P>
   Such a program is a ``good step,'' to getting off the Natural
Resources Defense Council's ``beach bum'' list, council spokeswoman
Sarah Chasis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The questions we would ask Texas is whether they have
comprehensive monitoring of beach water safety and whether they
alert the public when the monitoring shows that health standards
are exceeded,'' Chasis said. ``Another question would be what
health standards they are using.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Texas General Land Commissioner and Democratic
gubernatorial candidate Garry Mauro said the General Land Office is
beginning a program to monitor water quality at the state's 10
busiest beach areas five times a month.
</P>
<P>
   Results of the tests, which will look for bacteria from human
and animal wastes and other germs that can cause illness to exposed
swimmers, will be turned over to the Texas Department of Health and
the Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission, Mauro said.
</P>
<P>
   Chasis said the Natural Resources Defense Council is pleased at
Mauro's reaction to the council's July placement of Texas on a list
of states that fail to test beach areas for health safety.
</P>
<P>
   Critical to Texas improving its ratings in the environmental
group's 1999 national study of beach safety will be how quickly
officials manage to warn swimmers of potential health hazards,
Chasis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The faster the turnaround, the better, because then you can
alert people at a time when the threat is still present,'' Chasis
said. ``There are places that have a 24-hour turnaround.''
</P>
<P>
   Natural Resources Defense Council executive director Alan
Metrick confirmed that Texas ended up on the ``beach bum'' list
mainly because it lacks any comprehensive water testing program.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro maintained that the state does not have sewage pollution
problems like those in many other parts of the country, in part
because strong currents along the coast help keep waters clean. The
Natural Resources Defense Council noted that most sewage pollution
occurs in Texas bays rather than along barrier island island
recreational beaches.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
