<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1586 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-06 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE IS UNFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It is standard practice to justify Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr's relentless pursuit of President Clinton and
the Supreme Court's whittling down of his executive powers as
necessary to prove that not even a president is above the law.
</P>
<P>
   Fine. Clinton himself would certainly agree that this is a
democracy, under which all men and women are supposed to be treated
equally in the eyes of the law.
</P>
<P>
   So why, then, do we tolerate the legal favoritism that benefits
members of Congress, who may ultimately be asked to sit in judgment
of the president? We won't permit the president to be above the
law, but we allow Congress that rarefied status.
</P>
<P>
   This double standard is in part the fault of the Constitution,
which confers on members of Congress limited immunity from civil or
criminal action stemming from the performance of their legislative
duties. The idea is to protect legislators from potential punitive
executive or judicial action meant to intimidate them.
</P>
<P>
   It apparently did not occur to the Founding Fathers that the
executive branch might need safeguards against excessive political
intimidation as well. But they were operating long before Congress
created the abomination that the special counsel's office has
become.
</P>
<P>
   The Founders were thinking of the unhappy period in 16th and
17th century English history during which the Tudor and Stuart
monarchs hassled unsympathetic members of Parliament by hauling
them into court. To prevent a similar development in America, they
inserted the speech and debate clause in their great document to
reinforce the separation of powers among the three governmental
branches.
</P>
<P>
   Article I, Section 6 declares that members of Congress ``for any
speech or debate in either house ... shall not be questioned in any
other place.'' The Supreme Court has traditionally interpreted this
to mean members cannot be sued for inaccurate or libelous
statements made in debate on the floor of the respective chambers
or for views expressed during committee deliberations. The high
bench has also included congressional staffers under this
protection.
</P>
<P>
   The court, however, ruled in 1979 that freedom from liability
does not extend to statements made in press releases and
newsletters, which the court did not consider an integral part of
the congressional deliberative process. And while a legal inquiry
into the motivation for performing any legislative act is
protected, a probe is deemed okay if it looks into a specific
accusation of bribery rather than the legislative objective the
bribe was intended to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   This partial congressional immunity from legal liability
reflects the wise doctrine of separation of powers that was missing
when the Supreme Court ruled last year that a sitting president can
be sued in a private civil action. The court allowed the Paula
Jones sexual harassment suit to go ahead on the weird notion that
it would not interfere with Clinton's ability to govern the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The high bench was ridiculously wrong. For this stupidity, the
president and the country are paying a heavy price.
</P>
<P>
   But Congress has not been content to merely enjoy its
constitutional advantage. Our esteemed legislators have a habit of
helping themselves to other privileges that set them apart from the
rules that govern other mortals.
</P>
<P>
   Congress exempts itself, for instance, from the independent
counsel statute, which is written to initiate probes of potential
wrongdoing only in the executive branch. The appointment of an
outside investigator was meant to prevent a conflict of interest
that might result from a Justice Department investigation of fellow
Cabinet members or the president himself.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Congress is oblivious to its own conflicts of interest. It
insists that members suspected of ethical violations be handled
in-house by a committee of their peers. This is often a painful
process, hobbled by secrecy, delay and partisan pressure. Most
members view assignment to the House and Senate ethics committees
as akin to getting the plague.
</P>
<P>
   Only three years ago, Congress finally got around to obeying 11
federal labor and anti-discrimination laws that it had imposed on
the rest of the country. House Republicans had pledged in their
1994 ``Contract With America'' to apply all laws equally to
Congress, ending the broad workplace exemption that members had
granted themselves for decades. The Republicans kept their word
when they took control of Congress in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is also fond of special perks, which are not available
to ordinary Americans. One of the most irritating is that members
of Congress enjoy free reserved parking slots at Ronald Reagan
National and Dulles International Airports here, while other fliers
must hunt for spaces in the overcrowded the parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, however, members did give up the longtime
practice of having their city parking tickets fixed. How generous
of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
