<P>
   RENO _ A House committee voted 24-19 to cite Attorney General
Janet Reno for contempt of Congress for failing to turn over
reports recommending that she seek an independent counsel to probe
campaign fund-raising abuses. All Republicans supported it; all
Democrats, plus independent Bernie Sanders, were opposed. (Carr,
Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   MONICA-BEACH _ WASHINGTON _ Media frenzy on the streets of the
capital is expected to reach its zenith Thursday as Monica Lewinsky
arrives at the federal courthouse to testify before independent
counsel Kenneth Starr's grand jury. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   w/MONICA-TV _The crush to capture Monica Lewisky's every move.
(Jubera, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POLMONEY-HOUSE _ WASHINGTON _ Final approval or defeat is
expected in the House on Thursday for a bipartisan campaign finance
bill that would bar unlimited ``soft money'' gifts to parties and
restrict independent ``issue advertising.'' How the unlikely
victory was achieved and the outlook in the Senate. (Mollison, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   TECH-VISAS _ WASHINGTON _ House leaders decided Thursday to
delay consideration of a bill to increase the number of visas for
tech workers and other highly skilled foreigners. The move was
partly due to maneuverings by Democrats who insist on protections
for American workers. (Harlan, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANICS _ WASHINGTON - The Hispanic population in the United
States is nearing 30 million, or almost 11 percent of the total, a
trend that puts them well on their way to becoming the nation's
largest ethnic group, according to the latest report from the
Census Bureau. The report also shows that more than half were born
in the United States, raising questions about the practice of
viewing Hispanics as an immigrant population. (Shepard, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-FRAUD _ WASHINGTON _ Rep. Clay Shaw, R-Fla., and other
members of Congress issue a report touting the success of a program
that pays cash rewards to state and local jailers who help remove
inmates from the welfare rolls. (Shook, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-CHIMPS _ WASHINGTON _ The Air Force announces the
recipients of its chimpanzee divestiture effort at a Department of
Defense briefing on Thursday. The divestiture provides for the
continued care of the Air Force chimps used in research related to
the space program. (Montgomery, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   PFISTERIA _ WASHINGTON _ White House chief of staff Erskine
Bowles, EPA administrator Carol Browner and other federal and North
Carolina officials describe the outlook for new outbreaks this
summer of pfisteria and other harmful organisms along U.S. coasts.
(Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH _ Advance story on Newt Gingrich's trip to Ireland,
starting Saturday. (Sherman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-HEAT-DEATHS _ Checking for folo on prison deaths. Convict
family members reportedly are upset, poised for lawsuit or
something. Also checking on pending lawsuit concerning
heat-releated prison death in 1995. (Ward, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   DEADPET _ GREENSBORO, N.C. _ Guilford County Sheriff BJ Barnes
has decided to broadcast on the county's local access channel dogs
being put to sleep at the animal shelter as a deterrent to people
mistreating their pets. The first broadcast is Friday. It's caused
a national stir with people on both sides of the argument of
whether it's sensational or wise to publicize death of dogs and
cats. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   YAGER _ ATLANTA _ Faye Yager and husband Howard are the subjects
of a hearing in federal court Thursday. A Connecticut man has sued
the Yagers for hiding his son in their ``underground'' of allegedly
abused children. Hearing is for temporary restraining order to halt
the Yager's ``organized lawlessness'' and have them tell Jeffery
Rubenstein where he can find his son. Rubenstein was awarded
custody of the boy and through lengthy divorce and custody fights
there was never any claims he abused the boy. Bonnie Rubenstein
first made claims of abuse when she came to see Faye Yager.
(Williams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-MAURO _ Democratic gubernatorial nominee Garry Mauro
believes he has much greater Hispanic support than polls show.
(Herman, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-ROAST _ AUSTIN, Texas _ While most students are stocking
up on school supplies, Austin school bus driver Ida Collins is
freezing bottles of water in preparation for the first day of
school. Local meteorologists say it probably won't cool off until
September. Until then, students will trudge to and from school
beneath blazing skies, swelter on school buses without air
conditioning and sweat their way through outdoor athletic
practices. (Alford, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
