<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1600 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3TAKE     08-06 1354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECOMMENDED AND NOTEWORTHY MOVIES  
 (JT)  
 &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The Times of new or
noteworthy movies playing this weekend. Ratings and running times
are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``ARMAGEDDON,''  &LR;  starring Bruce Willis, Ben Affleck, Liv Tyler
and Steve Buscemi. Directed by Michael Bay (PG-13, 144 minutes).
This big, showy, spirit-crushing summer extravaganza includes not a
single heartfelt moment, unless you count its sequence set in a
strip club. Imminent doom (courtesy of an approaching asteroid)
becomes the excuse for rampant flag-waving, gung-ho patriotism and
a notion of heroism that has nothing whatever to do with real
courage. Willis gets the film's noblest lines for the same reason
that he probably got the set's biggest trailer. Affleck tries
gamely to seem mad about Ms. Tyler, who serves as window-dressing
at NASA headquarters. Totally predictable elements _ loud noises,
frequent explosions and bright computer-screen colors _ seem as
inevitable and deadly as the asteroid while they create the
illusion of escapist fun (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``BASEKETBALL,''  &LR;  starring Trey Parker and Matt Stone.
Directed by David Zucker &UR;  &LR; (R, 105 minutes). In David Zucker's
funny, gross-out spoof of professional sports, Parker and Stone are
two hapless post-adolescent dudes (the latest variation on Wayne
and Garth) who invent a silly driveway hybrid of basketball and
baseball that becomes a national obsession. The film is essentially
two movies stuck together. One is a dumber-than-dumb teen-age
comedy crammed with farcical sight gags and raunchy adolescent
humor. The other is a no-holds-barred satire of professional sports
and the greed, egotism and pomposity surrounding them. As in his
``Naked Gun'' series, Zucker's comic strategy is to fire off a
machine-gun volley of jokes of all shapes and sizes, trusting that
enough will land to keep the audience on the edge of a giggle
(Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``DR. DOLITTLE,''  &LR; starring Eddie Murphy. Directed by Betty
Thomas (PG-13, 85 minutes). When this Dr. Dolittle talks to the
animals, they pile on the back talk, thanks to the stellar cast of
vocal talent (Ellen DeGeneres, Garry Shandling, Paul Reubens, John
Leguizamo) that keeps the wisecracks flying. And Murphy plays
straight man with hilarious aplomb. This good-humored family film
is formulaic but steadily funny (and a lot less corrosive than
``The Nutty Professor''), thanks not only to Murphy's understated
timing but also to expertly computer-enhanced performances from the
animal cast (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``EVER AFTER: A CINDERELLA STORY,''  &LR; starring Drew Barrymore,
Anjelica Huston, and Dougray Scott. Directed by Andy Tennant
(PG-13, 120 minutes). The clever notion of reinventing Cinderella
as a self-motivated powerhouse who doesn't need a fairy godmother
to get ahead has been reduced into a bland mishmash of comedy and
soap opera. Drew Barrymore is appealing as Danielle, a plucky,
resourceful, slightly tomboyish 16th-century French girl who knows
how to stand up for herself. But her wimpish prince (Scott) isn't
much of a prize to crow over. And why is Leonardo da Vinci (Patrick
Godfrey) traipsing around France with the ``Mona Lisa'' under his
arm, giving advice to the lovelorn? The most orthodox refugee from
the standard fairy tale is Anjelica Huston's haughty stepmother
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``EVEREST,''  &LR; directed by David Brashears with Greg
MacGillivray (not rated; 45 minutes). If life in New York City
doesn't provide enough in the way of thrills, those in search of a
vicarious near-death experience can make their way to the Sony Imax
Theater at Lincoln Square (1998 Broadway, at 68th Street) for a go
at ``Everest.'' There, images of the world's highest mountain _
29,028 feet _ find a frame worthy of the peak's spectacular, lethal
beauty: the 8-story-high, 100-foot-wide screen. This account
focuses mainly on the efforts of three people to scale the peak in
1996 despite yawning chasms of ever-shifting ice, thundering
avalanches, the perils of air so thin that it addles the brain, and
sudden, blinding storms. While this expedition was on the mountain,
as many articles and books were later to relate, other teams made
their way into the so-called death zone, at 25,000 feet, where a
violent storm overtook them. Eight people perished in the worst
single disaster on the mountain. ``Everest'' makes it possible for
armchair adventurers to share the risks and glory of the team's
climb toward heaven (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE GOVERNESS,''  &LR;  starring Minnie Driver and Tom Wilkinson.
Directed by Sandra Goldbacher (R, 114 minutes). It is the early
1840's, and Rosina (Minnie Driver), a headstrong young Sephardic
Jewish woman living in London, poses as a Gentile to get a job as a
governess for the Cavendish family on a remote Scottish island.
Falling in love with the skittish, devoutly Christian head of the
household (Tom Wilkinson), a gentleman inventor with whom she has a
stormy affair, she becomes his collaborator in the invention of
photography. The ravishingly handsome film works on several levels:
as a proto-feminist fable, a meditation on still photography and
its relation to real life, and a portrait of lovers whose religious
difference becomes an unbridgeable emotional gap. Ms. Driver holds
the picture with a solid performance that falls short of great
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``HENRY FOOL,''  &LR;  starring Thomas Jay Ryan, James Urbaniak and
Parker Posey. Directed by Hal Hartley (R, 138 minutes). The
affectless precision of this filmmaker's previous work is
absolutely no preparation for the brilliance and deep resonance of
this contemporary parable. Without forsaking the clean, spare look
and hyperreal clarity that are his trademarks, Hartley moves into a
much larger realm with a meditation on, among other things, art,
trust, loyalty, politics and popular culture. When Henry Fool (
Ryan) bursts mysteriously into the thankless life of Simon Grim (
Urbaniak) and urges this silent garbage man to start writing, the
results are strange and sublime. Ms. Posey plays Simon's slatternly
sister with nonchalant wit in one of her best roles. A few
glaringly scatological touches don't detract from the film's
elegance of vision (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``HIGH ART,''  &LR;  starring Ally Sheedy and Radha Mitchell.
Directed by Lisa Cholodenko (R, 96 minutes). Ms. Sheedy gives a
fierce, tricky performance in the role of a once-celebrated
photographer, spooked by fame, who long ago retreated from the art
world to live a reclusive, druggy life among lesbian friends. This
steamily intense story follows her spider-fly relationship with Ms.
Mitchell's bright-eyed, ambitious ingenue, who works for a
desperately stylish photography magazine. Ms. Cholodenko's
seductive, powerfully atmospheric first feature explores their
relationship with intelligence and avidity. But it sacrifices any
hope of raw edges and real emotion to its own chic sensibility,
which proves so studiously alluring that it overwhelms the story.
Patricia Clarkson does a scene-stealing turn as Ms. Sheedy's lover,
a glamorously decadent German actress who never got past the
Fassbinder years (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``LETHAL WEAPON 4,''  &LR; starring Mel Gibson, Danny Glover and
Rene Russo. Directed by Richard Donner (R, 125 minutes). In the
full perspective-warping heat of the summer movie season, this
turns out to be one of the nicer blow-'em-ups around. The
characters are funny and likable, and they all live on earth. The
formula still has some zip. The stars, with the welcome new
addition of Chris Rock as a young detective who has literally
married into the ``Lethal Weapon'' family, play their roles with
breezy finesse. And the story, about slave smuggling and Chinese
gangsters, is a flamboyant, fight-filled adventure fueled by
kidding camaraderie and constant forward motion. Bear in mind that
this is still a film whose idea of high drama is watching a car get
pushed in front of an oncoming train (Maslin).
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``MAFIA!,''  &LR; starring Jay Mohr, Lloyd Bridges and Christina
Applegate. Directed by Jim Abrahams (PG-13, 86 minutes). This
sendup makes an offer you could probably refuse, but its
Mad-magazine-style hit-or-miss humor works well enough to be
reasonably bright. It's true, though, that a Mafia movie satire
without a single horse's head in a bed and without anyone who
sounds like Joe Pesci has left a few stones unturned. Concentrating
mostly on the ``Godfather'' films and ``Casino,'' Abrahams throws
in anything from canned meatballs by Spalding to vomit gags. Lloyd
Bridges, to whose memory the film is dedicated, has the role of a
dapper don and shows one last time how sporting and debonair he
could be (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE MASK OF ZORRO,''  &LR; starring Antonio Banderas, Anthony
Hopkins and Catherine Zeta-Jones. Directed by Martin Campbell
(PG-13, 130 minutes). Travel back to the days when swashbuckling
was serious business, when boyish adventure films still had their
innocence and when the bravado of thrilling stunt work was all a
movie needed in the way of special effects. Hopkins is marvelously
game as the film's dashing senior Zorro. Banderas was born to play
the aging hero's jokey, hotblooded protege. And he meets his match
in the story's heroine, whose beauty is inevitably described as
``beyond compare.'' This robust old-fashioned adventure should
appeal to older children, but beware of a few needlessly grisly
touches (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``MULAN,''  &LR;  with the voices of Ming-Na Wen, Eddie Murphy and
B.D. Wong. Directed by Barry Cook and Tony Bancroft (G, 86
minutes). Disney takes a sledgehammer to the subject of gender
stereotyping in this film, which not only breaks the cross-dressing
barrier but also ratchets up the violence level for children's
animation. This is the most inert and formulaic of recent Disney
animated films, right down to the clowning sidekicks, would-be
``Under the Sea'' production number and Destiny ballad from the
intrepid heroine (``When will my reflection show who I am
inside?''). Murphy's very funny wisecracks make the character of a
little dragon entertaining, but this black-sounding character is
also treated as a servile clown. The animation mimics live-action
crowd scenes more often than it takes audiences to the realm of the
imagination (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE NEGOTIATOR,''  &LR; starring Samuel L. Jackson and Kevin
Spacey. Directed by F. Gary Gray (R, 115 minutes). In a twist on
the Hitchcockian maxim, this thriller takes two extraordinary
actors and places them in surprisingly ordinary circumstances. In a
film whose title should have been plural, both stars play seasoned
hostage negotiators who are caught up in a by-the-numbers battle of
wits. Amazingly, both these shrewd, maverick actors are cast as
nice guys, team players and clean-cut family men. The movie's
brisk, familiar look of a police story, heavy with close-ups, that
escalates to a paramilitary operation will look right at home when
it comes to the video screen (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``NIGHTS OF CABIRIA,''  &LR; starring Giulietta Masina. Directed by
Federico Fellini (not rated, 117 minutes). Anyone dismayed by the
hyperkinetic emptiness of summertime film spectacles will find the
antidote in this 1957 Fellini masterpiece. It has been refurbished
and revived by the same team that brought back ``Contempt'' last
year, and they display the same acumen in reissuing a film of
special prescience; though it was shot in black and white amid the
poverty of postwar Italy, neither the style nor the searching of
``Cabiria' has grown dated at all. In a prize-winning and
heartbreaking performance, the star plays a scrappy Roman
streetwalker who drifts almost magically among the film's
astonishingly varied realms. There is more grace and courage in the
famous image of Masina smiling through her tears than in all the
fire-breathing blockbusters Hollywood has to offer (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE OPPOSITE OF SEX,''  &LR; starring Christina Ricci, Martin
Donovan, Lisa Kudrow and Lyle Lovett. Directed by Don Roos (R, 100
minutes). Wicked, foulmouthed and very funny, this gleefully
acerbic comedy finds that Ms. Ricci has morphed enchantingly from
nasty little Wednesday of ``The Addams Family'' into Lolita's evil
twin. Voluptuous and scheming, her poisonous Dedee narrates this
film and announces immediately that she won't be developing a heart
of gold. Which is, of course, mostly a lie. The film brutally
skewers preconceptions about gay and straight life, then lets its
characters intermingle in sweetly unexpected ways. Donovan and Ms.
Kudrow, as unlikely comrades brought together by Dedee's treachery,
deliver the zingers from Roos' screenplay with deadpan panache
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``OUT OF SIGHT,''  &LR; starring George Clooney and Jennifer Lopez.
Directed by Steven Soderbergh (R, 120 minutes). As directed with
terrific panache by Soderbergh in his most frankly commercial
effort, Clooney and Ms. Lopez take an intricate Elmore Leonard
crime tale and give it steam heat. Like ``Get Shorty,'' this story
has been adapted from a Leonard novel by Scott Frank, who knows
exactly how to capture the writer's shrewd, hard-boiled style on
screen. An outstanding supporting cast _ including Don Cheadle,
Dennis Farina and Albert Brooks _ provides the movie with a vivid
rogues' gallery and remains good fun even when the story is
occasionally confusing. To fill in the blanks, go back to Leonard's
version; there are certainly worse ways to spend a summer afternoon
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE PARENT TRAP,''  &LR; starring Lindsay Lohan, Natasha
Richardson and Dennis Quaid. Directed by Nancy Meyers and written
by David Swift, Ms. Meyers and Charles Shyer (PG, 128 minutes). A
super-cute remake of the old Hayley Mills hit, this time given a
privileged shelter-magazine gloss by the ``Father of the Bride''
team of Ms. Meyers and Shyer. Ms. Richardson and Quaid beam
appealingly as parents who somehow managed to separate their twins
at birth without a twinge of guilt, and who seem to have spent all
of the intervening 11{ years shopping. In her dual role as English
and American sisters (one lives in a grand London town house, the
other on a big Napa Valley vineyard; nobody lives in a coal mine),
the spirited Ms. Lohan commandeers the movie as if she had been
taking shrinking-violet lessons from Sharon Stone (Maslin).
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
