<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CALLS DYING TEEN WHO BECAME U.S. CITIZEN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, touched by the story of
16-year-old Gimel Aguinaga's wish to become a U.S. citizen, called
the cancer-stricken Houston teen-ager Thursday to offer his best
wishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president called Gimel Aguinaga this afternoon at his
uncle's home and congratulated him on becoming a U.S. citizen,'' an
aide said. ``He told Gimel that he must be proud because his mother
and his sister also became citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   The aide said the two spoke for five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Aguinaga, a Nicaraguan immigrant, his mother and his 14-year-old
sister were sworn in as citizens Tuesday thanks to the Texas Gulf
Coast Make-a-Wish Foundation, which grants wishes to children with
life-threatening diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, contacted the Immigration and
Naturalization Service to help overcome a citizenship backlog that
has 2 million people on the waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his age, the youth could only become a U.S. citizen
if his mother did. His mother, Blanca Sunsin, who speaks very
little English, had to study a citizenship test _ given in English
_ of 10 questions or more about U.S. history and government.
</P>
<P>
   Aguinaga was diagnosed two years ago with bone cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president was thrilled. He also was very proud that this
young man chose citizenship as one of his last wishes,'' the aide
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
