A1622 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PARK-STATUES-ART-N     08-06 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PARK-STATUES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE-FAMOUS FACES WATCH OVER MADISON SQUARE PARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 Thomas Mallon's most recent book is the novel ``Dewey Defeats
Truman''  
 By THOMAS MALLON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When I come here these days, it's usually from
Connecticut, by way of Grand Central. The terminal's newly restored
ceiling, which played a crucial part in one of my novels, delights
the eye, but its sudden absence of grime brings to mind not so much
the ceiling's Beaux-Arts infancy as the spanking prosperity of
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Once arrived, I'm off to the Madison Avenue building of Conde
Nast, whose magazines will soon move to a Disneyfied Times Square;
or to the New York Public Library, where even the lions have been
wearing hard hats; or down to the Strand bookstore, two blocks
south of Union Square, whose continuing glamorization would give an
anarchist spasms.
</P>
<P>
   But every so often I need to go see my paperback publisher in
the Flatiron Building, situated where Fifth Avenue meets Broadway.
Those last five words sound like a marketer's dream slogan, a
one-two punch of wealth and dazzle, but they also define an actual
crossroads, the nexus that occurs at 23rd Street, these days a
relatively humble haven in a city undergoing too much gleaming
renovation.
</P>
<P>
   The Flatiron's northern offices look out on Madison Square Park,
whose six acres stretch east toward Madison Avenue and north to
26th Street. The men and women who walk here are an unassuming lot,
less the cell-phoned swells of the new Bryant Park than
nine-to-fivers needing a smoke. The benches still fill up with men
killing time and, however slowly, themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Despite reseeding, the grass remains patchy, and the officially
designated ``Squirrel House'' (a hollow dead tree) is ignored by
its intended guests, scavengers with no time for cute.
</P>
<P>
   But Madison Square Park also offers the visitor a small
perpetuation of New York between the mid-19th and early 20th
centuries, a long period when the state and the city supplied the
country with some of its grandest political personalities. Several
of ``my'' men, minor and major characters in the historical fiction
I've been writing, are frozen stiff here.
</P>
<P>
   Seated at the park's southwest entrance is William H. Seward,
New York's governor and U.S senator before being made secretary of
state by Abraham Lincoln, with whom he nearly died on April 14,
1865. He sits casually, legs crossed, looking away from the state
paper that rests on an arm of his chair. This is the Seward who
bought Alaska for a song, serenely redeemed for his folly, enjoying
an eternal I-told-you-so.
</P>
<P>
   Just outside the park's western boundary, a triangular traffic
island supports the obelisk commemorating Maj. Gen. William Jenkins
Worth's triumphant 1847 entry into Mexico City. Like Seward's
statue, it's been recently restored, but one has to wonder about
its presence in an increasingly Hispanic city, and whether the
general may one day have to content himself with Fort Worth, Texas,
as his big American monument.
</P>
<P>
   The most impressive memorial inside the park, in its northeast
portion, belongs to Adm. David Farragut, to whom New York City gave
$50,000 to buy a home after his Civil War successes. The pedestal
to this early Saint-Gaudens masterpiece, a sort of swirling
triptych with two curving flanks, seems lighter and more animate
than the statue it supports.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Farragut, looking well attired but rather surprised to be
here at all, stands Chester A. Arthur, who became the country's
21st president upon the assassination of James A. Garfield in 1881.
The mutton-chopped and always fashionable Arthur (he had Louis
Comfort Tiffany help him redecorate the White House) appears to
have just risen from the chair behind him, summoned by history to a
task he performed rather better than most imagined he would.
</P>
<P>
   Anxieties about him had everything to do with the park's
remaining statue, that of the ever choleric Sen. Roscoe Conkling,
who has stood since 1893 as a sort of Cerberus near the southeast
entrance. The absolute boss of the New York Republican Party in the
1870s, Conkling quite simply owned the pre-presidential Arthur, who
as the port collector of New York watched over the Custom House,
the mightiest patronage engine in the country. Neither man suffered
from any of our recent confusion about just what constitutes
soliciting campaign contributions on federal property: kickbacks
were sometimes rendered at an office on Hanover _ dubbed
``Hand-Over'' _ Street.
</P>
<P>
   A gorgeous brute of a man _ casually cruel, unforgiving, an
orator who made his colleagues tremble and the galleries swoon _
Conkling looks absolutely certain of his right to be immortalized
in the park. In fact, he is in midspeech, his left hand at his hip,
his right one open at his side. He's sure he'll convince you, of
whatever it is, before you take another step.
</P>
<P>
   The living Conkling, with his blond forelock, violet ink,
bedazzled mistresses and lapses into statesmanship, is a historical
novelist's dream. I've written about two-thirds of the book he
marauds through, and when passing Madison Square I sometimes feel a
literal version of the satisfaction that Virginia Woolf expressed
to her diary when things were going well with her novel ``The
Waves'': ``I think it possible that I have got my statues against
the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   I still keep an apartment in the city, close to the United
Nations, whose abstract outdoor sculpture leaves me either bored or
suspicious _ so many noble sentiments springing from such dubious
donors. The one modern sculpture in Madison Square Park _ three
rectangular oblongs by Antoni Milkowski _ merely perplexes me. This
is my limitation, to be sure; but my mind, so drawn to replication,
is more akin to that of the 19th-century New Yorker, whose zeal for
statuary eventually got out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Park and the People,'' their 1992 history of Central
Park, Roy Rosenzweig and Elizabeth Blackmar note how ``in 1873 the
park board acted to restrict commemorative sculpture to the Mall
and the entrance gates and to require prior review of artistic
merit.'' But the review committee of artistic experts had only
advisory powers and often could not resist ``the pressure to
commemorate immensely popular figures.'' Only when the five
boroughs amalgamated themselves at the end of the century into the
current City of New York did an Art Commission of experts supersede
the park board and stop the proliferation of pedestals.
</P>
<P>
   It was this modern, swelling city that made Conkling and Arthur
obsolete. In fact, all the figures in Madison Square were set up to
face south in a city rushing north. The great edifice that has
dominated the square in this century, Napoleon LeBrun's
Metropolitan Life building (1910), towers over the park's forgotten
men, a sort of architectural memento mori, reminding the passer-by
that one can insure one's life but not one's name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
