<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1626 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AA-BOOK-COX     08-06 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AA-BOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former AA member criticizes organization in new book
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marianne Gilliam does not have a degree in medicine or
psychology, but she considers herself an expert on addiction. One
of three children in a middle-class family in Cobb County(Ga.), she
took her first drink at 14.
</P>
<P>
   By age 18, she was one of 14 million alcoholics in America, and
she had slid into drug addiction and bulimia as well. While her
classmates packed for college, Gilliam headed for the meeting halls
of Alcoholics Anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Then she tried Overeaters Anonymous, treatment centers and
special camps. Nothing worked. Especially Alcoholics Anonymous, she
says. After a few months it seemed to Gilliam that the 12-step
approach perpetuated addiction by replacing dependence on alcohol
and drugs with a dependence on the program itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although some members eventually stopped drinking,'' she says,
``many did not address the underlying problems that drove them to
drink in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Abandoning AA, Gilliam took a more individualistic approach to
solving her problems. Now clean and sober for four years, the
34-year-old mother of two has written a first-person account of her
successful recovery that harshly criticizes an organization that
for more than 60 years has helped millions on the road to sobriety.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's so effective, why is the rate of relapse among AA
members nearly 70 percent?'' Gilliam asks in ``How Alcoholics
Anonymous Failed Me: My Personal Journey to Sobriety Through
Self-Empowerment'' (Eagle Brook/Morrow, $22).
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many people who drop out of AA, I thought this
book would be useful to them. Since I found a way to overcome
addictions myself, maybe that would encourage them to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for AA said the organization doesn't respond to
comments or criticism, but an addiction expert at Emory
University(Ga.) says that relapses do not necessarily mean the
treatment is not working.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though you relapse, I think there's improvement,'' says
Dr. Michael Kuhar, chief of the neuroscience division at Yerkes
Primate Center and president-elect of the College on Problems of
Drug Dependence. ``Different things work for different people. It's
not that there's something wrong with the treatment, it's just that
people are so different. Nothing helps everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the conclusion Gilliam reached. ``Recovery is not a
one-size-fits-all proposition,'' she says. ``If AA works for you,
that's great. If it doesn't, there are alternative courses of
treatment. AA didn't work for me because AA's focus on character
defects and shortcomings kept me from discovering what was right
and beautiful about myself. For someone who doesn't have much
self-esteem to begin with, it's terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Until she decided to fight her demons alone, Gilliam's life had
been a blur of booze and parties, first at Emory and later when she
began working as a stockbroker in Atlanta. Every night she would
hit the bars to drink and score lines of cocaine. When she finally
hit bottom, she moved back in with her parents and sought help. A
month shy of her one-year anniversary at AA, however, she got drunk
and used cocaine again. And all the while she was bingeing and
purging three or four times a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the experts wanted to let me off the hook,'' she says.
``Some said it was a disease over which I was powerless. Psychology
experts told me I had a wounded inner child within and that my
behavior was a result of a dysfunctional family. Nobody wanted me
to take responsibility for my actions.'' When Gilliam decided she
would have to save herself, she moved into a small apartment and
used her MBA training to set up an import-export consulting
business. Much of her time, however, she spent at bookstores,
browsing through Deepak Chopra's ``Overcoming Addictions'' and
other self-help books. What she found convinced her that the root
of her problem stemmed from a lack of self-esteem that began in
childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``My food issues seemed to center around my searching for love
and comfort, perhaps the love and comfort I had been longing for
from my father and had never received,'' she says. ``He was always
there physically and materially for the family, but emotionally I
felt as if I had never gotten his approval or respect. By reading
self-help books and seeing a good therapist, I slowly learned to
accept my father just the way he was. When I was able to recognize
that, I was able to begin the psychological healing that in turn
led to physical healing and freedom from addictive behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   She quickly adds that one of the keys to her recovery was her
family's unconditional support. ``They were always there for me, no
matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilliam's book has been praised by Dr. Bernie S. Siegel, author
of ``Love, Medicine and Miracles,'' and other proponents of
self-empowerment. And now that she is clean and sober, Gilliam is
looking for ways to help others find the right path. When she spoke
recently at a Unity church, several women came up to her afterward,
related similar experiences and asked for her guidance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them there is hope,'' she says. ``My book may not have
all the answers, but perhaps it can set them on the right path.''
</P>
<P>
   What worked for Gilliam may not work for everyone, Kuhar
cautions. ``Some people need more structure. This woman has a high
degree of motivation and intelligence. She could sit down and
figure out what was wrong. She's a gifted person who was able to
solve her problems. Unfortunately, everybody is not that smart or
that dedicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
