<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1627 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-MSKUBE09-COX     08-06 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MSKUBE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: The challenges of rethinking Marx are made manifest
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 9: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nowhere does it seem more dated, less relevant, than in its
famous opening sentence. ``A specter is haunting Europe _ the
specter of Communism,'' its youthfully optimistic authors wrote in
1848. Whatever may haunt Europe today, it is not communism.
</P>
<P>
   The political movement that paid homage to Karl Marx and
Friedrich Engels is as dead as the divine right of kings. And yet
``The Communist Manifesto'' not only remains in print but has been
dressed up in a 150th-anniversary edition.
</P>
<P>
   More than one, in fact. Oxford University Press has issued, in
its Classics series, a $5.95 paperback with a lucid introduction by
David McLellan. In Verso's $11 hardback edition, Marxist historian
Eric Hobsbawm traces the manifesto's origins as a pamphlet and
tries to wring from its denunciatory rhetoric a moral vision that
survives the heat of a moment long since passed.
</P>
<P>
   The manifesto comes to mind not because of its 150th anniversary
_ I had quite forgotten _ but because of a letter from a reader.
All columnists have their faithful readers, and for every columnist
a special few occupy places of honor. It would embarrass this
particular reader to have me offer a testimonial to his wit and
acuity, so I am honoring his request _ I should say his cringing
plea _ not to be identified. It's enough to say that he took
exception to a column in which I mentioned Karl Marx and John
Stuart Mill in the same breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I know you value Marx as a first-rate intellect and a
brilliant writer,'' his letter tells me, ``but in your role as
Gadfly-in-Chief, you have to be more careful not to give succor to
the very objects of your criticism by even remotely hinting at a
species of equivalency between Marx and somebody like John Stuart
Mill.''
</P>
<P>
   A social philosopher's bankrupt ideas
</P>
<P>
   He goes on to detail the many and familiar ways in which
``Marx's key ideas crumple like buildings at ground zero.'' Marx
was wrong, he reminds me, on every count: his view of society, his
materialistic interpretation of history, his understanding of
economics. Besides which, ``Marx was a killer,'' a man in whose
name millions in our century would be sent to gulags or
slaughtered.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose this can be read, then, as a brief in behalf of a
monster. I'd ask that we all give Karl the Killer a hand _ Fred,
too _ but it would sound facetious and insincere. A better way of
appreciating, or at least understanding, Marx's legacy would be to
re-read David Denby's exhilarating ``Great Books: My Adventures
With Homer, Rousseau, Woolf and Other Indestructible Writers of the
Western World.''
</P>
<P>
   Published two years ago, Denby's book is a film critic's account
of returning to Columbia University 30 years after he graduated and
taking the required humanities courses he had taken as an
18-year-old. It was a brilliant idea, and not just for a book. What
Denby realized is that we read a great book differently at 48 than
we read it at 18 _ life has a way of altering, usually deepening,
our view of things.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Marx, Denby could see easily enough the errors
and misapprehensions, not just in ``The Communist Manifesto'' but
also in the richer works he published before and after. Yet he came
to see in Marx something else:
</P>
<P>
   ``We work for others, to fulfill other people's goals, and often
enough we confront what we produce with an indifference bordering
on disgust. And so the eternal cry of boredom and meaninglessness;
the impoverishment that so many feel, the hollow exhaustion at the
end of the day; the dull anger, the internal distancing of oneself,
the need to escape.''
</P>
<P>
   `An arena of anxiety and triumph'
</P>
<P>
   Reading Marx anew, Denby understood better a psychological
debilitation that afflicts so many Americans, professionals as well
as wage earners: ``They drag themselves through work to reach the
promised land of leisure, the ecstasy of the defining car, suit,
house or vacation that settles for all time who they are. The
disgust with work makes the act of buying things an arena of
anxiety and triumph. Alienation exists at all levels of American
life. It is called consumerism.''
</P>
<P>
   If this is reading a little bit into Marx, it's not reading
much. You'll find no evidence for it in the three dry volumes of
``Das Kapital'' and you must search hard for it in even ``The
Communist Manifesto.'' But it's scattered about in an assortment of
earlier writings, most of them collected in various editions. One
of the handiest is Viking's ``The Portable Karl Marx.'' The
manifesto is there and so is a telling self-analysis. In a parlor
game Marx's daughters Jenny and Laura put to him a series of
questions. Asked his idea of happiness, he answered, ``To fight.''
Asked his chief characteristic, he answered, ``Singleness of
purpose.'' Asked his favorite virtue in a woman, he answered,
``Weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   So he wasn't perfect. Yet he was loved by his wife and by his
four daughters, if by few others. In our day he is revered only by
academics for whom he would have the bitterest contempt. It might
surprise my friend in Roswell that he and Karl have that, if
nothing else, in common. He might even wish to bow his head,
repentant.
</P>
<P>
   -- E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
