<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1628 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-SLEUTHS-COX     08-06 1305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SLEUTHS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All Alone in the Dark
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 9: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   While other people sleep, sleuths take a different view of
night. For them, night is when the mind paces the floor, when the
menace to home and hearth overwhelms, when, says fictional
investigator Sharon McCone, ``the threat always comes from
within.'' SS Even if detectives doze off, they cannot rest, for
dreams, McCone muses, ``often carry messages from the subconscious
that, if properly interpreted, can serve us well.'' SS In
mysteries, nightmares embody a fear of powerlessness. Psychological
invasion, frequently accompanied by criminal intrusion into the
sleuth's home, assaults identity. SS Engrossed in a case,
investigators become insomniacs or are so denied sleep that lines
blur between good and evil, sanity and insanity, real and dreamed.
SS Today's whodunit interrogates those borders more than the usual
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   -- While Other People Sleep. By Marcia Muller. Mysterious Press.
$23. 344 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Life for San Francisco private investigator Sharon McCone turns
into her worst nightmare: A stalker is impersonating her. Her
double breaks into McCone's apartment, stealing financial and
personal information. Since the impersonator sleeps around,
McCone's reputation takes a bigger hit than her credit cards. Using
an expert who relates fascinating facts about stalkers, McCone
solves the puzzle of who is after her identity and why. But by the
end of this honed meditation on stalking, she can only hope that in
time she'll ``let go of this nightmare.'' The ``habit of fear,''
McCone implies, will linger in ``every creak of the floorboards.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Tanner on Ice. By Lawrence Block. Dutton. $23.95. 248 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence agent Evan Tanner was robbed of his ability to
sleep after shrapnel invaded his skull during the Korean War. He
lived ``twenty-four wide-awake hours a day'' as a spy-adventurer
until Lawrence Block retired his character 25 years ago. Now,
Tanner is back. It seems a Scandinavian spy froze him cryonically
in 1972. His body was discovered and resurrected, and though he has
not aged, the century has. Nixon is no longer president; computers
and faxes are mysteries; and Minna, his former 11-old-charge, is
now 36, only a few years younger than he is. For six months, Tanner
speed-reads 25 years of Time and Newsweek day and, of course,
night, catching up on events. Then his old boss, now in his 90s,
shows up, and Tanner is off to Burma, which became Myanmar as he
slept, on an assassination assignment. While the first half of this
modern-day Rip Van Winkle tale is ingenious, the plot thereafter is
watered-down James Bond. But Block's acerbic commentary keeps you
reading.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Pied Piper. By Ridley Pearson. Hyperion. $23.95. 497
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Things are bad enough for police detective Lou Boldt: As his
hospitalized wife battles cancer, he cares for their two children.
But when the Pied Piper, a West Coast serial kidnapper who snatches
babies from their homes, moves into the Seattle area, Boldt's life
runs on coffee. As he and colleagues work with (and in spite of)
the FBI to capture the kidnapper, they encounter scam artists, drug
dealers and online hackers. When his own toddler is snatched and
the kidnapper demands that the search be stymied, Boldt must decide
whether to save his daughter or his integrity. For days, he walks
the tightrope between honor and dishonor, and ``couldn't nap even
if he'd been awake a week.'' Even after the case is closed, Boldt
finds himself haunted by the sound of children sobbing. Ridley
Pearson's rich prose is as caffeinated as his detective in this
nonstop read.
</P>
<P>
   -- Death Row. By Jon Katz. Doubleday. $21.95. 228 pages.
</P>
<P>
   A family's welfare is also at stake in this newest mystery in
Jon Katz's suburb series. Private eye Kit DeLeeuw is busy taking
care of his job, the kids and car pools while wife Jane gets a
psychology degree. Then his elderly friend Benchley Carrolton winds
up in an overly guarded nursing home. When Kit manages to get into
the place, overseen by a version of Nurse Ratched and owned by a
state senator who issues threats, he decides his friend's life is
in danger. Kit kidnaps Benchley and persuades the state cops to set
up a sting. Lying awake the night before, he muses that ``this
wasn't really a plan. It was a giant crapshoot, with my career, my
reputation, and my family's financial security riding on the
outcome.'' Kit's sense of good is unerring, as is Katz's humorous
portrait of the suburbs. But the powerlessness of the elderly ill
is poignantly and seriously rendered.
</P>
<P>
   -- Moon Music. By Faye Kellerman. Morrow. $25.50. 424 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who likes mysteries salted with the Gothic will eat up
this tale of an obsessive compulsive turned cannibal. Women's
mauled bodies show up in the Las Vegas desert, and police Sgt. Rom
Poe investigates. Darned if some of the victims weren't lovers to
his colleague Steve Jensen, married to Poe's disturbed high school
love. Readers will quickly figure out who done it; Faye Kellerman
is more interested in why. This tour through the Vegas underworld
dispenses as much blood as the Red Cross, and the plot traverses a
long-ago suicide, A-bomb tests, a diamondback rattler and, uh,
werewolves. Poe's personal life is as diffuse as the action. His
twin brother commits their alcoholic mother to Rom's care, just as
Rom reaches a crisis in his relationship with a pathologist. Love
in Vegas has worse odds than roulette. After the crime is solved,
Rom is jolted from a nightmare. His house jerks, a water bottle
flies. Was it an earthquake? Or are ghouls for real? Place your
bets.
</P>
<P>
   -- Murder at the Watergate. By Margaret Truman. Random House.
$25. 333 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The milieu only seems more civilized in Washington. Law
professor Mackensie Smith and wife Annabel move to the Watergate,
home of presidential campaign headquarters for their friend Vice
President Joe Aprile. More than his Boss, the veep disapproves of
the drug policy of Mexico's ruling PRI government. When two Mexican
nationals with damning information about the PRI turn up dead,
Aprile's assistant asks Mac to contact a guerrilla leader in San
Miguel de Allende. But betrayal is at work on both sides of the
border, and Annabel dreams that a hairy, swirling mass rips Mac
from her. When the couple is endangered after the Mexican
elections, evidence points to a U.S. traitor. Margaret Truman's
inside knowledge adds to the crisp plot, and her portrait of
Capitol people, particularly hostess Elfie Dorrance, is superb. Who
can you trust? In D.C. politics, there's no way to know.
</P>
<P>
   -- Acts of Murder. By Laurali R. Wright. Scribner. $22. 278
pages.
</P>
<P>
   The murderers are more interesting than the sleuths in this
exploration of sociopathology by an Edgar Award-winning British
Columbian. A cleaning woman, long ago jilted by her husband,
interprets a dream about a snake as a message to continue her
serial killings. Determined to sweep the world of people she
perceives to be sinners, Mrs. O'Hara knocks off several citizens of
Sechelt. Meanwhile, one of her clients conks her adulterous husband
over the head with a cast-iron frying pan and, believing him dead,
hides his body. Investigator Karl Alberg seems strangely removed
from the investigations. He's just married Cassandra Mitchell, is
rethinking his career and has a new female sergeant, who is being
harassed by an old boyfriend. This finely drawn anatomy of marriage
shows how domestic anger can segue into murderous rage, how love
turns into a snake that eats its own tail, how everyday life trips
over the edge into nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
