<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1630 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDRESS-COX     08-06 1307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDRESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Murder, Marilyn and a Movie: Author spins `Crazy' tales of
celebrity
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY AUGUST 9: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was four years ago that Mark Childress met Marilyn Monroe on
a Costa Rica beach.
</P>
<P>
   Well, all right, it wasn't really the legendary actress, but the
woman looked like Monroe would have looked if she had not died and
were 15 years older. The resemblance was so striking, in fact, that
Childress kicked his imagination in gear and came up with the idea
for a novel.
</P>
<P>
   What if Monroe were still alive on some remote island? And what
if she were sharing the island with Amelia Earhart, Jimmy Hoffa and
a bunch of other ``dead'' celebrities? And what if a '70s rock
star, say someone such as Jim Croce, crash-landed there?
</P>
<P>
   The premise for ``Gone for Good'' (Knopf, $25) would be too
far-fetched for many writers to even attempt, but not Childress. He
is, after all, the author of ``Crazy in Alabama.''
</P>
<P>
   In that 1993 novel, Childress spins an outrageous tale of a
Southern woman who cuts off her husband's head, stashes it in a
Tupperware lettuce keeper and sets out to seek fame and fortune in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way she periodically ``burps'' the Tupperware and
checks its contents.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two novels are worlds apart, both deal with
celebrity, a subject Childress finds fascinating. ``It's the
scourge and religion of our age,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Alabama native didn't object to hanging out with
movie stars Antonio Banderas and Melanie Griffith in Houma, La.,
for the past three months. Banderas is directing the film version
of ``Crazy in Alabama,'' starring Griffith as the wacky Alabama
beauty. Childress, 40, a former regional editor for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, wrote the screenplay and acted as unofficial
adviser. The film is scheduled for release in spring 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got involved with the movie, I realized that a lot of
the things I was thinking about celebrity were confirmed,''
Childress says. ``These people have paper shredders in their houses
so people won't go through their garbage and read their mail.
People think that celebrities are their property.''
</P>
<P>
   Paparazzi were not exactly a problem in Houma, though. The main
challenge was finding entertainment in the small southeastern
Louisiana town.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a water-slide park and one good restaurant where we
hung out,'' Childress says. ``But it's just as well. We had a
shooting schedule of 15 hours a day. After that, all we wanted to
do was go to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffith and Don Johnson bought the film rights to ``Crazy in
Alabama'' several years ago when they were still married. After the
divorce, Johnson shopped the script around without success. When
Griffith heard it was available again, she bought it for Banderas'
first directing project.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Houma Courier, Banderas said the
opportunity to re-create America in the 1960s was appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the same movie,'' Banderas said, ``we go from black comedy
to political drama to almost a horror movie sometimes. It's just
trying to balance all that stuff together _ to link them together _
to see how they work.''
</P>
<P>
   One thread of the story follows Lucille (Griffith), who kills
her abusive husband, leaves her seven kids with her mother and
heads for California to be a star on the TV show ``Bewitched.'' At
the same time, there is a parallel story dealing with Lucille's
nephew, Peejoe (played by Lucas Black of ``Slingblade''), who
becomes embroiled in a civil rights struggle over the integration
of a public swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   Houma was picked because it resembled Alabama but was close
enough to New Orleans to use local film crews. The film has a
relatively modest $15 million budget but a big-name cast:
Griffith's co-stars include Elizabeth Perkins, Rod Steiger, Robert
Wagner and Meat Loaf.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, screenwriters are rarely seen or heard on the set,
but Childress says Banderas asked him for help on nearly every
take. ``Some of my suggestions he took, some of them he didn't. But
he was very concerned about getting everything right, especially
the accents.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, the accents were too good. ``In one scene, Lucas Black
was supposed to say, `You didn't even ask.' Instead, it came out,
`Youdinteenask.' I understood it, but nobody who wasn't from
Alabama did.''
</P>
<P>
   Childress, who resembles a pudgy cherub with blond-streaked
hair, has kept his Alabama accent despite leaving his home state
years ago. After a stint in San Francisco, he moved to Costa Rica
and built a small house on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Childress began vacationing in the Central American country
after one of his best friends died of AIDS and author Randy Shilts
(``And the Band Played On'') recommended it as a good place to
relax.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was the most beautiful place in the world,''
Childress says. ``The vacations kept getting longer and longer, so
I decided to build there. Costa Rica is paradise with chickens in
the street. It reminds me of the Alabama of my childhood _ a bit
shabby and undeveloped but very friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Childress has been possessed by the writing bug since he was a
child in Monroeville, Ala., the hometown of Truman Capote and
Harper Lee. ``To Kill a Mockingbird'' was the first adult book he
remembers reading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in Monroeville had read it because that's where it's
set,'' he says, ``so I always had the sense that fiction is born
out of reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta writer Charles McNair recalls meeting Childress in
author Barry Hannah's class at the University of Alabama. ``After
class, we'd get in my pickup truck and ride around, dreaming of the
days we'd become published writers like Flannery O'Connor. He was
precocious even then. He won the Thomas Wolfe Award for the most
promising fiction writer.''
</P>
<P>
   As a student of Hannah's, Childress studied the works of Latin
American writers and became enthralled with the concept of
supernatural intervention in human life, an approach he used in his
debut novel, ``A World Made of Fire'' (1984).
</P>
<P>
   After working as a journalist for Southern Living and The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution, he quit in 1986 to write fiction full
time. He honed his storytelling craft in ```V' for Victor'' (1988),
an adventure story about a young boy and German submarines off the
coast of Alabama, and ``Tender'' (1990), a fictionalized version of
Elvis Presley's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time he writes a book he intends to write something
different from before,'' McNair says. ``You can't depend on getting
a sort of John Grisham-like formulaic approach. When you get a book
that hits the nerve of American culture the way `Crazy in Alabama'
did, and the next book is not even about the USA, it throws
predictability to the wind. That's problematic for some readers and
critics who want formula.''
</P>
<P>
   This was true for ``Gone for Good,'' which has received wildly
mixed reviews. Childress admits the bad reviews bother him, but he
also has learned to put them in perspective. ``One paper ran a
review that said this book was not as good as the classic `Crazy in
Alabama,' which the paper hated when it was published.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Crazy in Alabama'' was Childress' first attempt at
screenwriting, and although it was painful cutting a 500-page
manuscript to 110 pages, he is satisfied with the results. The
script captures the spirit of the novel, he says, even if some
details had to be changed. The Tupperware lettuce holder used to
transport the severed head, for example, had to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company wouldn't let us use it in the movie,'' he says,
``so we had to make it a (generic) plastic container. I can't
imagine why they would object. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
