<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1631 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVANS-PHOTOGRAPHY-REV     08-06 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVANS-PHOTOGRAPHY-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALKER EVANS PHOTOGRAPHY REVIEW: 3 DEGREES OF SEPARATION ON THE
ROAD TO ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SARAH BOXER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You don't have to read Walter Benjamin to understand
the laws of mechanical reproduction. Anyone who has ever used a
Xerox machine knows that images reproduced time and again degrade
and change. The grays dissolve and eventually the subtle features
of the image disappear. At the same time, the aura, the authentic
atmosphere around the original object, vanishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the most perfect reproduction of a work of art is lacking
in one element: its presence in time and space,'' Benjamin, the
German philosopher and critic, wrote. ``The presence of the
original is the prerequisite to the concept of authenticity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Walker Evans: Murals From the 1971 MOMA Retrospective,'' at
the Laurence Miller Gallery, is arguably not a show of Walker
Evans' photographs, despite the title of the exhibition. It is a
show of some blowups of Evans' photographs that were printed from
his negatives as part of the wall decoration for his retrospective
at the Museum of Modern Art 27 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   These mural-size pictures have neither the stinging clarity nor
the melancholy aura of the originals. But they do offer something
else: a chance to ponder how radically images can change depending
on how, when and why they are reproduced. In the case of Evans,
this exercise proves rewarding, for, as Gilles Mora and John T.
Hill observe in ``Walker Evans: The Hungry Eye,'' Evans himself was
fascinated by ``the consumer image, multiplied by the media.'' In
the 1930s, he photographed hundreds of billboards, signs and
posters throughout the South.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, five of the six pictures on display at Laurence
Miller are blowups of some of Evans' best known pictures of
commercial objects: a torn movie poster, a shrimp fisherman's house
in Biloxi, Miss., full of mass-produced images of the Virgin Mary,
a shoe-shine sign, a billboard advertising a furniture business and
the window display of a cheap photo studio. (The sixth photograph
is of a Southern church.) Each picture is not only a study of
commercial imagery but also a many-layered meditation on the
vicissitudes of mechanical reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in 1936, the very year Benjamin published his essay
``The Work of Art in the Age of Mechanical Reproduction,'' Evans
took a photograph he called ``Penny Picture Display.'' The
photograph showed an array of tiny portrait photos with the letters
s-t-u-d-i-o printed over it.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, these portraits were originally intended as mementos
or perhaps identification photos. But when the studio put them up
for display as an advertisement, their function and even their look
changed. Each picture ceded its individuality to the commercial
demands of the group.
</P>
<P>
   In 1936, when Evans took his picture of the studio's window
display, the meaning of the portraits changed yet again. Evans'
purpose, after all, was not to get more business for the studio. He
was taking a slice of American life during the Depression. And he
succeeded so well that John Szarkowski, the curator of the 1971
show, wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to know now with certainty whether Evans
recorded the America of his youth or invented it. Beyond doubt, the
accepted myth of our recent past is in some measure the creation of
this photographer . . . It is now part of our history.''
</P>
<P>
   The many levels of visual interest and intention in Evans'
picture of pictures naturally direct our attention to the Miller
gallery's version of the same picture. Is the blowup of this
photograph so different from the picture Evans took? Sure it is.
</P>
<P>
   It was not printed by Walker Evans. It was produced by the
Modernage Laboratory in Manhattan as a graphic element in the 1971
retrospective, one of the 13 blowups that punctuated the exhibition
of 200 photographs. Because it is 6 by 8 feet, it is far grainier
than the original. And it has a different claim to fame. Its air of
authenticity does not derive from a direct connection with Evans
but rather from the Evans retrospective. It is a relic from that
event, and it is now on sale for $75,000.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is not such a bad thing. Benjamin said that the
whole idea of ``authentic'' photographic prints was senseless
anyway, since all prints are reproductions. He also thought there
was something good about killing an art object's air of
authenticity, its aura. Once the aura is destroyed, he hoped, so is
the elitist attitude toward art. There was, however, one danger:
that the aura of an object would be replaced by a new kind of aura,
which he called ``the phony spell of a commodity.''
</P>
<P>
   What would Evans have thought?
</P>
<P>
   His approach to American commercialism suggests he might have
been intrigued by the show. His picture of a torn movie poster is
shot in such a way that one of the movie stars appears to be
horrified not by the events in the movie but by the rip that runs
from the crown of her head to her chin.
</P>
<P>
   The same kind of twist is evident in Evans' 1936 photograph of
the furniture advertisement near Birmingham, Ala. The left half has
a picture of a landscape with river and trees and text that reads:
``Did You Know? J.W. McDonald Furn. Co. Can Furnish Your Home
Complete. Congoleum Rugs. Gruno Refrigerators.'' The right part of
the advertisement shows a primitive painting of a happily furnished
home: two women sitting on a couch and talking while two children
play on a nearby rug.
</P>
<P>
   But when Evans took the picture of the billboard he changed our
view of it. In his photograph he included not only the billboard
itself but also its wooden legs, the leafy ground under it and the
hint of houses on either side of it. Indeed, the bucolic part of
the billboard seems to be mocked by the ground it stands on. The
subject was no longer what was IN the billboard, a furnished home,
but the billboard itself, an icon in the American landscape. Once
again, Evans seems to have located a rift in the illusory world of
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   You could say he was an ironist. ``Walker Evans: The Hungry
Eye'' suggests he was a precursor of Pop Art and post-modernism
because he used commercial images for his own purposes: ``By
incorporating these images within his own and making them his own,
he was initiating a new esthetic act, close to that of Marcel
Duchamp, and prefiguring the wholesale reclamations of Pop Art and
ironic quotations of post-modernism.''
</P>
<P>
   It is too much to suggest that Evans, like Duchamp, wanted to
attack the very idea of authenticity. Still, he might have been
more amused than appalled that blowups of his photographs of
posters, billboards and displays had themselves been turned into
salable art objects, for this adds yet another level of commercial
irony to his pictures. They are advertisements become photographs
become posters become art.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
