<HEADER>
A1632 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STYLE-FUBU-COX     08-06 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-FUBU-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Designer aims for top of hip-hop wear heap
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 9: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having peeped mistakes made by his predecessors in the hip-hop
sportswear game, Fubu (``For us, by us'') founder Daymond John
isn't likely to repeat them.
</P>
<P>
   Black-owned urban sportswear firms that nibble at the edges of
the market segment's multibillion dollar pie come and go.
</P>
<P>
   Before John _ who's not yet 30 _ finishes his run, he thinks he
will have taken a big bite of that hip-hop couture pie.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the brothers (Thomas Walker and Carl Jones) who
brought you the carnival-colored Cross Colours collections back in
the 1980s thought similarly before their primary client _ the
Merry-Go-Round stores _ tanked and took them down, too. And if Karl
Kani ever thought his streetwear fortunes would continually rise,
he's had to reconsider the notion now that his once-indelible
imprint has started to fade.
</P>
<P>
   John, a native of Queens, N.Y., who operates out of a 66th-floor
Empire State Building suite, formed Fubu six years ago along with
three childhood friends. Though the shortest (5 feet, 7 inches)
member of his crew, John was its catalyst: He started the
sportswear line after being outraged when he was charged $20 for a
street-peddled rag that he could make for himself for mere pennies.
</P>
<P>
   John's bio progresses, loosely, as follows: Red Lobster waiter
sells his homemade caps on Queens street corners and plows the
profits into more bargain bolts of fabric for caps as well as logo
sweat shirts and T-shirts. The designer formerly-known-as a waiter
gets his mom to borrow $100,000 against her mortgage on her house
to get Fubu up and running. Somehow, Fubu sportswear winds up in
the hands of rapper LL Cool J, who hands John the free publicity
coup of all time by wearing a Fubu cap in a commercial produced and
aired repeatedly by the Gap. A Korean conglomerate happens along
and offers John sufficient financing and distribution support to
make and sell enough Fubu gear to stretch from Flatbush to Frisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Samsung) doesn't care if I'm selling Fubu on the street or on
Fifth Avenue as long as it's selling,'' John says. ``We made an
agreement that within three years we had to have it up to $5
million in sales, and I exceeded that in one year. So they're
satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   But John's not. He wants Fubu to be as diversified as the main
market segment's moneymakers: Tommy Hilfiger, Polo-Ralph Lauren and
Nautica by David Chu. Fubu has already evolved beyond caps and
fleece separates. The logo is stamped on sport and luxury
outerwear, shirts, jeans and trousers, men's and women's underwear,
kids' clothing and several new seasonal styles of shoes and boots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's less about trying to make it and more about creating
an identity for who we are as a company,'' John says. ``Before, the
primary goal was just to succeed ... now I can concentrate on the
integrity of the brand.''
</P>
<P>
   Though determined to reach the top of the hip-hop heap, John
readily shares advice with aspiring designers who'd like to emulate
his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Persistence is key,'' he says. ``Surround yourself with a
positive group of people. And always be morally correct. You don't
have to be ruthless and deceiving to make it anywhere. And,
obviously, when you make it big, make it a point to give back to
the people who helped make you.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
