<HEADER>
A1633 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SURF-CAMP-COX     08-06 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURF-CAMP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SURFIN', DUDE!: A visiting landlubber is tutored by a family of
legendary surfers and learns to hang 10
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 9: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN CLEMENTE, Calif. -- I did get up _ got my sorry, narrow
behind up in the air, knees wobbling, arms flailing as if calling
for some runaway water taxi, the rush of the (teeny tiny) wave
drowning out every other noise around me, including the sound of my
own saner thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   And then I wasn't up anymore. I was down. In the deep blue sea.
The board, Velcro-ed to my right ankle by a leash, bobbed in the
chilly Pacific a few feet away. It didn't mock me, exactly; it just
acted like I wasn't there. It nosed around in the opposite
direction whenever I reached for it.
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't blame it. I'd just had the shortest short course
possible at the legendary Paskowitz Surf Camp on San Onofre State
Beach, about an hour south of Los Angeles _ a five-minute lecture
from instructor dude extraordinaire Terry Simms, a yellow-blond
surf pro who answers questions about his well-being with replies
such as ``Rippin'!'' But even with only a quickie lesson in the
sand and a few short rides on some meekly crashing white water, I
tasted surfing's mythic pull.
</P>
<P>
   That pull was summed up earlier by Simms, who began surfing at 3
when he and an older brother scoured beach-town alleys for wooden
ironing boards to haul into the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're in the womb,'' Simms said of surfing, ``traveling in
time with this thing that blows you out like ... birth. And then it
annihilates you, man, on the beach. It's like birth, life and death
_ in one wave!''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it is a gas. Even riding my little white-water mound, I
could feel the power, the hydroplaning rush, the SoCal cool that a
waxed longboard on salt water generates.
</P>
<P>
   And it is pretty hard. That's why people _ kids and adults _ pay
$900 a week for this camp run by one of surfing's most famous
families. They promise to get you up on a board _ whether you're a
gawky mall rat or a buttoned-down, landlocked investment banker
who's never been in the ocean above your flabby thighs.
</P>
<P>
   The Paskowitzes say they shave months from a camper's learning
curve. But one soon learns that simply riding a wave isn't surfing.
</P>
<P>
   Campers ``can expect to learn how to surf, but I think what we
do is make surfers,'' says Israel ``Izzy'' Paskowitz, one of eight
brothers and a former longboard champ who manages the camp. ``We
don't want someone to just say they stood on a board. We turn out
people who are forever touched by whatever it is we all get from
surfing.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds his brother Jonathan, another former surf champ: ``It's not
a lifestyle. It's a life. We're into the romance, the spiritual,
the physical, the primal reward. It's like falling in love, or
falling off a cliff _ it's on that level.''
</P>
<P>
   They talk like that sometimes _ like they're one grain of sand
shy of a beach. Except ... you're with them for maybe a minute and
you're already sucked in by the vibe of a clan once described as
``a curious blend of Swiss Family Robinson and the Partridge
Family.''
</P>
<P>
   That vibe has a long history.
</P>
<P>
   Dorian ``Doc'' Paskowitz, the family's 77-year-old patriarch who
still surfs for campers an hour each morning, moved to Southern
California at 12 and became one of the West Coast's pioneering
surfers. After graduating from medical school, Dorian married
Juliette, a classically trained opera singer from Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The two bought a 12-foot-long trailer, and raised nine children
(one a daughter) inside it and traveled the world _ Israel, Hawaii,
Mexico _ in search of the perfect wave. Dorian became a
``missionary doctor,'' hanging his shingle in whatever outpost the
family landed. He and Juliette home-schooled the children, and in
1971 Dorian started the surfing camp to keep the kids together
during summers. They're grown now and live in the area, and as many
as six still work or help at the camp.
</P>
<P>
   Dorian and Juliette live in a tent in Baja, Mexico, the rest of
the year. Dorian surfs and peddles a self-published book, ``Surfing
and Health,'' an engaging blend of Carlos Castaneda meets the
longboard. It opens with the epigram: ``In the wave there is
wisdom.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisdom here begins at the beginning. Campers arrive by sky-blue
school bus at the San Onofre beach _ sacred sand among surfers who
fill its waters like wet-suited sea otters _ from their low-tech
campsite a few miles away at about 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The first day is spent demonstrating the basics: how to put on a
wet suit, lay down their boards, be safe in the water. Then they go
out with instructors: the Paskowitz family, some other pros like
Simms, and the occasional world-class surfer who drops by to ``pay
respect'' to Doc, who's counseled many of them. Skill levels are
determined and then improved the rest of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Instruction is intensely casual, with the lifelong practitioners
who run the camp as interested in the sport's seaside Zen as
ticking off a specific agenda. Campers surf mornings from around 8
to 11, eat lunch under a big beach tent, listen to ``Doc'' read
like some sea-risen mystic from his book, then surf the rest of the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, they return to the scrub mountain campsite, made up
of a series of communal tents with showers and grills.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no place on Earth like this to learn how to surf, with
the people here, the location,'' says Bobby Friedman, a pairs champ
who comes by occasionally to help Doc. ``This is more the surfing
lifestyle. Here there is no clock.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, it worked for Rosie Frangi, a 15-year-old from
Gainesville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I caught the most epic wave two days ago,'' she said one
morning. ``Terry took me way out to catch a special wave. I paddled
as hard as I could to catch one, and the last thing I heard Terry
yell was, `You're going to catch a wave with the great Doc
Paskowitz!' I turned my head and there was Doc, weaving in and out
beside me. I rode it all the way to the beach, and when I got there
Doc's wife and daughter were standing there, watching us.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like out of a book or something.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Information: Five-day, four-night sessions offered through
Sept. 18: $900. Includes equipment, food and campsite (bring
sleeping bag). Adults-only sessions held the last two weeks. A
weeklong session in San Jose del Cabo, Mexico, begins Sept. 21;
$1,925. (includes hotel, equipment and meals). 714-361-9283.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
