<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Sally's death severs link to way of life
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   My mother's lifelong friend and neighbor, Sally Barnes, was
killed in an automobile accident in front of her Alford, Fla., home
this week. For my family, it was more than losing a good friend,
the mother of my children's best Alford playmates. It was the end
of a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   Sally's late husband, Buck Barnes, was a maintenance man on the
Atlanta and St. Andrews Bay railroad, and therefore they had to
have a telephone.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the few telephones in the little town, and the
closest to my mother. It was in fact our sole connection with her
when we were at home in Atlanta, and her connection with us. If we
had to talk to her, we called the Barneses. If she needed us, she
called from the wall phone in the Barneses' front room. Messages
could be shouted from front gate to front gate, and we counted on
it in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Slender, sweet-voiced Sally would walk across the dirt street
and check on my mother in time of illness, calling me back with
always reassuring words. ``Don't worry,'' she would say. ``We're
gon' take care of your mother.''
</P>
<P>
   After my son called to tell me Sally had been struck by a truck
as she crossed the street in front of her house, I spent a long
time thinking about how the scarcity of telephones brought
neighbors together in that day. When everybody got a phone, which
they did shortly after the war, there was a slackening of visiting.
You didn't have the excuse of borrowing the phone to carry your
through the front gate. And there was a loss of messages back and
forth.
</P>
<P>
   In another day, listening in on a party line served the same
purpose. But when there was no phone in your house, and you
depended on a neighbor to take messages for you, whatever news
there was from your distant kith and kin got circulated.
</P>
<P>
   My little girls, spending summer holidays with their
grandmother, were best friends with Sally's daughters, Linda and
Catherine, who were always thrilled when they would came home with
us to savor the wonders of the big city. I remember that they were
especially impressed by the fountain in Hurt Park.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Alford taught my mother to appreciate the convenience of
her own telephone, the little town also introduced her to the
radio. When I visit there now, we wave in passing to neighbors, but
when radio was new, everybody gathered at the home of the affluent
Mathises for what was known as a ``radio party.''
</P>
<P>
   My mother reported to us about this elegant social-cultural
affair when she visited her relatives in Alford. ``Sarah asked us
all over to listen to her Atwater Kent,'' she told us. ``My, it was
wonderful! You could hear everything from New York and Atlanta just
as plain.''
</P>
<P>
   When I think of Sally Barnes _ a wonderful mother and daughter
who sewed beautiful dresses for her little girls, raised the
prettiest azaleas and camellias in town and lovingly fed and nursed
all her relatives in time of illness _ I think how she was an
important link connecting our family in another day.
</P>
<P>
   My son told me Sally's death brought a wave of grief to the
little town. Oddly enough, the telephone was not what drew
neighbors and relatives closer together. They met at the City Hall,
the fire station and Jay Kent's grocery store to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   They say Alford, and probably even Steele City up the road where
she was a member of the Salem Free Will Baptist Church, will never
be the same again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
