<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strokes could be prevented with estrogen
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The female hormone estrogen someday could be used to prevent or
treat stroke, if beneficial effects seen in rat experiments can be
duplicated in humans.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from the Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine
in Baltimore have completed a study in which they gave male rats
estrogen before inducing strokes.
</P>
<P>
   During a stroke, blood flow to the brain stops. Brain cells can
be damaged by the lack of blood as well as by toxic substances
released during the stroke.
</P>
<P>
   In the Johns Hopkins study, estrogen treatment halved the amount
of brain damage in the rats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very interesting use of a native hormone,'' said study
co-author Patricia Hurn, professor of anesthesiology and critical
care medicine at Johns Hopkins. Researchers aren't sure why
estrogen might reduce stroke-related brain damage although they
suspect the hormone helps improve blood flow.
</P>
<P>
   Hurn and others also are studying estrogen's effects in female
rats. Preliminary results confirm female rats similarly benefit
from estrogen administered before stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Stroke affects 740,000 new victims in the U. S. each year, and
is the third leading cause of death after heart disease and cancer.
Georgia has the third highest rate in the U. S., with 3,836
stroke-related deaths statewide in 1993, said Dr. Michael Frankel,
an Emory University(Ga.)stroke researcher.
</P>
<P>
   Leading stroke specialist Dr. Lawrence Brass of Yale
University(Conn.) said the study results are encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is tremendous evidence emerging that estrogen has many
more beneficial effects than we expected,'' Brass said.
</P>
<P>
   Estrogen's reputation was tarnished in the 1960s, when high
doses of the hormone used in birth-control pills were associated
with a higher risk of blood clots, strokes and heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Today, birth-control pills that contain estrogen have much lower
doses. Estrogen replacement therapy is increasingly considered for
post-menopausal women, to prevent bone loss, heart disease and some
types of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The Johns Hopkins study, which was funded by the National
Institutes of Health, was partly inspired by observations that
stroke rates are low among younger women, but begin climbing after
menopause, Hurn said.
</P>
<P>
   It will be long before researchers will know whether estrogen
can be tried as a stroke treatment for humans, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to do some further animal studies before the drug
could be considered for clinical trials,'' Hurn said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
