<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Little scream in new `Halloween'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Carpenter's bare-bones 1978 frightfest ``Halloween''
presented an unkillable boogeyman with a yen for butcher knives and
baby sitters. The same approach works less well in this
20th-anniversary sequel, which opened Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Lee Curtis gamely returns as Laurie Strode, survivor of
the first two films (she managed to steer clear of rotten sequels
Nos. 3 through 6). Now, she goes by the name Keri Tate and is a
single mother to 17-year-old John (Josh Hartnett). Also back is
Michael Myers, the shadowy, personality-free maniac who stalked
Curtis all those years ago. Curtis' real-life mother, Janet Leigh,
has a cameo that recycles lines from her famous ``Psycho'' role.
</P>
<P>
   What's surprising is how unsurprising ``H20'' is. You can easily
guess who'll survive and who'll get cut out of the picture,
literally. But when Curtis pulls a Sigourney Weaver, a la
``Aliens,'' stalking Michael instead of fleeing him, the movie
finally gets some juice. It whips up 20 minutes of decent scares,
which is at least 20 more than the other current teen-screamer,
``Disturbing Behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Halloween: H20''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jamie Lee Curtis, Josh Hartnett and Adam Arkin.
Directed by Steve Miner. Rated R for profanity, violence, gore and
alcohol use. 1 hour, 22 minutes. At metro theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Twenty years later, barely half as scary.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
