</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SNAKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Snake Eyes' (mostly) a winning throw
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oscar winner Nicolas Cage and longtime director Brian De Palma
roll the dice with ``Snake Eyes,'' and, while they don't come up
total winners, they're far from losers.
</P>
<P>
   Part detective story, part action-thriller, ``Snake Eyes'' takes
place in Atlantic City on the night of a heavy-duty heavyweight
fight attended by 14,000 screaming fans. Our protagonist, Rick
Santoro (Cage), is a cocky cop on the take. Over the next few
hours, he'll find out whether he's still more cop than crook.
</P>
<P>
   Rick's childhood buddy Kevin Dunne (Gary Sinise) is now head of
security for the secretary of defense. The secretary is in town to
enjoy the fight and take care of a little business.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Kevin, Rick has ringside seats _ with a higher cost
than he expected. As the champion goes down, shots ring out and the
secretary is hit. Where was Kevin? Apparently lured away from his
post by a mysterious redhead. He still manages to shoot the
shooter, but he's guilt-stricken over his dereliction of duty. No
problem, says Rick, who long ago learned to look the other way when
it was personally beneficial. ``You just tell 'em what you did
right,'' he advises, ``and you throw out the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest, however, won't be thrown out. What looks like an
open-and-shut case becomes more complex as different characters
reveal their stories. There's the champ (Stan Shaw), who has a bad
gambling habit and a lot of debts. There's a second mystery woman
(Julia Costello). There's Kevin himself, in both the wrong place
and the right place at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, the movie takes a single unexpected act of
violence, then deconstructs it by examining events from diverse
points of view. Forget the lone-gunman theory. Rick smells a
conspiracy. Oliver Stone would be proud.
</P>
<P>
   De Palma has a lot to be proud of, too. His energized camera
exhilaratingly captures the wired pandemonium surrounding a big
boxing match. The movie's first 20 minutes are, quite simply, a
knockout. That momentum continues as Rick doggedly puts together
the pieces of the puzzle surrounding the shooting. It's only near
the very end, when ``Snake Eyes'' lapses into routine heroics, that
it loses steam.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Cage holds things together with his manic, take-charge
energy. He's in his strutting, loosey-goosey ``Leaving Las Vegas''
mode, whether shaking down a small-time drug dealer or studying the
arena's vast array of surveillance equipment for clues.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, ``Snake Eyes'' is a lot like a night at a casino. By
the end, you know the wins and losses don't really add up, but
you've had such a good time it doesn't really matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snake Eyes''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Nicolas Cage and Gary Sinise. Directed by Brian De
Palma. Rated R for violence and language. 1 hour, 42 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Cage and De Palma are worth gambling on.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
