</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUBES-UNTIED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A family rebuilds five months after a Georgia couple lost their
daughter in a tornado
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Ga. -- Shannon Wilson had already fixed a breakfast
bottle for his 10-month-old daughter, Hannah, when he noticed the
rain outside the window. This, he thought, is one bad storm.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Robynn, also noticed something strange: The hail was
not hitting the ground, but smacking the window horizontally.
</P>
<P>
   As she turned back to tell her husband, the floor heaved upward,
boards splintering and cracking as a tornado raged through their
home.
</P>
<P>
   Robynn, screaming, grabbed Hannah and hit the floor, only to
have the wind suck the baby from her arms.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon crawled toward the other end of the trailer in an effort
to get to their 4-year-old daughter, Hayley, who had been born with
the birth defect, spina bifida.
</P>
<P>
   He never got to her. Instead, he was thrown 150 yards away,
fracturing his neck.
</P>
<P>
   In less than 10 minutes, the tornado _ which cut a 10-mile-long,
half-mile-wide path through northern Hall County March 20 _ was
over.
</P>
<P>
   Where there had been a forest and the Wilsons' mobile home,
there was nothing but debris.
</P>
<P>
   Robynn, bleeding, emerged first from the wreckage and started
digging through their broken home for her baby, whose cries cut
through the silence. Shannon, blinded because both eyes had swollen
shut from boards hitting him, followed the sounds and helped his
25-year-old wife pull wreckage off their baby.
</P>
<P>
   But they could not find 4-year-old Hayley, a little girl who
loved her pink princess dress and the television show, ``Rug
Rats.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors and passers-by took up the search as Shannon and
Hannah were loaded into an ambulance and Robynn followed in a
pick-up truck with a stranger.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, Hayley's body was found, tucked near the wreckage
of her bed. When Shannon's family identified the body, she merely
looked asleep _ with a small cut above her eye and a tear in her
pajamas.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 people came to her funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so proud to be her mother,'' Robynn said. ``I was really
touched when I realized how very special she truly was.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayley was buried in the Easter dress she had worn the year
before _ by chance, stored at her aunt's home.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of only a few personal possessions the tornado had
not stolen.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon and Robynn painstakingly searched the rubble for
memories of their eldest child: Robynn found her baby book. They
were able to retrieve some photos, their family Bible and Mother's
Day and Father's Day presents Hayley had made at her school,
Challenged Child &AMP; Friends Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Hayley's baby dedication dress was also found _ ``with no mud on
it,'' Robynn said.
</P>
<P>
   But that was it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The largest pieces (of the house) left could have fit in the
back of pick-up truck,'' Shannon Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time 27-year-old Shannon had lost loved ones.
In 1985, his mother, Pamela Howard Wilson, and youngest brother,
Corey, died in a house fire.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the pain of this moment was much worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've buried a parent and I've buried a child, and there's no
comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days and months that followed, the young couple would
learn lessons of loss and faith.
</P>
<P>
   They would also learn about the kindness of a community, a
doctor, a hospital and an insurance company that is helping them
rebuild their lives. And how from the darkest of days, hope can
emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Wilsons are rebuilding their fractured lives. They
started with help from their church, Woodlawn Baptist Church, and
other community organizations.
</P>
<P>
   And although they realize they could never replace Hayley, they
are hoping for a second chance at happiness _ with another child.
</P>
<P>
   Robynn had had her fallopian tubes tied after the birth of their
youngest child in December 1997. It had been a hard decision, but
made on a rational basis. Shannon and Robynn had been married for
five years before they choose this route of birth control. They had
a special needs child and a baby. They wanted to do the best by the
two children they already had and simply did not want to stretch
the family too thin financially or emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   When they decided in June to try to reverse the procedure, they
visited Dr. Clayton Cox, a Gainsville obstetrician who had overseen
the birth of Hannah.
</P>
<P>
   Cox had been waiting for this moment.
</P>
<P>
   After the tornado hit the town, Cox had been struck by how many
of the victims who had experienced loss were either patients or
family members of patients. More than a dozen of his patients had
either lost loved ones or their homes, he said. Twelve people were
killed and more than 100 were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Sending sympathy cards to the families didn't seem to be enough.
So when the Wilsons met to discuss the reversal, he was compelled
to offer a more tangible form of help. He agreed to perform the
procedure, known as a tubal re-anastomosis, free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seemed to be the right thing to do,'' Cox said. ``They
never even got to ask about the cost because I guess I kind of beat
them to the punch.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox had earlier tried to talk the Wilsons, both in their 20s,
out of having the tubal ligation in the first place. It is unusual
for young couples to choose such a route. And as life unravels,
doctors worry that patients who take such drastic measures will
regret the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 640,000 tubal ligations done each year nationally, about
10 percent of women who do them end up going back and asking for a
reversal, said Dr. Andrew Toledo, of Reproductive Biology
Associates Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The reversal is fairly easy - if the original procedure left
enough of the fallopian tubes to work.
</P>
<P>
   A small incision is made into the abdomen and a plastic tube is
placed through the cervic into the fallopian tubes. Dye is shot
through the tubes to see where the original blockage occurred. That
part is snipped out and then, each tube is resewed.
</P>
<P>
   After discussing the reversal procedure in June with Cox, the
Wilsons walked away with hope.
</P>
<P>
   Cox walked away with a plan.
</P>
<P>
   He would try to get the local hospital, Northeast Georgia
Medical Center, and the Wilsons' insurance company, Blue Cross &AMP;
Blue Shield of Georgia, to donate services and provide the Wilsons
a safety net if something went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   June Bozeman, of Blue Cross &AMP; Blue Shield of Georgia, was keenly
aware of the community's sorrow. With roots in Gainesville, she
understood the town and the scars the tornado left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had already been involved with the churches and blood
drives trying to do everything we could,'' said Bozeman, a provider
network consultant for the insurer.
</P>
<P>
   But when she got a call from Cox's office, she immediately saw
how the insurer could do some good.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, a reversal is not covered by insurance companies.
Couples often must pay between $4,000 and $8,000 for the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   But because of the unusual circumstances, Blue Cross decided to
cover any hospital bills for services. The hospital also agreed to
provide its services at a deeply discounted rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I know, we've never done anything like this
before,'' said Bozeman, who brokered the deal between the insurer
and the hospital. ``But we thought we could really help bring a
positive ending to a truly tragic situation.''
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of July 27, Robynn was admitted to the hospital's
outpatient surgery wing. She was calm as she was prepared for
surgery. Cox held her hand as she drifted into drug-induced sleep.
Shannon waited outside.
</P>
<P>
   The surgery, which took about an hour and a half, went well. Cox
shot a dye through her fallopian tubes at the conclusion to check
his handiwork. It traveled through her tubes without difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   When she woke, Shannon was waiting and told her the good news.
As she curled back to sleep, Shannon kept vigil by her bedside
through the night.
</P>
<P>
   Now the couple is back at home in an apartment complex outside
Gainesville. Shannon, a machinist, plans to return to his job at
SKF Bearing Manufacturers in Flowery Branch by mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   And Robynn plans to work as a day care worker in the fall at
Challenged Child, a special needs school that gave Haley so much
happiness.
</P>
<P>
   They hope for a child. The first six months is the most
promising after a reversal, with the pregnancy rate hovering
between 60 and 80 percent for women who've had the procedure.
Because Robynn is young and the tubal ligation was recent, the odds
are even better.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time, we're hoping for a boy,'' Robynn said. ``But we're
really leaving it up to God. Shannon and I have been through a lot
and we've learned to take things day to day.''
</P>
<P>
   Shannon agrees. Right now, he said his priority is to remember
the blessings and keep his marriage strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our marriage has gotten much deeper because of this,'' he
said. ``There's been so much togetherness. So much involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
