<HEADER>
A1644 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSTON-ART-HUB-1200(3     08-06 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-ART-HUB-1200(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BOSTON, ALL ROADS LEAD TO MUSEUMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston, the ``Athens of America'' a century ago, is called the
Hub by its current residents. Certainly in terms of art, the
moniker is apt. Museums abound, large and small, old and new,
independently run or affiliated with colleges. Some are in the
heart of the city; others form a bright constellation across the
surrounding countryside. At this time of year, most are conserving
energy for the season ahead, and big-effort shows are at a minimum.
But summer downtime is always a good time for a museum visit. The
atmosphere has a casual, glad-to-be-in-the-shade feel.
Permanent-collection galleries are uncrowded and inviting. And
exhibitions that are low on buzz but packed with ideas have a
chance of getting the attention they deserve.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Fine Arts in Boston, long one of the nation's
cultural treasures, is already revving its engines for ``Monet in
the 20th Century,'' a blockbuster, replete with advance-sale
tickets and hotel package deals, set to open next month. But
there's plenty to see before the crowds descend.
</P>
<P>
   Of two current shows, the smaller is a genial gathering of eight
big recent paintings by David Hockney, the British-born artist who
has lived in California since the early 1960s. Hockney is best
known for his figurative work, notably depictions of Angelenos
living the luxe life around backyard pools. But most of the
paintings here take the form of bird's-eye views of his native
turf: the villages and rolling moors of Yorkshire in northern
England. This is an art of pastiche in every way. Each landscape is
a composite both of snapshots taken by the artist and of various
styles from art history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Road to York Through Sledmere,'' for example, mixes a
splash of Stanley Spencer and a dab of Richard Diebenkorn in a rich
sauce of Fauve-Pop colors. Hockney has also cited as inspiration
the 19th-century landscape painter Thomas Moran, whose
billboard-size paintings of the American West creaked and rumbled
through the National Gallery of Art in Washington last year.
</P>
<P>
   Moran's flair for scale had roots in a popular tradition of
painted panoramas, the equivalents of Hollywood films in pre-Civil
War America. And Hockney's new work suggests his own preoccupation
with stage design, especially for opera. He brings to the dour
Yorkshire landscape the same hot, transformative palette and
perspectival ingenuity that have distinguished his sets for Mozart
and Wagner, and the results are pretty magical. (Incidentally, the
``Magic Flute'' production Hockney designed will be revived at the
Metropolitan Opera in December.)
</P>
<P>
   If the Hockney showcase is an uncomplicated delight, the second
Museum of Fine Arts exhibition, ``Photoimage: Printmaking '60s to
'90s,'' is something else: a thematic survey of complex variety and
conceptual ambition. Its premise is to examine the inventive ways
in which photography has been incorporated into contemporary art,
losing its documentary function and shaping hybrid versions of
reality in which fact and fantasy blend.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition that results, organized by Clifford Ackley and
embracing work by 72 artists, is visually arresting, historically
sweeping and packed with ideas. At the early end of the spectrum,
one finds Robert Rauschenberg's groundbreaking lithographs,
including ``License'' (1962), in which the Abstract Expressionist
brush strokes serve as busywork filler for a collage of news photos
and snapshots. Pop enters triumphantly with Andy Warhol's glorious
silk-screened Marilyns and Maos, which Ackley complements with less
familiar versions of the same icons: a blurry Mao by Gerhard
Richter, a sheet of Marilyns by the British artist Richard
Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Technologically, the show is brought into the present with
computer-generated prints by Ronald Jones and Annette Lemieux, and
by Kiki Smith's wall-filling, multipart ``Banshee Pearls,'' whose
reiterated self-portraits and images of skulls are exemplary of a
1990s sensibility. But then, the whole show feels very much of the
moment: Its blend of popular culture, personal obsession, social
uneasiness and formal finesse is entirely in the spirit of new art
being produced today.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, no visit to the museum is complete without a dip
into its dazzling permanent collections. These include the most
comprehensive holdings in Japanese painting in the West, a whole
roomful of John Singleton Copley portraits, and a matchless range
of American decorative arts, thriving under the admirable
stewardship of Jonathan L. Fairbanks.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard University, just across the Charles River in Cambridge,
has so many museums on campus that it constitutes a mini-Hub of its
own. And some of these have impressive offerings this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Pride of place goes to ``Princes, Poets and Paladins: Islamic
and Indian Paintings From the Collection of Prince and Princess
Sadruddin Aga Khan,'' at the Arthur M. Sackler Museum. The show,
alas, has only three more days to run, but anyone who can catch it
just under the wire will be amply rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   Originating at the British Museum and accompanied by an
authoritative catalog by Sheila R. Canby, the selection encompasses
nearly four centuries of manuscript pages from one of the world's
premier private collections. The images range from a portrait of
lumpish, red-cheeked Ottoman Sultan Selim II holding a teensy gold
wine cup (he was known as ``Selim the Sot''), to chic Mughal court
ladies waving lighted sparklers, to Deccani paintings whose
palettes of canteloupe-orange, mustards and lavender prefigure
Bonnard (or for that matter Hockney) by centuries.
</P>
<P>
   But the star attraction is a handful of pages from the so-called
``Houghton Shahnama'' or Book of Kings, commissioned around 1522 by
the Safavid Emperor Shah Tahmasp. The book survived intact into the
20th century, only to be broken up by an American owner in the
1970s. Among the gems at the Sackler _ and one of the greatest of
all Persian paintings _ is ``The Court of the Gayumars,'' a
visionary fantasia of gilded skies, purple rocks studded with
countless tiny faces, and courtiers dressed in leopard-skin coats.
It is said that the page took three years to complete. Stunning is
the only word for it.
</P>
<P>
   Half a block away at the Fogg Art Museum, other manuscripts, of
more recent date, are on view in ``Brice Marden: Work Books,''
organized by Dieter Schwarz, Michael Semff, James Cuno and Harry
Cooper, and visiting Cambridge from the Winterthur Museum in
Switzerland. The show brings together nearly 40 series of drawings
from the artist's notebooks, from 1964 to 1995, and executed in
locations from Greece to India to New York.
</P>
<P>
   The images include early landscapes, Minimalist grids and
organically spun-out skeins of lines inspired by Chinese
calligraphy. Together they suggest how much of a piece this
artist's career has been. Motifs recur, build and change over time,
varying in expressive weight from the hard, adamant verticals of
the ``Suicide Notes'' to the agitated lyricism of ``Athena's
Notebook'' (1979-81).
</P>
<P>
   Whether Marden is drawing with pen, pencil or twigs dipped in
ink, he is a searching draftsman in whom nature and the personal
meet, but always at what feels like a tentative distance. This is
the most persuasive show of Marden's I have yet seen.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Wellesley College, in a verdant suburb west of Boston, is home
to the handsome Davis Museum and Cultural Center, which is showing
``Who Are You? Selected Works by Adrian Piper.'' Ms. Piper, a
member of the Wellesley faculty, has long been one of the country's
more provocative political artists, and this tautly edited
anthology of her conceptually based autobiographical work is a good
summing up of her career thus far.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest piece is the drawing ``Self-Portrait Exaggerating
My Negroid Features'' (1981), followed by the series of business
cards she created in 1986, one of which reads ``Dear Friend. I am
black. I am sure you did not realize this when you made/laughed
at/agreed with that racist remark.'' In the 1988 video installation
``Cornered,'' Ms. Piper is sitting at a table and speaking directly
into the camera about the racism that permeates American culture.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when activist art is out of favor in the mainstream
art world, Ms. Piper's intelligent and implacable presence is
particularly valuable.
</P>
<P>
   A short drive from Wellesley, and not far from Thoreau's Walden,
the DeCordova Museum in Lincoln sits turretlike on a high hill
overlooking an unbroken woodland vista. Once a private estate, the
museum opened in 1950 with a strong educational bent and a mission
to collect and exhibit contemporary work, primarily by artists from
the region.
</P>
<P>
   The DeCordova recently inaugurated a new 15,000-square-foot
wing; its light-washed interior staircase climbs several stories up
the hillside. Exhibitions in place there include the 1998 edition
of the ``DeCordova Annual Exhibition''; a showcase of sculptures by
Niki Ketchman; photographs (Dore Gardner's black-and-white shots of
Mexico look especially good), and a lively series of videos made by
teen-agers in the working-class city of Somerville under the
direction of the photographer Roberto Arevalo.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, installed in the museum's original galleries, is a
selection of paintings from the permanent collection organized by
Nick Capasso, ``Abstract Expressionism/Figurative Expressionism:
Common Ground.'' The show is uneven, but it has good things,
ranging from abstractions by New England artists of an older
generation _ like Maud Morgan, who is 95 and represented by a
misty, romantic painting in yellow and beige _ to figurative work
by fine younger painters like Sam Messer and Adam Cvijanovic.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Morgan has a show of her own in Brockton, at the Fuller
Museum of Art, another small, New England-oriented institution
built in idyllic surroundings, in this case on a pond near an
Olmstead-designed park. ``Maude Morgan: Making Prints 1969-1976,''
organized by Wendy Tarlow Kaplan, includes 29 seriographs, two
lithographs and an embossed print by the artist, in all of which
the brushy style of the painting at the DeCordova is replaced by
stencil-crisp biomorphic forms in solid, saturated colors.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the compositions suggest battle-of-the-sexes
psychological narratives, as in ``Purple Dominant,'' with its
central phallic form, or ``Meeting,'' in which two identical
hatchet-shaped forms, one white, one black, intersect and seem
ready to come to blows.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the work gives evidence of the artist's rapt
enthusiasm for, and contribution to, postwar hard-edge abstraction
and Op Art. Ms. Morgan is a remarkable figure: she knew Hemingway
and Joyce in Paris, studied with Hans Hofmann in the 1930's and
showed with Betty Parsons in Manhattan for years. It's great to see
her here.
</P>
<P>
   Among Massachusetts museums, the Peabody Essex in Salem,
combining two formerly separate institutions, is a cross-cultural
marvel. Much of its collection was accumulated willy-nilly more
than a century ago in the venerable port of Salem, and the result
is a vast curiosity cabinet of art objects, artifacts and souvenirs
(the distinctions are hazy) brought together from America, Europe,
Africa, Asia and the South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Here one finds a major collection of American portraits (by
Copley, Trumbull, Stuart), marine paintings (several by the
Luminist Fitz Hugh Lane who spent his life in nearby Gloucester)
and ship figureheads (windblown maidens, highland dancers, Spanish
grandees). There are also fascinating Japanese and Indian materials
(two elaborate portable Shinto shrines, for example); world-class
holdings in China Trade porcelain, and acres of indigenous work
from the Pacific (with the requisite, scary ``headhunting''
relics.)
</P>
<P>
   The museum is still collecting, and is up-to-the-minute enough
to be showing both an interesting series of paintings by the
contemporary Indian artist M.K. Husain from the 1980s, dedicated to
Mother Teresa, as well as a small oil by the estimable Norman
Rockwell, an artist in the tradition of American genre painting
dating back to the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   And one can get no better sense of the depths of the museum's
fabulously unfocused collection than in a grab bag of an
exhibition, ``Tales From the Vault: A to Z,'' which includes, among
many, many other things, a size 37 shoe worn by the world's tallest
man, circa 1938; a formidable ``Nevaspred'' girdle from the same
era; an avidly grinning 17th-century Bhutanese dance mask, and a
little Chinese bridal headdress woven of azure kingfisher feathers
and meant to make its wearer feel like a goddess for a day.
</P>
<P>
   Two other important museums are situated at a distance from
Boston but are squarely on the route for visitors coming to or from
New York. The Worcester Art Museum, founded in 1896 by citizens
anxious to smooth the rough edges of an industrial boomtown, is a
textbook example of Gilded Age philanthropy in action. And although
the museum is relatively quiet at the moment, there is, as always,
much to see.
</P>
<P>
   The young Venezuelan-born artist Arturo Herrera, for example,
has recently completed a mural on a wall high above the museum's
imposing Renaissance Court. The painting, with its spare, clean,
wide-open forms (one is reminded of Ms. Morgan's prints), is
basically abstract but carries witty, oblique references both to
its architectural setting and to the extraordinary Roman hunting
mosaic installed in the floor below.
</P>
<P>
   Worcester's classical holdings, many acquired from a dig the
museum helped sponsor at Antioch in Syria in the 1930s, are strong
and a sampling of them is included in new Roman sculpture gallery
recently created under the direction of Christine Kondoleon. The
compact display, titled ``Roman Art and Life Revealed,'' is
elegantly arranged, annotated with stimulating texts, and includes
some memorable things: a marble bust of the somewhat dim-looking
Emperor Caligula from around A.D. 40 (note the Bill Clinton nose)
and a marvelously funky Etruscan cinerary urn (160-140 B.C.) on the
lid of which the elderly patron reclines, propped up on pillows,
while bas-relief soldiers duke it out below.
</P>
<P>
   Springfield comes near the western end of the Massachusetts
Turnpike and is a jumping-off spot for the Berkshires, upstate New
York and Vermont, areas that warrant art excursions of their own.
But the city's cluster of museums, which face one another across a
manicured, campuslike quadrangle, is solidly in the Hub's cultural
sphere: urbane in spirit, international in outlook, curatorially
savvy.
</P>
<P>
   The Springfield Museum of Fine Art was financed by one James
Philip Gray (1835-1904), a retired coal and lumber merchant who
left his estate for the ``purchase, preservation and exhibition of
the most valuable, meritorious, artistic and high class oil
paintings obtainable.'' A tall order, but he got what he paid for
in the museum's permanent collection of Colonial-era American
portraits and in Winslow Homer's exquisite ``Promenade on the
Beach.'' Another, later donor, Raymond A. Bidwell (1876-1954),
contributed more than 3,000 Japanese woodcut prints, which
instantly and forever put the museum on the Asian art map.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
</TEXT>
