<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1652 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WKD-BOSTON-ART-HUB-3R     08-06 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WKD-BOSTON-ART-HUB-3RDTAKE(730)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: art map. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Other American portraits are on view across the quadrangle at
the Connecticut Valley Historical Museum, in a fine little show
with the slightly iffy title of ``Wheelchair Unbound,'' devoted to
the painter Joseph Whiting Stock (1815-1855). A Springfield-born
artist who was paralyzed in a childhood accident and trained
himself to paint, he is represented here by a touching group of
family portraits, which give a sense of how precious and protective
a thing community was in early America. He is also seen in a
striking self-portrait from around 1843, and again in a
daguerreotype made a few years later, where he looks sucked dry by
the tuberculosis that did him in at the age of 40.
</P>
<P>
   Stock's was a sad story of pluck in the face of misfortune, but
to conclude a Boston area tour on an upbeat note, one has only to
return to the Springfield Museum and stay a spell in the permanent
gallery devoted to the painter Erastus Salisbury Field (1805-1900).
Born in nearby Leverett, he was a beguiling if idiosyncratic
portraitist (his female subjects tend to wear their hairdos like
ill-fitting caps) before turning his attention to biblical and
historical subjects.
</P>
<P>
   His masterpiece _ and it is a masterpiece _ is the ``Historical
Monument of the American Republic,'' which he began at the end of
the Civil War, when the country's heroic pioneer past seemed like a
mirage, and its future looked uncertain. The painting is a
mural-size panorama of classical temples and stacked-up ziggurats,
each decorated with minute copies of historical works by earlier
American painters, contemporary references (``The Assassination and
Apotheosis of Lincoln''), and allegorical emblems, from Pilgrims
and Indians, to angels symbolizing truth and righteousness.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting confection suggests both a painted backdrop for a
19th-century grand opera and, in its fantastical way, the bristling
skylines of contemporary cities like Boston and New York. One
senses that an artist like Hockney would feel right at home with
Field's spectacularly mongrel magnum opus. And there's no question
that its ingredients sum up an American artistic self-image in a
nutshell: think-big aspirations, down-to-earth facts, and the hope
for a home fire, a quick prayer and a good yarn at the end of the
road.
</P>
<P>
   Here is information about the Boston area exhibitions discussed
in the art review.
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM OF FINE ARTS IN BOSTON, 465 Huntington Avenue, Boston,
(617) 267-9300. ``New Paintings by David Hockney'' (through Aug.
23). ``Photoimage: Printmaking 60's to 90's'' (through Sept. 27).
</P>
<P>
   ARTHUR M. SACKLER MUSEUM, Harvard University, 485 Broadway, at
Quincy Street, Cambridge, (617) 495-9400. ``Princes, Poets and
Paladins: Islamic and Indian Paintings From the Collection of
Prince and Princess Sadruddin Aga Khan'' (through Sunday).
</P>
<P>
   FOGG ART MUSEUM, Harvard University, 32 Quincy Street,
Cambridge, (617) 495-9400. ``Brice Marden: Work Books'' (through
Sept. 6).
</P>
<P>
   DAVIS MUSEUM AND CULTURAL CENTER, Wellesley College, 106 Central
Street, Wellesley, (781) 283-2051 ``Who Are You? Selected Works by
Adrian Piper'' (through Aug. 16).
</P>
<P>
   DeCORDOVA MUSEUM AND SCULPTURE PARK, 51 Sandy Pond Road,
Lincoln, (781) 259-8355. ``Photographs From the Permanent
Collection: People and Places'' (through Sept. 7). ``Abstract
Expressionism/Figurative Expressionism: Common Ground''
(continuing). ``1998 DeCordova Annual Exhibition'' (through Sept.
7). ``Niki Ketchman: Fabrications'' (through May 1999). ``The
Mirror Project: Videos by Somerville Youth'' (through Oct. 4).
</P>
<P>
   FULLER MUSEUM OF ART, 455 Oak Street, Brockton, (508) 588-6000.
``Maude Morgan: Making Prints 1969-1976'' (through Sept. 6).
</P>
<P>
   PEABODY ESSEX MUSEUM, East India Square, Salem, (978) 745-1876.
``Tales From the Vault: A to Z'' (through Aug. 18).
</P>
<P>
   WORCESTER ART MUSEUM, 55 Salisbury Street, Worcester, (508)
799-4406. ``Wall Project,'' by Arturo Herrera, (through Jan. 3).
``Roman Art and Life Revealed'' in the new gallery of Roman
sculpture (ongoing).
</P>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD MUSEUM OF FINE ARTS, 220 State Street, Springfield,
(413) 263-6800. ``Japanese Scrolls and Prints'' (through Sept. 13).
</P>
<P>
   CONNECTICUT VALLEY HISTORICAL MUSEUM, 220 State Street,
Springfield, (413) 263-6800. ``Wheelchair Unbound: The Art of
Joseph Whiting Stock'' (through March 2000).
</P>
