<HEADER>
A1657 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      08-06 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADDITIONS IN TEXAS AND A NEW ARMORY SHOW IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Texas)  (js) 
 By Carol Vogel   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Australian Chief For the Kimbell
</P>
<P>
   After a six-month search, the Kimbell Art Museum in Fort Worth
has named Timothy Potts, director of the National Gallery of
Victoria in Melbourne, Australia, to be its new director. Potts,
who will begin his job in early fall, is replacing Edmund Pillsbury
who had been the Kimbell's director for 17 and a half years and had
announced his intention to leave in January. Potts will be the
third director the 26-year-old museum has had.
</P>
<P>
   Potts, 40, is not well known within the museum world here or in
Texas. But officials at the Kimbell looked beyond the usual roster
of names.
</P>
<P>
   As director of the National Gallery of Victoria for three years,
Potts presided over the oldest and largest public collection in
Australia. Founded in 1861, it has about 70,000 works in its
permanent collection ranging from antiquities right up through
modern masters.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure Potts, who is from Sydney , made the permanent
collection free to visitors for the first time in nearly 30 years.
This doubled the institution's annual attendance to more than 1.2
million, making it the most visited museum in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   He also led a building redevelopment, the first phase of which
will cost $85 million. Most of that money has already been raised
from public and private sources. The project will include
refurbishing and reconfiguring the museum's existing building and
creating more exhibition space. Currently only about 5 percent of
the collection is on display.
</P>
<P>
   Potts, whose background is in ancient art and archeology, has
been a professor at the University of Melbourne and an adjunct
professor at La Trobe University, also in Melbourne. He also has a
business background. For five years before joining the National
Gallery of Victoria he was based in New York and London as a
director of the media and telecommunications group in the corporate
finance department of Lehman Brothers, the investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   Potts said the offer to run the Kimbell, a modest-sized museum
with a small but top-quality permanent collection and a large
endowment, was irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no plans to leave Melbourne,'' he said. ``But this was
so much the right thing, I had to grab it.''
</P>
<P>
   Potts said he welcomed the opportunity to put on exhibitions
that, while serious, will appeal to a broad audience.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``One of the attractive things will also be the
ability to acquire works of art in earnest. I wouldn't be coming if
I couldn't.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Landscapes for Houston
</P>
<P>
   As American paintings catapult into the price stratospheres of
European paintings, the Museum of Fine Arts in Houston has received
two important American works: William Merritt Chase's ``Sunlight
and Shadow, Shinnecock Hills'' (1895) and Charles Willson Peale's
``Landscape Looking Toward Sellers Hall From Mill Bank'' (1818).
The paintings are a gift from Nancy Hart Glanville, a trustee who,
along with her late husband James Glanville, began collecting
American art during the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both paintings are significant,'' said Emily Ballew Neff, the
museum's curator of American painting and sculpture. ``The Peale
builds strength on strength. We have five works by members of the
Peale family, and this will be the sixth. That it is a landscape by
Charles Willson Peale makes it extremely rare because he did so
few. It is part of the nascent development that gave rise to the
Hudson River School.''
</P>
<P>
   Neff said the Chase work was one of the Shinnecock landscapes,
which are considered the most mature among the artist's works.
Though the museum has a number of pieces by Chase, this is the
first of the Shinnecock landscapes to enter the collection.
</P>
<P>
   The gift comes in the middle of the museum's capital campaign
drive to help finance a $50 million building currently under
construction. The new structure will more than double the museum,
adding permanent galleries for American art, which the museum has
never had.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dealers Show to Move
</P>
<P>
   The dealers who organized the highly successful Gramercy
International Art Fair announced after the fifth one ended in May
that they had had enough. Though they still liked the concept of a
fair that was accessible to small dealers, as the number of
visitors grew, the Gramercy Hotel, where the fair was held, became
an impractical place in which to see art.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted a new challenge,'' said Matthew Marks, the Chelsea
dealer who was one of the organizers of the Gramercy.
</P>
<P>
   Now Marks and some of the other dealers involved with the
Gramercy are planning a new fair, to debut in February.
</P>
<P>
   Called the ``International Art Show,'' it will be held from Feb.
18 to 22 at the 69th Regiment Armory at 26th Street, the site of
the famous Armory Show of 1913. The dates were purposely selected
to coincide with the American Art Dealers Association show at the
7th Regiment Armory, which will exhibit more classical material as
well as works on the secondary market, while the International Art
Show will feature only dealers who represent new artists.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most fairs in New York, which are the invention of
professional show organizers, this fair, like the Gramercy, is
being put together by dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a list of 100 galleries that we respected from all
over the world,'' said Marks, who explained that the armory can fit
70 dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Participants so far include Marks, Jeffrey Deitch, Brooke
Alexander, Paul Kasmin and Barbara Gladstone, all from New York;
Christian Nagel from Cologne; Marta Cervera from Madrid, and
Maureen Paley from London.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1820EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
