<HEADER>
A1658 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TITANIC-$ADV08-COX     08-06 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TITANIC-$ADV08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DISCOVERY CHANNEL PLANS LIVE VISIT TO SUNKEN TITANIC
 &HT;    680&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment
categories for release Saturday, Aug. 8.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a search for relics and ratings, the Discovery
Channel will send remote-control camera vehicles to the floor of
the North Atlantic next Sunday (Aug. 16) and telecast a ``live,''
two-hour visit to the sunken luxury liner Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the network's second visit to the legendary ship. An
account of the first expedition was seen in April 1997, by nearly
3.2 million viewers, making it Discovery's highest-rated program to
date.
</P>
<P>
   Using camera-carrying remote operating vehicles (ROVs), some as
small as three feet long, producers hope in the current expedition
to present views of the ship's bow, now famous because of scenes
from the 20th Century Fox movie that won 11 Oscar awards, as well
as the interior of the wreckage of the luxury liner.
</P>
<P>
   The program, titled ``Titanic Live,'' will be seen in more than
100 countries with simultaneous translations into Spanish,
Mandarin, Thai and Japanese, network officials said. In addition to
real-time views from a squadron of ROVs, the program is to include
some previously taped segments.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery Channel spokespersons said the expedition will last a
month. The network's Internet site, Discovery Online
(http://www.discovery.com), will post live ``webcasts'' throughout
the expedition and allow viewers to ask their own questions of a
team of explorers.
</P>
<P>
   Among other tasks, the expedition will try to retrieve a 20-ton
section of the ship's hull. A similar attempt in 1996 was
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Reid, executive producer for the Discovery Channel, said
that at the request of the Marconi Foundation, an attempt also will
be made to retrieve the wireless radio equipment over which
Titanic's largely futile appeals for help were broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   A team of scientists, historians and explorers accompanying the
expedition, hope to learn such things as:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The nature of microorganisms that appear to be eating away at
metal in the ship;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If and why rivets failed when the ship collided with an
iceberg 325 miles off the coast of Newfoundland in 1912 on its
maiden voyage.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Whether pieces of the vessel can be photographed and digitally
``reassembled,'' similar to the way federal investigators piece
together sections of a crashed airliner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to create a tool that naval architects and engineers
can use to study the wreck,'' Reid said. ``We plan to digitally
create a data bank of 24,000 photographs of the entire debris
field.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a camera vehicle will survey the sunken bow and stern,
which are separated by about a half-mile, as well as debris lying
between them, keeping track of its precise position each time it
takes a picture.
</P>
<P>
   When ``reassembled'' with the aid of computers, the images may
shed light on such questions as why the ship's stern shows so much
damage, whether parts of the ship ``imploded'' and where boilers
exploded after the collision, Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   He said microbial ecologist Roy Cullimore of the University of
Regina in Saskatchewan, Canada, will study iron-eating bacteria he
believes are devouring elements of the ship's steel, creating
rust-like formations called rusticles that have been observed in
previous expeditions.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Foecke, a metallurgist with the National Institute of
Standards and Technology, will try to extend his earlier
observation that the Titanic may have been built of metal that was
not consistently strong. Foecke says he has found poor-quality
metal in some of the rivets that held the ship's hull together.
</P>
<P>
   Angus Best, a British geologist, will collect geological samples
from the sea floor around the ship in an effort to determine how
fast it sank.
</P>
<P>
   Also on hand will be Bill Willard, a Seneca, S.C., high school
physics teacher, who with his wife, Susan, designed one of the ROVs
that will try to photograph scenes inside the remains of the ship.
Susan Willard, also a physics teacher, will be in the Discovery
Channel studio, providing commentary on the expedition, Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Robert Ballard, an undersea explorer, located the Titanic in
1985 in 12,000 feet of water. He earlier located the sunken remains
of the German battleship Bismarck and two months ago announced that
he had located the U.S. aircraft carrier U.S.S. Yorktown in the
North Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Cooperating in the expedition is RMS Titanic, Inc., a New York
salvage company that recently obtained rulings by a federal judge
in Norfolk, Va., giving it exclusive photographic rights to the
wreck and drawing a 175-square-mile ``keep out'' safety zone around
the ocean surface immediately above the sunken luxury liner.
</P>
<P>
   The rulings are being appealed by a British sightseeing company
that has sold tickets for $32,500 each for Titanic visits aboard
deep-sea submersibles.
</P>
<P>
   Although RMS Titanic Inc. has said it will keep any artifacts
retrieved from the wreck site in an intact collection for public
exhibition, it has sold several thousand pieces of Titanic fuel
coal, each about the size of a nickel, for $10 each.
</P>
<P>
   Company spokesman Allen Carlan said a law journal report that
the company would receive $6 million from the Discovery Channel for
the right to produce and air the program was not accurate. But he
refused to say how much RMS Titanic Inc. was being paid, explaining
that the company had a ``confidentiality agreement'' with the
network.
</P>
<P>
   The Discovery Channel is cable television network that includes
the Learning Channel, Animal Planet, Travel Channel and Discovery
Civilizational Channel. Cox Enterprises is a shareholder in the
Discovery Channel network.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
