<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1666 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-ART-2     08-06 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: de Wolfe.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Some of it is wackadoo stuff, just heaven,'' said Ms. Scaife's
decorator, Louis Talotta. His favorite piece is an early
18th-century Regence commode, which was encased in etched mirror in
the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Talotta added, ``Most mirrored furniture is just mirror over
plywood.''
</P>
<P>
   Depending on quality and provenance, the price of mirrored
furniture ranges widely, from a couple of thousand dollars for a
simple night stand to $38,000 for a trio of mid-Victorian mirrored
valances, owned in the 1940s by the decorator Rose Cumming and now
at the Manhattan gallery of R. Louis Bofferding on East 71st
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Finding mirrored furniture is easy, but finding it in its
original state is more difficult. ``It doesn't travel well,'' Ms.
Scaife said ruefully of her mirrored treasures.
</P>
<P>
   And should the original glass break, said Roger Prigent of
Malmaison Antiques on East 74th Street, ``matching it is not easy,
and finding someone who can do the work properly is a nightmare.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  At Malmaison, mirrored furniture _ like a chinoiserie
smoked-mirror dressing table by Jansen for $15,000 or a pair of
anonymous American night stands owned by the late philanthropist
Mary Lasker for $6,000 _ is always in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Mirrors were especially popular in the 1930s as the tops of
dining tables. Jansen, the deluxe Parisian decorating company
between the world wars, habitually specified them for grand clients
like the Duke and Duchess of Windsor.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, glare walked hand in hand with glamour, especially in
sunny rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``To give lunches on a mirror-top table must have been
blinding,'' said Bofferding, who specializes in high-style
decorator furniture from the 30s through the 50s. Not to mention
exceedingly unflattering. As Bofferding noted, ``Every double chin
was highlighted, every crow's foot magnified.''
</P>
<P>
   That might explain why the Duchess of Windsor soon replaced the
mirrored top of the three-pedestal dining table in her Parisian
house with a sober stretch of polished mahogany. The William and
Mary-style table, which the Windsors bought around 1938, sold at
Sotheby's last year for $112,500.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the Windsor sale was a Louis XV-style desk, covered with
reverse-painted mirrors depicting gold rococo scrolls. It sold for
$107,000, more than double its estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Like many rich women of her day, the duchess was introduced to
the marvels of mirrors through the English decorator Syrie Maugham
and her American rival, de Wolfe. Maugham, arguably the more
inventive, devised the defining mirrored object of the 1920s: a
room-height folding screen made of seven-inch-wide panels of mirror
framed in half-inch strips of chrome or beveled glass.
</P>
<P>
   When opened into silvery accordion pleats, wrote the decorator
Mark Hampton,``the screen gave the effect of a row of giant
prisms.'' He found one packed away in crates in a client's garage
and insisted on setting it up again.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, de Wolfe became a champion of the all-mirror
room, like the bedroom she installed around 1933 in the Park Avenue
apartment of Robert Rubin, where even the fireplace, cornices and
baseboards were made of molded and beveled mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   Later dismantled and owned by the auctioneer Robert Woolley,
many of the bedroom's architectural elements were eventually bought
by Bofferding. He sold the Rubin fireplace surround to the art
dealer Matthew Marks and recycled what remained of the reflective
odds and ends into a coffee table, a large mirror and a pair of
side tables.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the practicality of mirrored furniture that has made
it popular in America, Prigent said, especially dressing tables:
``If you spill perfume on a wooden top, it will eat through the
varnish. But glass _ you can spill anything on it and just wipe it
up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
