<SLUG> BC-AMEX-OUTLOOK-250&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN EXPRESS STOCK FALLS AFTER COMPANY CITES OVERSEAS WOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nervous investors drove shares of American Express
Co. down 6.8 percent Thursday after the company warned that its
growth overseas would be hampered by the Asian financial crisis and
a broader softening of the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the interdependencies among markets, the effects of Asia
will eventually spill over,'' American Express chief executive
Harvey Golub told analysts at a meeting in New York on Wednesday.
``We can expect to see the impact of Asia on Latin America, and
have seen it to some extent in Europe and the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   American Express is one of the most geographically diverse U.S.
companies and, while no single company is a proxy for financial
developments overseas, many analysts and investors look to American
Express for insights about global business prospects _ particularly
as they pertain to the company's core travel services and credit
and charge card operations.
</P>
<P>
   Golub said American Express had hoped, within a ``reasonable
time frame,'' to increase its overseas profit 25 percent to 30
percent a year, with earnings from abroad accounting for half of
overall profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current economic slowdown, however, is depressing the
financial results of both our card and travel business and will
likely delay our progress in attaining these `mix' goals,'' he told
the analysts.
</P>
<P>
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, shares of American
Express plunged $7.375 Thursday, to $101.0625, on nearly five times
the normal trading volume.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I don't think the sky is falling because it's too early to
figure it out,'' said Samuel Liss, an analyst with Credit Suisse
First Boston. ``I think the Asian problem and the impact of the
euro on their foreign-exchange business are among some of the
things they need to consider.''
</P>
<P>
   Golub spoke privately with the analysts Wednesday, and the
company did not distribute copies of his statements more widely
until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Golub said he thought the company would
``continue to do well, but it will not be as easy or simple to
match the performance of the last two quarters.''
</P>
<P>
   American Express has posted solid financial results lately,
driven by an upswing in its card business and tighter expense
controls. The company recently reported that its second-quarter
profit increased 11 percent, to $578 million, compared with $520
million in the quarter a year earlier. Revenue rose 8 percent, to
$4.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But Golub said there were important unknowns, including the
possibility of further economic deterioration in Japan or a
downturn in China, as possible ``risks in our ability to cope.''
</P>
<P>
   Another blow for American Express was its decision this year not
to bid on the U.S. government's card account, which had been an
important account to the company in terms of billing volume and
number of cards. Golub said American Express was not willing to go
after a contract with the government if a bidding war meant that
that the profitability of its card business would suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts thought that the stock market overreacted Thursday
to Golub's comments, noting that the warning was evidence of
cautious management and a prudent approach, given current economic
uncertainties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at this company and think they have a lot of
flexibility on the expense side and have a strong financial
cushion,'' said Susan Roth of Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. She
added that ``all financial service companies are considering how
their resources should be managed, given the spillover from Asia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
