<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-COMPUTERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER A NECESSITY ON CAMPUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - What once was a luxury for college-bound students now
has become as standard as JanSport backpack and a Sony Walkman.
</P>
<P>
   Personal computers have moved from novelty to necessity in the
'90s, despite large computing resources on most college campuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly encourage all students to come with a computer,''
said Bill Lewis, vice provost for technology at Arizona State
University in Tempe. ``We do provide computers on campus, but you
have to get in line and wait.''
</P>
<P>
   With one computer to every 17 students, ASU beats the
educational goal of 1-to-20. But statistics are little consolation
when you're camped out for hours watching other students hunt and
peck on a keyboard the night before your major research paper is
due.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for students, the price of personal computers continues
to plummet. Much of the credit goes to Intel Corp., which recently
slashed the price for its 266-megahertz Celeron processor to $86
from $106, its lowest in years.
</P>
<P>
   Even Mac devotees can find deals. Apple Computer is releasing
its first consumer-oriented Mac, the iMac, next week. Price:
$1,299.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers, never ones to miss a marketing opportunity, are
jumping on the back-to-school bandwagon to sell systems and
software.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly think that going back to school is a great time
to find some deals,'' said Carol Elfstrom, a spokeswoman for
CompUSA in Dallas. The chain is taking reservations for the iMac
and offering $800 worth of mail-in coupons for Apple-related
software and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   In the more prevalent IBM-compatible world, computermakers are
offering discounts for college students. Dell Computer Corp. is
offering five systems, ranging in configuration from minitowers to
notebooks, for students who can prove they are enrolled in college.
The systems start at $1,540 and top out at $2,950.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Compaq Computer Corp. is offering $100 mail-in
rebates on its Presario PC, monitor and color inkjet printer. The
PCs range from $799 to $2,299, after the rebate, and are sold at
major computer stores.
</P>
<P>
   But savvy students may want to wait to get to campus before
plunking down any money. At ASU, for example, Dell, Apple and
others offer discounts through its computer store. Other
universities offer similar deals through campus book stores.
</P>
<P>
   Even bigger savings can be had on software.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would wait to tell them to buy their software,'' ASU's Lewis
said. ``The educational price is much, much better than you get at
the computer stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis cited a $250 discount on a $300 word processing,
spreadsheet and presentation software package. Similarly, the
widely used Statistical Package for the Social Sciences goes for
$1,200 in computer stores but only $150 from the ASU Computing
Store.
</P>
<P>
   As for the laptop vs. desktop question, students should consider
space, convenience and theft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recommend a laptop because of the convenience of being able
to take it to class to take notes or work on in other areas of
campus,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   But the downside for laptops are their premium cost and
temptation for theft. Although cable locks are available to
discourage theft, a good pair of wire cutters can get around them.
</P>
<P>
   Desktop computers, meanwhile, are cheaper, less of a target for
thieves and can be expanded with faster microprocessors and other
components.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, more students than ever are investing in PCs. A
study last year by ASU found that 60 percent of students have PCs.
</P>
<P>
   And a recent survey by electronics store Best Buy found that 39
percent of all freshmen would pick a computer or word processor
over a stereo (23 percent) or TV (13 percent) if they could take
only one item to their college dorm room.
</P>
<P>
   Colleges are responding by wiring more of their dorms than ever
with high-speed Internet connections. At ASU, several dorms have 10
megabit connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're actually using it to help market certain dorms to
students,'' Lewis said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kerry Fehr-Snyder can be reached at kerry.fehr(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
