<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-MISSOURI-INMATES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS COUNTY EXPLORES POSSIBILITY OF SETTLING LAWSUIT WITH MISSOURI
INMATES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Mo.) 
 
By STEVE OLAFSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANGLETON, Texas _ With the potential of a large jury verdict
looming, attorneys for Brazoria County have agreed to explore
settling a lawsuit filed by Missouri prison inmates who say they
were mistreated by jail guards and sheriff's deputies.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement negotiations, which may occur next week, could
head off a September trial date for 25 Missouri prisoners who have
sued Brazoria County, five of its past or present law enforcement
officials, a private company that leased jail space from the county
and two of the defunct company's former employees.
</P>
<P>
   The prison is in Angleton, an east Texas city of 19,500
residents about 35 miles south of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The inmates' lead attorney, Lynn Klement of Angleton, said
Thursday that he is ``not extremely positive'' a settlement can be
reached but said he hopes Brazoria County Sheriff Joe King's
opposition to settling the case will not thwart an out-of-court
ending.
</P>
<P>
   County commissioners court would have to approve any settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The county leaders will make whatever decision is best for the
county, I hope,'' he said. ``This certainly has the potential for a
large jury verdict. There is a lot of information we've developed
that has the potential for making a lot of people angry.``
</P>
<P>
   Klement said that includes evidence that Missouri officials and
the Texas Commission on Jail Standards were misled about the events
of Sept. 18, 1996, when a videotape was made showing sheriff's
deputies clad in riot gear and one employee of Capital Correctional
Resources, Inc., conducting a shakedown of the jail that entailed
some prisoners being manhandled, bitten by a dog and subjected to
tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri officials, who reclaimed all their prisoners nearly a
year later after they saw the videotape, complained that officials
with Brazoria County and the private jail complain didn't fully
inform them of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   A flurry of civil suits have been filed by the Missouri
prisoners, including one in U.S. District Court in Galveston and
about a dozen others in Missouri federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   Three defendants in the Galveston lawsuit _ former Brazoria
County officers Lester Arnold, 47, and David Cisneros, 38, and
former CCRI officer Wilton David Wallace, 51 _ were indicted last
week by a federal grand jury on a charge of violating an inmate's
civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   They declined to answer questions this week during a deposition
for the civil suit and invoked their Fifth Amendment privilege
against self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Klement, the inmates' attorney, said videotape of the men
declining to answer questions will be shown to a jury if the case
goes to trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked them questions like, `Did you slam an inmate's face
into a wall on such-and-such a date?,' and when they answer `I
invoke my Fifth Amendment right,' that can be pretty damning. I can
show that to the jury,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Brazoria County and CCRI were not available for
comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
