<HEADER>
A1685 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONICA-TV-COX     08-06 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONICA-TV-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: TV tries to admit its Monica problem
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- TV was very sorry it had to bring you the day's
biggest story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't help but feel a little bit funny about it,'' co-anchor
Kevin Newman confided to Sam Donaldson on Thursday on ABC's ``Good
Morning America.'' He was talking about how it felt to talk about
Monica Lewinsky, the day's biggest story, again.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson could feel Newman's queasy tummy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a seamy story,'' agreed Donaldson, posted like a trusty
terrier on the White House lawn, where one could imagine that the
second the cameras blinked off he'd be standing on tippy toes to
peek through the Oval Office windows. ``None of us likes to talk
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody liked to talk about it. Goodness no. Apologizing for
covering the Lewinsky story has become an almost required preface
to the media's blizzard of coverage. It's a way TV can better
connect with us: We say we don't like to watch it, so TV says it
doesn't like to bring it to us. That way, when it brings it to us,
and we watch it, everybody can feel better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's talk about the dress: I think we can all concede this is
a distasteful topic of conversation,'' is the way Mary Tillotson
back-doored her way into the subject on ``CNN &AMP; Co.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people would like never to hear about this case
again,'' piped in Time writer Elaine Shannon, before helping
Tillotson fill a half-hour on the topic. She then added, as if
defending her opening her mouth: ``But it is in a court of law.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just the Lewinsky story that the media found so icky.
It was the way the media acted, too. They're all animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you say zoo?'' Katie Couric sighed on NBC's ``Today.''
``Apparently the media began assembling last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Couric then cued Lisa Meyers, the NBC correspondent stationed at
the U.S. District Courthouse in Washington. She looked as if she'd
been up all night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The place is crawling with reporters,'' put in CNN
correspondent Bob Franken, seated in a kind of camera-friendly deer
blind, above the fray and beside legal analyst Roger Cossack (and
later Greta van Susteren). Commenting on the day's comings and
goings, the two looked as if they were hosting a Rose Bowl parade.
</P>
<P>
   Cossack then observed from his perch, almost chuckling, ``Some
of the press is just covering the press.''
</P>
<P>
   He must have been peering down at WSB political reporter Bill
Nigut, who at almost that very moment, was busy interviewing
Cynthia Alksne, a ubiquitous TV gadfly.
</P>
<P>
   When it wasn't interviewing itself, TV interviewed regular
people _ about itself. It was televising its own therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it something we should be obsessing with?'' CNN's Brian
Cabell asked a resident of Albermarle, N.C., where he spent the
whole day.
</P>
<P>
   When the Albermarle resident told him it was not, Cabell moved
on to another resident. And another. And another.
</P>
<P>
   The first step toward recovery is admitting you have a problem.
TV's trying. But it's sure not pretty to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
