<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIMARY RAISES QUESTIONS ABOUT CONSERVATIVE GOP'S STRENGTH IN
KANSAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN A. DVORAK and JOHN PETTERSON  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: For two successive elections, conservative Kansas
Republicans claimed victory after victory, but Wednesday the
results of the primary election left them stung by defeat after
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Lifted by a powerful showing from Gov. Bill Graves, moderate
Republicans made gains in the Kansas House, claimed control of the
Republican Party in Johnson County and Shawnee County, and said
they might take back the entire state GOP organization.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the lopsided defeat, David Miller, who hoped to
translate conservative strength into an upset of the moderate
governor, didn't attend a Republican Party unity breakfast in
Topeka.
</P>
<P>
   Although conservatives will continue to wield power in the
Legislature and in the state's congressional delegation, the
election results raise questions about the vitality of the
conservative Republican movement in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be the turn in going back to a moderate Republican
Party,'' said Rep. Ray Cox of Bonner Springs, a GOP moderate who
survived a concerted conservative onslaught and won on primary
night.
</P>
<P>
   Some conservative Republicans said they remain a force in
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose a battle, it doesn't mean we've lost the war,''
said Tim Golba of Olathe, political director for Kansans for Life,
an anti-abortion organization whose members often back conservative
Republicans. ``We'll be back in two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Anti-abortion activists, he said, already were recruiting
candidates to run for the Legislature in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   With conservative-moderate emotions running high, Republicans
sought Wednesday to pull the two wings of their party together for
the November general elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to take the strands of this great party and start
weaving them together,'' U.S. Sen. Sam Brownback told the nearly
100 Republicans at the unity breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who lost to Graves 73 percent to 27 percent, was listed
by Republican Party officials as a speaker but never showed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is getting some much-deserved rest,'' said Kris Van
Meteren, the Miller campaign manager who did attend the breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   The state GOP chairman, Steve Abrams, was at a loss to explain
Miller's absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was going to be here,'' Abrams said. ``It would
have been better if he'd been here.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller's absence was emphasized by a lone empty chair and a
``David Miller'' nameplate at the head table.
</P>
<P>
   The magnitude of the Graves victory exceeded what many
politicians thought possible. Miller didn't win a single county,
and in some counties received as little as 16 percent of the
Republican vote.
</P>
<P>
   But at the unity breakfast, Graves embraced those who backed
Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly respect the views and the very significant
constituency within the Republican Party that David represents,''
Graves said. ``I have to acknowledge that constituency and those
views as we move forward toward this general election.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Miller who helped organize conservative Republicans
around Kansas during the early 1990s, an effort that resulted in
conservatives' taking control of the GOP organization in late 1994
and early 1995. In 1995, conservative Republicans dominated the
Kansas House, and in the 1996 elections conservatives gained
strength in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's primary, however, several notable results emerged:
</P>
<P>
   Three moderate House members, Cox of Bonner Springs, Rep.
Barbara Allen of Prairie Village and Rep. Cindy Empson of
Independence turned back strong challenges from conservatives.
Another moderate, Patricia Lightner of Overland Park, won in a
Johnson County district.
</P>
<P>
   In two House districts in Topeka, now held by conservative
Republicans, moderate Republicans won the GOP nomination and are
favorites in the November general election.
</P>
<P>
   A moderate Republican lost to a conservative in a House race
near Wichita, but moderate Republicans prevailed in key House races
in Garden City, and in two central Kansas districts.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives and moderates, each with five members on the state
Board of Education, engaged in a spirited tussle. Prognosticators
think that after the November elections, the 5-5 split will
continue.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said their candidates for precinct committeemen and
committeewomen in Shawnee County won solidly over conservatives. In
Johnson County, moderates said they won about 50 more precinct
committee positions than conservatives did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we got whipped,'' said Rep. Tony Powell of Wichita, an
outspoken Republican conservative. ``It is a big defeat. I think it
set us back. I think we will bounce back from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell said that some of the moderates who did well in the
primary election, like Graves, talked often of tax cuts, which were
a prime conservative issue.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the showing by moderates, the Kansas House still will be
controlled by conservatives _ although the split will be narrower
next year than it was this year.
</P>
<P>
   Another conservative, Sen. Karin Brownlee of Olathe, said
conservative Republicans won't disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``You win some and you lose some, that's how I look at it,'' she
said. ``We'll move forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1833EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
