<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1693 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAYOR-KC-KAN &LR;      08-06 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYOR-KC-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH CHANGES APPROVED, KC MAYOR LOOKS AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ With the successful Liberty Memorial and
stronger-mayor charter elections behind him Wednesday, Kansas City
Mayor Emanuel Cleaver moved quickly to reinvigorate an issue that
could consume the remaining eight months of his term and beyond _
light rail.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Cleaver praised the Kansas City Area
Transportation Authority for its recent progress on transportation
issues and urged the transit agency to spend $1.3 million in
remaining grant funds to complete its light rail corridor study.
</P>
<P>
   Also during Wednesday's interview, Cleaver:
</P>
<P>
   Assessed voter approval of the Liberty Memorial restoration and
stronger-mayor charter changes as a boon to his second-term legacy,
far overshadowing the public corruption convictions that have
marred his tenure since his 1995 re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Pledged to make another attempt at getting voter approval of a
storm water fee proposal that failed in Tuesday's election.
</P>
<P>
   Ruled out ever moving to Washington to accept a post in the
current or future Democratic administrations and said he would
remain active in Kansas City civic affairs after leaving office in
April 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But light rail was Cleaver's topic of the day, and he was eager
to make amends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never wanted to kill light rail, but rather intelligently
build light rail,'' Cleaver said.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Cleaver dismissed the ATA's light rail plans as
``touristy froufrou,'' saying it would do little to get poor people
to work. His comments sparked a critical review of the proposal by
the Greater Kansas City Chamber of Commerce that appeared to kill
its prospects.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, Cleaver praised the ATA's progress on
conventional surface transportation since his criticism. He said
the agency had done a good job of obtaining federal grants to buy
new buses, marketing and advertising its existing service and
exploring innovative ways of exploiting its current unused
capacity, such as its transporting Kansas City School District
students on city buses, rather than on leased vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ATA General Manager Dick Davis said he was encouraged to hear
Cleaver's thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm delighted to hear the mayor's comments and that we (have
been) more responsive to his concerns and open a discussion about
light rail,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Cleaver said he would support a light rail
planning process that involves all stakeholders in the project,
such as government and business leaders, property owners and
transportation providers. But the discussion must put light rail in
the context of a regional transportation system that gets workers
to their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a delicate period for poor people,'' Cleaver said.
``We've got to get people to jobs, and those are north of the river
and in western Johnson County.''
</P>
<P>
   Just such a program is under way.
</P>
<P>
   Chamber Executive Director Peter Levi, who met with Cleaver on
the issue Tuesday, said his group is working with the Mid-America
Regional Council to assess area transportation demands. That could
lead to integrating commuter rail, buses and possibly light rail
into a coherent regional public transit system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Light rail is not dead,'' Levi said. ``It needs to be
considered in the context of a total metropolitan transportation
system. The mayor and the chamber are interested in reviewing
public transit, and light rail is a key part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver did not endorse a particular route for a light rail
spine, but said he hoped any new plan would include spurs to Kansas
City's East Side and West Side communities.
</P>
<P>
   But any such proposal likely would come long after he has left
office, Cleaver acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver said the voters' decisions on two ballot issues Tuesday
_ Liberty Memorial and stronger mayor _ will allow his work at City
Hall to be judged more kindly when he's out of office.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Cleaver fretted that his legacy could be forever
tarnished by the City Hall's public corruption scandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will go a long way to overcoming the courthouse shadow
that has come over this building,'' Cleaver said. ``There was a
time when I wondered whether discussions about the '90s in
municipal government would center on corruption. As significant as
those events were, they still should only be a blip on the
screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver said he hasn't yet made specific plans for life after
the 29th floor, though some interesting, but untold, suggestions
are coming his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never sit on the sidelines and be a fan,'' Cleaver
said. ``But I'm not going to try and be a major player in the
political arena, and I've committed myself to spending the rest of
my life in Kansas City.''
</P>
<P>
   He also was a little ticked that voters approved all municipal
ballot issues Tuesday except for a measure that would have changed
the way the city calculates fees for storm water runoff. He
promised to return the issue to the November ballot without the
imposing ``Impervious Surface'' title.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to come up with a better synonym, put it on the
ballot and quit showing people we went to college,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
