<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYEES APPRECIATE EMPLOYERS' SPECIAL REWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Miranda Byrd noticed their faces. She saw
retail clerks at a Johnson County, Kan., mall flash expressions of
amazement, excitement and envy when they learned why there was a
sudden influx of giddy shoppers Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, along with about 145 colleagues from Barkley Evergreen &AMP;
Partners, went on a shopping spree, courtesy of their boss.
</P>
<P>
   At 3 p.m. Monday, the Kansas City marketing and advertising
agency took a break. President Scott Aylward and human resources
Vice President Kay Moore herded the entire agency work force from
the offices into four yellow school buses.
</P>
<P>
   Secret destination: The mall.
</P>
<P>
   Purpose: Spend a $100 gift certificate on yourself _ nothing for
anyone but you _ before you get back on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd bought what she calls a ``totally tangerine-faced fossil
watch that covers most of my arm.'' It was, the assistant broadcast
buyer added in understatement, ``not your typical Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Aylward said the agency always had tried to reward its workers.
In the past, he has walked around the office a couple of times a
year handing out $100 bills. This time, the reward came with a
twist: ``We wanted this to be a totally self-indulgent day.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Gage, a public relations senior account executive, said
the agency always had been good about giving its partners ``little
surprises.'' (Notice the word she uses _ ``partners'' _ not
``employees.'') This little surprise, which netted her a necklace
and a pair of shoes, ``showed that the company understands how
important it is to take time to reward everyone for their hard
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore said the secret shopping spree and other rewards programs
were a way to counterbalance the competitive, stressful environment
created in the ad business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very, very important for us as a company to remember it's
OK to have fun,'' the human resources officer emphasized. ``It's OK
to stop and say we've all been working hard...We spend a lot of
time and money to make sure this is the kind of place people want
to be.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Kevan Gibbs is pretty sure he made the right
choice, and we're not talking about the shoes he bought. Gibbs, a
public relations account supervisor, was on his first day on the
job when the exodus to the buses occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``While everyone was extremely nice and welcoming, I couldn't
help but wonder what my second day would hold,'' Gibbs noted. It
was, he added, a great way to begin a new job.
</P>
<P>
   Some employees missed the trip because of vacations and other
days off, but they, too, have gift certificates to spend on
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just an amazing way to say, `Thank you.' &UR; '' bubbled
Kristy Enlow, who works as a desktop publisher. Enlow, who bought a
purse, scarf and lotion, added, ``It doesn't matter what level you
are at this agency, they always find a way to make everyone feel
appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   Two hours out of a workday. About $16,800 out of company
coffers. It was an investment Barkley Evergreen &AMP; Partners could
afford. But that's not the point.
</P>
<P>
   The real issue, in a highly competitive and demanding work
environment, is how many companies can afford not to do something
similar. Such gestures go a long way to help retain and reward
productive workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
