<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE MEDIA PRECISE AND AMUSING, OR SIMPLY BOORISH? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: There was a time in the newspaper trade when decorum
counted for something.
</P>
<P>
   If a man reporter showed up in this office without a necktie,
George Burg, then the assistant city editor, would send him home to
fetch one.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds impossibly quaint now. But the reasoning was simple.
There was no knowing what the day might bring. It could be
necessary to send someone to interview a person of importance _ a
foreign diplomat, a captain of industry, a much-decorated general,
even possibly the president.
</P>
<P>
   George was not about to dispatch some staff member who looked
like he'd just crawled out of the corner pub.
</P>
<P>
   There were more intimate matters of discretion. In cases of
sexual assault, for example, not only did we not name the victim.
We let the description of the offense stand at that _ sexual
assault _ on the grounds that no interest except the prurient would
be served by providing further details.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the name of exactitude, we take great care to indicate
the orifices involved in the crime, probably delivering more on
that subject than many readers would prefer to know.
</P>
<P>
   I even remember pushing the envelope of propriety myself once.
</P>
<P>
   It was years ago, in the early '60s. In researching a story on
the vagrant and homeless, I had spent the night on a cot in the
vast common room of a 50-cent flophouse filled with men whose luck
had run out.
</P>
<P>
   In writing the piece, it was necessary to describe the odor in
that dismal hall _ a sour effluvium of unwashed bodies, filthy
clothing and other things, one of which I was hesitant to name.
</P>
<P>
   I searched the dictionary until I came upon a solution, a term
that was absolutely precise, yet clinical enough to avoid giving
offense. The word was ``flatus,'' and if you don't know what it
means, you're welcome to look it up for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   The story appeared on a Sunday. The next morning a senior editor
strode over to my desk wearing a solemn face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congratulations,'' he said, not meaning that at all. ``It's
the first time that word has appeared in our newspaper.'' From the
way he said it, I guessed it also would be the last time.
</P>
<P>
   I've thought of that little incident more than once, while
following the coverage of contemporary events in Washington in
general, and the matter of Monica's infamous dress in particular.
</P>
<P>
   With a specificity previously achieved only by publications that
arrived in plain brown wrappers, we have wallowed in speculation
about the alleged stain _ what it is, how it got there and what
implications it might hold for the fate of the republic.
</P>
<P>
   What's worse, now we are exploiting the subject for its pure
entertainment value, turning out jokey sidebars, playing to the
crudest sort of public taste, and proving by our cheap worldliness
that the press is as uncouth as it is free.
</P>
<P>
   We've come a long way, haven't we? But instead of feeling proud
about it, there are days when this business is embarrassing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1837EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
