<HEADER>
A1703 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRIDGEHAMPTON-MUSIC-F     08-06 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIDGEHAMPTON-MUSIC-FESTIVAL-ART-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MUSICAL IDYLL BY THE SEA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Bridgehampton Chamber Music Festival, which opens its 15th
season this weekend at the Bridgehampton Presbyterian Church on
Long Island, N.Y., was started for reasons that were entirely
noncommercial but sensible nonetheless. Marya Martin, a flutist
from New Zealand who settled in Manhattan, and Ken Davidson, who
ran his own investment company, had recently married, and Davidson
was dismayed by the prospect that Ms. Martin would be spending her
summers traveling the festival circuit while he worked in the city
and spent weekends on his own in the Hamptons.
</P>
<P>
   From what Davidson and Ms. Martin could tell, there was no great
demand for chamber music in the Hamptons; concerts they had been to
in the early 1980s were poorly attended. Nevertheless, when
Davidson flew to New Mexico to hear his wife perform at the Santa
Fe Chamber Music Festival, two weeks after their wedding, he had a
proposal. Why didn't Ms. Martin start her own festival so that they
could spend their summers together?
</P>
<P>
   As the new festival's director, Davidson raised the $15,000
budget for the first season, and as artistic director, Ms. Martin
invited three colleagues _ the violinist Ani Kavafian, the cellist
Fred Sherry and the pianist Andre-Michel Schub _ to join the
endeavor. She also persuaded the initially reluctant elders of the
Presbyterian Church to let her present her concerts in the
sanctuary of their 19th-century building.
</P>
<P>
   That first summer, the festival was really just a pair of
concerts, each a different program but both devoted entirely to
standard fare, from Telemann through Mendelssohn and Dvorak. Since
then the festival has grown slowly, and this year it has a budget
approaching $300,000, with a roster of 25 musicians who will join
forces through Aug. 25 in various combinations for six regular
programs, plus an opening benefit and a children's program.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the festival, concertgoers can attend programs
offered in the Hamptons this month by two musical training
institutes.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Bridgehampton Festival performances are held in a
440-seat church, the configuration of which puts everyone close to
the performers, there is a level of intimacy that the players
consider close to what has historically been the chamber music
ideal _ or at least, closer than they often find during the season,
when tours take them to all-purpose halls better suited to larger
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, much of the standard repertory, written before 1900,
was composed to be heard in even smaller spaces than the church;
composers' wealthy patrons commissioned works for semi-private
performances in their own salons and drawing rooms. On the other
hand, 20th-century chamber works, which are now a significant part
of the repertory, were composed with concert halls in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the contemporary repertory, particularly American music,
has been an increasingly important part of the programming mix at
Bridgehampton. Ms. Martin's concerts adhere to the current
programming fashion, in which diverse works are linked by common
thematic threads. So besides all-Bach and all-Mozart programs,
there is a concert called ``American Sounds,'' with works ranging
from Gershwin theater songs to Copland's Sextet and recent works by
Ned Rorem and Eric Ewazen, as well as a program called ``The South
American Soul,'' with works by Ginastera, Villa-Lobos, Nazareth and
Piazzolla. Another program, ``East Meets West,'' looks at Asian
influences on Western composers.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most programatically amorphous concert _ the opening
night program, which includes Stravinsky's ``Histoire du Soldat,''
a flute transcription of the Faure Violin Sonata and a Dvorak Piano
Quartet (Op. 87) _ has a theme of sorts, the journey from
Romanticism to early modernism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juggling the programs is the tough part,'' said Ms. Martin,
who discusses ideas with her colleagues and accepts suggestions
from them, but who in the end is responsible for both the
individual programs and the shape of the festival as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year I came up with another three programs I would love
to do,'' she continued, ``but which I'll have to save for another
year. In the `American Sounds' program, for example, I was going to
do a concert in which everything was related to the year 1900. Kurt
Weill was born that year, as was Aaron Copland. So was Colin
McPhee, whose `Balinese Ceremonial Music' we're including in `East
Meets West.' But then, I wanted to do the Rorem, because it's his
75th birthday, and this Eric Ewazen piece for flute, French horn
and piano is quite fantastic. So the 1900 concert will have to
wait.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also what Ms. Martin regards as necessary compromises;
the Gershwin works on the ``American Sounds'' program, for example,
are meant as drawing cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I programmed Copland, Ewazen, Rorem and something else that
people didn't know,'' she said, ``we may not be able to sell the
house. And I've got to think of that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Martin said the all-Bach and all-Mozart programs made it
easier for her to sell the more adventurous ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that the Bach and Mozart concerts help give me as much
leeway as I need for the `American Sounds,' `South American Soul'
and `East Meets West' programs,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the average concertgoer to feel there is something for
them to go to, and if someone who hasn't attended the festival
before sees the series, they may buy tickets to the Mozart concert,
but they will probably then buy tickets to something else as well.
Rarely do people buy only one concert. We've found that most people
buy tickets to three.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival has been a popular draw since the beginning. When
it opened for business in 1984, Ms. Martin and Ms. Kavafian were
rehearsing backstage just before the concert when Davidson asked
them to come to the front of the church, where a long line had
formed on the path leading to the door.
</P>
<P>
   The festival is also popular among the musicians. They say that
because Bridgehampton is a small community _ and because many of
them stay at the homes of board members while they are playing at
the festival _ they have gotten to know the audience.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a wonderful social scene at the festival,'' said
Sherry, the cellist who was a regular in the festival's early days.
``I don't know if people understand how important the social scene
is, among musicians. In the early days especially, it really was a
mom-and-pop festival, and everybody was involved in everything.
We'd spend the day hanging around the church, rehearsing, then we'd
all go to lunch at a coffee house, then back to rehearse some more.
Then we might practice on our own, then go to the beach, where we'd
all have picnics. It was idyllic, and the music making was very
relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Sherry is traveling this summer, he said he expected to
return in other seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The musicians also say that the festival, more than many others
on the summer circuit, allows them time to perform in a far less
pressured atmosphere than they are used to during the regular
concert season.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Kay, a clarinetist who is playing in all but the Bach and
Mozart concerts this summer, said: ``During the season, you're
playing chamber music but also rushing around doing 10 other
things. At Bridgehampton, the schedule keeps us pretty busy, but
it's not pressured. We have three or four days to put each program
together, and it's very collegial. We also have time to go out
after concerts, or hang out at the beach, and all that adds
pleasure to playing the concerts.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Martin said she considered the church where the performances
are held to be one of the pleasures of the festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very New Englandy,'' she said. ``It's got a beautiful
spire, and because Long Island is so flat, if you're at all above
the tree line, you can see it. And the building is very pretty;
it's all white, white inside, with white benches and a red carpet.
And the acoustics blew me away when I first went there, years ago.
That's why we wanted to do it there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
