<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CHASING GHOSTS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees aren't playing against other American
League teams anymore. For the rest of the season, they'll be
playing the ghosts of a team that existed nearly a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   As the Yankees return to the Stadium on Friday with an 80-29
record, they're chasing the 1906 Chicago Cubs that won a record 116
games. To overtake those ghosts, the Yankees must win at least 37
of their final 53 games, a reasonable .698 percentage for a team
that is performing at .734.
</P>
<P>
   But who are those '06 ghosts. And how did they do it?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly a person is now alive who saw those Cubs, best remembered
now for what appeared in The New York Evening Mail in 1910 when the
sportswriter Franklin Adams was told that his piece in the paper
that day was eight lines short. Quickly, he dictated:
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the saddest of possible words _
</P>
<P>
   Tinker to Evers to Chance.
</P>
<P>
   Trio of bear Cubs and fleeter than birds _
</P>
<P>
   Tinker to Evers to Chance.
</P>
<P>
   Thoughtlessly pricking our gonfalon bubble,
</P>
<P>
   Making a Giant hit into a double,
</P>
<P>
   Words that are weighty with nothing but trouble _
</P>
<P>
   Tinker to Evers to Chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Chance, the manager-first baseman known as the Peerless
Leader, often talked to shortstop Joe Tinker and second baseman
Johnny Evers, but the double-play combination didn't talk to each
other.
</P>
<P>
   The season before, instead of waiting for any teammates to join
him in a taxi to the ball park, Evers rode off alone. Tinker
objected, they threw punches at each other, then Tinker had a
solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we talk, we'll be fighting all the time,'' Tinker told
Evers, ``so don't talk to me, and I won't talk to you. You play
your position and I'll play mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Tinker and Evers would be friends and be voted,
along with Chance, into the Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, but their
poetic connection would prompt one of baseball's favorite trivia
questions: who was the Cubs' third baseman?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is Harry Steinfeldt, who shared the National League
lead in 1906 with 83 runs batted in while hitting .327.
</P>
<P>
   In that dead-ball era, the Cubs' home run leader in 1906 was
right fielder Frank (Wildfire) Schulte with seven; he shared the
National League lead in triples with 13. Chance, who batted .319,
shared the league lead with 100 runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   Those Cubs served notice as early as June 7 with a 19-0 rout of
the rival New York Giants, knocking out the legendary right-hander
Christy Mathewson in an 11-run first inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs would also win the N.L. pennant in 1907, 1908 and 1910,
as well as the World Series in 1907 and 1908 _ the last time the
Cubs did win the Series, as everyone who now inhabits Wrigley Field
knows only too well.
</P>
<P>
   Their ace in those years was Mordecai Peter Centennial Brown,
who would win 239 games as a Hall of Famer known as Three Finger
because of his mangled right hand.
</P>
<P>
   As a 7-year-old on his family's farm in Nyesville, Ind., he
reached into a feed-cutter. His index finger above the knuckle had
to be amputated; his little finger remained useless. In a fall
while chasing a hog, he later broke the third and fourth fingers.
But his deformities helped him pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives me a bigger dip,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   In that 1906 season, Brown had a 26-6 record with 10 shutouts
and a league-leading 1.04 earned run average. Jeff Pfiester was
20-8 and 1.56, Ed Reulbach 19-4 and 1.65, Carl Lundgren 17-6 and
2.21, Jack Taylor 12-3 and 1.83, Orval Overall 12-3 and 1.88. As a
staff, the Cubs had a 1.76 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   In their 116-36 record, the Cubs were a remarkable 60-15 on the
road and 56-21 at Chicago's old West Side Grounds. Sparked by a
26-3 record in August, they won 50 of their last 57 games.
</P>
<P>
   In the World Series, the Cubs suddenly soured. They lost to the
crosstown White Sox, known as the Hitless Wonders for their .230
team average in posting a 93-58 record. The White Sox batted .198
during the Series, but beat Brown twice, winning in six games as
the Cubs slumped to .196.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard Series to lose,'' Frank Chance said, ``but you
can't win all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   It's now a hard lesson for the Yankees to remember. They'll be
chasing the ghosts of those '06 Cubs until the end of the season,
but then they must chase the ghosts of all those Yankee teams that
have won a record 23 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
