<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ZHIVKOV-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZHIVKOV, COMMUNIST LEADER OF BULGARIA FOR 35 YEARS, DIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (subs grafs 2, 6, 13 and 23 for additional information and
refinements; inserts 2 new grafs after 23rd graf)  (Eds, an 800-word version of the obit moved as OBIT-ZHIVKOV-SHORT) 
(gm/bl) 
 By DAVID BINDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Todor Zhivkov, the Communist ruler of Bulgaria from 1954 until
his ouster in 1989, died Wednesday night at a hospital in the
capital, Sofia. He was 86. Doctors said he died of complications
following a respiratory infection in July.
</P>
<P>
   Zhivkov, the longest-serving leader in the old Soviet bloc and
last prominent survivor of its old guard, was a conventional party
apparatchik. This, more than anything else, enabled him to endure
the turmoil of Balkan politics and the periodic upheavals in the
Kremlin, to which he paid fealty throughout his long career. The
only known threat to his rule was an abortive coup in 1965
organized by a handful of party dissidents and some army officers _
believed to be the first of its kind against a Communist regime.
Zhivkov said the coup was a pro-Chinese conspiracy; others
attributed it to the rigidity of his regime and his dutiful
acquiescence to the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   In his heyday, he boasted more than any other European Communist
leader about his intimate ties with the Soviet Union, saying the
two countries `breathe with the same lungs, and the same blood
flows in our veins'' and that they were as close as ``teeth to
lip.'' This served him well through the three decades in which
Nikita Khrushchev and Leonid Brezhnev ruled the Soviet Bloc. In the
1970s, a Bulgarian critic wrote that he had earned ``the reputation
of a Communist leader who had caused the minimum of trouble for the
Soviet Union.''
</P>
<P>
   But in November 1989 as East European regimes were collapsing
one by one, he was brought down with the blessing of the
reform-minded Mikhail Gorbachev in Moscow in a bloodless putsch
organized by senior officials in the Sofia government, including
the army chief of staff, who recognized that the Communist system
in which they had all grown up was doomed and that Zhivkov would be
an obstacle to transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``My connection with Gorbachev became strained,'' Zhivkov
acknowledged in a 1993 interview with Henry Kamm of The New York
Times. ``I entered into a conflict with him and he and his helpers
organized my release,'' he said, using the traditional Communist
euphemism ``release'' for dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, Zhivkov authorized a forced assimilation drive
against Bulgaria's 1 million ethnic Turks in which more than 100
were killed and 310,000 forcibly expelled. In a campaign that
aroused international condemnation, ethnic Turks were deprived of
linguistic, cultural and religious rights. They were dismissed from
jobs and rounded up at night, trucked to police stations and forced
to change their Islamic Turkish names into Slavic names. In
1988-89, hundreds of thousands jammed borders in forced flight to
neighboring Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   He was responsible for the construction in 1959 of concentration
camps for political prisoners just as the Soviet Union was
dismantling Stalin's gulags. He was also said to be behind the
murder in London in 1978 of Georgi Markov, a Bulgarian writer in
exile who had made mocking broadcasts about Zhivkov for Radio Free
Europe. In one of the strangest assassinations of the Cold War,
Markov was killed on Waterloo Bridge by an agent who used a special
umbrella to shoot a poisoned pellet into his leg.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Zhivkov's actions paralleled those of other Soviet Bloc
leaders: brutal collectivization of farmlands; the installation of
nuclear power reactors that had a Chernobyl disaster potential; the
opening of a huge steel factory that polluted the air of the valley
of the Isker, including the nearby capital of Sofia. His legacy for
his country of 9 million included a foreign debt of $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Zhivkov-era concentration camps were at Kotsian, Bogdanov
Dol, Belene Island in the Danube and Lovech. As many as 1,000
prisoners were held in Lovech from 1959 to its closing in 1962 and
at least 100 died or were killed there, according to the Interior
Ministry. Disclosures of their existence came in 1990 a few months
after Zhivkov was ousted. A Ministry of Interior spokesman said,
``Todor Zhivkov at least knew or gave the orders. The problem is
that from this period there were few material traces. It was done
on the telephone.'' Or, as Zhivkov boasted in 1991: ``You won't
find Todor Zhivkov's name where the things were done.''
</P>
<P>
   He was never tried for political crimes; prosecutors concluded
it would be too difficult to make charges stick. Instead he was
tried on charges of illegally spending the equivalent of $24
million in state funds. In 1992, after a trial that lasted 18
months, during which he was scornful and defiant, he was convicted
of embezzlement and sentenced to seven years in prison. Apparently,
the post-Zhivkov government, which included many of his former
associates, was reluctant to rake over the coals of their mutual
past.
</P>
<P>
   In deference to his heart problems and age the middle-sized man
with the long thin nose and the heavy jowls was allowed to serve
his time under house arrest at the mountain slope home of his
granddaughter overlooking Sofia, and even to make a foray to his
birthplace in Pravets, 44 miles northeast of the capital. On that
occasion he bragged, ``The whole country loves me.'' In February
1996, Bulgaria's highest court acquitted him of the embezzlement
charges though he remained under indictment on charges that he
abused human rights.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Todor Zhivkov was born Sept. 7, 1911, in Pravets, a farm village
in the foothills of the Balkan Mountains. He was one of a
generation of Balkan Communists who were raised in poverty, got
some education, imbibed the militant Marxism of Stalin in the 1930s
and took power after World War II. His father and mother, Hristo
and Maroutsa, had grown up poor, and young Todor had to leave
school after finishing the sixth grade. He was accepted in the
Secondary School of Book Printing and Graphic Arts in Sofia in 1929
and became acquainted through it with the rigid Communists of the
printing trade. Within a year he was accepted in the Bulgarian
Young Communist League. From there he moved steadily forward in the
Communist Party apparatus.
</P>
<P>
   In 1941 Bulgaria aligned itself with the Axis powers. After the
Russians defeated the Germans at Stalingrad, the Bulgarian
Communist Party organized guerrilla movements in Bulgaria and
Zhivkov, still in his mid-30s, participated as a political
commissar of a guerrilla detachment.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1944 the Soviet army swept into Bulgaria, the
country's pro-German government was ousted and a Fatherland Front
coalition of anti-fascists was created by the Soviet occupation
force. The Bulgarian Communist Party, which numbered about 8,000 in
September 1944, became the dominant force of the Fatherland Front
and set about killing off its political opponents _ agrarians,
social democrats and monarchists _ in addition to fascists. In
Sofia alone, 2,138 death sentences were passed, marking perhaps the
bloodiest of all Communist takeovers in Soviet-occupied Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Zhivkov was credited with playing an important role in the
seizure of power as chief of the newly established Peoples Militia
with the rank of colonel. His ``Biographical Sketch'' published in
1981 in Sofia tells that ``under the direct leadership of Todor
Zhivkov,'' an armed force of Communists rounded up ``the most
reactionary elements of the bourgeoisie hiding in the villas'' at
the end of September 1944. He also wrote the orders ``to catch the
intellectual and physical murderers of the fighters for national
freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   He was elected to the central committee of the party six months
later and as a senior official in its organizational bureau,
presided over the expansion of the party to 460,000 members. In
this capacity he also served in the autumn of 1949 as an
interrogator of Traicho Kostov, the wartime secretary of the party,
in preparation for his Stalinist show trial on charges of
collaborating with Yugoslavia's maverick Tito regime and opposing
Soviet domination. Kostov was tortured before his brief trial and
then executed.
</P>
<P>
   Zhivkov had been elevated to full membership in the party's
governing Politburo in 1951 in the brief era of Vulko Chervenkov,
who like his famous predecessor and brother-in-law, Georgi
Dimitrov, had spent the war years in Moscow under Stalin's thumb in
the Comintern. Then, after the death of Stalin in 1953, Nikita S.
Khrushchev ascended to power in Moscow and began replacing the
``Muscovite'' lieutenants sent out to run the Soviet satellites
with ``home Communists.'' Zhivkov's hour had arrived and he was
installed as first secretary of the party in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Seven weeks following Khrushchev's epochal denunciation in
February 1956 of the crimes of Stalin, Zhivkov spoke gingerly
before his own party about the 1949 Bulgarian purge without
mentioning Kostov by name. With Bulgaria's best-known Stalinists
already relegated to the backwaters, he said only that ``innocent
comrades were accused and unjustly punished.'' He did not mention
his own role in the Kostov case.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, with the backing of Khrushchev, Zhivkov added the post
of prime minister. Then, following a pattern set in other Bloc
countries he became chairman of a newly established Council of
State in 1971, the equivalent of president in other countries,
while retaining his grip on the party. His speech, according to
Georgi Markov, the writer murdered in 1978, who met him in these
years, ``frequently showed the uneasy combination of simple peasant
language and pompous phrases.'' But Markov credited him with
``natural intelligence, quick wit and a magnificent memory.''
</P>
<P>
   By this time confident in his durability, Zhivkov began
publishing the first of 38 volumes of ``Works,'' mainly the
seemingly interminable speeches that party leaders of his era were
accustomed to make.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, at the height of his power, he turned his
birthplace of Pravets into a model town, reached from Sofia by a
rare four-lane highway. The house where he was born was opened as a
historical monument. In addition, Pravets got a ``historical''
museum chronicling his, and Communist Bulgaria's life, and a
factory where Bulgaria's first computer, the ``Pravets,'' was
manufactured.
</P>
<P>
   After Zhivkov's political demise, the Pravets memorials went the
way of so many other Communist monuments across the bloc. The
Zhivkov home was empty, the museum closed. But when Zhivkov visited
the town in 1995, he was handed the deed to the eight acres of
farmland owned by his father, collectivized by the son in the 1950s
and now returned to his private hands. A circle had been closed.
</P>
<P>
   In his final years, Zhivkov gave occasional interviews to
foreign media, ruminating on his career and reinventing history
somewhat by portraying himself as a Soviet bloc visionary who had
seen that technological and economic advance was essential, and
that the ailing Brezhnev should have relinquished power years
before he died in November 1982.
</P>
<P>
   He was largely ignored by Bulgarians themselves. As
post-communist misery grew, however, so did nostalgia for the
seeming stability and prosperity of the Zhivkov era. Early this
year, Zhivkov, who had been stripped of his Communist Party
membership, was suddenly reinstated as a member of the Socialist
Party, which succeeded the old Communists, and even inspired a
rousing ovation at a Sofia rally.
</P>
<P>
   Zhivkov married Dr. Mara Maleeva, a physician, in 1938. She died
in 1971. Their daughter Lyudmila, who, under her father's tutelage
became minister of culture at age 32 in 1975 and encouraged modern
art and published works by authors like Allen Ginsberg, died under
mysterious circumstances six years later. Some suspected that her
death in a bathtub at her father's official residence was a
suicide, others that she was killed by political enemies.
</P>
<P>
   A son, Vladimir, and two grandchildren survive.
</P>
</TEXT>
