<SLUG> BC-NRA-MUSEUM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NRA UNVEILS MUSEUM THAT TELLS `THE STORY OF AMERICANS AND THEIR
GUNS'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRFAX, Va. _ In a time when many Americans consider guns a
terrifying societal menace, a new museum near the nation's capital
hopes to entice tourists with a $3.1 million high-tech tribute to
American firepower.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 2,000 guns _ from Napoleon's ornately decorated rifle to
a standard Army-issue M-16 used in the Persian Gulf War _ line the
walls of the National Rifle Association's National Firearms Museum.
The 15,000-square-foot display is housed in the NRA's headquarters
in Fairfax, a Washington suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Its message is unmistakable: Guns are as American as apple pie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Firearms and American history are intertwined,'' said Doug
Wickland, the curator. ``We like to think of the National Firearms
Museum as being the story of Americans and their guns.''
</P>
<P>
   There are sections on presidents and guns, police and guns,
noted military leaders and guns, even children and guns.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's ``For the Fun of It'' gallery, dedicated to youth,
includes a ``typical'' boy's bedroom from the 1950s, complete with
a gun rack for BB guns and other weaponry. The floor is covered
with an authentic Hopalong Cassidy rug that was salvaged from a New
Jersey home.
</P>
<P>
   Across the hall is another relic of the past, a
turn-of-the-century Coney Island shooting gallery, from the days
when fairgoers fired real .22 caliber rifles at moving metal ducks.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, which is free and open to the public daily, attracts
a combination of gun enthusiasts, history buffs and curious
tourists drawn by signs along nearby Interstate 66. Attendance has
averaged more than 100 visitors a day since the facility opened in
June.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had one fellow who drove six hours to see this,'' said
Wickland, gesturing toward the museum's Wall of Winchesters, a
collection of 72 Winchester rifles. ``He spent two days looking at
it, and he left here a very, very happy individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, given the topic, not everyone gives the museum rave
reviews. Guns may have been a necessity in Colonial times, but
they're an emotional political issue today, when flintlocks have
evolved into semiautomatic assault rifles.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking back on a sepia-tone past when the theme in a
kid's room wasn't sports, but guns. It is, to them, a vision of a
sort of lost Valhalla,'' said Josh Sugarmann, executive director of
the Violence Policy Center, one of the NRA's political enemies.
``Most people have a very different view of American youth's gun
culture. What they're doing is fighting against what people see in
the newspapers every day.''
</P>
<P>
   In a coincidence that underscored the conflicting views, the
museum hosted a media open house Thursday at the very moment that
President Clinton was in the White House Rose Garden urging
Congress to retain a waiting period for handgun purchases. The
five-day waiting period required by the 1994 Brady law is set to
expire Nov. 30, and Clinton wants to keep a minimum three-day wait
for handgun buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the NRA's leading role in opposing gun control, the only
overtly political items at the organization's museum are in the
gift shop. Visitors can stock up on NRA pens, lighters, flags,
pins, belt buckles, caps, shot glasses, mugs and T-shirts declaring
``Armed with Pride.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also a commemorative plate depicting Charlton Heston,
the organization's president, and the words to the Second Amendment
proclaiming the right to bear arms. Souvenirs for children include
stuffed animals, backpacks, trading cards and lunch boxes featuring
Eddie Eagle, the organization's mascot.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the museum's climate-controlled display cases, politics
takes a backseat to history. Life-size dioramas show a Colonial
hunter in action, a St. Louis gunsmith's shop in the 1800s and
scenes from World War I and World War II. The exhibits are
supplemented by computers that can provide additional information
on specific items.
</P>
<P>
   The extensive firearms collection includes a rifle that came to
Plymouth Colony on the Mayflower, a musket that is believed to have
been used at the battle of Lexington and Concord in 1775, an air
rifle that Meriwether Lewis and William Clark used to impress
Indians on their storied 1804-1806 expedition across the West to
the Pacific Ocean, and a pistol that President Theodore Roosevelt
kept in a nightstand at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most remarkable weapons is a tiny flintlock pistol
that weighs less than an ounce and fires a .08 inch ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're showing periods where firearms were viewed in different
ways,'' Wickland said. ``This is an historical museum as opposed to
a political statement of any kind.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information about the National Firearms Museum, call
(703) 267-1600 or visit the museum's Web site at
www.nra.org/museum/museum1.html
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
