<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-JUSTICE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ORDERS GATES TO BE AVAILABLE FOR UNLIMITED QUESTIONING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rejecting Microsoft's argument that Bill Gates is
too busy to be interrogated by government lawyers for more than a
day, a federal judge Thursday ordered the company chairman and
chief executive officer to make himself available for unlimited
questioning about the company's practices.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson also ordered Microsoft to make
available 16 other company employees the government wants to
question. And Jackson refused to take any additional measures to
protect the secrecy of the code for Windows 95 and Windows 98,
which the company must release under seal to the government.
</P>
<P>
   During a 19-minute hearing before Jackson, Microsoft said that
on Monday it will file a motion asking the judge to dismiss the
anti-trust cases brought against the company by the Justice
Department, 20 state attorneys general and the District of
Columbia. The cases accuse Microsoft of illegal anti-competitive
practices.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who ruled against Microsoft in every motion he
considered Thursday, made it clear that he will look skeptically on
any motion to dismiss the case. The judge said that if there is
even one factual dispute between the government and the company, he
can not dismiss the case.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft attorney John Warden cited two reasons for dismissing
the case.
</P>
<P>
   On June 23, a federal appeals court overturned a preliminary
injunction Jackson had issued prohibiting Microsoft from requiring
computer manufacturers who license the Windows operating system to
also license its Internet Explorer browser. Warden said that
appeals court's decision, which found that ``integration brings
benefits,'' undermines the government's current case which argues
that integration of the browser into the operating system
constitutes a violation of anti-trust law..
</P>
<P>
   Warden also said that recent depositions of executives from
other companies has turned up no evidence that Microsoft's
practices have ``had the effect of foreclosing access to the market
on the part of anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the court can resolve this case now, without the
need for an expensive and time-consuming trial,'' William Neukom,
Microsoft senior vice president for law and corporate affairs, said
after the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   David Boies, the special trial counsel hired by the federal
government to prosecute Microsoft, shrugged off Microsoft's plan to
seek dismissal of the case, saying ``every defendant wants to file
a motion for summary judgment.'' Boies said the court of appeals
decision does not significantly undermine the current case, and he
said Microsoft's description of the information gathered about
market impact is ``not accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's hearing was one of numerous steps along the way from
the filing of the cases against Microsoft on May 18 to the
scheduled beginning of the trial Sept. 8. Over the coming weeks,
the parties must file various briefs and depose numerous witnesses,
and Jackson is likely to hold other hearings to mediate disputes
and to consider any motions that are filed.
</P>
<P>
   The government said Gates will be deposed starting Wednesday at
an undisclosed location in the Seattle area. The government said it
expects to need no more than two days to question Gates, but
Jackson said he would not impose limits on the deposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am well aware that a deposition can be abused by both the
interrogator and the deponent,'' Jackson said, before offering to
personally supervise the Gates deposition in his courtroom. His
offer was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said the deposition of Gates should ``continue from day
to day as long as is necessary, or until it appears to me that the
deponent (Gates) is entitled to be excused.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft had sought to limit the number of executives
questioned, as well as the length of time Gates is questioned,
saying that the Justice Department already has deposed 12 Microsoft
executives, waited until the last-minute to seek a new round of
depositions, and might be trying to distract the company from
preparing for trial.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft had also sought a special agreement to protect the
confidentiality of the source code for Windows 95 and Windows 98,
which the government wants to examine as part of its preparation
for trial. Jackson said he has already issued an order to protect
the confidentiality of that code.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am perfectly prepared to impose every penalty in my power''
if the code is leaked, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the various warring companies affected by the case
have shown some recent ability to get along in preparation for the
September trial. After Microsoft filed a motion in federal court in
Utah complaining about a lack of cooperation from Novell, that
company began cooperating, and Microsoft said yesterday that its
arch-competitor, Netscape Communications Corp., has been answering
Microsoft's pre-trial questions ``in a very cooperative fashion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
