<P>
   MICROSOFT-JUSTICE (Washington) Rejecting Microsoft's argument
that Bill Gates is too busy to be interrogated by government
lawyers for more than a day, a federal judge yesterday ordered him
to make himself available for unlimited questioning about the
company's practices.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson also ordered Microsoft to make
available 16 other company employees the government wants to
question. And Jackson refused to take any special measures to
protect the secrecy of the code for Windows 95 and Windows 98,
which the company must release under seal to the government.
</P>
<P>
   During a 19-minute hearing before Jackson yesterday, Microsoft
said that on Monday it will file a motion asking the judge to
dismiss the anti-trust cases brought against the company. Jackson,
who ruled against Microsoft in every motion he considered
yesterday, made it clear that he will look skeptically on any
motion to dismiss the case.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (story will move in the ``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-PRODUCTION (Seattle) The Boeing Co. will announce next
week it is sending next-generation 737 assembly work to its
underused Long Beach, California aircraft factory _ marking the
first time in Boeing's history that the company has shipped
airplane production work outside the Puget Sound area, people
familiar with the decision said yesterday. The company's largest
union has fought to keep the work in Washington but its counterpart
in California welcomed the decision. California officials bent over
backwards to get Boeing to bring the work south, offering tax
credits for each job saved. The plan is not expected to affect
employment in the Puget Sound area.
</P>
<P>
   By Karen West and James Wallace. (story will move in the ``f''
category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Detroit) Mariners at Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   By Jim Street. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-COLUMN-THIEL (Undated) The buzz over Randy Johnson
continues, in Seattle and in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SEAHAWKS (Cheney, Wash.) What's the biggest difference in
last year's No. 1 draft choices? They're in camp. Last year,
cornerback Shawn Springs and tackle Walter Jones didn't even play
in the team's second preseason game because they had just agreed to
their contracts, and they didn't report to camp until the week
before the third game.
</P>
<P>
   By Clare Farnsworth. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
