<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY FOLLY POSES QUESTIONS OF HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID LEIBOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - The chubby young woman in the midnight blue suit steps
into daylight and takes rushed strides toward Prettyman Courthouse.
Inside, she will testify for 23 grand jurors. The thought is, the
young woman bears important answers, answers to rattle a nation.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is, Monica Lewinsky bears only questions.
</P>
<P>
   They seem to lurk in the space between her white-shoed
footsteps, in the few bustling moments it takes for the witness to
cross the mobbed sidewalk to a side door. Questions like these you
rarely hear on television, because they do not concern bodily
fluids or the Presidential groin. These questions depress, perplex,
frighten. They beg you to change the channel. Oh, if only.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing else is on. Nothing but questions.
</P>
<P>
   How did we fall so far? Just 209 years have elapsed since
Washington's oath of office. The line of succession stretches for
only 41 men. An historical eye-blink this represents, a hiccup, but
time enough to shift a country's eyes from the balcony of Federal
Hall on Wall Street to a grand jury room in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Where does it end? The viewer shuts his eyes, tries to replace
the sight of the witness with an image of government clean,
government worthy. There is a flicker: Early in college, a long
drive to Washington, a teenage goof from 15 years ago. At the
Library of Congress, the Great Hall stole my breath like a fist to
the solar plexus. The quotation from Francis Bacon was inscribed at
the head of a staircase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowledge is power.''
</P>
<P>
   Those three words caution, but also speak to an ideal. Thinking
men had those three words chiseled in place as a statement of
purpose, of hope.
</P>
<P>
   Then, from the TV set on the office wall, the voice of CNN's
forensic scientist rises in impeccable counterpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' she says, ``there are certain things which definitely
can compromise the biological evidence, such as heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon would have wept at the edge of the 21st century. Knowledge
now is tears.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it: The machinery of government, of the justice system,
of the press, all working full throttle to determine if a young
woman sank to her knees before the President of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In his first inaugural address, on a Wednesday morning 197 years
ago, Thomas Jefferson spoke of ``equal and exact justice to all
men, of whatever state or persuasion, religious or political.''
</P>
<P>
   How did we get from that line of stark beauty to Kenneth Starr?
</P>
<P>
   Or, more to the point, from Thomas Jefferson, who wrote the
Declaration of Independence at 33, to William Jefferson Clinton,
who appears to prefer interns who are 23?
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom currently favors a ``mea culpa''
scenario: Clinton lashing himself before the American public,
confessing, apologizing, explaining, banking on mercy. The pundits
say this will beget a redefinition, and allow the public to see
Clinton anew.
</P>
<P>
   One more symptom of the fall: Now the truth is worth telling
only as strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Apology or no, Clinton, his recent peers and 25 years of
partisan zealots from both parties have already redefined
something: the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson wrote of ``exact justice.'' John Adams took a stand:
Virtue, he said, outranked honor ``in the scale of moral
excellence.'' As a boy, George Washington had a rule in his copy
book: ``Labour to keep alive in your breast that little spark of
celestial fire _ conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton's most memorable famous oration to date: ``I did
not have sexual relations with that woman, Miss Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the signature statement of the modern presidency, with all
its legacies: an 18-1/2 minute gap in a tape; smuggled guns and
contras; subpoenas, White House coffees and DNA on a dress.
</P>
<P>
   How did we fall so far?
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, the young woman again steps into daylight. Cameras
fire, men scramble. She has answered everything, and answered
absolutely nothing. &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Leibowitz can be reached at david.leibowitz(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
