<SLUG> BC-RETAIL-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETAIL SALES IN JULY IS STRONGEST IN FIVE YEARS
</HEADLINE>
  (af)  
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It took retailers more than a year to catch up with
the stellar American economy, and now, as growth slows slightly and
the stock market behaves erratically, shoppers are showing no signs
of slowing their spending.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers Thursday reported the strongest July same-store sales
in five years, a result of robust demand for clothing and
housewares. The figures resumed a trend that began with a 10.2
percent gain in April and a 7.1 percent rise in May. Sales stumbled
slightly in June, increasing 4.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.'s retail composite index rose 4.8 percent
last month, compared with figures from the month a year earlier,
the best July gain since 1993, when sales rose 5.4 percent.
Same-store sales, or sales in stores open at least one year, are
considered the best measure of a retailer's health.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred by hot weather, shoppers filled their carts with
ceiling fans, bathing suits, spiral notebooks and planting soil _
indeed nearly every category of merchandise flew off the shelves,
much of it at full price.
</P>
<P>
   Strong leading economic indicators combined to make it so.
</P>
<P>
   ``All our key indicators are flashing green,'' said Richard N.
Baum, a retail analyst at Goldman, Sachs. ``Real wage growth was up
in June, the most recent month, 3.2 percent, which is the strongest
in 25 years. Real personal consumption expenditures were up 5.3
percent in June, and you'd have to go back to about 1983 to find
the last time that number was over 5 percent. And housing turnover,
which is a key indicator of sales of home-related products, was
running up 14.7 percent in June.''
</P>
<P>
   The big winners were specialty apparel stores, which for years
lagged behind the rest of the industry as consumers stocked up on
basic casual clothes that have become the staple of the American
wardrobe. The church of basics, Gap Inc., reported sales gains of
19 percent, with strong performances in all of its divisions, which
include Gap Kids, Old Navy and Banana Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Other specialty stores showed similar gains. Limited Inc. said
same-store sales were up 7 percent, and Ann Taylor Stores reported
same-store sales gains of 23.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Among merchants of off-price clothing, which has been extremely
popular with shoppers for more than two years, the story was the
same. Ross Stores reported gains of 7 percent, the TJX Co. said its
sales rose 9 percent and Value City reported gains of 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lengthy period when apparel underperformed,'' Baum
said. ``So there was some pent-up demand, and we are still seeing
some residual of that. And there are favorable demographics:
Teen-agers are the fastest growing group, and they spend a lot of
money on clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   The strong apparel sales only made weaker players stand out
more. Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. said its sales rose a mere 1.7 percent,
mostly because of a weakness in their apparel department. At the
J.C. Penney Co., sales fell 5.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, department store results were mixed. Kohl's,
which sells less expensive merchandise, said sales rose 10.4
percent, and Saks Holdings said sales rose 9.9 percent. But Dillard
Department Stores reported a sales decline of 2 percent, and
Mervyn's, a unit of Dayton Hudson, said sales fell 3.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Department stores are likely to continue feeling the squeeze
from the off-price shops, as are discounters, where apparel
accounts for about one-third of their merchandise. Wal-Mart Stores
said its sales rose 7.1 percent, compared with figures in the month
a year earlier, while Target, another Dayton Hudson unit, reported
a 6.7 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   All these strong sales bode well for profits. ``Most retailers
are entering the third fiscal quarter with very clean inventories
and the wind at their backs,'' Baum said. ``They ought to have
really good second-quarter earnings.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
