<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1734 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONICA-BEACH07-COX     08-06 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONICA-BEACH07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FINALLY, D-DAY ARRIVES AT 'MONICA BEACH'
 &HT;    620&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ George Hancock plunged into the media madness,
holding up a bright yellow sign reading ``Good Luck Monica'' as the
star witness entered the courthouse Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been waiting for this shot for seven months and this
clown comes by and (ruins it),'' complained a television cameraman.
He described how the tourist from Bowling Green, Ky., popped up in
front of a row of photographers just as Monica Lewinsky was whisked
in a side entrance to begin her long-awaited testimony before a
federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's appearance amounted to D-Day at ``Monica Beach'' _
the name journalists have given the sun-drenched sidewalks and
plazas around E. Everett Prettyman U.S. Courthouse. Inside,
independent counsel Kenneth Starr is conducting his investigation
into whether President Clinton had a sexual affair with the former
White House intern and engaged in an illegal cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of reporters and technicians equipped with the tools of
their trade _ satellite trucks, cameras, microphones, tape
recorders, notepads, gall and gigantic egos _ chronicled the
fleeting arrival and departure of the witness. In between, they
filled long hours of emptiness when she was testifying inside in
secret.
</P>
<P>
   Cooled by electric fans and shaded by canopies, TV
correspondents somberly informed their viewers of the momentous but
unseen goings-on in the familiar building behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, this is the biggest day so far,'' explained CNN
correspondent Bob Franken, who said the courthouse has become ``my
home away from home.'' The broadcast networks and cable news
channels have occupied the same strategic positions almost since
``Day One'' in January, he said, noting the places ``are marked
with gaffers tape'' similar ``to the way a dog stakes out his
territory.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, though, regulars like Franken were reinforced by
news crews from Court TV and Inside Edition and around the world,
all anxious to report on the big development _ Monica Talks!
</P>
<P>
   ``There is massive interest in the story,'' said Jonathan Hunt,
a correspondent for Sky News, a 24-hour news channel in England.
``It's a mixture of sex and politics, and that's a combination that
has brought down a lot of leaders in the U.K.''
</P>
<P>
   The interest is both ``salacious and serious,'' he explained,
because ``whatever happens to the president has a big impact'' on
financial markets and governments.
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday, the media circus moved across town to the
sidewalk outside the offices of Lewinsky's attorney as Judy Smith,
a spokeswoman for the witness, summed up her testimony. ``She
answered completely and truthfully and honestly each and every
question posed to her by the Office of Independent Counsel and
members of the grand jury,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what was she wearing?'' wondered a young woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard blue,'' said a companion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duh,'' rejoined the woman, eliciting giggles from those who
knew of the blue cocktail dress being tested by the FBI for
evidence of a liaison between Lewinsky and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the journalists at the courthouse were scores of
tourists who stopped by hoping for a glimpse of the witness _ who
indeed wore a blue suit, pearls and white shoes for her testimony _
but mostly settling for a behind-the-scenes look at the media
operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a spectacle,'' said Larry Hause, who was touring
Washington with his family from Louisville, Ky. ``This is history
in the making.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy, we'd better watch what we say,'' cautioned his
9-year-old daughter, Tracy, as she looked warily at the microphones
and cameras.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Walterbach, a visitor from St. Louis, arrived early
enough to get a snapshot of Lewinsky entering the building. ``She
had a smile on her face,'' she said. ``I feel sorry for her. That's
a pretty big person to go up against.''
</P>
<P>
   The mother of three children aged 16, 11 and 7, Walterbach said
she was saddened by the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, ``every kid wants to grow up to be president,''
she said. ``Now, with younger kids, how do you explain what's been
going on? Did he lie? What about?''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Penati, a visitor from Milan, said nobody would make a
big deal if the president had an affair in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex _ we do it and enjoy it and that's it,'' he said, before
opining that ``if justice was obstructed, then sure, that's a big
deal'' and wondering about the alleged evidence on Lewinsky's blue
dress.
</P>
<P>
   So how does he know so much about a case that wouldn't be a big
deal in his country?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it's on television in Italy, too,'' he admitted. ``It's
very interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a wheelchair, Lillie Smith of Manassas, Va., held a
sign that said ``No Matter What Clinton Says or Does, No Matter Who
Supports Him, There Is A Vile Stain on the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the president's day of reckoning is coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can lie to the nation, but he can't lie to God,'' she said.
``God knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hancock repeatedly explained why he had brought the
sign that caused such anguish among some cameramen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't blame this entire circus on a 25-year-old girl,''
said Hancock. ``For the White House and the American media to put
it all on her like she was a sorceress or something is just plain
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   For his show of support, ``I got jostled pretty good. My mom got
so scared she gave me her sign,'' said Hancock, who recovered
quickly enough to give interviews to the journalistic hordes
desperate to hear from anyone who witnessed Lewinsky's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   At about 5:20 p.m., Lewinsky left the courthouse as quickly and
silently as she had arrived. She will be likely be back and,
certainly, so will her watchers on Monica Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
