u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-WHALE-HIT-BOS &LR;      08-06 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-WHALE-HIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOURIST BOAT HITS, PRESUMABLY KILLS, WHALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A high-speed whale-watching boat struck and seriously
injured an endangered humpback whale last Sunday 20 miles east of
Boston, prompting a federal investigation and a search for the
missing animal, which has not been seen for days.
</P>
<P>
   One passenger on the boat, Peggy Kornegger of Somerville, called
the collision ``a chilling experience few of us on that boat will
forget. The woman next to me was sobbing uncontrollably after the
boat hit the whale.''
</P>
<P>
   Some environmentalists consider the increasing popularity of
whale-watching a threat to the whales and pushed unsuccessfully a
few years ago for federal rules that limit how close the boats may
get. But Thursday whale-watch officials said Sunday's collision was
both rare and unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite honestly, it was almost like something jumping between
two parked cars. It just came up very quickly,'' said Rick Nolan of
Boston Harbor Cruises, which operates the double-hulled catamaran
Millennium that struck the whale.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time we've had contact'' with a whale in 18
years of whale-watching, said Nolan, the company's managing
partner, ``We feel awful about it. We just hope the whale is OK.''
</P>
<P>
   But passenger Kornegger wrote in a letter to the Globe that the
Millennium was going too fast because ``the captain was obviously
starting his rush back to Boston to keep the trip within the
allotted three hours.'' She said such ``quickie'' whale excursions
put the animals at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Humpbacks, which range in size from 30 to 60 feet, are among the
most popular whales because of their spectacular breaches where
they leap out of the water, exposing most of their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the National Marine Fisheries Service, which
enforces laws protecting marine mammals, praised Boston Harbor
Cruises for reporting the collision promptly, but, even if the
collision was an accident, it may have violated the Endangered
Species Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``With an endangered species, if you cause injury, there's the
possibility you could be cited,'' said Teri Frady, spokeswoman for
the National Marine Fisheries Service.
</P>
<P>
   The Millennium, which doubles as a commuter boat on weekdays,
was accelerating for the trip back from the whale-watching ground
at Stellwagen Bank when the captain saw a whale spouting between
the two hulls of the catamaran, Nolan said. The captain tried to go
into reverse, but the boat was going 18.3 miles an hour, less than
half the maximum speed, and struck the animal.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Cetacean Research Unit, a private group based
in Gloucester that provides naturalists for whale-watching tours,
saw the whale a couple hours after the 12:30 p.m. accident, noting
a deep gash near its dorsal fin that Nolan described as ``a pretty
significant wound.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the whale has not been seen since.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Shorr, spokeswoman for the Center for Coastal Studies in
Provincetown, said her research group is concerned generally about
the new fast catamarans that ply the waters off New England. But
she said whale-watch boats are generally safer for whales than
other boats because their captians observe strict speed limits and
other procedures when whales are nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Collisions with boats are a major hazard for whales, Shorr said,
but ``in general, whale-watch boats are not the big offender.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1906EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1745 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-WRAPUP-BOS &LR;      08-06 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-WRAPUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE WORKS TO WRAP UP LAST-MINUTE BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Speaker Newt Gingrich conceded Thursday that
the GOP would probably achieve only a modest tax cut before the
November elections, as the battle lines for the congressional
campaign hardened around the issues of Social Security and tax
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   As the House prepared to break for the August recess Thursday,
Democrats said any projected budget surplus must be used to fund a
long-term solution that guarantees the solvency of the Social
Security system before any tax cuts are adopted.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans asserted they could achieve both goals at the same
time, while Democrats contended that most of the GOP's proposed
$702 billion in tax cuts would be financed with revenues from the
Social Security Trust Fund.
</P>
<P>
   As Gingrich urged Republican House members to tout the proposed
tax cut to their constituents during the monthlong recess, he
acknowledged it was not likely to be approved this year. Moderate
Republicans in the Senate have vowed to block a large tax cut, and
Democrats on both sides of Capitol Hill are determined to delay a
tax cut until a solution is reached on Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe the president will sign a $700 billion tax cut
this year,'' Gingrich told reporters Thursday. ``I mean, I
understand that, so we're not going to get all of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich privately has told Republican lawmakers that a more
modest tax cut of $70 billion to $80 billion over five years is the
most they could expect from Congress this year.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides view a tax cut as the defining issue for the fall
congressional campaigns because it shows the sharp differences
between the two parties at a time when a swing of 11 seats could
cost the Republicans control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to put Social Security first. Republicans want to put
saving Social Security second,'' said House minority leader Richard
Gephardt at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton told Democratic lawmakers on Wednesday to
resist the call for tax cuts because the political appeal of saving
Social Security would prove to be an effective counterweight with
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Clinton told reporters, ``I was disappointed today when
the speaker proposed to drain $700 billion from the surplus before
we have realized the surplus and before we take even the first step
to save Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders, fortified by public opinion polls, are
convinced that tax cuts remain the most powerful issue for them in
the fall. But fearful that Democrats will put them on the defensive
as they did on Medicare two years ago, Gingrich did not mention tax
cuts in the same sentence without also pledging to ``save'' Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to saving Social Security, providing tax
relief and continuing economic growth,'' said Gingrich in remarks
to House Republicans Thursday. ``I think the choice over the next
few months is going to be very straightforward. Our friends on the
left are going to argue basically for higher taxes. If you oppose
tax relief, you're arguing for higher taxes. Let's be fair about
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said they favor tax reduction as well but not until
the issue of funding Social Security benefits for the baby boomers
is resolved. The pay-as-you-go Social Security system now acts as a
massive income transfer between workers and retirees. But
demographic trends show there will not be enough workers to pay the
retirement benefits for the baby boom generation in the next
century.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans would take the 11-year, $1.611 trillion budget
surplus projected by the Congessional Budget Office and use $761
billion for Social Security and $702 billion for a range of tax
cuts, including elimination of the so-called marriage penalty and
inheritance taxes, repeal of the 1993 tax on Social Security
benefits for affluent recipients and reduction of the capital gains
tax to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The surplus projections assume the economy will continue to
grow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1908EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
