<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1746 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-WARD-NYT &LR;      08-06 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-WARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEDRIC WARD GETS ANOTHER SHOT AT LIMELIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ He was a summertime flash, almost a mirage in the
heat as he sped down the sidelines with his kick returns in last
year's exhibition opener against Philadelphia. And then, just as
quickly, Dedric Ward returned to the obscurity of being an unknown
third-round draft pick out of the University of Northern Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the opening of another Jets exhibition season Thursday
night, again against the Eagles, and Ward is back in the mix,
talking of becoming a starting wide receiver. And if Bill Parcells
wants him to return punts, too, well, that's OK
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's starting I'm thinking of,'' said Ward, who has grown
into a confident, if still small, second-year player.
</P>
<P>
   His debut a year ago was spectacular: Against the Eagles he
showed why he was one of the the nation's top small-college kickoff
returners. He generated 79 yards on three kickoff returns, brought
back a punt 22 yards and, for good measure, scored the game's
pivotal touchdown on a 33-yard pass from Glenn Foley.
</P>
<P>
   But Parcells chewed him out in that same game. For Ward
misjudged a punt, calling for a fair catch and then having to chase
the ball when it landed over his head, a mistake that put the Jets
in jeopardy. Parcells soon learned, too, that Ward, accustomed to
returning kickoffs along the sidelines, couldn't get away with that
in the pros, where the wings are covered.
</P>
<P>
   The result? Ward saw limited action in the first three games of
the regular season, sat out two more, and then was used sparingly
the rest of the season. Ward became a 5-foot 9-inch, 180-pounder
without a position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was angered with him last year because he was not performing
under pressure,'' Parcells said. ``He'd make a play and give up a
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite being in a doghouse of sorts, Ward wasn't totally
ignored. As the season progressed, he returned a few punts, and
even came in on some third-down passing situations.
</P>
<P>
   In the off season, Charlie Weis, the team's offensive
coordinator and receivers coach, watched what Ward was doing and
was impressed. He not only was in the weight room, but also had
gone back to school. He was a course shy of a degree. And because
he was still an undergraduate, he was eligible to compete in track
for his school, which he did, entering the Missouri Valley
Conference championships and finishing second in the 55 meters.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was back to the Jets, where possibilities have been
emerging.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jeff Graham was traded I knew that would open up some
things for me,'' Ward said. ``I'm also fighting to get in as a
starter at some point in my career. Why not me as the third
receiver?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year he was playing uninhibited,'' Weis recalled. ``There
was no pressure on him to make the team as a receiver. Now he's
gotten considerably stronger. He's the fastest receiver on the team
and he used the off season to build his body and his speed.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he is the club's most dangerous receiver in terms of
speed. And even though his college credentials as a receiver hardly
were on the same level as Alex Van Dyke, now in his third season
with the Jets and also looking to advance, the preseason games this
month will determine whether it is Ward or Van Dyke who becomes the
Jets' third receiver, behind Keyshawn Johnson and Wayne Chrebet.
Van Dyke, remember, was the NCAA's Division 1A record-holder for
receiving yards in a season when he produced 1,854 for Nevada. The
Jets made him their second draft pick behind Johnson in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean anything to Parcells, who may have a
liking for Ward now that he has survived his introduction to the
coach and the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Bill Parcells, he'll either make you or break you. But
Dedric kept fighting back,'' said Weis.
</P>
<P>
   So now Ward is hoping to move up. He is the second
punt-returner, behind Leon Johnson. He could be the third receiver.
He is waiting to make an impact.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1908EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
