<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1748 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-VISAS07-COX     08-06 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-VISAS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE PUTS OFF VOTE ON MORE VISAS FOR TECH WORKERS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By CHRISTI HARLAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders in the House cancelled a planned
vote Thursday on a bill to create more visas for specially skilled
foreign workers, leaving high-tech companies, universities and
their foreign employees in limbo for another five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, sought primarily by high-tech companies that complain
of a shortage of qualified U.S. engineers and computer specialists,
needed substantial Democratic support to pass. In the end, only
four Democrats were willing to buck President Clinton's opposition
to the bill and vote for it, according to House Majority Leader
Dick Armey, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would fill a gap left by an unprecedented demand for
H-1B visas, a form of work permit that allows specially skilled
foreign workers to take jobs in the United States for up to six
years. This year's allotment of 65,000 visas ran out in early May,
and another 65,000 won't be available until Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Congress and the Clinton administration agree that more visas
should be made available as soon as possible and that the annual
allotment of visas should be increased in coming years. Beyond
that, the agreement disintegrates over what job protection and
training should be offered to U.S. workers.
</P>
<P>
   A solution to the impasse won't come until mid-September. The
House planned to adjourn Thursday for its August recess and won't
return until Sept. 9. The Senate is also in recess through August.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, universities are making plans to do without the
foreign professors and researchers they had planned to hire for the
fall, and some companies are letting go the engineers and other
workers whose one-year student work visas have expired.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of companies have been lobbing letters and phone calls
at members of Congress to encourage creation of more visas.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's top advisers have recommended that the president veto
any bill that did not require employers to certify that they made
substantial efforts to hire U.S. workers and that no U.S. workers
were laid off. High-tech companies, typically allies of the Clinton
administration, vehemently oppose additional requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the administration continues to pressure Democrats or
ultimately vetoes the H-1B bill, you can be sure the high-tech
community will take it very seriously,'' said a thinly veiled
political threat issued Thursday by a coalition called American
Business for Legal Immigration. ``This is a balanced pro-jobs,
pro-growth bill and the administration has every reason to support
this legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration is standing firm: ``We're negotiating in good
faith and have been for the last several days and would like to
work something out to raise the cap (of 65,000) and protect
American workers,'' said a spokesman for the president's National
Economic Council.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted overwhelmingly in June to increase the number
of visas and impose few new requirements on companies. In the
House, a bill written by Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, would have
imposed tough new requirements on employers and was so widely
opposed by the industry that House Republican leaders forced Smith
to accept a scaled-back version that was hashed out with Senate
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But the scaled-back version didn't fly with House Democrats,
even those whose districts include concentrations of high-tech
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats are the ones under pressure on this thing,
especially the ones that represent the high-tech industry, and that
includes the White House,'' said Joe McMonigle, spokesman for Sen.
Spencer Abraham, R-Mich., who supports the compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who narrowly escaped having to argue on the House floor
against his original bill, was less combative Thursday: ``At the
end of the day, I expect to see legislation that will meet the
needs of the computer industry and will provide meaningful
safeguards for American workers.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
