u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PALESTINE-RESIGN-290&AMP;     08-06 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALESTINE-RESIGN-290&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCUSING PALESTINIAN LEADER OF INACTION, TWO MINISTERS RESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In a new sign of dissatisfaction with Yasser
Arafat's governance, two of his cabinet ministers resigned Thursday
to protest what they said had been the Palestinian leader's failure
to address problems within the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   The resignations came a day after Arafat stunned many members of
the Palestinian Legislative Council by unveiling a long-postponed
cabinet shuffle that failed to respond to their calls for him to
root out graft and mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   One who resigned was Hanan Ashrawi, one of the most prominent
Palestinians on the international stage. The other was Abdul Jawah
Saleh, who had criticized Arafat before but who went on Thursday to
accuse him of blocking Saleh's efforts to crack down on corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I fought corruption in my own ministry I referred some of
the high-ranking officials to the attorney general,'' Saleh said.
``The chairman himself interfered to stop any legal proceedings
against them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Ashrawi said her relationship with Arafat was ``based on
mutual respect'' but complained that changes within the authority
meant that ``decision-making has in a sense been reduced to a few
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The resignations were a new blow to Arafat's prestige, which has
suffered since he returned from exile in 1994 to become chairman of
the Palestinian Authority, which rules Gaza and parts of the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Along with stalled talks on a broader peace with Israel, his
chief problems have been a worsening economy in Palestinian-ruled
areas and the nearly universal perception that the authority is
corrupt and inefficient.
</P>
<P>
   But these problems seemed unlikely to evolve into a threat to
his leadership, Palestinian analysts said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the shuffle that he announced on Wednesday, Arafat added 10
members to the 18-member cabinet, but did not dismiss any of those
most widely seen as corrupt. A year ago the 88-member Legislative
Council had called on him to make changes after an official
investigation alleged a widespread pattern of corruption,
mismanagement and waste within the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Ashrawi, who had been one of two women in the cabinet,
gained international visibility as the spokeswoman for the
Palestinian delegation to the Middle East peace conference in
Madrid in 1991. She has since appeared frequently on American
television broadcasts, and had served since 1994 as minister of
higher education.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the shuffle, Arafat had asked Mrs. Ashrawi to move to
the Tourism Ministry. Mrs. Ashrawi said Thursday that she had
decided not to accept that appointment, and she made clear that her
refusal to join the new team had been based on more than a job
preference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being part of this new formation, in my opinion, will not
achieve anything,'' she told reporters in the West Bank town of
Ramallah. She described herself as part of a ``genuine change and
reform campaign.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
