<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE APPROVES PLAN TO REFORM CAMPAIGN FINANCE LAWS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House gave final approval Thursday to a plan to
overhaul the nation's campaign finance laws and sent the measure to
the Senate where a similar proposal died earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   House supporters expressed confidence that the American people
would ``rise up and demand action from the Senate.'' Until now,
Republican Sens. Trent Lott, Senate majority leader, and Mitch
McConnell of Kentucky, chief Senate opponent of rewriting campaign
money laws, have blocked attempts to force a final vote on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved the measure, sponsored by Reps. Chris Shays,
R-Conn., and Marty Meehan, D-Mass., on a final vote of 252-179. The
action came after a vote of 222-147 to defeat a substitute measure
offered by a bipartisan coalition of freshmen lawmakers. Sixty-one
members also voted present on the freshmen's measure, rather than
vote for or against it.
</P>
<P>
   Both bills aimed to control the huge sums of unregulated and
unlimited contributions known as ``soft money'' to the political
parties. But the Shays-Meehan measure succeeded because it calls
for a complete ban on soft money donations from corporations,
special interests and individuals to both the national and state
parties.
</P>
<P>
   The freshmen's bill would have allowed the state Republican and
Democratic parties to continue to raise the controversial
donations, which do not have to be accounted for.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to have a ban on soft money, you have to ban it at
both the federal and state levels,'' Shays said, referring to the
freshmen bill's failure to prohibit it at the state level as a
``huge loophole'' that would only lead to more abuses of the
campaign system.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the freshmen's bill, however, said that banning
soft money contributions to the state parties was ``too
far-reaching'' and amounted to a federal assertion of power over
states' rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any business telling the state parties what to
do,'' said Rep. Kenny Hulshof, R-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan bill also went further than the freshmen's
measure in trying to control the use of so-called television and
radio ``issue ads'' by unidentified special interests to trash
specific candidates in the closing days of an election campaign.
The bill would restrict the airing of such ads until the final 60
days before an election and would force the sponsors of the
commercials to identify themselves and their financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shays-Meehan restores accountability to the political process
by requiring these groups to disclose who they are and where their
money is coming from,'' said Rep. Nancy Johnson, R-Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The freshmen's measure would have forced the sponsors of issue
ads to disclose their identities and funding as well, but it would
not have imposed any other restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Brady said the sponsors of the freshmen measure felt that
imposing restrictions on advertising would have been
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still think we have the stronger reform bill because we
know it will pass constitutional scrutiny,'' Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan and freshmen bills emerged as the two strongest
of a dozen campaign finance reform measures that the House began
debating in May. Most of the bills were withdrawn from
consideration because they had little support. Some would have
tightened or changed current laws governing campaign donations and
expenditures. Others would have removed current limits on
contributions or placed other restrictions on the way campaigns are
paid for.
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan bill was modeled after a similar bipartisan
bill in the Senate authored by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Russ
Feingold, D-Wis. The McCain-Feingold bill died earlier this year
after repeated attempts to force a vote on it were blocked by Lott
and McConnell.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
