<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING BACK TAXES, RUSSIA RAIDS 3 BIG OIL COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Tax collectors swooped down on three of Russia's
biggest oil companies Thursday, seizing executives' cars,
apartments and other assets to hammer home its demand for payment
of more than $150 million in back taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The seizures copied a highly successful raid six weeks ago on
the offices of the natural-gas monopoly Gazprom, Russia's largest
corporation and at the time its single biggest tax delinquent.
</P>
<P>
   And they came amid new indications that President Boris
Yeltsin's current army of economic advisers _ unlike his previous
ones _ are serious about carrying out the latest last-ditch program
to stave off fiscal collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from the Russian State Tax Service moved on the
offices of Eastern Oil, Onako and Sidanko, the three petroleum
companies, less than a day after Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko
met with oil executives to demand back payments and discuss changes
in tax policies.
</P>
<P>
   The Tax Service's chief of corporate collections, Vladimir
Popov, said at a news conference that the raids should not be
regarded as evidence of a war against businesses but as ``the
beginning of a well-thought-out program of working with major
taxpayers like oil companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Investment analysts agreed that the actions were well thought
out. ``It's an inexorable process,'' said Tom Adshead, co-director
of research for United Financial Group in Moscow. ``They're going
down the list of big tax debtors one by one. There are a lot of
people out there who owe them money.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday, the government placed a limit on oil exports by
Sidanko and Onako, saying the cap would not be lifted until the two
companies make good on previous agreements to pay their taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Popov said the next target for tax collectors would be Rosneft,
a huge petroleum producer owned in large part by the government
itself. The government has sought for months to privatize Rosneft
but has been unable to strike a deal because of falling oil prices
and the company's financial condition.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's advisers also took a newly toughened stance on another
front Thursday, confronting coal miners who have been taking
hostages, carrying on hunger strikes and blocking major highways
and rail lines to demand months of unpaid wages.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy prime minister for energy, Boris Nemtsov, said the
government would begin to withhold payments to coal-mining
industries in any areas where strikers are blocking rail lines. He
also said the government would ignore demands from any miners who
are breaking the law.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the head of the Federation of Independent Trade
Unions threatened to call a nationwide strike on Oct. 7 _ the date,
not coincidentally, when Bolsheviks began the 1917 revolution,
which began seven decades of Communist rule in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the government wants total war, it's going to get it,''
said Andrei Isayev, the union's political leader.
</P>
<P>
   Coal miners across the nation have sporadically blocked highways
and rail lines since last spring as government promises to make
good on past wages came to naught. Sometimes that was because
state-owned companies had refused to pay for shipments of coal;
sometimes it was because state payments to miners were siphoned off
by corrupt mine managers and others.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days the unrest has spread. One major electric
utility, which serves the 720,000 residents of Sakhalin Island, in
the Pacific, is preparing to shut down for lack of fuel. The miners
partially lifted their blockade Thursday, allowing limited coal
shipments into the plant, but said they would impose it again if
back wages were not paid by Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Nemtsov said Thursday that the government was already spending
more money to aid coal miners than for any other sector of the
economy, and that the added cost of the strikes cannot be borne any
longer.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin said only last week that he expected this autumn would
be politically difficult, and the government's new toughness
reflects preparations for that.
</P>
<P>
   The government is in a political and fiscal bind. International
lenders have made it clear that they will pull their money out and
refuse to make new loans _effectively bankrupting the government _
unless Russia reforms its tax system and improves collections.
</P>
<P>
   But those very changes seem destined to enrage citizens who
already have lost wages or pensions to corruption, inflation or
economic collapse, and who find the notion of new taxes repugnant.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has increased tax collections for three straight months,
to about $1.9 billion in July, and it plans to pass the $2 billion
mark in August. But those amounts are still only about 80 percent
of goals set by the International Monetary Fund, which controls a
$22.5 billion loan package intended to keep the government solvent
while it strengthens the economy and reforms its fiscal structure.
</P>
<P>
   Like many outside experts, Adshead, of the United Financial
Group, says the government has only until autumn to demonstrate
that it is on the road to recovery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
