<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1779 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROBE-LEGAL-BOS &LR;      08-06 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROBE-LEGAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY TESTIMONY KNOWLEDGE VITAL TO CLINTON LEGAL TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and his legal team will be using
all their contacts and resources to learn what Monica S. Lewinsky
told a federal grand jury Thursday, and they will use that
knowledge to shape the president's upcoming testimony before the
same panel, legal analysts said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on what they learn in this perfectly legal pursuit,
the president may still try to avoid making any statement to the
grand jury, some analysts speculated.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton agreed late last month to testify on Aug. 17 by video
hook-up from the White House, and he told reporters he was
``anxious'' to answer questions ``completely and truthfully.'' But
on Wednesday, the White House invoked a claim of executive
privilege to block prosecutors from taking testimony from White
House lawyer Lanny Breuer _ a move some analysts said could
foreshadow an attempt by Clinton to apply the same claim of
privilege to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is laying the groundwork for the president to exert
executive privilege,'' speculated Douglas Kmiec, a Reagan
administration adviser on constitutional law who now teaches at the
University of Notre Dame. ``I think the president is going to show
up on Aug. 17 and questions will be given to him, but at a critical
point he will say, `Mr. Starr, I'd like to cooperate, but the
interests of government preclude me from doing so.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Rothstein, a law professor at Georgetown University, said
invoking a privilege against testifying is one of several course of
actions still open to Clinton. Trying to use the privilege to
shield Breuer from testifying ``suggests that the president is not
averse to raising claims to bar information from the grand jury,
and he may then do it himself to keep himself out of it,''
Rothstein said.
</P>
<P>
   However, David Schertler, a former federal prosecutor, took a
narrow view of what information Clinton could withhold under a
claim of executive privilege, saying that privilege usually applies
to matters of government. ``It would not apply to questions about
his relationship with Monica Lewinsky,'' Schertler said.
</P>
<P>
   Executive privilege is a controversial power, not mentioned in
the Constitution, that has been occasionally invoked by presidents
to withhold documents or testimony on secret or sensitive matters
from Congress and courts. Raising it might allow Clinton to avoid
testifying without invoking a Fifth Amendment right against
self-incrimination, a move that some Republican lawmakers have
asserted could be grounds for impeachment in itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking the Fifth'' might also paint Clinton, in the public
eye, as a kind of criminal figure. ``The Fifth Amendment reminds
people of Jimmy Hoffa testifying to a committee. It tarnishes the
presidency,'' Kmiec said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there is some evidence courts might accept a claim of
executive privilege. The US Court of Appeals for the District of
Columbia has rejected claims that the attorney-client privilege
shields White House lawyers from testifying in the Lewinsky matter,
Rothstein said, but on two occasions the court suggested it might
be open to a claim of executive privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had apparently agreed to testify before it became known
that prosecutors had obtained a dress from Lewinsky that might
contain physical evidence of a sexual liaison between the president
and the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   The existence of the dress may have Clinton rethinking his
agreement to testify, several analysts speculated. Faced with ``he
said-she said'' testimony about a romantic link between Clinton and
Lewinsky, and possible attempts to cover it up, prosecutors could
use evidence from the dress, if it exists, to challenge the
president's version of the events.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's legal team will base some decisions about the
president's testimony on information they obtain about Lewinsky's
statements to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was a White House lawyer, I'd be calling up (Lewinsky
counsel) Plato Cacheris and taking him out to dinner, breakfast and
lunch,'' said Schertler.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can bet the White House will make an effort to get sources
in the courthouse to find out what she said, and to craft that
testimony in response,'' said Kmiec, who is on leave from Notre
Dame to teach at Pepperdine University in California, the same
school that extended a job to independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr.
Among other things, the White House will want to know if
prosecutors obtained testimony from Lewinsky or other witnesses
that can be used to lay traps for Clinton during his own testimony,
perhaps to induce statements from the president that prosecutors
can later claim amount to perjury.
</P>
<P>
   It would be legal, analysts said, for Clinton and Lewinsky to
have arranged a joint defense agreement in which each gives the
other details of any statements to prosecutors or the grand jury.
Starr, in fact, has no powers to block Lewinsky from telling
Clinton's lawyers what she said to the grand jury, Schertler said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as part of an immunity agreement, Starr could not have
forced Lewinsky to withhold details of her testimony from Clinton's
team, Schertler said. ``It's the opposite side of the principle
that prevents someone from influencing witnesses or obstructing
justice,'' he said. Silencing a witness ``interferes with the
defense's right to investigate a case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1933EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
