<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-U.S.-FISHING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS FISH AS RESENTFUL CANADIANS OBSERVE SALMON BAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala.)  (js) 
 BY THE NEW YORK TIMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ In a routine year for the Lax
Kw'alaams Indian tribe led by Don Reynierse, the sight of salmon
boats on the icy north Pacific at the beginning of salmon fishing
season would be cause for good cheer.
</P>
<P>
   But this year has been anything but routine for Reynierse's
people and hundreds of other Canadian fishermen in the communities
that dot British Columbia's rugged coastline south of the Alaska
Panhandle.
</P>
<P>
   The boats Reynierse can see from the dock in Port Simpson, a
fishing village near the Alaskan border, are American, he said in a
telephone interview. They are fishing a few miles up the coast and
come from Alaskan ports. In Port Simpson, the fishing boats have
been idle because of a Canadian fishing ban on the fragile northern
coho salmon stocks. The ban, imposed in June, has left Reynierse
with little more to do than watch.
</P>
<P>
   In Port Simpson and other communities on British Columbia's
northern coast, this fishing season has brought renewed
frustration, as stalled talks between Canada and Alaska on the
Pacific Salmon Treaty have exposed yet another dispute over salmon
fishing rights.
</P>
<P>
   Since the treaty expired in 1994, the United States and Canada
have been able to make only year-to-year agreements. Last year, in
a dispute over how the Americans and Canadians would share the
coastal waters, they were unable to manage even that much, which
led to a standoff between Canadian fishermen and an Alaskan ferry.
</P>
<P>
   This year, negotiations broke off on July 9 after Alaska refused
to observe the Canadian ban on fishing for coho, which pass through
Alaskan waters on their way to Canada's Skeena River. John Fraser,
the chief spokesman for Canada's Department of Fisheries and
Oceans, said that, while Alaskan fishermen continue to fish,
Canadians have been forced to halt or greatly reduce their harvest
of many of the more plentiful species for fear of catching coho
along with them.
</P>
<P>
   John Radosevic, president of the United Fishermen and Allied
Workers Union, said Canadian fishermen felt thwarted not just by
Alaska but also by their own government. A deal in southern British
Columbia with Washington state, which gives Washington 24.9 percent
of the southern sockeye run, has been condemned by Canadian
fishermen as a sellout.
</P>
<P>
   In the north, Canadians have grudgingly accepted the need for
the coho ban. But resentment lingers against the fisheries
minister, David Anderson, over his inability to reach agreement
with Alaska on the coho stocks. The negotiations on the specific
regions are carried out with the states involved.
</P>
<P>
   Alaskan officials contend that Canada's fishing ban, based on
its scientists' studies, is an extreme reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't willing to take that action when we had no evidence
of a so-called coho crisis,'' said Diane Regan of Alaska's Fish and
Game Department. ``As the season goes on, we'll see if it's true or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of July, Alaska declared the western part of the
state a disaster area in terms of numbers of returning salmon, but
that area is distant from the point of dispute with British
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   From the Alaskan side, Canadian fishermen are seen as less
altruistic than they represent themselves to be. Canadians have
been fishing the mouth of the Skeena River recently, Ms. Regan
said, and Alaskan officials contend that what they call a
``voracious'' harvest of sockeye salmon there has inevitably led to
a catch of the protected coho.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
