<P>
   Here are tonight's columns:
</P>
<P>
   KARAN-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ Donna Karan International
announced that it had narrowed its loss in the second quarter by
57.1 percent from a year earlier and that revenue had risen to
$124.9 million, from $111 million in 1997. But the crucial question
is how far can this company really go in imitating its more
successful brethren on Seventh Avenue, like Polo Ralph Lauren,
Tommy Hilfiger and Calvin Klein. By Jennifer Steinhauer. (Scheduled
to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Worldcom Inc. sold a record $6.1 billion of
bonds Thursday, attracting good demand in an otherwise choppy and
worried corporate bond market. The money will help pay for
Worldcom's acquisition of MCI Communications Corp. Jonathan
Fuerbringer. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``f'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHIHUAHUA-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ No one is more surprised about
the success of the Taco Bell talking Chihuahua than those who
created the quirky character. By Courtney Kane. (Scheduled to move
by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
