<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-SCENE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT SUMS UP COURTHOUSE SCENE: `IT'S A CIRCUS' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Under a bright summer sky, and with tourists and a
horde of journalists gathered nearby, a raven-haired young woman
entered the federal courthouse Thursday to deliver salacious
testimony that might darken the future of the U.S. president.
</P>
<P>
   Monica Lewinsky was whisked into the building to tell a grand
jury that she had a sexual relationship with the married chief
executive. Dressed in a gray blouse, dark blue blazer and dress,
white shoes and pearls, the former White House intern made no
effort to acknowledge the throng of television cameras, reporters
and tourists who anxiously awaited her arrival from a distance of
about 150 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky was just as reclusive inside the courthouse, turning
immediately to the left and taking an elevator usually reserved for
judges. On the third floor, the grand jury awaited.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the E. Barrett Prettyman United States Court House,
dozens of cameramen waited for Lewinsky's arrival. Many of them had
spent most business days since the Lewinsky story broke in January
waiting for a dramatic moment, such as the 25-year-old's
appearance. But, just as Lewinsky arrived in a green van at about
8:30 a.m., EDT, a man waved a home-made ``Good Luck, Monica''
banner in front of several cameramen, one of whom made no effort to
disguise his anger at the man who blocked the camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here seven months, and will kill you, and so will
several other film crews,'' shouted the cameraman, who declined to
give his name despite his willingness to hurl a scatological
description of the banner carrier. ``I've only been waiting seven
months for that shot.''
</P>
<P>
   George Hancock, who held the banner, said later that he
regretted getting in the cameraman's way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't mean to block anyone's shot,'' Hancock said. ``I just
wanted her to see my sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Hancock, who was visiting the courthouse with his mother,
Phyllis, also insisted he is not anti-Clinton. ``I'm just
anti-trash,'' said the Bowling Green, Ky., resident who stopped off
in Washington with his mother and father on their way to Niagara
Falls, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis, like her 32-year-old son, was holding a yellow banner
with black lettering in support of Lewinsky: ``Monica tells truth.
Slick Willie must.''
</P>
<P>
   And where was Mr. Hancock while his wife and son were at the
courthouse supporting Lewinsky and incurring the wrath of
cameramen? ``Daddy's back at the hotel thinking we're idiots,''
Phyllis said of her husband, David.
</P>
<P>
   Also toting anti-Clinton banners was Lillie Smith, a 72-year-old
homeless woman who uses a wheelchair. ``I don't know about you, but
I deserve better,'' stated one of the banners. ``The cruelest lies
are often told in silence'' and ``The president sets the tone and
climate of the nation,'' stated others.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, in conversation, placed much of the blame for the
presidential scandal on the public and said it has been more than
45 years since the United States has had an honorable leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people pay a tremendous price for their
government and demand nothing,'' Smith said. ``There has not been a
decent Democratic administration since (Harry) Truman, a man who
stood by his word.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Clinton also had supporters at the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Howard and Nancy Kleinberg of Toronto, survivors of the Nazi
Holocaust, said the president's sexual behavior should not be the
subject of a criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This episode is his own private life,'' said Howard Kleinberg,
who was in Washington with his wife to visit the U.S. Holocaust
Memorial Museum. ``I think people should leave the president alone.
It's excitement, but it's excitement at someone's expense.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Kleinberg said other presidents, such as John F. Kennedy,
have had extramarital affairs. Referring to the scandal that
brought Lewinsky before the grand jury, she added, ``I feel sorry
for them all.''
</P>
<P>
   American University student Joshua Silbert, sporting a camera,
said he was visiting the courthouse despite having a paper on
Abraham Lincoln due later that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a circus,'' Silbert said. ``I might as well just capture
it'' on film, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The public-relations and government major added that he hopes
the scandal does not hurt the Democratic Party's chances of
recapturing the House of Representatives in the elections this
November.
</P>
<P>
   Silbert, who is entering his senior year, said he sympathizes
with the president's plight. ``He can't sneeze without everybody
knowing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
