r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-ANDERSON-L     08-06 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-ANDERSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON DRAWING COMPARISONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Garret Anderson is just a pup in comparison to Joe
DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   But he's a pup with a bark so loud that sometimes it causes
baseball purists to turn and take notice.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio, of course, owns the major league record for the
longest hitting streak. The Yankees' Joltin' Joe hit safely in 56
consecutive games in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson got halfway to DiMaggio's mark, setting an Angels
record by hitting safely in 28 straight games. Before his streak
was stopped Saturday, Anderson had snapped Hall of Famer Rod
Carew's team-record hitting streak of 25 games set in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and DiMaggio. Anderson and Carew.
</P>
<P>
   ``C'mon,'' says Anderson smiling, ``Are you looking for a
comparison? Right.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, 26, who was raised by his mother in Granada Hills, is
too modest to get lured into comparisons with Hall of Famers this
early in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Those around him, however, including Carew, say the comparisons
will come.
</P>
<P>
   In his fourth season in the majors, Anderson has a career
batting average over .300. He's a left-handed batter, hits line
drives, uses the whole park, and has the mental approach suited for
putting big hitting streaks together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time he steps up to the plate he feels he should get a
base hit,'' Carew said. ``I think once you have that type of
attitude, you're going to be successful at the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson says he can't fathom what DiMaggio went through to
reach 56, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not about to go there,'' Anderson said. ``I told a
reporter the other day, until you live through that (a 56-game
hitting streak), you can't say, or put it in perspective, what he
had to go through.
</P>
<P>
   ``People started talking to me when I hit 20 straight. I can't
imagine what it would be like to reach 30 straight or 40 straight.
The pressure . . . I have no idea how tough that would be. Think of
what he had to do to accomplish that. He hit solidly for two months
. . . that's two months of hitting . . . that's a long time, a real
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Anderson passed Carew in the Angel record books, a
similar comparison wouldn't be fair, either.
</P>
<P>
   Carew had a lifetime average of .328, and won seven batting
titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, I still have a long way to go to be a polished hitter
like he was,'' Anderson said of Carew, now the Angels' hitting
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``His 25 straight, that was just one thing he did for a period
of time with the Angels. That doesn't say what his career was like.
My career is nowhere near that right now, so as far as I'm
concerned, there is no comparison at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The comparison, then, is Anderson vs. Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Since he joined the Angels in 1994 and played his first full
season in 1995, Anderson has gradually set his own milestones and
shown improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Before his call to the majors in July of 1994, Anderson had
three hitting streaks of 11 or more with triple-A Vancouver,
including a 27-game streak that ranked as the longest in the minors
in two years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Anderson became the first rookie to be named American
League Player of the Month, following a July where he hit .410,
with seven homers and 31 RBIs in 25 games. He also had a 14-game
hitting streak, the longest of any rookie that season.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Anderson became the first Angel to collect six hits in
a game, doing so in a 15-inning contest against Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Anderson's 189 hits were the most by a left-handed
batter in Angels history, passing Carew (179 in 1980) and Luis
Polonia (179 in 1991). He also hit safely in 17 straight, the
longest hitting streak by an Angel that season.
</P>
<P>
   This summer he has reached new heights. In his last 32 games,
Anderson is hitting .391.
</P>
<P>
   Still, all anyone has asked him lately is about the streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``People kept asking me questions about the streak, but I pretty
much just pushed them aside. I didn't want to talk about it,''
Anderson said. ``That's just my personality, it's no big deal,
really. After it was over, it was done and over with and you still
have to come out and play the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get caught up in something you did yesterday; that's
how I kept it in perspective. I have a lot of confidence in what
I'm doing and my abilities. If I get a hit, I get a hit; if I
don't, I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   As impressive as his statistics are, it is not something
Anderson consumes himself with.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a player, you don't have time to think about stuff
like statistics when you're playing every day,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even superstitious. I don't say I need to do this, or
need to do that, to be successful. I believe in my ability and my
swing. The rest will take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Carew, who hit over .300 for 15 straight seasons, says Anderson
is the type of hitter who will improve over time. He call his swing
``pure'' and says he has the potential to put together streaks
longer than 28 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everything goes right and he's feeling good and comfortable
at the plate with his timing and rhythm, anything can happen,''
Carew said. ``He uses the whole park. He doesn't just pull the
ball, he hits the ball to left, left-center, right, right-center,
so that in the future will help him if he gets into a streak like
this again.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I like about Garret, though, is that he's the kind of kid
not interested in records. He really wants to win. He also has the
attitude to say, `Well this streak is over, I'll just start another
one.' Players with attitudes like that will go a long way, which is
why I think we'll see longer streaks from him in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Anderson see longer streaks in his future?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that question again,'' he said, laughing, ``Please.''
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The SAN GABRIEL VALLEY TRIBUNE, WEST COVINA,
CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
