<SLUG> BC-FBC-RECRUITING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EYES OF TEXAS (AND OTHERS) ON NEXT MANNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   His father is the most revered football player in the history of
the University of Mississippi. And for the past four years his
brother turned the University of Tennessee into Peyton's
</P>
<P>
   Place.
</P>
<P>
   But chances are that Eli Manning
</P>
<P>
   ,
</P>
<P>
   a senior quarterback at Cardinal Isidore Newman High in New
Orleans, won't be spending his college days in Knoxville, Tenn. or
Oxford, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eli is his own person,'' said Archie Manning
</P>
<P>
   ,
</P>
<P>
   Eli's father, All-American at Ole Miss and former NFL veteran.
``It will be strictly his decision.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the favorite to land the 6-foot-5, 185-pounder
comes from among Texas, LSU, Florida State or Ole Miss. But Eli has
a wish list of 10 to 15 schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for the best fit for me,'' said Eli, who turns 18
in January. ``It doesn't matter if it's north, west, east or
south.''
</P>
<P>
   Eli might wind up wearing orange in college Texas is probably
the leader but it probably won't be in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't control comparisons,'' said Archie. ``But it's
tougher for Eli than it was Peyton. The comparisons (for Eli) to
Peyton are so current. It was just five years ago (at Cardinal
Newman) he was quarterbacking on the same field as Eli.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Eli will equal Peyton's accomplishments including
challenging for a Heisman Trophy and becoming a first round NFL
draft pick remains to be seen. But, at this point, Eli, who sports
a B average and 1,070 score on the SAT, compares favorably
physically and statistically to his older brother.
</P>
<P>
   Peyton, the 1997 Heisman Trophy runnerup and NFL's newest
multi-millionaire, threw for 7,190 yards and 92 touchdowns in his
three years as a starter. In his two seasons, Eli who's an an inch
taller than his brother at the same stage has compiled 4,887 yards
and 50 touchdowns for the Division 2-A (the second smallest of five
division) private school in an upscale section of New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't expect this type of quarterback to come through your
school,'' said Tony Reginelli
</P>
<P>
   , Cardinal Newman's head coach during Peyton's high school days
and the school's athletic director the past four years. ``And you
sure don't expect it twice. It's unheard of, really. Both kids are
once-in-a-lifetime kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Where they do differ, however, is in personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peyton is an assertive, go-get-em kind of guy,'' Archie said.
``Eli is a lot more laid back. He doesn't seem to react to either
good or bad. His buddies call him Easy. Ol' Easy, that seems to fit
him.''
</P>
<P>
   What won't be easy at least for the people in Oxford, Miss. is
another Manning turning down Ole Miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like, `We lost Peyton, we aren't going to lose
Eli,''' said Archie Manning, whose oldest son, Cooper
</P>
<P>
   , was a wide receiver at Ole Miss before a congenital neck
injury ended his career. ``I appreciate their interest and fully
understand the passion they have for Ole Miss football. But, you
have to understand, Peyton wasn't anti-Ole Miss, it just wasn't the
right choice for him at the time. I would love for Eli to go to Ole
Miss, but only if he chooses Ole Miss.''
</P>
<P>
   (sub head) Another son rising
</P>
<P>
   Another sought after quarterback with a well-known surname is
Chris Simms
</P>
<P>
   of Franklin Lakes Ramapo High in New Jersey. The 6-5, 215-pound
Simms, whose father, Phil
</P>
<P>
   , is a Super Bowl champion quarterback with the New York Giants,
may be the top quarterback prospect in the country. He's
considering Penn State, Ohio State, Texas, Michigan, Miami and
Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   (subhead) The commitments
</P>
<P>
   The top two quarterbacks in California Poly's Chris Lewis
</P>
<P>
   and Ken Dorsey
</P>
<P>
   of Orinda Miramonte haven't announced an early commitment.
However, a pair of California quarterbacks have announced their
respective decisions.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA landed Venice's J.P. Losman
</P>
<P>
   (6-3, 180) and Cal received an early nod from 6-foot-4,
210-pound Ryan Sorahan
</P>
<P>
   of Los Gatos.
</P>
<P>
   (subhead) Buckeyes, 'Horns on roll
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State and Texas continue to lead the nation in early
commitments with 11 each. But, with no early signing period, there
is plenty of time for recruits to be swayed elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Each player on Ohio State's list is from the state and all of
Mack Brown's
</P>
<P>
   Longhorn commitments are from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State would love to add LBCC linebacker Markus Steele
</P>
<P>
   (6-4, 225) to its list. But Steele, a native of Ohio and the
best JUCO linebacker in the nation, is reportedly leaning toward
USC.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
