<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1801 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPACE-CHIMPS07-COX     08-06 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-CHIMPS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AIR FORCE GIVING MOST 'SPACE CHIMPS' TO RESEARCH GROUP
 &HT;    By SAMAR ABULHASSAN
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Air Force, angering animal rights advocates,
decided Thursday to give most of 141 chimpanzees with ties to the
space program to a biomedical research group.
</P>
<P>
   At a Pentagon briefing, the Air force said 111 chimps will
remain with the Coulston Foundation, which has leased them since
1970. These chimps, 77 of which have been exposed to HIV or
hepatitis, would be transferred from Holloman Air Force Base near
Alamogordo, N.M. and would permanently belong to Coulston, which is
based there.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force said the other 30 chimps would go to a Texas group
that operates the nation's largest and oldest primate sanctuary.
Primarily Primates, Inc., of San Antonio will receive the
disease-free chimps from the laboratory by Sept. 30, 1999, when the
laboratory's lease with the Air Force expires.
</P>
<P>
   The chimps, which range in age from 5 to 38, are from an Air
Force colony established in the 1950s. Two chimps that actually
flew into space have died, but many others in the group took part
in space-related tests.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force move to allow the research group to keep most of
the chimps drew criticism from animal rights advocates. Famed
primatologist Jane Goodall said she was ``astounded'' by the
announcement, saying she believes the Coulston Foundation has a
poor animal care record.
</P>
<P>
   The advocates point to several U.S. Department of Agriculture
citations in the past few years of violations under the federal
Animal Welfare Act. In 1996, Coulston was fined $40,000 by the USDA
after three chimps died because of negligence. Charges were also
brought against the foundation this spring, and last month the USDA
launched another investigation after three chimps died earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're incredibly concerned about the welfare of the chimps if
they remain there,'' said Liz Clancy Lyons, spokeswoman for the
Washington-based Doris Day Animal League. ``I think there will be
substantial concern and outrage not only within the animal rights
community but with the general public.''
</P>
<P>
   Coulston spokesman Don McKinney has maintained that the
foundation has been targeted by a ``thuggish and irresponsible
smear campaign'' by animal-rights groups. Some of the Air Force
chimps, a part of a group of more 600 chimps at Coulston, are used
for HIV and hepatitis testing and has been instrumental in creating
a hepatitis vaccine, McKinney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want the public to know is what we do saves lives,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Jack Blackhurst, an associate deputy assistant Air Force
secretary, said there were five applicants seeking custody of the
chimps. Each was evaluated on four criteria, including past
performance of the organization, staffing capability and the
ability of each applicant to finance the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Air Force going into this had no preference,'' said
Blackhurst, who repeatedly stated that the Air Force was neither a
proponent of animal-rights groups or medical research. He said the
decision was solely based on how well each applicant proved they
had the ``capability and werewithal to care for the chimpanzees.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackhurst said that Coulston ``did as well or better than other
chimpanzee facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace Swett, president of the non-profit Primarily Primates,
said the chimps going to San Antonio would join 40 others already
at the sanctuary. It would cost about $2.8 million to retire the
new chimps, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that all the chimpanzees deserve a hard-earned
retirement and with sufficient resources, we would have welcomed
the opportunity to give them all a home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Noon, project director for the Center for Captive
Chimpanzee Care, a Boynton Beach, Fla.-based organization who
proposed building a sanctuary to retire the chimps, said she was
``delighted'' that a fraction of the chimps would be retired, but
said ``it doesn't allay my fears for the other 111.'' Her proposal,
which would have used 80 acres of donated land outside San Antonio
for a sanctuary, was rejected by the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
