<SLUG> BC-DRUG-RUNNERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDS CRASH ALLEGED DRUG CORRIDOR BETWEEN OHIO, TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-New  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ Federal prosecutors said Thursday that a
21-year-old man led a drug-supply operation using trucks, buses,
and overnight delivery services to move marijuana and cash between
here and Toledo, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the suspected ringleader, 23 people are accused
of participating in the operation. Seventeen people, including
several family members, were behind bars here late Thursday as
authorities hunted for the remaining suspects, Assistant U.S.
Attorney Jose Angel Moreno said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family that plays together stays together,'' Moreno said.
``We're still hunting.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernesto Alonzo Ramirez, 21, also was charged by Texas
authorities with murder. Federal agents arrested him, his
common-law wife and other family members on a ranch west of Laredo
late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to allegedly running a drug gang, Ramirez is accused
of killing a truck driver whose bullet-riddled body was left on the
streets of a Laredo residential neighborhood in June.
</P>
<P>
   The body of Aubrey Baker was found five days after he was caught
with more than 200 pounds of marijuana, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks he's another Tony Montana. He's a punk, big and
ugly,'' said Laredo Police Lt. Ismael Alardin, comparing Ramirez to
the Miami drug lord in the movie ``Scarface.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez, who has a shaved head and is more than six feet tall,
has had previous brushes with the law.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests came as part of a 30-month operation aimed at the
smuggling and money-laundering. A federal indictment unsealed
Wednesday alleges that Ramirez ran a criminal enterprise that,
since 1992, moved marijuana and cocaine between Laredo and Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   More than a ton of marijuana was stashed in tractor-trailer rigs
and in luggage shipped on commercial buses, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Express, United Parcel Service and Airborne Express
delivery services were unwittingly used to ship crates and boxes of
narcotics, according to the indictment. Drugs also were allegedly
hidden in acetylene tanks used in welding.
</P>
<P>
   Profits were sent back to Laredo using a stream of Western Union
transfers that were disguised by using other people's names,
according to the indictment. The transfers were kept at $2,000 or
less to avoid attracting the attention of the authorities, and some
were as little as $100, the indictment said.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez was implicated in Baker's murder by one defendant whose
confession was videotaped by the Laredo police, according to a
state arrest warrant.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez faces up to life in prison if convicted of running a
criminal enterprise, and he faces 12 other federal charges
including drug possession and distribution, and money laundering
for trying to hide the alleged illicit profits.
</P>
<P>
   Among the others named in the indictment were 11 Laredo
residents, including five of Ramirez's family members, and two
sisters in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration was the lead agency in
the operation, and aiding it were the Customs Service, the Internal
Revenue Service, the FBI and the Laredo police.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1947EDT &QL; 
