<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-CELLUCCI-BAKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAKER TO LEAVE CELLUCCI POST TO LEAD HMO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Cellucci Administration suffered the defection of
one of its key cabinet members Thursday when Charles D. Baker Jr. _
once touted as a lieutenant governor candidate this year _ said
that he is stepping down as secretary of administration and finance
to become president and chief executive officer of Harvard Vanguard
Medical Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Though largely an unknown to the general public, Baker achieved
renown within state government as one of the most effective and
influential figures of the Weld-Cellucci era. He is considered by
many as among the smartest people in state government, and his
departure, set for Aug. 1, was immediately cited by some observers
as evidence of an impending `brain drain' at the State House.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, 41, said he is leaving because the position at Harvard
Vanguard, a medical wing of Harvard Pilgrim Health Plan, was too
good an opportunity to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only a few jobs in health care that I consider jobs
you simply have to take, and this job for me is one of them,'' he
said Thursday. ``They have some of the very best physicians in the
world as part of their practice, and the opportunity to work with
them was something I felt I had to take advantage of.''
</P>
<P>
   As A&AMP;F secretary, Baker had been responsible for most fiscal
matters in state government. Despite never having run for office,
Baker was courted to become running mate to Acting Governor Paul
Cellucci, but ultimately decided not to attempt to make the switch
from bureaucrat to elected politician. The spot eventually went to
Jane Swift, a former state senator from North Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci heaped praise on Baker Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to express my appreciation on behalf of the people of
Massachusetts for the outstanding job Charlie Baker has done,''
Cellucci said. ``Although he will be leaving state government, he
will continue to be one of my very close friends and one of my key
advisors.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker's departure had been expected for months, and Cellucci
said he did not try to talk him into staying. Cellucci said Baker
might return to state government on a part-time basis, serving on a
state board or commission.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said he interviewed for the job in late June, and from
that point recused himself from issues involving the health care
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Baker who earned $82,000 in government, would not say how much
he will be paid in his new post. He begins Sept. 1, the day after
he leaves the State House.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said he would name a replacement in the next week to 10
days. He said he would consider candidates from both inside and
outside the government. He added that he already had some ideas,
though he would not name contenders. Assistant Secretary Lowell R.
Richards 3d was immediately named as a frontrunner by
administration sources.
</P>
<P>
   Baker is given major credit for many of the policy initiatives
of the past seven years, including welfare reform, overhauling
regulations in state government, and reforming medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   As secretary of Health and Human Services, from 1991 to 1994,
Baker presided over deep cuts prompted by the state's fiscal
crisis. Yet he won admirers among liberals and conservatives alike
for his deft management style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie is smart, rigorous and he's just extraordinarily
able,'' said Judy Meredith, a veteran human services lobbyist.
``He's a bureaucrat in the best sense of the word. He's also the
most charming slash-and-burn artist that this human services
advocate has ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite being a fiscal conservative, Baker was noted for his
accessibility and support for social programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the go-to person for issues of the poor and the
homeless,'' said Philip Mangano, director of the Massachusetts
Housing and Shelter Alliance. ``He brought the brain and the heart
together in dealing with public policy and that's unusual. What a
disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Meredith said Baker would be a big loss to the administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry to see him go because he's so much fun to deal
with,'' Meredith said. ``It's such a severe brain drain. He'll
certainly add an enormous amount of class to the HMO industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Vanguard Medical Associates was founded in January as a
nonprofit by 900 physicians and other health care types who provide
service to Harvard Pilgrim Health Care. The company provided care
for nearly 300,000 patients, according to Dr. Gene Lindsey, the
chairman of its board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
