<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1810 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRTRAN07-COX     08-06 0446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AirTran union threatens selective strikes
 &HT;    By Christopher Seward
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Contract talks between AirTran and its flight
attendants have broken down, and the union representing the workers
says it is ready to start selective strikes Sept. 5 _ around the
Labor Day holiday _ if significant progress isn't made by then.
</P>
<P>
   ``We deserve what other flight attendants in the industry take
for granted,'' said William Green Jr., president of the Association
of Flight Attendants, AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   The union, which represents 400 of AirTran's flight attendants,
is seeking pay increases, caps on medical insurance premiums and an
end to ``discriminatory'' rules it says treat flight attendants
less favorably than pilots and mechanics, most of whom are male.
Most AirTran flight attendants are female.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran officials say talks broke down because the AFA is
insisting the company ``force all flight attendants to join the
union.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the sticking points appears to be a ``union security''
proposal that nonunion flight attendants be required to pay a $39
monthly fee because they would benefit from some union programs,
such as training and safety procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of our flight attendants have specifically stated that
they do not desire to be a member of the union,'' said Thomas
Kalil, senior vice president of operations and customer service.
``Consequently, we do not feel it is fair to make complete
unionization compulsory, as the AFA is proposing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not insisting that everyone become a member,'' said
union spokesman Steve Francy. ``Both the male-dominated pilots
group and mechanics group have union security clauses in their
contracts.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Mediation Board has ruled the contract talks are at
an impasse. A 30-day, cooling-off period is in effect until Sept.
5,
</P>
<P>
   and the flight attendants can call a strike that day.
</P>
<P>
   The AFA began representing its flight attendants in 1995 and has
been negotiating a contract ever since. Talks have been in
mediation since March 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Francy says the two sides have made progress on some areas,
including training, scheduling procedures and sick leave.
</P>
<P>
   But other issues remain unresolved, such as regular breaks for
flight attendants and the service fee.
</P>
<P>
   The impasse comes as AirTran prepares to expand its schedule
this fall, shifting more nonstop flights from its headquarters in
Orlando to Hartsfield International Airport. In doing so, the
company says it will be hiring more employees, especially flight
attendants.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 1949EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
