<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Amid tough union talks, BellSouth wins service award
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- BellSouth Corp. for the third consecutive year has
won the J.D. Power and Associates award for best customer service
by a local phone company _ news BellSouth has trumpeted in past
marketing campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   This time, that award from the international consulting company
comes with BellSouth reaching crunch time in its high-stakes
contract talks with the union representing most of its workers, and
with the Atlanta-based regional company readying itself for
increased competition.
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Power has only ranked local phone companies three times.
BellSouth has won each time, and its lead over the second-place
finisher has grown. Last year, BellSouth beat out PacTel. This
time, second place went to Cincinnati Bell, with PacTel and
Southern New England Telephone tied for third.
</P>
<P>
   The award gauges customer service _ just as BellSouth officials
sat at bargaining tables with the union representing most of the
company's service employees, including operators and technicians.
Those talks face a deadline: At 11:59 p.m. Saturday, the contract
covering 48,000 workers represented by the Communications Workers
of America expires, and the union side is armed with the
authorization of its members to call a strike.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Smith, CWA vice president for the Southeast, said he wants
BellSouth to make the connection clear between the workers he
represents and the J.D. Power award. Smith says he wants the union
and its workers to share in the good fortunes of the company, which
has reported a long string of record profits.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has about 86,000 workers. Most represented by the CWA
are working for BellSouth Telecommunications, the phone unit that
supplies local service to the nine Southeastern states. Charles
Coe, president of BellSouth Telecommunications, said he sees no
connection between the contract negotiations and the J.D. Power
award. However, he said management is aware of its dependence on
its workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our employees, particularly our front-line employees, are the
best in the business,'' he said. ``We make no secret of the fact
that they deserve the credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Talks will produce a new contract, despite the differences that
remain, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials have said the biggest obstacles to a pact are
pension and other retirement benefits, compulsory overtime and the
use of non-company workers.
</P>
<P>
   Power's rankings were based on a study of more than 14,000
households, said Peter Dresch, director of telecommunications
market analysis for J.D. Power. He called the results especially
promising for a company like BellSouth, whose long-standing
monopoly is expected to end soon.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of companies have filed for local service competition
against BellSouth. In metro Atlanta, BellSouth faces about a dozen
competitors in the local service market, all selling only to
businesses except MGC Communications and MediaOne.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
