<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta expanding service to large business centers
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Delta Air Lines has announced a major expansion of
its daily flights to major business centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our business customers have demanded more service to key
cities, and Delta is responding,'' said President and Chief
Executive Officer Leo F. Mullin.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin, who made the announcement at the Metro Atlanta Chamber
of Commerce, said many Delta flights at Hartsfield International
Airport routinely have load factors, or the percentage of seats
filled, exceeding 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Oct. 1, Delta will add 21 flights. As a result, the
airline will have 633 daily flights from Hartsfield.
</P>
<P>
   Hourly service will begin to Boston and Newark. Also, there will
be more flights to New York's LaGuardia, Baltimore and Washington
Dulles.
</P>
<P>
   Delta will also start service to Chicago's Midway Airport, in
addition to existing service to Chicago's O'Hare.
</P>
<P>
   Business travelers account for more than half the passengers to
the markets being expanded.
</P>
<P>
   But Delta has also been cutting or eliminating flights to some
smaller markets, including Toledo, Ohio; Fort Wayne, Ind.; and
Columbia, S.C. As a result, Thursday's announcement means a net
increase of 11 flights, Mullin said.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin also pressed for fifth and sixth runways at Hartsfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not frustrated right now because I feel progress is being
made,'' he said. In July, a record 2.5 million passengers flew
Delta in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
