<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT OVERTURNS CHILD-PORN CONVICTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A federal appeals court has overturned the conviction
of a Maine man who allegedly crossed state lines intending to have
sex with children, a case developed by a well-known New Hampshire
``cybercop'' who's made a career of snaring on-line predators.
</P>
<P>
   While the case before the US Court of Appeals for the First
Circuit in Boston involved old-fashioned solicitation -- the
defendant, Paul George Gamache had answered an ad in a swingers
magazine -- the ad was placed by Keene, N.H. detective James
McLaughlin.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin's targeting of Internet chat rooms, particularly ones
frequented by pedophiles, has resulted in the arrest of more than
70 men, including some from overseas, on sex charges.
</P>
<P>
   But the unit's tactics, which include detectives like McLaughlin
posing as children on-line, has drawn the criticism of civil
libertarians who say such high-tech crimefighting has veered into
entrapment.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the First Circuit said jurors are entitled to consider
that possibility.
</P>
<P>
   While not ruling on the legality of police officers luring
pedophiles via computer chat rooms, the court found that defendants
like Gamache are entitled to argue before a jury that they were
entrapped. During Gamache's trial, the judge prohibited his
attorney, Michael J. Sheehan, from presenting an entrapment defense
and jurors were not told they could consider one.
</P>
<P>
   Gamache, then a 55-year-old service worker with the Maine Yankee
Nuclear Power Plant, answered an ad placed by McLaughlin in
Tri-State Swingers in May 1995. After exchanging a series of
letters with a fictitious woman who said she wanted Gamache to
provide ``sex training'' for her three young children, ages 8
through 12, Gamache agreed to meet her at Keene motel. When he
arrived in the parking lot he was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   He was later convicted and sentenced to five years in federal
prison.
</P>
<P>
   In its 27-page ruling, the three-judge panel said that Gamache
answered the ad intending to have sex only with the mother and it
was the detectives, who raised, and pursued, the idea of the
children participating.
</P>
<P>
   Gamache, the court noted, had no criminal record and there was
no evidence linking him to child exploitation in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the government that first mentioned the children as sex
objects... and it was the government that escalated the subject of
sex with children,'' the court found.
</P>
</TEXT>
