<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-RENO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PANEL VOTES TO CITE RENO FOR CONTEMPT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bitterly divided House panel voted Thursday to
cite Attorney General Janet Reno for contempt for refusing to turn
over memos that Republicans argue could bolster their case for
appointing an independent counsel to probe alleged Democratic
fund-raising abuses.
</P>
<P>
   The House Government Reform and Oversight Committee took the
rare step of slapping a Cabinet official with a contempt charge
after Reno refused to turn over written recommendations from FBI
director Louis Freeh and Charles LaBella, who headed a Justice
Department campaign finance task force.
</P>
<P>
   Those memos summarized the status of the probe into alleged
fund-raising abuses stemming from the 1996 presidential election
and recommend that Reno appoint a special prosecutor to pursue the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-19 vote was along party lines, with all Republicans
backing the extraordinary measure and all Democrats and one
independent, Bernard Sanders of Vermont, opposing it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
The two Texans on the panel split along party lines, with Rep. Jim
Turner, D-Crockett, voting against the measure and Rep. Pete
Sessions, R-Dallas, supporting it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The contempt recommendation now must be taken up by the full
House, which is not expected to consider it until members return
from summer recess in September.
</P>
<P>
   If the full House were to vote for contempt it would then have
to be enforced by the U.S. Attorney's Office for the District of
Columbia, who reports to the attorney general. The maximum penalty
for contempt is a $100,000 fine or a year in jail.
</P>
<P>
   After the vote Reno said that she would continue to seek a
compromise with the committee but would not agree to their demands
to turn over the entire memos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I simply have to draw the line and stand up for what I believe
to be a very important principle; prosecutions must be free of
political influence,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, who has so far refused to appoint an independent counsel,
said that releasing the detailed memos to Congress would compromise
her department's campaign finance investigation because they
contain sensitive information that may be used in the prosecution
of individuals.
</P>
<P>
   She had offered to brief the lawmakers on the contents of the
memo at the end of this month after she has analyzed the LaBella
memo, which was given to her in July.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republicans on the committee, led by their combative
chairman Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., refused to accept Reno's offer
and countered that it was merely part of the Clinton
administration's history of stonewalling Congress when it comes to
turning over sensitive information.
</P>
<P>
   Burton said the committee needed the memos to determine whether
Reno was following the law regarding the appointment of an
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it appears that the attorney general is not upholding the
law, then the people have a right to know what's happening,''
Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats countered that Burton was merely trying to grab
headlines and revive an investigation that has been plagued by a
series of missteps.
</P>
<P>
   ``This meeting of the committee is being staged in the hope of
doing something drastic. We will appear relevant once again. The
guiding principle seems to be that it's better to be reckless and
extreme than to be ignored,'' said Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., the
ranking Democrat on the committee.
</P>
<P>
   The debate had the same level of intense partisan rancor that
has infected the committee since it launched the investigation last
year. At one point when Burton referred to the ``historic''
significance of the contempt move, the Democrats burst out
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats argued that it would be imprudent to turn over the
documents to the committee, noting that Freeh and LaBella testified
earlier this week that such a move could harm the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans responded that they informed Reno that she could
black out information in the memos. Furthermore, they said that the
memos would only be read by members of the committee and not made
public.
</P>
<P>
   When Democrats responded that the committee has had a history of
leaking confidential information, Republicans retorted that the
existence of the Freeh and LaBella memos were leaked to the media
by Justice Department officials.
</P>
<P>
   Reno later denied that she or any of her subordinates leaked
those memos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering the pain it's caused me, that's the most
ridiculous thing I've heard of,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has said that in the next three weeks she will review her
previous decision last fall not to appoint an independent counsel
in light of the LaBella memo.
</P>
<P>
   If she appoints a special prosecutor, the House almost surely
would not take up the contempt charges.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said that the committee's action Thursday marked the
first time that a congressional committee had cited an attorney
general for contempt.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is not the first time that such drastic action has
been taken against other executive branch officials.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982 the House Energy and Commerce Committee cited Reagan's
Interior Secretary James Watt for contempt for refusing to produce
documents regarding Canadian energy and investment policies. The
charge was not taken up by the full House.
</P>
<P>
   The same year the full House voted to cite Environmental
Protection Agency chief Ann Gorsuch for contempt for refusing to
turn over documents regarding the superfund program.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975 the House Intelligence Committee cited Secretary of
State Henry Kissinger for contempt, but that matter was resolved a
few hours before the full House was to vote.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
