<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARINGS PROBE INFORMANT'S CREDIBILITY WITH FBI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Had he known that mob informant Angelo ``Sonny''
Mercurio didn't warn the FBI about the planned assassination of
boss Francis Salemme in June 1989, an FBI agent who vouched for
Mercurio's credibility before a federal judge might have viewed him
differently.
</P>
<P>
   The agent, Walter J. Steffens Jr., testified in federal court
Thursday that ``if Mr. Mercurio had been involved in the shooting
of Frankie Salemme and failed to notify the FBI ahead of time that
the shooting would take place, then, yes, that would have affected
his reliability'' as a bureau informant.
</P>
<P>
   Mercurio's ``reliability'' is at issue because Steffens, an
agent formerly assigned to the bureau's organized crime squad in
Boston, signed an affidavit in October 1989 which portrayed
Mercurio as a trusted informant.
</P>
<P>
   And that affidavit helped convince a federal judge to issue a
``roving bug'' _ a wide-ranging listening device that was used to
make a first-ever recording of a Mafia induction ceremony on Oct.
29, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony before Judge Mark Wolf Thursday, Steffens made
it clear that he was kept in the dark even as he prepared court
papers for submission to US District Judge David S. Nelson, who
authorized the roving bug.
</P>
<P>
   Steffens testified that at the time, he was unaware of two
facts: that Mercurio told FBI supervisor James Ring the time and
place of the ceremony hours before Steffens met with Nelson, and
that the bureau had a witness who was willing to wear a hidden
microphone.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Nelson might not have authorized the roving bug if he
thought investigators could get evidence that way, Steffens said.
The legality of the bugging is being challenged on two fronts in
federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Salemme, who survived the botched hit outside a Saugus pancake
house, wants the tape thrown out as evidence. So do his
co-defendants, mob soldier Robert DeLuca and Winter Hill gangsters
Stephen Flemmi and John Martorano. Winter Hill leader James
``Whitey'' Bulger, &UR;  &LR; the fifth defendant, fled before he was
indicted.
</P>
<P>
   The recording, which established for the first time the
existence of La Cosa Nostra, underpins the landmark 1995 indictment
that accuses the local Mafia and the Winter Hill gang of a
decades-long conspiracy to carve up the region's rackets.
</P>
<P>
   The same tape recording is being challenged in a different case
involving 15 mobsters and associates who engaged in a bloody,
five-year battle to topple Salemme in the late 1980s and early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf must decide whether Nelson was given accurate and complete
information at the time the bug was authorized.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers argue that the government should have told
Nelson that the FBI knew the exact time and location of the
induction ceremony _ a house in Medford on Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than request permission to plant listening devices in
that house alone, the government sought a roving bug, which isn't
tied to a specific location and is designed for organized crime
figures who avoid meeting at a specific place. The induction
ceremony was never mentioned to Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the lead prosecutor in the case testified that she
doubted that the mobsters would hold the secret ceremony in a
suburban neighborhood on a Sunday morning _ and, in any case, the
FBI had asked her not to mention it to protect Mercurio.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the government wanted the roving bug so it could
continue eavesdropping on the conversations of mob consigliere
Joseph J.R. Russo and capo regimes Vincent Ferrara and Robert
Carrozza for up to 30 days, regardless of where they met.
 &UR;  &LR; However, no conversations were intercepted after the induction
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Under several hours of questioning by DeLuca's lawyer, Randolph
Gioia, Steffens acknowledged that Mercurio _ who reportedly had
planned the attempted murder of Salemme along with Ferrara,
Carrozza and Russo _ was not a target of the bug, even though he
was described in the application as being ``responsible for murder
and racketeering.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
