<SLUG> BC-MA-TEEN-DRIVERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI SIGNS TOUGH NEW TEEN DRIVING LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The numbers are startling: Almost half of the state's
16-year-old drivers were involved in an accident last year, as were
nearly a quarter of 17-year-old motorists. Two-thirds of the
teenagers killed in car accidents are in vehicles driven by another
teenager.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, flanked by families who have lost loved ones in auto
accidents, Acting Governor Paul Cellucci signed a law to change
that grim reality by dramatically restricting teenagers' driving
rights.
</P>
<P>
   The law, which takes effect in 90 days, will require more
training and parental supervision for teenage drivers, forbid their
unsupervised late-night driving, and prohibit them from having
other teenagers in the car for the first six months of their
licensing unless accompanied by an adult.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statistics show that too many teens are reckless when they
drive,'' said Cellucci. ``This new law will help prevent teen
drivers from being a hazard to themselves and others.''
</P>
<P>
   The aim of the new statute is to give teenage drivers more
experience behind the wheel before they are put in distracting or
dangerous situations.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Christine Reif, mother of 16-year-old Ricky
Harrington, who died in a 1995 car accident that also claimed the
lives of two other youths, said such a law could spare other
families the pain hers had suffered. The driver, a 17-year-old, had
his license fewer than four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one family is spared the pain of a teen tragedy, if one
parent does not get the call that every parent dreads and the words
that I will never stop hearing in my head _ `your child is dead' _
if one parent is spared the trip to the morgue to identify the
child who had held so much promise and had everything to live for,
then the graduated license law will be a success,'' said Reif.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in hushed tones, Shawn O'Connell of Brookfield talked
of carelessly causing a fatal accident five years ago, when as a
16-year-old driver he tried to speed away from the car behind him,
lost control, and crashed into an oncoming vehicle, killing a woman
and severely injuring her young daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have spent the last four years of my life living with this
every single day, that I have devastated a family and countless
others,'' said O'Connell, who said the new law could help other
young drivers get the experience they need to prevent such
occurrences.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new law, to get a junior operator's license, anyone
under 18 will have to participate in a driver's education class,
which must include 12 hours of supervised driving with a parent.
</P>
<P>
   For the first six months after a teenager gets a license, he or
she cannot have another teenager in the car unless accompanied by
an adult sitting in the front seat. Further, no one under 18 will
be allowed to drive between midnight and 5 a.m. unless accompanied
by an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Only when a young driver turns 18 can he or she trade in the
junior driver's license for full driving privileges.
</P>
<P>
   The new law will also specify six-month license suspensions for
any teenager convicted of driving under the influence, attempting
to purchase alcohol, or drag racing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
