<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FCC-DATA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FCC GIVES REGIONAL BELLS OK ON DATA SERVICE SUBSIDIARIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Regional telephone companies, banned from entering the
long-distance telephone market, got Thursday what might be
considered a consolation prize: A potential chance to provide
high-speed data service to homes and businesses in their regions.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission said it would consider
allowing each regional Bell company to create a separate subsidiary
to provide advanced data services. What makes this a prize is that
these subsidiaries would not have to sell their data services to
competitors at discounted prices.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, regional phone companies are mandated to resell their
telephone services to rivals at discount prices. But under FCC
rules aimed at encouraging investment in new technology, the Bell
companies would not be required to resell their data services to
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   These high-speed data services would allow consumers in their
homes to instantaneously open World Wide Web pages with the click
of the button, instead of waiting minutes using much slower modems.
</P>
<P>
   ``By opening up and unleashing the power of these high-capacity
networks to promote (electronic) commerce, we are going to improve
the lives of American consumers in this country,'' said FCC
chairman William Kennard, adding that the nation's $20 billion
electronic commerce business will grow to $350 billion in four
years.
</P>
<P>
   While few disputed Kennard's optimism, Bell Atlantic and some of
its rivals had serious doubts about the structure of FCC's plan,
which will undergo public scrutiny in the next 60 to 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic, which in January was among the first local phone
companies to ask the FCC for permission to launch a high-speed data
network, said the FCC's decision will not help consumers
immediately because of regulatory limitations on subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately the (FCC) action falls far short of the `giant
leap' required to deploy advanced telecommunications services to
all Americans,'' said Tom Tauke, Bell Atlantic's senior vice
president for government relations.
</P>
<P>
   Both AT&AMP;T and MCI said they were opposed to Bell Atlantic and
the other regional phone companies establishing subsidiaries to
carry high-speed data traffic, claiming that only separate
ownership would protect consumers.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T officials said the subsidiary plan, as outlined by the FCC
Thursday, would still allow the Bell companies to use their
enormous monopoly power to favor their own data network operations.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Sallet, MCI's chief policy counsel, said allowing Bell
Atlantic the chance to get into data networking through a
company-owned subsidiary ``is like paying yourself to park in your
own garage: you can pay $1 or $1 million because it ends up all
staying with you.'' Sallet said MCI would oppose the FCC subsidiary
plan.
</P>
<P>
   But Congressman Edward J. Markey of Massachusetts, the ranking
Democrat on the House Telecommunications subcomittee, praised the
FCC's ruling, saying it promotes competition under the 1996
Telecommunications Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the FCC polices the separate subsidiaries and
offers equal treatment to every other company seeking to create
data networks, this policy should work for both Bell Atlantic and
MCI,'' said Markey. ``If a regional Bell company tried to block out
a competitor, then MCI or AT&AMP;T should blow the whistle on them at
that time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
