<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHIHUAHUA-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: SUCCESS OF TACO BELL TALKING CHIHUAHUA ADS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (af)  
 By COURTNEY KANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No one expresses more surprise about the success of
the Taco Bell talking Chihuahua than those who created the quirky
character.
</P>
<P>
   In just a year, the dog has earned a place alongside such adland
instant phenomena as the doubting youngster named Mikey of the Life
cereal commercials; the skeptical old woman named Clara Peller who
bellowed, ``Where's the beef?''; the smarmy guy who tried to cadge
limousine rides and free Bud Light by passing himself off as
someone important, and the battery-powered Energizer bunny that
keeps ``going and going and going.''
</P>
<P>
   The dog has appeared on the annual ``It List'' of hot trends
compiled by Entertainment Weekly magazine, has been profiled in the
Spanish-language People magazine and appeared on the
``Entertainment Tonight'' and ``Access Hollywood'' television
shows. It is even showing up on merchandise like T-shirts and hats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were surprised that the campaign became as popular as it
did and as quickly as it did,'' said Clay Williams, the copywriter
on the account. He is a managing partner and creative director at
the Venice, Calif., office of TBWA Chiat/Day, the Taco Bell agency.
</P>
<P>
   But now the challenge for TBWA Chiat/Day, part of the TBWA
Worldwide unit of Omnicom Group, is to keep its Chihuahua from
becoming a one-shot wonder that will soon be relegated to the
``Where are they now?'' corner of Madison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The Chihuahua was introduced in early July 1997 as part of an
umbrella campaign for Taco Bell, a chain owned by Tricon Global
Restaurants. Only one of the four commercials in the campaign
showed the Chihuahua, which was pursuing Taco Bell food and
proclaiming, ``Yo quiero Taco Bell'' (``I want Taco Bell''). The
campaign carried the theme ``Want some?''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you do something right, your customers let you know
immediately,'' said Vada Hill, chief marketing officer at Taco Bell
in Irvine, Calif. ``Once they saw the first ad, they wanted to see
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea has always been that the dog personifies the feeling
that customers have about our food, and the relationship that they
have with our brand. For as long as we remain true to that, we will
have a winning campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   So the ``Want some?'' theme was played down in favor of the
bug-eyed dog's ``Yo quiero Taco Bell.'' The first commercial with
the dog as the star ran later that month.
</P>
<P>
   Now the character has appeared in 15 commercials, performing
stunts as varied as taking on Godzilla and leading a revolution.
The common thread: ``the dog's relentless pursuit for Taco Bell
food,'' said Chuck Bennett, Williams' art director partner, who is
also a managing partner and creative director at TBWA Chiat/Day.
</P>
<P>
   Taco Bell does not disclose spending for individual campaigns,
but it spends an estimated $200 million annually in media
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   How and why did this funny-looking dog become such a hit?
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that ``we don't treat the dog as a dog,'' Williams
said. ``We treat him as a 19-year-old trapped in a dog's body,'' he
said. ``He's a cool character that happens to be a dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett agreed, saying, ``People see themselves in the dog,''
and they want to see what the dog will do next.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage that, Bennett said, a guide was written so the
Chihuahua behaves consistently in all ads. The contents include
information about the dog, which has no owner and lives in a
tropical world, and what it does and does not do as a free spirit
about town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We treat the campaign like a sitcom with the dog as the lead
character,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   That will be seen in another series of spots to be introduced
sometime this month, showing the dog's single-minded devotion to
eating at Taco Bell.
</P>
<P>
   To help avoid overkill, which can turn the public against a
character, Williams said, the agency intended to make sure the dog
``doesn't become a spokesperson for Taco Bell and that he is still
a fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett added, ``It's really important that he represents the
consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Stack, vice president for public affairs at Taco Bell, who
heads licensed-merchandise efforts for the company, said that
merchandise bearing images of the Chihuahua would be limited to
``merchandise that only enhances the brand and reaches our core
consumers in a positive way.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, 44, and Williams, 37, have been collaborating at TBWA
Chiat/Day for three years. Other campaigns they have worked on
include the ``Enjoy the ride'' ads for the Nissan Motor Corp. USA,
which never garnered anywhere near the attention of the Taco Bell
campaign despite the presence of a Jack Russell terrier in the arms
of the K character who represented Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't watch commercials,'' William said. ``They watch
what's interesting to them. So as long as we do our job in keeping
the Chihuahua and campaign interesting, and not so much force a
sales message down their throats, people will continue to embrace
our approach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
