<HEADLINE>
SHARP DROP NOTED IN EXPORTS FROM BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts exports fell sharply in the first
quarter, providing fresh evidence that Asia's weak currencies and
shrinking economies are eating into demand for goods manufactured
in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The state exported $4.245 billion in goods during the first
three months of the year, a decline of &UR;  &LR; $278.3 million, or 6.1
percent, from the final three months of 1997, according to Alliance
for the Commonwealth, a business group that tracks exports.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a big quarterly drop, exports in the January-March
quarter were actually $98.9 million higher than exports in the same
quarter of 1997. But that slim 2.4 percent rise over the year was
markedly slower than the 6.1 percent rise in US exports overall,
the report said. It may in part reflect the state's heavy reliance
on sales of computers and components to Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Exports to Taiwan, South Korea, and Singapore have been hardest
hit among the state's trading partners. Purchases by those
countries of everything from semiconductor equipment and computers
to scrap brass fell by $139.4 million over the past year. Exports
to Canada, the state's biggest trading partner, were also off.
Appreciation of the US dollar against that country's dollar made
American products extremely expensive in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first statistical evidence we have statewide that
there's an impact in Massachusetts'' of the Asian economic
collapse, said Charles McChesney, the Alliance's executive
director. ``I'm anxious about the second-quarter numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   The first-quarter drop in Massachusetts exports is the steepest
in a single quarter since the Mexican peso collapse cut into
exports to the Nafta trading partner two years ago, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the peso crisis, which caused a downward blip in
exports and was followed by record growth in exports, some
economists and trade experts fear that the Asia-induced export
slump may be more enduring.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's economic troubles have not yet had a big impact on the
state's exports, though the extent of that country's economic
troubles is still unfolding. Exports to Japan, the state's
second-biggest customer, were ``down slightly,'' the alliance said.
</P>
<P>
   It is too soon to predict whether Massachusetts exports will
continue to fall in future quarters. Overall, the state's economy
is still strong _ it is expected to grow by more than 3.5 percent
this year _ and the jobless rate remains at record lows.
</P>
<P>
   But there is increasing evidence of weakness, especially in the
electronics sector. LTX Corp., a Westwood supplier to the
semiconductor industry, said this week that it would lay off 300
employees _ nearly a third of its work &UR;  &LR; force _ due to a downturn
in demand from Asian customers. Stratus Computer Inc.'s stock
plunged in June after it said that a downturn in Asia's demand for
its sophisticated computers had hurt profits; the company announced
a merger with Ascend Communications this week.
</P>
<P>
   The export report contained hints that Massachusetts' economy,
with its cluster of computer and high-technology companies around
Boston, may be more vulnerable than the nation to Asia's woes.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts exports in the second-quarter were 2.4 percent
higher than exports in the second quarter of 1997. That pace of
growth was significantly below the 6.1 percent increase in exports
by all US companies.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's trade deficit shot up in May to a record $15.8
billion, and US economic growth slowed to 1.4 percent in the
April-June quarter, its smallest growth rate in three years. US
companies are beginning to report weaker profits in their
second-quarter reports. Some companies laying off workers site
reduced demand from their Asian customers.
</P>
<P>
   An increasingly diverse base of global customers has helped
Massachusetts, however. While exports to Asia and Canada were hit
hard, Mexico purchased $37 million more in goods in the first
quarter of the year than the country did a year ago. Exports to the
United Kingdom, the Netherlands and Ireland, as well as China _ the
country has not yet devalued its currency _ were also ``up
smartly,'' the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
