<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1836 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VW-ROLLS-ART-650(2TAK     08-06 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VW-ROLLS-ART-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: BRITAIN, GERMANY)  
 TWO GERMAN AUTOMOTIVE GIANTS SHARE CUSTODY OF LUXURY BRITISH
AUTOMAKER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
 By ALAN COWELL   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Early on the morning of July 28, two heavyweights of
Germany's car industry met at a discreet Bavarian country club for
an extraordinary bout of deal-making.
</P>
<P>
   Ferdinand Piech, the head of Volkswagen AG, flew in on a company
jet. Bernd Pischetsrieder, head of Bayerische Motorenwerke AG,
drove the 60 miles from Munich for the unpublicized 8:30 a.m.
encounter in a BMW 750i, the top model in the company's line.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, the two men were about to carve up the world's
most illustrious automotive names, setting the terms for a divorce
of Rolls-Royce and Bentley 67 years after they had merged.
</P>
<P>
   It was a deal that concluded months of acrimonious negotiations
over the future of Rolls-Royce Motor Cars Ltd. _ the British
manufacturer of Rolls-Royce and Bentley cars _ since Britain's
Vickers PLC put the company up for sale in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Those negotiations hinged on what analysts took to be two
critical miscalculations by Volkswagen over who owned the right to
use the Rolls-Royce name, and whose engines would power the
luxurious cars that sell for upwards of $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Only weeks before the meeting at the Neuburg country club near
Ingolstadt, Volkswagen had seemed to outflank BMW to become the
definitive buyer of Rolls-Royce and Bentley cars for about $790
million. But under the new deal, Volkswagen would have the rights
to both names only until January 1, 2003. Thereafter, the
Rolls-Royce name would be BMW's property and Bentley would belong
to Volkswagen.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement highlighted the overwhelming ambitions of German
automakers to break into the rarefied world of luxurious hand-made
automobiles: backed by solid profits, Piech in particular seemed to
have embarked on a personal crusade to acquire his own luxury name
plate _ an ambition matched only by BMW's stubborn refusal to be
dealt out of the prestigious niche.
</P>
<P>
   Both chief executives brought powerful political backers to the
table as referees _ Edmund Stoiber, the state premier of Bavaria,
where BMW has its headquarters, and Gerhard Schroder, a member of
the Volkswagen supervisory board as well as the state premier of
Lower Saxony, where VW is the largest employer, and Social Democrat
candidate for chancellor in national elections seven weeks from
now.
</P>
<P>
   Yet by the time Pischetsrieder and Piech flew on a few hours
later in the Volkswagen company jet to London to announce their
deal, they had signed an agreement that left key questions
unanswered: What, precisely, had happened to torpedo Volkswagen's
seemingly exclusive acquisition of both names? And what would it
mean for the future of Rolls-Royce Motor Cars and its clientele?
</P>
<P>
   Far from Bavaria, in Aylesbury to the west of London, Michael
Shrimpton felt he already knew. ``It's a disaster; it will kill off
both marques,'' huffed the 41-year-old lawyer and Bentley owner who
had spearheaded an unsuccessful attempt earlier this year to raise
enough money from Rolls-Royce and Bentley owners to keep both names
in British managerial hands.
</P>
<P>
   The final deal between the two German companies left a lot of
ambiguity. The ``memorandum of understanding'' signed at the
Neuburg country club meant that Volkswagen had paid the full price
of $790 million for only half the company, yet would secure both
the venerable Rolls-Royce factory in Crewe, England, and its 2,400
skilled workers. BMW, by contrast, pledged a relatively small
amount _ some $65 million _ for the Rolls-Royce name, but with no
factory and no work force: both of those have yet to be assembled.
</P>
<P>
   For both companies, the names were paramount. ``The trademark is
worth more than the assets,'' Shrimpton said. And, rather like a
divorced couple sharing custody of a child, the deal foresaw the
two German automakers pooling resources and technology to produce
the Rolls-Royce Silver Seraph at Crewe, even after 2003.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The logic of the deal was dictated by several intertwined
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   The engines from the V-12 Rolls-Royce Silver Seraph and the V-8
Bentley Arnage are supplied by BMW; and the Rolls-Royce name was
owned not by Vickers, but by Rolls-Royce PLC, the maker of jet
engines that had split from the car maker when their shared concern
collapsed in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, Rolls-Royce PLC had a separate deal dating to
1990 with BMW, which also owns the British-based automaker Rover,
to produce jet engines in Germany, and the two companies had a
strong working relationship. ``We had an understanding with BMW all
the way through,'' said Peter Barnes-Wallis, the Rolls-Royce PLC
spokesman. Indeed, Rolls-Royce PLC's support had been made clear on
March 30 when it publicly welcomed Vickers' acceptance of a $560
million bid from BMW for Rolls-Royce and Bentley, a sum later
trumped by Volkswagen's $710 million offer on May 7.
</P>
<P>
   Piech, the Volkswagen chief, though, seemed to be on a roll. In
mid-January, he had suggested in a German magazine interview that
the brand names be split. Oddly enough, in the light of what
finally happened, BMW said at the time that splitting Rolls-Royce
from Bentley would resemble splitting the ``V'' from the ``W'' in
VW.
</P>
<P>
   From then on _ protected from board criticism by Schroder's
support _ money seemed no object.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was enough cash on the balance sheet. It was not a
problem,'' said Lothar Lubinetzki, an automotive analyst with
Enskilda Securities in London. Indeed, at Volkswagen's annual
meeting in Hanover on June 4, Piech told shareholders that the
company, even with its conservative accounting procedures, had made
record after-tax profits of some $800 million. (Volkswagen also
announced in June that it would acquire Lamborghini SpA, the
Italian manufacturer of high-performance sports cars, through its
Audi unit.)
</P>
<P>
   Apart from outbidding BMW for Rolls-Royce, Piech used
Volkswagen's Audi unit to acquire Vickers' engine-building
subsidiary, Cosworth, for a further $194 million.
</P>
<P>
   And on July 3, Vickers and Volkswagen completed negotiations to
close their own deal, revaluing Rolls-Royce Motor Cars upwards by
some $80 million over the initial bid price of $710 million.
</P>
<P>
   Then, things began to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   In what other participants depicted privately as two critical
miscalculations, Volkswagen had been gambling that neither BMW nor
Rolls-Royce PLC would play hardball. Piech had dismissed threats by
BMW to stop delivering supplies of engines, software and
air-conditioning to Rolls-Royce as ``sabre rattling.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, soon after the July 3 deal between Vickers and
Volkswagen, lawyers for Rolls-Royce PLC informed Volkswagen of the
1973 licensing agreement that gave Rolls-Royce PLC exclusive
control over the Rolls-Royce name in the event of a sale to a
foreign buyer. ``BMW knew they had our support in the arrangements
for the brand name,'' Barnes-Wallis said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   By July 9, BMW fulfilled its threat by giving a contractual
12-month notice on its engine supply deal, leaving Volkswagen only
one year to develop an entirely new engine for the Rolls-Royce
Silver Seraph and the Bentley Arnage. ``That was the key,'' said
Lubinetzki at Enskilda Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Until that point, BMW had been depicted as the loser in the bid
to enter the high-end luxury market. But now, BMW, backed by
Rolls-Royce PLC, held the keys to both the licensing and the engine
supply problems confronting Volkswagen.
</P>
<P>
   In parallel negotiations, BMW executives met with Volkswagen
managers while they also struck at a deal with Rolls-Royce PLC: BMW
would pay Rolls-Royce PLC $65 million for the Rolls-Royce name in a
redeemable loan note to be used as an investment by Rolls-Royce PLC
in the new Rolls-Royce company to be founded by BMW after January
1, 2003. Rolls-Royce PLC would also be given a seat on the board of
the new company, reinforcing its influence over the brand.
</P>
<P>
   Piech could have gone to court to challenge Rolls-Royce PLC over
the name. And BMW could have gone through with the cancellation of
the engine and components supply contract.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the two German automakers risked forcing the closure
of the Rolls-Royce Motor Cars plant in Crewe as Volkswagen
struggled to develop a new engine _ a move that would have severely
harmed Volkswagen's already overpriced investment, not to mention
the very names that were so central to the negotiations. ``The
danger was that production could be terminated for a year or a year
and a half,'' Lubinetzki said. ``Volkswagen couldn't afford that.''
</P>
<P>
   Damage was already being inflicted. Potential Rolls-Royce and
Bentley buyers were shying away from committing themselves.
Rolls-Royce Motor Cars' dealers reported a 30 percent drop in
confirmed orders. (Rolls-Royce and Bentley together produce fewer
than 2,000 cars a year.)
</P>
<P>
   But the deal began to shape up. BMW promised to continue
supplying engines for the Silver Seraph and Arnage until Jan. 1,
2003, and even after that date for the Silver Seraph. BMW acquired
the Rolls-Royce license from Rolls-Royce PLC and gave it free to
Volkswagen until January 1, 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides got less than they wanted, although Volkswagen seemed
to come off worse. Volkswagen's spokesmen in Wolfsburg, Germany,
declined to return a reporter's calls to discuss the deal this
week.
</P>
<P>
   The one player left out of the entire process was Rolls-Royce
Motor Cars, whose chief executive, Graham Morris, a former Audi
executive, had promised his staff faithfully that, whatever
happened, the two names would not be split up. Two days after the
meeting in Bavaria, Morris quit to make way for a successor to be
appointed by Volkswagen.
</P>
<P>
   Enthusiasts like Shrimpton, moreover, fear that the new
arrangement will radically alter the profile of the two British
marques. Volkswagen has made no secret of its plan to develop a
more modest Bentley, possibly based on a sports coupe prototype
Bentley unveiled in 1994. Production at Rolls-Royce Motor Cars
could increase to 10,000 units a year _ most of them smaller
Bentleys, Richard Charlesworth, a company spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   A new generation of Rolls-Royce, moreover, could also have a
different character. After 2003, new models will no longer be built
at Crewe, according to the terms of the deal. Rolls-Royce has been
producing cars there since 1947, relying on a work force that has
generations of experience in such arcane matters as building walnut
dashes and hand-tooled leather seats.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
