<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROBE-SCENE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW ATTRACTION IN THE NATION'S CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ESTELLA DURAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Tourists flocked to the newest attraction in the
nation's capital Thursday, just a block away from the museums on
the Mall.
</P>
<P>
   The hottest spot in the city was the E. Barrett Prettyman
Federal Courthouse, where Monica S. Lewinsky testified for the
first time to a grand jury about her alleged relationship with
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   People called it ``Monica Beach'' for the hordes of reporters,
photographers and television crews sitting in folding chairs _ some
under umbrellas to shade the sun _ waiting to chronicle the comings
and goings at the courthouse. The nickname is a variation on
``Barry Beach'' as the courthouse entrance was known during
Washington Mayor Marion Barry's 1990 drug trial.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the tourists hoped for an up-close look at the former
White House intern now known almost universally by her first name.
They saw her for a moment when she entered the building _ and 8 1/2
hours later when she left _ dressed in a navy blue suit with white
shoes and purse.
</P>
<P>
   But the real show most of the day was the massed media, encamped
along the perimeter of the building. Tourists looked on in awe at
the reporters and photographers on hand to cover the Lewinsky
story. And the reporters there to do stories about all the
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the tourists and media coexisted peacefully.
But in one case, a spectator got too close for comfort.
</P>
<P>
   George Hancock, 32, a student at Kentucky State University in
Bowling Green, Ky., earned threats from cameramen when he walked in
front of the cameras as Lewinsky was entering the courthouse about
8:30 a.m. He was holding a yellow posterboard sign that read ``We
support you, Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Phyllis Hancock, watched as a camerman jumped at her
son to push him out of the way of the cameras. Other cameramen
shouted curses at the scared man, who still clutched his sign and
raised it. ``I just wanted Monica to see my sign,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Phyllis Hancock dropped her yellow sign, which read
``Monica tells truth, Slick Willie must.'' ``We just came down here
thinking we'd have a few posters to show our support, but my son
almost got himself killed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After the scuffle, reporters surrounded George Hancock, who gave
interviews for nearly an hour. ``I just want Monica to know that
someone in America supports her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``George, please don't give any more interviews!'' Phyllis
Hancock pleaded, but her son continued to talk to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Another attention-grabber was Lilie Smith, who said she was
disabled and homeless. She sat in a wheelchair and held a sign that
referred to the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal as ``a vile stain in the
White House.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He can lie to America, and he can lie to the press,'' she
said. ``But he's on his way down.''
</P>
<P>
   After talking with as many reporters as she could, she stood up
and pushed her wheelchair down the block.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Cook, 40, of St. Augustine, Fla., drew responses from the
crowd with his sign that read, ``It is not the stain on our
dress...It's the stain on our country...stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You speak for all of us, man,'' a spectator told Cook after
having his picture taken with him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 2013EDT &QL; 
