<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1840 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-BOS &LR;      08-06 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH HOUSE GOP AID, CAMPAIGN FINANCE BILL PASSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bloc of breakaway Republicans thwarted Speaker
Newt Gingrich Thursday in his last-ditch effort to kill a proposed
overhaul of the campaign finance system. The House then passed the
landmark plan and sent it to a reluctant Senate.
</P>
<P>
   With 61 Republicans defying Gingrich and joining the Democratic
minority, the House passed the measure, 252-179, ending one of the
more spirited and successful efforts to defy House leaders in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   That vote was taken after the defeat of the plan's final
roadblock, an alternative bill, backed by Gingrich, 222-147.
Sixty-one legislators voted present.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who has pledged to sign the plan into law,
said its passage, ``in defiance of the Republican leadership, is a
rebuke to the cynical view that political reform can never
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The milestone emboldened supporters, who vowed to triumph over
similar opposition in the Senate, where GOP leaders have killed the
plan twice in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a golden opportunity,'' said Representative Martin T.
Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat, who engineered the victory with
Representative Christopher Shays, a Connecticut Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Shays, who has endured Gingrich's ire for his renegade effort,
said he put his arm around the speaker after the bill's passage to
thank him and his leadership team for keeping their word to permit
a final vote on the measure before the House began its summer
recess last night. ``I know it was not an easy thing for them to
see this process work out the way it did,'' Shays said.
</P>
<P>
   Shays organized a group of moderate Republicans in April. They
joined Democrats in petitioning the speaker, and forcing him to
allow a debate on the overhaul plan.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition then withstood several months of political
pressure, procedural roadblocks, and ``poison pill'' amendments
orchestrated by GOP leaders in a futile attempt to scuttle the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Gingrich said the speaker had no immediate
comment on the bill's passage.
</P>
<P>
   The overhaul plan would ban unlimited, unregulated
``soft-money'' contributions, which were at the center of most
fund-raising abuses in the 1996 elections. It also would require
special-interest groups that broadcast ads within 60 days of an
election to disclose who contributes to the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous groups, including the Christian Coalition and American
Civil Liberties Union, have said they will challenge both
provisions in court as violations of free-speech rights.
</P>
<P>
   To the measure's supporters, the final passage marked ``an
extraordinary victory for the bill that would not die,'' said Ann
McBride, president of Common Cause.
</P>
<P>
   Backers said it was crucial to send the bill to the Senate
before it returns in September for the final month of the
legislative session. Until then, a coalition of interest groups,
led by Common Cause, plans to wage a grass-roots campaign aimed at
reversing the Senate setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, 52 members of the 100-member Senate endorsed the
overhaul plan, only to see it die when supporters were unable to
muster the 60 votes needed to defeat Republican-led filibusters.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, said it ``would be a
waste of time'' for backers to try again this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Democrats vowed to try to match the Shays-Meehan
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tough road because of the filibuster
resistance,'' Senator John F. Kerry said. ``But I intend to use
every parliamentary opportunity I have to make sure we have that
debate and vote in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Notable among the obstacles the House coalition overcame was a
rare procedure that called for 12 alternative measures to be
considered, with the one receiving the most votes prevailing.
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan plan received 237 votes on Monday, but it would
have died Thursday if the final alternative received more support.
</P>
<P>
   The last alternative plan, sponsored by Representatives Tom
Allen, a Maine Democrat, and Asa Hutchinson, an Arkansas
Republican, would have banned ``soft money'' contributions only to
national parties, permitting its continued flow to state parties.
The measure fell 91 votes short of defeating the Shays-Meehan
proposal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 2014EDT &QL; 
