u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREDIT-NYT &LR;      08-06 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 WORLDCOM SELLS RECORD $6.1 BILLION IN BONDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Worldcom Inc. sold a record $6.1 billion of bonds
Thursday, attracting good demand in an otherwise choppy and worried
corporate bond market. The money will help pay for Worldcom's
acquisition of the MCI Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The sale brought the total of corporate bond issuance for the
year to more than $560 billion, according to Securities Data Co.,
meaning that last year's record sales of $569.4 billion should be
shattered before the end of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers were eager enough to get Worldcom to raise the size of
its issue from the $5 billion expected as the final pricing took
place. The total sale easily outstripped the previous record for an
investment grade corporate bond, the $4.3 billion sale by the
Norfolk Southern Corp. in May of last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Worldcom sale came on a day when the government bond market
was little changed, with the price of the 30-year bond down 1/32,
to 106 16/32. The bond's yield, which moves in the opposite
direction from the price, was unchanged at 5.67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, investors will get the July employment report, which
usually has the power to move markets. July's data, however, may be
much more difficult than ususal for traders to interpret because of
the distortions caused by the United Automobile Workers strike
against General Motors, which was settled last week.
</P>
<P>
   What made the Worldcom bonds attractive were the name, the
industry _ telecommunications _ and the prospect that Worldcom's
credit rating will be increased to the single A level in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
   The sale was also helped by the fact that Worldcom's current
rating of BBB plus had just recently been raised two steps by
Standard &AMP; Poor's from BBB-, the bottom rung on the investment
grade ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Coley, the head of the capital markets and syndicate
group at the lead underwriter, Salomon Smith Barney, said that he
thought the success of the sale might help turn around the
corporate bond market, which has been spooked by the recent plunge
in the stock market and many of the same fears worrying stock
investors, including the economic crisis in Asia and the financial
turmoil in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This marks a shift in market psychology and may well give the
corporate bond market a needed boost,'' Coley said.
</P>
<P>
   John Bender, portfolio manager of the $795 million Strong
Corporate Bond Fund, bought some of the three-year and seven-year
notes and 30-year bonds from the issue. Because of the recent
turbulence in the market, he said ``we got it at a discount to what
we would have paid two or three months ago in a better
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale was in four maturities: $1.5 billion of three-year
notes with a 6.125 percent coupon priced to yield 6.163 percent, or
70 basis points over the comparable Treasury maturity; $600 million
in five-year notes with a coupon of 6.25 percent priced to yield
6.255 percent, 83 basis points over Treasuries; $2.25 billion of
seven-year notes with a coupon of 6.40 percent priced to yield
6.436 percent, 94 basis points over Treasuries, and $1.75 billion
of 30-year bonds with a coupon of 6.95 percent priced to yield
7.025 percent, 135 basis points over Treasuries. (A basis point is
one-hundredth of a percentage point.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 2015EDT &QL; 
