<HEADLINE>
EDUCATION, THAT'S THE TICKET
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any advice for  &UR; Clinton &LR; ?'' Playboy magazine asks Senator
 &UR; Daniel Moynihan &LR; , D-N.Y., at the end of a lengthy series of
questions and answers about the White House scandal in the
September issue. ``Politically right now,'' answers the senator,
``it might be good for him to become interested in education.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Washington newspaper the Hill reports that a
press breakfast with Secretary of Education  &UR; Richard Riley &LR;  was
canceled when only six out of 50 reporters invited said they might
show up.
</P>
<P>
   (Upon learning that Central Intelligence Agency headquarters is
to be renamed after  &UR; George Bush &LR; ,  &UR; John McCaslin &LR;  of the
conservative Washington Times asked readers to suggest federal
facilities that might be renamed for Clinton. The winner was the
Washington Monument.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DIANA HAD NOTHING TO WEAR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The last day of  &UR; Princess Diana  &LR; is covered in deep _ and
surprising _ detail in the September issue of Vanity Fair, which
includes a description of the scene in the Paris hospital as
morticians worked on her corpse.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Diana's hair was being styled and restyled, (chief nurse
 &UR; Beatrice &LR; )  &UR; Humbert  &LR; faced an alarming fact: They had nothing to
dress the princess in. The white pants and black top she had been
wearing had been cut off by medical personnel at the scene of the
crash.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mohamed al-Fayed  &LR; had already ordered that all the princess'
clothes be packed and flown from the Ritz to London; none were
available.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, for nearly two hours, British Embassy officials scoured
Paris for a suitable dress. Finally, the British ambassador's wife
offered one of her own _ a black dress in a light wool material
with a V-neck shawl collar.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S.: The  &UR; Duchess of York &LR;  told McCall's magazine that of her
many arduous professional obligations, she likes best to pose for
pictures and make TV ads. ``You go in, there's a hairdo, makeup.
Every day a bride. It's such a treat.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRE-PREVIN IDEAS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In a Vanity Fair story about  &UR; Andre Previn &LR; , whose ``A Streetcar
Named Desire'' premieres at the San Francisco Opera on September
19, San Francisco Opera director  &UR; Lotfi &LR;   &UR; Mansouri &LR;  talked about
other composers considered in the 15 years since he had envisioned
the  &UR; Tennessee Williams &LR;  play as an opera.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Leonard Bernstein &LR;  said no, said Mansouri, and then ``I
cornered  &UR; Stephen Sondheim &LR; , and he said, `Oh, it's such a good
play, it doesn't need music.' Well, you can say that about
Shakespeare's `Othello,' too.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Franco Zeffirelli &LR; , who was at one point going to be director,
wanted  &UR; David Grusin &LR; , who had never composed for voice; Lady
 &UR; Maria St. Just &LR; , co-trustee of Williams' estate, was partial to
 &UR; Marvin Hamlisch &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Previn said yes to the project 3 1/2 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ August 8 is annual Sneak Some Zucchini Onto Your Neighbor's
Porch Night in Mount Gretna, Pa., reports Esquire.
</P>
<P>
   _ People magazine interviewed an array of World War II veterans
about ``Saving Private Ryan,'' including  &UR; Robert &LR; 
 &UR; Slaughter &LR; , 73, who said, ``It's a tough film to get through. I've
had trouble sleeping,'' and revealed that he had seen it four
times; and  &UR; Tom Morrison &LR; , 74, who doesn't plan to see it once (``I
saw it in the original. Why look at that crap again?'').
</P>
<P>
   _ Country singer  &UR; Shania Twain  &LR; told Country American magazine
that she is taking her horse, Dancer, with her on a cross-country
tour this summer so that  &LR; she can get in some riding if she has
free time between shows. The magazine says she's never been able to
shake a frugal upbringing. ``That's just the way I am, and I'm
glad. There are too many people out there who need money for me to
be frivolous with it.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; The Artist  &LR; formerly known as Prince is said to have become a
Jehovah's Witness;  &UR; Geri Gerri  &UR; Halliwell &LR; , formerly known as the
Spice Girl  &UR; Ginger &LR; , is said to have become a Scientologist.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm saying the same things about race and sports that I was
saying in '68, maybe a little less stridently. Only difference is
then they called me a subversive and a revolutionary. Today, they
call me a consultant and pay me a bunch of money to say it.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR;  Harry Edwards, adviser to the 49ers and professor of sports
sociology at Berkeley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
