u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      08-06 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALM RETURNS TO WALL STREET AS HARD-HIT SECTORS LEAD MARKET
HIGHER  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While no one can say yet if the recent stock plunge
is over, a little calm returned to Wall Street on Thursday as some
of the worst hit sectors helped lead the market higher.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller companies stocks, which had plunged almost 14 percent to
a 1998 low in the last three weeks, rebounded, with the Russell
2000 index up 7.93 points, or 2 percent, to 406.62. Technology
stocks also rose, with Microsoft and Intel leading the Nasdaq index
up 41.31 points, or 2.31 percent, to 1,829.51. The index had fallen
11.3 percent since its recent high.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing more and more value out there,'' said Timothy
Ghriskey, senior portfolio manager at the Dreyfus Corp., who said
he was buying stocks Thursday and Wednesday. Such picking among the
rubble will be needed to turn the market around.
</P>
<P>
   But Ghriskey was not buying the big, well-known stocks that have
been popular this year, saying that such stocks were still
overpriced, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors had driven up the prices of these large capitalization
stocks earlier in the year based on an earnings outlook that in
retrospect was too optimistic, in part because of the drag from
Asia. As a result, stock prices may have to slip some more before
they are more in line with diminished expectations for corporate
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ghriskey said, ``Some stability in the market will bring
out the people who like to buy on the dips.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the signs of stability Thursday was the relatively narrow
range of trading in the major stock gauges. On Tuesday, the Dow
Jones industrial average swung almost 370 points from its high to
low and finished with a 163-point plunge in the last half hour. On
Wednesday, the trading range was 213 points, with the day ending
with a 184 point surge.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, as the Dow rose 30.90 points, or 0.4 percent, to
8,577.68, the day's point swing was just 107 points and there was
no big reversal at the end of the day. The broader Standard &AMP;
Poor's index of 500 stocks climbed 8.20 points, or 0.8 percent, to
1,089.63.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Dow and the S&AMP;P 500 fell more than 10 percent from
their July record highs during trading on Wednesday. But they
managed to finish the day down just under 10 percent, which is the
level that many analysts say means the market has suffered a
correction. The last such correction came last October, when a
554-point plunge in the Dow pulled the measure down 13.3 percent
from its August 1997 high.
</P>
<P>
   Another positive sign Thursday was the reversal of the
performance of advancing stocks versus those declining, with 1,699
stocks rising and 1,280 falling.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, even though the Dow ended the day higher, the
number of falling stocks on the New York Stock Exchange outnumbered
the advancers 1,841 to 1,270. One Tuesday the rout was even worse,
with 2,626 stocks falling and only 514 rising. Trading volume
topped 768 million, above average but below the over 800 million
days Tuesday and Wednesday that are now the second and third
biggest volume days ever.
</P>
<P>
   Given the volatility of trading this week, Thursday's release of
the July employment report could be unsettling to the market. But
the data may be hard to interpret because of the distortions caused
by the strikes against General Motors, which were just settled last
week.
</P>
<P>
   The report is the first look at the strength of the economy in
the third quarter, and stronger-than-expected job growth might ease
some concerns about earnings shortfalls. On the other hand, weaker
growth can help allay fears that the Federal Reserve will raise
interest rates to slow growth and contain inflationary pressures.
Last month, the chairman of the Federal Reserve, Alan Greenspan,
warned that if the economy did not slow, the Fed might have to
raise interest rates, setting off the market's recent slump.
</P>
<P>
   The range of forecasts for non-farm payroll jobs in July runs
from a decline of 50,000 to an increase of 100,000, well below the
recent averages. But figuring out how much of that slowing of
growth is because of the GM strikes and how much is from the
economy continuing to slow could be difficult, leaving the outlook
for the economy less clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people will just dismiss the numbers,'' said
Ghriskey.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
