<SLUG> BC-GAYS-DISCRIMINATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE KILLS ANTI-GAY MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a heated debate on gay rights and affirmative
action Wednesday, the House soundly rebuffed a measure intended to
reverse President Clinton's executive order banning discrimination
against gays and lesbians employed by federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The 252-to-176 vote marked a major victory for pro-gay forces.
The amendment by Colorado Republican Joel Hefley was the highest
profile gay issue to come before Congress this term, with the
exception of the stalled nomination of James Hormel as ambassador
to Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're absolutely jubilant,'' said Elizabeth Birch, executive
director of the Human Rights Campaign, a national gay lobby. ``For
the first time in the history of this country, the U.S. House of
Representatives voted that discrimination against gay and lesbian
Americans is wrong, and we're proud of Democrats and Republicans
alike.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hefley amendment was a top priority of religious and social
conservatives, who recently opened a broad campaign against legal
and political advances by gays.
</P>
<P>
   Both gay and anti-gay lobbying groups brought all their
firepower to bear on the Hefley amendment. Birch attributed the
victory to polls showing overwhelming support for Clinton's
executive order. A Wall Street Journal/NBC News polls last week
showed 72 percent of those polled were in favor of banning
discrimination against gays.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides framed the issue as a debate over whether the
executive order amounted to special rights or equal rights for gays
and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   That question is pivotal on political as well as legal grounds:
Polls consistently show that the public strongly opposes
discrimination against homosexuals but also opposes granting them
``special rights'' or job preferences.
</P>
<P>
   California Republican Tom Campbell called it ``deeply hurtful''
to those who oppose affirmative action ``to hear the argument that
to ban discrimination necessarily leads to affirmative action.''
</P>
<P>
   Another California Republican, Dana Rohrabacher, added that
Clinton's order ``simply states that the federal government will
not consider sexual orientation in making hiring, firing and
promotion decisions.'' Affirmative action is ``not what this is
about,'' Rohrabacher said. ``The government should never persecute
or promote homosexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   Hefley attached the provision to the annual spending bill for
the Commerce, Justice and State departments. He argued that
Clinton's executive order went further than banning discrimination,
warning that it would apply affirmative action remedies to gays,
including hiring quotas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does much more than address sex discrimination,'' Hefley
said. Clinton's order adds sexual orientation to President Nixon's
original 1969 executive order banning discrimination on the basis
of gender, race and other characteristics, Hefley said, arguing
that the affirmative action programs that sprang up in response to
Nixon's original directive will now apply to gays, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``History shows this means quotas and set-asides,'' Hefley said.
``This is a flagrant misapplication of presidential power.''
</P>
<P>
   When he announced the executive order in May, Clinton stated
that it merely ensured uniform policy across the federal
government, which already bans hiring discrimination against gays
and lesbians. Clinton said his order ``does not and cannot create
any new enforcement rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Hefley lost the support of more than 60 Republicans and won only
a handful of Democrats to the measure. Most Democrats, including a
large contingent of African Americans, described the issue as one
of simple civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a black woman who was forbidden from attending public
schools because of the color of my skin, I am especially troubled
to witness this divisive, unfair and un-American attack on the
civil rights of our fellow citizens and our constituents,'' said
Democrat Barbara Lee, who represents Oakland, Calif. ``And as a
Christian who was raised to believe in tolerance and respect and
justice, I am especially saddened to see animus and homophobia
cloaked in religious terms.''
</P>
<P>
   But Alabama Republican Bob Riley said the Clinton order ``grants
special rights and privileges based on sexual orientation.'' Riley,
joined by a number of other Republicans, argued that ``legitimate
civil rights'' are based on such immutable characteristics as
gender and race, while homosexuality is a behavioral choice that
does not merit discrimination protection.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Kolbe, an Arizona Republican who is gay, insisted that
Clinton's order does not give anyone a new right to sue or grants a
new ``protected class'' for affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   Birch said gay lobbyists' next priority is to kill an amendment
sponsored by Rep. Frank Riggs, a Republican from Northern
California, that narrowly passed the House last week. That
provision seeks to punish San Francisco for requiring groups
contracting with the city to provide health benefits for domestic
partners. The Riggs amendment was never approved by the Senate; its
survival would require acceptance by a House-Senate conference
committee, which is considered unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The Riggs and Hefley amendments are part of high-profile battle
over gay rights. Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, who recently
compared homosexuality to kleptomania and alcoholism in an
interview, has refused to schedule a vote on Hormel's ambassadorial
nomination. Then last month, conservatives started to take out
full-page ads that suggested gays could be ``reformed'' through
faith in God and prayer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
