r n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTS-INVASION-SFCHRON     08-06 0436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTS-INVASION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICIOUS ANTS INVADE CALIFORNIA ORCHARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID PERLMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    SAN FRANCISCO _ A viciously stinging insect called the red
imported fire ant has invaded almond orchards in Kern and Fresno
counties, and state officials have quarantined the invaded areas as
they mount a campaign to wipe out the pests before they can spread
further.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thirty-one colonies of the insects were recently discovered in a
Fresno County almond orchard near the town of Kerman, and 16
colonies were found last October near Lost Hills in Kern County,
according to Aurelio Posadas, a biologist and manager of the
eradication project with the State Department of Food and
Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   The ants are a particularly invasive species known
scientifically as Solenopsis invicta, and they apparently reached
California as hitch-hikers inside beehives shipped by a Texas
beekeeper, according to James Brazzle, the University of
California's entomology farm adviser for the Kern County
cooperative extension service. The Texas bees are used by almond
growers to pollinate the blossoms on their trees.
</P>
<P>
   Posadas and Brazzle said Wednesday they have worked out an
eradication campaign that will survey all potential invasion sites
and employ a chemical bait to attract the ants in the earthen
mounds they build, then apply a powerful but ecologically sound
insecticide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to move fast and attack them with a sledgehammer
before they become solidly established,'' Brazzle said.
</P>
<P>
   Both the invaded areas have now been quarantined so that state
officials and orchard managers can prevent the ants from spreading.
Officials will examine all produce, farm equipment and other
materials moving in and out of the quarantine zones, according to
Allen Clark of the Food and Agriculture department.
</P>
<P>
   The red fire ants are uniquely capable of stinging repeatedly,
and their venom is extremely powerful, Brazzle said. Their stings
have been known to kill calves and other small animals, and they
also feed on many plant species.
</P>
<P>
   They are more than a nuisance to humans because they respond
``rapidly and aggressively'' whenever they are disturbed, Brazzle
said. ``And when you stumble across one, it's a particularly
painful experience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another related species, the Southern fire ant Solenopsis
xyloni, has long been established in California, and it is
extremely difficult to tell one of the ants from another, Brazzle
said. Working together, farmers and state agriculture officials
have battled the established ant species continually for many
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
