u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-RENO-BOS &LR;      08-06 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-RENO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL'S GOP MEMBERS CENSURE RENO IN FUNDRAISING PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A House committee, led by Republicans determined to
put pressure on Janet Reno and embarrass the Clinton
administration, Thursday voted to hold the Attorney General in
contempt of Congress for refusing to turn over Justice Department
memos recommending she name an independent counsel to probe alleged
Democratic campaign-fundraising abuses.
</P>
<P>
   After a long and rancorous public hearing, all Republicans on
the Committee on Government Reform and Oversight voted to cite Reno
for contempt for refusing the panel's subpoena for the documents.
All committee Democrats, plus Independent Bernard Sanders of
Vermont, opposed the extraordinary measure.
</P>
<P>
   Reno reacted quickly, saying she regretted the committee action,
which she called a ``form of political tampering that no prosecutor
in America could accept.'' But she said she would not be cowed into
naming an independent counsel or turning over to Congress sensitive
prosecution memos that could damage the Justice Department's
ongoing probe of 1996 fundraising.
</P>
<P>
   ``I simply have to draw the line for what I believe to be an
important principle: Prosecutions in America must be free of
political influence,'' Reno said at a Justice Department press
conference.
</P>
<P>
   The House has never held a Cabinet officer in contempt of
Congress, and most lawmakers doubt that Thursday's recommendation
will reach the full House for a vote. Reno says she will review and
act on the memos in question within the next three weeks and then
discuss at least some of their contents with committee chairmen
before Congress returns in September from its summer recess.
</P>
<P>
   Because the House has no enforcement powers, the Justice
Department says a contempt citation would be handled by Deputy
Attorney General Eric Holder. He would have to decide whether to
appoint an independent counsel to prosecute a criminal case against
Reno. Criminal penalties range up to a $10,000 fine and a year in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most members understand that what happened today was political
grandstanding, an empty exercise that is going absolutely
nowhere,'' said Representative John Tierney, a Massachusetts
Democrat who is a member of the government reform committee.
``Chairman (Dan) Burton's efforts to make Reno look bad instead
made her look like somebody who can stand up to a bully.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Burton said he, too, regretted citing Reno for
contempt, but he insisted it was necessary for his oversight
committee to find out why Reno was ignoring the recommendations of
her own deputies and whether she was doing so as a political agent
protecting the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had hoped the attorney general would work with us in good
faith to try to resolve this impasse, but she hasn't,'' Burton said
as Thursday's hearing opened. ``The American people have a right to
know what is happening. If we believe that the attorney general is
not following the law, than we have a reponsibility to find out
why.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Burton is seeking confidential memos written for
Reno by FBI Director Louis Freeh and Charles LaBella, the former
head of the Justice Department's campaign-fundraising task force.
Freeh delivered his memo nine months ago; LaBella finished his last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh and LaBella have acknowledged that their memos say the
attorney general has no choice but to name an independent counsel
to investigate top Clinton administration officials in connection
with possible campaign-fundraising crimes _ a move Reno has
resisted for close to a year. But in testimony to Burton's
committee Tuesday, the men opposed giving the prosecution memos to
Congress, arguing it could thwart the ongoing Justice investigation
and violate grand jury privacy rules.
</P>
<P>
   Burton says Reno is stonewalling to shield the White House from
an independent investigation, and he accused her of
``orchestrating'' a political campaign to avoid his subpoenas and
dodge a contempt citation.
</P>
<P>
   Reno insisted Thursday she had tried to accommodate the
chairman, but that he had ignored her telephone calls and rebuffed
her offer to testify and explain why she was resisting his
subpoenas. The attorney general says she will brief Burton, as well
as the Republican chairmen of the House and Senate Judiciary
Committees _ Senator Orrin Hatch of Utah and Representative Henry
Hyde of Illinois _ as soon as she decides whether or not to name an
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Henry Waxman, a California Democrat and ranking
member on the government reform committee, charged Burton with
wielding the contempt citation to intimidate Reno into naming an
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every member of this committee should be offended and
embarrassed by this strong-arm tactic,'' Waxman said during the
hearing. ``This odious threat of contempt is below contempt.''
</P>
<P>
   But Senator Fred Thompson, the Tennessee Republican who has run
the campaign-fundraising investigaton in the Senate, said Burton
was justified in using all legal means to obtain documents the
Clinton administration has withheld.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contempt is an unusual proceeding, but these are unusual
circumstances _ circumstances the attorney general and the Justice
Department have created,'' Thompson said in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   The only time Congress has cited a member of executive branch
for contempt was in 1982, when Anne Gorsuch Burford, administrator
of the Environmental Protection Agency, refused to turn over
subpoenaed documents to Congress. A compromise was later reached,
and the contempt citation was rescinded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
