u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-BLINEBURY-COL-HNS     08-06 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-BLINEBURY-COL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grateful U.S. basketball gypsies accept way of life
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATHENS, Greece _ Jimmy Oliver and his wife are expecting their
first child in October, and the dad-to-be would like to be at home
in Akron, Ohio, to greet the new arrival.
</P>
<P>
   But fathers being fathers and the role of provider being
foremost in mind, it is possible the time will come and Oliver will
be an ocean away in one of the European pro leagues, doing what is
necessary for his growing family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, it's the first kid, and I really want to be there,''
Oliver said. ``My wife knows that, and I've told my agent to please
get the word out to any teams that might want to contact me about
playing that I have a desire to stay at home until October.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, now that we're having a child, I also have a
responsibility to do what's best for all of us,'' he said. ``And
with most of the leagues in Europe starting in September, a
big-enough offer might mean that I'll have to go.''
</P>
<P>
   David Wood and his family have become the basketball version of
migrant workers. He and his wife, Angie, have been married nine
years and have moved 12 times. With two small children in tow, the
task becomes more difficult. He split time last season between
Malaga, Spain, and the Continental Basketball Association. He has
played for four European teams and eight NBA clubs, making his tour
of duty with the Rockets in 1990-91.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pack 'em up, and take the whole show on the road,'' Wood said.
``We look at it like God sends us to different places all over the
world. We laugh and view ourselves as well-paid missionaries.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the gypsy life of pro basketball outside the bright
spotlight of multimillion-dollar contracts and lucrative
endorsement deals, where the players union is rattling swords and
threatening to wipe out the start of the NBA season.
</P>
<P>
   They are Oliver, Wood, Ashraf Amaya, Wendell Alexis, Michael
Hawkins and the rest, the major part of the U.S. team that is alive
for the gold medal and battling the odds in the World Championship
of Basketball.
</P>
<P>
   They are players like Oliver, who had a taste of NBA life _ at
Cleveland in 1990-91 and Boston in 1993-94 _ or Wood, who has
logged 412 games in the NBA. Or they are like Alexis, 34, who has
only sniffed the big time, cut from Golden State's training camp in
1986, and is finding his way in these strange and foreign places.
</P>
<P>
   It is a life where you must deal with different cultures and
strange languages and eventually, after so many years slip by, come
to grips with the reality that if you want to play pro basketball,
this is your place. Really, your only choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to accept at times,'' Oliver said. ``Sure. I have
people at home asking me why I don't call up the Cavaliers and ask
them to give me another chance. Hey, I've been living up the road
from them in Akron ever since I got out of school. I think the
Cavaliers know where I am. But I'm not going to beg anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins, the feisty point guard, is content playing for
Olympiakos of Athens. He spent two months with Boston in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``M.L. Carr gave me a chance to experience the NBA, and I'm
grateful for that,'' he said. ``But I'm also realistic. Maybe it's
an ego thing to try to get back for some guys. But I'm comfortable
that people on both sides of the Atlantic know who Michael Hawkins
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood said he had given up hope of making it back to the NBA
before this experience. He had spent 50 days in the CBA last
season, led his team in rebounds and didn't get a call up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty much resigned to it,'' Wood said. ``But this has
brought back the spark. I'm thinking there is a reason this all
happened with the lockout and the NBA not being here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know the scouts are here. You look in the stands, and
there's Jerry West. That's Rudy Tomjanovich coaching us. It's a
chance to be seen. A chance to get another chance.''
</P>
<P>
   There are younger players like Jason Sasser, 24, and Gerard
King, 25, who believe that chance is coming, though their talent
might say otherwise. And there is Alexis, whose time to dream of
the NBA has come and gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of what I've done over here,'' he said. ``I have had
a good career. I've been able to support myself playing basketball.
More than anything, I think I've persevered. It would have been
easy when I didn't make it in the NBA to quit, to turn in another
direction and get a different job. But I stayed with it. I came
here to Europe, and I found my place.''
</P>
<P>
   A different place, a strange place, but their place. A home away
from home where ``I love this game'' has to be not just an ad
slogan but a way of life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
