<HEADER>
A1855 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-A'S-SFCHRON &LR;      08-06 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-A'S-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A'S REGAIN THEIR SANITY 
BY DAVID BUSH
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    OAKLAND, Calif. _ The A's didn't exactly get even with the
Yankees on Wednesday night. But their 3-1 victory behind Tom
Candiotti's complete-game masterpiece at the Coliseum erased much
of the gloom the New Yorkers had inflicted on the Oakland clubhouse
the previous two days.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Candiotti, the 13-year veteran, was signed over the winter to
win games just like this, checking a losing streak before a feeling
of inferiority could become a teamwide condition. The baseball term
for that is stopper, and Candiotti (7-13) stopped a lot Wednesday
night, including the high-octane Yankees offense. He held New York
to four hits. which, truth be told, is twice as many as the A's got
off Hideki Irabu (10-5), himself the author of a complete game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an emotional game for us,'' said Candiotti, who was as
energized as he has been this year, pumping his fist after
successes in the game's decisive moments. ``Not only are the
Yankees a good team, but they're hot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who were 7-1 against the A's this year after losing
the season's first matchup, had bullied the A's through three
straight games this week, including that galling doubleheader sweep
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   But the victory not only salvaged the final game of the series
but wrapped up the homestand for a respectable 5-5. ``We did it
against the three best teams in the American League (Boston,
Cleveland and New York),'' said Candiotti. ``And I know we got
ourselves some respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez had given the Yankees a 1-0 lead when he belted
his 18th homer of the year in the fifth inning. But Candiotti was
steadfast, dodging a first-and-third, nobody-out situation in the
seventh, and ultimately striking out Tuesday night's villain,
Darryl Strawberry, to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   The A's took the lead in the bottom of the fifth with a two-run
rally built around one hit, an RBI single by Rafael Bournigal. The
A's other hit was Rickey Henderson's two-out homer in the eighth,
breaking his 0-for-21 skid.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Sprague got the A's fifth inning started by literally taking
one for the team. He undoubtedly would have preferred a more
dignified way to reach base, but when Irabu's pitch nailed him in
the left arm, he trotted to first.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Blowers worked Irabu for a walk, and A's manager Art Howe,
aware how precious runs would be, ordered Miguel Tejada to
sacrifice, which he did. Bournigal dropped a soft single into right
field. Sprague scored on that hit, and Blowers moved to third. He
was in position to score when A.J. Hinch lifted a sacrifice fly to
right field to put the A's up 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees appeared ready to take care of both that lead and
Candiotti when Paul O'Neill and Bernie Williams singled to open the
seventh. But Candiotti, feeding the Yankees a steady diet of his
knuckleballs, struck out Martinez, and after walking Strawberry,
retired the next two hitters on flyballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He mixed it up tonight. He was able to take speed off the
knuckler and add speed to it,'' A's catcher Hinch said. ``He even
threw a sidearm knuckleball. He was real creative.''
</P>
<P>
   And after he escaped the seventh. Candiotti was determined to
finish the job. He scooted through the eighth, but with two out in
the ninth, he walked Martinez to bring up Strawberry, author of the
game-turning grand slam Tuesday night. He never had a chance,
offering three futile swings at knucklers, each one slower than the
one before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darryl didn't look comfortable with the knuckleball all
night,'' said Candiotti. ``So I just tried to see how slow I could
throw it.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Candiotti's sixth strikeout of the night, and certainly
the most satisfying.  &UR; (For use by clients of the New &LR; 
 &UR; York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
