<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On DecK: San Francisco Giants
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: Tonight at 10:35 p.m., Saturday at 4:05 p.m. and Sunday at
8:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: 3Com Park at Candlestick Point.
</P>
<P>
   TV/radio: TBS will telecast tonight, WAGA (Fox) will telecast
Saturday and ESPN will telecast Sunday. night. 750-AM will
broadcast all three games.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: Tonight, LHP Tom Glavine (14-4,
2.61; 13-10, 3.54 lifetime vs. Giants) vs. LHP Kirk Rueter (12-6,
4.20; 1-2, 6.58 lifetime vs. Braves). Saturday, RHP Kevin Millwood
(12-6, 4.36; 1-0, 1.50 lifetime vs. Giants) vs. RHP Danny Darwin
(7-9. 4.74; 7-3, 3.20 lifetime vs. Braves). Sunday, RHP John Smoltz
(10-2, 3.14; 10-13, 4.11 lifetime vs. Giants) vs. RHP Mark Gardner
(8-5, 5.13; 5-5, 3.77 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   Series history: Atlanta trails the all-time series 260-272 but
has won 29 of the last 41 games between the clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Past meetings: The Braves took three of four from San Francisco
April 30-May 3. Michael Tucker homered four times during that
weekend, and Denny Neagle, who will not face the Giants this trip,
pitched the first of his two shutouts. The Giants avoided a sweep
with a 12-8 victory in the fourth game, Glavine nailed for seven
runs, including a pair of homers by shortstop Rich Aurilia.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly: The Giants took a nose dive after the All-Star break
but have begun to show life. The club went 2-11 to start the second
half but entered Thursday night's play at 6-3 on the current road
trip. The Giants completed a 10-game road swing Thursday night in
New York. . . . San Francisco's starting pitching has had trouble
shutting down anyone, but the team has responded with improved
offense after dealing for Joe Carter, Ellis Burks and Shawon
Dunston. While the team ERA the last eight games has been 5.78, the
Giants hit 465 in the same period and averaged 6.9 runs. The Giants
have gone 12-35 this year when scoring four or fewer runs. . . .
San Francisco's bullpen is the best in the majors with a 2.85 ERA.
The team is 49-0 when entering the ninth inning with a lead. Closer
Robb Nen has converted 29 of 31 save opportunities. . . . Barry
Bonds continues to play while appealing his three-game suspension,
handed down for his role in a bench-clearing incident in
Philadelphia on Sunday. . . . The Braves beat Rueter, tonight's
starter, 6-2, on May 1, when he gave up five earned runs, including
homers by Tucker and Andruw Jones. Rueter is 8-3 in his last 14
starts but has gone 2-3 since the All-Star break. He has allowed
just eight hits in his last 16 innings while striking out nine. He
won 15-3 Sunday in Philadelphia in his last start. . . . On the DL:
RHP Julian Tavarez (strained right lat), LHP Shawn Estes (left
shoulder strain) and C Brian Johnson (broken right thumb).
</P>
<P>
   Who's hot: OF Marvin Benard went into Thursday's play hitting
.556 on the road trip. OF Barry Bonds has 10 hits in his last 24
at-bats (.417) with 12 RBI in six games. 2B Jeff Kent had six home
runs in 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   Who's not: OF Joe Carter went 5-for-27 (.185) in his first eight
games as a Giant. INF Charlie Hayes was in a 0-for-10 slump. SS
Shawon Dunston was hitting .154 on the road trip.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
