</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia's recruits hit campus
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia's 1998 football season officially kicks
off today when the Bulldogs' highly regarded freshman class reports
to campus.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Donnan is expected to welcome 22 scholarship freshmen
to Athens, including Parkview High offensive lineman Jon Stinchcomb
and Jeff Davis High quarterback Nate Hybl, both of whom enrolled at
Georgia for spring quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Donnan says that as many as six freshmen could play this season,
including former Parade All-America quarterback Quincy Carter of
Decatur, who signed with Georgia Tech in 1996 before signing a
minor-league baseball contract with the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Both Carter, who won't count against the Bulldogs' limit of 79
scholarships because of his professional status in baseball, and
Hybl are expected to contend for the starting quarterback job.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Washington County High quarterback Terrence Edwards,
the younger brother of former Bulldogs running back Robert Edwards,
said Thursday that he will report to Georgia today. Edwards, a
6-foot-2, 175-pound Class AA all-state selection, says he still
hasn't been cleared by the NCAA Clearinghouse.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said a core course taken at Washington County High is
being questioned. He said he could be admitted as a partial
qualifier if he isn't cleared by the Clearinghouse, meaning that he
could practice at Georgia this fall but couldn't play in games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm coming to Georgia unless they tell me otherwise,'' Edwards
said from his Tennille home.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs already have lost three members of their recruiting
class to academic shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Miller County High linebacker Charles Grant, regarded by some
recruiters as the state's top overall prospect last year, will
enroll at Hargrave (Va.) Military Academy on Monday, according to
Miller County coach Ronnie McNease.
</P>
<P>
   Grant, a 6-foot-4, 225-pounder from Colquitt, did not graduate
from Miller County High, so he will have a chance to improve both
his grade-point average and his SAT score at Hargrave. If Grant
qualifies at prep school, he still would have four years of
eligibility remaining at a Division I school.
</P>
<P>
   ``His mother didn't particularly like it, but I thought it was
best (for him not to graduate),'' McNease said. ``That way, he can
improve his GPA and SAT while he's up there. Right now, I'd have to
say he'll definitely re-sign with Georgia, talking to him and
talking to the people up there. But things could change six months
from now. But I know Georgia's still talking to him, and he still
wants to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington County linebacker Jessie Miller and Peach County
quarterback Regan Torbert are expected to enroll at Georgia in
January. Miller, who had a qualifying SAT score negated by the
Clearinghouse, underwent shoulder surgery last month.
</P>
<P>
   Peach County High coach Rodney Walker said Torbert could have
been admitted to Georgia as a partial qualifier, but instead,
Torbert will sit out this fall and retake the ACT. Walker said
Torbert was only one point short of gaining the required score.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could be admitted as a partial qualifier, but there's no
reason to lose that entire season,'' Walker said. ``He wasn't going
to play this fall anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
