<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush has to prove himself all over
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Devin Bush was walking away from an interview on
Thursday when he said it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is big for me,'' Bush said while boarding a bus that
would transport the Atlanta Falcons to the Georgia Dome for a
practice session. ``I gotta get on some film. Gotta get some PT'' _
playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the thoughts of many Atlanta players as they prepare
to face the Tennessee Oilers at 7:30 p.m. today in the Georgia Dome
in the first of four preseason games. Eighty players are fighting
for 53 roster spots.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, a fourth-year safety, is in a tough spot. He started at
free safety last season and had the best year of his career _ 105
tackles and 10 passes defensed, despite being switched from strong
safety before the season.
</P>
<P>
   His reward has been a move back to strong safety, where he is
playing behind 10-year veteran William White. The 5-foot-11,
210-pound Bush has played well in the first two-plus weeks of
training camp and appears to be gaining ground. But he must play
well in preseason games, and he knows it. It's possible that the
loser of the battle between Bush and White would be gone before the
regular season begins.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is expected to play nearly two quarters tonight and is one
of several veterans in highly scrutinized battles for roster spots
and starting jobs. Former Rams teammates Todd Kinchen, who played
in Atlanta last season, and Keith Crawford are trying to win the
third receiver spot. Weakside linebacker Cornelius Bennett is out
to show that his age _ he'll be 33 in two weeks _ and 35 days in
jail in the offseason have not slowed him. And Robbie Tobeck wants
to prove that his switch from left guard to center _ something he
asked for _ is a good move.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's situation is different. He played exceptionally well
as the Falcons closed the season with a 6-2 run, and his latest
move was not expected. When the Falcons signed 13-year veteran
Eugene Robinson on March 6, Robinson was given the free-safety job.
Bush was left to battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my highest career totals, ... and that (change) hit
hard,'' he said. ``It was like, `Bam! We signed Eugene and you're
out.' ``
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to (coach Dan Reeves and secondary coach Ron Meeks) and
asked, `What's my role around here?' and they said, `We're going to
let you play behind Eugene Robinson (at free safety).' I said,
`Why? You've told me teams are calling about trading for me; why
don't you just go ahead and trade me so I can go and try to start
somewhere else?'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who left Florida State a year early to become the Falcons'
first-round draft choice in 1995, eventually simmered down, and the
Falcons changed their minds _ moving him to backup strong safety,
at least the fourth switch of positions for Bush in as many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to find the best mix for your team,'' Meeks said.
``Bringing Eugene in brings stability to the secondary. With Devin,
we felt in the long run he would be better as a strong safety. He's
a physical guy who has a knack for wanting to be in contact.''
</P>
<P>
   That fits the typical description of a strong safety, who
generally is expected to play more of a run-support role than a
free safety does. Actually, Bush's numbers in the second half of
the season were a lot more like those of a strong safety. In the
first eight games, he had 37 tackles. In the last eight games, he
had 68.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first half I was trying to learn how (an almost totally
revamped coaching staff) wanted me to play,'' he said. ``Then, they
were coming to me and saying, `We're not getting a lot of
production out of you.' They wanted interceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a problem. Bush had no interceptions and just three
passes defensed in the first half of the season. In his first two
seasons, he had a total of two interceptions and three passes
defensed. A free safety needs to be around the ball more, not so
much when it's in the hands of running backs but when it's in the
air _ a center fielder of sorts, like Robinson, the NFL's leading
active interceptor with 49.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush made a turnaround. He tackled, including games of eight
twice, nine, 11 and 12. And he intercepted a pass against New
Orleans and defensed seven passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told myself I'm going to go back to playing the way I
know I can play,'' he said. ``I just wanted to play hard, with a
lot of intensity, just be myself. Guys were giving me feedback,
saying, `Man, you're playing at a different level.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Bush's contract, which included a signing bonus of $1.08 million
and will pay him a base salary this year of $664,800 (to White's
$350,000), ends after this season. Even if he makes the roster,
he's not sure he'll be back next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not up to me,'' he said. ``That's up to the team. They
may not want me.''
</P>
<P>
   Falcon officials are not willing to say much about Bush's future
with the team. The Jets, Bears and Cardinals are among teams that
have shown an interest in acquiring him, and they will be among the
24 NFL teams with scouts at tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made up ground on White. He has a distinct edge in
speed and athletic ability, and he's trying to pick up some of the
savvy Robinson and White rely upon. He said he's just trying to get
back to where he was _ a starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a plus for us to have another veteran (in Robinson),
another guy I can learn from,'' he said. ``It's more competition,
but I welcome it. Our secondary will be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been a starter (in all 16 games last year and 36 of 43 as
a Falcon), and it's been kind of hard to swallow,'' he said. ``I've
had to sit back and play my role as a team player and do what I
have to do to be a better player. In this defense, the safety
positions are almost the same. I just want to be on the field. It
doesn't matter where, free or strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
