<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Full moon or fluke of physiology?
 &HT;    By Lisa Ocker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ A youth baseball coach denies accusations
that he twice mooned a tournament crowd last weekend, explaining
that his waist-less physique causes his drawers to droop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my pants are constantly falling down. My wife calls it
a plumber's butt,'' said Paul Tamboe, one of the coaches for the
Palm Beach Baseball Academy team.
</P>
<P>
   Tamboe said he was picking up baseball gloves and caps thrown
down in frustration by his 9- and 10-year-old team members after
losing the semifinals game to the Boca Raton Patriots Sunday, Aug.
2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was picking up a lot of stuff. I might've bent over more
than once,'' he said. ``By the time I get back to the dugout, I'm
being accused of mooning the crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Boca Raton police are investigating the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said Tamboe stopped near the pitching mound, yelled
something to the crowd, bent over and dropped his trousers, then
hoisted them and did it again near third plate, according to the
police report. Nineteen people saw a single mooning, while three
observed ``both exposures,'' police said.
</P>
<P>
   The game between the Palm Beach and Boca Raton teams at Sugar
Sand Park was marred by contested umpires' calls and, according to
Tamboe, racially derogatory remarks shouted by spectators at his
team.
</P>
<P>
   But the game's aftermath was worse: a Palm Beach coach accused a
Boca coach of shoving him during the post-game high-fives. And an
8-year-old Palm Beach player told police a Boca coach twisted his
arm rather than shaking his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very vulgar, very malicious, very rude and
inconsiderate,'' Tamboe said. ``You might've thought it was an
international soccer game.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
