<SLUG> BC-YAGER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Attorney accuses north Fulton pair of 'racketeering'
 &HT;    By Clint Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The attorney for a man whose ex-wife kidnapped his
son charged in federal court Thursday that Faye and Howard Yager
profit from helping women and children disappear into an
underground network.
</P>
<P>
   The Yagers, said Carrollton attorney Gary Bunch, ``engage in
organized racketeering conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Bunch has filed an $80 million lawsuit in U.S. District Court on
behalf of Jeffrey Rubenstein, a Connecticut man who has been
looking for his son, Randy, since September.
</P>
<P>
   Faye Yager is the controversial operator of the Children of the
Underground, a network of safe houses that hides children, and
generally their mothers, from allegedly abusive fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Yager was tried, and acquitted, in 1992 in Cobb County on
kidnapping and child cruelty charges. She has also been sued
before. This is the first civil suit that named Howard Yager as a
defendant.
</P>
<P>
   The Yagers, who live in north Fulton, didn't appear in court
Tuesday. They were not subpoenaed to testify.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing, which will continue today, was on a motion for a
temporary restraining order to stop the Yagers from continuing to
hide Randy Rubenstein and compel them to provide information on
where the boy can be found.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence introduced Thursday included photographs of Bonnie and
Randy Rubenstein together with Faye Yager as she worked to get them
out of the country. The photos appeared in the Pittsburgh
Post-Gazette last December in a series of stories that featured
Yager and her efforts to help women go underground. Several video
tapes of Faye Yager interviews were also introduced. Nick Souris of
Smyrna testified he rented an apartment near Paris to Faye Yager in
February. While in France later that month, he met a woman named
Liz and her son, David. Souris, when shown photos of Bonnie and
Randy Rubenstein, identified them as Liz and David. Bunch also
introduced evidence that Howard Yager was driving the Jeeps of
women who had gone underground. One of the cars was apparently
given to a friend of the Yagers, Jay Wilcox Davis, who repeatedly
invoked her rights against self-incrimination during questioning
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The claim that the Yagers profit from helping women ``is total
hogwash,'' said Robert Schroeder, attorney for Howard Yager.
</P>
<P>
   Bunch also introduced evidence he said shows Howard Yager bought
the airline tickets for women fleeing the country and accompanied
Faye Yager and the fugitives on flights to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
