<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAIDERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIDERS' LINEBACKERS UNDER CLOSE SCRUTINY 
BY RON KROICHICK
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The names drift along the football landscape, at once familiar
and intriguing. The Raiders considered signing Bryan Cox. Then they
flirted with Greg Lloyd. Both times, they passed.
</P>
<P>
   So here they stand, on the brink of the exhibition season, still
flowing with youth and obscurity at linebacker. They will start
Greg Biekert, Mike Morton and James Folston in Thursday night's
scrimmage against the Dallas Cowboys in El Paso, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the linebackers who have departed in recent seasons:
Winston Moss, Mike Jones, Rob Fredrickson. The Raiders historically
pour money into other positions on defense _ namely, linemen and
cornerbacks.
</P>
<P>
   That often leaves Oakland with an unheralded group of
linebackers. Nothing is different this season, as the Raiders steam
through training camp with only Biekert (59 career starts) firmly
established in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Morton (17 starts) showed flashes of promise last season, before
he suffered a serious back injury November 16 in San Diego. Folston
(seven starts) begins this season as the biggest question mark of
all.
</P>
<P>
   And make no mistake: Defensive coordinator Willie Shaw needs his
linebackers to play well. Shaw's defense is predicated on pressure,
something the Raiders seldom applied in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``More is expected of the linebackers,'' Shaw said. ``They're
under the microscope a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw remains open to change. He acknowledged that the Raiders
were thin and inexperienced at linebacker. He said they would
continue to scan the free-agent market, right up until the season
opener on Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Shaw refuses to reach conclusions based on
last season. The Raiders had the worst defense in the league,
allowing more than 26 points and 382 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   The linebackers were specific targets of blame. They missed
tackles, lagged in pass coverage and caused little havoc. Shaw
arrived eager to start anew.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're running around a lot more than we did last year, that's
for sure,'' Folston said, smiling. ``It makes you feel great when
the offense doesn't know what the hell you're going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Biekert, the middle linebacker, offered no excuses for the
disaster of '97. He placed the linebackers in the same unflattering
light as the defensive line and the secondary _ the entire team,
actually.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at everything as a whole,'' Biekert said.
``Nobody did as well as they should have done.''
</P>
<P>
   As Shaw suggested, the role of the linebackers will expand this
season. They must shed blocks and become reliable tacklers.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, they also must fly into the backfield. The
assignment rarely fell in Biekert's domain during his first five
years in the league; he's known as sturdy against the run.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Shaw unveils his wide variety of zone blitzes, Biekert
finds himself in an absolutely foreign role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot different for me,'' he said. ``In the past, most of
the blitzes came from the outside. Willie's schemes include a lot
of inside blitzes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like doing it. If I can get in on a blitz, let's do it. I
want to be the one who's back there making plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Morton is grateful he's healthy enough to make plays. He
suffered a herniated disk against the Chargers, leading to surgery
in December. Morton then endured a long, slow rehabilitation
process.
</P>
<P>
   Folston, who stepped into the lineup after Morton got hurt, sees
this season as his big opportunity. He's a former second-round
draft choice (1994) who has done little beyond special-teams play
for four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to solidify my starting place,'' Folston said. ``I'm
not knocking UPS or the Teamsters union, but I'd rather work in the
NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
