<HEADLINE>
DON'T SAY YOU WEREN'T WARNED 
BY C.W. NEVIUS
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do not attempt to resist. You are powerless to stop these
events, as much as you wish you could. They are as inevitable as
disaster movies in the summer and the crash of the Beanie Babies
market.
</P>
<P>
   There are moments on the sports horizon that are only distant
specks right now. But they are rocketing toward us at the speed of
a Randy Johnson heater.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Big Unit is a good example. We knew he was going to
leave Seattle, even though in a perfect world, he would not have
been traded. Now watch for the following:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MIKE TYSON:  &LR; I think we all can agree that getting a boxing
license is a given. Somebody is going to give him one, in some
state. Guys who were legally blind have gotten boxing licenses,
guys who have criminal records stacked up higher than Don King's
hair have gotten boxing licenses, and 84-year-old George Foreman
has not only gotten a boxing license, but he is going to fight
73-year-old Larry Holmes. (I might not have their ages exactly
right, but those are pretty close.)
</P>
<P>
   The real capper is going to be a rematch with Evander Holyfield,
who seems like a nice-enough chap who is being sucked deeper into a
quagmire. Holyfield has to fight Tyson for the monumental payoff,
and the result not only will be a sham of a bout, but we also will
have to spend another month attempting to understand the inner Mike
Tyson, crying out for help.
</P>
<P>
   The real question: Where will they fight? It's just a guess, but
remember these three words _ Montana log cabin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE YANKEES:  &LR; Well, of course they are headed for the World
Series, and that's just fine. The Yanks are a powerhouse team, just
like in the good old days. There's nothing wrong with that team, or
the way it plays.
</P>
<P>
   The problem will be the opening of the floodgates of latent
Yankees fans. There is no more unpleasant sound in sports than the
nasal honk of the latent Yankees fan who has just dusted off the
old blue NY cap and has begun wearing it everywhere. We didn't hear
a peep from them when they were struggling, but now ...
</P>
<P>
   And of course, the Series will bring out the Big Yank himself,
George Steinbrenner, who has been dying to explain his theory on
several important matters in America. This just in: George would
have settled the General Motors strike in three hours, four tops.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATRELL SPREWELL:  &LR; He is going to be moving to a new team soon,
you know. The trade will go through, and the Warriors will be
thrilled to acquire someone who both can back up Donyell Marshall
and grow eight inches and play center with a couple of seasons of
hard work. That's not the issue.
</P>
<P>
   No, the real story will be that Sprewell will find his way to a
team that makes the playoffs, and once he gets to the postseason,
he will play great. He's sure to be on an absolute crusade by the
time the season starts. He will be in great shape, and he is too
talented and experienced not to rise to the occasion on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   By then, all the questions about choking P.J. Carlesimo will
have been asked and re-asked, Sprewell will throw in a visit to a
children's hospital, make a contribution to the Boys and Girls
Club, and the postseason stories will begin, ``Latrell Sprewell was
considered a problem player with the Warriors, but his new
teammates wonder if he wasn't getting a bad rap ... ''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LAKERS:  &LR; It has to be said. They are going to win the NBA
championship, if not this season, then soon afterward. Who is going
to beat them? The Jazz?
</P>
<P>
   If the Chicago Bulls are truly broken and disbanded, the Lakers
will win by default. And won't that be a wonderful thing? More Jack
Nicholson, more Dyan Cannon, and much, much more Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   No, there is nothing inherently wrong with Shaq. As tattooed
basketball players go, he is funnier and more talented than most.
He raps, he acts, he dunks. What more do you want?
</P>
<P>
   How about a game? When the Lakers win, we are going to have to
hear all about the wonderful-ness of Shaq, and how he is redefining
the game, when all he is really doing is knocking people over and
making layups.
</P>
<P>
   I agree with the kids, who declined to buy his signature
sneakers so forcefully that the shoes were discontinued. They never
saw him get more than three inches on the floor in them. Why would
they want a shoe that does that?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE 49ERS:  &LR; Don't you feel it? This means getting in touch with
the darker you, the deep inner feelings that you don't want to
admit to having. The 49ers are going down.
</P>
<P>
   Admit it, the vibes are not good. There is the whole messy
Louisiana grand jury investigation hanging over Eddie DeBartolo,
the march of Carmen Policy off the gangplank, Jerry Rice's knee,
Steve Young's cranium and the loss to the Packers that ended last
season.
</P>
<P>
   You've got to like peppy Steve Mariucci, but when you run down
the list of old favorites _ Merton Hanks, Tim McDonald, Ken Norton,
Harris Barton _ you're thinking, these guys are high-mileage. And
then you look at the future, and all you can see is the looming
figure of Jim Druckenmiller. Tell the truth: Didn't you get a chill
there, just for a second?
</P>
<P>
   If not, be patient. It's coming. They all are.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
