<HEADLINE>
SECURITY COUNCIL CALLS IRAQ'S ACTIONS `TOTALLY UNACCEPTABLE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also IRAQ-U.S.)  
(lh) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The Security Council, in rare unanimity, closed
ranks Thursday to berate Iraq for ending cooperation with U.N. arms
inspectors, but it took no action other than to demand that Baghdad
reverse its decision.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Iraq was isolated in the Security Council, the
government got mixed signals from Secretary General Kofi Annan, who
suggested that the Iraqis, ``desperate'' for some movement toward
ending sanctions, needed to be brought more closely into
deliberations here.
</P>
<P>
   Normal monitoring went on as usual Thursday in Baghdad, but no
intrusive searches were attempted since Iraq barred them on
Wednesday, UNSCOM officials said.
</P>
<P>
   When Iraq decided this week that it would end cooperation with
arms inspections and allow only passive monitoring by surveillance
cameras, the Iraqis were aware that they were actually close to
meeting disarmament requirements in some areas, Richard Butler, the
chief arms inspector told the Security Council Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But officials of the U.N. Special Commission, known as UNSCOM,
said Thursday that the Iraqis also knew that problems in accounting
for biological and some chemical compounds were serious and
growing. Right up to the present, Iraq has continued to change
figures and alter other information earlier presented as ``full,
final and complete'' declarations.
</P>
<P>
   At times the Iraqis have been forced to revise a story when
confronted with evidence by inspectors _ as in the recent case of
the discovery of traces of VX nerve gas on shell casings. At other
times, they volunteer new information _ but that only raises more
troubling questions about why an account has changed.
</P>
<P>
   In recent examinations of old warhead remnants, for example,
weapons experts found more traces of anthrax than they could
explain. When the Iraqis were pressed, they revised earlier ``final
figures'' to say that they had actually filled three times as many
warheads with anthrax _ 16 _ as with botulism _ five. Until then,
Iraq said it had mounted weapons with more than three times more
botulism than anthrax.
</P>
<P>
   This admission has revived speculation among inspectors that
Iraq had produced not only more anthrax, but also two kinds of it,
one in a dry form that was easier to spray and had a longer shelf
life. Officials insist that this is only speculation at this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time Iraq changes the figures, it has a ripple effect
throughout their entire declaration,'' said Charles Duelfer, deputy
chairman of UNSCOM. ``That is a very complicated procedure because
a declaration is built and substantiated to support one set of
numbers, and to change that becomes very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   This week Tariq Aziz, Iraq's deputy prime minister and chief
negotiator on weapons issues, gave a new explanation of how VX
nerve gas could have been found on shells after Iraqis denied they
used it. In a letter to the Security Council on Wednesday, he said
the traces could have been created from the ``decomposition of
other chemical substances or from the use of equipment which had
already been used to produce the VX agent.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday morning, Security Council members, united in shock
and a touch of weariness at having to work their way through
another unexpected crisis created by Baghdad, called Iraq's
decision to freeze cooperation with inspectors ``totally
unacceptable'' and then sat back to see what Saddam Hussein's next
move would be.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
