<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORTIZ IS BIG NEWS IN WIN 
BY HENRY SCHULMAN
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    NEW YORK _ The Giants hit into a triple play Wednesday night,
but that was hardly the biggest deal in a 6-4 victory over the New
York Mets. Six different Giants doubled as the Big Orange Machine
(83 runs in their past 12 games) kept humming, but that was not the
hottest news either.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rookie Russ Ortiz, making his fourth start in place of injured
Shawn Estes, earned his first major-league victory, as he finally
got past his troublesome fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   In the greater scheme of things, that was the most significant
development for the Giants as they improved to 6-3 on this road
trip, which ends Thursday, and moved within 11/2 games of wild-card
leader Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz pitched into the ninth, netting six of his eight
strikeouts from the fifth inning on.
</P>
<P>
   After allowing a leadoff double to Carlos Baerga in the ninth,
Giants manager Dusty Baker called for Robb Nen, who allowed Baerga
to score but finished the game for his 29th save.
</P>
<P>
   In going as far as he did, Ortiz afforded the rest of the
bullpen a desperately needed night off.
</P>
<P>
   ``You like to see a young man like that get stronger as the game
wears on,'' Baker said. ``He was stronger in the sixth, seventh and
eighth innings. That's why I let him start the ninth. It looked
like he smelled the finish line. That's the sign of a guy who's
hungry, a guy who's determined and a guy who's in great shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, Barry Bonds doubled home the two go-ahead runs for
his 80th and 81st RBIs, while Ellis Burks, J.T. Snow, Marvin
Benard, Rey Sanchez and Doug Mirabelli also doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Benard had two hits and is now 14-for-24 (.583) in his last six
games. Burks (3-for-5) has hit safely in every game as a Giant.
</P>
<P>
   But you want to hear about the triple play.
</P>
<P>
   It occurred in the fifth inning after Bonds doubled home Burks
and Bill Mueller to give the Giants a 4-3 lead, and Jeff Kent
followed with a line single to left.
</P>
<P>
   With nobody out, third-base coach Ron Wotus held Bonds at third,
a fateful decision with which Bonds disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I could have scored, but he stopped me,'' Bonds said.
``He saw something different than I did. I'm not looking at the
play. I'm looking at him. I think I should have gone. Even if he
makes a perfect throw, Kent still gets to second base and we've got
a guy in scoring position.''
</P>
<P>
   Snow came up and smashed a one-hopper to first baseman John
Olerud. As Olerud quickly threw to second to force Kent, Bonds
began dancing off third and bolted for home when shortstop Rey
Ordonez threw the ball back to first to double off Snow.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud then fired the ball home, and though replays appeared to
show Bonds' leg sliding onto the plate ahead of catcher Todd
Pratt's tag, umpire Jim Quick raised his right hand emphatically.  &LR; 
 &LR;  The Giants had hit into their second triple play in two seasons.
Last May 10, Stan Javier hit into a bizarre one against the Cubs
involving a controversial infield-fly call.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants won that game as well, but oddly enough, lost a game
this year in which they turned a triple play, at Wrigley Field on
May 8.
</P>
<P>
   Snow said he had never hit into a triple play before but was
involved in one defensively with the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have the ball,'' Snow said. ``I guess I have the honor
now of saying I hit into a triple play. I'm just lucky it didn't
come back to haunt us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants added two runs in the sixth to take a 6-3 lead and
give Ortiz some room to work.
</P>
<P>
   In his last two starts against the Reds and Phillies, Ortiz
pitched beautifully until the fifth inning, when the hitters
knocked him out with big fifth innings.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Ron Perranoski spoke to Ortiz about mixing up his
pitches more and not firing fastball after fastball at hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of talked about feeding off what he's using and
changing speeds on his pitches rather than going full throttle on
all of them,'' Perranoski said. ``He's young. He's a little
concerned about hitters fouling off a lot of good pitches. When
that happens, it shows you're not getting your off-speed pitches
over enough for the hitters to be concerned about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz did change speeds Wednesday night with great success and
got into trouble only because of wildness. All three of the runs he
allowed started with walks.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz understood the bullpen situation, and he was committed to
giving his mates a breather.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to,'' he said. ``That's one of the things I thought
about going out there. I wanted to throw the least amount of
pitches and stretch it out, and not get the bullpen involved in the
middle of the game. That was a big thought on my mind.'' &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
