<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1869 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-U.N.-2NDTAKE-NYT     08-06 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.N.-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNITED NATIONS: the situation.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Beijing, Moscow and Paris, the capitals most sympathetic to
Iraq, governments distanced themselves from Baghdad in statements.
In Russia and China, there were expressions of concern about the
consequences of continued Iraqi defiance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is now extremely important not to stoke tensions over
Iraq,'' Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin told
a news briefing in Moscow. A Chinese spokesman, Tang Guoqiang, said
his government would do what it could ``to avoid a worsening of the
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   After Thursday's lengthy Council meeting on the new Iraqi
crisis, a Western diplomat said that nobody relished having to take
strong action to make Iraq conform to its agreements. Until the
arms inspectors are satisfied that Iraq has provided answers to
outstanding questions about biological, chemical, nuclear and
missile programs, Saddam cannot hope to see the end of sanctions,
which were imposed in 1990 after the invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was weary, everyone was annoyed and everyone was
concerned that this not turn into a crisis that would force the
United States to act as it had to act last year,'' the diplomat
said.
</P>
<P>
   The council action came after Butler briefed members on his
aborted trip to Iraq earlier this week. He also spoke on the Iraqi
leadership's refusal to turn over documents, including one
discovered in July that shed light on the amount of
``nonconventional munitions'' used during the 1980-87 war with
Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said that the document could prove that there are
larger quantity of chemical _ and possibly biological _ agents
unaccounted for in Iraq than inspectors were told about last year.
Iraqis said that they had filled 101,080 warheads with chemical
weapons in the 1980s, but the new document reveals that fewer than
that were actually deployed. The inspectors want to now what
happened to the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Annan also spoke to the council about his assessment of Iraq's
position after talking Thursday morning with Deputy Foreign
Minister Tariq Aziz, who leads Iraqi negotiators in dealing with
UNSCOM. Annan told the Council that Iraq was ``clearly in violation
of the resolutions of the Security Council and the memorandum of
understanding I concluded in Baghdad in February.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this is well understood by the government of Iraq,''
he said. Speaking to reporters later, Annan said that he had told
Aziz that Iraq could not dictate how inspections are conducted and
by whom.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he had made clear to Aziz ``that the Iraqi
suggestion that UNSCOM should be restructured and possibly moved
from New York is something that was not acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No individual state can tell the U.N. how to structure itself
to carry out tasks or mandates given to it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Annan added that he thought Iraq's position was ``not a
closed one,'' that Baghdad had acted out of frustration and even
desperation, and that it might be the right time ``to stand back
and make a comprehensive reassessment of where we are, where are
going and how to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In undertaking this comprehensive review,'' he said, ``it
might be helpful to engage the Iraqis much more closely than we
have hitherto done.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, Iraq has persistently and successfully
managed to broaden its diplomatic contacts with U.N. officials,
skirting the Security Council when it can. Iraqis complain
repeatedly that the council and the disarmament commission are
dominated by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the Arab League Thursday, Aziz appealed for
support against what he called the ``injustice'' of UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
   Arms inspectors see this as an Iraqi tactic to bring
international politics into what is essentially a technical
operation to disarm Iraq and destroy its capacity to make new
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Butler also provided the Security Council Thursday with results
of a technical evaluation in July of Iraq's ``full, final and
complete disclosure'' on biological weapons, a document the Iraqis
say closes the file on that issue. This was the third such
technical evaluation demanded by Iraq over the last year, and its
findings were no different than earlier ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``No new material was presented by Iraq at this meeting,''
Butler wrote in his report of the July technical evaluation. The
international experts again concluded that Iraq's latest disclosure
``was not adequate to allow for credible verification.''
</P>
<P>
   The biological experts _ whom, the Iraqis said, had been
``brainwashed by UNSCOM'' _ found problems with Iraqi accounts of
what they had done with bombs, warheads, spraying devices or
quantities of the agents themselves, including botulinum toxin,
anthrax bacillus and aflatoxin.
</P>
<P>
   During the meetings in Baghdad, the Iraqis refused to discuss
substantive issues, but demanded that sanctions be lifted because
there was no more disarming to be done. On Thursday Bill
Richardson, the U.S. representative, who was brought back from
vacation for the Security Council meeting, called the Iraqi demand
``disarmament by ultimatum.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not going to happen,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
