<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SEATTLE-SOUND-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BOX WITHIN A BOX TO BLOCK OUT NOISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (With MUSIC-SEATTLE-SFCHRON)  
 By JOSHUA KOSMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In addition to all the usual challenges of
concert-hall acoustics, the designers of Seattle's Benaroya Hall
faced a particularly acute problem: external noise.
</P>
<P>
   Situated downtown, the hall has to contend with the noise of
traffic on two busy city streets, as well as a major bus route
running along one side of the building.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, there's a train line running directly underneath.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the extraneous noise out of the hall, design partner
Mark Reddington of LMN Architects created a plan by which the main
concert hall is structurally isolated from the outside world _ a
box within a box within a box.
</P>
<P>
   To get into the concert hall, patrons step through a series of
doors designed to operate like an air lock. Then another built-in
gap separates the internal structure from its protecting wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it was all built,'' Reddington says, ``we had to go over
it inch by inch, shining flashlights down into the gap to make sure
nothing had dropped down there that would make a bridge to the
outside world.''
</P>
<P>
   But what about the bottom of the hall? Sound-absorbent rubber
does the trick. The hall rests on a network of 310 rubber bearings,
intermeshed with 210 more bearings designed to brace the hall
laterally.
</P>
<P>
   According to Reddington, the architects had to calculate how far
the hall would settle on the rubber, in order to make the inner and
outer floors line up properly. And yes, in theory, dropping the
hall from a height would result in a nice rebound.
</P>
<P>
   What happens, though, when the rubber starts to wear out? There
is a way to get access to individual bearings, although Reddington
says it would be dauntingly involved.
</P>
<P>
   But according to project manager Andrew Clapham, each bearing
was individually tested for up to 150 percent of its expected load,
and each has an anticipated life span of 150 years. ``That should
be long enough to get me out of the picture, at least.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
