</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SEATTLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE SYMPHONY FINDS A HOME IN A RUBBER HALL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSHUA KOSMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE &LR;   &LR; _ Benaroya Hall, the nearly completed new home of the
Seattle Symphony, promises two intimate performance spaces, a
spacious lobby, attractive design and, if all goes according to
plan, fine acoustics.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, if you dropped it on the ground it might bounce.
</P>
<P>
   The system of rubber bearings that supports the main concert
hall, designed to keep it free from outside noise, may be the new
building's most unusual aspect. But the $118 million structure,
which will open next month in downtown Seattle, seems likely to
have a big impact on the city's cultural life.
</P>
<P>
   The big unknown is the success of the hall's acoustics, which
will be put to the test during a gala series of concerts Sept.
12-19. Music director Gerard Schwarz will lead the symphony in a
handful of orchestral concerts with guest soloists Jessye Norman,
Yo-Yo Ma and more, and there will be solo appearances by violinist
Kyung-Wha Chung, pop-jazz trumpeter Chuck Mangione and pop legend
Gladys Knight.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, a recent guided tour through the hall _ named
after Seattleites Rebecca and Jack Benaroya, who donated $15
million to the project _ revealed a building of enormous beauty and
elegance, with an inviting mix of spaciousness and intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by the Seattle-based firm LMN Architects, working with
acoustical guru Cyril Harris, the hall occupies 187,000 square feet
covering a city block bounded by Second and Third avenues and by
University and Union streets.
</P>
<P>
   The main facade, a rounded form of glass and stone, faces the
newly rejuvenated Second Avenue, across from the Seattle Art
Museum. At the rear, running the length of the building along Third
Avenue, will be a public arcade with shops, cafes, the ticket
office and access to public transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Public artworks will be featured prominently. The arcade is
flanked by a pair of intricate lighting installations by Seattle
glass artist Dale Chihuly, each resembling a Medusa-like swarm of
coiling snakes.
</P>
<P>
   The main lobby, exquisitely lit by the glass facade, will be
dominated by a Robert Rauschenberg mural measuring 50 feet by 12
feet. And a sculpture by Mark di Suvero titled ``Schubert Sonata,''
currently on display at the Seattle Art Museum, will also be
installed.
</P>
<P>
   For musical performances, the building includes both a
2,500-seat main concert hall and a 541-seat recital hall. The main
hall, a traditional ``shoe box'' design featuring a new pipe organ
by Massachusetts builder C.B. Fisk, is _ visually at least _ a
stunner.
</P>
<P>
   The seats feel close to the stage, both at the orchestra level
and in the side boxes and the top balcony. The dark wood paneling
on the side walls gives the place a gleaming intensity; for the
sake of acoustical evenness, the entire space has been paneled with
the wood from a single South African mahogany tree.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of Benaroya Hall promises to ease this city's
concert-hall gridlock, a situation that should ring a bell for San
Franciscans who remember life before Davies Symphony Hall was built
in 1980. Currently, Seattle's symphony, ballet and opera companies
all perform in the Seattle Center Opera House, which leads to
fierce competition for access to the hall.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is the Seattle Symphony restricted to giving concerts
midweek, but the orchestra can't even rehearse in the same space
where it performs.
</P>
<P>
   The effects of the move will be evident immediately: According
to a symphony spokesperson, the orchestra's 1998-99 concert season
will feature 30 percent more performances than the current year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
