u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGO-REBELLION-ART-2     08-06 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-REBELLION-ART-235&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGO REBELS SEIZE OIL PORT, ATTACKING KABILA ON 2 FRONTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast _ Rebels in Congo on Thursday seized
control of a strategic oil port in the far west, according to rebel
spokesmen and foreign diplomats, significantly widening their
campaign to wrest power from President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   The seizure of the town, Moanda, an important oil depot to the
southwest of Kinshasa, and the nearby city of Banana, confirms the
dramatic opening of a second front in a five-day-old battle that
had been largely confined to Congo's far east.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the government said the rebels hijacked a Boeing 707
aircraft in the east and flew it 1,000 miles west, to the town of
Kitona, where soldiers from the defeated army of President Mobutu
Sese Seko were being retrained for service in Kabila's army by
instructors on loan from Rwanda. The rebels wanted to rally these
soldiers to their side, and it appears that these are the rebels
who traveled to the port.
</P>
<P>
   Making his first public appearance since the outbreak of
rebellion, at a news conference in the capital, Kabila on Thursday
threatened to ``take the war back to Rwanda, where it came from.''
The rebellion began Sunday and the rebels quickly took two cities
bordering Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda denies involvement in the current fighting, but according
to Western diplomats, it has emerged as a major backer of the
rebellion. Just 15 months ago, Rwanda backed Kabila against Mobutu.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Kabila also said he was preparing ``for a long war, a drawn-out
war, a people's war,'' and said ``ordinary Congolese'' may be
called upon to take up arms.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Kabila's threat Thursday, a Rwandan government
spokesman told the BBC: ``Aren't they putting the cart before the
horse? Hadn't they better take care of their problems with the
rebels?''
</P>
<P>
   The opening of a western front in Congo, moreover, one so near
to the capital, Kinshasa, comes as bleak news to Kabila, who has
lost nearly all of the international friends who supported his
drive for power, which began two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting was reported southwest of the capital, and any
consolidation of the rebels' position would enable them to
interrupt electricity from the huge Inga dam nearby and to stop
food and fuel deliveries to Kinshasa from the country's sole
seaport.
</P>
<P>
   Until the rebellion, Kabila mostly relied on foreign troops, on
loan from Rwanda, to assure security. With those troops gone, he
depends on the very elements of Mobutu's army that his rebellion
defeated, and thousands of recently recruited but untested youths.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between Kabila and his former allies in Rwanda have
soured over issues that once united them, including Kabila's
gradual marginalization of Congolese Tutsi _ the ethnic cousins of
Rwanda's leaders _ in his government, and the failure to suppress
anti-Rwanda guerrilla activity in eastern Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila has not been popular since overthrowing Mobutu, but the
government's nationalist oratory has apparently struck a powerful
chord at least in Kinshasa and other areas of the west, where
interference in the country's affairs by Rwanda is deeply resented.
</P>
<P>
   The depth of feeling against Rwanda and the Tutsi in the west
raises questions about whether the rebel movement could credibly
seize power even if it managed to defeat Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels ``have been trying hard to broaden their base in the
last couple of days and find some non-Tutsi names to identify the
rebellion with, but this is going to be a real problem later,'' a
European diplomat said. ``The people of Congo are not likely to
accept any kind of movement that springs from Rwanda,'' the
diplomat continued. With that in mind, the rebels selected a
Kinshasa politician, Arthur Zaidy Ngoma, who is not Tutsi, as
nominal leader.
</P>
<P>
   At a demonstration attended by thousands Thursday in the
capital, Congolese youth carried banners denouncing the Rwandans
and the Tutsi in particular, vowing in chanted slogans never to
surrender to their country's smaller neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   There have been persistent reports since the start of the
uprising of a campaign of house-to-house arrests of Congolese Tutsi
in the capital. By those accounts, hundreds of people have been led
away to detention in unknown destinations.
</P>
<P>
   A Western diplomat who spoke on the condition of anonymity said
today that he found credible reports that as many as 800 Tutsi have
been taken to Camp Tshatshi, a military base and former
presidential residence on the outskirts of Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kabila must be made to understand that he will be responsible
for these people,'' a spokesman for the rebellion, Mehta Mwanga
Chuchu, said in telephone interview from Washington. ``Whatever he
does to them, he will have to pay for.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
