<HEADER>
A1873 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEROES-COMMENT-SFCHRO     08-06 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEROES-COMMENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAD TRAILS: BABY BOOMERS LOSING THEIR TV HEROES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're falling fatally and disturbingly fast. Roy Rogers,
Buffalo Bob Smith, Shari Lewis _ all representing the last time the
world made sense to the Baby Boom generation.
</P>
<P>
   Even Robert Young made sense in the 1950s. If you're going to
get a whupping, it might as well be a benign word-whupping by a
kindly insurance agent in a cardigan sweater.
</P>
<P>
   The times seemed so utterly rational that an uncanny number of
icons had repeating initials. Roy Rogers. Marilyn Monroe. Mickey
Mantle. Mickey Mouse. Doris Day. Buffalo Bob.
</P>
<P>
   And Brigitte Bardot, who wafted into the decade on a forbidden
French scent. Marilyn Monroe did comedies. Bardot did sex, and shut
your mouth.
</P>
<P>
   I've decided I was wrong, but later in life I felt uncomfortable
with some of these iconic figures, especially the ones associated
with kiddie TV shows.
</P>
<P>
   They never junked their guises. They never changed. They tried
to remain surrogate uncles, aunts and even parents for a generation
that not only outgrew them but also scorned them.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo Bob wore fringe and glowed with giddy enthusiasm until
the end of his days. He probably wanted his obituary to say that he
was survived by Howdy, Dilly Dally, Flub-a-Dub, Mr. Bluster and
that great generational peanut gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Rogers kept the faith, too. He was born someone else
entirely, in Cincinnati, but he became Roy Rogers and stayed Roy
Rogers for all the buckaroos who adored him and then forgot him.
</P>
<P>
   He once said he expected to be stuffed, like his horse Trigger,
when the time came. It's a macabre thought, but not altogether
wrong. The King of the Cowboys, forever frozen in time.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton Moore, once the Lone Ranger on TV, held firm even after
the rights-holders stripped him of his mask. He switched to
wraparound sunglasses and kept firing silver bullet blanks.
</P>
<P>
   I was on a TV press tour, years back, when Moore strode into the
back of the room early one morning and announced his arrival by
firing his gun. Dozens of critics nearly had heart attacks, then
spun around angrily to see who'd splattered their eardrums.
</P>
<P>
   All I can say is that when you saw it was the Lone Ranger, in
the flesh, you felt a very odd mix of sensations. Whatever else
Moore is doing these days, I'm sure he's still Kemosabe.
</P>
<P>
   They were constant; we were malleable. Jay Ward came along with
Rocky the flying squirrel and Bullwinkle the moose, and by
increments the world changed. Fracturing fairy tales and teaching
us, charmingly, that heroes like Dudley Do-Right were dumb as
bricks, Ward planted the first seeds of subversion. You've got to
start growing up sometime, somehow.
</P>
<P>
   As life became a succession of political assassinations, wars,
scandals, careers, families and mutual funds, the figures from our
TV closets devolved into dusty, awkward quaintness. Among them,
only Shari Lewis, with her Lamb Chop sock puppet, seemed capable of
self-renewal.
</P>
<P>
   But think again. These were people who, upon their honor, would
not abandon us. They probably knew we scoffed at them as silly
anachronisms, and still they loved us. They no longer needed the
money, in most cases. They'd simply accepted lifelong
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe kids made decent choices in the first place, all those
decades ago. Constancy. Love. Responsibility. We knew heroes; we
just stopped wanting them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
