<HEADER>
A1875 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-SCHOUREK-B     08-06 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-SCHOUREK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX PICK UP ASTROS LEFTY SCHOUREK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Dan Duquette couldn't get Randy Johnson, so
he made a deal for the pitcher the Big Unit bumped out of Houston's
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Schourek, a 29-year-old lefthander who has undergone elbow
surgery in each of the last two seasons and was a seven-game winner
for the Astros this season, cleared waivers Thursday and was picked
up by the Red Sox for what Duquette described as cash
considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a winning major league pitcher who pitched effectively as
a starter for the Astros,'' said Duquette, who is believed to have
agreed to pay a portion of the incentives in Schourek's contract.
``We've added a starting pitcher with playoff experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Schourek, who has pitched exclusively as a starter for the last
four seasons, probably will bump Steve Avery out of the Sox
rotation and into the bullpen, though manager Jimy Williams refused
Thursday to reveal his plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a new pitcher,'' Williams said. ``We'll have to
figure that out. We already have five starters right now. We'll
have to reevaluate the situation if we decide to start him.''
</P>
<P>
   While Schourek may take Avery's place in the rotation, his first
order of business when he joins the Red Sox today may be to make
peace with ace Pedro Martinez. On Sept. 28, 1995, when Schourek was
pitching for the Cincinnati Reds, he hit Martinez with a pitch, an
act Martinez claims was deliberate, and the Sox pitcher hasn't
forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit me on purpose,'' said Martinez, who one inning before
had hit Reds catcher Benito Santiago in the hand with a pitch and
said Schourek was aiming for his ribs when he stuck up his left arm
in self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made it look like it was (retaliation), but that was back
when I was supposed to be a headhunter. They all wanted to get me,
the little guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Expos manager Felipe Alou admonished Martinez that day not to
throw at Schourek, who also hit Wilfredo Cordero in the same game,
but Martinez said he was just waiting for the opportunity to
retaliate. He thought it had come on Opening Day the following
season when he was supposed to face Schourek in Cincinnati, but
umpire John McSherry collapsed and died at home plate and the game
was rescheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept looking for him to hit him,'' Martinez said, ``but I
never faced him again. Now he's my teammate. Small world.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez intends to broach the subject when Schourek arrives.
``I hope I get to know he's a better person than I'm thinking,''
Martinez said. ``I'm going to ask him why he hit me.''
</P>
<P>
   Schourek's career in some ways resembles that of Avery, and on
one major occasion coincided: While with the Braves, Avery beat
Schourek and the Reds in the deciding game of the 1995 National
League Championship Series, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek was an 18-game winner for the Reds that season,
finished second in the Cy Young Award voting to Greg Maddux of the
Braves, and was Cincinnati's Opening Day starter the following
season.
</P>
<P>
   But like Avery, Schourek, who broke in with the Mets in 1991,
ran into injury problems. He won just nine games in the next two
years, underwent elbow surgery to tighten the ligaments in 1996,
and had another operation to clean out the elbow after last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds wanted Schourek to undergo elbow reconstruction, but he
reportedly balked, fearing the operation would end his career. He
signed a minor league deal with the Astros, made the club out of
spring training, and joined the rotation as the fifth starter in
May.
</P>
<P>
   Like Avery, Schourek was primarily a six-inning pitcher. Three
times he pitched seven innings, but in seven of his 15 starts, he
went five innings or fewer. Overall, he was 7-6 with a 4.50 ERA and
won his last two starts, the most recent a 10-6 win over the
Marlins last Wednesday in which he gave up eight hits and six runs
in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   When the Astros obtained Johnson at the trading deadline last
Friday, Schourek became expendable, and the Sox swooped in.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if the Red Sox decide to carry 12 pitchers,
one more than they have all season. At the moment, the Sox have six
outfielders, so if Avery goes to the bullpen, they could send down
seldom-used outfielder Keith Mitchell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 2024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
