<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1878 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMBODIA-ASSESS-650(2     08-06 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-ASSESS-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: ELECTION FRAUD REPORTS STIR DOUBTS ABOUT DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ Cambodia's election nearly two weeks ago
may, for a while at least, produce the political stability that
people here yearn for. But it is not clear whether it has advanced
the cause of democracy that the outside world has worked hard to
implant here since the start of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging reports of electoral manipulation and a campaign of
fear at the local level have led some political experts to suggest
that for many Cambodians, the lesson of this election is that the
will of the people must still bow to the raw power of their
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The quick stamp of approval by international observers, followed
by their quick departure from Cambodia, has left many people here
feeling abandoned and bewildered. The trade-off _ political
stability _ is not quite here yet. And given this nation's history
of political turmoil and the mutual animosities of its leaders, a
stable Cambodia in the long term would be a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the national election committee announced that the
incumbent leader, Hun Sen, had won a majority of the 122 seats in
Parliament, but not the two-thirds needed to form a government
without creating a coalition with his rivals. Opposition parties
are challenging the count and threatening to paralyze the opening
of Parliament six weeks from now with a boycott.
</P>
<P>
   And reports continued to accumulate Thursday of a sort of
political cleansing in villages around the country where threats of
reprisals are forcing supporters of opposition parties to flee.
</P>
<P>
   But most political experts predict that after a period of
political theater, threats and horse-trading _ and even a possible
constitutional crisis _ that could last well into the fall, the
second-place finisher, Prince Norodom Ranariddh, is likely to join
Hun Sen in some form of coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``If nothing else, he will be under intense pressure from his
party to take a share of the spoils of government,'' a senior aid
worker said. ``What's in it for them to stay out in the cold?''
</P>
<P>
   That outcome carries its share of irony. After muscling his way
into a coalition leadership with Ranariddh after the prince won the
last election, in 1993, Hun Sen pushed the prince overboard in a
coup one year ago and declared, ``I am the only captain of the
ship.''
</P>
<P>
   The clear domination of Hun Sen's party this time around, and
the weakening of military forces loyal to Ranariddh, may, through
force of arms and politics, create a more stable situation than
under the dual premiership of the previous government.
</P>
<P>
   After the coup last year, Hun Sen's supporters systematically
killed about 100 members of the opposition, monopolized the
broadcast media, took control of the mechanisms of the political
campaign, intimidated the voters and then invited the prince to
return from exile and take part in a free election.
</P>
<P>
   Election day, July 26, was an uplifting demonstration of the
desire of Cambodians to exercise their mandate, as more than 90
percent of eligible voters crowded into polling places. Foreign
election monitors were thrilled. Some called the spectacle ``a
miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   But many diplomats and aid workers who live here were incensed
at this quick-draw assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country has been perpetually in turmoil for the last 30
years,'' a diplomat said. ``It's going to take more than one Sunday
of relative peace and quiet to change that. It is incredibly
disingenuous and intellectually dishonest as well as possibly
immoral for the international community to come in here and say,
`OK, you have democracy,' when the reality on the ground is much
different.''
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to quantify the effects of any threats or
manipulation by the governing party. But the picture of voting day
that has emerged in reports from Cambodian and foreign observers
suggests that a good deal more was going on than was apparent on
the surface.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Voters had already been given the message in the previous weeks
and months that there was a right and wrong way to vote. Hun Sen's
party members, who virtually monopolize local and provincial
government, had thumb-printed voters, collected and held their
voting cards and selectively threatened, attacked and sometimes
killed villagers who opposed them.
</P>
<P>
   On voting day, those same party functionaries ran the polling
stations, sending a signal that, as one foreign monitor put it,
``we'll still be here tomorrow, and you're still going to have to
live with us.''
</P>
<P>
   A variety of ballot manipulation was used at the polling
stations, said the election monitor, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity. With a population that is more than 60 percent
illiterate, polling station staff marked ballots for many people,
the election monitor said. They sometimes engaged in a system of
``telegraph'' voting, in which pre-marked ballots were substituted
for clean ones. Once the count was under way, a disproportionate
number of opposition ballots were ruled invalid.
</P>
<P>
   There are unconfirmed allegations of larger-scale manipulation
that may have involved the switching of ballot boxes and the
massaging of vote totals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have heard people say that next time they won't vote _ it
makes no difference anyway,'' a European diplomat said. ``A lot of
people see this election not as a democratic exercise but as a tool
by Hun Sen to perpetuate his power. They feel used.''
</P>
<P>
   For two years leading up to the 1993 election, the United
Nations employed 20,000 foreign aid workers here and spent more
than $2 billion in an effort to plant the seeds of democracy in one
of the world's most battered and suffering countries.
</P>
<P>
   The years since then have been a struggle between Cambodia's
violent past and the small but growing corps of people who have
embraced the United Nations' democratic ideals. The country has a
wildly free press _ though journalists are sometimes killed _ and a
vigorous sector of private groups focusing on human rights, the
rights of women and children, legal reforms, environmental
protection and the alleviation of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   They are the real opposition to Hun Sen's monopoly of power.
</P>
<P>
   Now that representatives of other countries have returned
briefly, pronounced themselves satisfied and left again, Hun Sen
may feel himself under less pressure to permit this range of
democratic activity, said Thomas Hammarberg, the human rights envoy
to Cambodia from the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of the international community is that interest
moves from country to country,'' he said. ``Cambodia is now in
danger of being forgotten.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
