u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KARAN-MARKETPLACE-600     08-06 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KARAN-MARKETPLACE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: HOW FAR CAN DONNA KARAN GO? 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like any stock that hits the skids after its initial
public offering, Donna Karan International has attracted some
contrarian investors.
</P>
<P>
   And the financial condition of the fashion house has improved.
Thursday, the company announced that it had narrowed its loss in
the second quarter by 57.1 percent from a year earlier and that
revenue had risen to $124.9 million, from $111 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But the crucial question is how far can this company really go
in imitating its more successful brethren on Seventh Avenue. You
know, Polo Ralph Lauren, Tommy Hilfiger, Calvin Klein.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Donna Karan brought in John Idol as chief executive
after several wretched money-losing quarters with her at the helm.
Idol, who was hired away from Polo Ralph Lauren, wasted no time in
shaking things up. He proclaimed that the company's future included
far more licensed businesses and free-standing stores.
</P>
<P>
   Right away, he sealed a licensing deal with Estee Lauder Cos.
for Donna Karan's beauty business. The move was long overdue, since
production costs had wiped out much of the beauty products'
profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, he negotiated a licensing deal for the men's and
women's jeans and casual wear business, known as DKNY Jeans, with
Liz Claiborne Inc., under which Donna Karan got $30 million right
off the bat and a percentage of sales in the Western Hemisphere. A
license to market and produce DKNY and to sell Donna Karan's
high-end clothing in Japan was put together with a partner there,
although that business has been weak because of the country's
worsening economy. Some smaller deals were cut as well.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Karan's infamous spending was also reined in. Reductions in
advertising and marketing helped the company cut costs for selling,
general and administrative purposes to 28.9 percent of net revenue
in the second quarter, from 39.8 percent a year earlier. The
company's net loss narrowed to $6.3 million, from $14.7 million in
the second quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems he is doing all the right things,'' said Marc Ravitz,
vice president of Grace &AMP; White Inc., New York, an investment
group, which recently bought Donna Karan stock.
</P>
<P>
   But the stock remains mired far below the initial offering price
of $24 in mid-1996. It closed Thursday at $11.75, down 37.5 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Idol's licensing strategy is understandable, given its
extraordinary success at Polo Ralph Lauren, whose name graces
everything from towels to T-shirts to bras to house paint. Most of
the strong fashion companies rely on such licensees to bolster
profits and reduce overhead.
</P>
<P>
   But companies with successful licensing businesses have
something in common _a sterling name. Donna Karan is revered on the
West and East Coasts for her high-end duds and her 1980s move to
offer high-powered career women clothing antidotes to bow ties and
padded shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   In the South and Midwest, it is a different story. Calls to a
randomly selected group of stores there recently found that three
out of seven sales clerks did not know the name.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Ms. Karan rose to fame among urban career women, who
remain her core market, along with Barbra Streisand and a bevy of
starlets. What is more, her most expensive line, which sets the
tone for the entire fashion house, has gotten more ethereal in
recent years. The fall collection of padded dresses, for example,
is not likely to be a hit among women wearing anything bigger than
a size 4 or the very baby boomers she once cultivated. The company
recently reintroduced her line of Donna Karan ``essentials'' _
basic career clothes _ but that line is not getting significant
marketing support.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ralph Lauren, by contrast, tends to create a much tamer high-end
line, one influenced by American sportswear. And his signature item
is worn in every corner of the country _ the simple pullover polo
shirt. Ms. Karan has no such mainstream piece of clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not true that everyone knows Donna Karan's name,'' said
Faye Landes, one of the few retailing stock analysts who still
track the company. ``Part of the brilliance of Tommy and Ralph is
that they have a name known around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Building a name from China to Wyoming and the sales to back it
up takes time. Calvin Klein started his business in 1968, and last
year his revenue was about $5.1 billion. Ms. Karan, whose business
began in 1984, had revenue last year of $638.7 million, about the
size of Klein's fragrance business. Also, Ralph Lauren and Calvin
Klein have spent millions more than Ms. Karan has on marketing to
build name awareness.
</P>
<P>
   At this juncture, Ms. Karan's ability to generate substantially
more licensing business seems questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, she gave away her best chance at reaching middle America:
the jeans business. The DKNY Jeans products from Liz Claiborne are
similar to Donna Karan's secondary DKNY line, but cheaper. This has
hurt DKNY. Gross profit at Donna Karan International decreased to
19.8 percent of sales last quarter, from 20.4 percent in 1997, and
sales of the men's business fell 6.6 percent largely as a result of
Liz Claiborne's getting the best part of that business.
</P>
<P>
   Idol said in an interview this week: ``The reality is that
licensing will always appear as a small percentage of revenues, and
wholesale will always be the dominant revenue part of the company.
But as a percentage of earnings, it will be significant.''
</P>
<P>
   The wholesale business has been less than stellar.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue in the women's business rose 12.1 percent in the latest
quarter, but people who recently left the company and who agreed to
be interviewed on the condition that their names not be used said
the company had sold big chunks of DKNY fall inventory to off-price
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Idol denied that the sales to those stores were heavier than
usual. Still, a spokeswoman at Sam's Club, a unit of Wal-Mart
Stores, which rarely has access to such merchandise, said that it
now has DKNY in stock, and a merchant at another off-price company
said its warehouse stores had picked up some merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Such sales do not bode well for margins going forward. What is
more, some retailers say they have lightened their orders of the
company's men's clothes for fall, because of general weakness in
the category.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there is the question of Ms. Karan's stores. She has 65
stores abroad and 49 outlet stores in the United States, and she
plans to open one Donna Karan and three DKNY stores domestically
this year. But this is not a low-cost proposition. A
1,200-square-foot store on Madison Avenue, for example, can rent
for $400 to $500 a square foot, or $480,000 to $600,000 a year, and
building stores from scratch is costly.
</P>
<P>
   A final note. As part of the initial public offering back in
1996, Ms. Karan struck a deal to get 1.75 percent of the first $250
million of net sales each year, rising to 3.5 percent of sales that
exceed $1.5 billion. Shareholders derided her at the annual meeting
this year for keeping this share in the wake of poor performance,
but she argued that other designers do the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her deal we are not too happy with,'' said Lawrence Manley, a
portfolio manager at Manley Fuller Asset Management in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Such sentiment alone may keep all but bottom-fishing investors
away from the flashy house of fashion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
