</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-OIL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. OPENS PART OF ALASKA NORTH SLOPE TO DRILLING
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo and locator map is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Interior Department said Thursday that it would
open a new expanse of the Alaska North Slope wilderness to oil and
gas leasing, but it limited drilling in some areas that the
industry is most eager to explore.
</P>
<P>
   To protect lakes where migrating geese molt and the main calving
area of the local caribou herd, the Interior Department refused to
allow development in an area north and east of Teshekpuk Lake near
the Beaufort Sea, a coastal plain as rich in wildlife as it
probably is in oil.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, in a decision that was widely
anticipated, said oil companies would be allowed to look for oil on
four million acres of the National Petroleum Reserve, west of the
Prudhoe Bay oil fields where oil wells already feed the
trans-Alaskan pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   The petroleum reserve is a 23-million-acre tract between the
Brooks Range and the Arctic, set aside since 1923 as a strategic
reserve. The northeastern one-fifth of the reserve is thought to
hold about half a billion barrels of oil, about a month's supply
for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Congress approved the leasing of oil and gas in the reserve in
1981, but the oil industry became more interested in recent years
as oil and gas development approached the boundaries from the east.
Alaska Gov. Tony Knowles, a Democrat, asked President Clinton to
allow leasing, and the Interior Department has been studying the
question for 18 months. Conservation groups have opposed leasing
there because the land provides habitat for fish, birds and
caribou. But unlike the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge to the
east, the land is not set aside for wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   The plan establishes various restrictions on development in
different parts of the tract, depending mainly on the use by
wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of the goose-molting area was kept off limits. But in
some sections, only activity on the surface is barred, so oil
companies could drill into these lands from the side. In other
areas, conditions are imposed to minimize disruption of the caribou
herds, to protect the riverside nesting sites of peregrine falcons
and other raptors and to keep permanent oil and gas equipment away
from the shores of lakes that are deep enough to hold fish.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Department refused to allow development on 600,000
acres of the 4.6-million-acre tract that it studied for possible
leasing. Much of the land that it put off limits is around
Teshekpuk Lake and the coastal plain where the oil industry
believes the richest deposits lie.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a terribly shortsighted decision,'' said William
Meadows, president of the Wilderness Society, an environmental
organization based in Washington. ``This reserve contains some
world-class wildlife habitat, vital to grizzly bears, caribou and
millions of shorebirds, ducks, and geese.''
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt visited the area for several days last year and ordered
extensive scientific consultations before making his decision. He
said his plan had addressed the major environmental concerns and
the needs of residents who subsist on caribou, fish and marine
mammals.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the plan said it was unwise to begin producing oil
from a strategic reserve at a time when oil is plentiful and cheap.
Babbitt said that oil leasing would not begin until next year,
followed by exploration, and that production would be unlikely to
begin for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Meyers, president of Arco Alaska, a unit of the Atlantic
Richfield Company, said that he was pleased the Interior Department
was recommending a lease sale but regretted that more of the
coastal area was not to be opened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
