A1890 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RENO-CONTEMPT-WHAT-IF     08-06 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-CONTEMPT-WHAT-IF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO WOULD BE TRIED IN FEDERAL COURT IF CONTEMPT ACTION PROCEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sidebar with RENO-CONTEMPT) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It is doubtful that the case will go that far, but
if the full House of Representatives voted to hold Attorney General
Janet Reno in contempt, she would be prosecuted in federal court,
most likely by the U.S. attorney's office in the District of
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   If a grand jury indicted her and the dispute with Congress were
not settled one way or another, she would go to trial. If
convicted, she could be imprisoned for up to a year and fined up to
$1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The fine might not seem like much, but $1,000 was a lot of money
in 1857, when Congress passed a law specifically authorizing
punishment for contempt of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, prosecution of the attorney general for contempt seems
rather far-fetched at this point, largely because only one federal
official, Anne Burford, has ever been held in contempt of Congress
for refusing to produce information on grounds of executive
privilege.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 16, 1982, Mrs. Burford, who was Anne Gorsuch before her
marriage in 1983, refused on orders from President Ronald Reagan to
produce documents related to an investigation of the Environmental
Protection Agency, which she headed at the time. That brought a
contempt citation in 1983, but it was canceled after the Reagan
administration yielded enough documents to satisfy a House
committee.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 25, 1982, another House committee voted to cite Interior
Secretary James Watt for contempt for refusing to turn over
documents sought by investigators, but that dispute was settled
when Reagan gave committee members enough access to the papers to
satisfy them.
</P>
<P>
   It has been far more common for Congress to hold private
citizens in contempt when they have been deemed uncooperative in
investigations of criminal activities or, in the years after World
War II, inquiries into supposed communist infiltration.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional power to punish contempt, while never spelled
out in the Constitution, has been clear since the early 19th
century, when a land dealer named John Anderson tried to bribe a
House member. Incensed, Speaker Henry Clay had Anderson hauled
before the House, where he was upbraided and held briefly in
custody.
</P>
<P>
   Upon release, Anderson sued the House sergeant-at-arms for false
arrest. The sergeant-at-arms insisted that he had acted within his
authority, whether the Constitution explicitly said so or not. In
1821, the Supreme Court agreed with him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
