<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEADPET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    N.C. show reveals fate of unadopted animals
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C._ Sheriff BJ Barnes plans to use his weekly
television program today to show a dog being killed at the Guilford
County Animal Shelter, his way of illustrating the plight of
unwanted pets.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-second videotape segment already has pricked the nation's
fascination with animal euthanasia through snippets aired on
national TV news shows. The videotape shows a mixed breed dog
collapsing from lethal injection and being placed in a 55-gallon
disposal drum with other dead dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come in and do not think their little Fluffy is going
to be put to sleep,'' said Lisa Boughton, a veterinary technician
in Guilford County, where more than 10,000 animals were euthanized
last year. ``But little Fluffy is going to be put to sleep if there
is not room for it.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated six million to eight million animals are killed
annually in America's animal shelters because of disease or lack of
homes. ``It is inhumane what is being done here, when the answer
could be spaying and neutering,'' said Sheriff Barnes, 47, the
owner of a spayed Doberman Pinscher named Diamond. He said he has
been swamped by hundreds of phone calls, most praising his planned
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   But in Atlanta, Fulton County's animal control director, Robert
Fisher, said the broadcast is ``going to upset decent people and
isn't going to bother the irresponsible people.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Sinclair, a director with the Humane Society of the
United States, commended Barnes. ``We think it will at least create
a discussion among people, and that is always good,'' Sinclair
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
