<HEADER>
A1896 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWM-SMITH-COX     08-06 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWM-SMITH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smith suspended four years for tampering with sample
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Is the jig up for Irish swimmer Michelle Smith? The
1996 triple gold medalist at the Atlanta Olympics, whose victories
inspired mass celebration in her homeland, was banned for four
years Thursday after officials ruled that she had tampered with a
urine sample to spike a drug test.
</P>
<P>
   FINA, the international swimming federation, could have imposed
a life ban on Smith, 28, but the four-year suspension achieves the
same purpose by forcing her to miss the 2000 Olympics and the next
World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was already considered old at age 26 in Atlanta, when the
remarkable drop in her times aroused suspicion. But Smith never
tested positive for drugs _ and still hasn't. Her downfall: Both
samples from an out-of-competition test in January contained a
lethal concentration of whiskey, which insinuates an attempt at
masking banned drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's lawyer, Peter Lennon, would not comment until a news
conference today in Ireland. He said earlier that she would
consider an appeal to the International Court of Arbitration in
Sport.
</P>
<P>
   Under FINA rules, tampering with a urine sample is considered as
serious as taking steroids or other banned drugs.
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence that Smith was anything but clean at the
'96 Games, where she won the 200- and 400-meter individual medleys
and the 400 freestyle, and was third in the 200 butterfly. However,
the case reinforces the belief on the pooldeck that something was
fishy.
</P>
<P>
   As Allison Wagner, who was second in the 400 IM, pointed out
Thursday, ``I don't know of anybody that would start using
performance-enhancing drugs after winning three gold medals.''
</P>
<P>
   While Wagner said it was ``a little comforting'' to know that
FINA took a stand to ban Smith, she added, ``They've found the
whiskey, but she still has the gold at home and I still have the
silver, so it's not quite the same satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   As the East German doping trials resume next week, the
International Olympic Committee has promised to evaluate Olympic
results from the 1970s and '80s on a case-by-case basis, given the
testimony that athletes took steroids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see that they would take a look at this one,'' U.S.
Swimming president Carol Zaleski said of Smith's case. ``There
really isn't proof that she was doing it back then.''
</P>
<P>
   But she added, ``This test is the first real evidence of
wrongdoing. It certainly supports some of the suspicions.''
</P>
<P>
   Suspicion also was fueled by the fact that Smith's husband and
coach, Erik de Bruin, is a former discus thrower who was banned for
using drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I showed up at the Olympics, I'd never heard of her
before,'' said Wagner, who has the dubious distinction of also
placing second at the 1994 World Championships to China's Lu Bin,
who tested positive for steroids a month later. After the Olympics,
people told Wagner that she was the champion ``because everybody
doubted Michelle's performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Hailed as a hero in Ireland during the summer of '96, Smith had
to defend herself to the rest of the world. She has been so hounded
by the drug rumors that her endorsement opportunities suffered.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, whose best previous Olympic finish was 17th in 1988, said
she didn't take drugs. Her plight drew the admiration of President
Clinton, who congratulated Smith during the Games. ``He told me, 'I
admire the way you handled all the crap that they're throwing at
you. We've had to deal with that ourselves,' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   FINA's doping panel, which heard Smith's case two weeks ago,
said its investigation found that the urine was ``manipulated by
the swimmer but the way of manipulation is uncertain.'' FINA said
it found that the manipulation was not carried out in the
laboratory, during the transport or by the collectors of the
sample.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who hasn't swum in a major competition since winning two
events at the 1997 Europeans, stressed the fact that no banned
substance has been detected in her urine, FINA said. She also
stated that
</P>
<P>
   ``from her side there was no physical manipulation of the
sample.''
</P>
<P>
   Zaleski said that the observer who witnessed the test _
observers are supposed to watch the athletes urinate _ testified
that Smith was in a baggy sweater that came down to her knees. The
observer couldn't see her produce the urine, but heard the
appropriate sound.
</P>
<P>
   FINA said the content of alcohol in the sample was ``in no way
compatible with human consumption and the sample shows a very
strong whiskey odour.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith is not the first swimmer accused of tampering. Prior to
the 1992 Olympics, East Germany's Katrin Krabbe and two others were
suspended for four years because of a ``suspicious'' drug test in
which their three clean samples all apparently came from the same
person. The suspension was overturned on appeal, but Krabbe later
tested positive for drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the sports world has been slammed by
allegations of drug use in the Tour de France and by the
drug-related suspensions of Olympic track and field athletes Dennis
Mitchell and Randy Barnes and U.S. swimming's Gary Hall Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
