u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-435&AMP;     08-06 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-435&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE APPROVES SHAYS-MEEHAN BILL ON CAMPAIGN FINANCE REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ending a struggle that has gone on for months, the
House on Thursday approved a bipartisan bill to overhaul the way
the nation's political campaigns are financed and shifted the
spotlight back onto the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In a final rebuke to the Republican leadership, the House vote
for passage of the measure sponsored by Reps. Christopher Shays,
R-Conn., and Martin Meehan, D-Mass., was 252-179. That was even
stronger than a preliminary vote earlier in the week. Sixty-one
Republicans split from their party to back the bill, while 15
Democrats broke party lines to vote against it.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the surprising resiliency of the issue in the House, the
legislation is thought to have little chance in the Senate, where
it obtained bare majority support earlier this year and died in a
Republican filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate has dealt with this issue already,'' said John
Czwartacki, a spokesman for Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott.
``There's no more of a consensus now than there was in the
spring.''
</P>
<P>
   But heartened by a victory that would have seemed improbable
just a few months ago, the bipartisan House coalition immediately
turned its attention to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the House vote, Rep. Zach Wamp, R-Tenn., waved in
the air the green-covered record of last year's hearings in the
Senate, led by Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., Tennessee, into
campaign finance abuses of the 1996 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate started this process,'' said Wamp. ``We have paved
the way. And we want the American people to weigh in over the next
five weeks, get on the phone and get the Senate to take this issue
back up in September.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Allen, D-Maine, said Lott should be asked ``a simple
question _ what's wrong with a bill that has majority support in
the House of Representatives and majority support in the Senate?''
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan legislation would effectively end the unlimited
and unregulated donations to the political parties, known as soft
money, which have increasingly been used to evade the limits on
contributions to individual candidates that were enacted in the
wake of the Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   It would also curb the practice, which has been growing in
recent elections, of independent groups running ads attacking or
supporting a candidate. The bill would more strictly regulate such
ads that identify a candidate within 60 days of an election.
</P>
<P>
   The measure is opposed by most Republicans, who say it violates
constitutional guarantees of free speech and weakens political
parties.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rep. John Doolittle, R-Calif., said that Watergate-era limits on
donations to individual candidates drove givers to issue advocacy
ads and to make ``soft money'' donations to the parties. ``Those
are the results of never lifting those hard dollar limits,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leaders of the House used every plan they could
to defeat the Shays-Meehan legislation. While they failed to kill
the bill, they took solace in the fact that they had delayed its
passage until a week after the Senate left on its August recess.
</P>
<P>
   When the Senate returns there is only a month left before
adjournment and a long list of spending bills that must be passed
to start the new fiscal year. ``There's no way this bill,
Shays-Meehan, will ever become law,'' said Doolittle. ``So we are
really laying the foundation now for the next Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., one of the sponsors of the
Senate companion bill, has said that the brief time remaining makes
passing a Senate bill ``an exceedingly difficult task at best.''
And while Democrats say they will use parliamentary tactics to try
to attach the bill to other legislation, they are also looking for
ways to use the same tactic for other competing election-year
priorities such as regulating health maintenance organizations and
increasing the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the House at least, campaign finance overhaul proved
to be the bill that would not die.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich tried to dispense with the issue in
March under a procedure that never allowed a vote on Shays-Meehan.
When that backfired, he tried to kill the measure through openness.
</P>
<P>
   In the usually tightly controlled House, the bill was pitted
against 10 competing measures and scores of amendments in a debate
that went on for weeks, usually at night. Shays said Thursday at
almost all of the amendments were written by aides to Rep. Tom
DeLay, R-Texas, the House majority whip, and to Sen. Mitch
McConnell, R-Ky., who has led the Senate battle against the bill.
</P>
<P>
   But by last week, Shays and Meehan had managed to defeat all of
the amendments that they feared could fatally fracture their
coalition and on Monday their bill won majority support, keeping it
alive.
</P>
<P>
   The one last threat to the Shays-Meehan bill was another
bipartisan bill, drawn up by freshmen led by Rep. Asa Hutchinson,
R-Ark., and Allen.
</P>
<P>
   It contained a less stringent ban on soft money that did not
apply to state parties and it did not put the same limits on issue
advocacy as the Shays-Meehan legislation.
</P>
<P>
   While Hutchinson said that this bill was preferable because it
could withstand a Supreme Court challenge, the supporters of
Shays-Meehan said that the bill would simply allow large,
unregulated contributions to be funneled through state parties.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said that both DeLay and the Republican National
Committee had been working to persuade opponents of campaign
finance overhaul would vote for the freshman bill as a tactic for
defeating Shays-Meehan. But in the end, the freshman bill could not
command a majority and was defeated, 222-147.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
