<HEADER>
A1916 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAXES-REPUBLICANS-NYT     08-06 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAXES-REPUBLICANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAIT `TIL NEXT YEAR, GINGRICH ADMITS ON BIG TAX CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Speaker Newt Gingrich conceded Thursday that huge
tax cuts would probably have to be put off to next year, but House
Republican leaders said they would forge ahead this fall with a
more modest tax cut in the belief that President Clinton would
ultimately accept it.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings with fellow Republicans over the last week, Gingrich
has said Clinton will probably accept a bill cutting taxes by a
maximum of $70 billion to $80 billion over five years.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, the speaker's decision can be seen as a retreat
in the face of opposition from Clinton and moderate Republicans.
Gingrich and other conservatives had been promoting legislation
that would cut taxes by $167 billion over five years and by $700
billion over 10 years. On the other hand, Republicans said, the
strategy could prove to be a big advance toward getting a tax cut
enacted into law this year.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans had made clear that they would not approve
tax cuts of the magnitude Gingrich originally wanted. And the White
House sounded cool even to the idea of a more modest tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Thursday night, Gene Sperling, assistant to the
president for economic policy, said: ``The president is not going
to sign any new spending or tax initiative if it drains any of the
surplus that is reserved for Social Security, whether it's $700
billion, $70 billion or $7 billion. We believe that all of the
surplus should be reserved for Social Security until we have a
comprehensive bipartisan reform solution for that program.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, at a caucus of House Republicans, Gingrich said
Thursday, ``We believe the surplus money will go to save Social
Security and to provide tax relief.'' He vowed that ``every penny
of Social Security payroll taxes'' _ but not necessarily every
penny of the surplus _ ``will be used to strengthen Social
Security.''
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office foresees a surplus of $63
billion this year and a total of $1.5 trillion in surpluses over
the next 10 years. In this fall's elections, Gingrich said,
Republicans will ask voters, ``Do you want the money to go back to
the American taxpayer, or do you want the money spent by
bureaucrats in Washington?''
</P>
<P>
   The House Republicans' top priority for this year's tax bill is
to reduce the effects of a longstanding quirk in the tax code known
as the marriage penalty. Because of this provision, many married
couples with two incomes pay higher taxes than they would if they
filed separate tax returns as individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who writes tax legislation as
chairman of the Ways and Means Committee, said: ``I look forward to
producing a middle-income tax cut bill in September, and I hope the
president will sign it. If he doesn't, he risks being known as the
president who imposed a marriage penalty on the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the House Republican caucus Thursday, Gingrich
listed five other priorities for tax-cutting legislation this fall
and next year. For example, he said, Republicans will try to cut
capital gains taxes, eliminate estate taxes and increase the tax
deductions allowed for the purchase of health insurance by
individuals and small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Capital gains are profits from the sale of stocks, real estate
and other assets. Gingrich wants to reduce the top tax rate on such
gains to 15 percent, from 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said the Republicans also would work to repeal a law
that reduces Social Security benefits for elderly people who earn
over $14,500 a year. Critics say the Social Security earnings limit
punishes people for working and forces some people to retire even
though they would prefer to work.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Gingrich said the Republicans would try to repeal
provisions of the 1993 budget law that increased the taxation of
Social Security benefits for people with substantial income from
other sources.
</P>
<P>
   The president said Thursday that he would accuse the Republicans
of weakening Social Security if they pursued a big tax cut financed
by projected surpluses in the federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in the Rose Garden of the White House, Clinton
declared, ``We should reserve every penny of the surplus until we
save Social Security for the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the federal budget was last balanced in 1969, he
said: ``We waited 29 years for this, to get out of the red ink. It
looks to me like we could at least wait a year and enjoy it and
take care of future generations' challenges before we run right out
and spend this money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
