<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOP-STARR!-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MESSAGE TO KEN STARR: STOP SPENDING OUR MONEY!  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 525-word ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By DAVID USBORNE  
 c.1998 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, CONN. _ Everyone, it seems, has an opinion about
Monica Lewinsky and the investigation led by Ken Starr into
allegations that she and President Clinton had some kind of sexual
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   But, as a sampling of conversations at a strip mall in Stamford,
Conn., suggested recently, the spectrum of views is wide.
</P>
<P>
   There are some common themes, however. Almost no one believes
the President was not lying when he said on television last January
that he had not had sexual relations with ``that woman.''
</P>
<P>
   The question, however, is whether Starr should continue to
pursue him and threaten his very presidency.
</P>
<P>
   To a surprisingly consistent degree, Americans are concerned
about the amount of money _ their money _ that has already been
spent on the probe, which at the last count had topped $40 million.
Even those who support the investigation balk at the cost of it.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Gentile, for example, who manages a local video shop, is
visceral in his distaste for the President. ``I think they should
throw his ass out of there, because he is a liar. I think he is
guilty,'' he vented angrily, before adding quickly: ``But I don't
think we should be paying for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary, a local school teacher, also worries about the expense.
``I think they should stop this, because they're spending so much
money.''
</P>
<P>
   And the same goes for Paula, a property manager in this East
Coast town located about one hour north of New York. ``I think they
should get on with the business of running the country, instead of
spending all this money on Clinton's sex life, '' she complained.
</P>
<P>
   Both women, who preferred to withhold their family names, fall
firmly in the ``leave-the-man-alone'' camp. Like many others
interviewed, they said that whatever happened between Lewinsky and
the President is no one's affair but their own and Hillary
Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested in who slept with whom, I'm just not,''
said Mary, adding a view that seems to be most commonly shared by
women: ``It's really between Hillary and Bill. If Hillary can deal
with it, then so should the rest of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Gender, however, does not appear to determine the way Americans
think about the scandal. Lucia Hoffman, intercepted renting videos
for her children who are off school for the summer, believes Starr
is right to pursue the President, who, she said, had ``used his
power to press himself on co-workers and women.''
</P>
<P>
   She suggests the President needs professional help because he is
a ``sex addict.'' Mary also prescribes psychiatric treatment, but
for Starr, ``because he is obviously anal.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, a lot of Americans seem unable to settle in either
camp. Donald Winfield, who drives a truck for an electrical
contractor, believes that the President is a ``philanderer,'' who
has ``lied about this. And if the President has lied about that,
what else has he lied about in office?''
</P>
<P>
   Winfield believes the President should be ``punished.'' But
should he be impeached? ``Oh no,'' he answers quickly. ``I think
that would just bring shame on the country.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 525-word article, it must be purchased _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 2041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
