<SLUG> BC-EUDORA-FLAW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO GET AROUND PROBLEM IN EUDORA E-MAIL PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (sidebar with INTERNET-SECURITY) 
(ART ADV: Graphic on e-mail safety is being sent to NYT graphics
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are relatively easy ways to avoid the recently discovered
security flaw in Eudora, the world's most popular electronic mail
program, but the quick fixes should not obscure the need for
caution when reading unsolicited e-mail messages, Internet experts
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The flaw, which could allow malicious programmers to mask
harmful programs as simple links to the World Wide Web, affects
only the 4.0 and 4.0.1 versions of Eudora running on computers that
use Microsoft Corp.'s Windows 95 or 98 operating system.
</P>
<P>
   People who use Eudora on a Macintosh are not vulnerable. Windows
users can find out which version of Eudora they own by choosing the
``About Eudora'' option under the program's ``Help'' menu.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Qualcomm, which makes Eudora, would not say how
many thousands of people have bought the 4.0 and 4.0.1 versions of
the program since they were introduced last December. But by this
afternoon on the East Coast, Qualcomm plans to post a free software
``patch'' at www.qualcomm.com/eudora on the company's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   A patch is a small program that changes the code inside another,
larger program. Users who run the patch will be able to fix their
copies of Eudora so they are no longer vulnerable to the security
problem.
</P>
<P>
   People who like the latest software can also download a
``beta,'' or test, copy of the next version of Eudora, version 4.1,
from the same Web address. Qualcomm executives said version 4.1 did
not contain the security flaw.
</P>
<P>
   People who are unable or unwilling to download new software from
the Web can alter their current versions of Eudora so the security
flaw can no longer affect their computers.
</P>
<P>
   Eudora uses portions of Microsoft's Internet Explorer software
to view e-mail messages that can look as polished as Web pages. By
severing Eudora's relationship with Internet Explorer, the security
problem can be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, users must select ``Options'' under Eudora's
``Tools'' menu. Under the category of ``Viewing Mail,'' the user
must turn off the option ``Use Microsoft's Viewer.''
</P>
<P>
   The catch is that by disabling the Microsoft component, users
can no longer view e-mail that contains complex formats from the
Web, including tables and charts.
</P>
<P>
   But by fixing the security problem in Eudora, users are assuring
only that programs that are attached to incoming messages reveal
themselves as icons that can be clicked on like any other.
</P>
<P>
   Those programs can still be destructive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attachments have always been dangerous,'' said the programmer
who discovered the problem, Richard M. Smith, president of Phar Lap
Software Inc., which is based in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are sending stuff down the wire, and it could have bad
stuff in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said people should be wary about opening attachments that
come with unsolicited electronic messages.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Parks, Qualcomm's product manager for Eudora, said:
``People with e-mail in general need to be careful with
attachments. People should be aware of who is sending them
information.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
