<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REPUBS-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS AREN'T ANXIOUS TO OPEN IMPEACHMENT HEARINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Ark., Ga., Pa., Calif., Mo., Okla., Wyo.)   (With CLINTON-STARR and CLINTON-LEWINSKY)  
(lh) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With Monica Lewinsky testifying before a grand jury
at the federal courthouse, Republicans a few blocks away on Capitol
Hill were sensing the gravity of the task that might well await
them.
</P>
<P>
   They may have to investigate whether President Clinton lied
under oath or otherwise obstructed justice in covering up any
sexual involvement with Ms. Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   The House, where Republicans hold a 229-205 advantage, would
conduct any congressional investigation and initiate any
impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every member has to be reflecting in his own mind, `Is this a
question we have to resolve?''' said Rep. David McIntosh, R-Ind.
``As evidence is developed in the grand jury, we have to take that
very seriously. But it's not a good assignment for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most House Republicans, McIntosh has little use for Clinton
or his policies. But he and many others still said they wished the
matter would vanish. He said he gave the president the benefit of
the doubt at the moment and that any impeachment proceedings would
undermine the stability of the country.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with scores of Republican House members, most
expressed no desire for the task that may loom ahead, possibly as
soon as a week or two after they return from their summer vacation
in September. The distaste is both personal and political.
</P>
<P>
   ``The assumption is that something is coming in our direction,''
said Rep. Asa Hutchison, R-Ark. ``I don't think we want to receive
it, but it's a duty that we have to deal with it when it comes, not
at a politically convenient time.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one member, Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., expressed an urgency for
a report from the independent counsel and for the House to get an
investigation underway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that the inquiry into impeachment was justified back in
November, and there's nothing that has changed my opinion,'' he
said. ``I think it's even more appropriate today,'' he said.
``There seems certainly to be a fairly substantial body of evidence
that's being developed that perjury has been committed, that
subornation of perjury has been committed, there's a further
pattern of obstruction of justice _ none of that did we know about
back in November.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr said it was important that the House investigate the
questions surrounding President Clinton's behavior. ``If we let
them slide, we're telling the rest of the world that it doesn't
matter to us that we have a president who, from all appearances,
can't be trusted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others were less eager, saying they could do little until
Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, issues his report.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to focus on it, I don't really care about it,''
said Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa. He said he expected to have to
``engage'' in mid-September _ a time when Congress will also be in
the midst of tough negotiations with the Clinton administration
over the 13 spending bills that must be passed and signed to keep
the government running in the new fiscal year, which begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to have a life of its own beyond anything I can say
or do about it,'' Weldon said, ``so it's just not worth me getting
into.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., was equally dismissive. ``That's a
different planet,'' he said of the Lewinsky matter after talking to
reporters at length about health care. ``It doesn't affect anything
I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   But some Republicans said they could not help but think about
the political ramifications of and any House action. Some said they
worried that if Republicans went after Clinton on sexual matters,
the Democrats would do the same thing to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The War Room will be cranked up to a brand new height,'' said
one Republican lawmaker, referring to Clinton's political team.
``They'll all be working overtime.'' Said an aide to another
Republican: ``If they go after him on that, it will be no holds
barred.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rep. Marge Roukema, R-N.J., said Republicans had to be careful
to center any investigation on legal questions of perjury and ``not
violating President and Mrs. Clinton's privacy.'' She said that
women she talked with ``are very sensitive to Hillary and Chelsea
as being so vulnerable _ they identify with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Many seemed particularly concerned about the timing of Starr's
report to the House. The Democratic leader, Rep. Dick Gephardt of
Missouri, addressed that issue Thursday, saying that sending it to
Congress before the November elections would be ``very partisan,
very unfair and very demeaning to the process.''
</P>
<P>
   One Republican from the Northeast, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said he believed that party leaders wanted the report to
leak out before the elections but would not force the rank-and-file
to cast any difficult votes on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing our guys want to do is pick up seats in
November,'' he said. ``That's all this is about.'' The idea, he
said, would be for damaging bits leak out before the elections so
that Democratic voters are ``so discouraged or turned off that they
don't go to the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Others think that because of that very potential for
partisanship, the report should be held off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we don't even talk about this until after the
election,'' said Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla. He said that injecting a
House investigation into the fall campaigns would bring out ``the
dishonesty'' in both parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry that voters are going to lose even more confidence in
the political process because the politicians are going to
politicize it and demagogue it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barbara Cubin, R-Wyo., said the political process was
already damaged because the Lewinsky matter was dominating all news
from Washington. Having to deal with it head on before the election
``can't be good for the country,'' she said, ``but what's happening
now is not good for the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
