</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONICA LEWINSKY: A WOMAN WHOSE VOICE HAS NOT BEEN HEARD HAS PLENTY
TO SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-REPUBS)  
(ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(JT) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The American public has not yet heard the voice of
the young woman whose appearance at a federal courthouse Thursday
morning drew a dozen satellite trucks and scores of reporters who
mostly wound up interviewing each other about their brief glimpse
of her.
</P>
<P>
   But Monica Lewinsky has plenty to say, according to several
people she has spent time with since the independent counsel,
Kenneth Starr, began investigating her relationship with the
president more than six months ago. Sometimes, they say, she yells
at the televised image of her former friend and Pentagon colleague,
Linda Tripp, who after taping hours of her late-night confidences
is at the very top of her enemies list.
</P>
<P>
   Also prominently featured there is her former lawyer, William
Ginsburg, who sometimes embarrassed her with his public comments.
Another friend said she regrets having posed for a seductive Vanity
Fair photo spread and blames Ginsburg for pushing her to do it.
Neither, of course, was she thrilled with his comments to reporters
that she would ``tend to embellish.'' In the end it was Ms.
Lewinsky herself who made the decision to fire him.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, however, is apparently not counted as an
adversary. One friend said, ``It's pretty obvious she cared about
this man, and it's also pretty obvious he cared about her. Somebody
doesn't get that kind of access to the White House if they're not
wanted.'' Now, the friend said, she has ``mixed feelings'' of hurt
along with respect. Clinton has denied he had any sexual
relationship with her, and some of his supporters have suggested
she only fantasized a liaison with him.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Ms. Lewinsky's friends talked, none for attribution,
about her isolated existence, holed up in the Watergate apartment
she shares with her mother, Marcia Lewis. They said she worries
about the future. Sometimes she has trouble sleeping. And she has
been hurt by former acquaintances who exploited their friendship.
On occasion, they said, she breaks down and cries for her
interrupted life.
</P>
<P>
   But they also said she has never seen herself as anyone's
victim, and described her as a savvy and self-confident woman
worlds tougher than she has been portrayed. Just turned 25, the
one-time White House intern has the steel to wade through a press
gaggle without ever dropping her smile. And she is game enough to
sneak out in a wig and sunglasses in return for the freedom of a
run through Washington's Rock Creek Park.
</P>
<P>
   The single biggest misconception about Ms. Lewinsky in her own
mind, friends said, is the notion that she is enjoying any of the
circus that has surrounded her since allegations of an affair with
the President first broke in January.
</P>
<P>
   To fill her days in Washington, where she has few friends and
has largely stayed confined to her apartment, she walks on a
treadmill, reads voraciously and knits an endless series of
scarves. She favors romance and mystery novels, including ``Point
of Origin'' by Patricia Cornwell, whose work chronicles the
exploits of a medical examiner who has had a tumultuous affair with
a married official in the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky also reads several newspapers regularly and watches
a massive amount of television, mostly news shows obsessed with her
case, though her mother has tried to get her to stop watching.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't dare to use the in-house gym in the Watergate, and
sends others out to pick up anything she needs to avoid setting off
a press frenzy. When her mother, who is her closest confidante,
recently married a New York businessman, R. Peter Straus, at a tiny
ceremony in New York, Ms. Lewinsky did not feel she should attend
because of the attention she might draw.
</P>
<P>
   She is afraid to call friends because she believes her phone is
tapped _ especially since a couple of those she has called soon
found themselves talking to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   But she has had some lighter moments, too, particularly in Los
Angeles, where the press has been less attentive. She spent much of
the summer on the West Coast, living with her father, a radiation
oncologist in Beverly Hills, and her younger brother, a student at
Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh. And in Los Angeles, she
was able to resume some semblance of a normal life, going shopping,
catching a few movies, and relaxing at a family friend's pool.
Sometimes, she makes dark jokes about her predicament.
</P>
<P>
   And on occasion, she even allows herself to speak about the
future, and her old dream of attending graduate school in
psychology or social sciences. At a small dinner two weeks ago at a
restaurant in Brentwood, where her father lives, she said that for
her 25th birthday, what she wanted most was to get her life back.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, when she is not in disguise, strangers sometimes feel
free to give her a hug and a few words of encouragement. Others
apparently cannot quite believe she exists outside the television
world in which she is endlessly shown going through revolving doors
and getting in and out of cars. At a Los Angeles clothing store
recently, a shopper approached her and said, ``I'll bet people tell
you all the time you look just like Monica Lewinsky.'' Said her
companion, ``You know, they do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
