<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gingrich leads trip for peace in Ireland
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Speaker Newt Gingrich will lead a 28-person
contingent of House members, spouses and staff on a taxpayer-funded
trip to Ireland today that will focus on the peace process in
Northern Ireland _ and, to a lesser extent, the speaker's roots.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Gingrich's controversial trip to Israel in the
spring, when he criticized Clinton administration policy in the
Middle East, Gingrich's Ireland visit will lend support to the
president, who helped broker an agreement between Catholic and
Protestant groups in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message is the U.S. legislative leadership supports the
process 100 percent,'' said Rep. James Walsh (R-N.Y.), one of seven
House members who will make the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to visit Ireland next month. His 1995 trip
to British-ruled Northern Ireland was a symbolic boost to efforts
to end the sectarian violence there.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's weeklong visit includes two days in Belfast, where he
will meet with leaders of Sinn Fein, the political wing of the
Irish Republican Army, and other Catholic and Protestant leaders.
``That is clearly the most important aspect of the trip,'' Walsh
said.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker appeared at a hastily arranged performance by cast
members of the Irish revue ``Riverdance'' outside the Capitol on
Thursday. He declined requests to show off his dance steps, but
reaffirmed his support for the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   While in Belfast, the delegation is expected to work on two
houses being built by Habitat for Humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's first visit to Ireland also will take him to Donegal,
where the speaker will try to trace his maternal ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule leaves ample room for sightseeing, including a tour
of Trinity College in Dublin and a visit to Kilkenny Castle.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the members, six of whom will be accompanied by
their spouses, three Gingrich staffers, three other congressional
staffers, five military aides, House Sergeant-at-Arms Bill
Livingood, House Parliamentarian Charles Johnson, a security
officer and a Navy physician also will make the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Christina Martin, Gingrich's spokeswoman and a member of the
traveling party, said Livingood is accompanying the speaker for
security reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the third-ranking constitutional officer of the United
States travels outside the country, security is always an issue,''
Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's usual complement of plainclothes Capitol Police
officers is prohibited by law from making international trips.
</P>
<P>
   As is customary, the group will use a government plane and have
U.S. diplomats at their disposal
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
