</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-CONTEMPT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL VOTES TO CHARGE RENO WITH CONTEMPT OF CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (removes `political' from lede; inserts new material, about Reno's
order for a 30-day review, after 3rd graf; pick up original 4th _
now 6th _ graf ``The prevailing view...'')  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A House committee voted along party lines Thursday
to charge Attorney General Janet Reno with contempt of Congress,
transforming into a criminal case the battle over whether an
independent counsel should be appointed to investigate and
prosecute campaign finance abuses.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is Reno's refusal to give the committee reports on the
issue from the top Justice Department investigators: FBI Director
Louis Freeh and Charles La Bella, former chief of the department's
task force on campaign finance. They testified Tuesday that their
memorandums argued that the law required Reno to ask a special
court to name an independent counsel in the investigation of
Democratic fund raising in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans on the committee, the House Committee on
Government Reform and Oversight, have demanded that Reno seek an
independent counsel, but she has adamantly and repeatedly declined
to do so.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, in a decision that was not publicly disclosed,
Reno ordered a formal 30-day review of what government officials
described as a previously unexamined campaign finance issue that
could ultimately lead the attorney general to refer the tangle of
political finance issues to an independent prosecutor. The
officials would not disclose the nature of the accusations under
review or the identity of the subject of the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of Reno's decision seemed at odds with her public
refusal _ reiterated Thursday _ to seek an independent prosecutor
and her willingness to battle Congress in an effort to keep
lawmakers from obtaining the investigative memos.
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing view in the Capitol on Thursday was that an
accommodation would be reached and that the contempt issue would be
resolved before it reached prosecution. Congress often threatens
contempt proceedings, but no top government official has ever been
prosecuted on such a charge. Compromises have always been found
first.
</P>
<P>
   The vote Thursday _ with 24 Republicans in favor of contempt and
18 Democrats and Rep. Bernard Sanders of Vermont, an Independent,
opposed _ came at the end of a four-hour meeting infected with
partisan acrimony and personal animosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we believe that the attorney general is not following the
law, then we have a responsibility to find out why,'' declared Rep.
Dan Burton, R-Ind., the committee chairman.
</P>
<P>
   But the committee's top Democrat, Henry Waxman of California,
accused Burton of a ``blatant strong-arm tactic'' and said that his
request for the investigators' memorandums was ``ludicrous on the
merits.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference after the vote, Reno accused the committee
of tampering politically with a criminal investigation. She gave no
indication that she would ever comply with the subpoena for the
memorandums.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Representatives will not take up the matter until
after a four-week recess that begins Friday. If a majority of the
House votes for contempt, the matter will go to the Justice
Department for prosecution. Under an 1857 law, refusal to cooperate
with a congressional committee is punishable by up to one year in
prison and a fine of up to $1,000.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   House committees have voted twice to cite Cabinet officers for
contempt for refusing to turn over documents. But these cases _
involving Secretary of State Henry Kissinger in 1975 and Interior
Secretary James Watt in 1982 _ were dropped after compromises were
reached.
</P>
<P>
   The full House voted to charge Environmental Protection Agency
Administrator Anne Gorsuch Burford with contempt in 1983, but this
case was also dropped before prosecution after lawmakers were given
access to the documents they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Burton has made clear that he would withdraw the subpoena for
the Freeh and La Bella memorandums if Reno asked for an independent
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The Burton committee appears to be on solid legal ground. Courts
have ruled repeatedly over the years that Executive Branch must
comply with congressional subpoenas unless the committee issuing
the subpoena lacks jurisdiction or the president asserts executive
privilege.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, there is no question of jurisdiction, and no claim
of executive privilege has been brought.
</P>
<P>
   But the wisdom of the subpoena and the contempt citation is
another matter. At her news conference Thursday, Reno said that
important principles were at stake. ``The department cannot do its
duty if it is subjected to a process that can only shake public
confidence in our ability to make law-enforcement decisions free of
political pressure,'' she asserted. ``And it cannot perform the way
it should if required to submit internal memoranda to political
scrutiny in a manner that can only squelch candid, honest, open
advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Freeh and La Bella pleaded with the committee not to
demand access to their memorandums. Release of the documents, La
Bella said, would be ``devastating to the investigations.''
</P>
<P>
   Waxman played a videotape Thursday of that portion of the Freeh
and La Bella testimony. ``They're telling us that releasing the La
Bella memo would provide a road map to their case,'' Waxman said,
``and the chairman pays no attention to them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Burton was unswayed. He said: ``I understand their concerns.
I know why they fell that way. Under normal circumstances, we would
not have subpoenaed them. But these are not normal circumstances.
We have a reasonable basis for believing that the attorney general
isn't upholding the law, and we have an obligation under the
Constitution to find out if that is the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton insisted that ``the documents are not for public
consumption'' and that the committee would would be careful to keep
them confidential.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has said all along that she had not ruled out seeking an
independent counsel and would so if she received compelling new
evidence. In her recent statements, she has left a vague impression
that the La Bella memorandum, given to her July 16, might give her
the opportunity to reconsider her decision.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, she asked for three weeks to review La Bella's
document, 94 pages with a foot-thick stack of exhibits attached.
After that, she told Burton, she would brief him privately on the
contents of the memorandum and testify publicly if he wished.
</P>
<P>
   Burton was not satisfied. He said: ``The August recess is coming
up, and we'll be rushing to finish up in September. I'm not
inclined to leave this matter unresolved. At any rate, the attorney
general has given no indication that she is willing to be any more
forthcoming in September than she is today.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, the contempt vote Thursday reflected the frustration of
Burton and his fellow Republicans over the obstacles they have
faced in their campaign finance investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has been less than fully cooperative.
More than 100 witnesses have fled the country or asserted their
Fifth Amendment right against compelled self-incrimination. And
just last month, there were indications that Sen. Fred Thompson,
R-Tenn., had access to the Freeh memorandum that was being withheld
from Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dennis Hastert of Illinois expressed these frustrations.
``This committee has been shut out,'' he declared. ``Day in and day
out, week in and week out, month in and month out, year in and year
out. It's time to change the pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Shadegg of Arizona, a former prosecutor, accused Reno
of ``prosecutorial malpractice'' and ``incompetence.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats maintained that the investigation had been
crippled by the partisan spirit in which Burton and his committee
operated. ``The whole thing is about embarrassing the attorney
general,'' said Rep. Thomas Barrett of Wisconsin. ``It's not about
justice. It's not about the seeking of truth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
