u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-BANK-BAILOUT-4     08-06 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-BANK-BAILOUT-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S DEBATE ON BANKS GETS NASTY 
</HEADLINE>
 (js) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A six-month discussion about Mexico's $62 billion
bank bailout has suddenly turned into a national brawl.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition politicians are accusing pro-government businessmen
of enriching themselves at public expense, while government
officials are warning that the debate is degenerating into a witch
hunt.
</P>
<P>
   The debate began when President Ernesto Zedillo proposed that
vast debts from the government's rescue be assumed by the Mexican
Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   The widening confrontation of recent days led to opposition
demands for an investigation into the financing of Zedillo's 1994
campaign as well as to threats of lawsuits by wealthy bankers who
say they have been unjustly accused of financial wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts are calling the debate a watershed in Mexico's
political life.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time powerful forces, including the opposition
parties in control of the lower house of Congress, are demanding a
thorough airing of the cozy dealings between government officials
and the circle of wealthy industrialists and bankers who finance
Zedillo's Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   The latest battles flared on Monday, when the leftist Party of
the Democratic Revolution, or PRD, made public a list of 310
people, including several billionaires, characterizing them as
beneficiaries of the bank rescue that followed the 1994 peso
devaluation, though the party acknowledged that in many cases its
information was sketchy.
</P>
<P>
   Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador, the PRD president, said the party
pieced the list together from people in the banking and business
worlds after the government cited bank secrecy laws for refusing to
provide details of the bailout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been asking for information, bank by bank and file by
file, but the executive has refused,'' Lopez Obrador said at a news
conference. ``If this was a matter between two private parties,
where one owes and the other is trying to collect, we wouldn't care
about knowing secrets. But any attempt to make the debt of a
handful of private people public makes full information
indispensable.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the government contends that the bailout was aimed
at supporting ordinary depositors by saving the banks, but it
acknowledges that the banks cannot collect some very large loans
made to wealthy people, some of them bankers themselves, on the
basis of their reputations, and without collateral.
</P>
<P>
   The PRD's defiant action has provoked angry criticism from the
government and its supporters.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Officials at the bank rescue program, the Fund for Bank Savings
Protection, immediately attacked the PRD list as inaccurate and
sloppy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This list does not agree with the information that exists in
our databases,'' the fund said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department's spokesman, Marco Provencio, said at a
news conference that the PRD's tactics were similar to Sen. Joseph
McCarthy's demagogic use of a list of supposed Communists in
Washington in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican Bankers Association published full-page
advertisements in newspapers, expressing concern about the
``radicalization of positions,'' and the PRI issued a statement
calling publication of the list ``political impertinence.''
</P>
<P>
   Central to the showdown is the government's argument that while
it wants to inform the Congress fully about the bank rescue, and
has already made available 8,000 pages of documentation, it cannot
share the names of people whose unpaid loans have been assumed by
the fund. Mexico's bank secrecy laws prohibit such identification,
the government says.
</P>
<P>
   But the government has a history of enormous flexibility in
interpreting, and reinterpreting, statutes in ways convenient for
the PRI and its supporters. Given that, opposition leaders and some
independent analysts have characterized the government's legal
arguments as tactics to protect inappropriate transactions from
scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now, the tight alliance between the government and the
economic elite permitted that the most powerful industrial groups
could do almost whatever they wanted, as long as they did it within
a framework of support for the official party,'' Jonathan Heath, a
prominent private economist, wrote in a newspaper column on
Thursday. ``The publication of the list by the PRD, despite its
inaccuracies, has broken that taboo.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the debate has begun to challenge longstanding relations
between government officials and wealthy supporters, ``it is
marking a watershed in our political system,'' Heath said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
