<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPOS COMPLETE SWEEP OF DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The Dodgers' season did not end Thursday afternoon
with a 9-0 loss to the Montreal Expos.
</P>
<P>
   It might have ended two days earlier when they blew a four-run
lead in the eighth inning and lost in 10.
</P>
<P>
   There are games every year that players remember as the turning
point, a yardstick that can be used to measure greatness or to wrap
a team across the knuckles.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros wasn't about to say getting swept in three games by
the lowly Expos was the Dodgers' last stand. He knows the wild-card
race means never having to say you're lousy.
</P>
<P>
   But he remembered a bad game last season that seemed to have a
haunting ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in Texas, where we had a 12-7 lead in the ninth and
lost,'' said Karros, remembering when the Dodgers were beaten 13-12
by the Rangers. ``The routs aren't as bad as the ones you let get
away. People point to the Giants series (a sweep Sept. 17-18), but
we just never were the same after that loss in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Karros said the 1997 Dodgers, who finished two games behind San
Francisco in the West, didn't know they were doomed at the time,
just as it might be a week or two before they can assess the damage
of this series with the Expos.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their disappointing performance, the Dodgers' 4-6 trip
cost them only one game to the wild-card leading Chicago Cubs in
the 10 days. Getting whacked by nine runs to a team 30 games out of
first place puts them six games behind the idle Cubs with 47 to
play.
</P>
<P>
   And though they face the mighty Braves next weekend, the
Dodgers' next six games are against two of the league's worst
teams, Pittsburgh and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like when you're a kid and you get your butt whipped,''
second baseman Eric Young said. ``You're supposed to learn
something from it. We'll see what we've learned.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield returns from his three-game suspension tonight
against the Pirates. Sheffield and Pittsburgh catcher Jason Kendall
were involved in a June 28 brawl that led to the suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi, sidelined Thursday with more lower back pain, will
be examined today and is not expected to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think once we get Mondesi and Sheffield back, we'll be
OK,'' said Karros, who made outs to end three innings after doing
it four times Wednesday night. ``And if you look at the wild card,
I still think we are in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   But the last three games also looked very similar to 1991, when
the Dodgers were swept in four games at Olympic Stadium to begin
the second half. The Braves were in third place at the time, but
they picked up four games in the standings and wound up winning the
National League West on the next-to-last day of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In front of 11,791 on Thursday, the Dodgers were shut down by
right-hander Jeremy Powell (1-1), who was making only his third
major-league start.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a first-inning single by Trenidad Hubbard and a
sixth-inning base hit by Young, the Dodgers hopped on the team
plane a couple hours early.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos, on the other hand, have gone 7-4 in their past 11
games _ against San Diego, San Francisco and the Dodgers, the three
top teams in the West.
</P>
<P>
   And they have done it without center fielder Rondell White, who
went on the disabled list July 21 with a fractured right ring
finger. White's replacement, Terry Jones, went 2 for 4 Thursday
with a three-run double off Darren Hall that broke the game open in
the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the expectations are different here than they are with
the Dodgers,'' said Expos first baseman Ryan McGuire, a product of
El Camino Real High and UCLA. ``But this is a place for
opportunity. Rondell went down and Vladimir Guerrero (NL Player of
the Month) had an incredible July. Then we had the big trade. But
we don't get down, we just keep moving.''
</P>
<P>
   McGuire was referring to last Friday's seven-player swap that
sent left-hander Carlos Perez and shortstop Mark Grudzielanek to
the Dodgers for Wilton Guerrero and three prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Perez (7-11) started Thursday against his former team and said
he was very nervous after pitching seven scoreless innings against
the Mets last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs in the fourth, Perez allowed a two-run double to
catcher Bob Henley, who played at Double-A in 1997 before a
concussion ended his season. Mike Mordecai, once a promising
infielder with the Braves, followed with a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how it is done here,'' said Grudzielanek, who went 2
for 13 in the series. ``They play well against the good teams up
here. You always wanted to prove yourself against the Dodgers and
the Braves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
