<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONICA LEWINSKY TESTIFIES FOR SIX AND A HALF HOURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also CLINTON-REPUBS and CLINTON-LEWINSKY)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(lh) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr. and JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ending months of anticipation with a resigned
shrug, Monica Lewinsky, the former intern, walked into a federal
courthouse here Thursday and testified that she and President
Clinton carried on a sexual affair within the White House,
according to a lawyer familiar with her account.
</P>
<P>
   Her testimony before a federal grand jury, which contradicted a
previous sworn statement, tightened the legal and political vise
squeezing President Clinton. The president denied a sexual
relationship under oath in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct
lawsuit, and he has denied it as well to the American people.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr, the independent prosecutor, is investigating
charges that Clinton lied under oath and obstructed justice by
trying to conceal the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   More than six months of waiting for Ms. Lewinsky to tell her
story ended just before 8:30 a.m., when she stepped from a dark
green Toyota Land Cruiser, embraced a lawyer, shrugged and vanished
inside. As portable generators rumbled in the background and one
cameraman swept the scene from a cherrypicker 50 feet over 3rd
Street, about 20 satellite trucks beamed images of Ms. Lewinsky _
once an unpaid, anonymous sorter of White House mail _ around the
planet.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky, 25, answered questions in exchange for immunity
from prosecution for any wrongdoing she describes. In a deal worked
out with prosecutors nine days ago, she is vulnerable to
prosecution only if she lies in her testimony. In an affidavit in
January in the Jones case, Ms. Lewinsky swore that she did not have
a sexual relationship with the president.
</P>
<P>
   An associate of Ms. Lewinsky's described her six and a half
hours before the grand jury as grueling. ``She was asked very
specific questions about very private matters which are very hard
to discuss in public,'' the associate said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ms. Lewinsky has agonized for months over the prospect
of damaging Clinton's presidency, friends have said. One of her
friends described Ms. Lewinsky as saying Wednesday night, as she
prepared for her testimony, ``What I'm doing tomorrow is something
I never ever wanted to do. It breaks my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Before another media mob scene after Ms. Lewinsky completed her
testimony, her spokeswoman, Judy Smith, said that she answered
questions from prosecutors and jurors ``truthfully, completely, and
honestly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica and her family are relieved that this ordeal finally
appears to be coming to an end,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has never publicly described his relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky in any detail, beyond saying that it was not sexual.
</P>
<P>
   In a capital whipsawed between disclosure and denial, starkly
different days unspooled at the federal courthouse and the White
House. Summoning the authority and trappings of his office, as well
as his own storied political resilience, President Clinton went
about his official duties Thursday without betraying a hint of
interest in his former intern's testimony just a few blocks down
Pennsylvania Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have looked forward to this day for quite a long time,''
Clinton said in one speech at a Washington hotel, referring to his
opportunity to address a White House conference on building
economic self-improvement in Indian communities.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, the president appeared before a row of
uniformed police officers in the sun-gilded Rose Garden to call for
a permanent five-day waiting period for people seeking to buy
handguns. With a quick left-handed salute after the official
remarks, the president cued a brassy Marine band to strike up
``Stars and Stripes Forever.'' Reporters waiting to shout questions
about Ms. Lewinsky were stymied.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some White House advisers gave vent to frustration over the
media spectacle at the courthouse and the unremitting pressure of
the Lewinsky investigation. ``I hate the whole thing,'' said one.
``I hate you, I hate us.'' Then, in his disgust, words failed him.
``Uggh,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Toiv, a White House spokesman, provided the official
reaction to the testimony. ``The president has not expressed any
views to us on this,'' he said, ``except we know that he does agree
with us _ and probably all Americans _ that if this means that
we're coming to the end of this four-year, over $40 million
investigation, then that would be a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Another official said that the White House had no interest in
drawing attention Thursday. ``We're showing wise restraint,'' he
said. ``Nobody's going to criticize Ms. Lewinsky, and we're not
going to get in the story. It's a big enough story without us.''
</P>
<P>
   For all their restraint, White House advisers telephoned
reporters late Thursday evening to ask what they knew of Ms.
Lewinsky's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Ms. Lewinsky's version of her relationship with
the president was still in doubt. But Starr's investigation has
rushed forward since then, with her immunity agreement and
Clinton's own promise to testify at the White House on Aug. 17. In
striking the deal with Starr, Ms. Lewinsky also turned over a navy
blue dress that prosecutors have sent for testing by the Federal
Bureau of Investigation. They are trying to determine if the dress
stained in a sexual encounter with the president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
