u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRYSLER-DAIMLER-NYT &LR;      08-06 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRYSLER-DAIMLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRYSLER'S CHIEF WILL FARE QUITE WELL IN DAIMLER MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del.)   (af)  
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether the merger of Chrysler and Daimler-Benz succeeds or not,
Robert J. Eaton, Chrysler's chairman and chief executive, is
guaranteed to do well, documents released by the companies showed
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   To persuade Eaton, 58, to stay on for three years under the
combined DaimlerChrysler, he can earn nine extra years on his
pension _ in addition to the three he would earn anyway. Those nine
extra years alone are worth $30,000 a month for the rest of his
life.
</P>
<P>
   But if he quits or is dismissed during the two years after the
merger, he will be paid $24.4 million, with DaimlerChrysler paying
the ``golden parachute'' tax for him and the taxes on the
compensation paid to cover the tax.
</P>
<P>
   And he will also get stock appreciation rights on 2.27 million
shares of DaimlerChrysler, a benefit worth almost $23 million for
each $10 rise in the price of the company's shares.
</P>
<P>
   Severance benefits and stock appreciation rights were also
issued to 29 other Chrysler executives, but only Eaton was given
the pension sweetener.
</P>
<P>
   The pay plans were disclosed in a filing with the Securities and
Exchange Commission by the the No. 3 United States auto maker and
the German luxury-car company in anticipation of closing their
merger in November.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler has scheduled a special shareholder meeting for Sept.
18 in Wilmington, Del., to vote on the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Investors will be issued DaimlerChrysler shares, which will
trade on exchanges around the world, including the New York Stock
Exchange. Each Chrysler share will be exchanged for 0.6235 share of
DaimlerChrysler. A holder of 100 Chrysler shares would be issued 62
shares of the new company and a cash payment for the difference,
the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   Daimler-Benz shareholders will exchange shares on a one-for-one
basis unless 90 percent swap their shares for DaimlerChrysler
stock, in which case they will receive a bonus of one-half of a
percent, giving them 1.005 shares of DaimlerChrysler for each
Daimler-Benz share. That bonus is so small that either way,
Daimler-Benz shareholders will have 58 percent of the new company
and Chrysler shareholders the remaining 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of how the global economy will make life more
complicated for investors, the two companies said that Americans
who hold DaimlerChrysler shares would also face new tax
complications. One-quarter of each dividend payment will be
withheld to pay German taxes, but by filing a German tax form most
of the tax can be refunded, the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   The merger highlights key differences in the compensation styles
of German and American companies.
</P>
<P>
   No compensation details were disclosed for Jurgen Schrempp, the
chairman of Daimler-Benz, and the nine other top executives there
because their compensation packages are not being changed by the
deal. Schrempp was paid no more than $2 million last year, compared
with $6.1 million in salary, bonus, incentive pay and other cash
for Eaton, who also made $5.3 million from exercising stock
options.
</P>
<P>
   When the merger is complete, Eaton will also receive $66.2
million in DaimlerChrysler stock in exchange for Chrysler options
of the same value, and $3.7 million in cash, the bonus he earned
for the first 11 months of the year under Chrysler's pay plan.
</P>
<P>
   Chris P. Theodore, a vice president for engineering at Chrysler,
said that he and colleagues were joking recently about how they
hope compensation changes after the merger. ``What we said was: `We
have a great idea. We'll have Daimler vacation policy and Chrysler
pay policy,' '' Theodore said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
