A1976 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLOBE-COLUMNIST-2TAKE     08-06 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-COLUMNIST-2TAKES(1150)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBE COLUMNIST REFUSES TO RESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe and columnist Mike Barnicle found themselves at
a standoff Thursday, with the newspaper continuing to demand his
resignation and Barnicle declining to provide it.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper spokesman Rick Gulla said management had not fired
him, but still wanted him to step down.
</P>
<P>
   As the two sides continued their delicate dance, newsroom
employees reeled over the allegation that Barnicle had plagiarized
some material from a book by comedian George Carlin and had then
been less than truthful when questioned about it by the newspaper's
top editors.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute between the paper and one its star columnists came
barely two months after another Globe columnist, Patricia Smith,
was forced to resign after she admitted fabricating characters in
some of her columns. And it comes in a year in which several other
publications and a television network have had to retract
controversial stories deemed to have been inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   An e-mail message to the staff from Globe Editor Matthew Storin,
who was vacationing in Italy, did little to dispel the gloom and
confusion. An executive of The Globe, which is owned by The New
York Times Co., said Thursday night that Globe Publisher Benjamin
Taylor would meet with Barnicle Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   One senior newsroom employee _ who, like most others
interviewed, requested anonymity, _ said: ``People are really
dispirited, they are upset and a lot of people are angry that all
they know about this is from what they've read in the paper. It's
like the second death in the family in six weeks and the head of
the family hasn't got time to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   In attempting to force out Barnicle, the Globe has taken on one
of the last in a breed of powerful big-city newspaper columnists.
While he has his critics, Barnicle has built a reputation for
speaking for the working-class neighborhoods of Boston. Calls and
e-mail messages to the newspaper on Thursday were heavily in his
favor.
</P>
<P>
   His supporters contended that newspaper management was trying to
sacrifice him in a misguided attempt at fairness, that his offense
was not on a par with the admitted fabrications that led to the
forced resignation of Ms. Smith in June.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle, 55, is white and close to what Globe insiders call the
paper's ``Irish mafia.'' Ms. Smith, 42, is black and was brought to
the Globe by Storin, who was her editor at The Chicago Sun Times.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Barnicle's colleagues, however, supported Storin's
decision to ask for Barnicle's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talk radio chat has been, `Oh, this was a tit-for-tat
firing, a white columnist to make up for firing a black one,'''
said one newsroom employee who requested anonymity. ``But we know
and he knows, I think, deep down that we are a profession and we
have to have standards.''
</P>
<P>
   In between writing two to three columns a week, Barnicle has
often been among the guests at the wakes of his colleagues' parents
or slain policemen. He gave his Red Sox tickets to janitors and
telephone operators at the Globe. In print, he made a name with
two-fisted prose attacks.
</P>
<P>
   In one 1988 column he wrote, ``The people who dish out beatings,
robberies and rapes too often are not afraid of the police and
certainly do not fear the courts.'' And he added, ``A jail term is
too far down the road to be a factor in the daily life of a
maggot.''
</P>
<P>
   But while he rose to prominence, he also gave the impression of
bending the rules that bound his colleagues and ignoring criticism
that some of his quotes and characters were too good to be true.
</P>
<P>
   An early example came in 1979, six years after he was hired at
the Globe. A former political speechwriter, Barnicle was invited on
a congressional trip to Southeast Asia and offered to write about
it for the paper. According to Barnicle, the Globe declined.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle took vacation time and went on the trip anyway, writing
articles for James Bellows, then the editor of The Los Angeles
Herald Examiner. One of those articles ended up on the front page
of The Boston Herald American, the Globe's arch-rival, according to
both men.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the competition is forbidden by most newspapers. In
an interview earlier this week, before the latest furor, Barnicle
said, ``That was back in the time when we took ourselves far less
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle's flouting of that professional convention in the late
1970s was matched in the mid-1990s by his willingness to flout the
convention that there should be no smoking in a no-smoking
building. Barnicle said he smoked cigars in his office and welcomed
other smokers there.
</P>
<P>
   But it was his refusal to address criticisms of his work that
most concerned his colleagues. In 1991, Boston Magazine examined
one of Barnicle's articles and could find no evidence that two
characters in it ever existed. In the article, Barnicle was quoted
as telling the reporter that he had given one of the people he had
written about the magazine's telephone number. ``If he wants to
talk to you, he'll call you,'' he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   A year earlier, attorney Alan Dershowitz had accused Barnicle of
falsely attributing a racist quote to him. Neither Barnicle nor the
Globe retracted the column, but in a confidential legal settlement
reached after his complaint, the Globe agreed to pay Dershowitz
$75,000, according to a lawyer who has been briefed on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to police reporting, ``it's safe to say ...
Barnicle has a reputation for having an unusual high level of
access'' to police sources, said Alfred S. Larkin Jr., a former
managing editor who is now the Globe's vice president and assistant
to the publisher.
</P>
<P>
   One story that Barnicle based on sources, however, came under
heavy criticism. In early 1990, Barnicle had been leading the
coverage of Charles Stuart, a Boston man who shot and killed his
pregnant wife, blamed the shooting on a black man, then jumped to
his death from a bridge.
</P>
<P>
   While most of his reporting proved solid, Barnicle wrote one
article no other reporter could confirm. Under a banner headline,
he reported that the Prudential Insurance Co. had issued a check
for $480,000 to Stuart, in payment of a life insurance policy for
his wife, Carol DeMaiti Stuart. The day the article ran, the
company denied it. No similar check has been found. The Globe,
which has occasionally corrected other facts in Barnicle's columns
over the years, ran no correction.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Moore, the Globe's managing editor, said last week, ``Our
reporting on the Carol Stuart case after Charles Stuart committed
suicide still stands, except for the $480,000 check. I don't think
anyone involved in that case thinks we shouldn't have corrected
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle said of the incident, ``Three different people told me
about the check.'' Was it worth correcting? ``No. It had nothing to
do with Chuck going off the bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   But it fueled the pervasive sense that Barnicle operated by his
own set of rules.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When in late 1995, Walter Robinson, who was running the Globe's
Metro desk, brought to the top editors evidence of his suspicions
that Patricia Smith had been fabricating characters in 27 columns,
the issue of Barnicle's reputation quickly became part of the
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was dealing with a number of different factors,'' Storin
said in an interview last month. ``There were the rumors and
rumblings about Barnicle, none of them proven.''
</P>
<P>
   If Ms. Smith had been confronted with her alleged fabrications
in 1995, Storin said last month, the issue of Barnicle would
inevitably have been raised. ``If we had to dismiss her in that
time frame, then Barnicle would be caught up in the wake of that
and I wasn't sure if I could save him, even if the charges had been
unfounded,'' Storin said. ``He and the paper had been a little
dismissive and a little arrogant about the charges, unfair as they
were.''
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the choice of enforcing journalistic standards on Ms.
Smith, at the risk of seeming unfair, or choosing an approach they
believed would be fair to all, Storin and his top editors agreed
that the three Metro columnists _ Barnicle, Ms. Smith, and Eileen
McNamara _ would be informed about the paper's standards of
accuracy and that their columns would be spot-checked from time to
time.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday evening, a reader called The Globe asking about the
similarities between Barnicle's column and Carlin's book. Two days
later, the paper asked for Barnicle's resignation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
