<HEADLINE>
UNITED HEALTHCARE TAKING A $900 MILLION CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Ky., N.Y., N.J., Conn.)  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW and REED ABELSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Proving that few, if any, companies are immune to the financial
perils facing health care providers, the United Healthcare Corp.,
one of the nation's largest health maintenance organizations, said
Thursday that it was taking a $900 million charge in its second
quarter, in part to abandon unprofitable Medicare plans.
</P>
<P>
   The move ignited an investor stampede out of health care stocks
and possibly jeopardized United Healthcare's proposed $5.5 billion
merger with its rival, Humana Inc., which would create the nation's
largest HMO.
</P>
<P>
   Worse still, United Healthcare's announcement, unexpected by
Wall Street analysts and investors, raised serious questions as to
whether HMOs can make money covering Medicare patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``People seem to forget that Medicare was created because
private insurers could not make money on the elderly population,''
said Diane Archer, executive director of the Medicare Rights
Center, a consumer organization in New York. ``Now managed-care
plans are discovering the same lesson all over again and are
getting out.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts think that many people on Medicare will not be
affected. But the company did not give details about which markets
it might leave or how it might change its coverage. Analysts said
that the most vulnerable markets were those where United Healthcare
does not have enough enrollees to negotiate steep discounts with
hospitals and doctors. For example, Utah is nearly devoid of
managed-care coverage for people on Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   While United Healthcare had said it would realign its
operations, few analysts expected the scope to be so broad or the
write-off, covering future Medicare losses and its exit from some
markets, so steep. Having watched many of its competitors like
Oxford Health Plans stumble, United Healthcare, based in
Minneapolis, had emerged as Wall Street's best hope for managed
care.
</P>
<P>
   The company's chairman and chief executive, William McGuire, was
well liked and viewed as having a strong grasp of the fundamental
issues of managed care. ``They were and supposedly are the best in
the industry,'' said Larry Feinberg of Oracle Partners, a New York
hedge fund that specializes in health care.
</P>
<P>
   That belief was largely shattered when the company revealed the
reorganization charge as the cause of its $565 million loss in the
second quarter. United Healthcare said that the company's
continuing operations remained profitable, with its commercial
business remaining robust, but acknowledged that it could not
afford to cover Medicare patients in some areas. The company said
it was losing money in two-thirds of the 24 markets where it
provides care to people on Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medicare is clearly our largest disappointment,'' McGuire
said. The company also said it was leaving several commercial
markets as well.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, who were caught completely off guard by the news,
immediately fled the stock, dumping many other health care stocks
in their wake. United Healthcare plunged $15, or 28.4 percent, to
$37.875. Humana dropped $6.625, or 25.7 percent, to $19.125.
Pacificare Health Systems fell $5.375, to $63.75, and Wellpoint
Health Networks dropped $1.6875, to $56.25.
</P>
<P>
   With health care stocks tumbling, and with United Healthcare
indicating that it was rethinking its aggressive push into the
Medicare market, analysts questioned the fate of United
Healthcare's pending acquisition of Humana. A spokeswoman for
United Healthcare said Thursday that the deal was still progressing
on schedule, but Humana, based in Louisville, Ky., was not so
enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the announcement was made public, Humana, which
received no warning of United Healthcare's write-off, released a
terse statement saying it would not comment on the charge until it
discussed the matter with United Healthcare executives.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   McGuire said Thursday during a meeting with analysts that
federal and state regulatory review of the merger was continuing
and that the shareholder vote was expected at the end of this
month. Asked about Humana's statement, he refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the stock prices so low, the acquisition may be
renegotiated,'' said Linda Varoli, an analyst with Merger Insight.
``Humana's board of directors has a responsibility to their
shareholders. They may want more assurances from United Healthcare
or get more considerations from them in the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   And much of the merger's appeal is Humana's strong presence in
the Medicare market, although McGuire emphasized that United's
losses were caused by the start-up nature of its programs.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the acquisition is completed, United Healthcare, which
says it has 1.3 million people in New York, Connecticut and New
Jersey and is an aggressive player in the area, will face questions
about its commitment to Medicare patients. Consumer advocates
clamored Thursday that United Healthcare's move to drop certain
counties was typical given that HMOs tended to put profits in front
of health care.
</P>
<P>
   But McGuire said that United Healthcare was not abandoning this
group. ``We remain committed to serving seniors in a variety of
ways,'' McGuire said Thursday. United Healthcare will re-evaluate
its programs in specific markets to see whether it can generate
what he described as ``acceptable margins.'' Still, the company is
prepared, he said, to leave markets where it cannot make money.
</P>
<P>
   United is the latest managed-care company to stumble in an
attempt to make money serving the Medicare population, and many of
its competitors have decided to withdraw from that market. Oxford
has attributed some of its heavy losses on its Medicare programs in
some areas, and several companies, including Anthem Blue Cross and
Blue Shield and Health Net in California, have recently decided to
throw in the towel.
</P>
<P>
   The economics of serving people on Medicare make it virtually
impossible to make money, said Karen Korn, a health care services
analyst at Putnam Investments in Boston. The government has
approved rate increases for Medicare-managed programs of about 2
percent while medical costs are rising at 4 percent or higher.
``There's no way that translates into OK margins,'' Ms. Korn said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the government's push to have more Medicare members in
managed care, there may be few providers who remain interested in
serving the population. ``We'll see a lot more dropping out of it
than getting into it,'' predicted Barry Barnett, a principal at
Kwasha HR Solutions, a unit of Price Waterhouse Coopers.
</P>
<P>
   But United Healthcare's woes also raise the question of whether
managed care works as a model for the future of health care in
keeping costs under control. While the company's difficulties are
limited to caring for the elderly, it is unclear how successful any
managed-care company will be once it covers more people. The
backlash from consumers, who are increasingly demanding more from
their plans and want more choice of doctors and hospitals, adds to
the difficulty of containing costs. ``You can't make huge margins
in this business long term,'' Feinberg argued.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of Thursday's announcement on employers, many of whom
are now choosing health plans for their employees, is unclear.
While some benefits consultants said that they thought the news
would have little effect, others said that it would give some
employers pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of managed-care companies believing they can control
health care costs,'' said Todd Richter, a health care analyst at
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``They need to learn how to price
health care. They are insurance companies. And that means they are
in the risk-management business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
