<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-CANDIDATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEC TOLD OF FBI RECORDINGS OF EAST TEXAS CANDIDATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Orange, Texas) 
 
By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
and BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Telephone conversations secretly recorded by the FBI
show that east Texas congressional candidate Brian Babin knew about
the illegal funneling of contributions to his 1996 campaign, a
central figure in the case told the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Babin, a Woodville dentist running this year for the
second time against Democratic U.S. Rep. Jim Turner of Crockett,
has denied knowing about or participating in the illegal donation
of $37,000 through Cloeren Inc., a plastics manufacturer in Orange.
</P>
<P>
   Babin maintained his innocence Thursday, saying that federal
prosecutors would have brought charges against him if the
recordings contained evidence of a crime.
</P>
<P>
   But company owner Peter Cloeren Jr., who is serving two years on
probation and paying a $400,000 fine for his role in the scheme,
says in a complaint to the federal agency that Babin admitted last
February that he had known about the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Cloeren met with Democratic congressional
investigators Thursday in Houston to discuss his allegations, said
a spokesman for U.S. Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   It is ``so rare that you have one of the participants coming
forward. What Mr. Cloeren does moves this from being an allegation
to something specific and concrete,'' Waxman spokesman Phil
Schiliro said.
</P>
<P>
   A draft of Cloeren's complaint to the Federal Election
Commission says that Babin and Cloeren talked on the telephone Feb.
13, a day after both were interviewed by FBI agents.
</P>
<P>
   Babin remarked in the call that he was glad that he and his son
had personally picked up the contribution checks from Cloeren
employees, ``or else the government would have us on mail fraud as
well,'' according to Cloeren.
</P>
<P>
   Babin also expressed concern that a disgruntled Cloeren employee
had exposed the scheme, Cloeren told the FEC.
</P>
<P>
   A consultant for Babin's 1996 campaign, Walter Whetsell of South
Carolina, confirmed in a separate talk with Cloeren that day that
Babin had known about the illegal money transfer, according to
Cloeren.
</P>
<P>
   Babin said Thursday he was unaware until this week that FBI
agents made the recordings after asking Cloeren to make the calls.
</P>
<P>
   He denied making a remark about mail fraud and added that he may
have expressed concern that Cloeren may have been implicated by one
of his own workers.
</P>
<P>
   But, Babin said, he has already been cleared by the federal
prosecutors in Beaumont who brought the charges against Cloeren.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, prosecutors said they have no evidence of wrongdoing by
Babin. They were unavailable for comment Thursday about Cloeren's
complaint to the Federal Election Commission. Whetsell also could
not be reached, and the FEC does not discuss the specifics of the
complaints until they after they are processed.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Cloeren pleaded guilty to using his employees as a
conduit to evade the $1,000-per-person federal limit on
contributions to Babin's campaign. The company used fake travel
vouchers to reimburse employees who wrote checks to Babin,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Babin said Thursday that Cloeren, his former supporter, is
making the allegations out of bitterness about being caught.
</P>
<P>
   Babin also charged that Democrat Turner was manipulating Cloeren
to turn attention away from investigations of alleged fund-raising
violations by the Democratic Party. Turner is a member of the House
Committee on Government Reform and Oversight, which is conducting
hearings on campaign irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   Cloeren said his actions are not personal but are instead part
of the national effort to reform campaign practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prosecuting John Q. Public (himself) doesn't solve this
campaign finance issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He displayed a letter he received from Babin two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could take it all back I would,'' the letter said. ``I
would never have run had I known what would happen to you. I am
sorry. I am very sorry.``
</P>
<P>
   Babin said Thursday he was ``reaching out'' to his former
political supporter rather than apologizing for his own actions.
</P>
<P>
   Cloeren declined to discuss any meetings with congressional
staffers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Waxman, the Democratic congressman from California, on Thursday
urged the chairman of the oversight committee, Republican Dan
Burton of Indiana, to investigate the allegations about Babin.
</P>
<P>
   Waxman noted Cloeren's additional allegation that the Republican
majority whip, Tom DeLay of Texas, participated in discussions
about using Cloeren's money to help Babin in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay has denied wrongdoing
</P>
<P>
   Burton said that while no hearing has been scheduled on
Republican fund-raising groups, the committee has received
documents on Triad Management Services, which allegedly funneled
money from conservatives to key congressional campaigns. Cloeren
contributed to an offshoot of Triad which paid for television
advertisements in 1996 attacking Turner.
</P>
<P>
   Turner and Babin are vying to represent the 2nd Congressional
District, which runs from the northeast border of Harris County to
parts of East Texas and the Louisiana border.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
