<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROBE-LEWINSKY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY TELLS HER STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES AND DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Monica S. Lewinsky, the former White House intern
at the center of a national scandal that has jeopardized the
Clinton presidency, broke nearly seven months of silence Thursday
by testifying before a federal grand jury investigating her
relationship with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky was expected to tell the grand jury that she had a
sexual relationship with Clinton. She was also expected to say she
does not believe he encouraged her to lie under oath, though they
explored ways to keep the relationship a secret, a source close to
the case said.
</P>
<P>
   As the major witness against him finally started detailing the
events in the biggest personal crisis of his presidency, Clinton
tried to go about business as usual. A mile from the federal
courthouse, the president appeared at a Rose Garden ceremony with
gun control activists and later spoke to the Conference on Building
Economic Self-Determination in Indian Communities at the Grand
Hyatt Hotel, a few blocks from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, 25, spent about six hours in the closed grand jury
room and left without a word to the hundreds of journalists and
onlookers camped outside. Her family spokeswoman, Judy Smith, said
only: ``She answered each question truthfully, completely, and
honestly that was posed to her'' by prosecutors and some of the
grand jurors. ``Monica and her family are relieved that this ordeal
finally appears to be coming to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   Plato Cacheris, one of Lewinsky's lawyers, said his client has
not been told if she has to reappear before the grand jury. ``I
think she did a fine job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A relationship that allegedly began in private in a room off the
Oval Office two years ago is being dissected in public _ on radio
and television and in print media across the United States and
around the world. What started out as Internet gossip at the
beginning of this year has evolved into a full-sized scandal, with
Supreme Court rulings, speculation about a presidential apology,
and even talk of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The case goes beyond sex: Independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr
is attempting to put together a case that shows a pattern of lies
and obstruction of justice by the president.
</P>
<P>
   After Thursday's two public appearances, Clinton slipped out of
view for the rest of the day. He spent part of the afternoon with
his attorney, David E. Kendall, to prepare for his grand jury
appearance via closed-circuit television Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Walking out of the Rose Garden, Clinton did not respond to
reporters' shouted questions. The Marine Band struck up ``Stars and
Stripes Forever,'' drowning out the journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Later, deputy White House press secretary Barry Toiv said, ``I
found that music refreshing.''
</P>
<P>
   Toiv, who has followed a policy of saying as little as possible,
described Clinton's mood as ``great.'' Asked how Clinton felt about
Lewinsky finally testifying, Toiv repeated the official White House
line: ``If this means that we're coming to the end of this
four-year, over $40 million investigation, then that would be a
good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, who can shed light on whether Clinton committed
perjury and obstructed justice to hide the affair, arrived at the
US District Courthouse at about 8:30 a.m. under heavy security.
Dressed in a dark blue suit and pearls, Lewinsky gave a nervous hug
to Sydney Jean Hoffman, one of her lawyers, with whom she has
developed a special bond.
</P>
<P>
   Then Lewinsky disappeared through a side door, her legal team
and press spokeswoman in tow. She was whisked away to the third
floor on an elevator normally reserved for judges. She entered the
grand jury room alone; her lawyers had to wait outside.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no word on a navy blue dress belonging to
Lewinsky that the FBI is testing for genetic material that could be
linked to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's testimony followed an agreement reached last week
with Starr for full immunity in exchange for her truthful
testimony. Her mother, Marcia Lewis, also was given full immunity,
and reportedly, so was her father.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky testified amid questions about her credibility from
Clinton's allies and critics alike. In the Paula Jones sexual
harassment lawsuit, Lewinsky signed an affidavit stating she and
the president had never had sexual relations. But Thursday she
reportedly planned to contradict that statement. And in a taped
conversation with her former colleague, Linda R. Tripp, she
portrayed herself as a compulsive liar.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is damaged goods any way you look at it,'' said Laurie
Levenson, a former federal prosecutor and associate dean of the
Loyola Law School in Los Angeles. ``She's given conflicting
stories, and you can't be sure which time she told the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   In such a case, a prosecutor would likely say that a witness
lied because of fear or pressure, Levenson said. But now, the
prosecutor would argue, Lewinsky is telling the truth because she
does not want to jeopardize her immunity agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gloria Allred, president of the Womens Equal Rights Legal
Defense and Education Fund in Los Angeles, said Lewinsky's taped
statements could haunt her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said she would lie for her family, does that mean she
would lie for the president of the United States? ... Would she
encourage other people to lie?'' Allred said.
</P>
<P>
   The indications are that Lewinsky testified that she had sexual
relations with the president but that he did not ask her to lie
about their relationship. That mixed message, Allred said, would
confound the president's critics, who say they believe he pressured
Lewinsky. ``Are they going to pick and choose what they believe of
Monica Lewinsky, cafeteria style?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe correspondent Estella Duran contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
