<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY DETAILS SEXUAL RELATIONSHIP WITH CLINTON TO GRAND JURY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Monica Lewinsky, the former intern at the center of
a sex-and-perjury investigation that has rocked the White House,
appeared before a federal grand jury Thursday and described a
sexual relationship with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky spent a little over six hours providing grand jurors
with a first-person account of a relationship that reportedly
contradicts the president's denials six months ago that they
engaged in sex or talked about covering it up.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning from prosecutors and grand jurors, Lewinsky
provided details of a dozen sexual encounters with Clinton at the
White House over an 18-month period, The Associated Press reported.
She also recounted their discussions of ways to keep the trysts
secret, according to the account, based on unnamed sources. At the
same time, Lewinsky told the grand jury that Clinton never urged
her to lie under oath.
</P>
<P>
   The claims by Lewinsky, if supported by other evidence or
testimony gathered by independent counsel Kenneth Starr, open the
president to possible charges of perjury and obstruction of justice
in the now-dismissed Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Lewinsky left the courthouse, family spokeswoman
Judy Smith told reporters that Lewinsky ``answered each question
truthfully, completely and honestly.''
</P>
<P>
   As Lewinsky, 25, began her testimony in the investigation that
imperils his presidency, Clinton and his aides tried to maintain a
business-as-usual front several blocks away at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared in the Rose Garden with Vice President Al Gore,
Attorney General Janet Reno, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, Jim
and Sarah Brady and several police officers to call on Congress to
make permanent the five-day waiting period for handgun purchases.
</P>
<P>
   And for the second time this week, the president employed the
Marine Band to drown out reporters' questions. This time, the band
struck up a medley of patriotic tunes when Clinton gave a
left-handed saluted to the conductor, then began to make his way
through the crowd toward the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton later met with his private attorneys to continue
preparing for his Aug. 17 testimony to grand jurors via
closed-circuit television.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential spokesman Barry Toiv insisted that Thursday was
another routine day at the White House. ``What event?'' he
deadpanned when asked about Lewinsky's visit to the federal
courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Toiv insisted Clinton had expressed no opinion about Lewinsky's
grand jury appearance. ``But he does agree with us and all
Americans (that) if we are coming to the end of this four-year, $40
million investigation, that would be a good thing,'' the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's long-awaited appearance comes on the heels of a
parade of lawyers, secretaries, presidential bodyguards and other
former interns called by Starr's prosecutors to testify before the
grand jury over the past six months.
</P>
<P>
   Appointed four years ago to investigate Clinton's business
dealings in Arkansas and later broadened to include various
scandals at the White House, Starr's inquiry was expanded in
January to include allegations of sex-and-perjury involving the
president and the former intern.
</P>
<P>
   Since reaching an immunity deal in which she can only be
prosecuted if she lies to Starr or the grand jury, Lewinsky has
told prosecutors about efforts by herself and Clinton to conceal
the relationship that they had denied under oath as part of Jones'
lawsuit against the president.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Lewinsky reportedly was prepared to recount
conversations with Clinton in which they allegedly discussed how to
use Betty Currie, the president's personal secretary, as an
intermediary for returning gifts he had given her.
</P>
<P>
   As part of her deal with Starr, Lewinsky also turned over
voice-mail messages she had saved of telephone calls from Clinton.
She also has turned over a blue dress that the FBI was testing to
determine if it contains any DNA material that would prove Lewinsky
wore it, as she reportedly claims, during a sexual encounter with
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Until Lewinsky testified Thursday, grand jurors had only heard
her voice on tape recordings of telephone conversations with Linda
Tripp reportedly about the affair. The tapes were made by Tripp,
who triggered the investigation when she turned the illicit
recordings over to Starr.
</P>
<P>
   It was uncertain late Thursday whether Lewinsky would be called
back for more questioning before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's testimony and what Clinton has to say in his Aug. 17
appearance are key to a decision by Starr on whether, or when, to
send Congress a report that could cite possible perjury and
obstruction of justice by the president.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, House Democratic Leader Richard Gephardt said
he was ``sick of hearing'' about the Lewinsky investigation and
said Starr would be making a ``grave mistake'' to send an
impeachment report to Congress before the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be very partisan, very unfair and demeaning to the
process that I think all of us believe is important to this
country,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
