<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1985 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNBEAM-PROBE-NYT &LR;      08-06 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNBEAM-PROBE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNBEAM SAYS IT MIGHT ADJUST FINANCIAL RESULTS BACK TO 1996 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunbeam Corp. said Thursday that it would have to restate last
year's financial statements and possibly the results for 1996 and
the first quarter of this year as well, because of possible
accounting irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   The troubled appliance maker said it expected to restate the
results by the end of September and until then would be unable to
report second-quarter results, which typically would have been
available by the middle of this month. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The company had previously said it expected to have to restate
last year's numbers, but it is now signaling that there may be
problems with results for other periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever problems there may be started a little longer ago
than even I anticipated,'' said William Steele, an analyst who
follows the company for Buckingham Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam gave no hint as to the size of what it said would be a
``material adjustment'' of at least the 1997 results. But Steele
estimated that the company may have to reduce the profits for 1997
by between $25 million and $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of the adjustments came a day after Sunbeam and
Albert J. Dunlap, the former chairman and chief executive ousted by
the board in June, signed a ``joint cooperation agreement'' to
share various documents related to lawsuits and an investigation
into the financial results.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the company and representatives for Dunlap cannot agree
about what they agreed on.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap's representatives continue to maintain that he and the
company agreed to share information and legal strategies. Sunbeam,
while initially declining to comment on the arrangement, now says
it never agreed to share legal defense strategies or information
with Dunlap, only access to ``nonprivileged information'' so that
he would agree to resign from the board.
</P>
<P>
   The document, which was obtained by The New York Times from an
executive close to Sunbeam, includes a phrase that says ``a
cooperation agreement is advisable to minimize the possibility of
duplication of efforts.'' So the bickering comes down to an
interpretation of what it means to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   As both sides sought to put their spin on the agreement dispute,
the company also tried to reassure investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sunbeam's new management team is continuing its efforts to
rebuild Sunbeam and restore its business to profitability,'' said
Jerry W. Levin, the new chief executive. His assurances, though,
were not enough to soothe shareholders, who sent the stock down $1,
to a new low of $7.
</P>
<P>
   The company said in June, just two weeks after the board
dismissed Dunlap, saying it had lost confidence in his leadership
after several quarters of unexpected bad results, that there were
unanswered questions about its 1997 financial statements and that
the Securities and Exchange Commission was investigating its
accounting practices.
</P>
<P>
   The problems stem, in part, from sales promotions put in place
under Dunlap's watch. Those promotions pushed too much product
through the pipeline and may have resulted in sales being booked in
the wrong quarters, as well as other potential accounting
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   The troubles have resulted in a lawsuits filed by shareholders
who say they were misled about the company's health. Sunbeam and
Dunlap have denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
