<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0429 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1986 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-SAFETY-600&AMP;ADD-N     08-06 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-SAFETY-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO SAFETY: YOU'RE ON CANDID CAMERA. PAY UP. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., N.Y., Calif.)  (Duplication warning: also filed in `a' category.) 
(mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Drive aggressively on the Beltway, Interstate 495,
north or east of Washington, and a computer-operated radar gun and
camera will single your car out; the computer will look up the
registration and send a warning letter to the owner. A Maryland
state trooper may watch, too, but the system can operate on its
own.
</P>
<P>
   Run a red light at some intersections in Howard County, Md., and
even though no police officer is in sight, a $75 ticket will be
mailed to the car's owner. Do the same in Oxnard, Calif., and the
computer-generated fine will be $270, plus points on the driver's
license.
</P>
<P>
   Robocop has arrived, although not as the gun-toting cyborg
envisioned by Hollywood. Cameras and computers at strategic
intersections are taking note of thousands of violations annually,
and doling out more citations than an equivalent number of
flesh-and-blood officers could write up.
</P>
<P>
   About two dozen police departments around the country have begun
automated ticketing. New York City was one of the first, five years
ago, and now operates red-light cameras in all five boroughs. As in
Maryland, tickets are sent to the owners of the cars caught on
film.
</P>
<P>
   Some departments initially feared a public backlash, and have
mostly avoided using the systems for speed enforcement, a
technology that threatens virtually every driver and thus raises
the public's ire. But police say they have found widespread support
_ or at least, few complaints _ for using the technology to catch
drivers who run red lights. ``It's so much more blatant, and so
much more dangerous,'' said Joseph Genovese, a traffic engineer in
Oxnard, where the sanctions _ a big fine and points against the
license _ are relatively tough.
</P>
<P>
   And, officers say, technology is the only practical way to catch
red-light runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a marked police car at an intersection, they're
creating a hazard themselves by chasing a person down,'' said Lt.
Glenn Hansen, commander of the automated enforcement division in
Howard County, which is between Washington and Baltimore. ``If you
don't chase the person, it looks like you don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Hansen's program is an experiment authorized by Maryland
legislators for his county alone, but others would like to do the
same. The county has 12 cameras now, and plans to have 20 by the
end of the summer. They are rotated among 26 sites to keep drivers
guessing. Installation costs from $7,500 to $12,000 each, including
the placement of two ``loop detector'' wires buried in the pavement
that sense the presence of a car by measuring its magnetic field,
and a pole to put the camera on.
</P>
<P>
   The camera is off until the light is red _ in fact, it gives a
grace period of three-tenths of a second. If the light is red, the
shutter is activated by one loop detector at the crosswalk, and a
second in the intersection itself. If the system senses gridlock,
it does not open the camera's shutter.
</P>
<P>
   The color photos, showing the back of the car and the red light,
are persuasive on the summons, Hansen said; fewer people contest
the tickets issued by the machine than the ones given by human
officers.
</P>
<P>
   The computer records exactly when each picture was taken, and by
seeing where the car was in the first and second photo, officers
can calculate the vehicle's speed. They do not use that measurement
to issue speeding tickets, but if the car owner goes to court,
police use the calculation to show the judge how the car was being
driven.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland does not attempt to identify the driver. It tickets the
owner, for allowing the car to be used in an unsafe manner. Experts
say that the driver is almost always the owner or a close relative
anyway, and that if an accident resulted, the owner would be
responsible no matter who was driving.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Oxnard blames the driver. It issues tickets that carry points
against the owners' license, but people who say they were not
behind the wheel when the ticket was issued can go to court to show
that their faces do not match the machine's photos.
</P>
<P>
   Oxnard's photos are taken from in front of the vehicle, and in
only 40 to 45 percent of them are both the drivers' faces and the
license plates clear; if they are not clear, the case is discarded.
Howard County's system takes a picture from the rear and usually
gets a legible plate number.
</P>
<P>
   In the 13 months that Oxnard has been issuing the tickets,
Genovese said accidents caused by drivers' running red lights were
down by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Robocop has plenty of work to do. Nationally, the leading cause
of crashes are drivers who ignore red lights or stop signs, said
Richard Retting, a safety engineer at the Insurance Institute for
Highway Safety.
</P>
<P>
   Such crashes kill 800 people in cars every year, he said, and
probably a substantial number of pedestrians. But counting the dead
pedestrians killed by red-light runners is difficult. ``There is
very little good information to go by,'' he said, ``since the
driver is alive but the pedestrian is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The Maryland State Police are trying a highway variation on the
robocop approach, with a camera that can pick out the
fastest-moving car in a group. Big overhead signs warn,
``Aggressive driver imaging in use.''
</P>
<P>
   State law does not permit computerized ticketing for speeding,
so the system is now being used to issue warnings. The system can
be set up on a highway shoulder and is supposed to run unattended,
but the software still needs work, according to a state police
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   If the idea of machines reprimanding people seems too harsh, it
sits well with people who put safety first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your civil rights are different in a car,'' said Stephanie
Faul, a spokeswoman for the AAA Foundation for Traffic Safety, an
affiliate of the auto club. ``The Constitution mentions your house
and your gun, but not your car,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But traffic surveillance troubles some civil liberties
watchdogs. ``It has a Big Brother aspect,'' said R. Kent Willis,
director of the American Civil Liberties Union in Virginia. ``We
don't like it.'' But he added that his group had not yet mounted a
court challenge. ``Legally, we haven't been able to come up with a
good theory yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Oakland, Calif., announced that it would install cameras to
survey pedestrians as a crime-fighting measure, an ACLU chapter in
Northern California successfully defeated the plan, but the chapter
has not opposed traffic-enforcement cameras. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Faul of the AAA Foundation said automated ticketing ``does
not harm law-abiding citizens,'' adding, ``If we can put up
red-light cameras, and keep people from running them without
endangering officers, I'm all for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
