<HEADER>
A1989 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-DEBTS-NYT &LR;      08-06 1332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-DEBTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOUNTAINS OF BAD DEBT STIFLE RUSSIAN ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ It was April when Dmitri Chernikh saw the first ripples
of Russia's financial crisis lapping at the door of Galatica, one
of Russia's hottest computer software companies.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the collapse of the Russian financial markets, or the
dizzying leap in interest rates, or even the first uncertain steps
of the country's new untested government that worried Chernikh or
his fellow directors. Like most other young Russian businesses,
Galatica, with $8 million in sales last year, does not trade its
shares publicly, nor has it ever sought bank loans, rates for which
were prohibitive even before the latest financial panic.
</P>
<P>
   What hit Galatica last spring was something more basic, and more
endemic to Russia's unfinished economic crisis: a pile-up of unpaid
bills, which by midsummer had topped $3 million, as the company's
biggest clients _ mostly in the rich and powerful energy sector _
stopped payments on Galatica's popular management software package.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the agreement last month for a $22.6 billion package
of credits and loans, Russia's financial crisis is still playing
itself out on the wider landscape of the Russian economy _ if a
devastated industrial base, an infant private sector and a cartel
of moguls who control banking, raw materials and other key sectors
can be properly called an economy.
</P>
<P>
   Like the government, Galatica swung quickly into crisis mode.
</P>
<P>
   One option considered at the first emergency meeting was a joke:
``Change countries.'' But the company's directors _ computer
whizzes from Moscow State University who founded Galatica in the
early days of Soviet economic reform _ were searching for a more
realistic response.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly, they considered a get-tough approach. Threatening
letters were sent out to clients, warning them that Galatica would
cut off consulting services to companies that did not pay their
bills.
</P>
<P>
   But like other attempts at breaking through the wall of Russian
arrears, this bluff fell flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response was so tough that we backed off,'' Chernikh said.
``At that point we decided that if the country is in bad shape and
our clients are in bad shape, we would just have to suffer, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Looming largest of all is the mountain of unpaid bills that have
accumulated as companies, private and government, run out of money
to pay each other, their workers or their taxes.
</P>
<P>
   There is even a thriving trade in debts. At the end of 1996,
overdue debts constituted one third of all accounts payable to
enterprises, forcing producers to rely on barter for their
commercial transactions.
</P>
<P>
   As the government moves to tighten monetary policy further, even
less money is available, particularly for businesses like Galatica
that offer services that many of its customers _ caught in a
squeeze between newly aggressive tax collectors and angry unpaid
workers _ consider low priority.
</P>
<P>
   Small companies anywhere are vulnerable to sudden financial
shifts, but in Russia, the small-business sector _ much of which
exists below the radar of government data collectors _ is
particularly exposed, lacking both access to credit and the
protection of a well-developed system for bankruptcy and other
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   For most Russian businesses, borrowing money from local banks is
not feasible, given the continuing rise in interest rates, which
were already at punishing levels of about 40 percent a year for
short-term loans before the crisis hit. According to one recent
report, credits to the private sector in Russia amount to only 7
percent of gross domestic product, compared with 15 percent in
Poland, 24 percent in Hungary or 111 percent in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   For small companies like Galatica, which employs almost 500
people in offices scattered around the former Soviet Union, seeking
investors through a public offering of shares is not realistic
either, particularly now with the uncertainties that cloud Russian
markets.
</P>
<P>
   As the crisis deepens, many are predicting that more and more
Russian companies, small and large, are going to have to scale back
already pared down operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of whether people have access to bank loans, there
is a single pool of capital,'' said Edwin Dolan, president of the
Moscow-based American Institute of Business and Economics, which
offers a master's degree in business administration. ``The
tightening of monetary policy is going to affect access to working
capital, which in turn tightens the nonpayment crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Galatica's strategy has been to look beyond its big clients in
Russia's energy sector _ which have been hit hard by a drop in
world energy prices _ and focus on more stable sectors, like
retailing and food processing, which have more direct links to
consumers. It has been helped by a recent merger with Parus,
another Russian software company that built up a diverse clientele,
and by its operations outside Russia, in former Soviet states like
Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
   Coping with financial crises is not a new challenge for
Galatica, which also saw payments grind to a halt in the period
before the 1996 presidential elections. Then Russia's money supply
dried up dramatically for several months as foreign investors,
fearing a Communist victory, stayed away, and as the Russian
government drained its budget to help President Boris Yeltsin's
re-election effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1996, the crisis was much bigger than now,'' Chernikh said.
``Then people stopped paying altogether. But each passing crisis is
a little less alarming. It is like gunfire. The first time is
frightening, the next time a little less.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, after a boom year in 1997 when sales more than
tripled, Galatica's directors are relatively sanguine about their
ability to survive without layoffs or major restructuring. Even a
devaluation of the ruble, which to most analysts would be the
worst-case scenario for the Russian economy, might not so
devastating. For one thing, noted Chernikh, Galatica has always set
its prices in dollars, a practice that dates back to the early
1990s when the value of the ruble was being whipped by inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, when the company developed its first program to help
companies manage their resources, Galatica has geared its
management programs to reflect the way their clients actually do
business, not the way they should according to Western business
school textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   From Soviet-style bookkeeping to barter transactions, Chernikh
says Galtica's programs have kept up with Russia's reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Western companies solve their problems very differently from
Russian companies,'' he said. ``Here, for instance, a contract is
not a contract in the Western sense. It can change during
implementation, which is something we have taken into account.''
</P>
<P>
   From its beginnings as an entreprising team from Moscow State
University's prestigious mechanical and mathematics department then
operating on the outer edges of Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev's first economic reforms, the company has had the
advantage of direct experience with Russia's lurching progress
towards a market economy, even as it kept close ties with the wave
of Russian ``computershiki'' who emigrated in the late 1980s to
Silicon Valley in California.
</P>
<P>
   An important break came in 1988 when Galatica won the contract
to computerize the electronic voting at the Congress of People's
Deputies, an elected gathering that was to usher in political
reform to the Soviet Union. But its biggest advantage was to be one
of the first on what was then an empty playing field.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time in Russia, you could do something in Russia
without money,'' Chernikh said. ``Now it is already more
complicated. The importance of having a name, a reputation, has
much more meaning now than it did even five years ago, and that
requires more money up front.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 2139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
