A1991 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-WORLD-U.S.-HNS &LR;      08-06 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-WORLD-U.S.-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
U.S. has 
a chance 
to shine
<TEXT>
<P>
   Game with Italy opens &QL; 
medal-contention play
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATHENS, Greece _ Until now, the proving ground for the U.S.
basketball team has been confined to its locker room.
</P>
<P>
   But now that these replacement players for the Dream Team have
convinced themselves they have what it takes to succeed in the FIBA
World Championship of Basketball, they would like to let a few
people know about it.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly, U.S. fans who have ignored this event. One victory today
would get everybody's attention.
</P>
<P>
   The United States enters the quarterfinal round against Italy
(9:30 a.m. CDT), and the intensity goes up several notches. The
winner will be one of four teams trying for the gold medal. The
loser is out of medal contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, for every team, it's pressure,'' coach Rudy Tomjanovich
said Thursday. ``For us, what these guys have done is amazing.
Nobody expected them to do anything. Nobody even knows about them
in the U.S. It's not a big story, although it's starting to become
more and more of a story.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all important games, but this next game erases all
that wonderful work (if they lose). We know what we've done. We're
proud of what we've done. But back in the United States, if we lose
this next game, they'd say, `Ah, they just failed.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But these guys really haven't failed on what they've done so
far. We know that. We've already surpassed some expectations. But
we'd like other people back in America to feel good about this
team, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's a big game. We want to be going for the gold.''
</P>
<P>
   This is turning into a let's-prove-everybody-wrong tournament
for the U.S. squad, which was thrown together less than a month ago
and yet went 5-1 in the first two rounds against national teams
that have played together for years.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team is the No. 1 seed out of its half of the bracket.
It plays Italy, which squeaked into the quarterfinals as the No. 4
seed from the other bracket. The winner today plays the
Lithuania-Russia winner Saturday in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``With us getting the No. 1 seed and getting to where we
expected ourselves to be is a good compliment to this team,'' Jimmy
King said. ``A lot of people thought we weren't able to get even to
this spot. Our goal isn't over. But we're on track.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, the games really count. In order for us to get into the
medal round, we have to beat Italy. I don't really feel like we're
under any pressure. I feel like we're the No. 1 seed. We earned
that, and the pressure of getting it is off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've answered some questions. But if we lose, there's going
to be a lot of questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The first of which would be: Why did the NBA players cost
America the gold medal by not playing in these games?
</P>
<P>
   But the Americans don't want to dwell on that possibility. They
face an Italian team they beat 80-75 in an exhibition in Rome just
before this tournament. But Italy is the only team to have a win
against powerful Yugoslavia, the pre-tournament favorite. So the
Italians have the ability to beat anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a good team, a team we struggled to beat in an
exhibition game,'' Tomjanovich said. ``But to me, that game means
nothing. This is the real deal, and I'm expecting a real hard
game.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be nothing but hard games the rest of the way. The
remaining eight teams can make a case that they will win the gold.
And the Americans face a double whammy, to some extent.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are not the Dream Team of NBA players, they are not
as strong and their presence has created the wide-open feeling of a
tournament that has no clear-cut favorite, not even the
Yugoslavians.
</P>
<P>
   But the rest of the world would be humiliated if it were beaten
by what is essentially America's minor-leaguers. The U.S. players,
on the other hand, recognize this is a chance to show the world
that American basketball is so strong and so deep, it can handle
other countries' strongest competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individually, we've gone as far as we can go,'' David Wood
said. ``If we're going to go on from here, we have to do it as a
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's good about our situation is that we've had serious
pressure on us from day one. So it's not going to be any different
now. It was pressure just making this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have faith that it's our destiny to win the gold. Of
course, every event I've ever played in, I have had faith that we
were going to win. But this is a great door of opportunity opened
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It will take faith and a lot more in this case. The Americans
aren't invincible, but neither are they intimidated by the
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't fear anyone,'' point guard Michael Hawkins said.
``But it's funny. We've worked so hard and accomplished a lot as a
team. And now, it's all riding on this one game right here as to
whether we go to the medal round or not.''
</P>
<P>
   As Tomjanovich said: ``Talk means nothing now. Playing the game
means everything. That's why we're here. And I'll say this: This
(vying for the gold) is much more rewarding than it would have been
with the NBA players. We're right in the pack with everybody else,
and if we happen to do this, it's a tremendous feat.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
