<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1992 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-NYT &LR;      08-06 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER YET ANOTHER BULLPEN COLLAPSE, METS RALLY TO DEFEAT GIANTS,
9-8  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If the Mets have demonstrated anything over the last
week, it is that no late-inning lead truly seems safe when they're
playing, regardless of who happens to be ahead. Sometimes that
benefits the Mets, and sometimes it doesn't, and Thursday afternoon
at Shea Stadium served as a perfect example.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth time in the last seven games, the Mets'
precarious bullpen collapsed, this time by blowing a 6-2
eighth-inning lead over the San Francisco Giants. And yet for the
second time in three days, the Mets displayed resiliency by
rallying for the victory, with the winning run again coming
courtesy of a bases-loaded walk from Giants reliever Jose Mesa,
this time with Luis Lopez at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The 9-8 victory, before a crowd of 36,920, left the Mets with a
60-52 record, two and a half games behind the Chicago Cubs in the
National League wild-card race. It also enabled the Mets to depart
on a nine-game road trip that begins in Denver Friday night feeling
relatively good about themselves, even though Met relievers Dennis
Cook and Greg McMichael each managed to give up three-run homers in
the eighth inning Thursday as the Mets bullpen continued its
remarkable week of self-destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's good for the goose,'' Mets Manager Bobby Valentine
after happily watching another team's relievers blow a lead. ``We
were the gander.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesa walked Luis Lopez on a 3-1 with none out in the bottom of
the ninth to score Matt Franco with the winning run. It capped a
two-run rally that began with John Olerud (who had earlier extended
his hitting streak to 20 games) singling off San Francisco closer
Robb Nen, who had entered the game with no outs in the eighth to
squelch an earlier Mets uprising.
</P>
<P>
   Franco was the last available hitter on the Mets' bench and he
followed Olerud's hit with a pinch-hit single to right that moved
Olerud to third. And then Brian McRae tied the score, 8-8, with a
run-scoring single to center as Franco took third on the play.
</P>
<P>
   After McRae, who had earlier tied his career high with his 17th
home run, took second on defensive indifference, Nen intentionally
walked Lenny Harris to load the bases. On came Mesa, who had walked
Harris with the bases loaded and two outs in the bottom of the 10th
on Tuesday to give the Mets a 7-6 victory in a game in which they
had handed away a two-run lead in the top of the ninth. Lopez,
mindful of what happened Tuesday, said he was determined to take
two strikes from Mesa before he ever took the bat off his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Lopez never swung.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me to swing, it had to be right down the middle,'' Lopez
said. ``He was all over the place. It was kind of a flashback to
the other night.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Mets seemed to have been playing the same game
over and over for the last week, the way they were either blowing
apparently safe leads or frantically rallying for victories. There
were bad bullpen losses to the Dodgers on Friday and Monday, and
dramatic victories by the Mets in their final at-bat Saturday,
Tuesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's victory also included three hits by the struggling
Todd Hundley, which had to make everyone on the Mets feel a little
more confident. But at the same time, the latest bullpen failure
has to leave Valentine wondering when, and if, his relief corps
will ever get straightened out.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Elias Sports Bureau, the Mets have now blown 26
save opportunities this season, while converting just 25. Thursday,
Masato Yoshii pitched well enough to win for the fourth consecutive
time. After allowing two first-inning runs on three hits, the
Japanese right-hander allowed just two more hits over the next six
innings, as the Mets rode a three-run homer from Edgardo Alfonzo
off Orel Hershiser and solo shots by McRae, Tony Phillips and John
Olerud to a 6-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But then came the top of the eighth. Cook, on in relief of
Yoshii, surrendered a three-run homer to former Met Jeff Kent on
his very first pitch to trim the lead to 6-5. Cook got the next two
batters out but then surrendered a single to Rich Aurilia and a
double to Brent Mayne. On came McMichael, who had allowed five runs
and two homers in two-thirds of an inning on Monday night. This
time, he immediately surrendered a three-run pinch-hit home run to
the former Yankee Charlie Hayes, giving the Giants an 8-6 lead. The
Mets got one run back in the bottom of the eighth and had the tying
run on third when Nen struck out Tony Phillips, the only time
Phillips, who had four hits on the day, made an out in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Turk Wendell (4-0) then came on in the top of the ninth and
narrowly escaped a bases-loaded jam of his own escaping unscathed
by striking out Aurilia and Mayne on fast balls. Wendell had been
something of an afterthought in the bullpen, but he pitched two
strong innings against the Giants on Tuesday and just might start
to take on a bigger role in a bullpen in which McMichael and John
Franco and Mel Rojas and even the relatively consistent Cook have
plenty of recent scars.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these were all rookies and they had no stripes, I'd be
really concerned,'' Valentine said of his bullpen. ``But they've
all been through a few wars. They know how to right themselves.
These have been the two worst weeks of pitching and I think we're
something like 13-5 (actually, 14-6). That's the good news.''
</P>
<P>
   And Thursday, after watching his team rally for an emotional
victory in what has become a see-saw season, Valentine did not want
to talk about anything bad.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
