<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2000 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARN-TRUCKER-$ADV09-N     08-06 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARN-TRUCKER-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MODEL CAREER PATH FOR A SELF-STARTER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Tenn.)   (af)  
 By LAURA PEDERSEN-PIETERSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cesar Pacheco III of the South Bronx recalls vividly
the day that Nicole Brown Simpson was murdered _ June 12, 1994. He
nearly lost his life the same evening, after being shot point-blank
in the chest during a botched robbery outside his apartment in the
Castle Hill section. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instead of watching the New York Knicks in a playoff game that
night, as he had planned, Pacheco spent nearly nine hours on the
operating table at Jacobi Hospital, while his fiancee and her
6-year-old son waited anxiously.
</P>
<P>
   For a time it was touch-and-go, as the Jacobi surgical team
repaired his perforated lung, diaphragm and liver. ``You owe us
one,'' a surgeon later told Pacheco, then 23. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A near-death experience, Pacheco says, focuses the mind
wonderfully. During his slow recovery, while contemplating the
hundred or so stitches that held together the tapestry of his body,
he decided that it was time to get his act together, too.
</P>
<P>
   He had graduated from an alternative high school in the South
Bronx and held a string of low-paying odd jobs. That wouldn't do,
not with a family to support. Pacheco wanted a career. But in what?
</P>
<P>
   ``Trucking was the obvious choice,'' he now says, though when he
decided to become an operator of 18-wheelers, he didn't own a car,
much less know how to drive a truck. Still, having been raised near
the Hunt's Point Market in the Bronx, Pacheco grew up watching the
big rigs maneuver in and out of the industrial neighborhood. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once back on his feet, he applied for a learner's permit and
persuaded a friend to provide some informal lessons in driving a
truck.
</P>
<P>
   The next stop was Model Training Center on 14th Street in
Manhattan. No fly-by-night diploma mill, the vocational school has
been in business for 50 years. After six weeks of instruction,
Pacheco had a commercial driver's license; now, he was certified to
drive everything from ambulettes, city buses and garbage trucks to
flatbeds and triple tractor-trailers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just three weeks later, he was hired by MS Carriers of Memphis,
at $1,000 a week plus overtime, benefits and bonuses. In other
words, good money, particularly for someone who until then had
never earned more than $350 a week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a career self-starter, Pacheco is in many ways representative
of a new mode of working in America. Employees and entrepreneurs
find happy niches for themselves by following their instincts _ and
expect to reinvent themselves several more times before retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Even today's college graduates often tumble into careers very
different from the ones they have just finished training for. And
many workers are eagerly jumping into jobs that did not exist even
a year or two ago _ corporate Web site managers, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Pacheco drove tractor trailers professionally for just two years
before he had his second epiphany. It was at the funeral of a
36-year-old friend who had a heart attack during a basketball game.
The friend had two young children, and his death made Pacheco
realize that he wanted to spend more time with his family _ he now
had two children, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved driving across the country because it allowed me to
see that there was more out there than what was in front of me in
the South Bronx,'' Pacheco said. ``But I think it's more important
for kids in a ghetto atmosphere to have a full-time father
around.''
</P>
<P>
   The week after his friend's funeral, Pacheco, then 26, was back
at the Model Training School, this time offering his services as a
driving instructor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It has turned out to be a satisfying career switch. Part of the
payoff, he said, comes from helping others gain access to a better
standard of living. Salaries for truck drivers range from $35,000
to $100,000 and can come with good benefits _ especially jobs
covered by the International Brotherhood of Teamsters. Neither a
high school diploma nor proficient English is required.
</P>
<P>
   ``I teach immigrants who were making $5 an hour as dishwashers
and even a lot of college graduates who are sick of making eight
bucks an hour in an office,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend found Pacheco busy training a 47-year-old man, a
meat packer who has been with the Pathmark grocery chain for two
decades, to drive a rig.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have trouble understanding that just because a guy
didn't go to Harvard Business School doesn't mean that he doesn't
have dreams,'' he said, identifying strongly with his student.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do you need an MBA to see how things fit together in the
economy. From the cab of his big rig, Pacheco became his own
securities analyst. While he had never heard of Peter Lynch, the
legendary portfolio manager for Fidelity Investments, he approached
the market as if he had memorized a page out of Lynch's playbook:
Invest in what you know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trucking gives you an excellent idea of what's happening in
different businesses through watching the flow of traffic,'' he
explained. In July 1995, for example, he noticed that an
extraordinary amount of goods was being delivered to the loading
docks of Sears, Roebuck stores across the country, and he figured
that meant an extraordinary amount of merchandise was being carried
out the front door by customers, as well.
</P>
<P>
   His observation was keen: Sears stock, which had been
languishing in the low $30s, started to move; by the next March it
had climbed more than 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when Pacheco was ready to invest for the long term, he
selected MCI Communications and Sun Microsystems _ stocks that he
hopes will help pay for the education of his two boys, now 10 and
3. His plan, for now at least, is to set himself up in the trucking
business when his boys are a little older.
</P>
<P>
   For about $25,000 you can buy a secondhand rig and go into
business for yourself, Pacheco explained. He would also like to buy
a home in Westchester County. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It might not be the first thing to come to mind, but there are a
lot of dreams to be realized by driving trucks. Currently, there
are about 80,000 unfilled driving jobs in the industry, Traffic
World magazine has reported. And given the surge in ordering goods
by catalogue and from the Internet, it is no surprise that the
government says trucking is the eighth-fastest-growing occupation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You can walk out this door after a $365, 10-day course, and
another $175 for the road test, and get a job tomorrow,'' said Bob
Kousoulos, a longtime instructor at Model Training Center. ``You'll
make back the cost of the class in a week.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, after a year and a half on the job, Pacheco is
regarded by the school's owners as one of their top instructors. He
makes about $42,000 a year teaching others how to handle big rigs.
What about the bonus he used to collect as a driver? ``Seeing my
family every day is my big bonus,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 2144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0436 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2001 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPEND-CREDIT-LIMITS-A     08-06 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CREDIT-LIMITS-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKS AND CREDIT-CARD ISSUERS ARE RAISING THEIR LIMITS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(af) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carl Thomsen, a financial consultant in suburban Washington,
actively uses two credit cards, sometimes piling substantial
business expenses onto them. No matter how much he spends, though,
his Visa and Mastercard issuers keep automatically raising his
authorized credit limits, which now run well into five figures
each.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, of course, is to tempt people like Thomsen _ a
customer with a good payment record _ to borrow ever-higher amounts
at interest rates that often approach 20 percent. But for some
consumers, it also means a chance to get into ever-bigger financial
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Do not count Thomsen, 55, among the less-disciplined consumers;
he usually pays off his card balances in full at the end of each
month and has never asked for more borrowing power. Indeed, he
said, ``I've never bumped up against a credit limit.''
</P>
<P>
   In watching those limits grow, however, Thomsen has plenty of
company these days. Banks and other credit-card issuers are raising
their limits far faster than consumers are borrowing _ even as
lenders report record proportions of delinquencies and charge-offs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite protestations that they're trying to get rid of the
worst excesses, the marketing of card credit is continuing largely
as usual, with little let-up,'' said Warren Heller, research
director for Veribanc Inc., which rates banks and savings
institutions. ``One of the time-tested rules of business is that
your existing customers are your best prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   During the two years ended in March, credit limits for all
bank-issued cards in the United States soared 50.3 percent, to
$1.78 trillion, according to Veribanc _ more than twice the growth
in card charges.
</P>
<P>
   This pushed consumers' potential spending power to a record 8.3
times their current indebtedness, up from 5.7 just two years ago.
When the data were first collected in 1990, the multiple was a
little more than 2.
</P>
<P>
   Other figures, compiled by the American Bankers Association,
also point to fast-expanding credit. The most common credit limit
for a standard card sponsored by a large bank, the association
said, climbed for the second consecutive year in 1997, to $3,500.
</P>
<P>
   That is 40 percent higher than the typical limit of $2,500 in
1993. And some ``premium'' cards _ which are not all that difficult
to get _ are being advertised with limits of $50,000 and even
$100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The average account balance on standard credit cards issued by
large banks is $1,987, the survey found, up from $1,479 in 1993.
For gold cards, it is $2,497, up from $2,334.
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Federation of America sponsored a report on the
subject last month to bolster its opposition to a bill making it
harder for people to declare bankruptcy _ a bill that lenders are
pushing for Congress to pass.
</P>
<P>
   The organization attributes soaring bankruptcies largely to
``irresponsible'' promotion of credit cards and considers the
banking industry hypocritical in seeking legislation that they say
would make it easier to collect debts from consumers whom bankers
themselves had lured over the financial brink.
</P>
<P>
   The industry, increasingly dominated by a shrinking number of
major banks, often responds to such accusations by saying that
soaring credit lines are a statistical illusion or a reflection of
banks' improving ability to differentiate between the most
lucrative customers and potential deadbeats.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Chimerine, consulting economist for Mastercard
International, estimated that 75 percent to 80 percent of the
increase in total credit lines reflected the issuance of new cards
_ for which no reliable count exists _ rather than expanded
capacity for existing card holders.
</P>
<P>
   By itself, MBNA, the second-biggest card issuer after Citibank,
added 11.4 million customers last year on top of a 9.3 million gain
in 1996. But some in the industry say that to hasten that growth,
MBNA engages in mass expansion of credit lines.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Frank, a spokesman for MBNA, disputed this, saying that
the company's lines have grown an average of just 8 percent in the
last two years.
</P>
<P>
   At First Chicago NBD, which issues the First Card, potential new
card holders are offered lower lines of credit than they were two
years ago, said Ralph R. Mueller, senior credit officer for First
Card.
</P>
<P>
   First Chicago attributes the growth of credit limits to the
issuance of more gold and platinum cards, which have higher limits.
It also notes that many card holders now have more cards to use;
according to the Nilson Report, which tracks the credit card
industry, the average is now slightly more than four cards per card
holder, compared with slightly more than three in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly, though, the industry attributes the expansion of credit
limits to refined methods of judging their new customers' ability
to pay. Banks have become ``much more adept in distinguishing the
most profitable customers, those most likely to use their cards and
repay their balances,'' said Robert Stock, senior vice president
for credit products at Visa USA.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that issuers have reduced their exposure to new
credit-card charge-offs, what risks can expanded credit limits pose
for consumers? An obvious one is that a generally responsible
borrower could leap into expensive debt because of an emergency _ a
serious health problem, for example, or the loss of a job.
</P>
<P>
   But specialists say high credit lines pose some risks even if
they are not used. Access to other credit, like a mortgage, can be
impaired if an applicant has too many cards with too much borrowing
potential. Lenders are wary that a consumer or spouse could
suddenly tap several credit sources so heavily that not all could
be repaid.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is taken into consideration,'' said Charlotte Newton,
vice president for consumer affairs at Mastercard. ``Whether or not
you use it, it's still there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
