<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2003 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPEND-HOME-REBUILD-2T     08-06 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-HOME-REBUILD-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME REBUILDING POLICIES THAT OFFER 120 PERCENT OF INSURED AMOUNT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ill., Md.)   (af)  
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM COAST, Fla. _ The wildfires that swept through the piney
woods here this summer provided a test, of sorts, of a new kind of
home insurance that is being introduced gradually across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of paying whatever it takes to replace a destroyed home,
as had been the case for years, the leading insurers are now
selling policies that limit most payments to 120 percent of the
insured amount.
</P>
<P>
   And that has posed a powerful question: Would the scaled-back
coverage be enough for people to start over? Would there be huge
gaps between the cost of a new house and the insurance payment?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, based on evidence accumulating here, is that the
lesser coverage seems to suffice. Both the insurers and Florida
regulators say there have been no complaints and, in nearly a dozen
interviews, people who lost their homes had nothing but praise for
the insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't ask for better treatment,'' said Aida Meltzer, an
Allstate customer who lost her three-bedroom home here in central
Florida, near the Atlantic coast.
</P>
<P>
   Many fire victims have collected more than they expected, and
those who have come up short say they have only themselves to blame
because they consciously under-insured their homes, taking what
they thought was a reasonable gamble that disaster was unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The key to making the restricted policies work, consumer
advocates and insurers say, is in accurately calculating the cost
of rebuilding a home and then scrupulously adjusting each year for
inflation and improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``This approach requires much more vigilance,'' said J. Robert
Hunter, director of insurance for the Consumer Federation of
America. But done according to plan, he said, it seems fair to both
customers and insurers.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's new approach, which requires regulatory approval
in every state, has yet to be tested in the aftermath of a big
hurricane or earthquake, when laws of supply and demand _ as well
as profiteering _ can send rebuilding costs soaring off the charts.
</P>
<P>
   In the Florida fires, the number of homes lost was not enormous,
and prices for building materials seem to have changed little.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers also say they do not foresee problems in areas where
real estate values are skyrocketing, because coverage is based on
the cost of rebuilding rather than on a house's market value. A big
part of a house's sale price often reflects the value of the land
on which it was built. But homeowner's insurance covers the house,
not the site.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers introduced sky's-the-limit policies in the early 1980s
as a way to increase sales. But soon they became the industry
standard, so no company had an edge. The insurers did have much
greater liability, however.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Andrew cost the industry $16 billion in 1992, and
State Farm took the first step toward retrenchment the next spring,
refusing to sell unlimited policies in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it instituted the 120-percent provision. Judith K.
Mintel, a lawyer for State Farm, says the intent is to insure
accurately the cost of replacing a house. State Farm allows for a
10 percent margin of error in its estimate system, she said, and
throws in another 10 percent for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   Satisfied that the concept was workable, the company began
putting it into effect nationally in 1996, as state regulators
approved it. And the competition has followed. The policies, which
cost about the same as their predecessors, are now being sold in
more than 30 states, including California. The new approach has yet
to be approved by regulators in New York, New Jersey and
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The companies say that they sent notices to customers about the
changes and that they instructed their agents to spread the word,
but details of the coverage apparently were lost on many people.
Fire victims here said they did not realize _ until claims
adjusters told them _ that they could get up to 20 percent more
than the amount their policies specified.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, they also couldn't recall a time of unlimited
coverage. Without exception, they believed that if they were
insured for $100,000, they could expect $100,000 _ no more, no
less.
</P>
<P>
   They were also happily surprised to learn that they would
receive several thousand dollars, in most cases, to remove the
remains of their homes and for new landscaping.
</P>
<P>
   By spreading money around immediately, the insurers won many
friends in Palm Coast, which has a population of about 30,000,
scattered over hundreds of acres of thick woods a few miles from
the beach. Within hours of the fires in July, the insurers were
handing out thousands of dollars for living expenses; within a few
days, many people had received checks for the face value of their
policies.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When Rhon Dixon, the owner of a window-blind and kitchen-cabinet
company, drove up to the knee-high mound of ash that had been his
two-story, three-bedroom frame house, he found a State Farm claims
adjuster sitting in his driveway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Do you need some living expenses?' '' Dixon
recalled. ``I said, `Probably.' And he said, `What do you need,
$5,000, $10,000?' I said $10,000 would be fine. Then, about three
minutes later, he said: `You're going to need a deposit for where
you're living. Why don't I just give you $15,000?' And I said,
`That's even better.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Until the fires, Dixon had never expected to use his insurance.
He said he had guessed at what might be enough coverage and didn't
aim high. He never read his policy and doesn't remember anyone
telling him about the 20 percent cushion or other provisions that
will now put money in his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think your property is worth a lot, but when you talk with
the tax people and the insurance company, you try to claim it's not
worth anything,'' Dixon said. ``Until something like this happens
it just seems like you just keep paying and never get anything
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Dixon, 42, has been talking with contractors about
rebuilding. Their calculations show his coverage was low. His
policy was for $108,900; rebuilding will cost about $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my fault,'' Dixon said. ``I didn't have it insured for
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The gap, though, is not going to be as wide as he first thought.
State Farm has already given him $21,700 more _ the 20 percent,
plus $1,300 for things like replacing his driveway, sidewalk and a
patio. And he expects State Farm to supply an additional $5,000 to
bulldoze and cart away his ruins and about $5,400 more for new
landscaping. Changes in building codes have increased some building
costs, and State Farm routinely pays a percentage of those
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   A more litigious person might argue that Dixon's State Farm
agent should have made an effort to see that the insured value of
the house was closer to the mark. Executives at State Farm
headquarters in Bloomington, Ill., said that their policy is for
agents, armed with the latest costs of building materials and a
computer, to estimate as precisely as possible how much it will
take to replace each house they insure. Dixon said the only
estimate he knew of came out of his head.
</P>
<P>
   James I. Jones, 62, who got out of his house just as his trees
were catching fire, was also under-insured. He thought his agent's
estimate of $100,000 of coverage was low, but didn't argue: he did
not want to pay higher premiums. Now that concrete block walls are
all that remain of his three-bedroom home, he also blames himself,
not State Farm. Jones says two contractors have estimated the cost
of replacing his home at $135,000.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Florida fire victims said their biggest insurance
mistake was underestimating the value of their furniture, clothes
and the other contents of their homes. An Allstate homeowner's
policy automatically provides the equivalent of half the face value
for the home's contents; on a $100,000 policy, the contents are
covered for an additional $50,000. State Farm's automatic
allocation is 75 percent of the face value.
</P>
<P>
   Aida and David Meltzer, retirees from Baltimore, were among
those whose insurance coverage worked out just right. They did not
cut corners and fastidiously updated their coverage. When they
added a room to their beige-and-brown ranch house in mid-May, Mrs.
Meltzer increased their Allstate coverage by $10,000, to about
$80,000.
</P>
<P>
   After the fire, the Meltzers found it would cost about $85,000
to rebuild, well within the 20 percent margin. They have even
decided to add a few frills out of their own pockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very well satisfied with the insurance company and all the
people we've had to deal with,'' Meltzer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
