<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLLAPSE-225&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 DEMOLITION FIRM CITED IN COLLAPSE OF 42nd ST. BUILDING  
 (bl)  
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As investigators continued to look into the deadly
scaffolding collapse at a Times Square construction site, they
announced Thursday that a nearby building's collapse in December
was caused by a demolition company's failure to shore up a
construction site on 42nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of the 80-year-old Selwyn Theater building, which
happened amid a spate of similar accidents in Manhattan, disrupted
preparations for the city's New Year's Eve celebration in Times
Square and reinforced worries about the city's aging buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The company found at fault, Big Apple Wrecking &AMP; Construction
Corp. of the Bronx, had filed plans with the Buildings Department
last year detailing how it would underpin the Selywn building while
it excavated a construction site next door to build E Walk, a large
retail and entertainment complex. But according to a report
released Thursday by the Buildings Department, Big Apple never
provided the steel and concrete underpinning, or any bracing that
would have held in place the dirt and rock beneath the building.
Instead, the report says, the Selwyn building slid off its
foundation and collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The investigation has concluded that the collapse was due to
the failure of the subcontractor to follow through on the approved
plans,'' said Buildings Commissioner Gaston Silva.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Under the city's system of ``semi-controlled inspections,'' the
demolition contractor is responsible for insuring that demolition
and excavation work on the site comply with the construction plans
approved by the Department of Buildings. The city does not inspect
the work.
</P>
<P>
   Big Apple, a large demolition company with a troubled history,
was a subcontractor for Tishman Construction Corp. at the E-Walk
complex. Big Apple president Harold Greenberg did not return calls
seeking comment. In an unrelated case a decade ago, Greenberg was
convicted of bribing a federal inspector to overlook violations in
an asbestos-removal project.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the findings Thursday, Silva said there was little he
could do to punish Big Apple, which was involved in a similar
collapse six years ago at the Ansonia Post Office near Lincoln
Center. The Buildings Department expects to cite Big Apple for
several violations relating to the collapse, which could cost the
company several thousand dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we don't license demolition contractors, that's all we
can do,'' Silva said. ``This reinforces the need for a licensing
scheme for contractors in the city of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani submitted legislation
to the City Council that would require the licensing of
construction companies. The licenses could be revoked if a company
failed to comply with regulations or had a pattern of unsafe
working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   A call for the licensing of contractors was issued in 1992, when
a portion of the Ansonia Post Office collapsed on Broadway, between
67th and 68th Streets, injuring a passer-by. At the time, a
Buildings Department official said the cause of the Ansonia
collapse appeared to be ``improper demolition procedures and
careless supervision'' by Big Apple, which had already been cited
for 10 safety violations at the site.
</P>
<P>
   The Empire State Development Corp. and the 42nd Street
Development Project, which own the Selwyn building, have filed a
claim for millions of dollars against the construction manager,
Tishman Construction Corp., which hired Big Apple.
</P>
<P>
   Tishman is also the construction manager at the Conde Nast
construction site at nearby Broadway and 43rd Street, where a
scaffolding collapse in July killed an elderly woman and prompted
the city to cordon off several blocks in the area. That accident is
still under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Empire chairman Charles Gargano said Thursday that he was
seeking to recover the costs related to cleaning up the debris from
the Selwyn collapse, as well as the costs associated with building
a 10-story rehearsal studio and theater on the site of the Selwyn
building.
</P>
<P>
   Tishman spokesman Richard Kielar said that both his company and
Big Apple were ``in discussions about resolution of the state's
claims.'' He said that Big Apple and its engineer were responsible
for creating a safety plan and adhering to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no indication in the report that Tishman or its
associated entities on the project were at fault, or did not
fulfill all required procedures,'' Kielar said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
