u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PETER-PAN-FOUND-ART-N     08-06 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETER-PAN-FOUND-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOLEN PETER PAN STATUE FOUND IN EAST RIVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(af) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Following a beer-bottle-strewn trail of evidence and
the recollections of an eyewitness, the dogged detectives on the
case of the purloined Peter Pan Thursday found the missing statue
50 feet below the surface of the East River near Gracie Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the disappearance of the beloved statue from
Carl Schurz Park appeared, appropriately enough, to be the work of
a band of overly high-spirited youths, perhaps latter-day Lost Boys
who turned on their own icon.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Chief Kevin Farrell, the commander of Manhattan
detectives, said the police believed that the crime stemmed from a
party that took place in the park on Tuesday night just a few steps
away from the official residence of New York City's crime-busting
mayor, Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   There was evidence under examination, he said, ``including beer
bottles'' near the park's walkway where the nearly five-foot-tall
bronze statue was thrown into the river.
</P>
<P>
   The police said they had identified no suspects, but clearly
several strong people were needed to drag the statue and its
pedestal from the garden, cut or wrench the statue free from the
base, carry it up a flight of stairs and heave it over a chest-high
fence.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 officers were involved in recovering the statue,
Farrell said, including a half-dozen scuba divers at a time working
50 feet down in the murky, silty river. For much of the morning,
police details, including small craft resembling lobster boats from
the Harbor Unit, trucks from Emergency Services bristling with
esoteric gear and clumps of grim-faced supervisors in dark suits
ranged up and down the shore from the Heliport at East 60th Street
to an old boathouse just north of the mayor's residence.
</P>
<P>
   The statue was winched into one of the small boats _ it took a
700-pound counterweight to pull it up _ and finally taken to the
police facility at Rodmans Neck in the Bronx to be examined for
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Visually, it looks pretty good,'' said Farrell, adding that
the only apparent damage was a scrape on one knee.
</P>
<P>
   Dets. John R. Flannery and Patrick O'Donnell had spent most of
Wednesday prowling through scrap metal dealer's shops in the Bronx
on the possibility that the statue might have been chopped up and
sold.
</P>
<P>
   But the two detectives decided to make another canvass of the
park at night, hoping to find a visitor who might have been there
when the statue was stolen. And they did.
</P>
<P>
   A man who took his nightly constitutional along the river
opposite East 87th Street told them he had seen a group of eight or
nine young men, possibly teen-agers, Flannery said, ``carrying an
inanimate object.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He heard one yell, `No-no-no,' and then he heard the splash,''
the detective said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, Launch 37 of the Police Scuba Unit anchored
just off the park to begin the search. Sgt. John Cummings and
Officer Frank Pelligrino tossed a line with a grappling hook went
into the murky waters and followed it in their masks and fins to
begin what they call a pendulum search. After only 20 minutes they
found the statue on the silty bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a great eyewitness,'' Pelligrino said. ``It was right
where he said it would be. It's pretty complex, but if you have a
good eyewitness, that's half the battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding the statue was only the beginning. The water was calm
when they started, but in the hour it took to get the statue
winched aboard Harbor George's Launch 4, the current was ripping
hard through Hellgate at 4 knots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very brutal environment, a very dangerous dive,''
Pelligrino said of the stretch of river off the park. ``There's
lots of rebars, debris; its like a junkyard of garbage down there.
It's definitely very dangerous, a black water environment. Your
visibility is very limited.''
</P>
<P>
   Cummings, the more experienced diver, began tying lines around
the statue, running them around and through its arms and legs. The
visibility was so bad they had actually tied it to a 10-foot rebar
and had to pull it free. Then they hooked three baloonlike lift
bags to the statue to give it boyancy and the harbor unit boat
pulled it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty tricky job,'' Pelligrino said.
</P>
<P>
   A Parks Department spokesman, asked about the condition of the
statue, said that orders had been issued that statements about
Peter Pan would come only from the mayor's press office.
</P>
<P>
   At city hall, Giuliani mentioned the recovery in response to a
question about the disappearance of Irene Silverman, a wealthy
widow. ``No,'' he said, ``but I should tell you that Peter Pan has
been discovered in the East River.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounding irked at the attention the statuenapping had received,
and perhaps because all the news reports noted that it occurred
near Gracie Mansion, Giuliani added: ``I usually like to confine
myself to reporting on things that happen to human beings. I tend
to think the more important incidents are the ones that happen to
human beings. But the statue was found.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
