<DOCNO> NYT19980806.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2013 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEEBOOK0     08-06 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEEBOOK07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wohlers taking 10-day trip to minors as Braves shuffle pen
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the starting rotation remains the most rock-solid in the
major leagues, the Atlanta bullpen is still a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   A day after signing two veteran relievers to minor-league
contracts, the Braves were set to make more roster moves Thursday
involving the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving a cortisone shot for bone spurs in his pitching
elbow Thursday, middle reliever Russ Springer was expected to go on
the disabled list following Thursday night's game with Cincinnati.
Mark Wohlers, who has lost his control and closer's job but pitched
encouragingly Wednesday, agreed to a second assignment to Class AAA
Richmond. But for only 10 days, not 15.
</P>
<P>
   With the club flying to San Francisco immediately after
Thursday's game for tonight's start of a nine-game West Coast road
trip, Braves officials were still deciding which Richmond pitchers
would take Springer's and Wohlers' roster spots. One possibility:
Mike Cather, who was optioned to Richmond July 15. Cather was out
last week with an inflamed tendon but was scheduled to work an
inning Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Three Richmond relievers who won't make the jump: Pedro Borbon,
whose rehabilitation assignment there was extended Wednesday for
another 15 days, through Aug. 20; and right-hander Paul Wagner and
left-hander Norm Charlton, both signed Wednesday and assigned to
Richmond. Wagner and his 7.11 ERA were released by Milwaukee late
last month; Charlton (2-1, 6.94) was released July 28 by Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Since returning from Richmond July 15 after a special assignment
to try to regain his control, Wohlers had struggled badly yet said
he wouldn't accept another minor-league assignment. But after
pitching better Wednesday (walking Barry Larkin after just missing
low with a 3-2 fastball, then striking out Dmitri Young), Wohlers
agreed to go down to Richmond for 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to go and pitch,'' said Wohlers, ``but I don't need to
be gone for 15 days.''
</P>
<P>
   With Springer out, though, manager Bobby Cox couldn't afford to
risk going to the West Coast short one pitcher. Not the way Wohlers
has pitched the last three weeks, when he hasn't been able to get
through an inning, causing Cox to burn another reliever each time
Wohlers pitched.
</P>
<P>
   Springer, meanwhile, was again in pain after a bad outing
Wednesday. Entering the ninth inning with the score tied 9-9,
Springer lasted two-thirds of an inning, gave up four hits and two
walks and was charged with four earned runs and the loss. On
Thursday, he was examined by team orthopedist Dr. Joe Chandler, who
X-rayed bone spurs on his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I basically just wanted to see if the spurs were still
attached to the elbow. They were,'' said Springer, who had a couple
of spurs removed from the same place (the back of the elbow, where
the triceps meets the elbow) in late October 1995.
</P>
<P>
   These spurs began bothering him about two months before the
All-Star break, while he was still with Arizona. Springer was on
anti-inflammatory medicine there, just like he is here. Springer
got a cortisone shot Thursday and had planned to rest two days,
resume light tossing and then throw from a mound Tuesday in San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't gonna feel one way or the other until I see how this
cortisone works,'' said Springer. ``Right now, I'm not doing
anybody _ the team or me _ any good.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Springer had hoped to avoid the DL, his elbow,
Wohlers' situation and the road trip necessitated that move. And
others.
</P>
<P>
   Go West
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to scheduling problems due to expansion and interleague
play, this is Atlanta's only West Coast trip of the year. ``It's
been so long, seems like we haven't been out to California in five
years,'' said Cox. ``Interleague, interleague, interleague did it.
We always enjoy going to California, always been a pleasurable
trip.''
</P>
<P>
   This trip is more business, with San Diego leading the NL West
and battling the Braves for the best record in the league; and San
Francisco contending for the NL wild card. Even Los Angeles has
wild card hopes. After this trip, those three teams come to Atlanta
for seven games. That's 16 straight games against one, and perhaps
two, teams the Braves could see in the post-season. Time for an
October preview?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it makes any difference,'' Cox said. ``You can
only see a team so many times. I guess there's a little advantage
for both teams, but who knows? The Cubbies are the wild card team
right now and we were finished with them two months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's an important road trip for us,'' said Chipper
Jones. ``We could play these teams in the playoffs. It's important
to get that mental edge against them, if there is such a thing. A
lot of people think the Padres, us and the Astros are the three
best teams in the National League. When we go to San Diego, we want
to be at the top of our game.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
