<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Klesko swinging back into form
 &HT;    By Michael Lee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Big Cat always seems to carry a big smile rivaled only by
his size. Of late, Andres Galarraga has had good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Thursday's game, he was on a 10-for-23 surge amid an
eight-game hitting streak, which grew to nine games with a
sixth-inning home run, his 34th. But that wasn't all.
</P>
<P>
   The smile was for the guy who hits behind him, Ryan Klesko, who
is hitting .352 with seven homers and 27 RBIs in his last 35 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's especially good for the team,'' Galarraga said. ``But
it's a big help for me because I'm not seeing many good pitches
right now. More protection on my side.''
</P>
<P>
   Klesko sat out against left-hander Mike Remlinger, but in the
first inning of Wednesday night's game against the Reds, he gave
Galarraga and two other teammates tickets home via his 16th homer
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   It was Klesko's second homer since he returned to the roster
July 12. He missed nine games after having his appendix removed on
June 29.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the arthroscopic surgery, Klesko had a torrid month in
which he hit .382 with five homers and 16 RBIs. Klesko also raised
his batting average, which had been a season-low .236 on June 2, to
.271. Since his return, he has remained a pain in the side for
opposing pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before Andres got here, (Klesko) was the bomber of the team,''
catcher Javy Lopez said. ``We all knew that sooner or later, he was
going to produce. We were just waiting for him to wake up. He's
doing it at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Klesko concedes he was a tad sluggish when he came back, but
feels he's at full strength now. His average is up to .284.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been feeling pretty good,'' Klesko said. ``I'm up to par
... getting back in the swing of things.''
</P>
<P>
   But not the old swing-and-miss. This season Klesko has only 42
strikeouts in 310 at-bats. In 137 more at-bats last year, he
whiffed a team-high 130 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what, I'm always hungry. Sometimes I'm too
aggressive,'' Klesko said. ``The difference has been my pitch
selection.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of those guys who never stops working,'' said hitting
coach Clarence Jones. ``He's doing great and that's a plus for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Braves prepare for their first and only trip of the
season to California for nine games, the native of Orange County,
Calif., is looking forward to more than facing his West Coast foes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, most of my relatives are out there,'' Klesko said. ``We
get a day off, too. Me and some of the guys are going yellowtail
fishing in San Diego. It ought to be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
