<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore unities Florida Democratic party
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A fragile truce within the Democratic Party is being attempted
today with the hope that Lt.Gov. Buddy MacKay will finally get an
endorsement from U.S. Rep. Alcee Hastings.
</P>
<P>
   A private ``unity meeting'' with Hastings, MacKay and Vice
President Al Gore and about 25 others is scheduled for 2:30 this
afternoon at the Fort Lauderdale Sheraton. That meeting will be
followed by Gore's appearance at a money raising event for the
Florida Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   The unity meeting, orchestrated by Hasting, D-Miramar, may be
anything but unified. Some black members of the Florida House of
Representatives resent Hastings' aggressive attacks on black
leaders and what they perceive as his interference in state
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Some black lawmakers also complained that they were not invited
to the meeting with Gore and believe Hastings was slighting them.
As a result, there may be a second meeting between Gore and black
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Support from Hastings and other black leaders would be an
important political moment for MacKay. The Democratic nominee for
governor has little chance of defeating Republican nominee Jeb Bush
without overwhelming support from black voters.
</P>
<P>
   Few wanted to talk openly about today's meetings describing the
situation as ``volatile'' and ``unsettled.'' There was even a fear
that Hastings could, at the last minute, change his mind about
endorsing MacKay if MacKay doesn't give blacks a larger role in the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, MacKay will begin broadcasting his first campaign
commercial on Monday in West Palm Beach, Miami and other markets.
Frontrunner Bush has been on the air for weeks and MacKay's
campaign hopes the commericials will help close the gap.
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-08-06-98 2113E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
