</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WITCH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENVIRONMENTALISTS CLAIM `WITCH HUNT' BY ALASKA REP. DON YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
 HUNT-ALLEGED-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Don Young, the powerful chairman of the House
Resources Committee, wants to know if federal employees ``are
members of'' or ``have any contact with'' Arizona environmental
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists blasted the move as a ``witch hunt,'' and
likened it to the 1950s-era efforts of Sen. Joseph McCarthy to
search for communists in the ranks of government.
</P>
<P>
   Young's attempt to connect federal employees to environmental
groups is contained in a letter to the Southwest regional office of
the U.S. Forest Service. The letter stemmed from a congressional
hearing last month into the federal Endangered Species Act and how
it is being administered in Arizona and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hansen, a spokesman for Young's committee, said Young and
others don't believe they received complete or accurate answers
from U.S. Forest Service officials. He said an investigation is
being made into allegations that federal employees illegally leaked
federal documents to environmental groups and that those documents
later were used in lawsuits against the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen said he could not comment whether these were
congressional investigations or criminal investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists said Young's letter already is having a
``chilling effect'' on federal employees' ability to uphold the law
and communicate with the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Don Young is the Joe McCarthy of the 1990s. Anyone who
stands up for the environment, Don Young brings to his knees,''
said Sam Hitt, president of the Santa Fe-based Forest Guardians.
</P>
<P>
   Hitt's group, along with the Southwest Center for Biological
Diversity, the Sierra Club and the Wilderness Society are among the
groups mentioned in Young's July 28 letter to Eleanor Towns,
recently named by the Clinton administration as regional forester
for the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Young, R-Alaska, ordered Towns to respond to 19 questions by
Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to the Forest Service regional office in Albuquerque were
not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Young's committee staff wants to know details of
an agreement reached in April between the Forest Service and
environmental groups that calls for removing cattle from hundreds
of miles of rivers and streams in the Southwest in an effort to
save endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen said there are allegations that the Forest Service acted
in a biased manner in favor of the environmentalists and against
ranchers in reaching the agreement, which partially settled a
federal lawsuit brought by environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   Among the allegations being investigated, Hansen said, are:
``that there had been contact prior to the (court) hearing, deals
had been made, certain parties had been excluded, so they went into
it as a done deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Hitt's charges of McCarthyism, Hansen said, ``If he
is insinuating that environmentalists are like communists, ... I
have no control over his thinking process. But it's pretty clear
that anybody and everybody who has done nothing wrong here is
sleeping fine tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Hansen said federal employees should be concerned ``if there has
been this free-flow of documents in lawsuits against the federal
government.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Young's letter to the Forest Service was leaked to
the media is an example of how freely the information moves, Hansen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Galvin, conservation biologists for the Southwest Center
for Biological Diversity, said environmentalists are sent documents
from a wide variety of government agencies by employees who are
frustrated over their agencies' failure to uphold the Endangered
Species Act and other environmental laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most cases, these employees are beating their heads agains
the wall. The agencies are stacked with corrupt or gutless
bureaucrats,'' said Galvin, whose groups plans today to file yet
another lawsuit against the Forest Service.
</P>
<P>
   The latest lawsuit, to be filed in U.S. District Court in
Tucson, alleges that the Forest Service failed to protect five
endangered species _ Gila topminnow, lesser long-nosed bat, cactus
ferruginous pygmy owl, Huachuca water umbel and Yaqui chub _ by
allowing excessive livestock grazing across the Coronado National
Forest in southern and southeastern Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit is similar to the one that resulted in April's
agreement between the Forest Service and environmental groups that
affected 60 ranchers in central and eastern Arizona and parts of
New Mexico. &QL; 
Steve Yozwiak can be reached at 444-8810 or at
steve.yozwiak(at)pni.com via the Internet. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
