u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWIM-SMITH-DRUGS-1STL     08-06 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWIM-SMITH-DRUGS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHELLE SMITH, OLYMPIC GOLD MEDAL SWIMMER, BANNED FOR TAMPERING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (recasts lede graf to say `career appeared to end in disgrace';
clarifies to `manipulated a drug test by spiking her urine sample
with alcohol')  (ART ADV: Photo of Michelle Smith is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(Eds.: budgeted earlier as SWIM-DEBRUIN-DRUGS) 
(JT) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The career of Michelle Smith, the Irish swimmer who won three
gold medals at the 1996 Summer Olympics, appeared to end in
disgrace Thursday when swimming's world governing body banned her
from competition for four years after finding that she had
manipulated a drug test by spiking her urine sample with alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Even as she won her Olympic races in Atlanta and was
congratulated in person by President Clinton, suspicions arose
about the authenticity of Smith's performances, given that her
times had improved dramatically late in her career. Suspicion
continued to grow after Smith failed to appear for at least one
drug test following the Atlanta Games.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Thursday's announcement was shattering in Ireland, where
Smith had become a heroine as the country's first woman to win an
Olympic gold medal. Now she has become of most accomplished
athletes ever to be banned in a drug scandal. Her case is also
noteworthy because it is relatively rare for an athlete to be
caught cheating by tampering with a urine sample.
</P>
<P>
   Her banishment follows a long list of suspensions for Chinese
female swimmers and is the latest in a series of drug scandals that
have staggered Olympic-related sports this summer. The scandals
have prompted the International Olympic Committee to call for a
worldwide drug summit next January in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a shame that someone who has competed on such a
high level would be in this situation, but you've got to compete
with integrity and it's important to train with integrity,'' said
Anita DeFrantz of Los Angeles, the first woman to be selected as a
vice president of the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   Later this month, DeFrantz will attend a meeting of the IOC's
executive board in Lausanne, at which time plans will begin for a
reappraisal of the Olympic committee's drug-testing policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wish is that we can find ways to make certain that sport at
all levels is both safe and fair for the athletes,'' DeFrantz said
in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Last January 10, Smith was given an unannounced drug test in
Dublin as part of an out-of-competition doping control program
administered by FINA, swimming's world governing body. Random,
out-of-competition testing is considered a more reliable way to
catch cheating athletes, who are more likely to beat announced
tests taken at major competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Her sample, tested in a Barcelona laboratory accredited by the
IOC, was found to have ``unequivocal signs of adulteration,''
according to the lab report.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that the concentration of alcohol present in the
sample ``is in no way compatible with human consumption'' and that
the sample showed ``a very strong whiskey odor.''
</P>
<P>
   A second test on Smith's urine sample was performed on May 21
and the results were compatible with the January test, according to
FINA. At a hearing on July 24, a federation doping panel found that
the sample had been manipulated in an uncertain manner by Smith and
not by the laboratory, the collectors or the transporters of the
sample.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Smith was banned from national and international
competition for four years, which makes her ineligible for the 2000
Summer Games in Sydney, Australia. It is highly unlikely that
Smith, now 28, would be able to remain in competitive form for the
2004 Summer Games in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Drug experts suspect that the use of a substance such as alcohol
to manipulate a drug sample is an attempt to mask the use of
performance-enhancing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has continued to maintain that she does not use
performance-enhancing drugs. Neither she nor her attorney commented
on Thursday's banishment, but Smith is scheduled to hold a news
conference Friday in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   She has said previously that she would appeal any ban to the
Swiss-based International Court of Arbitration for Sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``The swimmer stressed that no banned substance had been
detected in her urine,'' FINA said of Smith, referring to her
presence at the July 24 doping panel hearing. ``She asserts that
from her side there was no physical manipulation of the sample.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's suspension is part of an embarrassing summer for sport
that saw the world's top cycling team was thrown out of the Tour de
France for the systematic use of EPO, a substance which increases
oxygen-carrying capacity. And last week, two other Olympic gold
medalists from the United States _ the 1996 shot put champion Randy
Barnes and the 1992 4x100-meter relay member Dennis Mitchell _ were
suspended by track and field's world governing body for possible
doping offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, American swimmers and coaches said they thought that
Smith's ban was a sign that FINA's assertive new doping control
program was working.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think FINA is doing the right thing with its out of
competition testing program,'' Carol Zaleski, president of the
United States Swimming Federation, said in an interview.
``Obviously people who are using things they shouldn't are most
likely to be caught there rather than in a competitive situation.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Atlanta Games, Janet Evans, along with other American
coaches and swimmers, questioned the legitimacy of Smith's
performances because she had moved to the top of international
competition at a relatively late age and after a mediocre career.
For instance, she was not ranked among the top 25 swimmers at any
distance, for any stroke, as late as 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Further suspicions were raised by the fact that her husband,
Erik de Bruin, a Dutch discus thrower, had been suspended by track
and field's world governing body for excessive levels of
testosterone, the male sex hormone that can also be used as a
muscle-building steroid. Both Smith and her husband said that her
performances were improved by weight lifting and by using the
training techniques of track and field athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard all the rumors; I tried to keep an open mind,''
Zaleski said. ``At that point, everything was circumstantial. The
fact that her urine sample was manipulated gives credence to those
suspicions. The kind of improvement she showed a couple of years
prior to the Olympics, based on her age, was extremely unusual. The
coaching community was up in arms about her. But, again, there was
no proof of anything.''
</P>
<P>
   In Dublin Thursday, Jim McDaid, Ireland's sports minister, said
that Smith's ban was a ``personal tragedy for the swimmer and her
family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like the rest of the Irish people, I'm saddened and
disappointed by this development,'' McDaid said.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish swimming federation said it accepted FINA's ruling,
pending the outcome of an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``As this is the first case of a drug-related penalty in the
104-year history of Irish swimming, it is the source of major
concern to everyone in the Irish swimming community,'' the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-98 2203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
