<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDS-CHAIRMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEF OF ELECTRONIC DATA SYSTEMS RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALLEN R. MYERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Lester Alberthal Jr., under pressure from board members
and shareholders to turn a faltering Electronic Data Systems
around, has resigned as chairman and chief executive, the company
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The board plans to recruit an outsider to lead the company,
whose shares and prospects have dropped since a spinoff from
General Motors in 1996. Until then, Alberthal, only the company's
second leader after its founder, Ross Perot, had succeeded in
multiplying its sales and profits around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Alberthal has become the latest of several corporate chiefs
to resign this year after performance suffered and board members
grew restive.
</P>
<P>
   The company, refusing to make Alberthal or any other board
members available for interviews, said that he was leaving for
personal and professional reasons in no way related to the
company's fortunes or board or shareholder discontent. ``His
decision to retire was voluntary,'' said Cecilia Stubbs Norwood, a
company spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   But conversations between board members and major shareholders
came to figure in Alberthal's resignation, people briefed on or
involved in the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, EDS has lost its lead in the computer services
industry to IBM. In an increasingly competitive market, several
major contracts have proved less profitable than anticipated _
among them its business with GM, which remains by far its largest
customer.
</P>
<P>
   The California Public Employees Retirement System, known as
Calpers, included EDS on its 1998 list of the nation's worst
corporate performers. In May, the fund's proposal to have Alberthal
hand over his chairmanship to an independent director, though
remaining as chief executive, won 21 percent of shareholder votes.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Pacheco, a fund spokesman, said he was encouraged by the
announcement of Alberthal's resignation, made after the stock
market closed. ``It's definitely time for new leadership at the
helm of EDS,'' Pacheco said.
</P>
<P>
   The General Motors pension fund voted against the Calpers
proposal, but its representatives discreetly communicated their own
misgivings to the board, according to a person involved in these
discussions. The fund has been reducing its EDS holdings, and now
has about a 26 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   Alberthal installed the board himself when EDS split from GM.
Calpers questioned whether those board members could exercise true
oversight, noting that five of the 11, including James Baker III,
the former secretary of state, either work for or do business with
the company. Although Baker's law firm serves EDS, the company has
said that Baker does not.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of the board's governance committee, however, Baker
appeared to take the lead in questioning the company's management.
In the company's statement Thursday, Baker thanked Alberthal for
his service and for agreeing to stay and take part in the search
for his successor.
</P>
<P>
   Alberthal, 54, joined EDS 30 years ago as a systems engineer.
Perot sold the company to GM for $2.55 billion in 1984, and
Alberthal took over as chief executive two years later and became
chairman in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The special class of stock that GM issued to track EDS'
performance yielded vast gains. But since their peak of $63.375 in
October 1996, EDS shares have fallen to a close of $36.6875
Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
