<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAANALYSIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREDICTABLY, TALKS BREAK DOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM McCURDIE  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. -- After less than two hours at the
bargaining table Thursday, representatives of the NBA's players and
owners decided to break for lunch. Apparently, all that talk about
salary caps, Bird exceptions and ``basketball-related income'' can
work up quite an appetite.
</P>
<P>
   But when the sides returned from their respective Manhattan
eateries, indigestion set in. Commissioner David Stern was suddenly
so overcome that he left the room.
</P>
<P>
   And, predictably, the day ended with the players and owners no
closer to a new agreement than they were on June 22, when a similar
meeting broke off after all of 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Lockout rolls on, with no bolt cutters in sight.
</P>
<P>
   What were you expecting? A breakthrough? In August? Not with the
kind of money at stake here. If you believe the doom and gloom
that's been projected by both sides, we could still be waiting for
meaningful progress on Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   Stern and a group of owners that included the Lakers' Jerry Buss
walked out of Thursday's meeting after representatives of the
players' union outlined a proposal that included no provisions to
reel in the ever-escalating growth of player salaries, at least for
those at the top of the pay scale.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the walkout was met with disdain by some of
the dozen or so NBA players in attendance. Those included Utah Jazz
forward Karl Malone, who took a break from his busy summer on the
pro wrestling circuit to sit in on the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have told them anything and they would have walked
out,'' Malone said. ``If I hadn't been here, I would not have
believed this. It's hard to believe someone is taking their ball
and going home.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern, the kid with the ball, said he was mildly encouraged by
the tenor of the meeting's morning session. ``We thought some hair
was let down, and that people were talking rather than posturing,''
he said in a conference call with reporters late Thursday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   It must have been nice while it lasted. But the first sit-down
session between the sides since June 22 ended abruptly, shortly
after the lunch break, when players' union attorney Jeffrey Kessler
informed the owners that they are in danger of losing on an unfair
labor practices charge filed to the National Labor Relations board,
and on a ruling to be handed down by arbitrator John Feerick on
whether approximately 220 players with guaranteed contracts should
be paid during the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, there was no point in letting our owners respond,''
Stern said, ``because the words they were using were insulting and
patronizing. We felt the better part of valor was to end the
session, rather than have it deteriorate.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Hunter, executive director of the players' union,
intimated that Stern's indignation was ``feigned,'' that the
walkout was choreographed for dramatic effect.
</P>
<P>
   Said Russ Granik, the NBA's deputy commissioner and chief
operation officer: ``What went on in their lunch to cause them to
shift gears, we don't know. We can only surmise that their counsel
told them, `You don't want to do anything constructive until you
play out the legal string.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, all of this might be interpreted as a sign of
progress. Real negotiations in professional sports labor relations
matters don't truly begin until talks ``break down'' a time or two,
and the name-calling starts.
</P>
<P>
   The core issues here are, of course, money, money and money.
</P>
<P>
   The owners claim they are devoting approximately 57 percent of
their basketball-related income to player salaries, and they want a
deal that reduces that number. They think the way to do that is to
eliminate the so-called ``Larry Bird exception'' to the league's
salary cap, which allows teams to re-sign their free agents without
regard to the cap, and by a system that doesn't permit rookies to
become free agents after only three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The players say they are united in wanting the lucrative Bird
exception to remain in place, and has proposed a plan that would
give teams right of first refusal for players at the end of the
three-year contracts they sign as rookies.
</P>
<P>
   Stern said the players' representatives indicated they may be
agreeable to including ``appropriate marijuana provisions'' into a
new agreement. That qualifies as some progress. But don't expect
the pace of these talks to quicken anytime soon, especially with
the way Thursday's session ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm saddened by this,'' Stern said. ``I know that we'll be
sitting down to make a deal at some point. It's just a question of
how much damage will be done (by then).''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
