<HEADER>
A2033 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-ART-1ST     08-06 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-500(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONICA LEWINISKY TESTIFIES FOR SIX AND A HALF HOURS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs for additions. The bottom half is new, as is graf 3.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(lh) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr. and JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ending months of anticipation with a resigned
shrug, Monica Lewinsky, the former intern, walked into a federal
courthouse here Thursday and testified that she and President
Clinton carried on a sexual affair within the White House, a lawyer
familiar with her account said.
</P>
<P>
   Her testimony before a federal grand jury, which contradicted a
previous sworn statement, tightened the legal and political vise
around President Clinton. The president denied a sexual
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky under oath in the Paula Jones sexual
misconduct lawsuit, and he has denied it as well to the American
people.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky testified to several sexual encounters with Clinton
in his small, private study down a short hallway from the Oval
Office, the lawyer said. As expected, she also testified that she
and the president had talked about ways to conceal their
relationship, the lawyer said, but she also said that he never
directly told her to lie under oath in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent prosecutor, is
investigating accusations that Clinton lied under oath and
obstructed justice by trying to conceal the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   More than six months of waiting for Ms. Lewinsky to tell her
story ended just before 8:30 a.m., when she stepped from a dark
green Toyota Land Cruiser, embraced a lawyer, shrugged and vanished
inside. As portable generators rumbled in the background and one
cameraman swept the scene from a cherrypicker 50 feet over Third
Street, about 20 satellite trucks beamed images of Ms. Lewinsky _
once an unpaid, anonymous sorter of White House mail _ around the
planet.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky, 25, answered questions in exchange for immunity
from prosecution for any wrongdoing she describes. In a deal worked
out with prosecutors nine days ago, she is vulnerable to
prosecution only if she lies in her testimony. In an affidavit on
Jan. 7 in the Jones case, Ms. Lewinsky swore that she did not have
a sexual relationship with the president.
</P>
<P>
   An associate of Ms. Lewinsky's described her six and a half
hours before the grand jury as grueling. ``She was asked very
specific questions about very private matters which are very hard
to discuss in public,'' the associate said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ms. Lewinsky has agonized for months over the prospect
of damaging Clinton's presidency, friends have said. One of her
friends described Ms. Lewinsky as saying Wednesday night, as she
prepared for her testimony, ``What I'm doing tomorrow is something
I never ever wanted to do. It breaks my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Before a media mob after Ms. Lewinsky completed her testimony,
her spokeswoman, Judy Smith, said that she answered questions from
prosecutors and jurors ``truthfully, completely and honestly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica and her family are relieved that this ordeal finally
appears to be coming to an end,'' Ms. Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has never publicly described his relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky in any detail, beyond saying that it was not sexual.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a capital whipsawed between disclosure and denial, starkly
different days unspooled at the federal courthouse and the White
House. Summoning the authority and trappings of his office, as well
as his own storied political resilience, President Clinton went
about his official duties Thursday without betraying a hint of
interest in his former intern's testimony just a few blocks down
Pennsylvania Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have looked forward to this day for quite a long time,''
Clinton said in one speech at a Washington hotel, referring to his
opportunity to address a White House conference on building
economic self-improvement in Indian communities.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, the president appeared before a row of
uniformed police officers in the sun-gilded Rose Garden to call for
a permanent five-day waiting period for people seeking to buy
handguns. With a quick left-handed salute after the official
remarks, the president cued a brassy Marine band to strike up
``Stars and Stripes Forever.'' Reporters waiting to shout questions
about Ms. Lewinsky were stymied.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Toiv, a White House spokesman, provided the official
reaction to the testimony. ``The president has not expressed any
views to us on this,'' he said, ``except we know that he does agree
with us _ and probably all Americans _ that if this means that
we're coming to the end of this four-year, over $40 million
investigation, then that would be a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   For all their restraint, White House advisers telephoned
reporters late this evening to ask what they knew of Ms. Lewinsky's
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Ms. Lewinsky's version of her relationship with
the president was still in doubt. But Starr's investigation has
rushed forward since then, with her immunity agreement and
Clinton's own promise to testify at the White House on Aug. 17. In
striking the deal with Starr, Ms. Lewinsky also turned over a navy
blue dress that prosecutors have sent for testing by the Federal
Bureau of Investigation. They are trying to determine if the dress
contained physical evidence of a sexual encounter with the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky was asked a series of questions about the dress
Thursday. Prosecutors have left open the possibility of recalling
Ms. Lewinsky before the grand jury, perhaps after the president
testifies.
</P>
<P>
   Since mid-January, Ms. Lewinsky's relationship with the
president has been the stuff of fevered speculation in the news
media and tawdry late-night comedy. She herself has remained in
virtual isolation, cautioned by her lawyers not to speak to anyone
outside her family.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters from across the country and around the world converged
on the courthouse Thursday, clucking over the spectacle and
contributing to it at the same time. Some reporters began claiming
choice spots as early as Wednesday evening for a glimpse of Ms.
Lewinsky _ only to be flummoxed Thursday morning as she took an
unexpected route through the courthouse, up to the third floor in
an elevator reserved for judges.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, as passers-by stopped to take in the scene, scores of
photographers lined up for a shot of her. When George Hancock, a
supporter of Ms. Lewinsky's from Bowling Green, Ky., tried to raise
his yellow sign wishing her luck, he cut off their line of sight.
``You wave that sign again,'' shouted one cameraman, ``I'll kill
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Ducking out of view, Hancock was surrounded moments later by
reporters and photographers, some of whom berated him while others
tried to interview him. ``How's it make you feel, buddy?'' Dominic
Mumeka, 33, murmured as if to himself as he stood off to one side.
``This is your 15 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Mumeka, who cleans a taxi depot, said he had dropped by to watch
history be made. ``There hasn't been anything like this since
Watergate, and before that since Andrew Johnson, 1869,'' he said.
But, he asked, ``Can a guy really get impeached for going to bed
with someone?''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the passers-by drawn to the drama Thursday expressed
irritation at the news media's panting pursuit of the story. As
reporters and bystanders pushed and shoved for position at Ms.
Smith's brief appearance late this afternoon, one cameraman
snapped: ``All you damn spectators can see it on TV. We have to be
here so you can watch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jeckanowski, a 28-year-old economist, shot back: ``You
cause all this.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House has resolutely refused to question Ms.
Lewinsky's credibility publicly. But fragmentary accounts have
emerged that White House officials were concerned that she had a
crush on the president.
</P>
<P>
   An Indianapolis lawyer who has worked as a Democratic operative
said in an interview Thursday that he had been asked to keep an eye
on Ms. Lewinsky at an Oct. 23, 1996, fund-raiser at the Sheraton
Hotel here to ensure that she did not ``embarrass the president.''
</P>
<P>
   John J. Sullivan, a lobbyist and lawyer from Indianapolis, said
that he was asked by a friend, Regan Burke, to keep an eye on Ms.
Lewinsky because she had recently left the White House and there
were concerns she was ``disgruntled.'' Ms. Burke works at the
Department of Education and was unavailable for comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `We don't know if she has fantasized a relationship
with the president,''' Sullivan recalled Thursday. ``But she keeps
showing up at these events.''
</P>
<P>
   At the fund-raiser, Sullivan said that he stood behind Ms.
Lewinsky on the rope line and chatted with her briefly. As Clinton
began shaking hands with supporters, Sullivan said, he watched Ms.
Lewinsky reach out with both hands to hug the president. ``And he
hugged her back,'' he said. ``Then he said to her, `How are you
doing?' She said, `Fine.' He said, `How's your new job?' And she
said, `Great.' He said, `I wish you the best of luck,' and that was
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said he spoke on Monday with a CBS television station
in Indianapolis about what he had seen. In a sign that the White
House is following up any lead to bolster Clinton's story, Sullivan
said that on Wednesday David E. Kendall, the president's personal
lawyer, called him to ask a number of questions.
</P>
<P>
   He said he felt no pressure by anyone to tell his story
publicly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
