<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 8/06/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) NEW YORK -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- DETECTIVE-PROFILE, 8-6 --
Les Levine knows the whole repertory of private investigator
tricks. ``I've been told - not by my kids - that I'm not as warm
and affectionate and demonstrative as they would like me to be,''
he says. ``I'm not a flowery guy. I don't squeeze people and tell
them I love them. But people who know me refer to me as a rough,
tough pussycat.'' (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- RENO-CONTEMPT, 8-6 -- A
House committee voted along party lines Thursday to charge Attorney
General Janet Reno with contempt of Congress, transforming into a
criminal case the battle over whether an independent counsel should
be appointed to investigate and prosecute campaign finance abuses.
The full House will not take up the matter until after a four-week
recess that begins Friday. (Carol T. Powers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- PETER-PAN-FOUND, 8-6 -- A
statue of Peter Pan that had disappeared from a park near Gracie
Mansion is found by police divers in the East River on Thursday.
Investigators say the disappearance of the beloved statue from Carl
Schurz Park appears, appropriately enough, to be the work of a band
of overly high-spirited youths, perhaps latter-day Lost Boys who
turned on their own icon. (Barbara Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) MCLEAN, Va. -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- CLINTON-STARR, 8-6 --
Independent prosecutor Kenneth Starr leaving his home in McLean on
Thursday morning. Ending months of anticipation with a resigned
shrug, Monica Lewinsky, the former intern, walked into a federal
courthouse here Thursday and testified that she and President
Clinton carried on a sexual affair within the White House,
according to a lawyer familiar with her account. (Justin Lane/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- ALASKA-OIL, 8-6 -- Sen.
Ted Stevens, the senior member of the Alaskan delegation, making a
point in Washington recently. The Interior Department said Thursday
that it would open a new expanse of the Alaska North Slope
wilderness to oil and gas leasing, but it limited drilling in some
areas that the industry is most eager to explore. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) AYLESBURY, England -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- VW-ROLLS, 8-6 --
Michael Shrimpton, a British lawyer and Bentley owner, spearheaded
an unsuccessful attempt earlier this year to raise enough money
from Rolls-Royce and Bentley owners to keep both names in British
hands. ``It's a disaster; it will kill off both marques,'' says
Shrimpton, 41. ``The trademark is worth more than the assets.''
(Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- CAMPAIGN-FINANCE, 8-6 --
Rep. Christopher Shays receiving a hug by a supporter Thursday
after approval of a campaign finance bill he sponsored. Ending a
struggle that has gone on for months, the House on Thursday
approved a bipartisan bill to overhaul the way the nation's
political campaigns are financed and shifted the spotlight back
onto the Senate. In a final rebuke to the Republican leadership,
the House vote for passage of the measure was 252-179. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) TODI, Italy -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- ITALY-UMBRIA-RETREAT-2,
8-6 -- Janie Lee and David Warren, museum curators, are among the
prominent Americans who make Todi their home in summer. All around
this medieval city, wealthy Americans have lovingly restored
14th-century fortresses, abbeys and farmhouses, and added luxury
bathrooms, swimming pools and tennis courts. Theirs is a search for
beauty, isolation and upper-class comfort. (James Hill/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) TODI, Italy -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- ITALY-UMBRIA-RETREAT-1,
8-6 -- Todi, a medieval town in Umbria, has been colonized by
Americans. Theirs is a search for beauty, isolation and upper-class
comfort. The province is not just rivaling neighboring Tuscany as
Italy's most alluring and expensive summer retreat. For America's
Happy Few, Todi is becoming as fashionable as Martha's Vineyard or
the Hamptons. (James Hill/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- CLINTON-LEWINSKY, 8-6 --
Monica Lewinsky leaving Federal Court after testifying in front of
a grand jury Thursday. At left is one of her attorneys, Plato
Cacheris. In long hours of testimony fraught with peril for Bill
Clinton, Ms. Lewinsky told grand jurors her firsthand account of an
improbable relationship with the president. (Stephen Crowley/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) SEASIDE, Calif. -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- CALIF-MISSING-GIRL,
8-6 -- Michael Williams, whose daughter Christina, 13, is missing,
at his home in Seaside with her dog, Greg. The youngest in a family
of five, Christina took her dog, Greg, for a walk in the
neighborhood on the evening of June 12. About a half-hour later, he
wandered back alone. ``I feel like we're stuck in a bad 'Twilight
Zone' episode,'' says Williams. (Darcy Padilla/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- VACCINE-TERROR-2,
8-6 -- Dr. Thomas Monath, a vice president of OraVax. Based in
Cambridge, OraVax was founded in 1990 to tap an emerging
multi-billion-dollar market in oral vaccines and antibodies to
combat infectious diseases. But the small company kept having
problems getting beyond research and bringing products to market.
(Pat Greenhouse/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- VACCINE-TERROR-1,
8-6 -- A researcher for the vaccine manufacturer Oravax takes a
bacteria sample for analysis. In 1996 and 1997, its survival at
stake, OraVax tried to win part of the Pentagon's expanding germ
work as a subcontractor to make smallpox and other vaccines. But by
early this year, that work had failed to materialize and the
company's stock price was down 90 percent from $10 a share in the
initial public offering. (Pat Greenhouse/Boston Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) ATLANTA -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- SWIM-SMITH-DRUGS, 8-6 --
Michelle Smith of Ireland after winning the gold in the women's
400m freestyle during the 1996 Olympics. Smith, who won three gold
medals in Atlanta, effectively had her Olympic career terminated
when she was banned from competition for four years after being
found guilty of manipulating a urine sample with alcohol, the
sport's international governing body said Thursday. (Jose R.
Lopez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) LENOX, Mass. -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- BERKSHIRES-WHARTON-B&AMP;W,
8-6 -- The room where Melville wrote ``Moby-Dick,'' at Arrowhead
farm. Lenox is an easy three-hour drive up the Taconic Parkway from
New York City, with meandering country roads to perk up the last
leg. (Don Heiny/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- NY-PARK-STATUES-2, 8-6 --
The statue of Adm. David Farragut in Manhattan's Madison Square
Park. New York City gave Farragut $50,000 to buy a home after his
Civil War successes. The pedestal to this early Saint-Gaudens
masterpiece, a sort of swirling triptych with two curving flanks,
seems lighter and more animate than the statue it supports. (Jack
Manning/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- NY-PARK-STATUES-1, 8-6 --
The statue of William Seward, the New York governor who became
Abraham Lincoln's Secretary of State, in Manhattan's Madison Square
Park. He sits casually, legs crossed, looking away from the state
paper that rests on an arm of his chair. This is the Seward who
bought Alaska for a song, serenely redeemed for his folly, enjoying
an eternal I-told-you-so. (Jack Manning/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- EVANS-PHOTOGRAPHY-REVIEW,
8-6 -- ``Torn Movie Poster,'' a blowup of a Walker Evans photograph
at the Laurence Miller Gallery. The show offers some blowups of
Evans' photographs that were printed from his negatives as part of
the wall decoration for his retrospective at the Museum of Modern
Art 27 years ago. (Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- ANTIQUES-COLUMN, 8-6 -- A
chinoiserie smoked-mirror dressing table, made in the late 1920s.
Despite its superficial modernity and streamlined chic, mirrored
furniture is a venerable, if underexplored, facet of the antiques
world. (Joyce Dopkeen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- TV-SEINFELD-REVIEW, 8-6 --
Jerry Seinfeld at a news conference at HBO headquarters in
Manhattan on Tuesday. Freshness is precisely not the point of
``Jerry Seinfeld: 'I'm Telling You For the Last Time' - Live on
Broadway.'' Looking backward is. New York is the last stop and
Sunday's live television show, broadcast on HBO, the final
performance in a two-month world tour. (J. Emilio Flores/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) BRIDGEHAMPTON, N.Y. -- Aug. 6, 1998 --
BRIDGEHAMPTON-MUSIC-FESTIVAL, 8-6 -- Marya Martin and her group
practicing at the Bridgehampton Presbyterian Church, where the
Chamber Music Festival opens its 15th season Sunday. In addition to
the festival, concertgoers can attend programs offered in the
Hamptons this month by two musical training institutes. (Lois
Raimondo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BECKET, Mass. -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- YANKEE-RODEO-2-BOS, 8-6
-- Kyle Robinson managed to hold on for about 4 seconds before
spinning off into the dirt - not long enough to win the
steer-riding contest at the Youth Rodeo in Becket. ``Rodeo is not
about winning, it's about believing you can do it,'' the 7-year-old
says philosophically. ``It's really tough to be a cowboy.'' The
only slightly worried parents say they feel that the risks are well
within acceptable bounds. (Barry Chin/Boston Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BECKET, Mass. -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- YANKEE-RODEO-1-BOS, 8-6
-- Kyle Robinson, left, of New Haven, Conn., and Kyle Payson, of
Wilder, Vt., discuss strategy prior to participating in the novice
steer riding competition in the Youth Rodeo in Becket. Because this
rodeo is especially for youngsters under 18, they ride steers
instead of broncos or bulls. As in adult rodeos, competition also
includes steer-roping, calf-wrestling, and racing horses in a
cloverleaf formation around three barrels. (Barry Chin/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- GENIUS-CAMP-BOS, 8-6
-- Jeremy England, 16, is one of the 80 most gifted high school
seniors in the world - 53 Americans and 27 international students
this year - who are conducting graduate-level independent research
in math and science at Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
Having been branded ``nerds'' and ``geeks'' in their own high
schools, students say here they can walk away from the stereotypes
and find other components of their identities. (Bill Greene/Boston
Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BOSTON -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- SCI-CANCER-V-BOS, 8-6 -- John
Cline of New Hampshire, center, an outpatient at Dana-Farber Cancer
Institute, takes advantage of a ``complementary'' qi gong workshop.
Cancer doctors today are reciting the mantra of ``complementary
therapies'' much as they proclaim the once-scorned virtues of
prevention. This workshop is available to families and caregivers
in addition to patients. (Suzanne Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) HYANNIS, Mass. -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- SCI-CANCER-KENNEDY,
8-6 -- Sen Ted Kennedy with his son Ted Jr. and grandson Ted III.
Ted Jr. was just the fourth participant in a clinical trial of
chemotherapy. Now 36, Ted Jr. can look back with some perspective
on his ordeal. ``My experience has given me a profound appreciation
of everything in my life today,'' he says. (Suzanne Kreiter/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BOSTON -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- SCI-CANCER-III-BOS-2, 8-6 -- At
Massachusetts General Hospital at breast cancer patient undergoes a
new technique of implanting radiocactive tubes into the breast.
Hollow tubes about the size of an intravenous line are inserted at
half-inch intervals around the tumor, then filled with seeds of
radioactive iridium, eliminating the need for less precise external
beams and taking just five days, compared to six weeks with
standard radiation. (Suzanne Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BOSTON -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- SCI-CANCER-III-BOS-1, 8-6 -- At
Massachusetts General Hospital, Dr. Simon Powell, who oversees the
implant program, reviews X-rays of radiation tubes in a patient.
``So far all our patients are fine, but we're still awaiting final
proof in five or 10 years that it's effective,'' Powell says.
(Suzanne Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BOSTON -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- SCI-CANCER-II-BOS-1, 8-6 --
Nelba MacMur, 66, receives SU101, a growth factor inhibitor to
treat her brain tumor whose tentacles couldn't be surgically
removed. Her daughter, Leslie, sits with during a recent treatment.
Leslie says that her mother has experienced few side effects and
has felt ``renewed zest just knowing there's something that could
potentially help her.'' (Suzanne Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BOSTON -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- SCI-CANCER-I-BOS-1, 8-6 -- Emma
Carey, 5, who was diagnosed in February 1997 with Acute
Lymphoblastic Leukemia (ALL,) is comforted by her mother, Tomasen.
She is receiving a maintenance dose of chemotherapy at
Massachusetts General Hospital. Emma's docotrs used a new
``molecular diagnostics'' test to spot telltale genetic alterations
in her blood cells. (Suzanne Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LOS ANGELES -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 9 --
INSTALLATION-ART, 8-6 -- An installation by Robert Gober at the
Museum of Contemporary Art in Los Angeles included suitcase, sewer
grates and this Mondonna and a steel drain pipe. Art today often
seems to aspire to the conditions of theater and film, installation
art above all, depend on a kind of physical interaction with
viewers. (Monica Almedia/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SAN FRANCISCO -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 9 --
INSTALLATION-ART-COLLECTORS, 8-6 -- Nora and Norman Stone
surrounded by a Mike Kelley installation in their exercise room.
Stones, are in their 50s, which is the average age of those who buy
contemporary art these days. But they share a teen-age enthusiasm
for buying the work of young artists who court controversy. Mrs.
Stone concedes, ``either about sex or excrement - it takes a lot of
explaining when people come to visit.'' (Marc Geller/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 9 --
BEVERLY-HILLS-FILM, 8-6 -- During a recent visit to Manhattan,
writer and director Tamara Jenkins takes a break on a stoop in
Soho. Ms Jenkins film, ``Slums of Beverly Hills,'' is a '70s-era
tale about the coming of age of 15-year-old Vivian Abramowitz
played by Natasha Lyonne. Although it won't be released until
Friday, her feature debut has already brought her comparison to
novelist Philip Roth. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LONDON -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 9 --
HENSLEY-OKLAHOMA-MUSICAL, 8-6 -- Shuler Hensle takes time to enjoy
the promenade near the Royal National Theater in London. Hensle, a
Georgia-born baritone, is playing the role of the menacing Jud Fry
in the Royal National Theater's current revival of ``Oklahoma!''
``I try to approach Jud as someone completely frustrated that he's
misunderstood,'' Hensley, 30, says. ``That no one gets him.''
(Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) LONDON -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 9 --
LONDON-THEATER-DESIGNERS, 8-6 -- Designers Mark Thompson, left, and
Anthony Ward in their connecting studios in north London. The two
men, who live together, concede that they found themselves in an
unusual situation last month: separately employed on competing
musicals, two of the season's biggest shows, and with back-to-back
opening nights. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
