<P>
   (NYT35) NEW YORK -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- DETECTIVE-PROFILE, 8-6 --
Les Levine knows the whole repertory of private investigator
tricks. ``I've been told - not by my kids - that I'm not as warm
and affectionate and demonstrative as they would like me to be,''
he says. ``I'm not a flowery guy. I don't squeeze people and tell
them I love them. But people who know me refer to me as a rough,
tough pussycat.'' (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- RENO-CONTEMPT, 8-6 -- A
House committee voted along party lines Thursday to charge Attorney
General Janet Reno with contempt of Congress, transforming into a
criminal case the battle over whether an independent counsel should
be appointed to investigate and prosecute campaign finance abuses.
The full House will not take up the matter until after a four-week
recess that begins Friday. (Carol T. Powers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- PETER-PAN-FOUND, 8-6 -- A
statue of Peter Pan that had disappeared from a park near Gracie
Mansion is found by police divers in the East River on Thursday.
Investigators say the disappearance of the beloved statue from Carl
Schurz Park appears, appropriately enough, to be the work of a band
of overly high-spirited youths, perhaps latter-day Lost Boys who
turned on their own icon. (Barbara Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) MCLEAN, Va. -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- CLINTON-STARR, 8-6 --
Independent prosecutor Kenneth Starr leaving his home in McLean on
Thursday morning. Ending months of anticipation with a resigned
shrug, Monica Lewinsky, the former intern, walked into a federal
courthouse here Thursday and testified that she and President
Clinton carried on a sexual affair within the White House,
according to a lawyer familiar with her account. (Justin Lane/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- ALASKA-OIL, 8-6 -- Sen.
Ted Stevens, the senior member of the Alaskan delegation, making a
point in Washington recently. The Interior Department said Thursday
that it would open a new expanse of the Alaska North Slope
wilderness to oil and gas leasing, but it limited drilling in some
areas that the industry is most eager to explore. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) AYLESBURY, England -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- VW-ROLLS, 8-6 --
Michael Shrimpton, a British lawyer and Bentley owner, spearheaded
an unsuccessful attempt earlier this year to raise enough money
from Rolls-Royce and Bentley owners to keep both names in British
hands. ``It's a disaster; it will kill off both marques,'' says
Shrimpton, 41. ``The trademark is worth more than the assets.''
(Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- CAMPAIGN-FINANCE, 8-6 --
Rep. Christopher Shays receiving a hug by a supporter Thursday
after approval of a campaign finance bill he sponsored. Ending a
struggle that has gone on for months, the House on Thursday
approved a bipartisan bill to overhaul the way the nation's
political campaigns are financed and shifted the spotlight back
onto the Senate. In a final rebuke to the Republican leadership,
the House vote for passage of the measure was 252-179. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) TODI, Italy -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- ITALY-UMBRIA-RETREAT-2,
8-6 -- Janie Lee and David Warren, museum curators, are among the
prominent Americans who make Todi their home in summer. All around
this medieval city, wealthy Americans have lovingly restored
14th-century fortresses, abbeys and farmhouses, and added luxury
bathrooms, swimming pools and tennis courts. Theirs is a search for
beauty, isolation and upper-class comfort. (James Hill/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) TODI, Italy -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- ITALY-UMBRIA-RETREAT-1,
8-6 -- Todi, a medieval town in Umbria, has been colonized by
Americans. Theirs is a search for beauty, isolation and upper-class
comfort. The province is not just rivaling neighboring Tuscany as
Italy's most alluring and expensive summer retreat. For America's
Happy Few, Todi is becoming as fashionable as Martha's Vineyard or
the Hamptons. (James Hill/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- CLINTON-LEWINSKY, 8-6 --
Monica Lewinsky leaving Federal Court after testifying in front of
a grand jury Thursday. At left is one of her attorneys, Plato
Cacheris. In long hours of testimony fraught with peril for Bill
Clinton, Ms. Lewinsky told grand jurors her firsthand account of an
improbable relationship with the president. (Stephen Crowley/New
York Times Photo)
