<P>
   (NYT25) SEASIDE, Calif. -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- CALIF-MISSING-GIRL,
8-6 -- Michael Williams, whose daughter Christina, 13, is missing,
at his home in Seaside with her dog, Greg. The youngest in a family
of five, Christina took her dog, Greg, for a walk in the
neighborhood on the evening of June 12. About a half-hour later, he
wandered back alone. ``I feel like we're stuck in a bad 'Twilight
Zone' episode,'' says Williams. (Darcy Padilla/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- VACCINE-TERROR-2,
8-6 -- Dr. Thomas Monath, a vice president of OraVax. Based in
Cambridge, OraVax was founded in 1990 to tap an emerging
multi-billion-dollar market in oral vaccines and antibodies to
combat infectious diseases. But the small company kept having
problems getting beyond research and bringing products to market.
(Pat Greenhouse/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- VACCINE-TERROR-1,
8-6 -- A researcher for the vaccine manufacturer Oravax takes a
bacteria sample for analysis. In 1996 and 1997, its survival at
stake, OraVax tried to win part of the Pentagon's expanding germ
work as a subcontractor to make smallpox and other vaccines. But by
early this year, that work had failed to materialize and the
company's stock price was down 90 percent from $10 a share in the
initial public offering. (Pat Greenhouse/Boston Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) ATLANTA -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- SWIM-SMITH-DRUGS, 8-6 --
Michelle Smith of Ireland after winning the gold in the women's
400m freestyle during the 1996 Olympics. Smith, who won three gold
medals in Atlanta, effectively had her Olympic career terminated
when she was banned from competition for four years after being
