</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BECKET, Mass. -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- YANKEE-RODEO-2-BOS, 8-6
-- Kyle Robinson managed to hold on for about 4 seconds before
spinning off into the dirt - not long enough to win the
steer-riding contest at the Youth Rodeo in Becket. ``Rodeo is not
about winning, it's about believing you can do it,'' the 7-year-old
says philosophically. ``It's really tough to be a cowboy.'' The
only slightly worried parents say they feel that the risks are well
within acceptable bounds. (Barry Chin/Boston Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BECKET, Mass. -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- YANKEE-RODEO-1-BOS, 8-6
-- Kyle Robinson, left, of New Haven, Conn., and Kyle Payson, of
Wilder, Vt., discuss strategy prior to participating in the novice
steer riding competition in the Youth Rodeo in Becket. Because this
rodeo is especially for youngsters under 18, they ride steers
instead of broncos or bulls. As in adult rodeos, competition also
includes steer-roping, calf-wrestling, and racing horses in a
cloverleaf formation around three barrels. (Barry Chin/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- GENIUS-CAMP-BOS, 8-6
-- Jeremy England, 16, is one of the 80 most gifted high school
seniors in the world - 53 Americans and 27 international students
this year - who are conducting graduate-level independent research
in math and science at Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
Having been branded ``nerds'' and ``geeks'' in their own high
schools, students say here they can walk away from the stereotypes
and find other components of their identities. (Bill Greene/Boston
Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BOSTON -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- SCI-CANCER-V-BOS, 8-6 -- John
Cline of New Hampshire, center, an outpatient at Dana-Farber Cancer
Institute, takes advantage of a ``complementary'' qi gong workshop.
Cancer doctors today are reciting the mantra of ``complementary
therapies'' much as they proclaim the once-scorned virtues of
prevention. This workshop is available to families and caregivers
in addition to patients. (Suzanne Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) HYANNIS, Mass. -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- SCI-CANCER-KENNEDY,
8-6 -- Sen Ted Kennedy with his son Ted Jr. and grandson Ted III.
Ted Jr. was just the fourth participant in a clinical trial of
chemotherapy. Now 36, Ted Jr. can look back with some perspective
on his ordeal. ``My experience has given me a profound appreciation
of everything in my life today,'' he says. (Suzanne Kreiter/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BOSTON -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- SCI-CANCER-III-BOS-2, 8-6 -- At
Massachusetts General Hospital at breast cancer patient undergoes a
new technique of implanting radiocactive tubes into the breast.
Hollow tubes about the size of an intravenous line are inserted at
half-inch intervals around the tumor, then filled with seeds of
radioactive iridium, eliminating the need for less precise external
beams and taking just five days, compared to six weeks with
standard radiation. (Suzanne Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BOSTON -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- SCI-CANCER-III-BOS-1, 8-6 -- At
Massachusetts General Hospital, Dr. Simon Powell, who oversees the
implant program, reviews X-rays of radiation tubes in a patient.
``So far all our patients are fine, but we're still awaiting final
proof in five or 10 years that it's effective,'' Powell says.
(Suzanne Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BOSTON -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- SCI-CANCER-II-BOS-1, 8-6 --
Nelba MacMur, 66, receives SU101, a growth factor inhibitor to
treat her brain tumor whose tentacles couldn't be surgically
removed. Her daughter, Leslie, sits with during a recent treatment.
Leslie says that her mother has experienced few side effects and
has felt ``renewed zest just knowing there's something that could
potentially help her.'' (Suzanne Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BOSTON -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- SCI-CANCER-I-BOS-1, 8-6 -- Emma
Carey, 5, who was diagnosed in February 1997 with Acute
Lymphoblastic Leukemia (ALL,) is comforted by her mother, Tomasen.
She is receiving a maintenance dose of chemotherapy at
Massachusetts General Hospital. Emma's docotrs used a new
``molecular diagnostics'' test to spot telltale genetic alterations
in her blood cells. (Suzanne Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LOS ANGELES -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 9 --
INSTALLATION-ART, 8-6 -- An installation by Robert Gober at the
Museum of Contemporary Art in Los Angeles included suitcase, sewer
grates and this Mondonna and a steel drain pipe. Art today often
seems to aspire to the conditions of theater and film, installation
art above all, depend on a kind of physical interaction with
viewers. (Monica Almedia/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SAN FRANCISCO -- Aug. 6, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 9 --
INSTALLATION-ART-COLLECTORS, 8-6 -- Nora and Norman Stone
surrounded by a Mike Kelley installation in their exercise room.
Stones, are in their 50s, which is the average age of those who buy
contemporary art these days. But they share a teen-age enthusiasm
for buying the work of young artists who court controversy. Mrs.
Stone concedes, ``either about sex or excrement - it takes a lot of
explaining when people come to visit.'' (Marc Geller/New York Times
Photo)
