<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2062 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN07-COX     08-06 0418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A. Jones' HRs back Maddux
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- As they prepared to embark on their lone West Coast
road trip of the season, the Braves had the perfect formula for a
quick getaway Thursday: Greg Maddux facing the Reds and Kid
Peroxide pounding Cincinnati again. Then again.
</P>
<P>
   With Maddux throwing a three-hitter and Andruw Jones _ he of the
newly dyed blonde hair _ belting two home runs, the Braves beat
Cincinnati 5-0 at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   For Maddux, his fifth shutout was also his 15th victory, tying
him for the major-league lead. For Jones, his first-inning solo
homer was his fourth off Mike Remlinger in just 12 career at-bats.
In the eighth, he crushed a two-run homer off John Hudek for his
19th homer of the year and fourth two-homer game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   That, and Andres Galarraga's 35th homer, was enough to end the
homestand 4-2 and quickly get the Braves onto their charter flight
to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Such a contrast to Wednesday's ugliness. That 13-9 loss marked
the most runs scored against the Braves since they moved into
Turner Field last year, and the most runs allowed by the Braves in
Atlanta since a 16-4 loss to Colorado Aug. 12, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Cox had the remedy for that: Give Maddux the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Despite pitching brilliantly since the All-Star break, Maddux
had gone just 2-3. On this night, he was, if not untouchable,
absolutely dominant.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first seven innings, the Reds (who hadn't beaten
Maddux since June 1, 1996) managed to hit just seven balls out of
the infield: three singles and four fly balls. Cincinnati managed
no more than one baserunner in an inning, only two advancing as far
as second. The Braves, meanwhile, quickly gave Maddux some support.
</P>
<P>
   When Jones drove Remlinger's first pitch of the second inning
over the center field wall, it was his fourth homer in his last 11
games _ and his fourth in just 12 career at-bats against the Reds
left-hander. Of Jones' 41 major-league homers, 11 have come off
Cincinnati pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta made it 2-0 in the second. After singles by Walt Weiss
and Chipper Jones, Galarraga hit a one-out grounder to second. The
Reds got the force-out at second but when shortstop Barry Larkin's
throw to first bounced away for an error, Weiss scored. In the
sixth, Galarraga made it 3-0 with a 418-foot homer, his first since
July 24.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
