<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2063 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-MODESTI-LADN     08-06 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORY BIG LOSER AT TRACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; DEL MAR _ Bit by bit, the National Thoroughbred Racing
Association is unveiling a plan for the sport's future. But does it
have a plan for the sport's past?
</P>
<P>
   One duty of a ``league office,'' which the 100-day-old NTRA
proposes to be, is to be the keeper of the historical flame. A
league office pulls together statistics, other records and other
aspects of its stars' biographies.
</P>
<P>
   We know what the home-run record is, and which batters have a
chance to break it this year, because all the numbers, names and
dates are written down in a book bearing the seals of the National
and American leagues. Almost every sport, from baseball to bowling
to stock-car racing, has a similar record book or encyclopedia or
Who's Who.
</P>
<P>
   Not thoroughbred racing. The last edition of the annual American
Racing Manual was published by the Daily Racing Form in 1994,
containing only skeletal history. There is no definitive racing
encyclopedia. If you're a journalist or a curious fan, and you want
to know about the personalities of the past, you had better be
prepared to leaf through dozens of media guides and books. This I
discovered during a frustrating couple of days researching the
early Triple Crown winners at the California Thoroughbred Racing
Association library in Arcadia in May.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, there must be a single paragraph summing up the life
and accomplishments of Sunny Jim Fitzsimmons, one of the great
trainers of all time. But I couldn't find one.
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood Park publicity staff has done a good thing,
surveying major tracks around the country and compiling a national
records section for its media guide. If you want to know the amount
of the highest pick-six payoff ever or the most stakes won by one
jockey in a day, finally there's somewhere to turn.
</P>
<P>
   But there's much more to be done. And soon, before the
generations that remember the old days take their secrets to the
grave.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that NTRA executives say they know it.
</P>
<P>
   In Del Mar this week for a board meeting, NTRA commissioner Tim
Smith enumerated the association's many tasks, including marketing
the sport, expanding television coverage, promoting new wagers that
might compete with state lotteries, encouraging equine welfare and
sorting out the increasingly confusing medication issues. And
consolidating information and making it more available to fans than
it has been.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunity we have, and I think it's an important one, is
to tie everything together for the fan,'' Smith said, promising
``one-stop'' information sources.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing newspapers and magazines lack the space to publish
rankings of leading horses, jockeys and trainers, as they might for
more popular sports, the NTRA is putting out that information in
its print ads. This will be especially important when or if
national racing series, producing points standings like NASCAR's or
professional tennis', come to be.
</P>
<P>
   NTRA executives say they're also exploring ways to educate
potential fans about the complexities of racetrack wagering, and to
simplify it by publishing simpler alternatives to Racing Form
past-performance charts.
</P>
<P>
   But information is more valuable in context. And how will the
NTRA impress the public that today's leading horses and horsemen
are accomplishing something historic unless it also promotes the
idea that history matters?
</P>
<P>
   The weekend: Del Mar offers a pair of modest $100,000 stakes for
fillies and mares, making this the calm before Pacific Classic
week.
</P>
<P>
   Two-year-old fillies sprint 6{ furlongs Saturday in the
Sorrento, whose last notable winner was Phone Chatter in 1993. The
favorite is Bob Baffert-trained, Mike Pegram-owned Silverbulletday,
coming off a stakes victory at Churchill Downs and a
fastest-of-the-morning 6-furlong workout at Del Mar.
</P>
<P>
   The 6{-furlong Rancho Bernardo Handicap on Sunday will get a new
champion. Track Gal was retired for breeding _ and is in foal to
Deputy Minister in Kentucky _ after winning the race the past three
years. She tied the Del Mar record for a single stakes held by
Native Diver (San Diego Handicap, 1963-65) and Flawlessly (Ramona
Handicap, '92-94).
</P>
<P>
   The Rancho Bernardo favorites are familiar faces anyway: Tiffany
Diamond, trying to be the first double stakes winner of the Del Mar
season after capturing the Fantastic Girl on opening day; Corona
Lake, back at her distance and class level; and Advancing Star, a
multiple stakes winner seeking her first '98 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The $1 million Pacific Classic is Aug. 15. Probable runners:
Touch Gold, Gentlemen, Puerto Madero and Free House.
Less-than-probable runners: Mud Route and Hal's Pal.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere: Real Quiet's injury, to his right hind leg, canceled
this weekend's hoped-for rematch with Victory Gallop, the colt
whose Belmont Stakes rally prevented a Triple Crown. It could also
cost Real Quiet the 3-year-old championship.
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop and Coronado's Quest, the leading active
candidates, resume their campaigns in the $1 million Haskell
Invitational at Monmouth Park on the New Jersey seashore Sunday. A
small field is expected to include Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's other major race, the $400,000 Whitney Handicap at
Saratoga, draws the leading eastern handicap horses except
top-ranked Skip Away. Expected to run: Frisk Me Now (assigned 119
pounds), Awesome Again, (117), Precocity (116), Crypto Star (116),
Banker's Gold (115) and Tale of the Cat (112). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
