<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2070 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-KRIKORIAN-LADN     08-06 1374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KRIKORIAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOMMY SHOULD WAKE UP AND SMELL THE LINGUINI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. -- Does my old pal Tommy Lasorda know
something I don't know?
</P>
<P>
   While he's done everything during his brief time as general
manager of the Dodgers to improve the station of his team short of
offering Rupert Murdoch legal advice on his divorce proceedings or
volunteering to join John Glenn on his space flight, he blindly has
ignored a most harrowing reality.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Dodgers somehow are able to leapfrog past the
Chicago Cubs, San Francisco Giants and New York Mets in the
wild-card derby -- and you need an imagination as zany as Lasorda's
to envision this happening -- then the team would face the Braves'
execution squad from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   And then, if by small quirk of wacky fate, these erratic Dodgers
somehow had an out-of-body experience against the Braves, they
would have to endure the gauntlet against either the San Diego
Padres or Houston Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Ol' Tommy, luvvie (cq)
</P>
<P>
   dear, please, wake up before it's too late, smell the orchids,
enjoy the perks of your new calling, watch those calories, get your
sleep, invite Fred Claire up to your Dodger Stadium box for a
linguini clambake, and stop becoming so enraged with those
numbskulls in the fourth estate who haven't skinned their knees
leaping aboard your hysterical bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   I beg you, Tommy, cool it with your fanatical attempt to inject
some superficial excitement into a Dodger season before this
agonizing team of yours actually rises up out of its season-long
stupor and realizes your fanciful dream.
</P>
<P>
   We suffer enough sporting humiliation here in Southern
California -- no NFL franchise, no NHL franchises worth mentioning,
too many Donald Sterlings, too few championships -- without another
0-3 Dodger playoff impalement staring ominously at us on the faint
horizon. ...
</P>
<P>
   --Actually, there are benefits to Tommy Lasorda stripping the
Dodgers of their best minor-league prospects to bring in a bunch of
guys whose surnames I can't pronounce. Hey, he has kept the Dodgers
ahead of both the Milwaukee Brewers and Philadephia Phillies in
that hair-raising wild-card chase that for some strange reason has
left me in a perpetual state of indifference. ...
</P>
<P>
   --OK, I'm not hooked on phonics, but you try pronouncing Mark
Grudzielanek's name without suffering an asthmatic attack. ...
</P>
<P>
   --Brace yourself because I'm going to make the boldest statement
I've ever made in this newspaper -- the Angels won't make it to the
playoffs with their current feeble pitching staff. Now if I know
that, why didn't Tony Tavares and Bill Bavasi know it at the
trading deadline? ...
</P>
<P>
   --I'm not surprised by Mark McGwire's 4-for-43 slump. He's
always been a prolific home-run hitter during his career but never
has hit for much of an average. ...
</P>
<P>
   --When I shook hands with UCLA coach Bob Toledo the other day at
the Pac-10 media session, he asked me, ``Are you a tennis player?''
I laughed, and told him no, that I'm a yachtsman. ...
</P>
<P>
   --I keep hearing that Shaquille O'Neal is working out
passionately and is determined to be in the best shape of his life
for the upcoming season that will take place despite the current
NBA lockout. ...
</P>
<P>
   --The Jewelry Doctor, Jack Lipeles, is re-doing the 1996 Chicago
Bulls' championship ring of Ron Harper, enhancing its value with
several additional carats of diamonds. ``It's now worth several
thousands of dollars more than the fifteen hundred dollars it was
when Ron brought it to me,'' says Lipeles, the Pine Avenue jeweler
to boxing and rap stars. ...
</P>
<P>
   --As I walked around the American Boating Jubilee the other day
at the Shoreline Village Marina, I was astounded by the incredible
revival that has taken place in an area that was a doormat only a
short time ago. ``Long live praying mantises and all their
brothers, sisters, moms, dads, uncles, aunts, nieces and nephews,''
cracked Parker's Lighthouse resident wit Jolly John Grady,
referring to the impact that the recently opened Aquarium of the
Pacific has had in the teeming vicinity. ...
</P>
<P>
   --Paul Hackett sounds like a football coach, acts like a
football coach, talks like a football coach, even walks like a
football coach. Now all we have to find out is if the guy can
actually coach like a football coach. ...
</P>
<P>
   --The Mother Teresa of my Long Beach neighborhood, Esther
Fawcett, recently retired after serving 40 years as a volunteer
aide at Memorial Hospital. I'm not sure I'd be typing these words
out had Esther not been around during those dangerous bachelor
years when I too often needed to be saved from myself. ...
</P>
<P>
   --Forum matchmaker Tony Curtis, not to be confused with
Hollywood actor Tony Curtis, who's younger, tells me that Monday
night's NABO bantamweight title fight between Mauricio Martinez and
Marcos Badillo at the Pond should not be viewed by spectators with
faint hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a bloody, all-out war,'' says Curtis. ``If you
don't like violence, then you better not watch it.'' Will it be as
violent as Bill Clinton vs. Monica Lewinsky? ...
</P>
<P>
   --I can't believe it. A whole week has passed, and I haven't
read one story speculating on Michael Jordan's future. ...
</P>
<P>
   --I don't feel sorry for Cecil Fielder. If the guy would have
kept himself in proper shape over the years, he'd still be an
effective batsman. ...
</P>
<P>
   --Long Beach celebrity restaurateur Phil Trani to projected
Stanford starting quarterback Todd Husak, former St. John Bosco
star and son of Loyola Marymount athletic director Bill Husak:
``You gotta meet Cade McNown.'' That would be great, cooed young
Husak, a big fan of UCLA's Heisman Trophy candidate. Trani has
become McNown's surrogate father. ...
</P>
<P>
   --It'll be interesting to see how Mike Piazza performs next
season when his contract hassles are behind him. If he hits below
his usual standards again, then it will become indisputable that
the Dodgers were the perfect fit for him and that he made a
terrible career move disrupting it. ...
</P>
<P>
   --The death this week of the one-time colorful NBA referee
Richie Powers brought back some fond memories for me. I used to tip
a few with Powers after Laker games at the old King's X in
Inglewood a long time ago. Richie was an artful raconteur and
terrific official oblivious to the taunts of unfriendly crowds. ...
</P>
<P>
   --A day seldom passes in my life when I don't think of my late
friend and colleague, Allan Malamud. ...
</P>
<P>
   --Our city is booming, and yet the Pine Avenue visionary who
played a vital role in this phenomenon, John Morris, is now waging
a bitter war with those nasty bureaucrats from the Alcohol Beverage
Control, whose disdain for Long Beach is exceeded only by their
disdain for resourceful capitalistic entrepreneurs like Morris who
are thriving. ...
</P>
<P>
   --Are the Goodwill Games set for later this month, or will they
be staged in September? ...
</P>
<P>
   --OK, Les Robbins, maybe I overreacted a while back when I said
Long Beach politicians had a God-given knack for making the wrong
choice on every issue. Maybe it's just every other issue.
</P>
<P>
   Mea culpa.
</P>
<P>
   They must be doing some things rights in light of the prosperity
that has visited our celestial paradise. But I still think the
rascals blew it when they decided not even to look into the
viability of building a football stadium here that would have
inevitably resulted in Long Beach luring an NFL team. What would
that have done for the city? ...
</P>
<P>
   --A publicity firm called the office the other day with the
startling announcement that swimming great Susie Atwood, who
performed in both the 1968 and 1972 Olympics, was going to make a
comeback Sunday in Portland in the Nike Masters competition.
</P>
<P>
   Nice local yarn, except it was news to the principal herself,
Susie Atwood, who, instead, plans to spend the day with her hubbie
to be, former Secret Service gumshoe Dave Butler, sprucing up their
new Peninsula digs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have greater priorities in my life now than to swim the
backstroke 12 miles a day,'' says Susie, now a State Farm agent and
local social arbiter.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
