<HEADLINE>
INTEREST IN THE BABE IS A HOME RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. -- At a time when the attention span of the
average American is measured in seconds and history is considered
non-essential, Babe Ruth, deceased for 50 years, still packs a
wallop.
</P>
<P>
   With the baseball community very homer happy at the moment, the
image of Ruth and Roger Maris are almost tangible alongside Mark
McGwire, Ken Griffey and other sluggers challenging their domain.
In Ruth's case, he will at least be visible.
</P>
<P>
   HBO and Black Canyon Productions, which have collaborated on
most of the top sports documentaries in the '90s, will pay homage
to Ruth with a one-hour documentary special debuting Aug. 16, the
50th anniversary of Ruth's death.
</P>
<P>
   HBO is also premiering the documentary in various cities prior
to its Aug. 16 release, including Long Beach at 7 p.m. Wednesday at
the Carpenter Performing Arts Center on the Long Beach State
campus.
</P>
<P>
   The invitation-only premiere and reception, hosted by HBO,
Charter Communications and the Press-Telegram, will be attended by
a dozen former ballplayers from the area. Hall of Famer Bob Lemon
will attend, along with former area prep stars such as Rod Gaspar,
Bruce Ellingsen and Buck Taylor, ex-Dodgers Tommy Davis and Norm
Larker, and local coaching legend John Herbold.
</P>
<P>
   The Ruth documentary was a challenge for the cable movie network
and production company. Many of their past efforts have looked at
issues and stories which had gone untouched for years. This time,
they had to find a way to look at Ruth's life that offered more
than his statistical achievements and well-known anecdotes.
</P>
<P>
   Black Canyon found some never-before-seen color home movies of
Ruth that they use in the last half of the documentary and decided
to focus on two areas of his life -- his sad last days in baseball,
and why he still resonates today, 50 years after his passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to create a documentary that explains why he still
has such a vibrant impact on the game of baseball,'' said HBO
senior producer Rick Bernstein. ``This is less of a linear look at
his career as much as a character-driven documentary. We wanted to
show people why Ruth was bigger-than-life and the last years of his
career, which a lot of people may not know much about.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth never realized his dream of managing the Yankees, or any
team for that matter. He thought he was going to become a
player-manager with the Boston Braves, but it turned out he was
little more than a ticket attraction. He was very ill the last few
years of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ruth was a simple man who enjoyed life to its fullest,'' said
Bernstein. ``I think it's interesting that he earned a reputation
as a hard-drinking, hard-loving man, yet he always seemed happiest
when he was around kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth's adopted daughter, Julia Ruth Stevens, is one of 31
different people who were interviewed for the documentary.
Bernstein admits he was concerned how she would feel about the
segment on Ruth's drinking and carousing. ``That was a part of his
life, and we were not going to exclude it or sugar-coat it,'' he
said. ``But I hated the idea of making an 81-year-old woman
upset.''
</P>
<P>
   She wasn't. Ms. Stevens was a guest at the New York screening
last month and called it the best work she's ever seen on her
father.
</P>
<P>
   HBO and Charter are donating $1 for every new HBO subscription
this month to the Major League Baseball Players Alumni Association
as part of the premiere showing Wednesday. More former players are
expected to be added to the list of invitees between today and the
premiere.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred tickets to the premiere also are being offered to
the public via a contest in today's Press-Telegram. The first 50
people to correctly answer 10 questions about Ruth and fax them to
the P-T will each get two tickets to the premiere. The ad is on
Page B5 in today's sports section.
</P>
<P>
   BOB STARR: In 1993, former Angels' and Rams' radio announcer Bob
Starr contracted the rare and often deadly Legionnaires' disease
while traveling. He spent 10 days in the hospital and would recover
well enough to continue his broadcast career.
</P>
<P>
   But he never totally recovered from that episode and often
suffered respiratory problems. Late last season, he had to begin
carrying oxygen with him at all times at Angels' games. He became
bed-ridden in December and passed away Monday at his home in
Orange. He was 65.
</P>
<P>
   Starr called Angels' games from 1980 to 1989 and again from 1993
to 1997, and Rams' games from 1980 to 1989 and again in 1993. His
career in broadcasting included stops with the Boston Red Sox and
both the baseball and football St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   His best work in Los Angeles was the crisp, assured work he did
as the play-by-play voice of the Rams. He was smooth and had a
voice which transmitted the excitement on the field to his radio
audience.
</P>
<P>
   GAME ON: The latest skirmish in the on-going war between Disney
(ABC/ESPN) and Fox moved to the ice this week. Published reports
say Disney has offered a $600-million deal to the NHL for exclusive
over-the-air and cable rights for five years, beginning in the
1999-2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   That $125 million-a-year offer represents a nearly three-fold
increase in the NHL's annual take. Fox (over-the-air) and ESPN
(cable) currently pay the NHL $46 million a year. Fox has one year
left on a five-year, $155-million deal, and ESPN one year on a
seven-year, $100-million cable deal.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL plans to snap that loose change up quicker than one can
say Pavel Bure. The league's TV ratings have actually declined the
last year despite Fox's commitment to a game of the week.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the over-the-air package is an add-on. Disney's
quest is to lock up the cable package and keep it away from Fox,
which would love to add a national NHL contract for its
ever-growing regional cable systems.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has until next Friday to counter the ABC offer, and it's
unlikely they will.
</P>
<P>
   AND NOW THE NEWS: Fox Sports West 2 will air four Charger
preseason games, beginning Saturday with their game against the
49ers (7 p.m.). ... Fox (11) will air the finals of the Toshiba
Tennis Classic Sunday at 12:30 p.m., its first-ever tennis
coverage. ... ESPN Classic Sports will feature Martina Navratilova
in a special and replay of her 1984 U.S. Open win against Chris
Evert on Sunday. The network will also air Bud Collins' top 10 U.S.
Open matches, beginning Sunday with John McEnroe-Jimmy Connors in
the 1984 Open.
</P>
<P>
   THE TV SPORTS WORLD ACCORDING TO ME: The women's sports market
obviously is still in its infancy. How else can one explain why
three figure skaters topped the list of the most marketable female
athletes in Street &AMP; Smith's Sports Business Journal, and why
soccer star Mia Hamm topped a similar survey by The Sports Business
Daily (SBD). Hamm did not make the S&AMP;S top 10, and the skaters
placed second (Michelle Kwan), fourth (Tara Lipinski) and 17th
(Kristi Yamaguchi) in the SBD list. ... The spinmeisters at ESPN
commissioned a study by A.C. Nielsen to illustrate how many viewers
watch the cable network in bars, hotels, restaurants and even at
work places. The results bump ESPN's typical audience numbers for,
say,
</P>
<P>
   SportsCenter by nine percent, and say that a third of all
out-of-home viewers watch ESPN. No one denies ESPN's appeal, but
chasing down a number for sports bar attendance -- what else would
they watch? -- is a weak response to Nielsen's usual numbers which
indicate ESPN's numbers are down and Fox Sports News numbers are
up. ... Must-read: Rich Marotta, the KFI sports voice and TV boxing
commentary, has an awesome website at www.kfi640.com. The most
recent edition featured Marotta's take on Mike Tyson, flyweight
Mark Johnson, Don Dunphy and other topical boxing items, plus his
list of the top pound-for-pound fighters. ... The Goodwill Games
posted a 1.6 rating on Turner, proving that some people will watch
anything.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
