<HEADLINE>
BARNICLE, GLOBE PUBLISHER TO MEET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ AND DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ On a day when Mike Barnicle challenged The Boston
Globe's decision to ask for his resignation, everyone from a
``stunned'' Acting Governor Paul Cellucci to CNN talk show host
Larry King to nearly 2,000 Globe readers weighed in on the
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not submitting this resignation,'' said Barnicle Thursday
while pleading his case on local and national media outlets. The
Globe said it was still insisting on it, adding that a meeting
between Barnicle and publisher Benjamin B. Taylor was scheduled for
Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an overwhelming majority of readers who contacted the
Globe Thursday expressed the hope that the paper would retain the
popular 25-year Metro columnist.
</P>
<P>
   Globe editor Matthew V. Storin asked for Barnicle's resignation
Wednesday night after an Aug.2 column in which, Barnicle
acknowledged, he had used a number of jokes that appeared in
comedian George Carlin's 1997 book, ``BrainDroppings.'' Barnicle
told the Globe he had received the column material from friends and
was unaware that it had come from Carlin's book.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, on Wednesday afternoon, the Globe accepted Barnicle's
explanation and suspended him for one month without pay for using
``poor judgment.'' But the paper asked for his resignation after
seeing a WCVB-Ch. 5 clip from the station's June 22 ``Chronicle''
program that showed Barnicle holding up the book and recommending
it as ``a yuk on every page.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Barnicle had told editors he had never read the
Carlin book, Storin concluded that he ``misrepresented himself
either to his television audience or his editors,'' adding that
``this contradiction is unacceptable.'' Globe editors said that
Barnicle did not tell them about his endorsement of the book.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued Wednesday, publisher Taylor said ``it's
essential that we maintain the highest standards and that they be
applied evenly across the board. Credibility is our most important
asset.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle suggested Thursday that his endorsement of the book did
not mean he had read it. ``Clearly they have not looked at the
(Channel 5) tape,'' he said. ``BrainDroppings'' is part of a
``suggested reading list. There are about 15 books included. The
Carlin book is up there for four seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   The Barnicle story was at or near the top of every local
newscast Thursday, with interviews of the columnist. In addition,
the story was reported on national networks such as ABC and CNN,
and was the subject of animated discussion on a nationally
syndicated radio show and local talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe was deluged with calls and e-mail messages Thursday.
As of late last night, the Globe's city desk had received 1,569
calls and e-mail messages from readers, with only 95 of those
people saying that Barnicle should lose his job. The rest said that
Barnicle should face no more than a brief suspension.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 463 people had contacted the ombudsman's office by
3 p.m. Thursday, and another 500 people had called other
departments of the Globe, with most in support of Barnicle. About
100 readers had canceled their subscription by noon.
</P>
<P>
   The calls came from throughout New England and from as far away
as Maryland and Colorado. A common theme among callers was that the
issue was not as serious as the fabrication of characters and
quotes that cost former Globe columnist Patricia Smith her job, and
that the Globe was overreacting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best column in the Globe,'' said Anita Milano of
Quincy, who described herself as a Barnicle reader for many years.
``It's real. It's a part of us. I clip many of the columns and send
them to people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand the outpouring of support for Mike,'' said
Storin, who is on vacation overseas. ``But professional standards
and good communication between writers and editors are absolutely
crucial to any newspaper. We made a tough and painful decision that
was necessary under the circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   A poll &UR;  &LR; conducted Thursday by MSNBC, a national cable network,
elicited 1,549 responses, one of the strongest viewer reactions to
a poll the network has seen. To the question, ``Should Mike
Barnicle be forced to resign from The Boston Globe?'' 90 percent
responded that he should not, according to MSNBC spokeswoman
Cameron Blanchard.
</P>
<P>
   A poll &UR;  &LR; conducted by ABC News on its website found 57 percent
supported Barnicle while 43 percent thought he should resign.
Locally, a poll conducted by WHDH-Ch. 7 last night found that 60
percent of respondents believed Barnicle should lose his job, while
40 percent said he should not.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy attracted attention from media personalities.
Radio host Don Imus contended Barnicle's transgression is ``not a
fire-able offense.'' Barnicle is a frequent guest on ``Imus in the
Morning,'' a nationally syndicated radio show that is televised on
MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Larry King called the radio program and argued that
``firing him is insane. They're giving up one of the best
columnists, who will have a hundred offers tomorrow'' from other
newspapers. ``He's too good a columnist and this is too weak a
case,'' said King.
</P>
<P>
   King took issue, though, with Barnicle's recommendation of a
book he had not read. While acknowledging that he himself sometimes
does not read the books of authors he is interviewing, King said he
makes that clear on his TV show.
</P>
<P>
   Even Cellucci weighed in, saying, ``I am just stunned by how
quickly that story has developed. I am going to watch and see what
happens. But certainly I have been a fan, read his column all the
time, you know. It's a stunning development.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of Barnicle's other employers were also evaluating his
status Thursday in light of the Globe controversy. Channel 5 issued
a statement saying, ``Mike Barnicle has been an important
contributor to WCVB for the past 15 years. We have always had
confidence in his work and continue to have confidence in his work
at this television station. He admits making a mistake by
recommending a book on `Chronicle' he did not read and we accept
his explanation and expression of regret. He remains a contributor
to WCVB-TV.''
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC, which has Barnicle under contract as an on-air
commentator, said, ``His commentary has no relationship to the
content of his Boston Globe columns. Currently, he remains a valued
contributor for MSNBC. We will continue to assess the situation as
it develops.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle also receives a small honorarium as regular regional
commentator on PBS's ``NewsHour with Jim Lehrer.'' Thursday, the
program's communications director, Bruce Lott, said Barnicle would
not appear on the the ``NewsHour'' until his situation with the
Globe is resolved. ``As of right now, no decision has been made on
whether we'll continue to use Mr. Barnicle,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, journalistic analysts were assessing the
Globe's decision on Barnicle and offering a mixed verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, either to the editors or the viewers of that
show, he was dissembling,'' said Bill Kovach, the curator of
Harvard's Nieman Foundation. ``I don't think (the Globe) had a
choice. I think Mike has gotten caught'' at a time of changing
journalistic ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Aly Colon, an ethics instructor at the Poynter Institute for
Media Studies in St. Petersburg, likened Barnicle's assertion that
he recommended a book he hadn't read to CNN reporter Peter Arnett's
plea that he had narrated the network's ill-fated nerve gas report
without really being aware of its contents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he's using the kind of Peter Arnett excuse,'' said Colon.
``At least at this point it seems like the Globe took the right
step asking for his resignation.''
</P>
<P>
   One dissenter is Marvin Kalb, director of Harvard's Shorenstein
Center on Press, Politics and Public Policy. ``My belief is
Barnicle ought to be cut some slack.'' said Kalb. ``He did
something hurried and foolish, but he did not do something evil.''
</P>
<P>
   The request for Barnicle's resignation follows the June
departure of black Metro columnist Smith, who admitted fabricating
characters in quotes in some columns. After Smith's resignation,
Harvard Law Professor Alan Dershowitz accused the Globe of acting
inconsistently for not similarly disciplining Barnicle for a 1990
column that Dershowitz said contained a fabricated quote attributed
to him.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, both the New York Times and Steven Brill's ``Content''
magazine reported that the Globe paid Dershowitz a $75,000
settlement in that case. Neither the Globe nor Dershowitz would
confirm that report Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Burnham, a civil rights attorney who wrote a Boston
magazine article accusing the Globe of a racially tinged double
standard for treating Smith's transgressions more harshly than
Barnicle, said Thursday, ``I think the Globe had no choice but to
ask for his resignation. If anyone's to be faulted here, it is the
Globe for not taking seriously the complaints about Barnicle long
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Scott Lehigh of the Globe staff and Globe correspondent Patrick
Flaherty contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
