<SLUG> BC-STREET07-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREET SMARTS/MARK VEVERKA  
 THIS INTERNET OFFERING WOULD BE IN THE EYE OF THE BEHOLDER 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - STREET SMARTS   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Although it appeared dead in the water, the much-anticipated
initial offering of CBS MarketWatch is back on track.
</P>
<P>
   The financial news Web site could file to go public as early as
mid-August, according to sources familiar with the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the sky-high valuations placed on other
Internet-related offerings this summer, such as Broadcast.com and
Inktomi, institutional investors began to wonder what was keeping
CBS MarketWatch from taking advantage of overly ripe market
conditions for Net IPOs. CBS MarketWatch chief executive Larry
Kramer would not comment on the company's financing plans.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, part of the delay is being blamed on legal and
accounting complications stemming from the company's status as a
50/50 joint-venture.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; x  &LR;  CBS MarketWatch was formed in October 1997 by its two
parents: Data Broadcast Corp. of Jackson Hole, Wyo., and CBS, a
unit of New York-based Westinghouse.
</P>
<P>
   The co-lead investment bankers on the proposed deal, BT Alex.
Brown and Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, had advised the company to
seek ``outside evaluations on the (financial) contributions of the
two (parent) companies'' to avoid any pitfalls with the Securities
and Exchange Commission, according to a source.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; uncx  &LR;  Another deal-structuring snag was the fact that CBS
MarketWatch is a limited-liability corporation, or LLC _ a status
that carries federal tax implications similar to a limited
partnership. To change that, the financial news company will
convert to a standard public corporation at the time of an
offering.
</P>
<P>
   CBS MarketWatch, which has 55 employees in Los Angeles,
Washington, D.C., New York and San Francisco, provides financial
news and stock quotes to individual investors. According to the
company, the number of visitors to its Web site has more than
doubled to 1.7 million by the end of last month.
</P>
<P>
   One cyber-publisher that is sure to keep its eye on a CBS
MarketWatch IPO is rival TheStreet.com. The New York-based
financial news site (the current employer of the previous occupant
of this column slot) is starting to do some spadework for a
possible offering of its own.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the two companies have informally explored the
notion of some sort of combination. But a marriage between the two
seems less likely now that CBS MarketWatch is teeing up its IPO.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh  &LR;  Asian Flu Pill
</P>
<P>
   We interrupt the Asian economic implosion to bring you this
contrarian news blurb from across the Pacific. ...
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's economy isn't that bad. It isn't nearly as debilitated
as those of Japan, Indonesia, Singapore et. al. That's according to
author and international investor Steve Champion, chief investment
officer of Aetna International in Hartford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout Asia there is carnage, but Taiwan has sailed
through relatively unscathed,'' says Champion, a former chief
international investment officer at Bank of America in San
Francisco and former vice chairman of the Bank of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that Taiwan is immune from the Asian bug, only
that its current symptoms aren't as severe as neighboring nations,
he says.
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of spreading their economic good cheer, bureaucrats
from Taiwan's Ministry of Economic Affairs are slated to meet with
Silicon Valley business leaders today. Their pitch: build high-tech
plants in Taiwan because the island nation is more financially
stable than the rest of the region.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the officials are expected to court Bay Area companies
by extolling the benefits of raising capital on the Taiwan Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they've got a good story to tell,'' says Champion, who
is author of ``The Great Taiwan Bubble: The Rise and Fall of An
Emerging Stock Market.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they've managed the economy pretty well and kept the
integrity of their banking system intact,'' says Champion, who
among his other jobs was also president of International Investment
Trust, the first fund management company in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Champion says the average price-earnings ratio of Taiwan's stock
market is now in the low 20s, which is much improved over its
100-plus ratios earlier in the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its stock market volatility is just nothing compared to what
it used to be. It used to be the wildest of the bunch,'' Champion
says.
</P>
<P>
   But since then, cronyism has been reduced, markets have been
liberalized and government financial regulations have been enacted
that actually have teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country's technocratic government is run by competent
people,'' Champion says. ``One-party (political) rule has its
advantages, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., SF 94103,
by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at mveverka &LR; sfgate.com. He
also appears regularly on KRON-TV's Daybreak.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
