<SLUG> BC-SAFEWAY-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFEWAY BUYS BIGGEST ALASKA RETAILER 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - SAFEWAY   By Carol Emert  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Safeway Inc. bit off another chunk of the supermarket sector
yesterday when it announced the acquisition of Carr-Gottstein Foods
Co., Alaska's largest retailer.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Pleasanton-based grocery chain will pay $110 million in
cash, or $12.50 per share, for all outstanding Carr-Gottstein
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Safeway will also assume $220 million in debt, an amount that
the supermarket giant can digest easily, but which was a heavy load
for the Alaska company.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Carr-Gottstein closed yesterday at $7.88, unchanged
for the day. The retailer's stock is up 60 percent for the year but
still considerably lower than the company's 1993 initial public
offering price of $14.50. Meanwhile Safeway stock closed yesterday
at $43.31, up 6 cents for the day.
</P>
<P>
   Carr-Gottstein suffered a net loss last year of $5.6 million on
revenues of $589 million, due in part to a one-time charge for
shuttered operations. By comparison, Safeway generated a profit of
$557.4 million on sales of $22.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunities for cost reduction and profit improvements
this presents to us is significant,'' said Safeway chief financial
officer Melissa Plaisance. ``We expect it to be additive to
earnings in the first year.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal is scheduled to become final in early 1999 pending the
approval of federal regulators. In a conference call with reporters
yesterday, executives with both companies declined to speculate on
whether any stores might be closed due to antitrust concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The planned acquisition will give Safeway access to
Carr-Gottstein's extensive distribution network, including a fleet
of trucks, a distribution center in Tacoma, Wash. and the only food
distribution warehouse in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   The system allows Carr-Gottstein to ship merchandise to Alaska
six days per week, whereas Safeway brings goods in twice a week.
</P>
<P>
   Carr-Gottstein's retail operations include 15 food, drug and
general merchandise stores called Carrs Quality Centers, 12 smaller
stores which operate under different names, 16 Oaken Keg Spirit
Shops liquor stores and five tobacco stores called The Great Alaska
Tobacco Company.
</P>
<P>
   Safeway operates 16 supermarkets in Alaska. Other competitors
include Fred Meyer, Costco, Wal-Mart, Kmart and Sam's Club.
</P>
<P>
   Safeway intends to cut costs by combining buying and
administrative functions, refinancing Carr-Gottstein's debt and
adding a private-label program similar to Safeway's Select line.
</P>
<P>
   The deal comes just three days after Boise-based Albertson's
Inc. announced its impending purchase of American Stores Corp.,
parent of Lucky Stores, for $11.7 billion in cash and debt.
</P>
<P>
   Plaisance said her company continues to actively seek additional
companies to purchase.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
