<HEADER>
A2082 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALLMER-SFCHRON-BALLM     08-06 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLMER-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT STARTS BUILDING ITS VALLEY HOME  
 BY BENNY EVANGELISTA 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - BALLMER   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. President Steve Ballmer broke ground yesterday
on the site of his company's new Silicon Valley campus in Mountain
View, a virtual stone's throw from rival Netscape Communications
Corp.'s headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   But the ebullient Ballmer chuckled at the suggestion that the
software giant's new five-building office complex was akin to a big
bully moving into the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a company that has far more partners down here in the
valley than we do competitors,'' the new Microsoft president said.
``There are thousands of companies who we benefit from and who will
benefit from a closer relationship with us.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are, of course, our competitors,'' he added. ``And
whether you are at Oracle or Netscape or Sun, we look forward to
supporting you even better from our facility here in the valley.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, which is headquartered in Redmond, Wash., will build
a 515,000-square-foot, 32-acre complex that will house nearly 800
employees now scattered in several offices from Cupertino to San
Jose.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest contingent is from WebTV, a Palo Alto firm acquired
by Microsoft last April. The 525 WebTV workers now work in six
different offices.
</P>
<P>
   The new facility, which will be dubbed Microsoft South Campus,
will also house about 170 workers who develop and test PowerPoint
presentation software for PCs and Apple Macintoshes.
</P>
<P>
   The campus also will be home to the sales and marketing staff
from Hotmail, a free e-mail service now based in Cupertino.
Microsoft bought the firm in December.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft agreed to a deal with property owner Berg &AMP; Berg
Development of Cupertino to lease the land, a former Kaiser Sand &AMP;
Gravel facility at L'Avenida near Shoreline Drive. Microsoft will
construct the buildings, and the first is scheduled to open by July
1999, said Barney Kinzer, Microsoft's real estate program manager.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not announced, but Berg &AMP; Berg President
Carl Berg said Microsoft has an initial seven-year lease with
various options that could extend the deal another 20 years. Berg
estimated Microsoft's plans could cost between $200 to $300 per
square foot.
</P>
<P>
   Rival Netscape was not quite loading the welcome wagon for its
new neighbor. A spokesperson for Netscape said, ``Our hope is
they'll be a good neighbor but we don't plan on having a block
party anytime soon.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
