<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-06 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2090 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CT-COMPTROLLER-CAMPAI     08-06 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-COMPTROLLER-CAMPAIGN-500(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP COMPTROLLER CANDIDATE QUITS DUE TO FINANCIAL ALLEGATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Fla., Mo.)   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ The Republican nominee for Connecticut's state
comptroller, part of the ethnically diverse hand-picked slate of
candidates touted by Gov. John Rowland, withdrew his candidacy
Thursday amid concerns about his involvement in a bank fraud case
in Puerto Rico, a partially falsified resume, and his lateness in
paying federal income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Antonio Serbia, 58, was acquitted in 1986 of charges he
participated in a bank fraud scheme in Puerto Rico. He also listed
two education degrees on his resume that he did not receive, and
has often not paid his federal income taxes on time, according to
officials at the schools and the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy, which came to light in an article published
Thursday in The Hartford Courant, was a surprise to Rowland and
other Republicans, who suffered the first bump in a campaign where
they have mainly watched the governor's Democratic challenger, Rep.
Barbara Kennelly, struggle raising money and generating excitement
about her candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Rowland was apparently so comfortable with the race that
he was on Block Island, R.I., this week, enjoying his second
vacation of the summer, when the news broke.
</P>
<P>
   During the federal trial, Serbia was accused of helping prepare
false loans at a bank in Puerto Rico and in some cases using the
money for his own purposes, according to a 1986 article in the San
Juan Star. During the trial, he defended himself by saying he had
signed blank notes for the bank's president because he trusted him.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Wednesday evening, Serbia said he would
withdraw because he realized continuing questions about his trial
would hurt the rest of the Republican ticket. ``This election
should be about the future of the state of Connecticut, not about
my past,'' Serbia said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I was acquitted _ found to be innocent after a full
trial _ I looked on that episode of my life as over,'' Serbia
added. ``Unfortunately, in the world of politics, that is not how
it works.''
</P>
<P>
   State party chairman Christopher DePino, who spent the day
talking with Serbia, said he felt the withdrawal was best for the
Republican Party, a sentiment also expressed by Rowland in a brief
written statement. ``The Democrat Party doesn't have any issues to
run against John Rowland on,'' DePino said. ``And I did not want
his personal situation to be their issue for 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean Pagani, Rowland campaign spokesman, said that Serbia did
not mention the Puerto Rico bank fraud trial when was asked about
his background. Republican leaders knew Serbia was behind on
federal taxes, but Pagani said that because they were being repaid
Republicans were not concerned about that.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Republican leaders expressed frustration that Serbia
had not revealed his indictment to them. ``It sort of like the old
Steve Martin joke,'' said one Rowland campaign official. ``Oh! I
forgot armed robbery was against the law.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kennelly on Thursday blamed Rowland for not more thoroughly
checking Serbia's background.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the responsibility of a governor to ensure that the
people in positions of leadership in state government have the
highest level of personal and professional integrity,'' Mrs.
Kennelly said in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his haste to score political points, John Rowland failed to
put the state's best interest first.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kennelly was referring to the ``Rowland rainbow'' that the
governor had assembled for his underticket. Running with Rowland
and Lt. Gov. Jodi Rell are Santa Mendoza, a woman of Mexican
descent who is running for attorney general and Ben Andrews Jr., an
African-American and former president of the Connecticut NAACP
running for secretary of the state. Serbia was born in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have been criticized by Rowland for having only one
minority candidate on their ticket. Denise Nappier, who is black,
is running for treasurer, but she is facing a primary challenge
from Frank Lecce, a white man who had vied for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Democrats were happy to note that the Republican
ticket problem resulted from a desire to balance their ticket
regardless of a person's qualifications.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of mistakes are the by-product of a closed-door
process in which the goal was political points, the goal was
political pandering,''said Jonathan Pelto, Mrs. Kennelly's campaign
director, on Thursday. ``And they paid a price for their haste to
score political points.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he was tapped to run for comptroller, Serbia had been the
state building inspector from 1995-97 and then was assistant to the
state treasurer in charge of economic and community development, a
position he left recently to focus on campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   According to the San Juan Star, Serbia was acquitted of eight
counts of aiding and abetting a vice president of a bank in Puerto
Rico in a scheme in which they prepared false loan documents, then
used the money from the loan for themselves. Serbia said he was
duped by the vice president, who had pleaded nolo contendere to the
charges, then testified against Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   In the San Juan Star article, Serbia said he was eating lunch
when a secretary came to ask him to sign some documents. ``With the
napkin still in my waist, I went to the lawyer's office and asked,
`where do I sign?''' the newspaper quotes Serbia as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic incumbent, Comptroller Nancy Wyman, said Thursday
she was surprised by the allegations, but said she would continue
running on her strong record. Asked if a person who had signed
blank documents should be running for comptroller, a job of
overseeing the state's finances, she said: ``I won't sign anything
until I read it and understand it. I know what I've been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference announcing his candidacy, Serbia, an
architect who once ran for mayor of San Juan, he said he had a
degrees from the University of Florida in Gainesville, the
University of Puerto Rico, the University of St. Louis, Parks
College of Aeronautical Technology and Alexander Hamilton Institute
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the University of Florida and the University of
Puerto Rico confirmed he had received bachelor's degrees at their
schools. But an official at St. Louis University said Serbia had
attended but not received a degree.
</P>
<P>
   And Alexander Hamilton Institute, now in Ramsey, N.J., was never
an accredited college, but instead offered correspondence courses
in business administration. The institute is now solely a
publishing house, an official there said.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia has also had significant federal tax problems. The IRS
placed a lien against Serbia in October 1992 for taxes due in 1988
and 1989 of $8,910.51, which was released in February once he paid
all taxes, interest and penalties, according to the IRS. The
Connecticut secretary of the state's office had record of a second
lien, but did not have the amount available Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia told the Hartford Courant that he is paying another $300
monthly to the IRS on a 1997 tax bill of either $4,000 or $7,000.
</P>
<P>
   According to The Hartford Courant, he also was alleged to have
not kept up child support payment for his ex-wife, but said that
was a record-keeping error in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Pagani, Rowland's campaign manager, said resumes for possible
new comptroller candidates had already been arriving at Republican
headquarters Thursday, and DePino said the party hoped to name a
replacement in a week to 10 days. They wouldn't talk about possible
candidates, but two people whose names had been floated this spring
_ state Rep. Marilyn Hess of Greenwich, and Alan Schlesinger,
former mayor of Derby _ were being mentioned again Thursday for
comptroller.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
