<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' HUNDLEY WAKES UP ON 3-FOR-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Todd Hundley did not get much sleep Wednesday night.
But he had a good reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat up half the night looking at videotapes,'' Hundley said
before Thursday's noontime game with the San Francisco Giants at
Shea Stadium. ``Seth and I were on the phone until about 1
o'clock.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Hundley and his agent, Seth Levinson, learned from
their separate viewings of Hundley at bat, it worked. Hundley
entered Thursday's game with a .161 batting average in his first 24
games, no home runs and only six runs batted in. He went 3 for 3,
with two singles sandwiched around a hard-hit double.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good day for Todd,'' manager Bobby Valentine said.
``Yesterday was the first day he sat against a right-hander. And
today, he came out with a vengeance. He looked very relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley had appeared to be overswinging. He said he worked on
changing to a more fluid motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play the outfield, you have a lot of energy and you
take that energy up to the plate,'' said Hundley, who is being
converted from catcher to outfielder. ``On a scale of 1 to 10,
you're at a 10. I need to relax and not try to hit it 10 miles.''
</P>
<P>
   The Piazza Saga Goes On
</P>
<P>
   General manager Steve Phillips said he has had some discussions
with Mike Piazza and his representatives and that he has not been
told that Piazza will test the free-agent market after this season.
When asked if the plan was still to try and re-sign Piazza,
Phillips said: ``I'm hopeful. I'm hopeful.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is no secret in the Mets' clubhouse that Piazza seems
unhappy with his situation. Those close to him are saying the
all-star catcher will go the free-agent route.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, who had little to say after Thursday's game, seemed
upset when Valentine removed him in a double switch in the eighth
inning of a game that the Mets were leading by 6-5, a move
Valentine later called a hunch.
</P>
<P>
   In went Todd Pratt as catcher while Greg McMichael entered as
the pitcher. The switch enabled Pratt to bat third in the bottom of
the eighth in what had been the pitcher's slot. But when the Giants
called on the right-hander Robb Nen to protect their 8-6 lead with
runners on first and second and none out, Valentine pinch-hit for
Pratt with the left-handed hitting Jorge Fabregas. Fabregas
delivered a run-scoring groundout to leave the Mets trailing, 8-7.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were still down a run when what would have been
Piazza's turn to bat came in the ninth. Valentine used Matt Franco
as a pinch-hitter for Turk Wendell, the pitcher, and Franco
responded with a single that moved John Olerud from first to third
and was instrumental in the winning rally.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza went 0-for-4 to more cheers than boos. Before the game,
Phillips again said he thought Piazza was pressing. As for the
boos?
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand it,'' Phillips said. ``It's not exclusive to
Mike. It's the way the fans in New York communicate their feelings
about someone's performance at any given time. Whatever the
underlying reason, it does have an impact. But that's part of
playing in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   There's No In-Between
</P>
<P>
   Tony Phillips pointed to the booing as an incentive for his
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I can get the job done,'' said Phillips, who went
4-for-5 with a double and a homer to raise his average in six games
as a Met to .385. ``I know if I don't, I'll get booed, so I don't
have much choice. Being booed doesn't feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Chants of ``To-ny, To-ny'' do feel good, however. Phillips
joined New York knowing that if he performed, he would win over
fans quickly and that if he did not, he would hear about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There ain't no in-between,'' the 39-year-old outfielder said.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Valentine said that Phillips has given him more than
he expected. Valentine also added that he almost did not start
Phillips Thursday because of the quick turnaround from Wednesday
night's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't sure if that old body could do it,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii Doesn't Feel Snakebit
</P>
<P>
   Masato Yoshii, who has not won since May 27 despite four strong
outings in a row, was asked if he felt a little snakebit. ``I would
feel snakebit if the team kept on losing,'' Yoshii said through his
interpreter. ``It's nice to get a win for yourself. But I'm happy
because we won today.''
</P>
<P>
   John Franco's two-year contract extension will pay him a base
salary of $6.15 million _ $2.8 million next season and $3.15
million in the year 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
