<SLUG> BC-TV-VIEWERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEFORE THE TV CLICKER, WATCHING WAS A SCIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paul Klein died in his sleep last month. Among other things, the
former NBC researcher and programmer, who made his reputation in
the 1960s and 1970s, created the ``L.O.P.'' theory.
</P>
<P>
   L.O.P. means least objectionable program. In its obituary, the
New York Times sniffed that Klein ``enjoyed modest fame in the
television industry'' for his theory.
</P>
<P>
   It was a theory a couch potato could love. Klein knew that
people parked themselves in front of the TV set at night and stayed
there until they trundled off to bed. It was an ingrained habit,
and viewers would stay put and watch shows so long as they weren't
objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   Klein would even insist that a network could maintain a 10 share
_ a 10th of the viewing audience _ with a test pattern. People
simply didn't want to get up and turn the dial.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1980, NBC captured a meager 9 share with a cultural
special called ``Live From Studio 8H.'' Grant Tinker, who'd later
become chairman of NBC, recalled in his memoir, ``Tinker in
Television,'' that Klein had an explanation for that awful 9 share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viewers hated this program so much,'' Tinker quoted Klein as
saying, ``that all across America, thousands of disabled people
threw themselves out of bed and crawled to the set, on their
elbows, just to turn the dial.''
</P>
<P>
   By now, the L.O.P. theory is pretty much a relic from the big
networks' halcyon days.
</P>
<P>
   People have remote controls now. No more heaving yourself toward
the set to change channels. The three-network hegemony is over.
Cable has fragmented the audience so much that there's actually a
viable market for objectionable programs. How else to explain
``South Park''? Nintendo and the Internet vie for attention. In
1998, a 10 share is starting to look respectable.
</P>
<P>
   Klein's notion that viewers would stay put so long as they
weren't offended seemingly applies only to a few nooks and crannies
on today's television landscape.
</P>
<P>
   One is Friday night on ABC, where the ``TGIF'' package has long
given middle-American families a simplistic slate of shows they can
watch without chronic moments of awkwardness.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's Thursday-night lineup is probably the best surviving
example. Grab the audience, then don't give it a compelling reason
to split. With strong shows at 8, 9 and 10 p.m., NBC has been able
to pull ratings with subpar shows at 8:30 and 9:30. On paper, ``The
Single Guy'' was a monster hit; in actuality, its ``popularity''
was a bag of gas.
</P>
<P>
   With Americans all over the dial _ well, really there is no dial
anymore _ and all over the house, Klein's theory has been replaced
by a costly search for ``appointment'' television.
</P>
<P>
   The object now is to develop distinct hits that fickle viewers
will fight to find, rather than a seamless stream of inoffensive
programs for the indiscriminate masses. ``Ally McBeal'' is an
appointment show. ``The X-Files.'' ``Dawson's Creek.'' ``South
Park,'' sad to say. ``Frasier,'' as a Tuesday show.
</P>
<P>
   Appointment TV is a naturally bloody approach to programming.
It's every show for itself. What once would have fit into schedules
as solid, conventional shows _ a ``George &AMP; Leo,'' say, or maybe a
``Michael Hayes'' from last fall _ are dying in droves. Nearly 40
new series premiered last autumn; four were renewed for a second
season.
</P>
<P>
   So Klein's theory, not so modest as his obit suggested, preceded
him in death.
</P>
<P>
   As for Klein himself, he'd helped form a pay-per-view movie
service for hotel rooms in the 1970s, between his two stints at
NBC, and in 1982 he founded the Playboy Channel.
</P>
<P>
   At NBC, he set ``Holocaust,'' ``Shogun'' and ``Centennial'' into
production. Also ``Supertrain,'' a legendary flop in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Big stuff. But the Times didn't identify Klein in the obit
headline as NBC's research director or vice president for programs.
No, he was ``a developer of pay-per-view TV channels.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC? That was merely a network, whatever networks used to be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
