<SLUG> BC-CALIF-DORNAN-EXPENSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL APPROVES MONEY FOR OUSTED CONGRESSMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (mk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an unusual move, a House panel has awarded
Robert Dornan, the conservative former congressman, $320,526 in
expenses for his unsuccessful effort to overturn his 1996
California election defeat. His opponent, Rep. Loretta Sanchez, a
Democrat, was awarded $250,500, $70,000 less than Dornan.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted earlier this year to seat Ms. Sanchez after the
Committee on House Oversight found there was not enough evidence to
overturn the election. Dornan is running against Ms. Sanchez to
reclaim his seat in this year's election.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's decision on Wednesday to award money to both sides
in the dispute infuriated Democrats, who said it was unprecedented
to give taxpayer money to the loser in a contested election.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's out of money, he's down in the polls and he's a terrible
candidate,'' said Rep. Xavier Becerra, D-Calif., chairman of the
Congressional Hispanic Caucus. ``So what do they do? They give him
$320,000.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee decided to reimburse both Dornan and Ms. Sanchez
for their lawyers' fees, but it opted not to pay expenses involving
court actions. As a result, Ms. Sanchez, who spent close to $75,000
in expenses challenging the constitutionality of a series of House
subpoenas, was awarded less money.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., chairman of the committee, said the
panel had wide latitude in reimbursing members and challengers for
``reasonable'' expenses. The panel, Thomas said, deemed the
reimbursement appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a payment for his attorney, for his attorneys' fees,''
not for Dornan's campaign, Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats for months engaged in a rancorous
partisan battle over Ms. Sanchez's election, which Dornan
maintained was tainted by the votes of undocumented immigrants and
unregistered voters. Ms. Sanchez won the race by 984 votes. In the
end, the House committee investigating the matter found that 748
noncitizens had voted, an insufficient number to overturn the
election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
