<SLUG> BC-TEN-SELES-FAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAN'S SPIRIT, ASHES WITH `MO-NI-CA'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD _ Two of Monica Seles' biggest fans, Catherine
Trachtenberg and John Alexander, are here this week for the Toshiba
Tennis Classic. They'll also be in Manhattan Beach next week for
the Acura Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Trachtenberg is the one in the shorts and sandles. Alexander is
the one in the little cloth bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, Mo-ni-ca!'' Trachtenberg screamed from the third row
at the La Costa Resort &AMP; Spa stadium as Seles defeated Sandrine
Testud in two tough sets Wednesday night. ``For Jonathan!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's Jonathan?'' said the box-seat holder in front of her.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother,'' Trachtenberg said. She lifted the bag off her
lap and held it up to the other woman's eyes. ``In here.''
</P>
<P>
   Trachtenberg, a registered nurse, lives in Winnetka, in the San
Fernando Valley. As she tells the story, her brother died in
January at age 42 after having a heart attack in Gainesville, Fla.,
and was cremated.
</P>
<P>
   Each of six relatives received a portion of the ashes.
</P>
<P>
   And just what is some of Alexander doing on his sister's lap at
center court?
</P>
<P>
   Trachtenberg said her brother was confined to a wheelchair for
the last 14 years of his life following a motorcycle accident, and
he felt an understandable bitterness. One of the times he felt
whole was when he attended tennis matches, especially when he
watched Seles.
</P>
<P>
   Trachtenberg said they met when she and Alexander complimented
Seles after a practice during the Manhattan Beach tournament in
1990. She said Seles' mother snapped a photograph of them
Trachtenberg still has. And the player then ranked No.2 in the
world left tickets to the late rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to go to a tennis tournament in a wheelchair,'' said
Pam O'Connor, Trachtenberg's stepsister from Texas, who is here on
vacation. ``He'd have to sit in a special section and he'd feel
like people were staring at him. She (Seles) got him tickets that
put him in a section where he didn't feel like a disabled person.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Trachtenberg brings her brother to Seles' matches whenever
she's in Southern California. She even sprinkled some of the ashes
in the grass under her court-side seat. She plans to do the same
next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spreading his spirit around,'' O'Connor calls that.
</P>
<P>
   The stepsisters say Alexander could get loud and obnoxious at
times. And they remember that for whatever reason, Seles related to
him surprisingly easily in their brief encounter. Now, the box-seat
neighbors might say, Trachtenberg is loud and obnoxious enough for
two, cheering ``Mo-ni-ca'' with more emotion than anybody else in
the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, shut up,'' a guy in the front row muttered.
</P>
<P>
   Some people never will understand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
