<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Security Flaw is Found in Eudora E-mail Software
</P>
<P>
   Just days after a security flaw was revealed in two popular
electronic mail programs, an equally troubling vulnerability has
been discovered in Eudora, the most widely used of all e-mail
software.
</P>
<P>
   The Eudora flaw makes it possible for a computer user to
booby-trap an e-mail message by inserting a seemingly harmless link
to an Internet location that executes a malignant code. This could
permit an attacker to destroy or steal data or to tamper with a
personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   Slower Growth at American Express
</P>
<P>
   Shares of American Express fell 6.8 percent, or $7.375, to
$101.0625, after the company warned that its growth overseas would
be hampered by the Asian financial crisis and a broader softening
of the global economy. The chief executive of American Express,
Harvey Golub, told analysts that the current slowdown is hurting
both the travel services and credit card businesses.
</P>
<P>
   A Profit for Chrysler's Eaton
</P>
<P>
   Whether the merger of Chrysler and Daimler-Benz succeeds or not,
Robert Eaton, Chrysler's chairman and chief executive, is
guaranteed to do well, documents released by the two companies
show.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam Plans to Restate Earnings
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam expects to restate its financial statements for 1997 and
possibly for 1996 and the first quarter of this year, because of
possible accounting irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   EDS Chief Resigns
</P>
<P>
   Lester Alberthal Jr., chairman and chief executive of Electronic
Data Systems, has resigned. Shares of the company have declined
since it was spun off from General Motors in 1996. It has also lost
its lead in the computer services industry to IBM and several major
contracts have proved less profitable than anticipated for EDS.
Alberthal was the company's second leader after its founder, Ross
Perot.
</P>
<P>
   Worldcom Bonds Are Well Received
</P>
<P>
   Worldcom sold a record $6.1 billion of bonds, attracting strong
demand in a choppy and worried corporate bond market. The sale
brought the total of corporate bond issuance so far in 1998 to more
than $560 billion.
</P>
<P>
   New Chief is Reviving Donna Karan
</P>
<P>
   Donna Karan International has started to turn around under the
guidance of its new chief executive, John Idol. Revenue rose 12.5
percent in the second quarter and the apparel manufacturing company
narrowed its loss by 57.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Factory Orders Rose 0.1 Percent in June
</P>
<P>
   Orders to factories rose only one-tenth of 1 percent in June,
held back by slumping demand for aircraft and autos.
</P>
<P>
   Retail Sales Rose 4.8 Percent in July
</P>
<P>
   Retail sales at stores open at least a year jumped 4.8 percent
last month, the best July gain since 1993, when sales rose 5.4
percent. Specialty apparel stores and off-price clothing merchants
were the big winners.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment Dips in Germany
</P>
<P>
   The German unemployment rate fell to 10.9 percent, the lowest
level in 20 months, in July, as companies hired workers to keep up
with the economy's growth.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Economic Problems Grow
</P>
<P>
   Russia's financial crisis is creating problems for companies as
bills go unpaid and businesses run out of money to pay each other,
taxes and their workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
