</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TENT-REVIVAL-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING JESUS UNDER THE TENT IN CITY LOTS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By VIVIAN S. TOY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By the time the Rev. John H. Boyd Sr. stepped up to
the pulpit beneath his gospel big top the other night, his audience
had already been on its feet for some time, swaying to the music
that pulsated from towering stacks of loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   Like teen-agers screaming for a rock idol, grown men and women _
perhaps 1,500 of them, in tailored suits and beaded gowns, in
sundresses and blue jeans _ cheered wildly as they reached their
arms skyward and toward the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, listen,'' the pastor pleaded. ``You got to hear what
God is saying. I don't care what happened yesterday, it's your time
to be blessed tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Cries of ``Yes, Lord'' and ``Thank you, Jesus'' rang out in the
warm night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every promise you've been waiting for, tonight is the night,''
Boyd thundered. ``It'll happen to you.''
</P>
<P>
   It did not seem to matter that the preacher could barely be
heard above the pounding of the organ and the shouting of the
congregation. The wall-less sanctuary shook with energy as the
crowd at the makeshift church settled in for a night's worth of
communing with God: the foot-stomping, hand-clapping,
throat-crackling kind that evokes nothing so much as summer in the
Bible Belt.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of sitting in a field somewhere below the
Mason-Dixon line, this tent was planted in a sprawling vacant lot
in South Jamaica, Queens, surrounded by scrap iron vendors and auto
repair shops.
</P>
<P>
   A rural tradition that slaves adopted as their own when they
were denied the luxury of four walls for religious observances,
outdoor revival meetings like Boyd's arrived in Northern cities
with the blacks who came seeking work at the turn of the century.
Over the years, tent revivals in vacant lots across New York have
become as much a part of summertime as humidity and haze.
</P>
<P>
   The tents usually go up for three or four weeks at a time, in
neighborhoods in southeastern Queens and parts of Brooklyn and the
Bronx. Most tents hold afternoon and evening services that last
from two to four hours. And while tent revivals of yore in the city
were fairly simple operations with a few folding chairs and a light
bulb or two powered by an extension cord, tents today have become
much more elaborate, with booming sound systems, floodlights and
multitiered altars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tent is just like church _ only the walls have been rolled
up so that everybody can see what goes on,'' said Pam Dye, a member
of Boyd's New Greater Bethel Ministries, based in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   For the churches, the tents are an informal and open setting for
spreading the word and attracting new members. For the congregants,
they offer a warm and ready sense of community that often recalls
childhood in the South or the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   To Willie Tolliver, a professor at the Hunter College School of
Social Work who has studied the black church, the tent revivals are
somewhat akin to the increasingly popular retreats of corporate
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a chance for a special rekindling of the spirit,'' he
said. ``But it's also an opportunity to bring in new believers or
people who have fallen away, or as they say in the black church,
people who have backslid.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Are there more tents out there these days bringing in the
backsliders? The experts say they really do not know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tent meetings now are a little bit like storefront churches,''
explained the Rev. Charles Rawlings, director of urban programs at
the National Council of Churches. ``They're episodic, and you don't
really know when or where they're going to pop up next.''
</P>
<P>
   But Charles Atiles, who coordinated a three-week tent revival in
July for the Tabernacle of Prayer in Jamaica, said, ``Part of the
reason you don't see even more tents in the city is because there
isn't a considerable amount of land to make it easy to put up a big
tent, especially in densely populated areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The billboard for the Tabernacle of Prayer's tent urged
passers-by to bring ``the sick and afflicted'' and ``the down and
out'' for some ``Old Fashion Holy Ghost.''
</P>
<P>
   Atiles said the church decided to rent a vacant lot in downtown
Jamaica for its twice-daily revival meetings because of the area's
heavy pedestrian traffic. It did not hurt that there was a homeless
shelter across the street. In addition to giving the shelter
residents a place to spend a few hours every day, the church also
provided free meals each Friday. ``You've got to catch the fish
before you clean it,'' Atiles said.
</P>
<P>
   The sight of New Greater Bethel's bright yellow-and-blue tent
caught Linda Gourdine's eye one afternoon and reeled her in, even
though she is a member of a different church. ``I saw the tent as I
was riding on the bus, and I decided to come back,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gourdine said she was heartened by the thought that she was
probably surrounded by people who ordinarily would not go to a
service at all because they were intimidated by the stained glass
and dress code of a church. She also said that the services
reminded her of South Carolina, where she spent every summer as a
child, visiting family and listening to her grandfathers, both
preachers, who often held forth at open-air meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being back there again,'' she said. ``I like the
atmosphere, being outdoors and close to nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyd, the 77-year-old pastor of New Greater Bethel, has pitched
a tent somewhere in the city every summer since 1972. He said he
started planning his summer revivals months in advance, lining up
nationally known evangelists as guest speakers for the nighttime
services.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd said in the five weeks under the tent, the church would
collect about $75,000 in offerings, a large sum but not enough to
cover the estimated $100,000 in costs. In addition to renting the
city-owned lot, the church also had to pay for a temporary power
line, two air-conditioned trailers for the preachers and staff,
portable toilets, the main tent and two smaller ones _ one used as
a bookstore and another used as a child-care center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be in the red this year, but it costs money to
restructure people's lives,'' the pastor said.
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Curtis, a public hospital worker, said going to the tent
each night for five weeks had indeed changed her life. ``Before I
was out there partying and having a good time,'' she said. ``I was
out in the flesh, and now I'm in the spirit. And people ask me:
`Girl, what's gotten into you? You're glowing all over the
place.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
