<SLUG> BC-FBN-COX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO FOOTBALL: BRYAN COX'S TEMPER MASKS A GOOD SIDE
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The problem with Bryan Cox, now a linebacker with
the New York Jets, is that over the years he has been his own worst
enemy. Reporters love to chronicle players with big mouths who say
obnoxious things, make obscene gestures to fans and tell the
commissioner he knows what he can do with his fines. Even if you
act like the pope off the field, that image of a chronic bad boy is
forever forged by the media if you constantly act the fool on the
50-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   The National Football League was once irritated with the Miami
Dolphins after they nominated Cox their man of the year because of
all the charity work he was doing in his free time. Since Cox has
paid over $100,000 in fines and always seemed to be on the ESPN
highlights screaming at officials, at first glance you can't blame
the league for being a little annoyed.
</P>
<P>
   But what has been lost in Cox's uncanny ability to self-destruct
is that in his eight seasons in the NFL there have been fewer
better off-the-field role models. The good deeds he has done away
from football have become overshadowed by what has happened on the
field. Quietly, Cox has been one of football's most charitable men.
</P>
<P>
   Few know of the tens of thousands of dollars he has given to
various charities. Or how when he was with the Dolphins, every
Tuesday, the only day players have off during the regular season,
Cox would go to the rough neighborhoods in the Miami area and speak
with youngsters about the importance of staying in school. After
one Monday night game in San Diego, the team flew all night back to
Miami, landing at 5 a.m. Cox went home, showered, and three hours
later was speaking at a school.
</P>
<P>
   He did this every week, among many other generous acts. There
was little fanfare, few headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, Cox has even treated the news media with respect.
When a Dolphins rookie once boycotted the Miami media because he
was upset with them for making fun of the fact that he had seven
toes, Cox told the player that speaking to the media was part of
his job. The player talked.
</P>
<P>
   The good deeds, though, have seemingly been outweighed by the
bad ones. Cox has thrown helmets, he has been kicked out of games
and once cursed so many times with television cameras rolling, all
that viewers could hear was a steady stream of bleeps. Several
years ago, he taunted the entire Cincinnati Bengals bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing is no fun to me,'' Cox has said. ``I don't want to be
associated with people who accept losing. I don't accept losing.
Sometimes that causes me to go berserk.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox is no longer the player he was, a three-time Pro Bowl
selection who could dominate a game. In the Jets' exhibition game
against the Philadelphia Eagles last night, he played sparingly,
which must seem strange for a player who when healthy played almost
all the time, in every game. What you get with Cox now is a
hot-blooded fighter who relies more on the fire instead of pure
physical skills. NFL scouts say the best the Jets can hope for from
Cox is a solid pass rush on third downs. He no longer has great
speed, or NFL caliber physical strength, so he tends to
overcompensate with passion. Sometimes, those emotions spill onto
the field like an oil slick.
</P>
<P>
   What Cox needs is an edit mode between his brain and his mouth.
The Chicago Bears' releasing him on June 2 did not change him in
the least, and there is no question he will blow up again. There
will be another incident. Bryan Cox wouldn't be Bryan Cox without
one.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is how will the Jets, both players and coaches,
handle that explosion when it comes? The last two coaches Cox
played for, Don Shula in Miami and Dave Wannstedt in Chicago, gave
up trying to understand or change him. Coach Bill Parcells can do
both. Parcells is a lot of things, mainly a boisterous bully with a
Hall of Fame ability to coach football players.He has his faults,
but he is able to get what he wants out of players.
</P>
<P>
   When Cox pulls one of his stunts, Parcells has both the clout
and the skill to stop it cold. Besides, the Jets signed Cox to just
a one-year deal worth $500,000 with no signing bonus, which is
pocket change in the NFL. If his act suddenly gets old again, the
Jets can put him back on the street.
</P>
<P>
   One thing Cox has is a life outside of football. He has taken
care of his money so he's not playing for a paycheck. What he's
playing for now is a chance to win again. Maybe that is just enough
to prevent him from ending up on the wrong side of a headline. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
