<HEADLINE>
SALOMON SMITH BARNEY EXECUTIVE JOINS GOLDMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Pa., N.Y.)   (bl)  
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Michael Carr, co-head of Salomon Smith Barney's
global mergers and acquisition group, has joined Goldman, Sachs &AMP;
Co. as a managing director in its mergers and acquisitions group.
He will be primarily responsible for covering industrial companies.
</P>
<P>
   Carr's compensation package was not disclosed. But people close
to the companies said Goldman, Sachs had been offering recruits the
promise of stock as an incentive to join the firm. Goldman, Sachs,
one of Wall Street's premier investment banks, has agreed to sell
shares of the company to the public this fall.
</P>
<P>
   It is thought some high-level recruits could get stock valued
from $10 million to $25 million, a large portion of it vested over
five years, these people said. Carr was contacted only recently by
representatives of the firm about a job. But Goldman, Sachs has
been talking to a select group of bankers and analysts at Wall
Street firms _ some of whom have already rejected offers _ and more
announcements are likely.
</P>
<P>
   The move is not a new one. Investment banker Bob Matschullat,
who had worked at Morgan Stanley in the 1970s and later became a
board member, rejoined Morgan Stanley in 1986 as a managing
director and got stock months before that company went public,
people at that firm said.
</P>
<P>
   Carr is a graduate of Wesleyan University in Middletown, Conn.,
and received an MBA from the Wharton School of the University of
Pennsylvania. He joined Salomon Brothers in 1985 out of graduate
school and advised several clients, including Federated Department
Stores, General Dynamics and Beatrice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved my experience at Salomon,'' he said in an interview
Thursday. ``The attraction of Goldman, Sachs, is its integrity and
the depth of its relationships.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carr's departure is the most recent from Salomon Smith Barney
after the announced merger between Travelers Group, its parent, and
Citicorp. Frank Yeary, a telecommunications banker, left early this
summer to work at the Carlyle Group. Gregg Polle will replace Carr
as co-head of the Salomon group
</P>
</TEXT>
