<HEADLINE>
SUSPENDED JUDGE SENT TO JAIL FOR SIX MONTHS FOR ALCOHOL USE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DON HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. -- Suspended Judge Robert C. Bradley
pleaded guilty to violating his probation and was ordered to begin
serving a six-month sentence immediately for an earlier violation.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley pleaded guilty Thursday to one count of violating
probation after officers determined that he had been drinking two
days earlier. Santa Barbara Municipal Court Judge Denise de
Bellefville ordered Bradley taken into custody and moved to the
main jail in neighboring Ventura County, where he will be held for
the time being.
</P>
<P>
   De Bellefville did not give Bradley additional jail time for his
latest probation violation, said Bill Maile, a spokesman for the
state Attorney General's Office, which prosecuted Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upon his release in six months, he is required to put himself
in the custody of the Probation Department and enter a six-month
residential (alcohol) treatment program,'' Maile said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, 57, had been on probation since pleading guilty in
February to two drunken-driving offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's arrest Tuesday, his sixth in eight months, came two
weeks after he prematurely left a residential treatment program in
Prescott, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   The cases were prosecuted by the state Attorney General's Office
and heard by a judge in Santa Barbara to avoid a possibility of a
conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley remains on paid leave from his job. Although his
judicial term expires at the end of this year, the Commission on
Judicial Performance plans to hold a hearing in October to consider
removing him from office.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
