<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPOS HUMBLE PEREZ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Unlike Mark Grudzielanek, Carlos Perez was cheered in
his return to Olympic Stadium. And when he allowed seven runs in
Thursday's 9-0 Dodgers loss to the Montreal Expos, the place went
wild.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, acquired with Grudzielanek last Friday for Wilton
Guerrero and three minor-leaguers, was a member of the Expos
organization. When he returned this week, he found it difficult to
remember these were no longer friends on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was very emotional for me, and I think that hurt,'' said
Perez (7-11). ``I used to be a guy here that people on the street
used to come up to and say hello. I would sign things for them and
give them gum. I'm moving on, but there was still a lot of me here
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez, who pitched seven scoreless innings Saturday in his
Dodgers debut, faced the minimum nine batters in the first three
innings. But in the fourth, he gave up a two-run double to Bob
Henley and a two-run homer to Mike Mordecai.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, he hit center fielder Terry Jones, who later
scored, and lasted only two batters into the sixth. Struggling
Darren Hall came in and allowed two runs, raising his earned run
average to 10.45.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the attention was on Perez, who was making his
second Dodgers start since breaking his nose in a July 26 auto
accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``My right shoulder is still a little sore from the accident,
but other than that I am fine,'' said Perez, who patiently answered
questions for more than a half-hour on a getaway day. ``In New
York, my control was bad (six walks), and today it was good (none).
I needed to get this game out of my system. It was hard, but now
it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Protest ruling: National League President Leonard Coleman will
rule today on a protest by the New York Mets that the Dodgers
illegally inserted second baseman Eric Young into the lineup last
Friday after Guerrero was traded.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are expected to win the protest. If they lose, the
Dodgers would forfeit the game to the Mets, who lead them by 2{
games in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero was traded eight minutes before the first pitch. Young
was on the disabled list and first had to be activated. Infielder
Tripp Cromer was put on the DL, and Young walked to the plate to
start the game.
</P>
<P>
   First-base coach Mickey Hatcher brought the lineup card to home
plate with Guerrero's name at the top, but manager Glenn Hoffman
later notified the umpiring crew of the change. The Mets think
that's a lot to do in less than 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Len is out of the office, but he will decide (today),'' NL
vice president Katy Feeney said Thursday by phone from New York.
``We tell clubs when they are making a transaction close to game
time they need to let the league office know. They also must advise
the umpires and the opposing team.''
</P>
<P>
   Fair ball:!off! One play certain to make the highlight reel came
in the Expos' four-run fourth inning. Wilton Guerrero bunted up the
first-base line. Carlos Perez watched the ball, then got on his
stomach as it came to a stop on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``He even tried to blow it a little,'' home-plate umpire Mark
Hirschbeck said with a laugh. ``But that ball wasn't going foul no
matter what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   The usually cheerful Perez wasn't so happy. ``Wilton came around
to score,'' he said. ``Maybe if he doesn't, we can come back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
