<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUIMA FILES SUIT, CITING `BLUE WALL' OF SILENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Abner Louima, the Haitian immigrant who was
reportedly tortured in a Brooklyn police station, asserted in a
lawsuit Thursday that New York City and the police officers' union
were ultimately responsible for what happened because they had
jointly encouraged a ``blue wall'' of silence that fostered police
misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit brought in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn, lawyers
for Louima claimed that the policies, customs and practices of the
Police Department and the union, the Patrolmen's Benevolent
Association, ``have promoted an atmosphere in which the very worst
police officers feel assured that evidence of misdeeds depriving
citizens of their civil rights, no matter how awful, will be hidden
by PBA representatives and the `code of silence.'''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to naming the city and the union as defendants, the
suit _ which does not specify the amount of damages being sought _
also includes as defendants the five officers who have been charged
in a criminal case with attacking Louima or with trying to cover up
the attack, and three former supervisors of the precinct involved
in the case. The former supervisors are accused of failures of
oversight.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the city's Law Department, Lorna Goodman, said
she could not comment on the suit because her agency had not
received a copy of it. But a spokesman for the police officers'
union, Joseph Mancini, termed the suit ``without merit as it
applies to the PBA.'' He said that ``shortly after the incident,
the PBA publicly encouraged police officers to come forward with
what they knew about this incident.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the suit claimed that the union and several of its
officials, who are also named as defendants, ``suppressed''
admissions of criminal behavior they had received from police
officers and ``adopted a strategy of obstruction.''
</P>
<P>
   As Louima, 31, stood by without speaking in the downtown
Manhattan office of two of his lawyers, one of them, Johnnie
Cochran Jr., said that the suit was ``not necessarily about money''
but about attacking the ``endemic societal problem of police
brutality.''
</P>
<P>
   Another lawyer, Peter Neufeld, said this goal explained why the
defendants were not only the city and the officers charged in the
brutality _ the usual parties in such suits _ but the union, police
officers ``who stood by and did nothing'' and supervisors whose
failures ``amounted to gross negligence, deliberate indifference or
intentional misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Louima's cousin and spokesman, Samuel Nicolas, said he planned
to use part of any damage award to aid victims of police brutality
and to support officers who want to expose such behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Also named as defendants are the two members of the city
ambulance crew that responded to the precinct station house when
``finally summoned'' by police to treat a severely injured Louima
after he had been beaten and tortured, the court papers said.
</P>
<P>
   They charged that the two, William Pagan and Frank Birnbaum,
members of the Emergency Medical Service, ``delayed treatment'' of
Louima and aided a police coverup by intentionally omitting in
their ambulance call report ``Mr. Louima's statements to them that
he had been beaten by police officers and had a stick shoved into''
his rectum. Pagan and Birnbaum could not be reached Thursday
through their union or the Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Justin Volpe, one of the officers charged with
torturing Louima, said his client denied the civil suit claims,
just as he denied the criminal charges he faces. And despite
Cochran's statement that money was not the prime consideration,
Volpe's lawyer, Marvyn Kornberg, contended that ``Louima has had
monetary reasons for telling the story he has told.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
