<SLUG> BC-NY-PORN-SHOPS-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE INVOKES PUBLIC HEALTH TO SHUT STRIP BAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A state Supreme Court justice ordered the padlocking
of a second strip club in Manhattan Thursday and indicated in his
ruling that it could be difficult for such clubs to remain open
under a restrictive new zoning law, even if they devote just a
fraction of their floor space to nude dancing.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge, Justice Stephen Crane, did not rule on attempts
by video stores to stay in business under the Giuliani
administration's new anti-sex-shop law by using a similar tactic:
devoting the majority of their stock and floor space to non-sexual
goods.
</P>
<P>
   Crane made his ruling about the strip club, Angels, after police
officers testified that they found evidence of sexual activity and
possible prostitution during an inspection on Wednesday night. He
said the club on Walker Street in downtown Manhattan posed a public
health threat.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also suggested in his ruling that attempts by clubs to
scale back their operations as a way to remain open under the
restrictive new law will be strictly judged for compliance, and may
not pass muster in court.
</P>
<P>
   Across the city, strip clubs are trying to take advantage of
wording in the new law that describes a business as adult if its
``substantial use,'' in legal terms, is adult entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   City officials have said in court that ``substantial use'' means
more than 40 percent of a store or club's floor space or stock is
devoted to adult entertainment. In Angels and other strip clubs,
owners have restricted nude dancing to small, screened-off areas
that make up less than 40 percent of their floor space in the hope
of no longer being considered an ``adult establishment.''
</P>
<P>
   But Crane said in his ruling that the use of a series of
Japanese Shoji screens by Angels to block off a stage where women
danced nude was not enough to make the club a non-adult
establishment. He pointed out that activities that could be
considered adult entertainment were occurring ``throughout'' the
basement strip club.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attempt to abide by the 40 percent rule'' through the use
of the screens, the judge said, ``doesn't quite do the job of
separating adult from non-adult entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the club was failing to abide by its own version of
the 40 percent rule. Detective Richard Providence testified
Thursday that when he entered Angels on Wednesday evening, the
club's ``transvestite night,'' he saw customers fondling fully
clothed female and transvestite dancers in the part of the club
theoretically considered ``non-adult.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Daniel Connolly, the corporation counsel lawyer arguing the case
on the city's behalf, said Thursday that officers also recently
discovered evidence of sexual activity in the Harmony II strip club
on West 22nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   During a hearing Monday, Crane ordered the Harmony Theater on
Church Street padlocked after city officials presented evidence of
sexual activity there.
</P>
<P>
   The judge has so far not granted the city's requests to
immediately padlock three video stores _ Show World, a 20-year-old
sex emporium at 669 Eighth Ave.; NRS XXX Video at 414 Eighth Ave.;
and Les Hommes, a video store on 217 W. 80th St. _ that officials
says violate the new zoning law.
</P>
<P>
   He is instead carrying out lengthy hearings, expected to last
into next week, in which the stores and strip clubs are presenting
evidence that their frantic renovations and new operating
procedures make their floor space and stock less than 40 percent
adult.
</P>
<P>
   City officials have dismissed the efforts to change as
subterfuges, and have said only changing a former adult video store
or strip club to another type of business is acceptable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
