<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: BEST NHL ACTION IS THE BATTLE OVER TV RIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This has been a good year for Gary Bettman, the National Hockey
League commissioner. First, he met the owner of the Tampa Bay
Lightning, whom no league official had seen, then he helped
engineer the team's sale. And this week, without wishing upon a
star, Bettman got a $600 million, five-year offer from the Walt
Disney Co. to carry the NHL on ABC, ESPN and ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   Now, when you're the recipient of a $120 million-a-year bid _
and your league has been getting an average of $45 million annually
from Fox and ESPN _ you don't ask Michael Eisner, the chairman of
Disney, if he's gone a smidgen goofy.
</P>
<P>
   No, you are one grateful and gleeful commissioner, who certainly
knows that in the 1991-92 season, which preceded his tenure, the
NHL's entire take from U.S. television rights came to $5.5 million.
The league had only a cable-rights holder then, SportsChannel
America. No broadcast network wanted in.
</P>
<P>
   So if you're Gary Bettman, you don't ask Disney why it's doing
what it's doing. You simply say, ``Michael, your investment is even
dandier than staging `The Lion King' on Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   But it looks only to be a good investment for the lucky NHL. Who
would have thought this would happen after U.S. players trashed
property at the Winter Olympics? Or when Fox's regular season
Nielsen rating slid to a 1.4? Or when Detroit won the Stanley Cup
with the fourth consecutive four-game sweep?
</P>
<P>
   You must wonder what Disney's strategy is beyond guaranteeing
that hockey will stay on ESPN and ESPN2 for five more years.
Clearly, this is heavily a cable play, with $350 million of the bid
ascribed to ESPN and ESPN2. In buying National Football League
rights, ESPN is paying $600 million a year for Sunday night rights,
more than ABC's $550 million for ``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   But adding ABC to the mix is dumbfounding. Does ABC, a
struggling network, need more low-rated programming? Wouldn't its
affiliates prefer an eighth-run flick to a Saturday or Sunday night
game that gets a 1.4 rating?
</P>
<P>
   Does ABC think that ousting Fox from the money-losing hockey
broadcasting business will make its overlord, Rupert Murdoch, cry
for his glowing pucks?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, ABC, ESPN and ESPN2 can cross-promote hockey
(``Nightline'' can glide right from a report on Kosovo to a Pavel
Bure hockey spot, eh?), but the rewards will be slim compared with
those of the cross-promotion ESPN and ABC are now engaged in to
make absolutely certain we know beyond a reasonable doubt about
their full seasons of Sunday and Monday night football.
</P>
<P>
   But ABC is stepping into a quagmire. At Fox, ratings have fallen
only 33 percent since 1996, but ratings among key demographics are
tumbling. Between 1995 and 1998, the rating among men 18 to 34 has
fallen from a 2.2 to a 1.3. And last year, the teen-age male
demographic fell from a 1.3 to an 0.8.
</P>
<P>
   ABC shouldn't contemplate putting an All-Star Game in
prime-time. Fox's 2.8 rating for the 1997 event stands as the
lowest prime-time rating ever.
</P>
<P>
   And ABC will surely remember that when it carried NHL games
last, in 1994, the barely promoted schedule managed a 1.7 average
rating.
</P>
<P>
   Despite heavy promotion by Fox, the NHL has an even lower
rating, 1.4. ESPN, also a vigorous marketer, saw its rating slide
last year, from a 0.8 to a 0.7.
</P>
<P>
   The ESPN2 rating stayed flat at 0.4.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Disney sees benefits to making a blockbuster bid. The Mouse
Kingdom's target for such spending is questionable enough, but why
do it at a time when big losses are expected from the stupendous
NFL deals? At least Disney has reasons for its wild NFL spending:
``Monday Night Football'' is a top-five prime-time program, and
football is ESPN's highest-rated sport.
</P>
<P>
   But hockey? Does Disney know something about hockey's future the
rest of us don't? The emergence of a dozen astonishing superstars?
The amazing impact of adding Nashville, St. Paul and Columbus to
the league's national footprint? Five consecutive Rangers Stanley
Cup titles to start the millennium?
</P>
<P>
   Can Eisner foretell that ABC's hockey rating will suddenly rise
to Fox's 2.7 baseball rating, soar to ABC's, CBS's and NBC's
combined 2.9 golf rating or rocket to CBS's 4.3 NASCAR rating?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it will come down to corporate egos. Disney and Fox
dislike each other for many reasons, if only because they are
powerful entities, with different styles and lots of money, that
are building sports kingdoms.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe Disney opted to overpay to make sure it swept Fox from
hockey. Fox can counter, by Aug. 14, with a bid to keep the
broadcast rights and let ESPN and ESPN2 simply renew their cable
deal. But if Fox plays hardpuck it could match Disney on the
broadcast side and try to outbid Disney on the cable level. If
successful, a Fox double play would force ESPN and ESPN2 to
scramble for replacement programming for four combined games per
week. But just as ABC made sure it would outbid NBC to guarantee it
would keep ``Monday Night Football,'' it's unlikely that Disney
would let the cable package be wrested away by Fox.
</P>
<P>
   But by not quickly bidding adieu to the NHL after being told of
Disney's bid, Fox is sending a mixed signal: Either it is seriously
considering a counteroffer or it wants to make Disney sweat.
</P>
<P>
   This is the coolest game on earth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
